<SLUG> BC-CEO-RESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH MOBILE-PHONE MAKER OUST CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchae by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Ericsson AB, the Swedish telecommunications company
that is the world's third-largest mobile telephone producer, ousted
its chief executive Wednesday in a surprise move only 15 months
after his appointment, sending its stock spiraling down nearly 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is threatened by Nokia of Finland and
Motorola of the United States in the booming mobile telephone
market, said that Sven-Christer Nilsson, its chief executive and
president, had resigned to assist the ``increased pace in the
restructuring efforts to insure Ericsson's continued leading
position and profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson was replaced by his predecessor as chief executive, Lars
Ramqvist, the company's chairman. Kurt Hellstroem, the head of
Ericsson's Southeast Asia division, took over as president.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have grown concerned about Ericsson's direction under
Nilsson, who rattled them throughout his short tenure with repeated
profit warnings. Though Ramqvist's return to the job was seen as a
positive development, it was overshadowed by the surprise of
Nilsson's abrupt departure, and Ericsson's stock price tumbled on
fear that the move presaged another profit warning ahead of the
half-year results, which are due July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Ericsson, controlled by the Investor AB holding company, is
Sweden's biggest company by market capitalization. But its fortunes
have been uneven, with mobile phones sales down and costs rising.
In April, it warned that a combination of market uncertainty,
increased costs, lower profitability and restructuring expenses was
expected to push profits down this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nilsson took over as chief executive and president in March
1998, and announced restructuring plans in October that were
supposed to help prepare Ericsson to compete in a new generation of
wireless technology using high-speed Internet and data hookups. The
plan called for cutting 11,000 jobs _ a tenth of the work force _
at a cost of $352 million. A company statement Wednesday said that
the plan for a reduced work force remained intact, though less than
half of the job cuts had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But, the statement added, ``The next phase of implementation of
this strategy and continued technological changes requires strong
and expeditious leadership.'' The company said the management
change was ``intended to improve profitability and long-term growth
in the company.''
</P>
<P>
   After the announcement, Ericsson's shares, which hit a high for
the year of 287.5 kronor, or $33.82, on Monday, plummeted 22.50
kronor, or 7.9 percent, to 262 kronor, leading a broad decline on
the Stockholm market. The company's American depository receipts
fared even worse, falling $3.1875, or 9.3 percent, to $30.4375 on
the NASDAQ market, where it was among the day's most heavily traded
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives said Nilsson had been held responsible for
failing to expedite the revamping. During Nilsson's tenure,
Ericsson watched as Nokia surged past Motorola to become the
world's biggest manufacturer of mobile phones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
