<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN STILL PLAY CATCH-UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when you thought the U.S. women's World Cup
team was winning fans and influencing chauvinists, a high-ranking
official of international soccer's governing body cleared his
throat _ the better to make room for his boot.
</P>
<P>
   At a media gathering in Century City on Wednesday, Keith Cooper,
the communications director of FIFA, introduced Marla Messing. She
is the president and CEO of the 1999 Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But that isn't how Cooper described her. Instead, he glibly
referred to her as ``the little lady, Marla Messing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a gaffe on par with U.S. defender Brandi Chastain's own
goal against Germany in the quarterfinals. The only difference was
Chastain knew right away she had made an egregious mistake and
wasted little time atoning for it, beating the German goalkeeper
once to help the U.S. to a 3-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper gave not the slightest indication he had goofed. To her
credit, Messing neither blanched nor blinked before extolling the
efforts of the four remaining World Cup participants _ the U.S.,
China, Norway and Brazil _ in advancing the cause of gender equity
in sport and society.
</P>
<P>
   Her words, however heartfelt, floated over the crowd in the
hotel ballroom like a balloon leaking helium. Cooper, without
realizing it, had let a little air out of a crusade.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter now how riveting, how rousing, Saturday's
title match is between the U.S. and China. As Cooper's gaffe made
so clear, to write the story of the 1999 Women's World Cup as an
Emancipation Proclamation for female athletes is to write fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Women and men have been fighting a civil war on the sporting
turf since the passage in 1972 of Title IX. Logic dictates that
it's going to take more than three weeks of scintillating soccer to
tear down convention and build a new consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Logic, though, has gone the way of empty seats at U.S. matches.
To be sure, it's hard not to buy the hype if your feet aren't
firmly grounded in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Parlow came along six years after Title IX. The
21-year-old starting forward on the U.S. team is the beneficiary of
battles not her own.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't have to pay her own way to play soccer at the
University of North Carolina, like teammate Julie Foudy did at
Stanford in the late 1980s. She hasn't had to wash her U.S. uniform
in the sink after games like teammate Michelle Akers did when she
joined the national team in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The road was paved for Parlow, so she can be forgiven for not
anticipating any bumps or detours ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The commotion created by the U.S. team en route to the World Cup
final ``just shows there's an opportunity for women in sports,''
Parlow gushed. ``Little girls can see they don't have to grow up
being a secretary or a nurse. There is room to be a professional
athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what all the marketing and media mavens are saying, too.
</P>
<P>
   As much as she would like to believe it, Tiffeny Milbrett knows
better.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett is the offspring of a 50-something, soccer-playing mom
who was confined to recreational club competition by the mores of
her day.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, Milbrett's perspective is broad enough to see where U.S.
soccer's grand dame, Akers, and the young pup, Parlow, are coming
from.
</P>
<P>
   She knows the women's work is only beginning when the World Cup
ends. She was reminded anew of this on a commercial flight the U.S.
team took the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett was seated next to a passenger who glanced at all the
women wearing red, white and blue sweat jackets and asked, ``What
kind of high school basketball team is this?''
</P>
<P>
   At that instant, Milbrett felt as small as a salted peanut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're on top of the world,'' Milbrett said, ``but
then we . . . jump on a plane and it's easy to be brought down to
earth real fast. The reality is, we still have a long ways to go
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbrett and Parlow were late arriving to the press conference.
Traffic spared them Cooper's reminder of just how much ground they
have to make up. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
