<HEADLINE>
THE KOCH VERSION: HOW HE'S DOING  
 TOP COP  
 ON CONDITION OF ANONYMITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHARLES STRUM with ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Have no fear,'' writes Ed Koch in the latest
monthly packet of press clippings he sends to friends and
associates. ``I'll be out of the hospital by Tuesday, probably back
in the office next week, and back at the gym in four weeks. I have
dodged another bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ebullient former mayor, 74, who suffered a heart attack
last week, was a tad optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Koch's note was dated last Friday, the day after he was
stricken. He remains in intensive care at New York Weill Cornell
Center of Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   George Arzt, his former press secretary, said Wednesday that
damage to Koch's heart was found to be less extensive than
initially thought. Last week, a blocked artery was reopened.
</P>
<P>
   But the flow of blood through two other arteries was found to be
reduced, by 70 percent in one. Arzt said doctors were considering
``opening that up,'' too. He said Koch could be home by Friday or
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Koch has made the most of his stay. He has told
friends that he had ``the best room possible'' for the fireworks
over the East River on Sunday night, and he delayed the monthly
packet to add press coverage of his illness. His column Friday in
The Daily News is all about the dodged bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Interpol Selects Yank as Top Man
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Noble is soon to be an American in Lyons, France _ not
only the first American, but also the first non-European to go
there as secretary general of Interpol, the international police
agency.
</P>
<P>
   International he may become, but his is a very American success
story.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an Army sergeant, Noble, 42, grew up in a biracial,
bilingual household. His father, who is African-American, met his
mother, who is German, just after World War II. By the time the
elder Noble had retired and opened a small janitorial-supply
business, the family was living outside Fort Dix, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I was 16, I just wanted to take over the business,''
Noble said.
</P>
<P>
   But his father had other ideas, which the son heeded: University
of New Hampshire, Stanford University Law School, the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   As a Treasury Department undersecretary, he was the author of a
scathing report on the bloody federal assault on the Branch
Davidian compound in Waco, Texas, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Noble will succeed Raymond Kendall, a former Scotland Yard
official, in October 2000. The term is five years and is renewable.
</P>
<P>
   No-Name Museum
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Pierce Brosnan ever wants to get into the
Metropolitan Museum of Art again, he may have to do more than pay
the standard donation.
</P>
<P>
   In a remake of ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' that opens next
month, Brosnan stars as a corporate raider who chases women,
dresses really well and steals art.
</P>
<P>
   But when production started, Brosnan, who is also the producer,
discovered that Philippe de Montebello, the Met's director, was
troubled that the film would show how to steal a painting and would
depict the Met's security staff as bumbling.
</P>
<P>
   So they agreed that in publicity materials the Met would become
``an unnamed, heavily guarded New York museum.'' No filming was
allowed. Interiors were shot on a sound stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to cooperate with filmmakers,'' said the Met's chief
spokesman, Harold Holzer, citing recent professional visits by Ben
Stiller and Woody Allen. ``But a movie that suggests that our
security is lax is not something we want to encourage. At least
this way, it's referred to as `an anonymous lookalike museum.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anonymous? On Tuesday, about 100 guests, including Andrew Stein,
the former City Council president, and Patricia Duff, a former Mrs.
Ronald Perelman, attended a screening whose hosts were Pamela Gross
and Jimmy Finkelstein, founders of LuxuryFinder.com. No one was
fooled.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Siegel, a guest and a film critic for ABC-TV, said: ``It's
like making a deal with the Vatican in which you can only refer to
it as `the unnamed headquarters of a major religion in Rome.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
