<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENT CANDIDATE SNUBS BOARD AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City Board of Education is turning
its attention to Benjamin Demps Jr. as the next possible school
superintendent, having been rebuffed for a second time Wednesday by
Pascal Forgione Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Board members met privately Wednesday afternoon and voted 7-2 to
ask Forgione, a former U.S. education commissioner, to reconsider
his decision to withdraw as a candidate. Terry Riley and Lee Barnes
Jr. opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, board members and other community leaders
discussed sending a delegation of civic leaders, led by Kansas City
Mayor Kay Barnes, to Washington to persuade Forgione to change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   But Forgione's attorney later told a district representative
that his client was no longer interested in Kansas City. Board Vice
President Patricia Kurtz said she had not been able to contact
Forgione.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he calls me back firsthand to tell me,'' Kurtz said.
``This thing is taking some unusual twists and turns, and I just
don't know where it will go.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple ordered a conference
for this morning, to be updated on the search. And Demps, a
longtime state and federal administrator, told district officials
Wednesday that he remained interested in the position.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, the court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring
Committee told school board members it still expected them to hire
a superintendent by midday Friday from a field of four candidates
originally submitted to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Three of them later withdrew from consideration. But one,
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Jay T. Edwards, has since reconsidered
and says he is interested in the job.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite certain what will happen if the board fails to
reach agreement with Demps. Some board members have speculated that
if they are unable to come to terms with a superintendent, Whipple
might put the district in receivership, giving the court complete
control over district operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Receivership has been a potential end game or outcome ever
since I've been on the board and even before,'' Kurtz said.
``That's an option the court has. But from my perspective, given
all the constraints we have on us...the board is working hard and
trying to do the job. It's just tremendously difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz also said intense media scrutiny of the process was making
the selection even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a little bit like were under siege almost,'' she said.
``It's almost impeding the process. It makes our job that much more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgione, a former U.S. education commissioner for statistics,
abruptly withdrew his candidacy Tuesday afternoon in the midst of
discussions on a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview late Tuesday night, Forgione expressed anger at
the negotiating tactics employed by the district's legal counsel,
Blackwell Sanders Peper Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Forgione contended that board members initially agreed to
provide him salary and benefits similar to the $200,000 annual
package paid to former Superintendent Henry Williams. But Forgione
said that when a Blackwell Sanders lawyer faxed a contract offer
Tuesday, it included far less compensation. He said it was apparent
he and the board were starting their relationship too far apart and
with too little trust to ensure a successful partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a board can't give direction and be accountable for this
one decision, what does that say about the tougher struggles we
would have to face together down the road?'' Forgione said.
</P>
<P>
   School board members and the Desegregation Monitoring Committee
spent much of Wednesday trying to reconstruct what had gone wrong.
Many, including all three monitoring committee members, tried
unsuccessfully to reach Forgione by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, members said they thought Forgione had
mischaracterized events and simply got cold feet. Board members
said that they had authorized their attorney to offer up to
$164,500 in base salary, $33,800 in performance incentives, plus
benefits, but that Forgione withdrew before the parties even began
discussing salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting the Washington spin,'' board member Lance
Loewenstein said. ``The mature thing to do would have been to call
and say, `Is this a typo?' Not to quit. If he has such a monumental
ego that he can't make a phone call to make sure there isn't a
misunderstanding, then we don't want him.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgione could not be reached Wednesday. His Kansas City
attorney, Norris Greer, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Barnes said she had offered to get involved in the search
after a day of phone calls and conversations with school board
members and civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision regarding the selection of a superintendent
crosses all political, social and racial boundaries, and must be a
top priority for all Kansas Citians,'' Barnes said. ``I will do
whatever I can to assist in the selection of a qualified
superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, some board members say they expected Demps to encounter
the same kind of opposition as Edwards, who now works as general
administrator of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission. Many in the
minority community complained that Edwards had no background in
education and argued that the district needed someone with
experience as an urban school superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Demps, who lives in Oklahoma City, also has no experience in
public education. He could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Demps also already has expressed concern about whether he would
be able to complete negotiations on a contract by the DMC-imposed
Friday deadline.
</P>
<P>
   He also faces a divided board. At Wednesday's meeting, the
board's vote to pursue Demps should Forgione decline the offer
passed 5-3, with one abstention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like now we're going to the last option _ door number
3,'' board member Connie Clark said of pursuing Demps. ``What's
that say about how confident we feel?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
