<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marlins left floundering by Maddux
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ reg Maddux is officially back in his element, complete
with frustrated hitters, ridiculous control and streaks like the
one he rode into Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He wound up losing his scoreless streak at 20 innings but not
much else, restoring some order to this series with a 7-3 win over
the NL East cellar-dwelling Marlins. The Braves are back on top in
the series 2-1 with one game to go, and with the Mets' loss to the
Expos their first-place East lead is back to four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good, I felt relaxed, really relaxed,'' said Maddux,
now 9-5. ``I don't know. Some nights you're just more relaxed than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   The same Marlins that slapped 15 hits on Tom Glavine Tuesday _
the most ever allowed by an Atlanta pitcher _ scratched out only
three on Maddux, including one Preston Wilson home run that broke
up his scoreless streak. Maddux got his third consecutive win and
fourth in the last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's in a zone, he's in a zone,'' Braves right fielder
Brian Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux's ERA is down to 3.55, and he moved to 9-2 with a 2.01
ERA vs. Florida. He left the game after six innings having taken a
Bruce Aven grounder in the left foot, diagnosed as just a bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux threw 72 pitches _ 55 of them strikes.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the control spectrum was Marlins 22-year-old
right-hander Ryan Dempster, who'd walked 15 batters in his previous
13 2/3 innings coming into the game. He added four in five innings
Wednesday night and gave up one of his seven charged runs on a wild
pitch. He didn't fare much better with his pitches over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones and Andruw Jones each launched home runs, Bret
Boone and Maddux each doubled and new All-Star Jordan got his 69th
RBI to start the scoring off on a single in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are getting in scoring position for me, Boonie,
Chipper,'' Jordan said. ``I hit my little 18-hopper between first
and second, drive in a run. I'll take that every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones led off the third by hitting a line-drive home run
to right, his fifth in six games and 19th of the year, to give the
Braves a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
