<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVS ROOKIE LEON SMITH LOOKS TO FIND A HOME IN NBA
</HEADLINE>
 SMITH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nine-year-old Leon Smith was swinging on a Chicago
playground with his 8-year-old brother Jerry Sanders when a woman
called to them, ``Hey, you two, come over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and his brother walked over to the woman, who demanded,
``Give me a hug.'' They obliged and then the woman asked, ``Do
y'all know who I am?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you're our mother,'' Leon and Jerry responded. Then they
went back to the swings.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, Leon Smith, 18, is the newest Mavericks
project, a 6-foot-11 forward drafted from Chicago's Martin Luther
King High School by the San Antonio Spurs last week and traded to
Dallas. He is one of two high school players picked in the first
round of the 1999 draft, the reigning Illinois high school player
of the year who averaged 25.5 points, 14.5 rebounds and eight
blocked shots per game.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a survivor who yearns to reunite his family after
spending the past 14 years as a ward of Illinois, living in
state-run housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon is a successful story for kids who are taken from their
parents and go on to become wards of the state,'' said Ormon
O'Quinn, a former King assistant basketball coach who helped
retrieve Smith from despair. ``Here goes a story that needs to be
written, that needs to be seen, that needs to be heard by these
other kids that are wards of the state, because a lot of those kids
turn rebellious and get mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon could be making commercials telling kids, `Hey, stick in
there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He has stuck with it through a transient life that saw him live
in five group homes from ages 4 through 18, a life that came after
his parents' divorce that left Smith and his seven siblings
scattered throughout Chicago in group homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things just happened along the way,'' is the way Smith
explained his life. ``But I had to keep my nose clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith grew up around gangs and drugs on Chicago's south side. He
said his parents' breakup and his mother's personal problems led to
him and his siblings becoming wards of the state. He has no
relationship with his father, and he said he last talked to his
mother two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   O'Quinn said both Smith's parents tried to start a relationship
with Smith once his name became prominent on the Chicago basketball
scene. Smith can't remember the last time he saw his father, and
there was a period from ages 10 to 16 when he didn't see his
mother.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Smith said he declared for the NBA Draft for one
unselfish reason. He has one brother and six sisters scattered in
group homes in Illinois, and he figured he could use his NBA money
to buy a house and put everyone under one beautiful roof.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the NBA is a means to an end for Smith, a way to
finally give his siblings some much-needed love, peace and
happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to do everything the right way,'' said Smith, who is
wise beyond his years. ``I'm trying to put my family back
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was at his group home, Sullivan House, when he learned he
had been drafted by the Spurs with the final pick of the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did that because I knew everything would work itself out,
and I just wanted to let them know we're all in this together, and
if I made it, they were going to make it,'' Smith said. ``The
people at the Sullivan House will always be a big part of my life
because they helped make me become the person that I am today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a regular (family) setting before. It was
hard at times living in the group homes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smith persevered, using basketball as an outlet. Whether he
starts his NBA career with the Mavericks this year or next, he will
get a three-year guaranteed contract worth approximately $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon is a good kid who just wants to be loved,'' O'Quinn said.
``They need a ward of the state story so these kids know that they
can still make it, because a lot of these kids who become wards of
the state feel like they're failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I used to tell Leon all the time, `Hey, you've got a
lot going for yourself son. Don't blow it.' '' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
