<HEADLINE>
SAMAKI WALKER DRAWING INTEREST, AGENT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Still convinced his client won't get a favorable offer
from the Mavericks, agent Norm Nixon said forward Samaki Walker is
receiving interest from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two teams that have shown a lot of interest /Rare/S
Milwaukee and Vancouver,'' Nixon said. ``But right now they're only
talking about offering the $2 million exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting on the Clippers, Utah and Minnesota, because those
teams have a lot of (salary) cap room.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker turned down a four-year, $20 million extension from the
Mavericks in February, but Mavericks coach/general manager Don
Nelson has told Walker he would match any deal as high as $2.5
million. If the Mavericks can't re-sign Gary Trent, Nelson might
have to up the ante.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Trent is the Mavericks' top priority, but the best they
can offer him is a two-year, $4.2 million deal or a one-year, $2
million deal. Trent and Walker are power forwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go about my business one way or the other,''
Walker said. ``I want to go somewhere where I can help somebody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that's playing, they know my abilities. Anybody that
knows basketball knows that I can play this game.'' ALL'S FORGOTTEN
</P>
<P>
   Everything was back to normal a day after 18-year-old rookie
Leon Smith was booted out of the first day of minicamp by assistant
coach Donnie Nelson for failing to run wind sprints.
</P>
<P>
   Smith later apologized to Nelson and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the growing process,'' Donnie Nelson said.
``We're just going to continue to have conflicts like this and have
resolution, and over a period of time we're going to grow together
solid as a rock.'' ACE IN THE FOLD
</P>
<P>
   Forward Ace Custis is trying to win a spot with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Custis was on injured reserved the entire 1997-98 season, and
was waived by the Mavericks in training camp last season. Custis
wound up playing for the Pennsylvania Valley Dogs of the United
States Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Former NBA player ``Darryl Dawkins was my coach, so that was
interesting,'' Custis said. ``He's a true character, but that was a
good experience. He used to tell stories about when they used to go
on the road and name his dunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Add Custis to the list of players impressed by rookie Leon
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a strong kid,'' Custis said. ``He's real aggressive, and
he's willing to go and block shots.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
