<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-ARCHITECT-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY ART MUSEUM CHOSES ARCHITECT TO DESIGN ADDITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANTRELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art has picked
American architect Steven Holl, widely considered a rising star in
his profession, to design an $80 million addition to the original
1933 building.
</P>
<P>
   Holl's plan will place a series of new galleries underground on
the east side of the existing building, along Rockhill Road, in a
slender triangle widening from north to south. Seven above-ground
lanterns, clad in transparent and translucent glass, will draw
natural light during the day and glow from within at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, this stood out as something that was
magical,'' Nelson-Atkins director Marc Wilson said of the Holl
scheme. ``It was definitely not conventional.''
</P>
<P>
   The design includes a new entry lobby at the north end, to be
entered primarily from a new underground parking garage north of
the present building. Capping the garage will be a reflecting pool,
positioned off center to integrate new and old buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing down the new structure's procession will be a cafe,
spaces for special exhibitions, modern and contemporary art,
prints, drawings, African art, the Noguchi sculpture court, and an
educational facility and library. Given the slope of the land from
north to south, the procession will be broken up by stairs and
ramps.
</P>
<P>
   The new entry lobby also will connect to the lower level of the
existing museum building, just outside the Atkins Auditorium.
Visitors will take an expanded staircase into a new grand gallery,
reconfigured from space now used for special exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Holl, who will appear at a press conference
at the museum at 3:30 p.m. today, has attracted international
acclaim for his boldly chiseled contemporary art museum Kiasma in
Helsinki, Finland, which opened in 1998. Holl, 51, also is working
on a redesign and expansion of the Cranbrook Institute of Science
in Bloomfield Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Holl, who was unavailable for comment Wednesday, is a native of
Bremerton, Wash. He was educated at the University of Washington
and at the Architectural Association in London, and he established
his architecture firm in 1976. He has been a tenured professor in
the Graduate School of Architecture and Planning of Columbia
University since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelson-Atkins project will expand the museum by more than 55
percent, from its present 234,000 square feet to 374,000 square
feet. Now in conceptual form, Holl's design should be completed by
February 2001. Construction is expected to begin in spring 2001 and
end in 2004. A local architect of record will be selected in fall
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The project is being funded from a $175 million capital
campaign; $95 million will go toward an endowment for programming,
education and outreach. So far, the museum has pledges of
approximately $135 million.
</P>
<P>
   Holl was one of six internationally prominent architects invited
to submit sketchbook proposals for the museum expansion. The
others:
</P>
<P>
   - Tadao Ando Architect &AMP; Associates, Osaka, Japan
</P>
<P>
   - Annette Gigon//Mike Guyer, Zurich, Switzerland
</P>
<P>
   - Carlos Jimenez Studio, Houston
</P>
<P>
   - Machado and Silvetti Associates Inc., Boston
</P>
<P>
   - Atelier Christian de Portzamparc, Paris
</P>
<P>
   Holl's was the only design that did not envision a large new
structure on the north side _ now the main entrance _ of the
existing neoclassical building.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals by Ando, Gigon//Guyer and Jimenez would have
completely obscured the 66-year-old building's north facade with
enormous boxes. Machado and Silvetti proposed a narrower structure
that would have left the colonnaded wings of the older building
exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Portzamparc's design called for a slender corridor extending
from the present entrance, with free-form galleries spreading out
from its sides.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, each of the architects gave in-person
presentations of their designs for the museum's architect selection
committee, led by senior trustee and Hallmark Cards chairman Donald
J. Hall. Before the presentation, committee members also visited
completed buildings by the architects in the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Holl's design was radically different from the other
five,'' said committee member Henry Bloch, a Nelson-Atkins trustee,
leader of the building committee and chairman of H&AMP;R Block Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all left the south terrace alone. But Steven Holl came
out with a completely different configuration on the east side,
where you could enjoy the sculpture court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't fight with this building. It would enhance it. And
the committee was unanimous in selecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although construction will require temporary disruption of the
east edge of the Nelson property, the main south lawn will not be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson-Atkins director Wilson praised all the architects for
being ``very sensitive to the issues.'' He said the choice became
clear only at the end, after Holl made the last of the
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The others were to a degree conventional,'' Wilson said,
``based on Western European architecture of the last 500 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee member Ada Louise Huxtable, architecture critic of The
Wall Street Journal, formerly of The New York Times, praised the
Portzamparc and Ando designs. But she said most of the designs
would have yielded ``a very big building'' north of the existing
structure.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, she called Holl's plan ``a miraculous response,
really, to the landscape, to the original building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be one of the best buildings anywhere.
It's going to be a pilgrimage point for people who are interested
in museums and architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Gaunt, dean of the School of Architecture and Urban
Design at the University of Kansas and another member of the
Nelson-Atkins selection committee, shared the enthusiasm for the
Holl plan. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
