<SLUG> BC-SMALL-RACECARS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TINY CARS PROVIDE BIG EXCITEMENT AT RACE TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANT HILL, Mo. _ It's a familiar scene. Lap one, turn one.
Six race cars funnel into the turn, every driver trying to be
first. Cars kiss briefly. One flips into the air as more cars smash
into one another. Some spin, others cartwheel down the track or
over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Such a sight would bring gasps of horror and a red flag at
Indianapolis or Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   But it's cause for whoops and chuckles among spectators at the
Real R.C. Raceway near Pleasant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   These vehicles are radio-controlled, one-eighth or one-tenth
full size, and their drivers are safely looking on.
</P>
<P>
   The racing cars look like frolicking puppies as they scamper
over the jumps, nibble at one another's heels and tumble into a
heap.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake: Although the cars are not real, the racing
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raced full-scale cars, and I rode dirt bikes seriously,
and I get as much of an adrenaline rush (here) as I did from any of
that stuff,'' said Chris Kovachevich of Independence, a former
Sports Car Club of America driver.
</P>
<P>
   Crashes generally would finish full-size cars for the day, but
not the models. Most land on their wheels and sprint away. Course
marshals pick up those that are stuck and set them back on the
track to rejoin the chase.
</P>
<P>
   They might be way behind, but hey, those guys out front could
flip or spin out. It's anybody's race.
</P>
<P>
   It's a typical Friday night at Steve Hale's track just west of
Pleasant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 racers and their families and friends have come to the
dirt track. The track simulates an off-road course with left turns,
right turns, jumps and bumps packed into an area 90 feet by 120
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers mount an elevated stand from which they can see the
whole track. There are men and women; a gray-bearded veteran may be
standing next to a child too young to drive a real car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about this,'' said Tony Mineart of Raytown,
Mo., ``is kids can compete against their dads. It doesn't matter
what your age.''
</P>
<P>
   The cars are sophisticated enough to allow considerable tweaking
of suspensions, which are fully independent, with coil springs and
tiny oil-filled shock absorbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything you can do on a real race car, you can do on
these,'' Mineart said.
</P>
<P>
   Their engines can rev to 35,000 rpm, Hale said. On a long enough
straightaway, they can hit 50 to 55 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Clutches are automatic, but the drivers can steer, brake and
throttle.
</P>
<P>
   The track started as a small dirt oval in Hale's back yard,
where he and 10 or 15 friends would run their cars. Over the years
it grew to its present size, with a concession stand, announcer's
booth, computer timing and scoring and a roofed area where crews
can work on their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Kovachevich has been racing the cars for years and writes about
it for magazines. He started when his son got a radio-controlled
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought him one and ran it up and down the driveway,'' he
said. ``That was fun, now what? My stepson said, `They've got a
whole racetrack on the other side of town.' I've never looked
back.''
</P>
<P>
   A car, spare parts and equipment for racing can cost $400 to
$1,000, racers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a cheap hobby,'' Kovachevich said, ``but money
doesn't necessarily mean winning. It's more driver skill than
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Racers compete in divisions according to skill, from novice to
expert.
</P>
<P>
   On a Friday night in June, Tracy Dinwiddie of Blue Springs, Mo.,
won the first heat, a race for novice drivers of electric cars. Her
car quit in its second race _ a dead battery _ but she came back in
the third and finished strong in the main event.
</P>
<P>
   She is in her first full year of racing, she said, having been
drawn into the sport by her husband, who also races.
</P>
<P>
   Racers mostly decide their own competitive level, Hale said. But
if someone has been running as a novice for a couple of years and
is winning everything, there might be a few gentle hints that it's
time to move up.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is Reggie Tongue, a safety for the
Kansas City Chiefs. He's been racing about 3 1/2 months but
competes as an expert and holds his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' Tongue said. ``It takes your mind off
things to come out and play with your toys for a couple of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a couple of hours, actually.
</P>
<P>
   Racing begins at 7 p.m. and consists of three qualifying heats
for each division, followed by mains. The races go off in quick
succession, but by the time everyone has had a chance to race _
electric or gas-powered cars, novice, sportsman or expert, trucks
and buggies _ it is often past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Hale is on the public address system throughout the night
reminding everybody to come back next week. By then, he will have
rebuilt the track with a whole new layout to challenge the drivers.
</P>
<P>
   That's racin'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
