<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS-THEFT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVES EXPERTS CONCERNED ABOUT FIREWORKS THEFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAWNA A. HAMEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERSIDE, Mo. _ In the hands of anyone other than a
professional, the highly volatile fireworks stolen from a Riverside
store are ``a coiled rattlesnake, and you're playing with it,'' a
federal official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jimerson, supervisor of the bomb and arson unit of the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, said the investigation was
continuing into the theft of display fireworks from a Riverside
warehouse over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Area police and the Missouri fire marshal's office are helping
with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a large quantity of fireworks and launching tubes
were reported missing about 9:10 p.m. Saturday from Cousins
Fireworks Co.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen fireworks, if detonated, could do considerable damage
to an apartment building and might destroy smaller buildings,
Jimerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Police have recovered some of the stolen goods, but the
fireworks that are still missing could easily be set to detonate,
Jimerson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a high priority with us because these fireworks are so
dangerous, so volatile,'' he said. ``They will maim and kill if
they get in the wrong hands, and no one has any idea how little it
takes to set them off.''
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks, which police described as mortar shells used in
large aerial displays, require a federal license for use.
</P>
<P>
   Each contains photoflash powder, which is more sensitive to
accelerants than black or smokeless powder used in common fireworks
such as firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these stolen fireworks are in the hands of John Q. Public,
or anyone without pyrotechnics training, especially juveniles,
you're literally talking about playing with fire,'' Jimerson said.
``If they're in a confined space, you've basically got the power of
a small bomb. It takes one second and one mistake to cause an utter
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks could be set off by a minimal amount of friction
or static electricity, Jimerson said. If one of the shells burst
and loose powder was touched by a spark, it probably would detonate
the entire stock, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks are more volatile in humid weather, Jimerson said.
Photoflash powder that gets wet and then dries out becomes more
sensitive to heat and friction, increasing the risk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   An ATF agent was killed several years ago when illegal fireworks
detonated while he was trying to destroy them, Jimerson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're talking about professionals here, people who are
specially trained to handle these things,'' he said. ``But for
anyone, if you want to see the big stuff, see it professionally on
the Fourth of July. In any other hands, you've got a very good
possibility of disaster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
