<HEADLINE>
FORMER POSTAL WORKER WINS RULING FROM FEDERAL BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sorting mail at the Kansas City Post Office
was a tolerable job for Robert F. Hernandez _ as long as he could
sit in a special orthopedic chair.
</P>
<P>
   The chair gave him support to avoid aggravating back injuries
from the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But postal supervisors four years ago took away his chair,
Hernandez said, forcing him to risk further injury or quit his job.
</P>
<P>
   He quit _ but Hernandez did not stop fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has won a ruling from the federal Merit Systems
Protection Board that says the Postal Service must reinstate him to
his job on Pershing Road and pay him lost wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, hard haul,'' said Hernandez, 53. ``A friend
of mine told me the whole third floor of the post office where I
was working erupted with people cheering because this guy had
beaten them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City postal officials said they could not discuss the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The order of the Merit Systems Protection Board came after the
Postal Service had appealed an initial decision in Hernandez's
favor in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez plans to return to the Postal Service and then take
early retirement. He also has a civil discrimination suit pending
in federal court against the Postal Service and the American Postal
Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez had neck, back, knee and shoulder problems stemming
from his service in Vietnam. Doctors' opinions indicated he needed
an orthopedic chair to perform his work.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service provided Hernandez with an orthopedic chair
in 1994 but removed it in July 1995, when his work status changed
and he was no longer under worker's compensation, according to the
Merit Board ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Postal supervisors instead substituted a ``leaning bar,'' a
metal device to lean against while he performed the manual sorting
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wiggles all night and you're fighting it with your back
muscles and rear muscles to stay level,'' Hernandez said. He
claimed the bar aggravated his injuries and caused him to miss work
until March 1996, when he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The merit board found that a supervisor wanted either to
pressure Hernandez to return to an automated processing position
that required him to stand, or to force him to leave the Postal
Service altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service argued that Hernandez quit voluntarily, but
regional Administrative Judge Victor Russell disagreed and in May
the merit board in Washington, D.C., backed his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so great because people have tried to go after
them and win,'' said Hernandez. ``But...I had all my documentation,
and I had witnesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
