<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ATHLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMERMAN PITCHES LIKE AN ALL-STAR AS RANGERS DEFEAT ATHLETICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The boxscore from the Rangers' 7-4 victory
against the Oakland Athletics yesterday reveals the wealth of
talent at manager Johnny Oates' disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Rick Helling, the Rangers' 20-game winner from
1998, took the mound at Network Associates Coliseum. All-Star
closer John Wetteland recorded the game's final three outs.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lineup included a two-time American League most
valuable player in right fielder Juan Gonzalez and All-Stars in
catcher Ivan Rodriguez and designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be argued,'' Oates said, ``that he's our most
valuable player through the first half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates referred to none of the aforementioned players.
</P>
<P>
   The manager spoke of right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, the
26-year-old rookie phenomenon who learned of his All-Star selection
Wednesday morning and again pitched like one during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Lee Stevens delivered the game-winning runs with
his two-run, seventh-inning single, and Zimmerman pitched 2 1/3
scoreless innings for his eighth victory in as many decision this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff has been right there every time we've called upon him,''
left fielder Rusty Greer said after the Rangers snapped their
four-game losing streak. ``He's been about as good as you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the bottom of the sixth inning with a 4-3
lead after a two-run double by center fielder Roberto Kelly, but
Oakland's Ben Grieve tied the score with his solo home run on a 3-2
fastball from Helling.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter John Jaha followed with a double before Oates
summoned dependable left-hander Mike Venafro from the bullpen.
Venafro retired first baseman Jason Giambi and right fielder Matt
Stairs, two left-handed hitters, without allowing Jaha to advance.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the Zimmerman, who induced an
inning-ending ground ball from catcher Ramon Hernandez and
surrendered only a seventh-inning single to third baseman Eric
Chavez before completing his 16th consecutive scoreless appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' Stevens said of Zimmerman. ``He's done
everything that's been asked of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens also came through in the clutch despite entering the
contest hitting .161 (5-for-31) in his previous nine games.
Stevens, who entered as a defensive replacement for Jon Shave in
the bottom of the sixth inning, fought off a first-pitch fastball
from right-hander Tim Worrell and dumped it into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to be aggressive early in the count,'' Stevens
said. ``I was looking for a fastball and fisted it into left field.
In all honesty, it was a good pitch. I think he put that pitch
where he wanted. All I know is that hit took the bad taste out of
my mouth for this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' two-out, bases-loaded single scored Gonzalez and third
baseman Todd Zeile and gave the Rangers a lead Zimmerman and
Wetteland would not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland loaded the bases in the ninth inning by issuing three
walks, but the three-time All-Star induced a game-ending popup from
shortstop Miguel Tejada to record his major-league-best 26th save.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's nothing-out-of-the-ordinary performance improved his
earned-run average to 0.89 _ thanks to 192/3 consecutive scoreless
innings _ and made him the Rangers' first pitcher to accumulate
eight victories before his first loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Where would the Rangers be without Zimmerman?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to try and explain it,'' Oates said. ``I'm just
going to enjoy it.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
