<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKIN, Kan. _ over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there's a definite possibility we've missed out on
some rain,'' Downing said. ``This thing is controversial enough, we
need a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawlins County opted to hold an election. The mail ballots go
out soon with a question reading: ``Shall weather modification
(cloud seeding) be allowed in or over Rawlins County?'' The
election is purely advisory.
</P>
<P>
   Weather modification is under way in several places outside
Kansas, with Texas among the most active.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the federal government helped study weather
modification in states ranging from North Dakota to Utah, said Joe
Golden, a senior meteorologist for the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, who managed the project, said the potential for changing
the weather is very real. It's essential, he said, for cloud
seeding to take place in the right way in the right storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very promising possibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
