r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOUD-SEEDING-2TAKES-     07-08 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOUD-SEEDING-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSANS DISAGREE OVER MERITS OF CLOUD SEEDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKIN, Kan. _ What a strange place to try to change the weather:
a yellow metal building not much bigger than a double garage, no
sign out front, accessible by gravel road at a little-used rural
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, when thunderstorms develop nearby, meteorologist Curtis
D. Smith operates radar, peers at computer screens and dispatches
airplanes that seed clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: suppress hail and thereby safeguard valuable farm
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeding all the severe storms we can get our hands on,''
Smith said. ``We know we're having an effect on the clouds.''
</P>
<P>
   Hocus-pocus?
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's say there's a lack of general agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Kansas Weather Modification Program began in 1975,
an attempt to enhance rainfall and reduce hail. Gradually, hail
emerged as the main focus.
</P>
<P>
   By one calculation, hail damage to crops has fallen 27 percent
in some of the area covered by the program.
</P>
<P>
   Major studies in the past found no proof that cloud seeding
really spurs rain or diminishes hailstones.
</P>
<P>
   And doctoring the sky has so angered a group of farmers in
northwest Kansas that they demanded a public vote. An advisory
election on weather modification takes place this month in Rawlins
County.
</P>
<P>
   Every Kansan has a stake in the debate. The cloud seeders will
spend $840,000 of government money this year.
</P>
<P>
   The program started in the early 1970s. Ground Water Management
District No. 1 in Scott City wanted to remove a little of the risk
of farming.
</P>
<P>
   The High Plains region often sees a lack of rain, but also often
sees ruinous hailstorms. So the water district undertook cloud
seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, seeding involves vaporizing a substance containing
silver iodide. The resulting ice nuclei enter clouds, providing
vast opportunities for hailstones to form. With so many nuclei
present, the thinking goes, hailstones don't grow large enough to
cause damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the economic benefits are tremendous,'' said Wallace
Robinson, owner of 4,200 acres near Modoc, Kan., and one of the
originators of the program.
</P>
<P>
   About two months ago, Robinson, who is 70, saw his wheat crop
damaged, but not destroyed, by hail.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that if we hadn't had weather modification,
we would have had a wipeout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the program evolved. The counties originally
funding it were joined by others. State funding came later.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 59, the radar operator and meteorologist, arrived in 1985
and serves as manager. A Lakin resident, he said he has traveled
the world conducting weather modification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more exciting than about anything else I can imagine in
meteorology, including storm chasing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the program runs from April 20 to Sept. 2. It covers
part or all of 22 western Kansas counties, including areas around
Dodge City, Garden City and Goodland.
</P>
<P>
   Checks after big storms, Smith said, have found that farmers in
areas covered by the program make fewer hail-insurance claims than
farmers in noncovered areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said we can't stop it all,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots say they can take off within 15 minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   During operations, Smith will use both hands to operate the
radar, judging what part of which storm to seed. By radio, pilots
provide crucial information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Concentrate on that cell just north of Garden City,'' he told
one airplane during a recent storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're burning,'' a pilot told him, meaning the seeding
solution was being ignited and spread into a storm.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is obvious. Although cloud seeding frequently takes
place alongside thunderstorms, not in the midst of them, the
airplanes do encounter turbulence. And sometimes hailstones.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Brian Bergman, who flies a one-engine cloud-seeding Piper
Comanche stationed in Lakin, points to numerous dents on his
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't advise pilots to do this kind of flying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The program typically sees about one airplane a year lose a
windshield to hail.
</P>
<P>
   But Bergman has returned to the program year after year. ``It's
very rewarding,'' he said. ``It feels good to help the local
farmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Water Office, a state agency, considers the program
worthwhile enough to contribute $360,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Darrel Eklund, environmental scientist for the office, studied
long-term hail damage in various western Kansas counties.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in a recent issue of the Journal of Weather
Modification, Eklund estimated that hail damage to crops in six
counties covered by the weather-modification area decreased 27
percent. Estimated benefits were about $4 million a year, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't sure the airplanes prevent hail.
</P>
<P>
   An extensive study, financed mostly by the National Science
Foundation, seeded clouds in northeast Colorado in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   With the results inconclusive, the study ended ahead of schedule
because scientists discovered they couldn't show that seeding
suppressed hail.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Doswell, a research scientist for the National Severe
Storms Laboratory in Norman, Okla., said the weather-modification
industry hasn't proved itself effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have considerable concern about the wisdom of investing
taxpayer resources in this type of program,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when the Kansas program suggested its cloud seeding
may have defused the beginnings of a tornado, Doswell responded
sharply: ``Nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of cloud seeding has broken out in northwest Kansas,
where areas joined the weather modification program in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can prove anything on either side of it,'' said Keith
Downing, who heads a group called Citizens for Natural Weather and
farms 3,000 acres northwest of Colby, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers allied with Downing contend that cloud seeding has
reduced rainfall, although they don't offer studies to substantiate
the claim. They demanded an election over the issue. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
