<HEADLINE>
MCDONALD'S HEADS TO COURT OVER A BURGER KING MEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (js) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's just the sort of thing parents frown on _ a food fight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the latest twist in the never-ending Battle of the
Burgers, McDonald's is suing its archrival, Burger King, saying its
Big Kid's Meal food-and-toy combination is essentially a knock-off
product.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, filed June 30 in federal court in Detroit,
McDonald's Corp. said that packaging and promotional material for
Burger King's meal, which the company introduced last month, was
too similar to a logo and product of the same name that McDonald's
introduced for a limited time in Detroit last year. The only
difference is one consumers may well overlook: Burger King uses an
apostrophe in ``Kid's''; McDonald's does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a school assignment, we think Burger King would
get an F for plagiarism,'' Charles Ebeling, a spokesman for
McDonald's, said.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King had two words for its biggest competitor: grow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has a kid's meal program,'' said Richard Taylor, vice
president for marketing at Burger King, a unit of the London-based
Diageo PLC. ``You can bet we'll defend our right to use this name
vigorously.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Burger King promotion, youngsters can get a
combination of a regular-size meal and toy, currently tied to the
recently released movie ``Wild Wild West.'' The McDonald's meal,
which the company said represented an investment of more than
$500,000, came with a regular-size meal and a coupon booklet to be
used at an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's said that it had filed to register the Big Kids Meal
phrase and logo as a trademark and that the application was
pending. But Burger King contends that the phrase is generic.
</P>
<P>
   A burger-and-treat combination has become serious business.
Youngsters have been known to ditch the food and go straight for
the Teenie Beanie Babies in a Happy Meal or beg parents to pull in
to a Burger King for an action figure in a box. The Big Kid's Meal
is intended to lure somewhat older customers.
</P>
<P>
   The current battle is the latest in a war that will almost
certainly wage on. The companies have traded barbs over which chain
has the tastiest fries and the best cooking system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Burger King, which makes the Whopper, introduced the
Big King, calling it ``a bigger, better Big Mac.'' And last year
McDonald's revamped its kitchens with a new cooking system that it
says produces the freshest fast food available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
