<SLUG> BC-SOC-REMATCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CLOSES GAP ON U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There used to be a time in this country when our men's Olympic
basketball team was invincible _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1980, no one could touch the United States in the sport,
save for that incredible display of highway robbery suffered
against the Soviet Union _ also known as the gold-medal game at the
1972 Summer Games in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Things eventually changed and the rest of the world caught up,
forcing America to assemble a ``Dream Team'' to restore order and
regain supremacy in a sport it invented.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women's soccer team had a similarly untouchable nature
for most of this decade since the inaugural Women's World Cup in
1991. But the gap it once held over the rest of the world has
closed considerably as sexual stereotypes have begun to slowly die
down and female soccer is receiving the support it needs in other
traditionally male-dominated societies.
</P>
<P>
   One team that has been with the U.S. nearly every step of the
way in this evolution has been China, and it is no coincidence the
two will face each other in the 1999 tournament final at the Rose
Bowl on Saturday. The rivalry has been one of the best, although
the Americans have come out on top in almost every major
competition when the teams have met.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese must be bitter toward us,'' said U.S. forward
Tiffeny Milbrett. ``Until this year, every major competition since
1995 has always gone our way. They must think, `God, we've got to
get this thorn out of our side.'''
</P>
<P>
   China lost the Olympic gold medal to the U.S. in 1996 and it
lost the Goodwill Games to the Americans last summer. But is the
tide finally turning for the Chinese? Recent results seem to point
in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   China has captured two of the past three meetings against the
U.S., including a victory in the Algarve Cup in Portugal in March,
its first major triumph. In April, the teams split friendlies
played in the U.S. as China snapped the Americans' home-soil
winning streak at 50 games with a 2-1 win at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got away from our game plan a bit and we were sending
everyone forward at the end,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said at the
time. ``We can learn a lot from this game to take with us into the
World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the U.S. took its coach's words to heart in making it
to this point, but the players remain cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just goes to show that anything can happen when two of
the best teams in the world play,'' said U.S. midfielder Kristine
Lilly. ``Great teams make great things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of the three meetings this calendar year _ all 2-1
results, incidentally _ the U.S. has outshot China every time. In
contrast, China seems to have always made the most of its chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hate to lose any match, but this is a great tournament with
great teams,'' U.S. defender Carla Overbeck said at the time about
the Algarve Cup. ``We have to look at the big picture, and the most
important time to win is in June and July at the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The time has arrived.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
