<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNCLAIMED-MONEY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS WORKS TO TRACK DOWN OWNERS OF UNCLAIMED MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. _ Kansas Treasurer Tim Shallenburger is having the
time of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He's giving away money, and he couldn't be happier about it,
unless, of course, he could give away even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great fun,'' said Shallenburger, a former speaker of the
Kansas House. He moved into the treasurer's office in January after
winning the post in last fall's election.
</P>
<P>
   The great giveaway is the bottom line of the state's
unclaimed-property law.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of unclaimed money, such as banks, utilities, insurance
companies and governments, are required to send it to the
treasurer's office once the accounts are determined to be dormant.
</P>
<P>
   The state is charged with holding it until the rightful owners
turn up. But rather than just wait, the treasurer has decided his
office should be working hard to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Shallenburger has about $80 million that belongs to
about 375,000 people. Some are no longer living, and the search is
on for their heirs. Others are easy to find, and they are getting
their money back.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a Leawood man is on the verge of receiving a check
for more than $95,000. That is money he had no idea was his. It
came from his late father's estate but somehow never found its way
into the initial settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger tracked the man down and phoned him with the good
news. An official presentation could come as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   On the treasurer's desk are lists of Kansans who are entitled to
money the state is holding. Shallenburger spends a little of each
day tracking down the missing people.
</P>
<P>
   ``As best I can determine, there's been a considerable effort in
the past to advertise that we had it, but no effort to try to find
who it belongs to,'' he said. ``No one wanted to spend the
resources to do more than say, `Here's what we've got.' ''
</P>
<P>
   People said they did not have time to spend on the search, the
treasurer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided we'd make time to do it,'' Shallenburger said.
</P>
<P>
   The money that is not returned is invested by the state, which
retains the interest it earns.
</P>
<P>
   The man who leads the program is former state Rep. Dennis Wilson
of Overland Park. He has been banging on a few doors in Mission
Hills and Overland Park in his efforts to return some sizable
amounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month his division returned about $700,000. He said that
was about three times more than had ever been returned in a single
month.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson says the chances are between one in 10 and one in 20 that
you or people you know are entitled to a check from the treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the phone calls, the treasurer's office has other ways
of finding the money's owners.
</P>
<P>
   There's the Cash Caravan _ a motor home with computers linked to
the list of names of people entitled to money the state holds.
</P>
<P>
   The motor home is driven to county fairs, and people stop by to
see whether their names are on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Computer systems also are taken to the State Fair in Hutchinson.
Some large companies are audited to see whether they have money
that should be forwarded. A credit bureau has been used to track
down some Kansans.
</P>
<P>
   Shallenburger said he learned how to track people when he was a
repo man for a bank in Baxter Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty easy,'' he said. ``Everyone is out there
somewhere. Most people can be found with three phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the people Shallenburger calls can't believe the good
news. They have to be convinced.
</P>
<P>
   An Overland Park woman got a call telling her the state was
holding $77,600 from an old stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation went something like this, Shallenburger
recalled:
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her who I was, and the first thing she said was, `Are
you a Republican or a Democrat?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm a Republican if it makes a difference.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I don't give to Democrats. How much do you want?' I
said, `I don't want anything. We have some money for you.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Oh, yeah, sure you do.'''
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't believe it and asked for Shallenburger's phone
number. She called him back to double-check.
</P>
<P>
   ```I'll believe it when I see it,''' Shallenburger said she told
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I sent the check out, I sent her a note and said, `You
can see it. Now believe it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0042EDT &QL; 
