<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVE MONEY, DON'T MAKE HANFORD SAFE FOR HUMAN HABITATION, REPORT
URGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If anybody out there has been thinking about
someday building a nice waterfront home amid the sand, sagebrush
and nuclear waste at the Hanford Nuclear Reservation, a top federal
official has some advice: Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy's inspector general is urging his
agency to drop plans to clean up the most scenic portion of Hanford
_ the stretch along the Columbia River _ to make it habitable for
human beings. People are never going to live there, the inspector
general says, and the Energy Department could save money by
acknowledging as much.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion issued in a report drew a fast and furious
reaction from Washington state and federal officials, as well as
environmentalists. The Energy Department late Wednesday seemed to
be backing away from a part of the report indicating that the
agency agreed with the inspector general's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a key portion of the Hanford reservation, which is
560 square miles acquired by the federal government in 1943 and
used to produce plutonium for the world's first atomic weapons.
Plutonium production was phased out by 1987, and the highly
contaminated site is now home to the world's largest environmental
cleanup project, with radioactive and hazardous waste that the
Energy Department expects to spend 50 years and $100 billion
cleaning up.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas at Hanford are expected to be contaminated forever,
while others will be usable only for industrial parks. But cleanup
advocates have hoped that part of the stretch along the river, the
so-called 100 Area once used for agriculture, will be suitable
someday for farming or rural housing.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Inspector General Gregory Friedman says that is not
realistic. He said all projected uses for the area are
non-residential, such as recreation and wildlife preservation, and
that the Energy Department is wasting money trying to make the land
suitable for people to live on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuing to support cleanup objectives that are inconsistent
with projected land uses unnecessarily increases restoration
costs,'' Friedman wrote. ``Changing the cleanup objective from
residential to industrial for just three waste sites within the 100
Area would reduce the cleanup cost from $85.5 million to $73.4
million, a 14.2 percent reduction. Other cost reductions are also
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Friedman reported that the Department of Energy had
concurred with his recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   His report was not well-received.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to leave all the waste along the Columbia River,
cover it with soil, and leave it there for all time,'' said Doug
Sherwood, Hanford project manager for the Environmental Protection
Agency, who said the stretch of Hanford along the river should be
clean enough for rural residential use. ``Yes, you can save a lot
of money by not doing any cleanup, but does that really mean
cleanup? That's just not acceptable to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Pollett, executive director of the watchdog organization
Heart of America Northwest, also was incensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one in a long line of highly political efforts by the
inspector general to assist the agenda of people who do not want
the area alongside the Columbia River to be cleaned up, as required
by state and federal cleanup laws,'' Pollett said. ``The Department
of Energy is trying to avoid its commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sheryl Hutchison, a spokeswoman for the state Department of
Ecology, said she was ``flabbergasted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this report doesn't indicate a desire by the feds to
walk away from their cleanup obligation, because it's an atrocious
mess they have out there, and we're trying hard to get it back in
shape for human use and fish recovery,'' she said. ``There isn't
too high a cleanup standard to set when you're talking about the
Columbia River and the people of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials said the inspector general
mischaracterized their reaction when he wrote that ``Richland
concurred with the recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see our cleanup changing,'' said Linda Bauer,
assistant manager for environmental restoration at the Energy
Department. ``In the near-term, we're doing the right kind of
cleanup out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Holten, the director of remedial projects at the Energy
Department, agreed, saying: ``We are very proud of the cleanup
activities we've got going out there right now. This talks about
something that might happen in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
