<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-LOCOMOTIVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY TO SPEND $100 MILLION ON NEW
LOCOMOTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City Southern Railway has placed a
$100 million order for 50 new locomotives, the biggest one-time
purchase of locomotives in the railroad's history.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern said Wednesday that it would buy the
machines from GE Transportation Systems, a General Electric Co.
subsidiary. The locomotives are expected to be delivered in
November and December.
</P>
<P>
   GE Transportation also will build a maintenance facility next to
Kansas City Southern's rail yard in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern employees will do most of the maintenance
work there, but a few GE technicians also will occupy the facility,
said Kathy Simpson, a Kansas City Southern spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern said it was buying the equipment in
anticipation of growth from its rail network, which it calls the
NAFTA Railway. NAFTA is an acronym for the North American Free
Trade Agreement, which was implemented to eliminate trade barriers
among the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Through acquisitions, joint ventures and alliances, Kansas City
Southern has created a rail line that runs from Canada to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Southern has 450 locomotives now. It last acquired
locomotives in 1991. The new ones are considered among the most
advanced produced by GE Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upgrading our locomotive fleet will help us provide North
American shippers with higher standards of service while achieving
substantial operational efficiencies,'' said Michael R. Haverty,
the railroad company's president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   GE Transportation officials said the new machines had nearly
twice the hauling capacity of Kansas City Southern's older models.
In addition, the railroad will spend less on fuel consumption and
maintenance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
