A2649 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      07-08 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S DRESS CODE IS A SHOCK TO SOME EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Memo to clothing stores around the new Sprint
office campus: Stock up on men's dress slacks. There will be
noontime runs on your inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Sprint dress code tempest, currently whirling in
the scattered offices of the Kansas City area's largest corporate
employer, may subside by the time thousands of workers move to the
new spread.
</P>
<P>
   The furor concerns a companywide ``Sprint Dress Policy'' memo.
For the most part, it clarifies a code already followed at the
current headquarters. But for thousands of Sprint employees in
buildings elsewhere, the policy was a shock.
</P>
<P>
   In many Sprint offices, Dockers rule. The dress is ``business
casual'' every day. Some offices even have jeans days on Fridays.
The newly disseminated policy seems to some employees to be out of
touch with current Sprint reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people view business casual dress as a job benefit,''
said one Sprint worker. ``I certainly believe that I am more
productive because it allows for a more relaxed work environment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bureau of National Affairs, 79 percent of
employers surveyed say casual dress improves employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the worker said, why ``dress for success'' if you
have no aspirations about rising in management ranks and no
customer contact with outside business people?
</P>
<P>
   Some workers say they'll have to spend a lot of money to upgrade
their wardrobes _ and that's no job benefit. It's tantamount to a
pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   A Sprint spokeswoman says that the policy intends to create a
professional image for the new campus and that cotton slacks
``don't promote the type of corporate image Sprint strives for.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees say they hope the policy withers away before they
have to go shopping. Meanwhile, the policy says what attire is
inappropriate at Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The no-nos: T-shirts, sweat shirts, jeans, cotton slacks, sweat
pants, leggings, shorts, miniskirts, sundresses, athletic shoes,
sandals, going without socks or hose, denim clothing, shirts with
letters or logos (except for occasionally sanctioned Sprint
promotions), and anything soiled or frayed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pretty reasonable list. You can make a strong case that,
according to contemporary standards, anyone wearing most of the
above items would look less professional than someone wearing a
business suit or hose and heels.
</P>
<P>
   The wicket gets sticky, though, when policies dictate things
that are unenforceable. For example, what is a sundress? Is it any
sleeveless dress? It it a thin-strapped dress? Is it a
thin-strapped, low-necklined dress?
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to do the measuring? Who's going to decide whether
she's wearing a banned miniskirt or a fashionably short suit skirt?
</P>
<P>
   Professional standards are great, and the only way they can work
is if they're precisely detailed. But I wonder about the
Dockers-type ban. Will there be label or pocket checks? There's an
exceedingly fine line between some dress slacks and some cotton
casual slacks. I'd suggest that Sprint honchos not worry about the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   I also would suggest that pressure-cooker jobs in
pressure-cooker industries need productive, satisfied workers. And
I'd let the Docker debacle fade real fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2650 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ALLSTARS-     07-08 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ALL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMERMAN A SURPRISE ALL-STAR
</HEADLINE>
 STARS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Seattle manager Lou Piniella recently
described right-hander Jeff Zimmerman as ``the difference in the AL
West.''
</P>
<P>
   New York manager Joe Torre recognized Zimmerman's impact
Wednesday by selecting the Rangers middle reliever to the American
League roster for the 1999 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, the organization's 26-year-old rookie and poster boy
for perseverance, will be accompanied by Rangers closer John
Wetteland and first baseman/designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro, whom
Torre also chose to represent the league in the annual classic
Tuesday at Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, Wetteland and Palmeiro will join catcher Ivan
Rodriguez, the Rangers' only starter after the league announced
results of fans' balloting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comprehend it,'' Zimmerman said. ``I'm a middle
reliever. We're supposed to be the bottom feeders of the baseball
world, so this is ultimate pinnacle for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's selection could be described as highly irregular.
The TCU product bucked the system to become only the fourth pitcher
with no starts and fewer than five saves to be selected an
All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been a whole lot of guys do what he's done or
the way he's done it,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman pitched 2 1/3 scoreless innings for his eighth victory
in as many decisions as the Rangers defeated Oakland, 7-4,
Wednesday. Zimmerman has the best earned-run average (0.89) and
lowest opponents' batting average (.110) among major-league
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most exciting part for me is that he was able to make
history in a season he's defined as historical,'' Wetteland said.
``You couldn't ask for it to happen to a better guy, and you know
he's going to take it well. Nothing would go to that guy's head.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland will make his third All-Star Game appearance despite
undergoing arthroscopic surgery in October to remove a bone spur
and chip from his right elbow. Opponents' .243 batting average and
Wetteland's 4.04 ERA suggest that the right-hander might not be as
dominant as in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not really over that,'' Wetteland said of the elbow
injury. ``I still haven't pitched the way I'm capable of doing day
in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wetteland converted his major-league-best 26th
save in 30 opportunities with a scoreless ninth inning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro underwent arthroscopic surgery Feb. 10 and March 7 to
remove torn cartilage from his right knee, but the left-handed
power hitter responded favorably to earn his fourth All-Star
selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought my knee would be a problem as far as my
offense,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro will begin the series in San Diego this weekend hitting
.351 with 20 home runs and 73 runs batted in to join Cleveland
right fielder Manny Ramirez as the league's only players to rank
among the top 10 in all three triple crown categories. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
