<HEADLINE>
DEALS WON'T COME EASILY FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Dodgers reached the 81-game halfway point of the
season Tuesday and were 11 games under .500, their worst mark since
1979.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of balance in the lineup has become the focal point for
the National League's worst hitting team and has led to speculation
the Dodgers will unload one of their right-handed bats, most likely
Eric Karros, or possibly either pitchers Ismael Valdes or Darren
Dreifort, if a left-handed bat becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   There's even talk of teams looking for speed trying to acquire
second baseman and leadoff man Eric Young, who's third in the NL
with 32 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   The talk will be bantered around a lot with the July 31
nonwaiver trading deadline approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I anticipate us doing something?'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said Wednesday. ``Probably not.''
</P>
<P>
   However, much will tell in how the Dodgers do during the next
three weeks, whether they play better baseball and try to climb
back into the wild-card race before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends in three weeks where we're at and what we're trying
to do,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the problem is the contract situation this regime
inherited. The Dodgers are locked in long term for nearly every
player who would have significant value on the trade market. That
makes unloading players difficult.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to trying to bring in the big left-handed bat, the
Dodgers haven't been willing to part with their young players,
particularly catcher Angel Pena and third baseman Adrian Beltre.
They also don't have many top-flight prospects above Single-A level
to deal. Therefore, teams aren't interested in dealing impact
players to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, much like the flexibility Johnson lacks in making out his
lineup card, Malone has restrictions in trying to work a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as easy to make trades as it used to be,'' Malone
said. ``It's more involved. There's limited prospects out there,
financial implications with contracts. I work at it every day to
see what other clubs are doing and what options are there, and how
we can make ourselves better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Johnson's made no secret as to wanting a left-hander in
the middle of his lineup _ he's tried Devon White, Todd Hundley and
Todd Hollandsworth _ he said he won't use that as an excuse as to
why the team is playing dismally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we can do . . . what's available,'' Johnson
said. ``(Karros) has probably been as productive as any other guy
on the club. Whether they're easy matchups or not, Eric's done a
good job. What I saw before is, I'd like it to be a little more
challenging for the opposition (with matchups).''
</P>
<P>
   Brown pushed up: Since staff ace Kevin Brown wasn't selected to
the All-Star Game, Johnson said his immediate plans call for Brown
to start against Anaheim in the series opener following the
All-Star break. That will keep him on four days rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would work better to (have Brown) get Arizona twice if he
throws the first day back,'' Johnson said, alluding to a pair of
series with the Diamondbacks in late July.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said the right-handed Valdes will probably work his
way into the No. 2 spot in the Dodgers' rotation after the All-Star
break and pitch next Friday against Anaheim while Chan Ho Park
drops to No. 3 and ends the series Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Trying anything: Johnson continues to fiddle with the lineup to
get the sickly offense going. A day after resting Karros, who
usually demolishes Coors Field pitching, he sat Raul Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who despises having days off, entered the series
hitting .302 with seven homers and 24 RBI at Coors Field. But he's
mired in a powerless slump in which he hasn't homered in 84
at-bats. He has one homer in his last 122 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, meanwhile, returned to the lineup after resting so
Johnson could get Hollandsworth's bat into the mix. Karros, who was
1 for 4 in the opener, is a lifetime .363 hitter at Coors Field.
He's hit 13 homers and driven in 34 runs here.
</P>
<P>
   FYI: Dodgers trainer Charlie Strasser said results of Tripp
Cromer's examination for an irregular heartbeat might not be
available until the weekend. Cromer returned to Los Angeles before
Tuesday's game with Colorado after being diagnosed with the
ailment. . . . Right-hander Antonio Osuna, who had elbow surgery in
May, threw 19 pitches in one perfect inning in a rehab stint for
Single-A San Bernardino against High Desert. It was Osuna's first
game action since the surgery. The Dodgers are hopeful he'll return
after the All-Star break. . . . Rockies right fielder Larry Walker
returned after missing one game with flu-like symptoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
