<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY AGREES TO IDEA OF AGENCY ON NUCLEAR WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.M., Alaska, Texas, Tenn.)  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said Wednesday
that he would work with Congress to establish a more independent
nuclear weapons program as a remedy for security problems, but key
details of the proposed reorganization are still in dispute,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson altered his previous position and said he would
consider a semi-autonomous program within his department. ``I'm
ready to move on it,'' he said, adding that he would seek
bipartisan agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's change in position was first reported in Thursday's
editions of the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   But even Richardson's acceptance of the idea may not resolve the
issue. Some House Republicans have demanded creating a wholly
autonomous agency, or moving the nuclear weapons work to the
Pentagon in response to allegations that China obtained weapons
secrets from one of the Energy Department's laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republican senators, Pete Domenici of New Mexico, Jon Kyl
of Arizona and Frank Murkowski of Alaska, have been pushing for
reorganization. But Richardson has resisted changes that would
remove the weapons program from his control.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial issue _ and one on which there is no agreement with
Congress _ is whether the department's counter-intelligence and
security chiefs would report to the head of the new weapons
program, as some Republicans would like, or to the energy
secretary, as Richardson wants. Richardson has maintained that
having those officials report to the head of the weapons programs
would create conflicts and would not benefit security.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a semi-autonomous agency, its definition still
under negotiation, was proposed in a report issued in mid-June by
President Clinton's Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board, but
Richardson had been resisting. ``I hate the `agency' word,'' he
said at a Senate hearing on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   The plan now under discussion, which would create an Agency for
Nuclear Stewardship, would be headed by an undersecretary.
</P>
<P>
   It would include the three main weapons laboratories, Los
Alamos, Sandia and Lawrence Livermore; the weapons-assembly
operations at Pantex, in Amarillo, Texas, and at Oak Ridge, Tenn.;
the naval nuclear propulsion program, and various non-proliferation
and bomb-fuel storage programs. These last two barely existed when
the department was formed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson would like the undersecretary to report to him. But
focusing the program under the control of one high-ranking official
would improve accountability, department officials believe.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson has argued in the last few weeks that he has already
undertaken reforms to improve security, including naming a
``security czar,'' Eugene E. Habiger, a retired four-star Air Force
general.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Energy Department's establishment, it has had an
office of Defense Programs, which oversees weapons production, and
reports to an assistant secretary of energy.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department has a surplus of bomb-grade uranium and
plutonium, which it is no longer producing. It is trying to safely
store the excess material until it can dispose of it, and help the
Russians do the same with theirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
