<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH POISED TO RESHAPE NHRA'S LANDSCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minus the anticipated sizzle, we have reached the halfway point
of the NHRA Winston Drag Racing Series' 25th anniversary season.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a drag racing fan, but what is new and different about this
National Hot Rod Association season? The 4.60-second quarter-mile
pass has become mandatory just to be a player, and speeds in excess
of 320 mph also are routine. How many ways can we get excited about
the vagaries of the five-disc clutch, or a Top Fuel or Funny Car
engine that actually completes a pass with all eight cylinders
firing?
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the contrived format that will pit Top Fuel
dragsters against Funny Cars at the inaugural Winston No Bull
Showdown this weekend, the points races have fallen into too many
predictable patterns. The NHRA's lack of a fan-friendly live TV
package also has tested the resolve of even the most diehard
devotee.
</P>
<P>
   It is against this background that NHRA officials and
motorsports mogul Bruton Smith are preparing what is being billed
as a true all-star event at the reinvented Bristol (Tenn.) Dragway.
Beginning with qualifications tonight and concluding with Saturday
night's finals _ live on ESPN! _ 64 of drag racing's best will
compete at Smith's version of Thunder Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and his Speedway Motorsports Inc. are best-known for their
involvement in NASCAR's Winston Cup Series. Smith owns six tracks,
including Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, that currently play
host to nine Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith's Sears Point Raceway in Sonoma, Calif., also is a
regular stop on the NHRA schedule. His revamping of Bristol Dragway
is the culmination of a $15 million project Smith and general
manager Jeff Byrd believe will convince NHRA officials to grant
them one _ two would be better _ national events for the facility.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 seats are in place at Bristol for this
non-points event. Additionally, a new four-story tower featuring 21
luxury suites, a control room, conference room and awning-covered
observation deck will be available to approximately another 800
occupants. A $500,000 Musco lighting system, another Smith staple,
will allow the drag cars to run at night.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's expanding interest in NHRA drag racing hardly ends
there. On July 20, the NHRA's brass plans to assemble in Las Vegas
to announce that Smith's LVMS will be added to the national event
calendar in 2000. Engineer Devin Horihan, who designed the new
Bristol Dragway, will oversee a similar project at Las Vegas on a
site that currently is a quarter-mile gravel pit.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, industry sources say that Houston Raceway Park in
Baytown will lose its spring NHRA event to accommodate Smith's
newest state-of-the-sport facility in Vegas _ and all those SMI
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``NHRA is not Winston Cup. But nothing else is either,'' said
Chris Powell, executive vice president and general manager of Las
Vegas Motor Speedway. ``I think you'll find that Bruton's ability
to be a `visionary' is not restricted to stock cars. You'll learn
more about that in the next few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   We await the details. Because at halfway, the NHRA needs all the
sizzle Smith can serve up.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON... STEWART MARKS `ARRIVAL' WITH SIGNATURE WHEELS
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Tony Stewart has arrived as a NASCAR Winston Cup driver,
and he didn't need to consult the top-10 points standings or hear
it from team owner Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Nation _ the nomadic fans who follow the series from
racetrack to racetrack _ bestowed that honor upon Stewart at the
Daytona International Speedway last week. Like all those who either
work or ``reside'' in the sprawling infield at DIS during race
week, Stewart had to drive through the tunnel under Turn 4 while
preparing for the Pepsi 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came through the tunnel the other day and turned right to
come towards the garage area,'' Stewart said, ``and there was an
orange school bus with `Home Depot and 20, Tony Stewart and Joe
Gibbs Racing.' And I thought, `I've arrived.' When a school bus in
the infield is painted up in my colors, I'm a Winston Cup driver
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, teammate to native Texan Bobby Labonte, has been
sensational during the season's first half. After 17 races, Stewart
has booked four top-five and nine top-10 finishes and a single Did
Not Finish (DNF). In comparison, three-time and reigning Cup
champion Jeff Gordon has suffered through four DNFs _ results that
basically have doomed his chances of a repeat title.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-place Gordon is only 19 points ahead of Stewart as the
tour cranks up for the Jiffy Lube 300 at New Hampshire
International Speedway this weekend. This will be the series' first
visit to Loudon, N.H., in 1999, although Stewart won on the flat
1.058-mile track en route to the Pep Boys Indy Racing League title
in 1997. And Stewart finished second in the NASCAR Busch Grand
National Series race at NHIS last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart and crew chief Greg Zipadelli are more excited about
returning to the tracks where they already have raced this season
in their Pontiac Grand Prix, and now have a baseline for setups.
</P>
<P>
   And what about his ``inevitable'' first Cup victory?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what is going to happen,'' said Stewart, 28. ``It
means more to me to finish in the top five three or four weeks in a
row than it does to win one week and finish 30th the next week and
crash the week after that. You guys \Rthe media\S are more antsy
about me winning a race than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS CREW CHIEF FINED
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Scott Eggleston, who was paired with Sterling Marlin
at Sabco Racing on June 2, has been fined $50,000 for a rules
violation detected before the NASCAR Winston Cup Pepsi 400 at
Daytona International Speedway last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston, 37, also has been placed on probation until Oct. 20,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors found an illegal insert in the intake manifold of
Marlin's No. 40 Coors Light Chevrolet Monte Carlo. Modifications to
the intake manifold are particularly frowned upon at the 2.5-mile
DIS, one of the two tracks where the cars compete with carburetor
restrictor plates to reduce speeds in the name of safety. That's
why the fine is so severe.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sullivan, NASCAR's manager of communications, said Marlin's
car raced with an approved manifold Saturday night. And Marlin
finished 12th. MARTIN HAS SURGERY
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup star Mark Martin underwent surgery Wednesday in New
Smyrna Beach, Fla., to repair a broken tibia plateau in his left
knee. Martin suffered the injury during an accident while
practicing Friday at the Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin plans to wear a leg brace that will allow him to drive
the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus at New Hampshire International
Speedway this weekend. Martin, who also fractured his wrist in the
crash, plans to have NASCAR Busch Grand National regular Matt
Kenseth standing by as a relief driver. HILL SEEKS SPONSOR
</P>
<P>
   Texan Eddie Hill is 63, and searching for a new primary sponsor
for his NHRA Top Fuel team for 2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Pennzoil officials announced last week they would not renew the
one-year contract signed with Hill on Jan. 11. Pennzoil has
sponsored Hill for 11 consecutive years, including his
championship-winning season of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he and wife Ercie, whose shop is located in Wichita
Falls, are not considering retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel on the brink of another breakthrough on the
racetrack,'' Hill said. ``Frankly, the concept of retirement
frightens me more than anything that could go wrong on the
racetrack.'' LAST LAPS
</P>
<P>
   _ Juan Montoya could tie Nigel Mansell's CART FedEx Series
rookie record of five victories in the Texaco/Havoline 200 at Road
America in Elkhart Lake, Wis., on Sunday. Mansell set the record in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ His start in Sunday's race will be the 264th of Al Unser Jr.'s
CART career, tying him with Bobby Rahal for first place on the
all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ford's NASCAR Winston Cup teams are scheduled to test at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway Tuesday and Wednesday. GM teams are
booked for July 19-20 at IMS, in anticipation of the Brickyard 400
on Aug. 7. LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can become the poster boy for the AARP.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Eddie Hill, 63, on his decision to keep drag racing in 2000
and beyond.
