<SLUG> BC-MINORITIES-MEDIA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN HALF OF MINORITY JOURNALISTS EXPECT TO LEAVE NEWSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HEATH FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At a time newspaper editors are facing their
industry's failure to reach ambitious year 2000 minority hiring
goals, a new survey shows that more than half of the journalists of
color are planning to leave the profession.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists questioned in a Freedom Forum survey are not
planning their exits because they're dissatisfied with their
prospects in daily newspapering _ 77 percent rated their chances
for advancement as excellent or good.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, 41 percent said they plan to leave within five
years. A total of 55 percent said they plan to leave the newspaper
business altogether. And their top-ranked reason for moving on was
their ``interest in another field of work.'' Fiction writing,
teaching and business careers were named as the most enticing
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the 200 blacks, 152 Asians and 100 Hispanics questioned said
there are things that editors could do to get them to stay: better
hours, improved pay, and more opportunities for professional
development. (The surveys from 15 Native American participants were
not included because they were not considered statistically
meaningful.)
</P>
<P>
   Robert Giles, executive director of the Freedom Forum's Media
Studies Center in New York, said the survey would help crystallize
for editors around the country how crucial holding onto the
minorities already in their newsrooms is if they hope to reach
their diversity goals.
</P>
<P>
   Giles released the survey results at a news conference in
Seattle Wednesday as part of the UNITY '99 conference, a national
meeting of minority journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the American Society of Newspaper Editors (ASNE) made
a controversial decision to adjust its goal of having the nation's
newsrooms reflect the ethnic diversity of the country by the year
2000 to 2025. The 2000 goal was set in 1978, when minorities
accounted for only 4 percent of the newsroom employees.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two decades the industry has taken huge strides in
increasing the diversity of its work force. But in recent years
some of those gains have been reversed even as the U.S. population
becomes increasingly diverse.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, minorities make up about 28 percent of the
population. But according to an ASNE January census, the number of
minority newspaper journalists crept up only slightly in 1998,
increasing 1.5 percent so that people of color now make up 11.5
percent of newsroom employees.
</P>
<P>
   In radio and television newsrooms, minority journalists have
fared somewhat better. A survey by the Radio &AMP; Television News
Directors Association this year found that minorities make up 19
percent of newsroom staff and 11 percent of radio staff.
</P>
<P>
   While those numbers are lower than they were a year ago,
association President Barbara Cochran said the number of minorities
in management track positions has increased greatly in the past
three years. For instance, today 18 percent of all assistant news
directors are minorities, compared with 10 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there are efforts under way to revitalize the drive
for bringing more people of color into journalism. ASNE and another
editors' association, the Associated Press Managing Editors
Association, are sponsoring a Time Out for Accuracy and Diversity
initiative. The effort's core premise is that newspapers are
incapable of accurately reflecting the diversity in their
communities if newsrooms don't.
</P>
<P>
   Since the initiative's inception, 2000 journalists in 200
newsrooms have participated in discussions about how to create a
staff that mirrors the variety in race, genders, sexual
orientation, age, class, and religious and political affiliations
in the community so their news coverage can be more balanced and
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   David Yarnold, executive editor of the San Jose Mercury News who
is leading the effort, said by reframing the issue, he is hoping
newspapers will re-examine their hiring for the sake of higher
quality journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just common sense'' that a diverse staff will ``make
coverage richer and deeper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giles said it's obvious newspapers need to do a more exhaustive
job of sparking minorities' interest in journalism early on through
internships, and then holding onto to them with mentoring programs.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the main complaints by journalists of color _
burnout, long hours and poor pay _ are shared by many in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   But he guessed there are some challenges minority journalists
don't share with whites. For instance, 77 percent of the minorities
surveyed said they have to work harder than their white
counterparts to get ahead. Among black journalists, the sentiment
was especially high _ 90 percent either strongly agreed or somewhat
agreed they had to work harder, compared with 67 percent of Asians
and 66 percent of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Giles suggested that black journalists' higher frustration
reflects the fact that African Americans began advocating 30 years
ago for better representation and may be more weary than other
groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
