<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-MALLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES HOT AT MALLS IN SAN FERNANDO VALLEY, MADE FAMOUS BY `VALLEY
GIRL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FERNANDO VALLEY _ If you want proof that the San Fernando
Valley's economy is humming, look no farther than its malls.
</P>
<P>
   Cash registers at the Valley area's malls are as hot as the
weather, with sales increasing up to 10 percent during the first
five months of 1999 compared with the same period last year. That's
considerably higher than either the national or state averages and
a testimony to the strength of the local economy and its mall
culture, which was made famous _ some might say infamous _ by the
1980s ``Valley Girl'' pop fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a retailer can't make money in this environment, they can't
make money, period,'' said Richard Giss, partner with the trade
retail services group at accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Malls across the region have seen healthy sales increases among
stores open at least a year. That measure _ known as store-to-store
in the retail industry _ is the one traditionally used by analysts
to gauge the health of the retail scene.
</P>
<P>
   Sales increased 6 percent at Fashion Square Sherman Oaks, 6.9
percent at the Valencia Town Center in Santa Clarita, 7.1 percent
at the Glendale Galleria, 8 percent at The Oaks mall in Thousand
Oaks and at the Northridge Fashion Center, and 10.5 percent at the
Panorama Mall in Panorama City.
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York City-based International Council of
Shopping Centers, malls across the nation saw an average 2.2
percent increase and in California a 5.1 percent jump through
April, the most recent figures available.
</P>
<P>
   Local mall representatives attribute their success to both the
strong economy and their individual efforts to lure more customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, retail is back on the rise,'' said Alison DiLeva,
Fashion Square's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   The Sherman Oaks mall hopes to build its foot traffic by luring
shoppers who otherwise might go to places like the Century City
Shopping Center &AMP; Marketplace and the Beverly Center outside the
Valley as well as to the Glendale Galleria, the Westfield
Shoppingtown Topanga Plaza in Canoga Park and Westfield
Shoppingtown Promenade in Woodland Hills, and the Northridge
Fashion Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a customer that is fashion-conscious that we're
trying to reach here,'' DiLeva said. ``We're really trying to pull
more upscale tenants in, but we're also at an achievable price _
we're not trying to be Rodeo Drive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thousand Oaks, some retailers at The Oaks have upgraded their
merchandise and looks, resulting in greater sales, said mall
general manager Becky Bresson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of tenants have upgraded their merchandise, adding
new product to stay fresh and current,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the factors that have pushed the Panorama Mall past the 10
percent mark are the two-story Wal-Mart, which opened May 21, 1998,
in a space once occupied by The Broadway, and a strong marketing
program by La Curacao, a department store catering mainly to
Latinos, said Louise Marquez, the 66-store center's general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Panorama Mall has benefited from The Plant, the
commercial/industrial center at the old General Motors site nearby,
where stores began opening in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think The Plant has added new traffic to the community at
large,'' Marquez said. ``It's typically what a big-box provider
will do. It's an enhancement to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Clarita, promotional efforts and the booming Santa
Clarita Valley's economy have pushed the Valencia Town Center to
its 6.9 percent gain, said general manager Charles Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I think the shopping center as a whole is something that
the community has taken under their wing, and (they) have enjoyed
coming here,'' Sullivan said. ``We're just trying to make it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, new businesses are moving in and office vacancies
surrounding the Galleria are low, said Annette Bethers, senior
marketing director for the 260-store shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the mall gets healthy traffic from the lunch crowd,
contributing toward its 7.1 percent store-to-store increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``So things are looking good,'' Bethers said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local malls continue to attract new tenants, which in
turn are boosting traffic and sending overall mall sales _ that is,
sales that include outlets that opened after May 1998 _ to even
greater heights.
</P>
<P>
   At the Northridge Fashion Center, for example, overall sales
through May jumped 26 percent when figures are included from the
Claim Jumper restaurant, Old Navy clothing store, Borders Books,
Pacific Theaters' 10-screen multiplex and the Farmer's Market. All
are recent additions to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added a lot of new, exciting tenants, (and) traffic is
increasing every month,'' said general manager Carol Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
