<HEADLINE>
OBSERVERS MAKE A BIG STINK ABOUT PLANT'S BLOOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STIFFLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The smell hits you from all the way down the hall, the
minute the greenhouse door is opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smells like when the mouse got caught and died in my
drain,'' said Chris DeCrease, a University of Washington research
technician. ``And it looks like the `Little Shop of Horrors.'''
</P>
<P>
   A description like that can mean only one thing _ the reeking,
heating wonder from Sumatra, the Amorphophallus titanum, is finally
blooming at the UW greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's center stalk, or spadix, has turned a
yellowish-purple and grown 8 inches in the past four days to a
height of more than 6 feet. Wednesday afternoon the upside-down
pleated skirt surrounding the base of the spadix began to open,
revealing a deep crimson color _ and the odor.
</P>
<P>
   The spadix emits pulses of heat that can be felt inches away;
with every pulse, a wave of stench fills the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wet manure,'' proclaimed Zoology graduate student Deniz
Erezyilmaz. ``It smells like a horse stable that hasn't been
cleaned, when buried manure is first exposed to air.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tropics of Sumatra, carrion beetles flock to the foul
odor and pollinate the plant. They climb into the plant, and if
carrying pollen from another A. titanum, they pollinate the
numerous small female flowers tucked into the bottom of the flute.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the smell begins, it starts to wane, and the female
flowers stop being receptive to pollination. The male flowers, also
nestled in the flute, then release their pollen and the insects
depart. Two or three days later the bloom rapidly dies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday there were no beetles, but dozens of people and flies
crowded around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to see this flower my whole life,'' enthused
66-year-old Marjorie Lou Ericksen from Renton. She tried to see the
bloom on other occasions at conservatories around the world, but
always missed it because the bloom lasts only days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be more excited,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Ewing, manager of the UW greenhouse, is thrilled. Six years
ago he planted a seed the size of an olive pit that gave rise to
this bloom, which only two months ago was barely above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday marked only the 10th time this century an A. titanum
has bloomed in the United States, and the first time that it's ever
happened west of St. Louis or at an American university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been totally addicted to it,'' said Joanne Rosen, a
resident of the nearby Montlake neighborhood. Rosen has visited the
greenhouse with camera in hand and fluffy white poodle in tow for
eight days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sensuality of it makes it fun for photography,'' she said.
But ``I expected the smell to be worse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
