r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN     07-08 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL AN ALL-STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Troy Percival was the sole Angel player named to the
American League All-Star team Wednesday, and that's the way it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   No other Angel put up numbers worthy of All-Star consideration,
with the possible exception of Mo Vaughn (.281, 16 homers, 53 RBIs
going into Wednesday's game). And while Percival is appreciative of
the selection -- the third of his career (he was an All-Star in
1996 and '98) -- he's going to feel a little lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real difference (from '96 and '98) is that I don't
get to share this with any of my teammates,'' said Percival, who
ranks third in the league with 22 saves. ``It's a little hollow
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun (in '98) watching (Darin) Erstad go for the first
time and it was a thrill (in '96) going with Chuck (Finley). This
time I'm on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   But what about the chance to hang out with the stars, the best
players in the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows I don't associate with position players from
other teams, Percival said. ``I'll talk to other relievers then fly
back home.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise to Percival that the Angels have only one
All-Star -- they're in last place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we're sitting in the standings says it all,'' he said.
``But we're only 7 1/2 games out. We're still in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three All-Star appearances and the Angels single-season club
record for saves (42 last year) don't mean much to Percival if the
team doesn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes 50 saves from me for us to win the division,
that's all I care about,'' he said. ``All the other stuff doesn't
matter. I saved 42 games last year, but all I think about are my
seven losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival was also quick to give credit to the Angels bullpen,
which has been at or near the top of the league in ERA all season.
Mark Petkovsek has been key setting up Percival, going 8-2 with a
1.69 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could have him go instead of me, I'd do it,'' Percival
said. ``I got a 4-month-old (son Cole) at home I'd like to spend
time with.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders Tim Salmon (sprained left wrist) and Jim Edmonds
(surgery on right shoulder) continue to make progress in their
recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon hit off a tee for the third day in a row Wednesday and if
all goes well, he might hit soft toss this weekend and live
pitching next week.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds hit off a tee Tuesday and also could begin hitting in
the batting cage soon. Still, there is no timetable for the return
of either.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins has decided pitcher Mike Fyhrie will start
Sunday's game in Colorado, the final game before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had been undecided, but after Fyhrie held the Mariners
to two runs and six hits in seven innings Tuesday, it was an easy
decision. Collins' other options were Jarrod Washburn and
Shigetoshi Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Greene's demotion to triple-A Edmonton might have been a
surprise to some, considering his 12 homers and 31 RBIs. But Greene
has been horrible with runners in scoring postion (.197), his
at-bats looking worse and worse as he continued to swing at pitches
out of the strikezone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to get him out of that was to have him go play,''
Collins said. ``He needs at-bats. He needs to go find his stroke.
He knows what he needs to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Greene on the roster is Tim Unroe, who had hit in 10
consecutive games for triple-A Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   It's Unroe's third tour of duty with the Angels this season. He
made the team out of spring training, was sent down June 13, then
called up June 16 when Mike Colangelo was injured. He was sent down
again June 22 before being called up Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough being the 25th man,'' Unroe said. ``But it's better
than being the 26th man.''
</P>
<P>
   Unroe started Wednesday's game at DH.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are off today, then will begin a three-game series in
Denver against the Colorado Rockies on Friday. Pitching matchups
for the series: Friday (6:05) -- Chuck Finley (4-9, 5.52 ERA) vs.
Darryl Kile (5-6, 5.57); Saturday (5:05) -- Omar Olivares (7-6,
3.26) vs. Pedro Astacio (8-7, 5.30); Sunday (12:05) -- Mike Fyhrie
(0-0, 2.57) vs. Bobby Jones (4-7, 5.76).
</P>
</TEXT>
