<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S EXTORTION, COMING TO A BALL FIELD NEAR YOU
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ I love The Ballpark in Arlington. I mean, I
``really'' love it. In a purely platonic way, of course. Nothing
kinky, you understand. This feeling is too pure, too sacred.
</P>
<P>
   I adore its colors, its smells, its sightlines, its sounds. With
the exception of a couple of minor items, I love everything about
it.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have moved in there permanently a long time ago, in fact, if
Tom Schieffer would have let me.
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly roomy enough for a king-size bed, and the dogs
would love romping on groundskeeper Tom Burns' ``yard.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why a lot of folks, yours truly included, implored the
citizens of Arlington _ and I was one at the time _ back in the
early '90s to approve the sales tax increase, partner up with the
Texas Rangers and build this magnificent structure.
</P>
<P>
   There was some stiff, vocal resistance, you'll recall, but a
record turnout of voters approved the measure by a 2-to-1 margin.
Those of us who had fought long and hard were justifiably proud.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, somewhere, buried way back in my conscience where none of
us really like to wander around for fear we'll stumble over
something we don't want to think about, there was this tiny, little
guilty feeling. Claims of blackmail and extortion by Seattle media
and Mariners fans this week have reminded me that that uneasy
feeling is still very much there.
</P>
<P>
   So here's my warning to you: Don't think that just because
Arlington and Seattle are separated by thousands of miles and the
Continental Divide means what's happening there won't affect you
right here in Texas. It can and probably will.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been keeping up, Seattle's Safeco Field will
officially open for business a week from tonight, following the
All-Star break. It is a palace, the Taj Mahal of baseball. Then
again, for $517 million, there should be a few bells and whistles,
right?
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Seattle fans is that cost overruns on the new
stadium have exceeded $100 million and the Mariners' owners are, in
effect, holding star players Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez as
hostages in a high-pressure game of extortion. Their message is
simple: Pay up, or say goodbye to Griffey and/or Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   In a copyrighted story Sunday, ``The Seattle Times'' said that
Mariners owner John Ellis and others in the team's ownership
structure have subtly ``played the Griffey card'' almost from Day
One in its dealings with the King County Public Facilities
District, which oversees the construction project.
</P>
<P>
   The team's claim: If we're forced to pay these overruns, as we
agreed to do, then we may not be able to keep Griffey or Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we have moved from the threat of
``build-or-we-will-leave'' to direct intimidation regarding a
team's superstars. You want to see Griffey play in a Mariners'
uniform, Seattle fans? Then you have to step back up to the plate
as a citizenry and bail us out one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has lashed out at the team, saying he doesn't want to be
used as a pawn in the negotiations, and fans are in an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if the overruns are $1 or $100 million, the
Mariners said they would pay them and they should,'' Mariners fan
Larry Garvin said at Safeco Field's open house Tuesday. ``As
someone said, our response isn't just `no' to the Mariners, it's
`hell, no.'''
</P>
<P>
   We said ``yes'' to the Rangers back in '91, and while I
certainly don't regret it, now and then my conscience gives me a
tweak because, in a way, we too succumbed to subtle extortion.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' lever when they wanted Arlington to build The
Ballpark was the same one that most franchises use: ``We need a new
facility. You can build it and we'll agree to stay here, or we'll
go someplace that will.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever really came out and said it. They didn't have to.
They just made it clear that they were exploring all their options,
meeting with planning boards in other cities, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they weren't going to Florida, or North Carolina, just to
Dallas, or Irving, or Lewisville. But they'd still be gone from
Arlington. As someone who lives west of the Trinity, I didn't want
to see that, and Arlington didn't either.
</P>
<P>
   Build this grand new facility for us, the Rangers vowed, and we
can be more competitive. We can afford to keep our star players and
pass some savings along to our fans.
</P>
<P>
   Everything they promised has come true except one. The Ballpark,
built for a mere $191 million, isn't Safeco Field with its
retractable roof, but it's superb. The bonds used to finance the
construction will be paid off even earlier than expected. And the
Rangers have been more competitive, and they kept Pudge Rodriguez
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been no savings for the fans. On the contrary,
since The Ballpark opened in 1994, ticket prices have soared at
least 50 percent in most areas and in some, Home Run Porch, for
instance, they've almost doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, very soon the Rangers must ante up again if they want to
keep two-time MVP Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel the hard, cold steel of a symbolic gun barrel
prodding your rib cage in the very near future, you'll know soon
enough who gets to pay for that honor, too.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
