<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO EAGER TO RETURN TO FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Rangers' upcoming series with the Padres
at San Diego's Qualcomm Stadium should produce a second tour of
duty at first base for Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't talked about it,'' Palmeiro said, ``but I'm sure
I'll be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who underwent arthroscopic surgery Feb. 10 and March 7
to remove torn cartilage from his right knee, made his 76th start
Wednesday as the Rangers' designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro made five consecutive starts at first base from June
5-9 during the Rangers' previous interleague swing through
Arizona's Bank One Ballpark and Los Angeles' Dodger Stadium.
Palmeiro hit .391 (9 for 23) with two home runs and nine runs
batted in during those five games, and went 1-for-4 during his only
other start at first base June 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm to the point now where I'm not going to be where I want to
be,'' Palmeiro said, ``but I feel I can do a pretty decent job.''
</P>
<P>
   Interleague games at National League ballparks prohibit the
designated hitter, so Palmeiro likely will replace Lee Stevens in
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think so,'' manager Johnny Oates said, ``but it all
depends on Raffy and how he feels.'' KELLY DAY-TO-DAY
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Roberto Kelly remains day-to-day after suffering
a strain to his left biceps muscle during his seventh-inning at-bat
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder Scarborough Green completed the at-bat for
Kelly, who departed in pain after overextending the arm while
swinging at a 1-1 pitch from right-hander Tim Worrell. Kelly first
experienced a twinge in the arm during his sixth-inning at-bat,
which resulted in a two-run double that gave the Rangers a 4-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The injury increases the probability of center fielder Ruben
Mateo (strain, left groin) being reinstated from his medical
rehabilitation assignment for this weekend's series with the
Padres, should the Rangers deem him healthy. STEVENS SITS, THEN
STARS
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates inserted reserves Jon Shave and Luis Alicea
into Wednesday's lineup for the slumping Lee Stevens and second
baseman Mark McLemore with Oakland left-hander Kenny Rogers on the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens went 5-for-31 (.161) in his previous nine games, and
McLemore has struggled this season with left-handers by hitting
.137 (7-for-51). Shave, who replaced Stevens at first base, also
needed the at-bats after making his most recent start June 19 in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens replaced Shave in the sixth inning and delivered the
game-winning hit with his two-run, seventh-inning single.
ZIMMERMAN'S ZEROS
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman, who Wednesday matched right-hander
Tim Crabtree's club record with his 16th consecutive scoreless
appearance, has pitched 192/3 innings without allowing a run. That
ranks second among Rangers relievers to the 232/3 scoreless innings
pitched by Jim Kern during the 1979 season: Pitcher Year Innings
Jim Kern 1979 232/3 Jeff Zimmerman 1999 192/3 Jim Kern 1979 182/3
Steve Foucalt 1974 172/3 Dave Tobik 1983 17 Briefly
</P>
<P>
   _ Third baseman Todd Zeile extended his hitting streak to 16
games with his run-scoring single in the fourth inning. The streak
matches the best of Zeile's career, and he is hitting .450
(27-for-60) during that span.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rafael Palmeiro and closer John Wetteland earned bonuses of
$50,000 with their selections to the All-Star Game as reserves.
Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman's contract did not include a bonus for
his selection. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
