</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ A FALLEN STAR 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ He gave a 14-karat performance in his
final tuneup for his All-Star start next Tuesday in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   But while Pedro Martinez's 14 strikeouts Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night were
the most anyone has seen here in the 1 1/2 seasons since they
opened the doors to baseball in Tropicana Field, Martinez won't be
riding a winning wave back home for his 'Star turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Devil Rays came from behind to edge Martinez and
the Red Sox, 3-2, as a pitcher who didn't have a big-league win in
almost four years beat the man with more wins than anyone in the
majors. This, on a night Martinez said he felt like he had no-hit
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt in command all night,'' said Martinez, who fell short
in his attempt to become the first pitcher to have 16 wins at the
break since Randy Jones of the Padres in 1976. ``I felt I was
really strong. I took a peek at the radar gun in the eighth inning,
and I was still throwing 94, 95 miles an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette didn't have to see this loss, the
Red Sox' second straight to the Devil Rays and fourth in five
meetings over the span of a week, to opine that it was
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be able to win these games,'' said Duquette, who
listened to the game on the radio back home in Boston but already
is attuned to what he has to do in the 23 days leading to the July
31 trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   With the baseball world convening in Boston this weekend,
Duquette will be accelerating his efforts to find help for a team
that was missing All-Star shortstop Nomar Garciaparra for the fifth
straight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the playoffs,'' Duquette said. ``We want to
win the division. Generally, when you want to do that, you trade
younger players for established major league players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking around now, and we should have a much better
idea soon what players are potentially available.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping Duquette's wish list is a hitter. ``I'm still hopeful
that (Tom) Gordon and Ramon Martinez will come back,'' he said.
``If they pitch at a high level, then we'll look to bolster our
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't come back, then we may also need to look for
some type of pitching. But generally, there are professional
hitters available.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a Jim Leyritz, Duquette was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, who dumped the King last summer at Leyritz's request,
chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players of that type are probably available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had won his last four starts and hadn't lost in
almost a month (June 9 at Montreal), gave up more than two earned
runs for the first time in five starts and came away a loser
because of it. He was beaten by Dave Eiland, a righthander of
modest ability and immodest record (6-20 lifetime) who last won in
the big leagues on July 21, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, don't ever underestimate anybody,'' said Eiland,
a 33-year-old journeyman who played college ball at Florida with
Mike Stanley and whose 15 minutes of fame is yet to come, as he was
Kevin Costner's body double in the soon-to-be-released baseball
movie, ``For the Love of the Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first win in a long time and it feels good to beat a
guy like that, and it was worth the wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox took a 2-1 lead in the sixth on singles by Darren Lewis,
Jose Offerman (a bunt that died on the first-base line), and Brian
Daubach. That lead could easily have expanded, but Offerman was
thrown out on a close play at third trying to advance on Daubach's
single, and Troy O'Leary's double took an ill-timed hop over the
fence, which kept Daubach, who could have scored easily, at third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was yelling at that fence to grow, but it didn't,'' manager
Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Lou Merloni, lined out to end the inning, and
the Red Sox went hitless in the last three innings against
relievers Norm Charlton and Roberto Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who struck out six of seven batters in one stretch and
finished by striking out the side in the eighth, whiffed at least
one batter in every inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Tampa Bay took a 1-0 lead in the second when Fred McGriff
skidded an opposite-field double into the left-field corner and
scored when former Sox benchwarmer John Flaherty singled past a
diving Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty started the winning rally in the sixth with a one-out
single to center, Wade Boggs singled through the left side, and
Paul Sorrento bounced a grounder through the right side to tie the
score, Flaherty just beating Trot Nixon's throw home.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Ledesma then chopped a ball toward short that third
baseman Wilton Veras, whose first big-league home run had tied the
score at 1 in the fifth, fielded and flipped to second for a force
as Boggs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has allowed three straight hits in an inning only five
times this season. The Devil Rays have done it three times, twice
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   He threw 133 pitches, 90 for strikes, but despite the heavy
workload, Williams said he never entertained a thought of taking
him out, unless the Sox had tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave the game to the man,'' Williams said. ``You respect
him for who he is and what he has done for the team, let him
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the standpoint of giving us one last shot in the ninth, I
thought he deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Merloni led off the ninth against Hernandez, the Devil Rays'
closer, with a liner to the wall. Jason Varitek drew a walk, but
Reggie Jefferson, pinch hitting for Veras, looked at a third
strike, and Damon Buford tapped into a game-ending force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no luck in this game,'' Martinez said. ``You create
your own luck . . . They just played better, they did the little
things. No excuses, nothing to look for. Just let it go. There'll
be some other days.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has now lost to the White Sox (4-0), Expos (13-1),
and Devil Rays, will go into the break with a 15-3 record and 2.10
ERA, both major-league bests, and 184 strikeouts, second only to
Arizona's Randy Johnson (200).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pitched 18 games and kept us in the game 18 times,''
Williams said. ``That statement says it all. It tells you how good
he is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
