u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-08 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT TRADE ONLY GETS SONICS BACK WHERE THEY STARTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The best part about the Sonics' trade for Horace Grant
last week is that the club unloaded personnel mistakes whose
contract value approximated the GNPs of all the European
principalities.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part is, that deal gets them merely back to even.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when a pro team churns the roster without
direction (see Mariners bullpen).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Sonics president Wally Walker sees it another way,
contending the Sonics are neither directionless nor back to even.
</P>
<P>
   As far as having direction, Walker has a difficult case to make,
because the entire NBA in 1999 was directionless. The
thrown-together teams, compressed schedule and reckless disregard
for the quality of the game removed the last veil obscuring the
ruthless shamelessness in the NBA's Microsoft-like pursuit of a
buck.
</P>
<P>
   As rewarding as it was to see the stalwarts among the San
Antonio Spurs win the championship, that title will forever pack an
Oliver Miller-sized asterisk:
</P>
<P>
   ( season had no business being played).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were among the sporting disaster's primary victims,
having to absorb the empty trade of Jim McIlvaine while indulging
two of the most ghastly examples of the NBA's unprofessionalism,
Anything But Thin Baker and Belly Owens.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Olden Polynice's title as the worst single-season free
throw shooter in NBA history, and the Sonics at least should have
invested in a free agent cat to scrape litter over the mess.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the contention can be made that the Sonics, by
trading Don MacLean and Owens (and to a far lesser extent, Dale
Ellis), and dumping Polynice and other veterans, have removed the
worst mistakes of the Walker regime and returned the club nearly to
the pre-McIlvaine days.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, of course, sees progress where others see carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``All GMs have skeletons in their closet,'' he said Wednesday,
managing a small smile at the Sonics gym while watching
summer-league preparations. ``It's part of the business. I don't
look at what we did as trying to fix mistakes as much as making
moves to get better right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft-day deal with Orlando that brought Grant, a 6-10
forward on the downhill of a productive career, instantly made the
Sonics a better rebounding and defensive team, although Grant often
will be overmatched when he's forced out of position at center (how
often has that been said about a Sonics post man?).
</P>
<P>
   Another virtue is that Grant buys another year of development
time for Jelani McCoy and Vladimir Stepania, two frontliners of
whom large improvement is expected after a summer league full of
teaching. Both were bit players last season in a season nearly
devoid of practice time.
</P>
<P>
   The final asset was the departures of MacLean, Owens and Ellis.
It ridded the Sonics of three multi-year contracts that would have
been cripplers in improving a roster that tumbled out of the
Western Conference elite so abruptly that some feared a mass
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Their departures _ all three may be waived by Orlando, although
their salaries will count against the Magic's cap _ along with
Grant's arrival, created a net $1 million reduction in the Sonics
payroll counted against the salary cap, meaning that the Sonics
potentially have more cash in the free agent derby than all but
Toronto, Chicago and the L.A. Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The virtues made the trade a smart one, the only losses being
the 39-year-old Ellis and a draft choice _ Orlando had Seattle
choose Corey Maggette _ that would have added a guaranteed
four-year contract for a player unlikely to get time the next two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The caution is that the organization might be as wrong on Grant
as it was with Owens, whom the Sonics claimed to have thoroughly
researched and declared a good fit. This was despite the fact that
he was among the few NBA players in history to have his scoring and
rebounding averages decline six consecutive seasons. Now, it's
seven straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought Billy would be a good fit,'' Walker said. ``We got
him for below the average NBA salary and he had a skills set that
helped us with rebounding and ballhandling.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be fair to Billy, I don't know if he had a fair chance to
show his skills'' because of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to the fans, Owens should have retired after showing
up looking like Mr. Sta-Puf. His lack of conditioning, along with
same for Baker, violated a minimum requirement for pro athletes and
killed the season.
</P>
<P>
   But their jock crimes cannot be charged against Sonics
management, which was forbidden to even talk to players during the
lockout, much less work them into shape.
</P>
<P>
   One more win would have pushed the Sonics into the eighth seed
in the playoffs, a place from which in the Eastern Conference the
New York Knicks did some damage, even without Patrick Ewing. That's
a fine example of how random was this NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal conclusion is that Walker, and coach Paul Westphal,
as well as just about every other NBA president, GM and coach,
rates a get-out-of-jail card this summer for lack of evidence that
intentional basketball badness was committed.
</P>
<P>
   The Grant trade helped clear out Walker's ghost closet. The free
agent signing period that begins Aug. 1 will be the moment for
Walker to do something more than getting to even.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
