<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA HAS ALL THE TOOLS TO UPEND AMERICANS IN WORLD CUP FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was quite intentional that the coach and star
players of China's Women's World Cup team did not make it to a very
formal news conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Wen, the 26-year-old striker whose seven goals make her the
World Cup's leading scorer (along with Brazil's Sissi), was back at
camp. So was acrobatic goalkeeper Goa Hong, who has allowed just
two goals in five matches.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, coach Ma Yuanan already had made it clear that his
speedy and highly technical team understood what it faces Saturday,
when China plays the U.S. in the final.
</P>
<P>
   Ma told reporters earlier this week that China accepts ``the
responsibility to move the game to a higher level against the
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, instead of taking time away from training, the
Chinese sent another team official to Century Park Hotel to make
nice with the world press _ a gathering that has grown rapidly and
monstrously, infatuated with this incredible, expanding women's
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an honor to be in the final of the World Cup,'' Yan
Zhongjian said through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   No translator was needed, however, to interpret his confident
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well prepared for the final. That is also why the head
coach is absent,'' Yan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese feel they have yet to win anything so far, which
makes them supremely hungry for this World Cup finale.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, well, you have to wonder just a bit.
</P>
<P>
   They have already won something extremely important, which is
why coach Tony DiCicco said Wednesday they are relaxed and happy,
less tense and no longer suffering anything resembling performance
anxiety _ things that may have been issues during their tough
quarterfinal match against Germany and again against Brazil in the
nerve-wracking semis.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and its coaching staff already have pulled off one of
the great sales coups in the history of sports. They have sold a
nation on a women's event that has racked up viewership the likes
of which pro hockey would die for.
</P>
<P>
   We already know that 2.9 million watched on TV as the U.S. beat
Brazil in the semifinals in Palo Alto, Calif., on the Fourth of
July. We already know that 79,123 were at Stanford Stadium and that
a sellout of close to 90,000 is guaranteed at the Rose Bowl
Saturday for the 1:50 p.m. kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   But what we're less sure about is the ability of the U.S. to
tackle this next and last obstacle, China, to say nothing of the
heavy expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that the best two teams in this World Cup have
made it to the championship round. However, there may be a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Out from under the massive red, white and blue brush strokes of
this tournament, many World Cup observers have begun to realize
that the Chinese are not only one of the best two teams left
standing, they are quite possibly the favorite to win.
</P>
<P>
   That is why this steamroller of a sporting event called the
Women's World Cup ought to come with a warning label, especially
for those who think the U.S. booters are a shoo-in to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   May we suggest ``Buyer beware.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the hype and all the determination to reclaim the World
Cup crown _ the U.S. women won the inaugural tournament in 1991 but
lost in the semis of the last Cup, in 1995 _ this could be a lot
more difficult than called for in the All-America Hollywood script.
</P>
<P>
   After being trampled 5-0 by China in the semifinals, Norway
coach Jarl Torske was hard-pressed to hide his appreciation for the
Chinese attack. He said Wednesday the U.S. will be severely tested,
especially defensively, where it is weakest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (U.S. women) keep on like they have been so far, they
will definitely run into serious problem in the back line, and they
would probably get goals against them. So they have to be tighter,
and they can't give the Chinese so much space,'' Torske said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe the U.S. takes too many risks, too many chances.
They underestimate maybe their opponents sometimes, instead of
kicking the ball wide. They don't seem concentrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the U.S. women have been offensively superior
for the first decade of elite international soccer competition,
defense has been a secondary consideration. There has always been
Michelle Akers or Mia Hamm or Kristine Lilly or Tiffeny Milbrett to
counterattack with fury.
</P>
<P>
   But now, at the moment for which this wildly likable and highly
skilled U.S. team has worked years, on the largest stage ever for
women's sports, the American players face an opponent that is truly
their competitive equal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talk about it being a showcase game, I guess it
encompasses everything. But I'm a coach, so I'm just talking about
what you're going to see on the field,'' DiCicco said Wednesday,
still promoting the event as much as championing his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see two teams that are fit, that are ready,
that are going to go out to win this game, they're not going to
hold anything back, and they're going to play attractive soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be attractive soccer, but it will also be for blood.
That's why this World Cup finale should come with a buyer-beware
warning.
</P>
<P>
   At the very pinnacle of this history-making, rolling-stone
sporting spectacle, a serious game could break out.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
