<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUNDS OF SILENCE FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER -- The Dodgers' clubhouse is empty and quiet after games.
Not many players around, not much to say.
</P>
<P>
   This is what it's like when a team with such lofty aspirations
and expectations crashes and burns. There are loads of questions
and no answers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers lost again. This is nothing new. They've been losing
for the better part of a month. The way it's been, it's not a
matter of winning or losing, but how the loss will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, it came via a three-run opposite field homer from
Vinny Castilla to break a tie in the seventh inning and lift the
Rockies to a 7-5 win at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game the Dodgers led 4-1, but the usually reliable
bullpen faltered when Jamie Arnold (2-2) got beat with his third
best pitch _ a hangin' slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make better pitches than that,'' said Arnold, who
allowed four runs in two innings. ``The team is struggling right
now, and I'm hangin' sliders. We had an opportunity to win, and I
let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the homer as the pitch that became the homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just inexperienced, and he got beat with his third-best
pitch,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``It was a hangin'
slider, and that's what got me. It's probably the third time he's
done it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of a turnaround before every game from the
Dodgers. Then they do just enough to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen's been fantastic most of the season, going 4-3 with
a 2.57 ERA in the last 37 games. But it was the pen that couldn't
protect Carlos Perez's 4-3 lead after five innings. You kind of get
the idea if Perez left trailing by a run, the bullpen would have
been superb but the offense would have lacked the one huge hit.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a way to lose, the Dodgers have it covered. They are
35-47. They say the season isn't over. Everyone else says it is.
The Dodgers are a Chan Ho Park blow-up away from getting swept by
the Rockies. That aside, the Dodgers have lost three straight, nine
of 10, and 24 of 33. Oh, heck, they've lost 47 of 82 and are last
in the National League with a .259 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing like a championship club, obviously, but I
still keep thinking we'll be a good offensive club,'' Johnson said.
``We keep misfiring.''
</P>
<P>
   The hitters are pressing, gripping the bats so hard they
seemingly turn to ash. The pressure to perform has been there since
opening day, which Johnson said should have helped instead of
hindered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should be more of a stimulant,'' Johnson said. ``People
think you're good, get in there and have a quality at-bat. That's
what we have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most damning statistic is this: The Dodgers haven't
won more than two games in a row for more than two months. What
reason is there to believe they're capable of putting together a
bigger streak?
</P>
<P>
   ``The table is set for a dramatic comeback,'' said Trenidad
Hubbard, who started in right field and had two hits and threw a
runner out at home. ``Rehearsal is over. It's time for the big
show. If Tony Gwynn is 0 for 4 in a game and comes up for a fifth
at-bat, he's not dwelling on the other four.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers built a lead with their battery. Rookie Angel Pena's
three-run homer, the first of his career, gave them a 3-1 lead in
the fourth. Perez followed with his fourth career homer, marking
the second time the Dodgers have hit back-to-back homers. (The
other came April 7, when Raul Mondesi and Todd Hundley did it.)
</P>
<P>
   The cushion lasted two outs. Kurt Abbott hit a two-run homer to
right-center to pull the Rockies with 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold gave up the tying run in the sixth on a double-play
ground out. The Dodgers had runners on first and second in the
seventh, but Eric Karros grounded into an inning-ending double
play. A few minutes later, Castilla hit Arnold's first pitch over
the fence in right-center for a 7-4 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
