r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES-LADN     07-08 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT-SO-CLOSED PRACTICE FOR U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The U.S. National team tried its best to have a
closed training session at Pomona-Pitzer College, Wednesday, but
nothing stopped the camera crews, media and several fans from
stopping by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was it closed?'' said a surprised Cindy Parlow. ``I don't
think so, there were a lot of people there.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of having a closed session was so the U.S. could
prepare tactically for China, their opponent in Saturday's Women's
World Cup final at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in the two games we lost to China (in the past year)
they had two breakaways for the two winning goals,'' said U.S.
coach Tony DiCicco. ``We had to work on how to to eliminate the
space in front of our defense, but also protect the space behind
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a good job of that in the World Cup so far. We've
cut down on clear breakaways that the Chinese used to expose us
since the 1996 Olympics. We also worked on our traps. If you are
going to trap the Chinese you have to be very organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm struggling? That was a question posed to DiCicco
because Hamm failed to score in both the quarterfinal and semifinal
victories. She has scored two goals in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won both games with her not scoring and that's a good
thing,'' said DiCicco. ``We all know that when she doesn't score
there's usually one not far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But having said that, we don't define Mia as just a goal
scorer. With some players you do. Some just sit up there and don't
do a lot of work. Giorgio Chinaglia (former New York Cosmos
standout) comes to mind. He was very talented but he just sat up
there. If he scored he did his job. If he didn't he didn't do his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Mia has so many more dimensions to her game. She got us
the penalty kick (against Brazil) the other day. And defensively
she does a lot too, helping everyone else out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'll tell you, she's excited about this game and she wants
to make a statement in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many have asked DiCicco what the popularity of the women's
national team says to naysayers who didn't feel they could pull off
this huge event.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure there are people dismayed by the success of this
event,'' he said. ``Now they've got to compete with girls playing
sports. No matter how we look at it, we're still in the attitude
changing business. We're more advanced here in the United States
but all over the world we're in the attitude changing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some people that are not happy about what's
transpired here the last few weeks, but they won't be able to come
out and publicly announce that. They will just wait for their turn
to squash soccer or put down women's athletic's at some point in
the future. But what's happened is in motion. Of course it will
slow down, but it's not going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with many of the U.S. National team's families in town,
captain Carla Overbeck asked if the team would have dinner
together. In another example of the team's closeness, the vote was
unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having three meals a day in hotels so we all wanted
to get together and go out and have a dinner together,'' said
Parlow. ``We wanted to be away from everyone. Away from the press
and people to have a dinner for ourselves and have a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what's special about this team and why people are
getting behind us. We just love going out together, taking pictures
and having a good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
