u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     07-08 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY M'S ONLY ALL-STAR; RODRIGUEZ SEEKS MOTIVATION IN SNUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Only one Mariner was honored Wednesday, and it
wasn't with an All-Star selection.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of his teammates, left-hander Jamie Moyer was
bypassed for a spot on the American League All-Star team when
reserves were announced Wednesday. For Moyer, that meant he will
start for the Mariners when they open Safeco Field on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   For shortstop Alex Rodriguez, it meant that for the first time
in his four full seasons, he will not take part in the midsummer
classic, to be held next Tuesday at Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Rodriguez said. ``But maybe it will give
me motivation to prove to guys like Joe Torre that I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   As manager of the World Series champion New York Yankees, Torre
selected the All-Star reserves, with input from AL president Gene
Budig. Two shortstops, the Yankees' Derek Jeter and the Cleveland
Indians' Omar Vizquel, were chosen to back up starter Nomar
Garciaparra of the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Wednesday that he considered Rodriguez, adding that
Rodriguez's numbers were impressive even though he missed 32 games
with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's disappointment was understandable. When reserves
were named, he was batting .322 with 17 homers, 47 runs batted in,
59 runs scored and a .400 on-base percentage. With five errors, he
had a better fielding percentage than the Gold Glove-winning
Vizquel, .980 to .975, and all of the offensive numbers are better
except batting average (Vizquel was hitting .333).
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing to point out is that he has comparable
numbers (to other All-Stars) and he did miss six weeks,'' said
catcher Dan Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who has no errors and was batting .286 before Wednesday
night's game, was another Mariner whose numbers matched up well
with a player picked instead. Detroit's Brad Ausmus, the AL reserve
catcher, has a lower batting average (.274) and two errors, though
he does have 12 more RBIs than Wilson. Ausmus is the Tigers' lone
representative. Every team must be represented on the 28-man
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be 35-40 spots,'' said starting outfielder Ken
Griffey Jr., who is the only Mariner going to Boston. ``It's an
All-Star Game. It's not about making it fair, because it's not.
Guys deserve to go, and they should expand the roster. It's one
day. Who cares if you take 40 guys? ... It would give a chance for
guys that deserve to go, to go.''
</P>
<P>
   With 28 spots and 14 teams, picking the roster is not an easy
job. When Mariners manager Lou Piniella piloted the National League
team as the Cincinnati Reds manager in 1991, he asked league
president Bill White pick the roster. White did, leaving just one
spot for Piniella, who gave it to his right fielder, Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Piniella was disappointed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping we'd have two or three,'' Piniella said. ``I
thought that Jamie certainly warranted (a spot), (Freddy) Garcia is
a rookie and he's won nine ballgames, Dan Wilson _ outside of
(Ivan) Rodriguez, no other catcher is having an outstanding season.
Alex was hurt six weeks, and he's hitting over .300 with 17 home
runs and 50 RBIs or so. That's nothing to snub at.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since 1991 that only one Mariner will go
to the All-Star Game. In 1996 and '97, the M's sent five; this
time, there are more ex-Mariners (Mike Hampton, Randy Johnson and
Vizquel) than current Mariners on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer was surprised Garcia was passed over, though Garcia's ERA
(5.04) is almost a run higher than the highest on the AL staff.
Griffey was also surprised _ and feeling a little lonely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always fun to have your teammates to go with you,'' he
said. ``It's not too much fun to make flights by yourself. Now I've
got to hang out with Cleveland _ they've got their whole team
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Sr. will be on hand, at least, and Griffey joked
that he'd like to bring along an injured teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bring Jay so he can throw me BP,'' Griffey said. ``I'll
have my own BP thrower for the home run contest that I'm still
waiting to be asked to.''
</P>
<P>
   ROTATION SET: The decision to start Moyer at the Safeco opener
was easy, Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been in the All-Star Game, it would have been
necessary to change the rotation,'' Piniella said. ``But right now,
Jamie is certainly very deserving of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be exciting whether I start or not,'' Moyer
said. ``I'll just try to approach it like another day, not get
caught up in anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Jeff Fassero will follow Moyer and start Friday,
followed by lefty John Halama and right-handers Freddy Garcia and
Gil Meche. Piniella grouped the three lefties together because the
San Diego Padres have struggled against left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   By starting Sunday, Garcia could end up facing the pitcher whose
trade brought him to Seattle, the Arizona Diamondbacks' Randy
Johnson. Johnson likely will pitch Sunday if he works in the
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE TALK: It's not just the small-market teams that may be
looking to move quality starting pitching before the July 31
trading deadline. Reports from New York indicate the Yankees could
try to trade left-hander Andy Pettitte, and he could interest the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is trying to upgrade its pitching for the stretch run.
Woody Woodward, M's vice president for baseball operations, has not
been given permission to raise his club's payroll, but has
indicated that if he feels strongly about a player, he can take the
case to management. Pettitte is making $5.95 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   He stands to make up as much as $2 million more next season in
arbitration, even though he has struggled. The former 21-game
winner is 9-14 with a 5.56 ERA since last July 14. The Yankees, who
have a wealth of starting pitching talent, would like to improve in
left field and in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners did make one trade Wednesday, sending shortstop
Domingo Cedeno to the Philadelphia Phillies for Class AAA infielder
Jose Flores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
