<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURF WAR FOR USC, NFL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Whether Eli Broad or Michael Ovitz eventually
brings professional football back to Los Angeles, one undeniable
winner would seem to be USC.
</P>
<P>
   Without spending a dime, the Trojans will enjoy playing in a
completely renovated, state-of-the-art Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my judgment, it would be appropriate to rebuild the
Coliseum,'' USC president Steven Sample said. ``We'd be very
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath the official statements of support for bringing an
NFL team to Los Angeles, there are reservations that what's good
for the Coliseum isn't necessarily good for USC.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans might inherit a sparkling facility, but at what
cost?
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial side is a grave concern for us,'' said a USC
official who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Already, internal estimates speculate USC could lose between
$3-4 million a year if the NFL returns to the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   That's a significant amount of money _ enough to sway whether
USC's athletic department has a profitable year or loses money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd probably just as soon not see the NFL move here,'' said
another USC administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Talk like that might make a football fan seethe, but it's simple
economics that foster such opinions. Whoever owns the NFL franchise
will undoubtedly lock up all parking, concession and corporate
suite revenues, along with advertising and signage rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly what Disney did when the Mighty Ducks moved into
the Pond in Anaheim, making it nearly impossible for the arena to
lure an NBA franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't the only probable lost sources of income. There is
also an expected decrease in ticket revenue if the new Coliseum is
unable to expand to 92,000 for the UCLA and Notre Dame games.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to dampen the university's enthusiasm for the
flashy drawings and models that Ovitz and Broad have unveiled to
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these potential obstacles, Sample is steadfast that USC
will not lose money if the Coliseum undergoes a massive renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would want a better agreement,'' he said. ``I think it's
probable and absolutely necessary. It has to be (a superior) deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be better for USC financially than the program could
have expected without rebuilding the Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are strong words, but even Sample can't guarantee that USC
will indeed secure a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legitimate to be concerned about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to prevent a financial disaster, a four-member
committee of the university's board of trustees, led by John Argue,
has begun working on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Argue, who helped bring the 1984 Olympics to Los Angeles, said
he has met or talked to Broad, Ovitz and Edward Roski, who is one
of Broad's partners and the man many credit for getting the
Coliseum this far into the NFL's selection process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both Ed Roski and Eli Broad have told me in writing the
situation would be better for USC in a new Coliseum,'' Argue said.
``That's pretty strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general concept is they'll see to it one way or another
that 'SC will come out ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Argue said it is too early to place a dollar figure on the
amount of money USC would need to offset potential losses.
</P>
<P>
   But according to sources, the NFL, or the new franchise's
owners, would need to compensate USC as much as $4 million per
year.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is the NFL has distanced itself from Roski and
relied more on Broad and Ovitz, meaning USC might have to start
over, since the majority of discussions have been with Roski.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a fear,'' USC athletic director Mike Garrett said.
``We're always trying to talk to the relative powers to make them
aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But USC might also have some bargaining leverage with whomever
owns the new NFL team. A revamped Coliseum almost certainly will
not work unless the university opens its parking facilities on game
days.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's plan involves tearing down the Sports Arena and
building 25,000 parking spaces in Exposition Park, an idea that is
considered financially impossible.
</P>
<P>
   There's already been some backing away from that idea, as
Broad's plan envisions relying on USC to ease the parking crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible ally in USC's eyes is the Coliseum Commission.
Sample and Garrett believe USC's loyalty to the Coliseum and Sports
Arena will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bargaining power is that we've been here for a long
time,'' Garrett said. ``NFL clubs have left and we've stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   That opinion is backed up by Pat Lynch, general manager of the
Coliseum and Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the Coliseum Commission's original agreement with
Roski ensured USC would be dealt with ``fairly and properly.'' That
agreement is no longer in place, but Lynch said he doesn't foresee
USC losing money in a new Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have USC's interests first and foremost in our minds,''
Lynch said. ``We would make sure in our agreement USC would have a
proper seat at the table. Until someone cuts a deal, we don't know
if the concerns are real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe those concerns materialize or maybe they don't. 'SC has
certain revenue they need to generate.''
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics _ including those within USC _ are taking a
wait-and-see attitude before proclaiming that USC's predicament
will be properly addressed.
</P>
<P>
   They worry that since USC has no other legitimate alternatives
for a football venue, the NFL might ignore the school's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   If the NFL scenario collapses, even Sample will be content to
see things remain as they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a college football stadium, the Coliseum is in good
shape,'' Sample said. ``From USC's perspective, it works fine for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
