<HEADLINE>
TROJANS TO JOIN BRUINS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _With Los Angeles likely to receive an NFL team and
Coliseum renovations expected to last at least two years, USC has
begun preliminary discussions with the Rose Bowl about playing
there in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are interested in having USC play in the Rose Bowl,'' said
Darryl Dunn, general manager of the Rose Bowl. ``I would hope it is
in the next 30 days that we begin discussions. We're anxious to
begin discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the very near future, we expect the process to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   If USC moved to the Rose Bowl, it would present a minor
scheduling problem. At least three games would conflict with UCLA's
home schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Trojans athletic director Mike Garrett said it's almost certain
USC will play some Thursday night games to prevent a scheduling
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential hurdle is the Arroyo Seco ordinance, which
limits the Rose Bowl to 15 major events per year, including UCLA
football, Galaxy soccer games and the New Year's Day bowl game.
Dunn said he did not anticipate a problem revising the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a good fit. It would generate a lot of revenue for
the city,'' Dunn said. ``There are an awful lot of USC alumni in
Pasadena.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
