<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
JOSE Lima watches from the top step of the dugout and begs for
rallies with his cap sitting on his head like some sort of
upside-down rudder.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he walks around the cage at batting practice wearing
his glove as a cap, looking something like a Dominican Darth Vader.
Sometimes, he screams into his glove. We'll worry if the glove ever
starts talking back.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, he points his finger at the batter's box and shoots a
couple of imaginary rounds at his latest strikeout victim. He
slide-steps off the mound and jiggles from head to toe. He dances
all by himself in the clubhouse, even when there's no music
playing.
</P>
<P>
   He stands out. And, sure, it takes some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   When Lima first had a measure of success for the Astros a couple
of years ago, one Astros veteran tried to put Lima in his place by
asking if a gag banner emblazoned with Lima's number could be
raised to the rafters next to Nolan Ryan's.
</P>
<P>
   The request was denied, but eventually the Astros all began
realizing what the rest of the league knows now: Sometimes the
biggest deals are the smallest ones.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lima is on his way to Chowder Town, surely poised to turn
it all into his own luscious bowl of spicy menudo. And the big deal
about it all is that it started with no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   When Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker pulled the trigger
on the first major trade of his tenure here in 1996, all he really
wanted was Brad Ausmus. He also got Daryle Ward, C.J. Nitkowski,
Trever Miller and Lima from Detroit in exchange for Doug Brocail,
Brian Hunter, Todd Jones and Orlando Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with the other three major acquisitions Hunsicker
has made for the Astros. He got Moises Alou, which certainly was a
good trade. He traded for Randy Johnson, which didn't work out as
hoped. And he signed Ken Caminiti to a free-agent contract, making
everyone bustle about, but no one more than Astros trainers.
</P>
<P>
   Then think about the trade that nearly was _ the one for Roger
Clemens last spring, which might have cost the club Lima or Mike
Hampton, who also was named to the National League All-Star team
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   None of those big names will wear an Astros uniform in the
All-Star Game, while Lima will waltz _ OK, maybe merengue _ into
Boston as one of the hottest pitchers in the league and with a
better record than either Johnson or Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Lima and Hampton _ who was acquired in 1993, before
Hunsicker's arrival _ are the perfect pictures of why winning
baseball is such an imperfect proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're talking about a trade, on the one hand there's
pressure from the public, from the media and from your own players
to do something big to make something happen,'' Hunsicker said.
``But as a GM you know one trade is not always going to get you
where you want to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risky to bank on a trade. Most players just aren't
predictable. Fine, there are some that year in and year out you can
bank on. But what about Kevin Brown?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the Dodgers' $100 million man, will watch Tuesday's
All-Star Game like so many others, while Lima dances for the
cameras and Hampton gives the nation the business end of his stare.
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker can laugh about it all now, joking Wednesday, ``I knew
all along Jose Lima would be an All-Star,'' because he knows what
never has been more clear than right now.
</P>
<P>
   If it is the little things that build championship runs, then it
is the Lilliputians on this Astros team who are keeping it in the
hunt going into the break despite all the injuries and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, after winning 102 games and obtaining Johnson,
Hunsicker remembers thinking, ``We have it all.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with Johnson, there was another first-round playoff
exit. Most significant, Johnson's presence on the team was what
prevented Lima from getting a chance to start even one playoff game
against the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Now, without Johnson, without Clemens, with Caminiti and Alou
hurt and Derek Bell struggling, where would the Astros be without
the little deals that brought Lima and all those who followed?
</P>
<P>
   Where would they be without the 1997 trade that brought Carl
Everett from the Mets? Where would they be without Tim Bogar, who
was claimed off waivers in 1997? Where would they be without Bill
Spiers, who seemed like a ho-hum free-agent signee the year before?
</P>
<P>
   ``To win in any given year, there has to be some unexpected
surprises for you,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lima is not alone as a surprise. It has been a mighty
struggle all season for this hobbling team, and surely the Astros'
stars eventually will have to live up to their billing.
</P>
<P>
   But the big deal so far has been the little deals. And no one
has stood out more than Lima, in more ways than one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
