<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2711 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REAX-AZR &LR;      07-08 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CHARMED WHILE OTHERS PROTEST CLINTON VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton swept into Phoenix on Wednesday, stirring up
reactions that were good, bad and ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Some people smiled with pride and were wowed by his style.
Others trashed him and his motorcade. A few entrepreneurs took the
opportu nity to hawk T-shirts and food specials.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot, dusty afternoon, hun dreds of people from around the
Valley _ all ages, all races _ turned out, energized by the appear
ance of the chief executive. They were charmed with straight talk,
thrilled with impromptu hand-shak ing, disappointed at being
ignored, disenchanted by his record in office.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Vasquez, 44, was simply touched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's warm-hearted,'' she said. ``You can tell by his
handshake. He was very warming, very apprecia tive of all of us, no
matter what race or color.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles away, Lynn Zapert held up a sign in silent protest: ``Mr.
Clinton you disgrace my America.''
</P>
<P>
   The day began as early as 10 a.m., when 11-year-old Grant Laten,
of Fountain Hills, showed up at Sky Harbor International Airport
wearing a black T-shirt with an American flag and baseball. He
found the perfect viewing spot on the top level of the Terminal 2
parking garage. Carrying a police scanner and camera, the boy
didn't want to miss out on anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love airplanes, and I just thought it would be kind of a
nice once-in-a-lifetime experience,'' Laten said.
</P>
<P>
   So did Chris Gabrielson, 39, of Phoenix. With his 2-year-old son
Junior in tow, he showed up about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times in your life do you get to see a president
close up?'' he said. ``It's like seeing a movie star, almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrying an American flag, he lamented the reason for the presi
dential visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a poverty tour. It doesn't make us look too good,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Air Force One touched down, about a hundred people
were pressed up against a yellow security tape, craning their necks
for a view of Clinton. Some waved, but the group was mostly
subdued.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Chicanos Por La Causa, at 11th Street and Buckeye, an
enthusiastic crowd greeted the presi dential motorcade with cheers,
ap plause and honking horns. The neighborhood, meanwhile, took on a
carnival-like atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Budding entrepreneur Becca Lay ton, sold $10 T-shirts reading,
``Welcome President Clinton.'' Lynn Adams, manager of Pete's Fish
and Chips across the street, offered a ``Secret Service Special'' _
a three-piece fish-and-chips dinner with a drink and, of course, a
secret sauce, all for $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a secret sauce we've been selling for 52 years,'' Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't enough to bring in the Secret Service.
</P>
<P>
   Army 2nd Lt. Chris Gonzales, 20, said Clinton's visit was
important to the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that he showed up here means something,'' he
said. ``Just showing up says a lot more than if he just talks about
Hispanics on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``His personal life aside, I think he's done a good job. The
econo my's booming.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more that needs to be done, said Angel Sanchez, 37,
who lives in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he can clean up the act around here,'' she said.
``There are lots of drugs, lots of prostitutes. Every day something
bad's happen ing in the neighborhood. It's getting worse. It's not
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside Chicanos por la Causa, Clinton wowed business leaders and
others with his straight talk and charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``He supports the equity capital ization fund for small business
and zeroed right in on the importance of education,'' said Sandra
Espinoza, who with her husband, Perry Monge, owns Perry Monge Salon
in the Mercado.
</P>
<P>
   Monge added, ``It was fantastic. He walked around and met folks,
learned what the CPLC has done for the community. You look at him
and you can't believe he's real. He's very charismatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Garcia, president and chief executive officer of the
organiza tion, said Clinton was ``very per sonable. He listens, and
he has a good grasp of what we're doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important now is that we follow through with the state
congressional delegation, the mayor, the banks about what can occur
in this community,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   After the brief visit, Clinton thrilled onlookers as he got out
of his car and waded into the crowd of 100 to 150 people. Over
screams and cheers, Clinton smiled, shook hands and then was
whisked away to his second stop.
</P>
<P>
   At La Canasta, the crowd built to several hundred, and the mood
shifted dramatically _ from upbeat and enthusiastic to impatient
and, at times, hostile.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters carried signs with mes sages criticizing Clinton for
his foreign policy decisions and Monica Lewinsky indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   One threw trash at the presiden tial motorcade. Another held a
sign reading, ``1969 draft dodger. 1999 warmonger.''
</P>
<P>
   Zapert, 52, who accused Clinton of disgracing the country, said,
``I should be home in Peoria, but I'm out here protesting for the
first time ever because of his dishonesty, his insincerity and his
lying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame that people are being taken in by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Kellybrew, 32, a mother of five, also took a few shots
at the president. She questioned why Clin ton focused on Hispanics
instead of Blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about Black business owners?'' she said. ``We've got
plenty of small Black business that need to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support him because I love him. He's doing a good job, but
there's some issues he needs to attend to.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Torres, 26 and uninsured, made a desperate personal plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, I need a kidney transplant. Please help me''
read her placard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping the president will see the sign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the La Canasta factory, a crowd of about 200
businesspeople fanned themselves and chatted as they awaited
Clinton's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Mariachis kept the crowd enter tained as Port-a-Coolers loudly
tried to pump cool air into the high-ceil inged space, blocked off
from the factory by pallets stacked with sacks of tortillas and
yellow corn.
</P>
<P>
   Many had dressed expecting to swelter. Golf shirts and
sleeveless dresses were more prominent than the die-hards'
white-shirt-and-tie look.
</P>
<P>
   Workers, meanwhile, busied themselves making tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Clinton swept through, squeezing hands, and then
settled in for a quick speech and roundtable discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcade left under a dark blue sky, just before a dust
storm hit.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz Morales, 17, a Carl Hayden High School student, peered
through binoculars out the window of his first-story apartment
hoping for a glimpse of Clinton and his entou rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' he said. ``It's rare that the president
comes here, and maybe he wants to help.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2712 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-MIDYEAR-HNS &LR;      07-08 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MIDYEAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ONE young superstar fires first, winning golf tournaments
machine-gun style. The other phenom zings back a barrage of his
own, victories mounting up virtually every week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   An old war horse proves the heart of a champion beats beneath
that hokey costume he wears.
</P>
<P>
   A local grinder sheds his label as Mr. Second Place by winning a
$1 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   And a lefty proves it is all right to put golf on the back
burner sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   As these highlights suggest, it already has been a spectacular
year on the PGA Tour. Great stories have unfolded, and grand golf
has been played. Just look at the two marquee players who have
hogged the spotlight the way most people expected them to.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval started the year dominating the way nobody has in
recent years. Now, it is Tiger Woods' turn, threatening to win
every time he has played since mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``What any player strives to do is be in contention, to always
have a chance,'' Woods says. ``And that's where I've got my game
now. I have a chance almost every week. And I'm very proud of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a fabulous year. I look at my stats, and
I'm right up there. I'm very pleased. Extremely pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last few events, starting at the (Byron) Nelson, I've gone
seven, one, one, three and one. That's not too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been good enough to push Woods back to the No. 1 world
ranking that he surrendered to Duval at The Players Championship in
late March.
</P>
<P>
   If Duval owned the first three months of the PGA Tour season,
Woods has made the past three his personal domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you one thing that's more important (than being No.
1), and that's winning,'' he says. ``Being No. 1 in the world and
not winning, like I was doing in all of '98, that's not that great.
I don't like going home and knowing that somebody beat me.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval knows the feeling. He knew it well during January,
February and March, when he won four times in his first eight
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good year for me,'' he says. ``And there's a lot
of time left to accomplish a great deal more.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval posted golf's most hallowed number _ 59 for 18 holes _ at
the Bob Hope Chrysler Classic, one of his four victories. Woods has
responded with a torrid streak in which he has finished seventh or
better five consecutive weeks with three victories. Their rivalry
is growing, even if we haven't seen them in a head-to-head battle
on Sunday yet.
</P>
<P>
   But there were other riveting moments in the first half of the
PGA Tour season.
</P>
<P>
   Payne Stewart, the knickered one, won his third major when he
needed only three putts on the last three holes at Pinehurst No. 2
for a U.S. Open victory. But as much as Stewart's brilliance was
applauded, it was Phil Mickelson who stole his share of hearts when
he said being at his wife's side for the birth of their first child
would outweigh any situation he could be in during the U.S. Open
week.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson said time and again that he would leave the tournament
regardless of his standing if his wife paged him with news that her
labor had begun.
</P>
<P>
   The golf gods smiled on Mickelson in a different way. They
didn't permit him to win the Open, but they did allow it to end in
regulation. Had Stewart missed his 15-foot putt on the 72nd hole, a
Monday playoff round would have been played. Amy Mickelson went
into labor at the same time her husband and Stewart would have teed
off Monday, and the baby was born just a few hours later. Mickelson
had something far more precious than a U.S. Open trophy in his
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert, meanwhile, was rewarded handsomely when he finally
broke through for his first victory in six years. He chipped in a
shot on the 38th hole to win the World Match Play Championship over
Andrew Magee. It wasn't the glamour matchup for which ABC had been
hoping. But it was good golf.
</P>
<P>
   Maggert's sand wedge, by the way, has since been plated with
gold and sent to the World Golf Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it has been a good year for golf. And there's so much more
that remains unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Will the U.S. be able to win back the Ryder Cup that has been in
European hands for the past five years?
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the 30 players at Champions Golf Club for the Tour
Championship in October? Will it be Duval or Woods taking home
player-of-the-year honors?
</P>
<P>
   Will either win a major this year?
</P>
<P>
   Have we seen the last of Fred Couples and Greg Norman in the
winner's circle?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are questions. And answers will be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   There are 48 official-money events on the PGA Tour this season.
A little more than half of them have been played, and traditionally
the British Open signifies the beginning of the second half of the
tour season. Many of the players already have hauled themselves
over the pond to begin preparations for next week's tournament at
Carnoustie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mysteries that will unfold:
</P>
<P>
   Who will make the Ryder moves?
</P>
<P>
   There are six weeks left before the Ryder Cup teams are
finalized. There are a lot of players still looking to earn spots
on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of fellows that are trying very hard,'' U.S.
captain Ben Crenshaw says. ``The last few weeks, it's getting a
little more on their minds. All of the fellows you see from eight,
nine and on down still have to perform the rest of this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the players closing in on a spot on the team is Hal
Sutton. He is sixth on the points list, and one more top-10 finish
probably would clinch a spot for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the points I have are a cinch yet,'' Sutton
says. ``So I need to keep accumulating points to the best of my
ability because I really very much would like to be on the Ryder
Cup team. So every week when I show up, I think about that. And I'd
certainly like to accumulate enough as quickly as possible, so that
I don't have to sweat it out to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum is Duval. He is No. 1 on the
points list, and Crenshaw already has told Duval to get ready
because he is going to be playing every match.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval's mentality isn't necessarily focused on the Ryder
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as the end-all, be-all thing in golf that a lot
of other people seem to view it,'' Duval says. ``I'm not going to
be playing halfway, not trying. I will be ready to go, don't get me
wrong. But I'm not going to be bedridden for a month if we get
beat. It's not going to destroy me or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every intention of giving it my best. So please don't
take what I say the wrong way. I just have heard some European
players remark that it's the biggest event in golf to them. I just
don't see it that way. If I had to choose between a U.S. Open and a
Ryder Cup, I mean, there's not much of a choice for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Two majors down. Two to go.
</P>
<P>
   And neither of the first two was won by Duval or Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't win a major, I don't win a major,'' Woods says. ``I
know I've had a very successful year so far. I've won four times.
I'm very pleased with the way I've been playing. To win major
championships, you not only have to put yourself in a good
position, but you have to get lucky. The point is, you've got to
give yourself a chance in each and every major on the back nine on
Sunday with a chance to win. You never know what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will be in Houston in late October for the Tour
Championship?
</P>
<P>
   At the current rate, it appears it will take between $1.2
million and $1.4 million to make the top 30 in money this season,
which qualifies a player for the tournament at Champions Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of big-name players who would be missing if the
tournament started now.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there are nearly four months of golf left between
now and then. And the way this season is going, it will be four
memorable months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
