</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY_OLSON-DBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ALL ELSE FAILS, STICK WITH OLSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All he wants is another chance. Another opportunity to make
things right.
</P>
<P>
   But as he sits inside his cubicle at Bank One Ballpark, Gregg
Olson knows last call may have come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they're going to do,'' Olson said. ``But I
think I've been pushed. And the next time I get the ball, I'm going
out there with nothing on my mind but destroying as many of the
opposition as I can destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   As crazy and contradictory as the notion sounds, a bit of advice
for the teetering Diamondbacks: If attempts to acquire a legitimate
closer fall by the wayside, wipe the slate clean. Let Olson clear
his mind over the All-Star break. And when the second half begins,
give him what he covets.
</P>
<P>
   One more chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt I can go out and do what I did last year,''
Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, ignore all the bouquets on the periphery. Forget
the four All-Stars and the cover story in ``USA Today.'' The
Diamondbacks have lost their mojo, and if you're looking for omens,
it rained inside BOB on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Like the bullpen, the roof sprang a serious leak. And just like
the roof, the bullpen can be fixed with one phone call, a fact not
lost on Jerry Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the NBA draft, Colangelo sat on the side of the
makeshift podium. As he watched his baseball team lose another game
on television, you could almost see the steam coming from his ears.
The anger would dissipate, but the patience has finally expired.
</P>
<P>
   By his directive, the pursuit of a closer has now intensified.
The phone is ringing, and no one's demanding Travis Lee any longer.
The mind-set is focused on making a deal. Now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back to the NBA Finals in 1976,'' Colangelo said. ``I'm
standing in the Boston Garden. Red Auerbach is being interviewed on
one end of the court and I'm being interviewed on the other end. I
remember thinking that it was only the start, that I'd be at a lot
of these things. Well, it took 17 years to get back. So the moral
of the story is, when you have a chance to win, you go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo confirmed that the Diamondbacks have targeted
Montreal's Ugueth Urbina and Florida's Matt Mantei, and the
bartering has begun. Urbina is a big-time fireman who would make an
instant impact. Mantei is a grade below, but clearly better than
anyone currently warming up in the D-Backs' bullpen. Either one is
more than welcome in this space.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the Marlins are uncertain whether to peddle Mantei,
and the Expos are content to take their time, dangle Urbina in the
wind, wait for the best offer. As much as Colangelo wants it to
happen, there is no guarantee anything will get done.
</P>
<P>
   No one comes close
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to closers, the demand far outweighs the supply.
And no matter how bad things may seem, it makes no sense to trade
away the farm without acquiring a proven pitcher, a reliever with a
track record of posting the 27th out.
</P>
<P>
   It's also painfully obvious that the in-house parade of
successors have failed in trying to win the closer's role.
</P>
<P>
   Olson comes off the disabled list today, and says he's
completely healthy. He claims to have found a new trick in the
bullpen, a way to be more effective against right-handed hitters.
And he insists his confidence is just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm ever going to lose the mentality,'' Olson
said. ``I don't think I'll ever be afraid to go out there in
pressure situations. So it becomes a matter of stuff, and my stuff
is better than it has been in a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to earn everyone's trust back. But June, July,
August and September is my time of the year. And I'm really looking
forward to getting the ball again.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the best option, but neither is pushing the panic
button. And in a worst-case scenario, they should reinstate Olson.
Even if it's the most unpopular move since Coolergate. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
