<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS' BASH  
 5 HOMERS WALLOP ASTROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks put their home-run shoes back on Wednesday
night and jogged around the bases five times to equal a club record
in a 13-7 victory over the Houston Astros at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona raised its record to 46-39 and climbed to within two
games of San Francisco in the National League West Division after
the Giants lost at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, which fell to 47-36, got home runs from ``Killer B's''
Craig Biggio (solo shot in the first inning) and Jeff Bagwell
(three-run blast in the third) off left-hander Brian Anderson to
take a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona then took control with six runs in the third, hitting
three home runs off right-hander Wade Miller, who was making his
major-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams hit a two-run shot, catcher Damian
Miller a three-run blast and shortstop Andy Fox a solo homer to
make the score 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Steve Finley capped the team's scoring with a
two-run homer in the sixth and another two-run smash in the
seventh. The homers gave Arizona the league lead with 116.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell, named the starter at second base for the National
League team team in next week's All-Star game in Boston's Fenway
Park, had four hits, including a club-record three doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson struggled for the most part and was followed to the
mound by right-hander Bobby Chouinard, left-hander Greg Swindell
and right-hander Vladimir Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   Chouinard, recalled from Triple-A Tucson for the third time this
season on Saturday, got credit for his second victory.
</P>
<P>
   He also was the winning pitcher in Arizona's 7-6, 16-inning
victory over Los Angeles on April 13. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
