<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-JOHN     07-08 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-JOHNSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON CONFIDENT WINS TO COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strikeouts are a bonus. But give Diamondbacks pitcher Randy
Johnson wins. That's what drives the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   He knows they'll come again, even if it means topping what he's
done in his last three starts.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out 43, gave up a total of 16 hits and four runs, and
lost all three complete-game efforts with a total of three hits and
zero runs for support.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Wednesday he is not frustrated by his efforts and
isn't critical of an offense that lately has disappeared when he
takes the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be fine,'' said Johnson, who, despite the three
recent tough-luck losses, was chosen by Manager Bruce Bochy of the
San Diego Padres as one of the National League pitchers for
Tuesday's All-Star Game in Boston. ``The offense carried us and now
the pitching needs to step up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it means pitching better than what I have been, then pitch
better than what you have. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was short with the media after his last start, a 1-0
loss to St. Louis on Monday. He walked away after fielding four
questions.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, after throwing more than 130 pitches in the searing
St. Louis afternoon heat and humidity, his legs were cramping and
he was feeling more fatigued than frustrated by the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to give my time, win or lose,'' Johnson said. ``The
reason I didn't give enough of my time was because I was beat, I
was tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sit there for a half an hour and go right to the training
room after that and lay down . . . The reason I'm saying that is
because some reporters didn't understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, said he understands how baseball goes in cycles and
he can't let a defeat consume him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1990, I lost eight straight games,'' he said. ``I was
frustrated then as a young player. I'm a veteran player now. I'm a
mature player. That's part of baseball. I've won close games and
I've lost them. There's nothing to be ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   The efforts Johnson gives impresses third baseman Matt Williams.
That competitiveness, that want and will to win, is what the
Diamondbacks admire about Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize every time he goes out there on the mound, we can
be part of something very special,'' Williams said. ``He's a
no-hitter waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Astros closer Billy Wagner found out with Johnson on
Wednesday, while playing golf together, that they were chosen for
the All-Star Game. This is Wagner's first. Wagner got to know
Johnson last season when Johnson was traded from the Seattle
Mariners to the Astros. Both throw serious heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good person to learn from, for me especially,'' said
Wagner, who has 21 saves. ``He's always been supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down there and gave up five runs (in a game last season)
and he hollers at me and says, `Hey, it's going to be all right.'
That's nice to have that support.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's next start is Saturday against the Oakland Athletics
at Bank One Ballpark and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be frustrated if I wasn't pitching well,'' he said. ``How
can you be frustrated as a ballplayer when someone is doing their
job better to beat you?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he was prepared not to make the All-Star Game,
which will be his sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wins and losses are really what seems to catch people's eyes,
and rightfully so,'' he said. ``That's your job, to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Strikeouts are nice, he says, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Strikeouts didn't win any of my last ballgames. I didn't
strike out the guy that got the base hit and the RBI.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
