A2717 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-D-BACKS_ALL-STARS     07-08 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-D-BACKS_ALL-STARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STAR, VETERAN STAR: GONZALEZ, JOHNSON ADDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luis Gonzalez has never put himself above anybody. He is
grateful just to be able to put on a major league uniform and go to
work.
</P>
<P>
   But, on Tuesday, the Diamondbacks left fielder will be living a
dream, standing among the best in baseball as he's introduced as an
All-Star at Boston's Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's goal is to try to get to the World Series, but to
be recognized as one of the elite players to get to an All-Star
Game definitely means a lot to myself,'' Gonzalez said Wednesday
after being selected by Manager Bruce Bochy of the San Diego Padres
as one of the National League All-Star reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, making his first All-Star appearance, will join a
veteran of this gala, left-hander Randy Johnson, who was picked
Wednesday by Bochy as one of the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time Johnson will be on the National League
side. Five times, he was an American League All-Star for the
Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson expressed surprise that he was chosen, despite having
200 strikeouts and a 3.03 earned-run average. In his past three
starts, he struck out 43 but lost all of them with a total of three
hits for offensive support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked, first of all, that I made it,'' Johnson said.
``My record is 9-6.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, scheduled to pitch Saturday against the Oakland
Athletics, will find out Monday whether he'll be the NL starter.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is honored just to be chosen for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To start, that would be a great honor,'' Johnson said. ``But
you have pitchers in the National League who have more wins, and I
think they're probably more deserving.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter felt both players were deserving, along
with third baseman Matt Williams and second baseman Jay Bell, who
were voted in as starters by the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Four Diamondbacks in the All-Star Game shows how far the
franchise has come in only its second season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, center fielder Devon White, now with the Los Angeles
Dodgers, was the lone Diamondback representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very proud moment for all of us, especially for the
four guys selected,'' Showalter said. ``My tip of the hat to Bruce
Bochy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a tough decision, being there (managing the AL
All-Stars in '95) and knowing everything involved. I think he made
a real good choice with Luis. I'm very proud of what Randy has
accomplished and the things he's done for us. He's certainly very
worthy of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine an All-Star Game without him there.''
</P>
<P>
   With two days' rest, it is uncertain how much Johnson will pitch
in the game. But Showalter is certain, whatever it is, Johnson will
give it his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody thinks Randy is going to warm up and pitch against
the best players in baseball in front of the world and not give his
best effort doesn't know Randy very well,'' Showalter said. ``It's
not like he's going to go out there and throw batting practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been living a sort of fairy tale since he was
traded by the Detroit Tigers to the Diamondbacks last winter. No
disrespect to the Tigers, but he said he could have walked to his
home in Sugar Land, Texas, after receiving the news a few days
after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   He's been ``riding the wave,'' he said, since then, and isn't
ready to get off any time soon, putting up career numbers. He led
the league in hits with 112 entering Wednesday's game and was third
in the league in hitting at .359.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Diamondbacks didn't put Gonzalez on the All-Star
ballot, a write-in campaign, spearheaded by local sports radio host
Brad Cesmat, was successful. The final votes have yet to be
released, but the number could be around a half million, Cesmat
said he was told. That would put him among the top 10 for his
position in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless, if it was 100,000 or 1, I greatly appreciated what
Brad did at the station, generating some excitement, and people
taking time out to do it,'' Gonzalez said. ``Little kids to adults
to older people, everybody was rallying around me and that means a
lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez could probably walk to Boston after Sunday afternoon's
game, but he'll take a plane with Bell, Williams and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little kid every day I go to the ballpark,'' Gonzalez
said. ``I get to do this every day. Millions of people want to do
this. Now, I get to do something that not many players get to
do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
