r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-SPARKS-MERCURY-AZ     07-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-MERCURY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY MAY HAVE CURE FOR AILING OFFENSE IN LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was no win for the gimper Wednesday night, but the Mercury
might have stumbled upon a cure for its lame offense.
</P>
<P>
   With forward Clarissa Davis-Wrightsil ruled out of the second
half due to a foot injury, Phoenix went with a three-guard lineup
that infused speed and life into a team shooting even worse (25.9
percent) than in its record low shooting and scoring Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet 51.6 percent from the field in the second half was not
enough to overcome 48 percent from the free throw line overall as
the Mercury (3-8) lost, 67-61, to the Los Angeles Sparks (9-4)
before an encouraging 11,363 at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without Coach Cheryl Miller, at home recovering from
surgery to repair a ruptured Achilles tendon suffered at the start
of practice Tuesday, Phoenix continued its free fall from the 1998
near penthouse to the Western Conference cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Now 7.5 games behind Houston, the Mercury is 4.5 games out of
playoff position a little more than a third into the 32-game
season. And coming to town Friday are the two-time champion Comets
(11-1), nearly upset by Phoenix in the 1998 WNBA Finals that seem a
lifetime ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so emotional at this stage,'' Phoenix point guard Michele
Timms said. ``We're 3-8 and every game we come back in here and
players are all in tears. It's a different experience for us this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying our guts out. If you didn't see that tonight, I
don't know what you were watching. We never gave in, and we're
trying so hard to get it right, but we just haven't got it right
just yet. It feels like it's coming, but we can't afford to wait
any longer. We're all so desperate out there, but we just can't
seem to come up with a W.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire tone of the game changed with guards Edna Campbell
and Bridget Pettis on the floor together to start the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix scored the first two buckets on a 13-footer by Campbell
and Pettis on break layup, off a full-court pass from Campbell, to
erase most of a 28-22 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury led for the first time since 3-0 off a series in
which 5-foot-5 Kristi Harrower came up with two offensive rebounds,
allowing a third chance that Marlies Askamp converted from eight
feet for 45-44. A Pettis 3-pointer, the one of 13 that Phoenix hit,
made it 50-48 with 8:25 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Pettis said she has suggested the three-guard lineup to Miller,
whose NBA All-Star brother Reggie flew to town to offer support and
was at the game, but seemingly since Campbell was drafted, the
coaches have tried to decide between the two while starting
Davis-Wrightsil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought playing with Edna was a great combination on the
floor, and was finally got to do it,'' Pettis said. ``We really ran
the floor, and that's something the old Mercury used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell and Pettis combined for 17 points. Most significantly,
the Mercury outscored a team in the paint, 30-26, for the first
time all season and had an 11-6 advantage in fast-break points. At
halftime, LA led 18-8 in points in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun playing with Bridget,'' Campbell said. ``But I'm not
the coach, I don't make the decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   LA scored seven straight points, five by Mwadi Mabika, to go up
55-50, and the Mercury could pull no closer than one in the final
6:25.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Gillom, who had a game-high 17 points, fouled out with
1:40 left to take away Phoenix's best weapon with LA leading 61-58.
Lisa Leslie converted both free throws off that foul then Campbell
missed a jumper, and the Sparks' franchise-record sixth consecutive
win was assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not have put ourselves in the position to have to
work so hard to win,'' LA Coach Orlando Woolridge said. ``We
allowed their fans in the game and they came at us, but we found a
way to get the win. It was very physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolridge was hit with a technical for objecting to a foul, and
Timms got a T for defending Gillom after a flagrant foul by DeLisha
Milton. Then Timms was hit with a flagrant foul vs. Leslie with
4:35 remaining. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
