<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_ASSISTANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES ROUND OUT STAFF  
 BOWNESS, FLEMMING TO ASSIST FRANCIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Coyotes' newest brain trust is finally complete with the
addition Wednesday of veteran NHL head Coach Rick Bowness and Wayne
Flemming to fill first-year head Coach Bob Francis' coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the guys I wanted off the bat,'' Francis said. ``I
talked to up-and-coming guys and to some even more experienced.
These guys are quality people who are knowledgeable and who _ I
feel is very important _ know to communicate in a manner that
players respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick has been head coach of three teams and all three worked
very hard and were always well prepared. Wayne has coached overseas
and is extremely knowledgeable of the technical aspects of the
game. I feel very privileged to have them on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith had said he hoped to
surround Francis with someone who has NHL head coaching experience.
It was accomplished with Bowness, who actually has coached four NHL
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Bowness, 41, returns to the franchise where he served 28 games
as the interim head coach in the 1988-89 season, replacing Dan
Maloney after two seasons and 52 games when the team was located in
Winnipeg. He ended his NHL playing days with the Jets, and had been
with the Atlanta Flames, Detroit and St. Louis in an eight-year
career.
</P>
<P>
   Bowness was head coach at Boston in 1991-92, leading the Bruins
to a 36-32-12 record and to the Eastern Conference finals before
losing to Pittsburgh, the eventual Stanley Cup champion. He was
head coach of expansion Ottawa in 1992 and led it through the
growing pains, serving 3{ seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bowness, who spent last season as a consultant for the expansion
Nashville Predators, likes his new setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of meetings with Bob and we share a lot of
common ideas. A coaching staff works closely together and I
wouldn't put myself in a position where it didn't. The head coach
makes the final decisions, but you have to support each other, give
input to reach decisions. I think we will do well together.''
</P>
<P>
   One major job the new staff has is putting teeth in a power play
that was the NHL's second worst last season.
</P>
<P>
   Flemming coached the Islanders' power play and it's considered
his forte. It's a role that Francis also flourished in with Boston
last season, and Bowness, as a head coach, has had to oversee all
aspects so all are knowledgeable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong point of Wayne's but I don't believe in making
it one guy's responsibility,'' Francis said. ``If the power play
goes bad, I'll take the blame. If it goes good, we'll share credit.
Ultimately, it's my responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought three heads are better than one. We will
all chip in our ideas and Wayne will oversee their execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Flemming, 51, was head coach at the University of Manitoba for
eight years, where he still holds school records for wins and games
coached.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as Bowness' assistant in 1997-98 with the
Islanders, after serving as assistant coach/general manager of the
Canadian National Team, which he helped guide to a silver medal in
the 1992 Winter Olympics at Albertville, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne is an excellent hockey man,'' Bowness said. ``He's a
loyal, hard-working guy. He was a big help to me with the Islanders
and he's a guy you would want on any staff. He coached our power
play and had it among the top four or five in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   While Francis is approaching his first NHL season as head coach,
he has years of minor league and NHL experience as an assistant and
likes the bench knowledge the trio represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bench management is very important,'' Francis said. ``Rick has
been through it all and can slap me in the head if I get too
excited. Wayne is very a calm person, a technical coach who can
talk one-on-one as the play is occuring, and I believe in
on-the-job teaching. Some coaches like to wear a headset and be
linked with somebody in the press box giving suggestions, but I
believe in correcting something when it happens as opposed to
waiting to do it later on. We've all been in the hole before and
can do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
