<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2721 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-MEN'SJUNIORWORLD-     07-08 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-MEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENTLEMAN PREFERS BLOND  
 BLEACHED-LOOK CALIFORNIA STAR ENTERS NEW LEVEL 
</HEADLINE>
 JUNIOR WORLD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only 55-point scorer on the USA Basketball Men's Junior
World Championship Team has a logical explanation for his new,
bleached-blond locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only player from California,'' 6-foot-6 swingman Casey
Jacobsen said. ``The rest of the guys just think it's the Cali
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, the career Southern California high school scoring
leader trying out for the U.S. team this week in Tempe, doesn't
have to explain himself to his parents.
</P>
<P>
   They not only approve of his hairstyle, they encourage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom likes the look,'' said Jacobsen, who will be a freshman at
Stanford. ``She wants me to do it, and it's the fourth time I've
done it. She does it for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen, a native of Glendora, Calif., did little during his
high school career that didn't make his family proud.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 3,284 points, the second most in California history.
His senior year was an off year. He averaged ``only'' 31 points per
game, down from the 32 he averaged the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   He also was selected a John Wooden scholar in honor of the
legendary UCLA basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   On great nights, Jacobsen scored in the 50s. On off nights, he
was held under 30. Not once did he score in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't set out my high school career trying to break that
record,'' Jacobsen said of the California state scoring mark. ``In
fact, I had a few awful nights. Twelve points was my low.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, I struggled with my shooting. I wasn't strong
enough. I was very skinny. It took me a while to learn to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I learned is that you will have streaks.
Sometimes, you'll go 0 for 10. Sometimes, you'll got 10 for 10. My
goal is to go 10 for 10. That's why I have to shoot a million J's
(jump shots).''
</P>
<P>
   He learned to shoot playing against his older brothers, Adam and
Brock, on the family's backyard court.
</P>
<P>
   Their dad, Von, who played at San Diego State, is a carpenter
and built the court, one Jacobsen calls ``the nicest backyard court
I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned by osmosis from watching my brothers shoot,''
Jacobsen said. ``I watched them have good shooting games and bad. I
experienced it living with two perimeter shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're around something so long, you just start to pick
up on things you might not even think about. Even being in a car
with them after their games, I'd hear them discuss what happened
and what they thought they could improve on. I remembered almost
everything, and maybe that's how I got my style of play.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being the top scorer in California last year, Jacobsen
had to prove he belonged on the same court as many of the nation's
best high school players.
</P>
<P>
   He showed that in the 1999 McDonald's All-America Game, when he
scored 22 points in 24 minutes for the West team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had something to prove,'' said Jacobsen, who
picked Stanford over Utah and Duke. ``No one (nationally) had seen
me. I didn't go to the Nike camp. I was not as high-profile as many
of the high school players. It wasn't pressure I was under in the
all-star games. I was just excited to show people what I could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody had any doubts I could play at the next level, I
wanted to show people and put that aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State Coach Rob Evans, the head coach of the USA Junior
World team, doesn't have any doubts that Jacobsen will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will be a great player in the Pac-10,'' Evans said.
``Not only is he a great shooter, he's a very tough competitor. You
can't wear him out. He goes hard every single play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let up on him, he might hit for five or six baskets in
a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobsen thinks the physical style of the USA team's practices
will get him ready for the Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what college (basketball) is going to be
like, but I can't imagine it being more difficult than this,''
Jacobsen said. ``This is like a college experience because many of
the players here are bigger and stronger than me. People say the
biggest transition from high school to college is to learn to play
a physical game. So I won't be in awe when I realize how big and
strong (college) people will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
