   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ Moving swiftly to make good on his
pledges to restart the stalled Middle East peace effort, Ehud Barak
announced as he moved into the prime minister's office that he will
hold a series of meetings with Arab leaders and President Clinton
in the coming days. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   PENTAGON-EUROPE (Washington) _ The Pentagon is aggressively
pursuing a policy encouraging trans-Atlantic mergers in the defense
industry, using its Kosovo experience to talk directly with
European allies and major defense contractors in Europe in a new
push for cooperative agreements. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISTS-UAE (Washington) _ U.S. officials say they believe
that two suspected terrorists wanted by the FBI have received help
through two Persian Gulf countries with close ties to Washington,
complicating the administration's counterterrorism efforts. By
James Risen with Benjamin Weiser
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LIBYA (London) _ Britain announced that it will resume
ties with Libya, which agreed to pay compensation for the killing
of a policeman outside its London Embassy in 1984. By Warren Hoge.
