<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTES-AZR &LR;      07-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON REITERATES PREFERENCE TO RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Manager Bryan Colangelo, between a trip to scout a
summer pro league in Los Angeles and a family trip to Disneyland,
has begun discussions with a number of agents representing NBA free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have two salary cap exceptions to use on free agents _
for $1 million and $2 million. But Colangelo said the most
important negotiations are with the club's own top free agent,
forward Clifford Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had conversations with a number of agents, but I can't
elaborate on any of those,'' Colangelo said. ``And as well, we've
taken the opportunity to speak to representatives for our own free
agents, particularly Clifford. Our main priority is to take care of
Clifford.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams were free to begin negotiating with free agents on July 1.
But no deals can be made until Aug. 1. Robinson, reached at his
Portland, Ore., home, said he has been contacted by several NBA
teams, but his preference is to remain in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's interest out there,'' said Robinson, 32. ``But at this
point, it's still kind of early in the process. The main people I'm
interested in talking to are the Suns.''
</P>
<P>
   The collective bargain rules allow Robinson, as a so-called
``early Bird free agent,'' to receive 175 percent of his salary of
last season, which was about $3.5 million, or the league average,
whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   For Robinson, who made more than the league average last season,
the 175 percent raise means he can sign a pact that begins at about
$6.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a bad position to be in,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The point of contention will be the length of the contract. By
rule, the Suns could offer a maximum of seven years with annual
increases of about $730,000 _ or a total of $58.6 million for a
seven-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   But there also is an ``over-36'' age rule, which places cap
restrictions on long-term deals once a player passes age 36, which
complicates Robinson's deal. As a result, the Suns are not likely
to offer a contract of more than four years, which would pay about
$29 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get as many years as I can, of course,'' Robinson
said. ``I'm dealing with a credible organization, so I don't doubt
they'll do whatever they can for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had two good years for them. I'm fitting in very well,
and Jason (Kidd) and I played well together last season.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Robinson said if a team with a better chance
to win a championship made a comparable offer, he would have to
consider it. But he said that isn't likely to happen because of
salary cap restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think the Suns are probably in the best position to
take care of me even close to what I would like,'' he said. &QL;  &QL; 
In training &QL;  &QL; 
Kidd, a guard, and forward Tom Gugliotta reported for the start of
USA Basketball's pre-Olympic training camp Tuesday in Orlando. They
are part of the 12-man USA men's Select Team that will compete July
14-25 in San Juan, Puerto Rico. The Americans are heavily favored
to win one of the two berths from the Americas to the 2000 Olympics
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team will wrap up its training camp Saturday with an
exhibition game against Team Canada, featuring former Suns guard
Steve Nash. &QL;  &QL; 
Summer plans &QL;  &QL; 
The Suns will hold a rookie/free agent camp beginning July 23, then
will have a team at the Rocky Mountain Revue summer league in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The summer Suns will play five games in Utah. In addition to the
club's newcomers, young players such as Pat Garrity, Gerald Brown
and Randy Livingston get an opportunity to work on their games
within the club's system.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft pick Shawn Marion also may participate in the
LA summer pro league.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd tournament &QL;  &QL; 
Kidd will play host to his first Jason Kidd Celebrity Golf
Tournament on Sept. 24 at Estrella Mountain Ranch Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament offers golfers an opportunity to tee it up with
sports celebrities, and proceeds will benefit the Jason Kidd
Foundation, which provides funding for children's medical research
and charitable organizations supporting the needs of children. As
an example, Kidd and his wife, Joumana, recently launched Kidd
Shots, a free immunization program for local youth. For tournament
information, call (602) 607-1633. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
