<HEADLINE>
YOUNG LATIN IMPORT DEFENSIVE STANDOUT IN OUTFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the name:  &UR; Luis Terrero.
</P>
<P>
   He's 18, 6 feet 2, 190 pounds and a defensive gem in center
field who appears to have the power, speed, arm and glove to be a
future star in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks hope so anyway. So far, they've been impressed
with what they've seen in Missoula, Mont., where Terrero has helped
their advanced Rookie team to 17 victories in its first 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   In 17 games, Terrero, a converted shortstop from the Dominican
Republic, was hitting .308 and led the Pioneer League with six home
runs. He also had 21 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   With a logjam at short, Terrero, signed last year by Latin
American scouting coordinator  &UR; Junior Noboa, was moved to center
field, where he's adjusted amazingly well, said  &UR; Tommy Jones, the
Diamondbacks' director of minor league operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really opened up a lot of eyes,'' Jones said. ``He has
major league defensive abilities, and he's showing progress with
the bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrero has drawn comparisons to New York Yankees outfielder
 &UR; Bernie
 &UR; Williams, but, Jones said, the comparisons are unfair at this
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a Bernie Williams-type body,'' Jones said. ``That's
where I'd end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a chance to be a five-tool category guy.'' &QL; 
Myers hurt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft pick  &UR; Corey Myers, playing shortstop at
Missoula, has been out of action for a week after fouling a pitch
off his left shin, which caused an infection. Myers, who graduated
in May from Desert Vista High, is expected back in the lineup
Friday, when the Osprey begin a home stand.
</P>
<P>
   Myers was hitting .290 with three homers and nine RBIs in 69 at
bats.
</P>
<P>
   He's made 11 errors in 16 games, ``but he's had some tough
chances early,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making all the routine plays now,'' Jones said. ``He's
the first to admit that the game is played at a much faster pace.
Everything is quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making the adjustment very well.'' &QL; 
Lefty luck &QL; 
Left-hander  &UR; Nick Bierbrodt didn't throw a pitch in his short stay
as a Diamondback, but the 21-year-old can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they want me to do, I'll do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Diamondbacks' first-ever draft pick is starting for
Triple-A Tucson, where, in his first two outings, he gave up one
earned run and struck out eight in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been real lucky,'' Bierbrodt said.
</P>
<P>
   Bierbrodt pitched at Double-A El Paso, before the Diamondbacks
called him up to the big club June 24. He was sent to Tucson four
days later.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Triple-A batters are more selective than those he
faced in El Paso, but, he said, he's gotten away with strikes up in
the zone in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both games I pitched, I would have gotten hammered in
Double-A,'' Bierbrodt said. ``My mechanics haven't been real good.
It comes and goes.'' &QL; 
Short hops &QL; 
Right-hander  &UR; Erik Sabel has been a pleasant surprise as a starter
in Tucson. He has won four games without a defeat and has a 2.77
ERA. He has struck out 26 in 48 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
