<HEADLINE>
ROOF CAN'T KEEP FANS DRY DURING STORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The swimming pool wasn't the only area at Bank One Ballpark
where people got wet on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A group of fans sitting in areas underneath the the large
affixed truss that holds up the retractable roof on the ballpark's
south side got a surprise shower early in the game as the result of
rain being blown inside from a small area where the roof overhangs
the truss.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks team President Rich Dozer said that there is a one-
to two-foot gap where large wheels move the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that there would be a possibility for water and wind
coming in on the north and south sides if the conditions were just
right. If it were from the east or west, this wouldn't have
happened. This is something that is rarely going to happen,'' Dozer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind would have to be coming straight in from either of
those directions, and apparently, it was tonight. I went outside
and the street poles were really bending back and forth. We had a
bad storm last night (Tuesday night), too, but it wasn't anything
like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no hole in the roof itself. The water was essentially
sucked up and into the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously don't want the fans to have discomfort, but it
looked to me like most were being good-natured about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One fan in the upper deck came prepared, opening his
red-and-white umbrella for a brief period.
</P>
<P>
   Quipped managing general partner Jerry Colangelo, who was dry in
his front-row perch next to the Arizona dugout: ``We're going to
tell them to keep their ticket stubs in case we have a
rain-out.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer to a closer? &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks inched closer to landing a closer on Wednesday,
talking to the Montreal Expos about right-hander Ugueth Urbina and
the Florida Marlins about right-hander Matt Mantei.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the people we are concentrating on, yes, but there
are others who we are considering,'' said General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr., confirming published reports. ``It's so hard to tell
how these things are going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As to which players the Diamondbacks might be offering, the
focus seems to be on one of two top pitching prospects, either
left-hander Nick Bierbrodt or right-hander John Patterson, perhaps
another minor league position prospect and maybe even a player from
the current 25-man roster. One name that was floating about before
Wednesday night's game was that of outfielder David Dellucci.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said that while the club is reluctant to part with top
prospects, ``it's always the case that you have to do what you
might not like in order to get a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said, ``These teams haven't put their signs out. You
have to approach them sometimes. You have to try to keep a balance
in what you're willing to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
