<SLUG> BC-GLF-USSENIOR-OPEN-JACOBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MORE DRIVEN MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, John Jacobs probably couldn't have
picked a better site for playing a U.S. Senior Open than Des Moines
Golf and Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, coming off two solid finishes in the past two Senior PGA
Tour events, is among the pros who'll tee off today on the
6,904-yard course in West Des Moines, Iowa, which is hosting its
first major event.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs leads the senior tour in driving distance with an average
of 286.6 yards, and finds himself on a course that is forgiving of
errant shots as Open courses go.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my game,'' the Scottsdale golfer said by phone after
his practice round Wednesday. ``If I drive the ball well, I play
well. If I don't, I'm down the road. This course is more generous
than most of the Open courses I've played on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it caters to a longer hitter. If I can just explain to
my ball what I want it to do, I'll be in good shape. My ball might
not know I'm leading in driving distance or what direction I want
it to go.''
</P>
<P>
   This year started with the ball doing exactly what Jacobs wanted
as he won the season-opening MasterCard Championship, formerly
known as the Senior Tournament of Champions, in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant a lot because all of the top players are there and
it lets you know you can compete on their level,'' Jacobs said. ``I
always knew I could drink on their level, but wasn't sure if I
could play on their level.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, 54, always has been known as a free spirit, who lived
life to the fullest in his younger years but didn't take advantage
of his talents as a golfer.
</P>
<P>
   His resume includes giving lessons to Vietnamese Premier Nguyen
Cao Ky, but not much in the way of PGA Tour prowess, as he earned
just $119,790 from 1968 through '80. He later played Asian and
European tours and led the Asian money list in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played with him quite a few times on the Western States
Tour, and we were pretty competitive with each other,'' Papago Golf
Course pro Joe Huber said. ``But he's improved his game, and that's
what happens when you get on a tour and start competing on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both went to qualifying school (in 1986), and he made it
and I didn't. The last couple times I've seen him, he's really been
swinging the clubs well. In his younger years, he was free-spirited
and wasn't really committed to his golf game. He's gotten more
serious about it and it shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' breakthrough came in '96, when he tied for second at
Q-school and won $510,263, finishing 23rd on the money list. He
moved up to 12th the next year, was 15th last year, and this year
ranks eighth with earnings of $713,947. In 19 events, he has eight
top-10 finishes and 11 in the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs admits he lost focus for a while after his Jan. 24
victory in Hawaii, and it showed with a string of disappointing
finishes until he took third two weeks ago in the Ford Senior
Players Championship in Dearborn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   He followed that last week with a tie for sixth in the State
Farm Senior Classic. Jacobs also played well in the PGA Seniors
Championship in April, tying for eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In his three Senior Opens thus far, Jacobs' best finish has been
a tie for 17th in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am playing pretty well and I feel good about my game right
now,'' Jacobs said. ``But when you get over 50, you just take it
week to week. You don't get that same adrenaline rush you did when
you were younger. Sometimes you wake up with a bad this and a bad
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does look like a course I can play well on, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open will be the biggest golf event staged in Iowa and
already has been a stunning success at the gate. The tournament was
sold out in advance for the first time in Senior Open history, and
the practice rounds drew crowds of 25,000 Monday, 27,000 Tuesday
and 29,000 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hale Irwin and tour rookies Allen Doyle and Bruce Fleisher, with
three victories each this year, are the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, who won the Ford Seniors, ranks third on the money list
and is trying to become the third to win back-to-back titles in the
Senior Open. Doyle, whose victories include the PGA Seniors
Championship, tops the list and Fleisher is second.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this course, I think it's pretty wide open this week,''
Jacobs said. ``Now that I say that, Hale will probably win by 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``As big as his house is, he better win a few of these things.
Have you seen it? I drove by it the other day and it's the biggest
. . . thing I've ever seen. I don't know how anybody can afford
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin won last year after opening with a 77, the highest
one-round score for a winner in the history of the senior tour. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
