<HEADLINE>
MONARCHS SLIGHTED  IN VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
 ALL-STAR-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Basketball League and Sacramento Monarchs were the
biggest losers in WNBA All-Star voting.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 10 starters selected by fans for next week's game is
out of the ABL, with the highest vote-getter out of that defunct
league being Orlano's Taj McWilliams, who has better numbers than
starter Kym Hampton of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The real crime, though, is that Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith,
another former ABL player with Most Valuable Player-type
statistics, is not starting ahead of Houston's Tina Thompson as a
West forward. Thompson remains an important cog for the Houston
Comets, but Griffith has elevated the Monarchs from last place to a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   And Sacramento second-year point guard Ticha Penicheiro, who
leads the league in assists and is seventh in steals, deserves to
start ahead of the Mercury's Michele Timms. In assist-turnover
ratio, Penicheiro is at 1.71 compared with 1.58 for Timms, third in
league assists through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the 34-year-old Timms is having a bad season. But
Penicheiro and Griffith deserve to be rewarded for Sacramento's 8-4
start and probably will be among the West reserves named today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my all-around game, I'm playing much better this year
than the last two years,'' Timms said. ``I feel really confident
and really good, especially defensively. I feel much quicker
defensively, and none of the point guards has scored on me this
season. In fact because the (shooting guards) and (small forwards)
from the other teams have been scoring, they've been having me on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition starting point guards, including Penicheiro twice,
are averaging 7.0 points vs. Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
