<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS POUND MOYER, HANDING M'S LEFTY HIS FIRST LOSS SINCE MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When the first words in manager Lou Piniella's
postgame news conference are a calling to God, it's easy to tell
how the night went for the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   For the second night in a row, the Anaheim Angels used a six-run
inning to sink Seattle. This time, the final was 10-3, and the loss
dropped the M's five games behind the division-leading Texas
Rangers, who won Wednesday in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played like a tired team tonight,'' Piniella said. ``I
think we can use the day off today.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Jamie Moyer lasted 42/3 innings, his shortest outing of
the season, and lost for the first time in 13 starts. Moyer (8-5),
who had won his last seven decisions, allowed eight runs for the
first time since his last loss, to Toronto on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meanwhile, came into the game with the fewest runs
scored in the American League and a patchwork lineup beyond the
four veterans at the top of the order. But they broke out against
Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good hitters,'' Moyer said. ``They probably haven't
been swinging the bats the way they'd like over the last week or
couple of weeks. Tonight they swung the bats well. They were very
aggressive and didn't back down. I probably didn't make adjustments
when I needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, who lost eight pounds in the Texas heat in a no-decision
last Friday, said he wasn't tired or drained Wednesday night. But
there's little doubt he can use the eight days of rest before his
next start, in the opening game at Safeco Field on July 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's given us an awful lot of innings,'' pitching coach Stan
Williams said. ``So the break might be coming at just the right
time for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed seven earned runs on 10 hits, by seven different
Angels. Mo Vaughn had the first, a towering homer that struck the
right-field foul pole and gave the Angels a 1-0 first-inning lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners went ahead in the second off knuckleballer Steve
Sparks. Alex Rodriguez, passed over for the American League
All-Star team earlier in the day, hit his sixth homer in five days
(No. 18 on the year). One batter later, designated hitter Butch
Huskey, starting in place of Edgar Martinez, who missed another
game with a tight left hamstring, followed with a homer of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But Anaheim quickly reclaimed the lead in its half of the
inning. Moyer hit Angels' DH Tim Unroe to lead off the second, and
singles by Reggie Williams, Gary DiSarcina and Darin Erstad gave
the Angels a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer worked a scoreless third and fourth, but could not escape
the fifth. Vaughn singled, Anderson reached on an infield hit, Troy
Glaus added a run-scoring double and Unroe an RBI single. When
Williams brought in two with a double over Ken Griffey Jr.'s head
in center field, Moyer was replaced by Ken Cloude.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude himself could not survive the inning. Three singles and a
Vaughn double drove Cloude from the game, and by the time Damaso
Marte retired Anderson on a comebacker, the Angels had built a
seven-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude allowed more than one run for the seventh time in 10
outings since moving to the bullpen in early June. He seemed to be
making progress in sideline drills with Williams in which he worked
on driving the ball to the outside corner. But the results haven't
showed in games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he threw well the last time (in Texas), even though
he gave up a few key runs,'' Williams said. ``Today, everything was
flat, and he never got an out. It didn't look like he was throwing
it very well tonight. It's a tough role to be in, long relief, but
you have to keep yourself pitching to the best of your ability.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Moyer has done in the first half, though he missed
out on an All-Star bid Piniella felt he deserved. With his own
first half over, Moyer was hopeful about the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a fun second half,'' he said. ``I think this
division is wide open. It's up for grabs. Texas is in the lead, and
there are three clubs chasing it. Anaheim has talent, Oakland has
talent and we have talent _ and the Rangers have talent as well
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come down to who wants it bad enough, because in
the first half, nobody's played that well, I don't think, in our
division. Nobody's taken it by the horns and run with it. The three
teams that are chasing are very fortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
