<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIAMONDBAC     07-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIAMONDBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks rip rookie starter &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ First it rained inside Bank One Ballpark, the result of a
leak in the retractable roof. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the rain was accompanied by thunder and
lightning, the result of a leak in the two pitching staffs on
display. A bomb shelter might not have provided the Astros enough
protection from the storm that was the Arizona Diamondbacks'
offense Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros allowed a season-high five home runs, including three
in the decisive sixth inning of a 13-7 loss that prevented them
from reclaiming first place in the National League Central
Division. The Astros remained percentage points behind Cincinnati,
which lost to St. Louis on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks broke the game open with six runs in the third
inning and held on to the lead behind the solid relief pitching of
Bobby Chouinard, Greg Swindell and Vladimir Nunez. Meanwhile, the
Astros' bullpen allowed six runs in relief of rookie Wade Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a horse, I'd shoot myself,'' lefthander Trever
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of heroes at the plate, led by All-Star second
baseman Jay Bell, who reached base in each of his five plate
appearances and had three doubles. Former Astro Steve Finley hit a
pair of two-run homers, while Matt Willliams and Damian Miller had
three RBIs apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' Craig Biggio, who also reached in all five plate
appearances, tied a career high with four hits and came within a
triple of hitting for the cycle. But the Biggio-led Astros were
unable to score with the frequency of the Diamondbacks, who won for
only the fifth time in 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Miller's major-league debut was hardly memorable. In fact,
it happened so quickly, there's a good chance the rookie won't
remember many of the gory details a couple of days from now. The
Diamondbacks shell-shocked the 22-year-old righthander, punishing
him for seven runs on eight hits in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous at first, but I calmed down after that,'' Wade
Miller said. ``I just didn't hit spots like I normally do. If you
make bad pitches at this level, they're probably going to hit them
for home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-inning stint matched the shortest outing by an Astros
starter this season. Shane Reynolds also was knocked out after
three innings May 8 against the Expos. The Astros plan to keep
Miller on the roster for the remainder of the week, although he
isn't expected to pitch in relief.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, he will return to Class AAA New Orleans after
the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade had velocity, and he made some good pitches, but he also
left a lot of pitches over the plate,'' interim manager Matt
Galante said. ``He started getting his pitches up, and he couldn't
get back down. You never know what you're going to get with
rookies, but this was a good experience for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential of Miller, pressed into duty because of Mike
Hampton's wrist injury, was evident during the brief outing, but
his lack of experience showed through.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Diamondbacks starter Brian Anderson has been around
for parts of the past five seasons, including an appearance in the
1997 World Series with the Cleveland Indians, and he didn't fare
much better.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pillaged Anderson for six runs on nine hits in 3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time this season and the 20th time in his career,
Biggio homered to start the Astros' first inning, sending a 1-2
pitch from Anderson into the left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks tied the score in the bottom of the inning when
Bell doubled and scored on Luis Gonzalez's looping single up the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bagwell's 27th homer, a three-run shot to left, gave the
Astros a 4-1 lead in the third inning, but once again the
Diamondbacks erased the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Williams, Damian Miller and Andy Fox combined for 1,138
feet worth of homers _ and six runs _ off the Astros rookie in the
bottom of the third. Wade Miller allowed only eight home runs in
101 innings while with New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wade lost his focus and his concentration after
Williams' home run,'' Galante said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros knocked Anderson out of the game with two runs in the
fourth, but the Diamondbacks then won the battle of the bullpens.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' franchise record for homers allowed in a game is
six, established at Wrigley Field on June 3, 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
