<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN; NO ALL-STAR TRIP FOR VAUGHN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mo Vaughn wouldn't be wrong if he wanted to stir it up
a little, but he won't do that.
</P>
<P>
   For only the second time in the past five seasons, Vaughn will
not be going to the All-Star Game. The Angels' only All-Star
representative is closer Troy Percival.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his numbers compare favorably to some players who
will be going to Boston's Fenway Park next week for the game,
Vaughn didn't complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed? Nah,'' Vaughn said before Wednesday night's
game, a 10-3 win over the Seattle Mariners before 23,623 at Edison
Field. ``If I were out there healthy the first part of the season,
I could make a case. But I started playing first base what, two
weeks ago? Had I been in my element...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to make any excuses, but that's the way it goes.
I'll look at it as a chance to take a load off _ it's going to be a
circus there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who sprained his ankle on opening night and missed 14
games, went 3 for 4 with a walk Wednesday, including his 17th homer
of the season in the first inning to give the Angels a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After back-to-back homers by Alex Rodriguez and Butch Huskey in
the top of the second inning made it 2-1, Mariners, the Angels
scored three times in the second to regain the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners cut the lead to 4-3 in the fourth inning, but the
Angels responded with a six-run fifth inning to take a 10-3 lead.
They had nine hits in the inning alone, including two by Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The game marked the end of a 15-game stretch against AL West
opponents for the Angels, during which they went 9-6. They've won
four of their last five series, the only series loss in that time
coming when they were swept by the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into that stretch knowing we had to play well,''
manager Terry Collins said. ``Obviously we didn't play well against
Texas, but against the other teams we did. We're happy about it.
Now we take a day off and get ready for the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughn, an All-Star appearance would have been a chance to
make a triumphant return to Boston, where he played eight seasons.
Instead, the Angels are in last place and the Red Sox are 12 games
over .500 and in the playoff hunt.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Jose Offerman. Many scoffed when the Red Sox
``replaced'' Vaughn by signing Offerman to a free-agent contract.
Offerman (.283, 3 homers, 35 RBI) was named to the All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's numbers (.288, 17 homers, 55 RBI) are better than
Offerman's, but Offerman is a second baseman. Cleveland's Jim
Thome, though, is a first baseman like Vaughn, but his numbers fall
short _ .276, 13 homers, 46 RBI). Thome was elected a starter by
the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd been selected, I'd be happy,'' Vaughn said. ``But I
know I didn't play like I know I can play. I don't want anything
given to me. The most important thing is you want to make the game
because you've been making the game. I'll try again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Steve Sparks (4-5) allowed 12 hits but only three
runs in eight innings to get the victory. Mariners starter Jamie
Moyer (8-5) got the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you score that many runs, it allows you to mix up your
pitches and be more aggressive,'' Sparks said. ``It also slows down
their running game and makes them play station to station, so I was
fortunate in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to give them (bullpen) a rest. They needed it and
I haven't stayed out there very long lately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
