A2735 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALLSTARS-H     07-08 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ALLSTARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All-Stars
</P>
<P>
   Lima, Wagner, &QL; 
Hampton join &QL; 
Bagwell on NL team &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ Jeff Bagwell is the front man of the Astros' All-Star
contingent _ the veteran who has been there and done that. It's a
good thing, too, because the other Astros All-Stars might need a
little guidance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, Jose Lima and Billy Wagner were selected to the
National League All-Star team for the first time Wednesday by
Padres manager Bruce Bochy and league president Len Coleman, who
also named Bagwell among NL reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Craig Biggio was not named to the team; Jeff Kent
of the San Francisco Giants will be the backup to Arizona's Jay
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Making the game even more special than usual for Bagwell is the
fact it will be played at Boston's Fenway Park. Bagwell was born in
Boston and grew up a Red Sox fan. His hometown team drafted him in
1989 but traded him to the Astros for Larry Andersen in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game will mark the first time Bagwell has stepped
onto the field at Fenway Park as a major-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be special for me,'' said Bagwell, who played
in a college all-star game at Fenway. ``It's going to be great to
sit in that dugout for the first time. It's going to be fun but not
emotional. When they traded me, the emotion went out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was business; I understand why they did it. They were
trying to build their team up for a shot at the postseason, and if
I were in that situation, I would have been saying, `Trade that
Bagwell kid.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be the only one in Boston defending the trade.
I'm just excited to have an opportunity to go back and to share
this with three of my teammates who have never gone before.''
</P>
<P>
   The four representatives are the most the Astros have had since
Bagwell, Biggio, Ken Caminiti, Doug Drabek and John Hudek made the
team in 1994. This is only the second time in franchise history
three Houston pitchers have been selected to the team. Joaquin
Andujar, Joe Niekro and Joe Sambito made it in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner and his wife, Sarah, had planned a fishing trip for the
three-day All-Star break, but they were glad to change their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many good pitchers around that it's hard to
expect to make it,'' said Wagner, who is tied for the NL lead with
21 saves. ``It's special to make the team in only my third year in
the big leagues, and it's special for it to take place in Boston,
which is where I saw my first big-league game.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he thought American League hitters would react to
seeing such a blazing fastball coming from a small package, Wagner
said: ``Those guys know who I am. They've seen good fastballs
before. Ask (Mariners shortstop) Alex Rodriguez. He hit a ball
against me in the minor leagues that's still going.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, Lima and Wagner joined 13 other NL players as
first-time All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a very excitable guy,'' Hampton said. ``But I'm pretty
excited about this. Going to the All-Star Game is like a
once-in-a-lifetime experience. To be in the company of such great
players will be an honor. Hopefully, there'll be more to come. But
this is something I'll cherish for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The only intrigue remaining is whether Bochy will put an Astro
in the starting lineup. Bagwell would seem to be a candidate to
start at designated hitter, and Lima's numbers are good enough to
warrant consideration for the starting assignment, but that's not
going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Lima is scheduled to start for the Astros on Sunday, which
likely would limit him to an inning of work in Tuesday's All-Star
Game. Batting orders and starting pitchers will be announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lima will not start the All-Star Game,'' Astros general
manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``I promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lima is happy to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great privilege,'' Lima said. ``You get to see the
best players in the world, and now I'm one of them. I want to
start, but I don't make that decision. That would be an honor, but
my team comes first. I'm just going to go down there and enjoy
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful; I'm coming for you, Boston. It's Lima Time!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
