<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZHEIMER-VACCINE-SFC     07-08 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMER-VACCINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ALZHEIMER'S VACCINE SHOWS PROMISE IN MICE  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An experimental vaccine against Alzheimer's disease has achieved
startling success _ in mice _ and could be ready for early trials
in humans within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting Wednesday in the journal Nature, Bay Area researchers
sponsored by drugmaker Elan Pharmaceuticals outlined a potential
strategy to prevent the buildup of brain-damaging plaques, one of
the biological hallmarks of Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary tests suggest that it may someday be possible to
take a series of injections in middle age _ perhaps at the first
hint of symptoms, perhaps sooner in those with a family history or
other risk factors _ to preserve mental function in later life.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the tests also hint that the vaccine may have a
therapeutic effect _ capable perhaps of reversing symptoms in those
already suffering memory loss and other signs of Alzheimer's
dementia.
</P>
<P>
   Medical experts warned that many questions have to be answered
before a therapeutic Alzheimer's vaccine can be considered a
serious possibility. Still, doctors said the results reported
Wednesday mark a new turn in the battle against one of the most
feared afflictions of an aging population.
</P>
<P>
   The disease, capable of producing a profound degeneration of
memory and mental function, afflicts about 4 million Americans,
including 1 in 10 of those over the age of 65 and nearly half of
those over the age of 85. There is no cure, and current treatment
options, aimed at replenishing neurotransmitters depleted as the
disease progresses, generally achieve little beyond a slight delay
in symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bruce Miller, an Alzheimer's specialist at the University of
California at San Francisco, said the new study ``brings up a whole
exciting area none of us in the field has even thought about
before, and that's immunization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The field is moving from trying to replace the chemicals
destroyed in the process of brain degeneration to new strategies
looking at primary prevention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Elan researchers injected an experimental protein drug
called AN-1792 into a mutant strain of mice with human gene forms
designed to produce biological symptoms of Alzheimer's disease as
the animals age.
</P>
<P>
   Treatments triggered an immune response in the animals that
seemed to clear away the telltale brain plaques, while preventing
new plaque from being deposited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were astounded,'' said Dale Schenk, Elan Pharmaceuticals
vice president for neurobiology and lead researcher on the new
study.
</P>
<P>
   The company, formed through the recent takeover of San
Francisco-based Athena Neurosciences, plans to petition the U.S.
Food and Drug Administration later this year for permission to
begin launch  &LR; the first safety tests in people.
</P>
<P>
   If those succeed, the company could then begin larger clinical
trials to determine whether AN-1792 is truly effective. Even if all
goes well, it could take several years before any therapy or
vaccine is in widespread use.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial appearing in the same issue of
Nature as the Elan study, Alzheimer's specialists from the
University of Toronto noted the long-standing controversy as to
exactly what causes Alzheimer's dementia and outlined key questions
that have yet to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be a little cautious,'' said Dr. David Westaway,
one of the commentary's co-authors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first questions the Elan team has to answer is
whether an appropriate immune response can be induced in humans as
was seen in the laboratory mice.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to trigger release of a specific type of antibody _
the body's guided missiles against disease-causing organisms _ that
can attack a particular form of protein known as amyloid-beta
peptide.
</P>
<P>
   The peptide, consisting of a string of 40 or 42 amino acids, is
the main ingredient in the drug that Elan injected into the mice.
The idea is to show the immune system how to recognize as an enemy
what would otherwise appear to be a benign substance in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies of potential cancer vaccines suggest this may
not be so easy to do. Results in so-called ``mouse models'' of
complicated human diseases have not proved very reliable, partly
because the human immune system often balks at attacking the body's
own proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the researchers had to induce relatively high levels of
antibody in the mice in order to achieve the desired results. It
may be hard to get such a robust result in humans while at the same
avoiding side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming those questions can be answered, the next key stumbling
block will be proving that amyloid plaque build-up is what lies
behind the behavioral and neurological impairments of Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the question was posed by the Toronto specialists, ``does
immunization with (amyloid-beta peptide) simply clear a
neuropathological by-product or can it cure the disease?''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview, Westaway said the new study should go a
long way toward clearing up the fundamental question of whether
amyloid plaque is the central problem or just one element in a more
insidious process that has yet to be fully explained.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies suggest the death of brain cells and loss of
memory in Alzheimer's is rooted in a cascade of events in which at
least some of the damage is done inside brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, then preventing plaques from being
deposited all around the brain may not be enough to prevent or
reverse all the symptoms. It might take several years of
large-scale study to know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   The study authors said there are grounds to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see what we're seeing now in human testing, we're going
to have a profound effect on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease,
there's no question about that,'' Schenk said.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the field cautioned family members and caregivers
against expecting too much, too soon. But they, too, said the
prospects are not so far-fetched that those now in their 40s and
50s can get more effective treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that you could immunize people against something
like Alzheimer's disease is pretty exciting stuff,'' said Bill
Fisher, Bay Area executive director for the Alzheimer's
Association, a support group with branches nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that other options are also in the testing stage and
could be available sooner, although most would have only modest
impact on the disease. Vitamin E, estrogen and nonsteroidal
anti-inflammatory drugs, for example, are being investigated as
possible protective agents against cognitive decline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
