<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SITES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IN SICKNESS AND IN HEALTH _ WEB SITES OFFER HELPFUL DATA  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Dr. Ed Penhoet, dean of the University of
California at Berkeley's School of Public Health and vice chairman
of Chiron Corp., likes to conduct a little market research whenever
he speaks at public gatherings.
<P>
   ``How many people here have used the Internet to look for health
information?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the audience, he says the question always elicits
a sea of hands _ anecdotal evidence to support what the experts
say: The Internet is fast becoming the place where people turn to
find out about staying healthly or coping with disease.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Staff, chief economist with Zona Research in Redwood City,
Calif., offers several reasons for the Internet's growing
popularity as a medium for health advice:
</P>
<P>
   -- The abundance of Web sites offering easy access to
information that used to be found only in medical libraries.
</P>
<P>
   -- The ability to make queries anytime and in almost complete
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   -- The existence of online discussion groups where people from
all over the world can share their experiences with
sometimes-obscure diseases.
</P>
<P>
   But like everything else in cyberspace, the real challenge &LR;   &LR; in
searching for health information is not finding something _ it's
finding exactly what you want to know, and from a reliable source.
</P>
<P>
   No single Web site lists and ranks every online offering. But to
help jump start a health search, here are some suggestions for
sites of proven usefulness, reliability and ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic reasons to begin a health search: Either you
or someone you know is sick and you want to learn everything you
can about the illness, or you're in good health and you're looking
for information or products to help stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with illness as a motivation and then move to the
wellness search. Addresses for all Web sites mentioned are listed
in an accompanying chart.
</P>
<P>
   As a biotech reporter, I constantly encounter new ailments. My
first stop on many stories is Citeline.com, a San Francisco service
that lets people search for information about virtually any
disease. It provides definitions, articles about the latest
treatments and other facts to get you up to speed in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Citeline.com sells an advanced version of its database to drug
and biotech firms, so the information is high caliber. But the
basic service is, and will remain, free, said marketing director
John Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Finding Doctors
</P>
<P>
   Once you've found out a bit about your disease, you might want
to look for a physician who specializes in its treatment. The
American Medical Association maintains a nationwide directory of
physicians that you can search by specialty and state.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, your choice of physician is probably limited by your
health plan. But it may be useful to know where you can turn for a
second opinion. The AMA page has another great advantage. It
reveals where a doctor went to school, did a residency and earned
credentials _ tools that can help you learn more about any
physician you encounter.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare ailment that isn't treated by some form of
medication. PharmInfoNet is a great place to learn about
prescription drugs, their side effects and possible interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the site. Click on drug info. Type in the name of your
medication. PharmInfo will pull up a list of articles that mention
the drug. No telling what you'll find, but you will learn what has
been written about the drugs you take.
</P>
<P>
   To test the system, I typed in Neoral, one brand name for a drug
that transplant patients take on a daily basis. Up popped an
article about how grapefruit juice interacts with a number of
medications to dramatically increase their effect on the body _
surely a good thing to know!
</P>
<P>
   Support From Others
</P>
<P>
   One way people cope with disease is by joining support groups.
People who've been there and done that are often the best sources
of solace and information. Your physician may steer you to a local
support group. People who suffer from common ailments, like
diabetes or heart disease, can easily find support groups through
the American Diabetes Association or the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But it's harder for those with rare or genetic diseases to find
people with similar experiences. Fortunately, the University of
Kansas Medical Center posts an A-to-Z support group directory for
everything from Acoustic Neuroma (a loss of hearing) to Xeroderma
Pigmentosum (extreme sensitivity to sunlight).
</P>
<P>
   When other sources of information fail, try HealthFinder.
Maintained by the Department of Health and Human Services, this Web
site provides a simple way to find the health information that
pours out of government agencies like the National Institutes of
Health or the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The nicest thing about HealthFinder is its simplicity. At the
top of the screen is a question box. Type in your query and the Web
site looks for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   I went looking for a central list of clinical trials. These are
experiments, carried on by medical researchers, to gauge the safety
and effectiveness of new drugs or surgical treatments. A person
with a serious ailment who has learned that conventional treatments
won't work might be willing to take part in such an experiment.
</P>
<P>
   HealthFinder pointed me to a series of Web pages that listed
various clinical trials being sponsored or supervised by several
federal agencies, although the list did not seem to include all
clinical trials. Still, enrolling in a trial, provided an
appropriate one is available, could sometimes be a patient's last,
best shot.
</P>
<P>
   Staying Healthy
</P>
<P>
   If you start from the other point, trying to maintain your
current health, there is an even larger universe of sites from
which to choose. Many of these sites also contain useful
information about diseases, but their focus is on how to stay
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of my list would be the Web sites maintained or
sponsored by research centers. The Mayo Clinic and Johns Hopkins
University, two noted medical research centers, both sponsor
excellent pages aimed at laypeople.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll be able to find information about diseases and
drugs on either page, but the emphasis is on ways to avoid disease
through diet and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, clicking on ``nutrition'' on the Mayo Clinic site
leads ultimately to a heart-healthy menu plan emphasizing fish over
meat. Headlines on the Johns Hopkins page talk about how to relieve
the stress of caring for an elderly parent. These pages approach
health in a holistic way, encompassing everything from attitude to
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A plethora of commercial Web sites have sprung up that dispense
health information while trying to sell you products or services to
maintain your health.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting the reputable sites from the snake oil vendors is
difficult. But the Federal Trade Commission, the U.S. government
agency that polices the truthfulness of advertising claims,
recently posted a list of recommended Web sites for health
information.
</P>
<P>
   Koop's Coup
</P>
<P>
   Among the commercial Web sites that won FTC kudos is Drkoop.com,
the new health site launched by former U.S. Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop, who is chairman of the company. The site recently
went public on Wall Street, and America Online this week designated
Drkoop.com as its main health information center, giving the site
huge visibility.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Drkoop.com shows a mixture of the useful and
commercial. In addition to providing access to medical
encyclopedias, disease directories, and basic nutrition and health
information, the site gives you a chance to buy cancer insurance or
join a weight-loss plan that promises to help you lose 10 pounds in
30 days.
</P>
<P>
   If your interests run toward alternative medicine,
HealthGate.com is another commercial Web site that won FTC
accolades. A quick visit to the site shows a blend of up-to-date
information about cutting-edge biomedical technology, blended in
with New Age techniques like aromatherapy (the name explains it
all) and reflexology (physical techniques, like rubbing the soles
of your feet to help with headaches).
</P>
<P>
   Other Web pages, like OnHealth.com and Caresoft.com, follow the
same approach as Drkoop and HealthGate: They provide health
information as a lure to attract consumers to click on their banner
ads or buy their drugs, vitamins or health products.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these sites are quite reputable. The best way to avoid
those that aren't is to follow the FTC's advice: If a health claim
sounds too good to be true, it probably is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the FTC did such a good job of listing dependable Web
sites for health information that our best recommendation is to
visit its list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
