<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SALON.COM TO SELL TICKETS TO PERFORMANCES  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Nothing like the whiff of e-commerce to pump up an
Internet stock.
<P>
   Salon.com's stock shot up nearly 17 percent Wednesday, jumping
$1.81 to close at $12.75, after the San Francisco online magazine
announced a deal to sell tickets to cultural events on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   That's after Salon's critics had been panning the company for
its lack of e-commerce offerings. Such sniping was a big factor in
Salon's initial public offering failing to soar last month. While
other dot-coms typically ascend on takeoff, Salon.com opened June
22 at $10.50, closed its first day at $10 and hovered in the single
digits all last week.
</P>
<P>
   Few investors saw the merits of a Web site with provocative
literary journalism, yet without the market-making potential of a
Priceline.com. For e-commerce, all Salon offered was a link from
its book reviews to Barnesandnoble.com.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Salon does offer the kind of educated, well-heeled and
Internet-savvy audience that an e-commerce company craves _
particularly a company like New York's CultureFinder.com, which
sells tickets to more than 350,000 theater, ballet, opera and
symphony performances in 1,300 cities on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tied right into the kind of readership we have,'' said
Andrew Ross, vice president of business and strategic development
at Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Salon covers the arts but rarely reviews arts
events. The new deal means Salon is likely to beef up its reviews
later this year. ``We should do more and we will do more,'' Ross
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed. Salon and
privately held CultureFinder will develop a ``co-branded'' site at
www.culturefinder.salon.com, which should be online by August 1. In
addition, Salon's sales force will sell ads on the CultureFinder
site. The two companies also plan to link the ticket sales into
discussion groups about arts and entertainment, such as Salon's
TableTalk and the Well communities.
</P>
<P>
   Salon says this is only the beginning. The firm plans to plunge
into more e-commerce deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a growing part of our business,'' Ross said.
``The trick is to do it right and choose the right partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross couldn't say whether the stock market uptick validated the
deal. He just chuckled and said, ``The day traders are having fun
at last.''
</P>
<P>
   SECOND THOUGHTS: It turns out Cnet didn't really want the
Presidio anyway. Or Cnet CEO Halsey Minor has talked himself out of
the plum, since the Presidio Trust chose to give the former
Letterman Hospital property to Lucasfilm Ltd. instead of to the
Shorenstein group that included Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those buyer's remorse things,'' Minor said in a
phone interview. ``I literally think it may end up being the kind
of deal where it takes you two extra years to move in. Already,
environmental groups are looking to sue. Our company can't look at
a move-in date two years out. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The other bad part about being there _ don't get me wrong, it
would have been wonderful _ but there's no other place to expand.
We would have had to put people across town.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing to Lucas has some benefits, too. ``Now, everybody's
coming out of the woodwork wanting to try to help us. People know
we're looking,'' Minor said. ``Our preference would be to stay in
the city, but we're not ruling out leaving. We have to look at all
options.''
</P>
<P>
   TECHIES ON THE TUBE: Several of the Internet's marquee media
firms, including Cnet, have made various television announcements
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Net may be a new medium, but its stars know that television
still has staying power. TV not only makes money _ something hard
to come by on the Web _ but it also promotes the online product.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month, a weekly show on investing called
``TheStreet.com'' will debut on the Fox News Channel. It will be
co-produced by the online financial news site and feature former
CNBC anchor Brenda Buttner.
</P>
<P>
   Cnet, which already produces television programs for cable
syndication, will be archiving six months' worth of shows at a time
on its Web site. The shows aren't Webcast, but they'll go on the
site close to airtime and stay up for six months. Cnet will use the
shows' closed-caption text to enable people to search, so they can
go right to the segment of the show that's relevant to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what the Web is all about,'' said Cnet CEO Minor.
``It's not about trying to stream this stuff and watch it for half
an hour. People are not there to be entertained. They're there to
learn something.''
</P>
<P>
   It's part of the company's strategy to gear up as more people
get high-speed connections to the Net _ connections that will
enable them to see video easily.
</P>
<P>
   Minor said Cnet will see how the experiment goes, tweaking it if
necessary, before it tries to make any money out of it. ``The Web
works best when you get the user experience to work right first,
and then the advertiser second,'' he said. ``If not, you don't have
any users for the advertisers to reach.''
</P>
<P>
   SPLITTING THE GATE: As the owners of Chronicle Publishing Co.
investigate the sale of some or all of their assets _ including
this newspaper and KRON television station _ the company Web site,
SF Gate, is in the strangest position of all.
</P>
<P>
   SF Gate employees are happily ensconced in their cavernous new
office in the KRON building on Van Ness Avenue. They moved from
their ground-floor digs in the same building into the former
third-floor studio two months ago and hung inflatable toys,
including a giant horseshoe, from the tall ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   A staff of 40 produces original content, and also puts content
from The Chronicle, Examiner, KRON and cable station BayTV onto the
site at sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to federal rules adopted after Chronicle owners bought
KRON, no one can own a television station and newspaper in the same
city _ making it likely that The Chronicle could be sold to one
company and KRON to another.
</P>
<P>
   In that scenario, it's unclear which entity would end up with SF
Gate _ or if it could go to yet another company entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' SF Gate General Manager John Coate
said. ``Until some bids come in, there isn't a way to know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's somewhat reminiscent of last year's deal in which Conde
Nast bought Wired magazine but didn't acquire its Web site. The
site still has an arrangement to post the magazine's archival
content, and they share the brand name.
</P>
<P>
   SF Gate might have to move if it's cleaved from KRON, but the
loss of content wouldn't be a killer. ``Television is very
polished, very produced and does not play well on the Web,'' Coate
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, SF Gate is ``being positioned to go with the
newspaper,'' Coate said. ``Nothing would affect our traffic
overnight like a loss of Chronicle content. That would be a
supermarket without much food on the shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   CLOSING WINDOWS: Let us mourn the passing of a fine publication,
Windows magazine, which this week takes leave of its glossy,
tactile realm and will hereafter reside strictly in cyberspace, at
www.winmag.com. Windows was published by CMP Media, which last year
shut down the print operation of venerable Byte magazine in favor
of online-only publishing.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the news, CMP, which is now a division of San
Francisco's Miller Freeman, said ad pages for magazines covering
the desktop computer market had declined 23 percent in the first
five months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   GROK RULES: I don't usually plug contest winners, but I happen
to agree with this one. The American Society of Business Press
Editors last month awarded the Industry Standard's punchy e-mail
newsletter Media Grok a national prize as best original news
section or newsletter. The Grok critiques online and mainstream
coverage of key technology stories. You can read back Groks, and
subscribe, at www.thestandard.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
