<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGDISTANCE-CHARGES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CONSUMERS PAYING HIGHER CHARGES FOR LONG-DISTANCE  &HT;     By DEBORAH SOLOMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- You can reach out and touch someone, but the costs
are going up.
<P>
   A study conducted by a San Francisco consumer group found that
some customers are paying higher monthly charges to long-distance
carriers than they were a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   While long-distance rates have come down in price, more phone
companies are requiring that customers pay either a monthly fee or
a minimum amount each month, according to a survey by Consumer
Action of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that 21 phone company calling plans now charge a
fee compared with 11 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And none of the big three long-distance carriers _ AT&AMP;T, MCI
WorldCom or Sprint _ offers a calling plan without a monthly fee or
minimum spending requirement. That leaves consumers with fewer ways
to avoid hefty bills.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Wednesday, also found that monthly charges
are on the rise, with the maximum fee imposed on customers soaring
to $25 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the highest monthly fee charged by a long-distance
carrier was $4.95.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not say how much the average customer pays per
month in fees.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, Sprint and MCI WorldCom generally charge between $3 and $5
in monthly fees and minimums. Some companies, like Qwest, charge
$14.95 per month but offer rates of 5 cents per minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies, in the absence of being able to make money on
rates, are stepping in there with fees and minimums,'' said Linda
Sherry, the survey's lead researcher. ``And these fees are hurting
the people who don't make a lot of calls and who can least afford
high bills.''
</P>
<P>
   The group identified just five smaller carriers with low
per-minute rates that don't charge monthly fees.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly minimums are imposed on customers who don't sign up for
a calling plan or those who choose a ``basic rate'' plan. The
minimum requires that a customer pay a set amount each month,
regardless of how many calls they make. For example, if a company
sets a $5 monthly minimum but a customer makes only $2 in calls per
month, the company will charge the customer an extra $3.
</P>
<P>
   Monthly fees are imposed on customers who sign up for calling
plans with low per-minute rates. In exchange for getting 10 cents
per minute, for example, a customer usually will have to pay about
$5 per month. Customers who qualify as low-income are exempt from
most minimums and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The long-distance companies defend the charges as a way to
recoup costs.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1996 Telecommunications Act was passed, the
long-distance carriers have been required to pay fees to fund
federally mandated programs. Most companies have passed along those
fees, which pay for services like wiring classrooms and libraries
to the Internet, to consumers. The government does not require that
the fees be passed on, but most companies have done so to recover
their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Other fees are access charges that long-distance carriers must
pay local phone companies. Those also are passed along to
consumers, who generally pay between $1 and $2 per month in fees.
</P>
<P>
   But to impose those fees, long-distance companies now have to
generate monthly bills for all customers, regardless of whether
they made any calls that month. That costs money, which the
companies need to recoup, said Brad Burns, an MCI spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to generate bills now that we didn't have to generate
before, and we have to field calls from customers that before, we
didn't have to field,'' Burns said. ``We have shareholders to live
up to, so we most definitely have to recover these costs. We're not
a not-for-profit company.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates said the long-distance carriers have
found a convenient way to siphon additional money from customers
while technically not increasing rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have consumers over a barrel. Rates may not be going up,
but these charges certainly are,'' said Regina Costa, a
telecommunications analyst with The Utility Reform Network, a
consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T officials say the increased fees and minimums don't add up
to much on a customer's monthly bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about cents here in most cases,'' said Andy
Boisseau, an AT&AMP;T spokesman. He defended the increases, saying his
company's costs have been rising.
</P>
<P>
   For a comparison of plans and rates, consumers can go to
www.consumer-action.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
