<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYMBOREE-MAKEOVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GYMBOREE PLANS BIG MAKEOVER  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Gymboree, the troubled Burlingame, Calif.,
children's wear retailer, announced a wholesale makeover Wednesday
of its outdated stores, fashions and even its logo.
<P>
   It also said its loss for the second quarter will reach 55 to 60
cents _ up from a previous estimate of a 2-cent loss.
</P>
<P>
   Amid declining sales, the company will close 12 poorly
performing stores out of its total of 589. The makeovers and store
closures will cost the company $13.5 million (35 cents per share).
It also expects a per-share loss from operations of 20 to 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Cox, Gymboree's president, was recruited from trendy
teen retailer Urban Outfitters earlier this year to bring Gymboree
up to date.
</P>
<P>
   Cox plans to revamp the children's line to pay more attention to
trends rather than adhering to Gymboree's signature bright colors.
The company is also jettisoning its traditional coordinated
ensembles in favor of separates.
</P>
<P>
   Stores' selling floors will be opened up to eliminate the
alcoves where matching ensembles are now displayed. Clothing for 4-
to 7-year-olds will be moved to the front of the store and
separated distinctly from the baby and toddler area, since older
children dislike shopping in a ``baby'' store, said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Storefronts, fixtures, signs, labels and the Gymboree logo will
also be modernized.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's turnaround announcement had a similar ring to
changes announced in years past. Gymboree has been trying to get
its act together since late 1995, when inventory problems and
fashion mistakes contributed to a dismal holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially what they're saying here is that it's going to be
a bigger project than they expected,'' said Jeanne Kraus, an
analyst with First Security Van Kaspar in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Cox agreed. ``The difference here is that rather than
manipulating an outdated brand, we have ... determined that the
entire brand needed to be updated,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a customer what they think of Gymboree today and
five years ago and five years before that, how much has the picture
really changed?'' Cox asked. The answer: not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think next year at this time when you think about Gymboree
you will think very differently about it,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the planned changes were influenced by
Gymboree's new Zutopia chain, which targets children ages 7 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   Zutopia, with 10 stores, carries more fashionable clothing than
Gymboree and fun merchandise like space alien dolls, inflatable
chairs and Pop Rocks candy. Stores feature a disco ball and
Nintendo games to play.
</P>
<P>
   Positive consumer response to Zutopia helped convince Gymboree's
decision-makers that kids _ and their parents _ prefer trendier
merchandise than the traditional Gymboree offerings, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Nine more Zutopias will be opened by the end of the year. Cox
declined to say how many are planned for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, store renovations and new styles of apparel will be
seen at Gymboree beginning this fall. Early next year, customers
will begin to see new storefronts and signage.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are expected to yield improved financial results
next year, said Gary White, Gymboree's chief executive and
chairman, in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the turnaround strategy announced Wednesday,
Gymboree said sales for the five-week period ending July 3 declined
20 percent to $40.9 million from $51 million in the same period
last year. Sales at stores open at least a year plummeted 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company blamed much of the problem on unpopular boys'
fashions, which retail analysts have said are too brightly colored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
