<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Tobacco jury finding may be addictive
 &HT;    (For release July 11, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Five men and a woman, after listening to witnesses and
viewing documents for a full year, have torched the tobacco
industry in a class-action suit held in a Miami-Dade courtroom. It
was an overwhelmingly significant jury verdict and opens the door
to similar suits in the 49 other states, and possibly other class
actions claiming illness or death of one kind or another from other
products.
</P>
<P>
   With damages not yet set by the jury, we are anticipating a
finding for billions of dollars. There remains a long road to the
ruination of Big Tobacco, however. Appeals and, eventually, the
Supreme Court likely will prolong this one for years.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Big Tobacco ultimately coughs up the money, the
Miami decision nevertheless was a huge blow. The jury said, in one
count, that nicotine is addictive, that some of the tobacco
companies colluded to misrepresent information relating to the
health aspects of smoking cigarettes and that smoking cigarettes is
responsible for a wide assortment of diseases including aortic
aneurism, bladder cancer, cervical cancer, kidney cancer, lung
cancer, coronary heart disease ...
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the United States, or maybe the entire world, there
are people today saying, ``See, I told you so!'' In truth, the
decision was not so revealing about the facts regarding tobacco;
the Surgeon General's Office has been telling us about that for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   What Big Tobacco was arguing in its defense was that people,
already informed by the Surgeon General's Office, continued to use
cigarettes and therefore should not be compensated for their own
stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   That's a point well made but apparently not enough to hurdle the
larger question, particularly that about conspiring to misinform
the public.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Big Tobacco, if there can be any good news out
of this, is that the jury held that asthmatic bronchitis,
infertility and bronchioalveolar cancer are not caused by smoking.
</P>
<P>
   As a smoker who quit in 1983 _ and thus almost an anti-smoking
missionary _ I do have an expectation that similar suits will pop
up in the other states, a continuing stream of litigation _ almost
as addictive as the cigarettes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So, what of the future? First, of course, is the determination
of damages. With 500,000 Floridians signed onto this suit, the
assignment of damages will be humongous. When a jury can award a
woman millions of dollars for accidentally spilling boiling hot
coffee in her lap at McDonald's, what can we expect of the Miami
decision?
</P>
<P>
   While some hold that this decision will lead to the death of the
tobacco industry, don't hold your breath. Big Tobacco probably
could raise the price of a pack by 50 cents and still find enough
willing smokers to get back their money in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   With the finding of the addictiveness of nicotine, however, does
there not arise a possibility that either the federal government or
state governments will tinker with legislation that would treat
nicotine as a drug? I know of few doctors who would write a
prescription for Camels or Kools.
</P>
<P>
   This case really didn't tell us anything most of us already
knew. What it did was set a precedent for forcing Big Tobacco to
clean up its act and, eventually, will set a punishment price tag
for the lies and deceits it already has broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Big Tobacco cannot escape the now chiseled image of an industry
covertly colluding to keep information from the public, or to sway
them into doing something that is not in the best interest of their
health.
</P>
<P>
   No overturning of a lower-court decision, or reduction of
punitive damages, ever can alter the findings of those six jurors _
one a smoker _ who sat diligently for an entire year, going through
more information than most of us tread through in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
