A2917 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN09-COX     07-08 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why Silicon Valley? Follow the money
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Question: Why do George W. Bush and Al Gore go
to Silicon Valley?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The same reason Willie Sutton gave for robbing banks _
because that's where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   So the Texas guv has racked up a cool $36-plus million in his
first few weeks of fund raising for a presidential run. Big bucks
to you and me, yes.
</P>
<P>
   But to Bill Gates, whose net worth now hovers around $90
billion, that's chump change _ way less than the interest Gates
earned on his money just during the three days W. was in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, just as W.'s troops are crowing that they may pass up
the federal matching funds system so they can go toe to toe with
Steve Forbes' personal deep pockets, the cluck-cluck of criticism
begins.
</P>
<P>
   It's led by Bush rival U.S. Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) who
co-sponsored a failed effort in Congress to limit runaway ``soft
money'' contributions to political parties by corporations, labor
and others. McCain did not mention Bush and wasn't talking about
circumventing the individual campaign-spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain picked the same day Bush chanted his new fund-raising
figures to call for politicians to wean themselves from ``special
interest'' government. Speaking in New Hampshire, McCain issued a
``patriotic challenge'' to Americans, ``declaring war on the
cynicism that threatens our public institutions, our culture and,
ultimately, our private happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed public officeholders _ yup, he is one _ ``for the
sickness in American public life today. It is we who have
squandered the public trust. We who have, time and again, placed
our personal and partisan interests before the national interest,
earning the public's contempt for our poll-driven policies, our
phony posturing, the lies we call spin and the damage control we
substitute for progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we are the defenders of a campaign-finance system that is
nothing less than an elaborate influence-peddling scheme in which
both parties conspire to stay in office by selling the country to
the highest bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong words. Doesn't sound like someone angling to be W.'s vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   (However, George Bush the Elder still got the VP nod from Ronald
Reagan _ just weeks after tagging Reagan's claim he'd balance the
budget, even while cutting taxes and increasing defense spending,
as ``Voodoo Economics.'')
</P>
<P>
   But even without singling Bush out, McCain's campaign spending
criticism hit the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Already a Wall Street Journal story said Bush was undermining
the last vestige of the post-Watergate efforts to limit spending.
Headline: ``Flush Bush Undercuts Federal Funding of Campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorialized that Bush's bypassing the
spending limits ``is a serious mistake for a candidate who promises
to practice a new and better brand of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, if you're accusing someone of trying to buy the
election with special-interest cash, you've got to figure out a way
to get that message out.
</P>
<P>
   The story in The Wall Street Journal, and the criticism by The
New York Times, will be read by some people and spread a little
further by some of the TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't keep coming up over and over again _ unless McCain
or someone else can come up with the money to put it on TV, over
and over. Not likely Forbes will do it, since he'll also be
circumventing the matching funds approach as he seeks to buy the
nomination with his personal wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush, if his re-election campaign in Texas is a
guide, will use that money for saturation TV exposure in Iowa and
New Hampshire, and other early primary battlegrounds. There'll be a
bunch of good-guy ads about a Bush who cares about education,
people, good government, personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain and the others who do accept matching funds will have
a lid on how much they can spend in the primaries, and in each
state _ even if they could raise it. Bush, who already enjoys
saturation name identification because of Dad, presumably will
bypass those limits.
</P>
<P>
   Money may not necessarily buy happiness, but it can buy an awful
lot of TV. That's what drives American politics _ and Bush knows
it.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
