r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NERD-WORD09-COX     07-08 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NERD-WORD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Listen up, nerds: You've been insulted with the wrong word all
these years
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Who would have ever thought the Fonz could be
wrong? That the man who gave us the universal sign for ``I'm OK,
you're OK'' _ a thumbs up and an ``Ayyyyyyyy!'' _ could err in his
word usage? And that his errant usage would have such an impact?
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Fonzarelli's lexical mistake would usually take place in
Arnold's over a spilled shake or a ``bonehead'' move by Potsie or
Ralph Malph. After such an incident, the leather-jacketed one would
shake his head (as only he could) and then, with arms akimbo, utter
the word that quickly took the world by storm: ``Nerd!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nerd'' soon became the rote insult used against the bookish
and technologically advanced. When computers first came out, their
users were labeled nerds. When the Internet connected us, anyone
online was called a nerd. Bill Gates was crowned by Newsweek as
``King of the Nerds'' and The New York Times' J.C. Herz recently
declared, ``It's now cool to be a nerd.'' Wired magazine has more
than 17,000 ``nerd'' references in their database, Excite.com shows
more than 21,000 sites with the word ``nerd'' somewhere in them _
and how could we forget those delightful ``Nerds'' candies? And to
think, of all people, Fonzie was mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the mistake wasn't in the reprimanding of his two
acquaintances: Potsie and Ralph were bungling characters who
deserved constant verbal spankings. The question is whether these
two were ``nerds.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Dr. Seuss published ``If I Ran the Zoo.'' In it was a
picture of a perturbed, furry Chester A. Arthurlike character that
Seuss labeled as a ``nerd.'' There was a short mention (''I'll sail
to Ka-Troo and Bring Back an It-Kutch a Preep and a Proo a Nerkle a
Nerd and a Seersucker, too!'') and no further explanation.
According to the Oxford English Dictionary and Terry O'Connor,
renowned etymologist and author of ``Word for Word,'' the next time
the word appears is in a 1957 Scottish Daily Mail article, ``ABC
for SQUARES,'' in which ``nerd'' is defined by a catty Scot writer
as ``a square, any explanation needed?''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Fonz would note my defeat by laughing that
Fonzie laugh and telling me to ``Sit on it!''
</P>
<P>
   Hold on, Mr. Fonzarelli. The next time the word appears is in
1970, in the book ``Current Slang.'' The book defines ``nurd''
(sic) as ``an uninteresting person, a `dud.' '' According to the
book, nerd is supposedly derived from the practice of calling
someone who didn't drink a ``knurd,'' which is ``drunk'' spelled
backward. Our friends in Arnold's weren't necessarily
uninteresting, and who knows whether they boozed it up or not?
</P>
<P>
   Though not a hot point in the etymological world, experts have
argued about the origin of the word ``nerd.'' Most agree Dr. Seuss
is the true originator of the term but define it as a ``comically
unpleasant creature.'' Etymologists guess ``nerd'' was picked up by
5- and 6-year-olds in 1950 and passed on to their teen-aged
siblings, where the definition became ``a square.'' While
buffoonery and boneheadedness are indeed reprehensible, Ralph and
Potsie are beyond being called ``nerds.''
</P>
<P>
   Better hold that ``Sit on it,'' Fonz; the law of lexicon rules
against you. Maybe on the reunion show, when your friends start
spilling shakes, you can find a better noun than ``nerd.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you insist on using your sugar-coated expletive, at least
make sure that the script calls for a Ralph Malph and Potsie that
more closely resemble the term's true meaning, the meaning that Dr.
Seuss intended. In other words, make sure they're played by a
couple of perturbed, furry Chester A. Arthurlike characters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
