<HEADER>
A2919 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-COX     07-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talk about feminine mystique; how about this one?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The 11-year-old in our house came in from the
darkened driveway distraught. A favorite shirt he'd acquired had
been stripped of a button.
</P>
<P>
   Ruined, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not true, I said. Buttons can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   He was not soothed. He grabbed a flashlight and went on a button
hunt in the front yard. He emerged sweaty and defeated. His grim
report to his mother: Button lost. Shirt ruined. World ended. (I
think bedtime was calling.)
</P>
<P>
   He slumped toward his room in utter dejection. Knowing it wasn't
the end of the world, his mother regardless heaved a sigh, got up
and headed out the door with the flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't 30 seconds later that she returned. Maybe it was 15
seconds. The button was in her hand. Her smile was straight from
Michelangelo's brush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uterus thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I can't tell you how many times I've heard those words, and
marveled at the meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The uterus is all-knowing. Nothing is lost if the uterus is
around.
</P>
<P>
   I did not assign the credit as so stated. It came from my wife.
She thinks it's a biological, female thing. She can find any lost
item. Or her uterus can.
</P>
<P>
   As the sole female in a house of males, she lays it on heavy and
often about her know-it-all plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   This truly must be one of those biological-survival,
nest-instinct things. She doesn't have a photographic mind. She
admits her long-term memory is faulty. In fact, she needs picture
books to recall the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But she can find anything she looks for around our house, or her
uterus can. Am I to assume that all mothers have this spooky
quality?
</P>
<P>
   I imagine this mysterious power as akin to that of the divining
rod, the stick that tells the surveyor where the underground water
is. Maybe it's like the capillary action that draws a pooch to a
fireplug. If it's something of value to our family, it calls out to
Mom's innards like a beacon from the deep.
</P>
<P>
   Call it biological. Call it psychic. It never fails. And my wife
always lets us know about it _ those of us who are
bio-psycho-kinetically challenged, that is, those of us who are
males.
</P>
<P>
   I'm so sold on this power that I expect it to come into play on
the campaign trail once women decide they can exploit their power.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton says of candidate Rudolph
Giuliani, ``He says he thinks he can find a solution to the
long-term solvency of Social Security. I have a uterus. I have no
question I can find it.''
</P>
<P>
   (This of course begs the question about those Whitewater-related
billing papers Hillary couldn't find until they suddenly
materialized. The uterus can find anything the bearer wants to
find.)
</P>
<P>
   I've often advocated the need for a woman president, and for a
host of reasons, in part because females are less likely to look at
people as interchangeable parts (each having had a mama.)
</P>
<P>
   Now I think of the feminine mystique in leadership not just in
abstract but in utilitarian terms. Put a uterus in charge of our
country to answer some nagging mysteries:
</P>
<P>
   Where is Jimmy Hoffa?
</P>
<P>
   What about that ozone hole?
</P>
<P>
   What became of most of Rush Limbaugh?
</P>
<P>
   We don't know where the networks found Jerry Springer, but can
you find someplace where we could deposit him and no one could find
him again? Try where Hoffa is.
</P>
<P>
   What about finding the missing link between animal and man?
(That which predates Limbaugh.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman running the country would explore recesses not probed by
mankind in the search for answers to all that ails us.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that America has lost its soul. A uterus can find it.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
