<HEADER>
A2920 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUFFETT-PARROTHEADS09     07-08 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFETT-PARROTHEADS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buffett show aims to capture the spirit of Atlanta fans
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Parrotheads, it's time to claim your 15
minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's probably only six or seven. But when a crew from
NBC's ``Today'' show hits town this week to document the antics of
these exuberant music fans _ whipped into a quasi-tropical frenzy
by the annual concert appearances of their hero, pop singer,
entrepreneur and mystery novelist Jimmy Buffett _ it will be a sign
that the Parrotheads have come of age.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true of the Atlanta Parrothead Club, which has
the distinction of being the oldest such outfit in the country.
Founded in 1989 after Buffett enthusiast Scott Nickerson placed a
two-line classified ad in the free weekly newspaper Creative
Loafing, the group spawned a nationwide phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were using Jimmy as a medium,'' says Nickerson, 38, who
quit his corporate day job five years ago to follow his bliss,
singing and playing percussion in a Buffett tribute band called
A1A. ``It was just a really off-the-cuff idea. Then my phone
started ringing off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   There are Parrotheads _ loosely anyone who shows up at a Buffett
concert _ and then there are Parrotheads, officially someone who
frequents Parrothead Club functions, which include anything from
weekly happy hours to picking up trash on Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   Coinage of the name is usually attributed to former Eagles
member Timothy B. Schmitt, who, while on tour with Buffett in the
1980s, supposedly likened the singer's fans to ``Deadheads with
Hawaiian shirts _ Parrotheads,'' says Nickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, unlike the Grateful Dead fans known as Deadheads or their
late '90s successors, Phishheads _ young fans of the improvising
rock band Phish _ Parrotheads neither bathe in patchouli nor twitch
and twirl as if at a Summer of Love ``be-in.'' They've got too many
frequent flier miles to be part of the counterculture. And though
they might take a few days off to catch some Buffett concerts,
they've usually got to be at work in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Such distinctions are important to the faithful Parrothead, for
whom, says Nickerson, fellowship and community service are as
important as the wacky garb. It's something that impressed the
``Today'' staff when Buffett made a recent appearance on the show,
cheered on by a gazillion sign-waving Parrotheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to show the world that Parrotheads are not a bunch
of drunken beach bums,'' says Roland Woerner, a ``Today'' producer
who will spend this morning filming local Parrotheads at work and
Saturday night amid the riot of plastic shark fins, blender drinks
and Carmen Miranda headgear at Lakewood Amphitheatre in Atlanta,
where Buffett concludes a two-day stand. The segment is scheduled
to air July 28. Says Woerner, ``They have real jobs and real
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, on nights like a recent Friday. Sporting the
de rigueur Hawaiian shirts, brandishing Cuban cigars and sweaty
bottles of Miller Lite and Heineken, a trio of manly Parrotheads is
holding court on the patio of Hemingway's, a Key West-themed bar on
the square in Marietta. Inside, A1A (the title of an early Buffett
album and, of course, the name of a coastal highway in Florida) is
tuning up to play several hours worth of Buffett cover tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, no one would think to nominate the Parrotheads as an
oppressed minority group, but they insist it's true. These people
are misunderstood. They need to clear the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think we Parrotheads worship Jimmy Buffett,''
says Wade Jenstead, 28, an Atlanta-based sales manager who is one
of about 160 members of Atlanta's Parrothead Club. He contends
that's an overstatement. ``We just all enjoy his music. All of us
got to be really good friends because we have the same lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett is simply a role model, not the incarnation of the
divine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does what we want to do,'' says Joel Oates, 39, of
Norcross, who runs the customer support department of a medical
supply company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have some diehard guys,'' Jenstead continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffett is God!'' Oates interjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the extreme. We love all kinds of music. We're
going to see Poison tonight,'' Jenstead says in a way that lets you
know he won't be within 10 miles of that pop metal band's concert.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Myers, the 35-year-old leader of the Atlanta Parrotheads,
summarizes the group's raison d'etre: ``Tell corporate society to
get bent. Work three months of the year and spend the rest of the
time in the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this won't happen soon, gatherings such as this one
re-create a ``Margaritaville'' of the mind. A1A _ Nickerson and
singer-guitarist Jeff Pike _ mugs its way through a batch of
pun-laden tunes by Buffett and his harmonica player, Greg
``Fingers'' Taylor. Mildly risque by ``South Park'' standards, they
celebrate a distinctly relaxed '70s attitude toward the use of
alcoholic libations and carnal knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Frivolous as it seems, however, Buffett's music has inspired
proceedings at Parrothead weddings and Parrothead funerals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had really planned a traditional wedding,'' says Felicia
Myers, a 30-year-old computer programmer who met husband Wayne on
the job five years ago, when she mentioned reading Buffett's latest
novel. ``It's just the stuff that everybody brought in. I looked
around and wondered, `Where did all the coconuts come from?''' As
tuxedos were shed to reveal Hawaiian shirts, and blenders
materialized as if from thin air, the new couple was toasted in
true Parrothead style.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the Myerses are still celebrating. As A1A rollicks
through ``Fins,'' Buffett's saga of shark-infested waters, they're
in the middle of a narrow dance floor with about 20 other
Parrotheads, shaking their hips and making snapping shark-jaw
motions with their forearms and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Myers flashes a cigar-stoked smile. ``Stick around,'' he
says. ``It gets a whole lot worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
