<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2921 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXOTIC-BIRDS09-COX     07-08 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXOTIC-BIRDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exotic birds' beauty balances responsibility of care
 &HT;    By Katherine Ullmer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In the back room you can hear them meowing,
whistling like madcap sailors and making raucous noises.
</P>
<P>
   Walk in the front door of the Sugarcreek Bird Farm Inc. in
Bellbrook, and a cheery ``Hel-lo'' will greet you.
</P>
<P>
   Store owners Paula and Pete DiSalvo will likely stop whatever
they're doing to see who Katie, their resident parrot, a green
yellow-naped Amazon, is greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a false alarm. Katie is just looking for
attention, a few pats on the head and snuggles from Pete, or a word
or two from Paula, food or a toy to play with. At other times, she
decides to entertain, calling ``Whoa ... whoa,'' while swaying on
her perch as if on a roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for a bird not to be jealous when surrounded by
150-plus other exotic birds of beautiful plumage _ big, deep-blue
hyacinth macaws with yellow eye rings, rose-breasted cockatoos,
African greys _ with multiple verbal skills, including meowing like
cats and whistling like sailors.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July the Bird Farm, which specializes in exotic birds and
other bird-related items, like seed mixes, nuts and veggies, cages,
toys, harnesses, bath sprays, DNA sex testing, and boarding and
grooming, will be moving to a real farm about 2 1/2 blocks away.
The DiSalvos live on a 10-acre farm in Bellbrook, where they're in
the midst of renovating an outbuilding into a store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a larger space, which we needed,'' said Pete DiSalvo.
</P>
<P>
   The DiSalvos, who also own the International Pro Bike Shop next
door to their bird shop, breed and raise most of their birds, so
they've limited store hours to have time to take care of their
breeding stock. Caring for the babies (there are about 60) means
feedings every two hours.
</P>
<P>
   A ban was placed on importing exotic birds in 1992, Pete DiSalvo
said, ``so everything now is domestically raised.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn left when you enter the store and you'll find the breeding
area with birds in all stages of growth. On a recent day, several
dozen small eggs were waiting to hatch in an incubator. In a coffee
cup in the corner of the incubator, a 3-day-old Quaker parakeet
raised his featherless head in ``feed-me'' fashion. Nearby, fluffy
brown baby pheasants the size of chicks, destined for the DiSalvo's
farm, scurried around in a small pen. Black baby Eclectus parrots
ran around in another pen, while African greys, Lories, and Amazons
rested in cages. Sleepy-eyed blue and red greenwing macaws about 7
or 8 weeks old and already bigger than the Amazons, were taking a
siesta.
</P>
<P>
   Some people like to raise their own pet birds, DiSalvo said, so
they buy them at a young age. ``We show people how to hand-raise
them and how to mix the formula and to feed them,'' he said. ``We
give them instructions on how to do it. We don't just hand them
over to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The DiSalvos breed 25 types of pet birds, from $25 American
parakeets to blue-throated macaws costing $1,600 and the rare,
deep-blue, 40-inch hyacinth macaw, the Rolls Royce of birds and a
macadamia nut lover, which costis $8,000 to $10,000. For several
breeds on the endangered species list, like the bright yellow
Golden Conure, the DiSalvos have a special government permit to own
and breed them.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the birds from egg to adulthood allows them to be
handled, touched and get used to humans, Pete DiSalvo said.
Imported birds that grew up in the wild often didn't make very good
pets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is constantly busy. If they're not taking phone calls,
the DiSalvos are helping customers pick out seed or toys for their
birds, trimming wings, or grinding down nails and beaks.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, Sue Humphrey, 50, of Bellbrook, stopped in to
buy a special seed mix for her yellow-naped Amazon, an anniversary
present she and her husband, Steve, gave one another. Her husband
named him Nacho, she said, so he'd learn to say, ``I'm Nacho
parrot.'' They've had him 2 1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just keeps us laughing,'' she said. ``He clowns, talks,
answers the phone and sings 'Nacho, Nacho Parrot.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Saettel, 12, and his brother Nick, 16, of Centerville, came
in to buy some feed and have their birds' wings clipped and their
nails done. Ben said his English parakeet, Buddy, is the Michael
Jordan of the bird kingdom. Buddy says ``I scored'' whenever he
dunks his ball in the water dish.
</P>
<P>
   Nick chose a larger (about 11 inches) Quaker parakeet, whom he
named Bob, because he wanted a bigger bird that would talk better
and be more personable. ``He mimics about anything you do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only the male of the parakeet and cockatiel species talk, while
both male and female macaws and Amazons talk, Paula DiSalvo
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Moore, 43, and her daughter Lisa, 16, of Bellbrook, picked
up Bailey, their gray and white cockatiel, who had been boarded at
the shop while they were on vacation. They said they stop in about
once a month. The birds in the back room seemed to know them, as
they started whistling, saying hello and squawking as the two moved
about.
</P>
<P>
   Though the DiSalvos have had their store just four years,
they've been working with birds for more than 30 years. Pete
DiSalvo said his love of birds started as a child. He had a pet
crow the family rescued and also a cockatiel. When he and his wife
married 30 years ago, a friend gave them a cockatiel as a wedding
present. Then they got an African grey and an Amazon. What started
as an avocation grew into a vocation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides running their bike shop and bird business, the DiSalvos
sponsor the Dayton Bird Expo, a bird fair and auction featuring 40
to 50 exhibitors, held three times a year in the coliseum at the
Montgomery County Fairgrounds. The next expo will be Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   While most people think exotic birds are beautiful, they should
give careful thought to becoming a bird owner, DiSalvo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bird is a real big commitment,'' he said. ``They can be
loud. They can be messy. They like to chew on things. They require
a lot of time (to exercise) and a lot of patience. But they're like
a dog or cat in terms of companionship,'' he said, ``and in
addition to that they can talk. They're very affectionate.''
</P>
<P>
   They're also aware of one's presence or absence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As customers left the store, Katie called out, ``Bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   The gang in the back room meowed, whistled and squawked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
