</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Sugarcreek Bird Farm Inc.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK WHO'S TALKING
</P>
<P>
   If you are buying a bird for its talking ability, it's good to
remember that although all parrots can mimic to some extent, not
all talk with the same ability or extent of vocabulary. Among the
parakeets and cockatiels, only the males talk.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pete DiSalvo of Sugarcreek Bird Farm Inc.:
</P>
<P>
   _ The best talkers: Amazons and African greys. They are capable
of saying 100 to 200 words and imitating all kinds of sounds. The
Amazons are extroverts who like to scream and yell, hang upside
down and entertain, while the African Greys are quieter, laid-back
birds that don't always talk on command or in front of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fairly good small bird talkers: Indian ringnecks (small
parrots with long tails) and Quaker parakeets (larger than American
and English parakeets) can have a 20-30 word vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limited talkers: Cockatoos (lovers who like to cuddle); macaws
(big gaudy birds who can learn about a dozen words); Meyers and
Senegal parrots (small African birds that are fairly shy and not
good talkers); cockatiels (males learn up to a dozen words but
whistle a fair amount of tunes); parakeets (males can learn 20 to
30 words but usually are hard to understand because they whisper);
Patagonian conure (four or five words) and Pionus (Maximillan) _
not a very good talker; black-head caique and white-belly caique
(not good talkers but playful, comical birds); Blue Streak and
Rainbow lories (about five words, but playful and comical antics).
</P>
<P>
