   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   POWERBOATS _ Big Boats and the Rich People Who Love Them.
(Ricardo, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NERD-WORD _ Better hold that ``Sit on it,'' Fonz; the law of
lexicon rules against you. Maybe on the reunion show, when your
friends start spilling shakes, you can find a better noun than
``nerd,'' because you were wrong on that, too. (Kallenberg, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EXOTIC-BIRDS _ In the back room you can hear them meowing,
whistling like madcap sailors and making raucous noises. Walk in
the front door of the Sugarcreek Bird Farm Inc., and a cheery
``Hel-lo'' will greet you. Store owners Paula and Pete DiSalvo will
likely stop whatever they're doing to see who Katie, their resident
parrot, a green yellow-naped Amazon, is greeting. It's hard for a
bird not to be jealous when surrounded by 150-plus other exotic
birds of beautiful plumage _ big, deep-blue hyacinth macaws with
yellow eye rings, rose-breasted cockatoos, African greys _ with
multiple verbal skills, including meowing like cats and whistling
like sailors. (Ullmer, Dayton Daily News). MOVED WITH
</P>
<P>
   EXOTIC-BIRDS-COST _ A look at what exotic birds cost and which
ones are the best talkers. (Dayton Daily News). 10. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   EATING-DISORDERS _ Janet Seay's 9-year-old daughter already
reads nutritional labels when deciding what to eat. Little Caitlin
doesn't have an eating disorder, but more and more preteens are
turning up with them _ because kids are increasingly aware, at
earlier ages, of weight and body image. Eating disorder specialists
say we're now into the second generation of dieters, and that
parents are unwittingly passing on their hyperawareness of food and
weight to their kids at early ages. Kids notice that the fridge is
full of fat-free or light condiments; they overhear their moms
complain that they're ``too fat.'' We talk to nutritionists and
psychologists about adolescent eating disorders as well as to
``healthy'' families about how they eat and how they view
themselves. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50 WITH
ILLUSTRATION and PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
