<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 8, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-INTERPRETERS (San Francisco) _ Hoping to slow the loss of
translators in California courts, the state Judicial Council has
announced it is increasing the daily pay for certified interpreters
from the $200 most were being paid a day to $243. More than 200
languages are spoken in the state _ and more than 100 on any given
day are interpreted in the courts. By EMILY GURNON.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-BUMPING (San Francisco) _ Overbooked planes and crowded
skies mean more and more passengers are getting left on the ground
_ involuntarily ``bumped'' from their flights. During the first
quarter, the number of fliers bumped rose 55 percent compared to
the same period last year, according to U.S. Department of
Transportation statistics. The government figures also showed a
general increase in consumer complaints about air travel. By
VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-PARTNERS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ California Gov. Gray
Davis has come out of the closet on domestic partnerships _ forcing
a San Francisco lawmaker to water down her measure and limit the
benefits only to state workers in same-sex relationships. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-SERGEANTS (San Antonio) _ Two Brooks Air Force Base
sergeants face an August hearing on charges they had sex with
several female students at the base, the Air Force announced. By
SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SUBURBAN-COWBOY (Kinsgbury, Texas) _ On a recent afternoon, a
cantankerous rodeo bull eluded Bubba Jahns, 39, the ``contract
cowboy'' in Guadalupe County, Texas. The suburban wrangler is
responsible for rounding up livestock that gets loose in this
county east of San Antonio where subdivisions and ranches exist
side by side, though not always harmoniously. By ROGER CROTEAU.
</P>
<P>
   GADGET-MAN (Undated) _ The movie ``Inspector Gadget'' is
bringing with it a new round of toy mania. McDonald's Happy Meals
will each come with one piece of Gadget Man. Total number of pieces
needed to assemble Gadget Man: eight. By JEANNIE KEVER.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-DOORS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Although not widely used today, the
split door, which is more commonly known as a Dutch door, has been
around since the early 1600s. In addition to privacy, the split
door can provide ventilation and natural light. By FRANCES INGRAHAM
HEIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK (Rome, N.Y.) _ Control is the word for Woodstock 99
organizers hoping to avoid the surreptitious influx of drugs and
alcohol and to regulate the chaos of crowd-surfing, moshing
throngs. The 30th anniversary of the historic gathering of ``peace,
love and understanding'' is expected to lure 250,000-300,000 former
hippies and children of flower children to the decommissioned
Griffis Air Force base July 23-25. By MIKE FRICANO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALCIUM (Undated) _ The facts were all over the news last
weekend: Americans aren't getting enough calcium. As a result, the
body leaches the mineral from your bones, weakening them and
leaving them brittle, a condition called osteoporosis. A lack of
calcium also may contribute to high blood pressure and increasing
calcium may cut the risk of colon cancer and the symptoms of
premenstrual syndrome. But increasing calcium intake may be
difficult and confusing. Here's help. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO-SANDWICH (Undated) _ Heaven on earth is a tomato
sandwich. As long as the tomatoes are locally grown, that is. I
devour thinly sliced tomatoes placed with mayonnaise, salt and
pepper between two slices of plain white bread. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   McCAIN-CAMPAIGN (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Looking for traction in
his uphill campaign for the presidency, Sen. John McCain is tying
his chances for the Republican nomination to his longtime bid for
campaign finance reform. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Major league baseball can't get
to Fenway Park fast enough. The All-Star Game is coming up and the
event will look spectacular in Boston, at the sport's most charming
venue. Baseball needs a dose of Fenway, a reprieve from the
decidely less charming events of recent weeks. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-SCURRY (San Francisco) _ One of the first things that
strikes you about Briana Scurry is her patience. Following her
dominating performance in the United States' 2-0 win over Brazil in
the Women's World Cup semifinal at Stanford Stadium last Sunday,
Scurry stood in the sun and answered questions for the best part of
an hour. As the session went on and on, the questions took on a
numbing familiarity, but she never lost her smile _ or her cool. By
DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ President Clinton managed to
arrange his national poverty tour so this Saturday he can be at the
Rose Bowl to watch the American women's soccer team play the
Chinese women in the World Cup finals. Hey, there are poor people
in shorts. Soccer is underfunded. Once again, Bill is multitasking.
By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ On the Fourth of July, a day
that is uniquely ours, a day in which we are supposed to reflect
upon the greatness of this 223-year-old nation, another
disaffected, disturbed, hate-filled white male went on a violent
rampage. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
