<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-LORNA-LUFT-ON-JUDY-GARLAND-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORNA LUFT AND A TALE OF TWO JUDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of singer Lorna
Luft and of her as a baby with her mother, Judy Garland. 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The role of Judy Garland may seem impossible to cast, but Lorna
Luft _ daughter of the legendary singer and author of the book on
which an upcoming television film will be based _ thinks she's
found the right woman for the role.
 &HT;    ``She is my dream to play my mother _ she has such
vulnerability,'' Luft says. ``She was my first choice, the absolute
top of my wish list.''
 &HT;    The object of her delight is the Oscar-nominated Australian
actress Judy Davis, who has been signed to play Garland in a
three-hour-long ABC adaptation of Luft's best-selling book ``Me and
My Shadows'' (Pocket Books, 1998), about the enormously talented
but tragic singer, who died too young at 47 in l969.
 &HT;    Garland may be gone, but she seems very much present in a bare
rehearsal room in Hollywood. On a huge television screen, Garland
is singing one of her hit ballads, ``I Can't Give You Anything But
Love,'' while just a few steps away, Luft is singing with her as a
duet.
 &HT;    She's rehearsing her new one-woman show, ``Songs My Mother
Taught Me,'' first launched in May in Atlantic City and due to play
other North American venues into 2000. And, yes, some of those
songs _ including Garland's signature tune, ``Over the Rainbow'' _
are sung, through the wonders of modern technology, as duets with
Garland herself.
 &HT;    Suddenly the picture on the giant screen changes. It's footage
from one of Garland's 1960s television shows.
 &HT;    ``I have a daughter who's pretty angry because nobody has ever
written a song about her _ until now,'' she says.
 &HT;    Then the camera pulls back to show the mother facing the
dewy-eyed 6-year-old, and Garland sings ``Lorna'' to her little
girl. When the song ends, mother and daughter embrace.
 &HT;    In l999, the scene still brings tears to the eyes of the
46-year-old Luft, who has stopped to watch.
 &HT;    A bit later, more collected, Luft sits in a shady corner outside
the rehearsal room to talk about her two favorite Judies.
 &HT;    ``Judy Davis is an extraordinary actress, and she has all the
tools to play my mother,'' she says. ``Look at her wide-ranging
work, going all the way back to `Passage to India' (1984) _ she can
do anything. When I heard she was interested in doing a musical, I
told my producer, `Boy, do we have a story for her.'''
 &HT;    The cast of characters includes Luft, her brother Joey and their
father, producer Sid Luft, as well as their half-sister Liza
Minnelli, daughter of director Vincente Minnelli. But everyone else
seems dwarfed by their mother, whose talent was matched only by her
propensity for self-destruction.
 &HT;    ``I didn't want to glorify or to vilify my family,'' Luft says.
``I want to tell a truer and much more interesting story about a
group of people who grew up in the public eye and got through it
the best they could.
 &HT;    ``Sure, we were a dysfunctional family _ but what family
isn't?''
 &HT;    By the time her 30-year-old mother gave birth to her, Luft says,
Garland had been hooked on prescription drugs for almost half her
life. The three children grew up having to look after their
constantly ailing mother.
 &HT;    Garland's personal problems ran in the family: Luft chronicles
her mother's drug escapades and her sister's drug problems, but is
equally candid about her own cocaine and alcohol habits, as well as
her troubled romantic history, including affairs with Barry Manilow
and Burt Reynolds.
 &HT;    Today, Luft admits, she has no relationship with Minnelli. The
two daughters of Judy Garland haven't spoken in years, and Luft
doesn't know if Minnelli is even aware of her one-woman tribute to
their mother.
 &HT;    ``I wish Liza the best,'' Luft says sadly, ``but we are not
close. We once were. But I have chosen to live my life without her
for now.''
 &HT;    As for Garland, many of her problems were traceable to drugs,
Luft believes.
 &HT;    ``When she was a teenager and doing `Wizard of Oz' (l939), they
fed her benzedrine to help her lose weight and cope with the
exhausting film schedule,'' she says. ``Doctors were ignorant about
treatments for addictions. Sure, they had A.A. in those days, but
women didn't go. And movie stars _ are you crazy?
 &HT;    ``Today it's so different,'' she adds. ``There's the Betty Ford
Center and clinics like Hazelden to help. But in those days a star
going into rehab could have kissed her career goodbye.''
 &HT;    Luft was a troubled teen-ager when Garland entered the final
stages of her long decline, and made frantic, ultimately futile
efforts to save her mother.
 &HT;    ``It led to my own breakdown from severe emotional and physical
exhaustion,'' she says. ``One by one my mother had worn us all
down.''
 &HT;    Today the singer proclaims herself better than perhaps she's
ever been. Since 1996 she's been married to Englishman Colin
Freeman, a musical arranger who leads the orchestra for her
one-woman show.
 &HT;    She has two children _ 15-year-old Jesse and 9-year-old Vanessa
_ from an earlier marriage, and says that the book, the television
movie and the one-woman show are all part of her effort to help
them understand the grandmother they never knew.
 &HT;    ``I want to tell them who their grandmother was,'' she says.
``After all, `The Wizard of Oz' is part of their legacy.''
 &HT;    Luft admits to being nervous about the show.
 &HT;    ``You have to make friends with the legend first,'' she says.
``It took me a long time to do that _ I fought who I was related to
for a long time. I remember, early in my career when I was trying
to break into the record business, an executive called and said,
`Why don't you do a disco version of ``Over the Rainbow?''' I got
out of that place fast!
 &HT;    ``When your parent is a public idol, you never really have a
chance to lay that parent to rest,'' she muses. ``I am reminded
daily of my mother's life and her death. Every day I miss her and I
miss the relationship she would have had with my kids.''
 &HT;    In some way, she says, she sees her show as an embodiment of
that relationship.
 &HT;    ``It took me a long time to pluck up the courage to do it,'' she
says. ``But writing the book helped me come to terms with my mother
and her legend. Then I heard Nancy Sinatra say that we have a
responsibility to keep our parents' legends alive in the proper
light. I agree. It's vitally important that people don't forget
what they left us.
 &HT;    ``Frank (Sinatra) was my godfather,'' she adds, ``and for a long
time there were just the two great artists, Frank and my mom. They
are no longer here, but we mustn't let people forget.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Me and My Shadows,'' consult
the Simon and Schuster Website at www.simonsays.com. And don't
