<HEADLINE>
DUTCH DOORS ADD TOUCH OF COUNTRY TO A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Although not widely used today, the split door,
which is more commonly known as a Dutch door, has been around since
the early 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of the split door is found throughout much of rural
Europe,'' said Roderick Blackburn, architectural historian, author
and antiques dealer in Columbia County, N.Y. ``It was originally a
convenient way to keep kids in and pigs and other animals out. It
created a social distance by allowing you to communicate with the
public, without having them in your home.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to privacy, the split door provided ventilation and
natural light.
</P>
<P>
   Blackburn also noted that dense populations made the split door
popular in rural towns and cities to keep vermin, neighbors and
vendors at bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Split doors aren't used on houses very much today,'' Blackburn
said. ``They are basically a quaint survival of years past. I've
seen them in Greece, Norway and Spain.''
</P>
<P>
   Dutch doors also can be found on barns and stables, where the
top half can be opened for ventilation, while keeping animals in,
or locked together for use as a standard door.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch doors may be custom ordered to add a bit of country charm
to your home, barn or garage.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the material, size, finish and whether or not glass
inserts will be used, split doors cost $500 and up.
</P>
</TEXT>
