<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE REAL ALL-STARS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of
country singer/songwriter Kenny Rogers.) &QL; 
 &UR; By KENNY ROGERS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers, a living legend of country music, writes about
winning, losing and the meaning of baseball in this special column
just in time for the Baseball All-Star Game _ to be played on July
13 in Boston _ and his new hit, ``The Greatest,'' which is about
children and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers recounts how he came to record the song, shares some
baseball-story letters he's gotten from fans and discusses what
baseball means to him in a funny, heartwarming essay that has all
the easy charm of his best songs.
</P>
<P>
   For information on this story, contact New York Times Syndicate
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-KENNY-ROGERS-ON-BASEBALL-ART-NYTSF, priority code
w, category code e)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate)
