<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AMERICANPIE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD `PIE': COMEDY MIXES EQUAL PARTS TEEN SEXUAL ANGST WITH GROSS
HUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new comedy ``American Pie'' doesn't seem new. It shrewdly
rekindles the spirit of the 1982 raunch-comedy, ``Porky's,'' where
every member of the cast was obsessed with sex. But _ surprise _
``Pie'' manages to be both smart and calculating. In the end, the
movie is about romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pie'' is another of those high-school movies where the
protagonists make a pact, placing it squarely in the new-school
tradition of ``She's All That'' and ``10 Things I Hate About You.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, four friends, all seniors, resolve to lose their
virginity. The most determined, and the most hapless, is Jim (Jason
Biggs). It's Jim who makes the moves on the apple pie (which has a
hilariously spelled note on it). It's Jim who blows his cool when
he gets a chance to be alone with another kind of deep-dish, the
willowy foreign exchange student Nadia (Shannon Elizabeth). And
it's Jim whose father (played by a wonderfully deadpan Eugene Levy)
tries to walk him through the minefield of adolescent sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin (Thomas Ian Nicholas) and his longtime girlfriend (Tara
Reid) are trapped in the classic teen movie dilemma _ wondering
when they should go all the way. ``Pie'' is made of ``classic''
gambits: Oz (Texas Christian University student Chris Klein, who
made his laid-back debut in ``Election'') is a jock who discards
the in-your-face approach to chasing women for the sensitive route
to get Heather (Mena Suvari, a doe-eyed wonder); Finch (Eddie Kaye
Thomas) is the odd man out, an obsessive-compulsive bohemian with a
dry, arch delivery who carries a thermos of mochaccino wherever he
goes.
</P>
<P>
   These guys all seem like such confident smoothies _ with the
exception of Jim, whose heart rises up into his cartoonishly bright
eyes whenever he gets near a girl _ that we know it's only a matter
of time before they get what they want. To its credit, ``Pie''
doesn't say that the quest makes them better people. It sees the
joke in their shallow obsession, and the fact that humiliation is
never more than a heartbeat away for any of them.
</P>
<P>
   The women here aren't degraded or treated as meat. For the most
part, they're creatures whom the foursome just can't understand.
The wisest is Jessica, played by Natasha Lyonne with a mature rasp
and a levelheaded grasp of the games being played out. At 17, she's
already a veteran of the relationship wars, and she knows when to
keep her distance. Alyson Hannigan, as a chattering band-geek who
goes after Jim, knows exactly who she is, too. That's what all the
young women have in common: They know what they want. They have the
real power. It's the guys who can only concentrate on sexual
conquest, just like real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pie'' is set in the moneyed suburban paradise that John Hughes
brought to the screen for teen movies, without the
``in-every-dream-a-heartache'' angst that gave a little Tang to his
white-bread settings. (Here, that setting is emphasized when we see
Oz and his girl in a choir doing lite-FM versions of R&AMP;B classics.)
Instead, the brand of bad taste that ``National Lampoon's Animal
House'' helped to institutionalize is prevalent (for example,
there's a super-laxative joke).
</P>
<P>
   But the bad taste is so energetic and good-natured that it
almost doesn't matter if it masks cynicism; the script is as
determined to score as the fellas. The straightforward direction by
Paul Weitz spreads on such CoolWhip optimism that's it hard to be
offended by the material.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``American Pie'' doesn't traffic in the Ivy League
ruthlessness of Hughes or ``Animal House,'' pictures whose
go-for-the-gusto crudeness clearly inspired it. Instead, it's got a
heart, and enough of a brain to not pass judgment on its
characters.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``American Pie''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Paul Weitz
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jason Biggs, Chris Klein, Thomas Ian Nicholas
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ sexual content, nudity, gross-out humor and alcohol
consumption
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
