<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADULT ENTERTAINMENT STARRING THE FIRST COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton managed to arrange his
national poverty tour so he can be at the Rose Bowl Saturday to
watch the American women's soccer team play the Chinese women in
the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, there are poor people in shorts. Soccer is underfunded.
Once again, the president is multitasking.
</P>
<P>
   The dirty-old-man-in-chief just wants to watch young women run
and sweat, you say. His wife is doing that in 100-degree weather in
New York, and he's in comfy La-La Land to watch women dribble and
head the ball and kick the bejabbers out of each other.
</P>
<P>
   You could say our president just like sports, but it gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was scheduled to be at the Bonaventure Hotel in Los
Angeles on Thursday, the same day the Adult Entertainment Expo sets
up shop in the same hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has promised not to bother us, and we promised not to
bother him,'' said a woman I talked to who works for the adult
video expo.
</P>
<P>
   And no, Clinton's famous X-rated, Kenneth Starr-directed video,
``Bubba Redefines Sex,'' is not up for an award.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything in politics. The same week Clinton is in
Los Angeles for the adult video convention and women's soccer
match, his wife launched a historic run for the Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   None of this can be a coincidence. Very little happens in the
Clintons' life by coincidence. They can't even take a vacation
without strategic planning, polling and focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' life is one of eternal triangulation.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts believe that Hillary Rodham Clinton's
popularity stems from voters' sympathy for her because of her
husband's affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   What better strategy could there be than for Hillary Clinton to
start campaigning while the president is sharing a hotel with the
leading figures of the adult entertainment industry?
</P>
<P>
   It reminds voters of last year's nonstop White House porno loop,
and thus the Hillary Clinton sympathy vote grows. Then voters turn
on the TV Saturday, and there's the president again, appreciating
women and the sporting life.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, no matter who wins the soccer finals, the first lady
should be breaking out of her statistical tie in the polls with New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani may have a clean Times Square on his side, but Hillary
Clinton has a dirty husband.
</P>
<P>
   And no, a statistical tie was not the kind of tie Lewinsky gave
the president.
</P>
<P>
   When Hillary Clinton was campaigning in Republican-dominated
upstate New York on Wednesday, she dodged a question about whether
she was the beneficiary of a sympathy vote.
</P>
<P>
   All she said was, ``I look forward to meeting with New Yorkers.
I think they will have a lot to tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   What? She thinks New Yorkers will have a lot to tell her? Has
she ever taken a cab or watched a Martin Scorsese movie? Are you
talking to me? Her comment isn't really naive. It's completely
cynical. It's part of a typical Clintonian strategy. Hillary
Clinton's campaign trip upstate was billed as a ``listening
stour.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I hear your pain.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has moved to address the carpetbagger issue,
saying that while listening and learning from New Yorkers she hopes
``to demonstrate that what I am for is maybe as important, if not
more important, than where I am from.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I feel your doubt.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked Hillary Clinton if she felt it took a lot
of ``chutzpah'' to run for office in New York, she said, ``I'm told
that characteristic is not all bad in certain parts of New York. I
may need a little of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the mayonnaise. Pass the white bread. Pass the vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton plans to keep listening in New York all summer.
She is always billed as ``strong on the issues,'' but when asked
what they were she said, ``All I can say is that I care deeply
about the issues that are important in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   She's going to have to do a lot of listening, and fast, the way
New Yorkers talk.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady would only say that as senator she would
emphasize education, health care and ``New York getting its fair
share from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   This whole thing is completely calculated. Hillary Clinton, like
her husband, has learned never to be too specific, and to find tiny
issues to cultivate like bonsai plants.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Clintons aren't breaking up. They're as unified as mush.
</P>
<P>
   How does that joke go? If Hillary starts dropping in the polls,
all Bill has to do is start dropping his pants.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, though, the folks at the Adult Entertainment Expo
really, really don't want him to.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
