<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROSS-OUT TEEN COMEDY FOLLOWS IN `MARY'S' FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ A lot has happened since Warren Zide and Craig
Perry got the green light from Universal Pictures to make
``American Pie.'' The movie, a good-natured but often raunchy teen
comedy that follows four Midwestern high school seniors who
desperately want to lose their virginity by prom night, opens
today.
</P>
<P>
   First, a movie called ``There's Something About Mary'' came out
while ``Pie'' was in pre-production. That movie's success showed
there was a broad audience for comedies that mix romance and
gross-out humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studio was a lot more open to our movie when they saw how
well (`Mary') did,'' said Perry, who formed Zide/Perry Films with
Zide two years ago. The two partners are very young _ in their
early 30s _ as is virtually everyone associated with the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Added Zide, ``It definitely allowed us to do things we wanted to
do, which the studio wasn't so sure about at first.'' These things,
which can't be described in detail in a family paper, include a
lewd act with the baked dessert of the title and a sexual reference
to a musical instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as Universal cranked up to market ``Pie,'' theater owners,
under pressure from politicians and parents, vowed to clamp down on
selling tickets to minors for R-rated movies. The filmmakers
remained adamant that ``Pie'' must be R-rated to be funny and true
to its subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, there's nothing we can do about (theater owners
checking IDs); we just have to roll with it,'' sighed Zide, who's
quickly made a successful career out of managing and producing the
work of young writers. ``But,'' he added, ``I don't think this is
the kind of movie that they wanted to stop kids from seeing.
There's no violence in it.''
</P>
<P>
   No violence, but plenty of sexual content and gross-out humor,
which can be just as offensive to some. The pendulum of what's
acceptable in teen-oriented films swings back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit ironic that ``American Pie'' is being touted as the
most raucous coming-of-age tale since ``Porky's'' and ``Fast Times
at Ridgemont High,'' since both those movies were released in the
1980s _ not generally considered to have been an adventurous time
for film. ``American Pie'' follows in their R-rated footsteps, but
comes at a different time in the political/social climate.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weitz, one of the film's producers and the younger brother
of director Paul Weitz, contends that the movie is actually less
cynical than many of the teen flicks that have recently flooded
theaters. ``This film isn't that spiritually distant from the world
of Andy Hardy,'' said the 29-year-old Weitz. ``The kids are kind of
innocent and naive in their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Fast Times,'' ``Pie'' may end up spawning several stars
among its ensemble of little-knowns. Perhaps the best-known young
cast member is Alyson Hannigan, who plays Willow on the WB
Network's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Lyonne, Mena Suvari and Chris Klein have received notice
for their recent roles in such films as ``Slums of Beverly Hills,''
``The Rage: Carrie 2'' and ``Election.'' Jason Biggs, who has the
movie's largest part, is known to soap viewers from his role on
``As the World Turns.''
</P>
<P>
   But these faces are all fresh, allowing them to portray awkward
adolescents believably. ``A lot of these kids are from the
heartland,'' said Perry of the cast. ``They're not Hollywood teens;
many of them are religious.'' In fact, some of the youths may have
been more cautious than their parents about taking these roles:
Klein was recently quoted as saying that when he expressed concern
that the script might be ``too gross,'' his mother replied, ``Don't
be retarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who bears a passing resemblance to Keanu Reeves, seems to
be one cast member who's marked for stardom. He's already filming
his next movie, ``Here on Earth,'' co-starring Leelee Sobieski of
the recent television miniseries ``Joan of Arc'' and ``A Soldier's
Daughter Never Cries.'' To some of the more worldly cast members,
the clean-cut Klein _ who grew up in the Midwest and has attended
Texas Christian University as his work schedule has allowed _ seems
almost hilariously perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all-American boy ... I'm in shock,'' said Hannigan,
patting Klein on the shoulder. ``I didn't know that people like
Chris existed. I thought it was just something you saw on `The
Brady Bunch.'''
</P>
<P>
   One cast member whose appeal is definitely un-Brady Bunch is
Shannon Elizabeth, who bares nearly all in the film in her role as
a sexy foreign exchange student. As the movie opens, Elizabeth is
capitalizing on it by appearing in a 10-page layout in Playboy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really goes along with my character,'' said Elizabeth,
``and it just seemed like a fun thing to do. (Posing for the
magazine) has always intrigued me, and it seemed like this might be
a good time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie's young stars all say they were impressed with
the script, they also seem genuinely surprised that the movie now
has so much positive ``buzz'' surrounding it. ``
</P>
<P>
   ``It never entered my mind that we'd be here, talking to the
press (about this movie),'' admitted Eddie Kaye Thomas. Baby-faced
Thomas, at 18, is the youngest cast member, but also one of the
most experienced: He attended Manhattan's Professional Children's
School while appearing on Broadway and in movies, beginning at age
12.
</P>
<P>
   Casting young no-names allowed the filmmakers to keep the cost
of the movie down to a reported $11 million, a fraction of what
many star-driven movies cost. This virtually assures Universal will
make money on the film, regardless of whether some box-office
admissions are lost to enforcement of the
no-kids-under-17-without-an-adult rule.
</P>
<P>
   The cast members, like the filmmakers, are trying to be
philosophical about the possible loss of audience. Most think kids
will find a way to get into the film, whether by sneaking in or by
getting parents or older siblings to buy tickets for them. Hannigan
has a particularly creative suggestion for teen-age would-be movie
patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, take the homeless,'' said Hannigan, eliciting a roar of
laughter from her fellow castmates. ``I think they should put that
on the poster.'' &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
