</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROAD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS `ROAD' TAKES SOME FRIGHTENING TURNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The '90s are on view in ``Arlington Road'' _
all-the-houses-look-alike subdivisions, the Internet, tragedies in
Waco and Oklahoma City (with St. Louis acting as a fictional
stand-in for the latter) _ but so are the '70s. Specifically, the
'70s of paranoid thrillers such as ``The Parallax View'' and ``The
Conversation,'' movies that took venerable Hitchockian themes and
gave them a post-Watergate cynical spin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Road,'' directed by Mark Pellington, feels a little like a
pastiche of the genre's movies: a little methodical Alan J. Pakula
paranoia here, a little manic Brian de Palma paranoia there, with
the Hitchockian undercurrent still in place, all wrapped up in
Pellington's music-video background. The surprising thing, given
all these ingredients, is how well ``Arlington Road'' manages to
cohere.
</P>
<P>
   Pellington has the advantage of a great cast. The teaming of
Jeff Bridges and Tim Robbins alone will be enough to get some
people into the theater, much like the pairing of Samuel L. Jackson
and Kevin Spacey drew audiences to last summer's mediocre ``The
Negotiator.'' In Hope Davis and Joan Cusack, who play the actors'
significant others, Pellington has two of the most reliable
actresses working today. (Cusack is especially good here, in the
movie's most deceptively subtle performance.) But it's really
Bridges' show, at least when Pellington isn't letting his
hyperactive style get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges, who wears a look of haunted dishevelment better than
any other actor, plays Michael Faraday, a college professor who's
been troubled ever since his FBI-agent wife was killed in a
standoff with a right-wing group. Ostensibly a government
professor, Faraday obsesses over terrorism to the point where
everybody begins thinking that he's a little nuts, especially when
he starts casting suspicion on his new neighbor Oliver Lang
(Robbins), a nice-guy engineer with a supportive, cheerful wife and
three kids (the characters are brought together through an opening
sequence so eerily striking, you might think you're still watching
trailers for another movie).
</P>
<P>
   Because of ``Road's'' bumpy history _ it's finally hitting
screens after two earlier release dates were postponed _ its
trailer has been around seemingly forever. And it's a lousy
trailer, one that has Internet movie geeks up in arms because it
reveals too much of the film.
</P>
<P>
   They have a point, but then ``Road'' also reveals a little too
much of itself _ Robbins gives an ominous twist to every one of his
lines, and the Lang children appear to have been adopted from
``Village of the Damned.'' The audience never thinks Bridges is
crazy but might start wondering about the sanity of the other
characters.
</P>
<P>
   This is another Hitchcock trick _ letting the audience in on
secrets that the people in the movie don't know _ but Pellington,
in his second feature, doesn't quite pull off the ambiguity needed
to make this work as well as it should.
</P>
<P>
   But Pellington seems virtually alone among music-video grads in
that he wants to make movies, not glorified videos, using the
quick-edit techniques to heighten suspense rather than show off.
And ``Road'' is a step up from the mundanity of his first feature,
the 1997 coming-of-age story ``Going All the Way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pellington doesn't seem quite ready to make ``his'' movies,
though, borrowing heavily from other directors _ an odd habit for
someone who directed the video for Pearl Jam's ``Jeremy,'' one of
the most stunning clips of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy'' addressed high-school violence nearly a decade before
the Columbine High School shootings, which occurred shortly before
``Road's'' second scheduled release date and allegedly had
something to do with its postponement. Studio representatives say
that this isn't the case, but even if it were, ``Road'' still comes
at a time when mass violence is in the news, trailing reports of
race-based slayings in Illinois and Indiana by less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   This makes ``Road's'' themes _ of how life can change in an
instant, and how little we know about the people around us _
fortuitously timely. It also makes the movie, despite its
sharpness, less scary than real life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Arlington Road''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Mark Pellington
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jeff Bridges, Tim Robbins
</P>
<P>
   Length: 117 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and strong language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
