A3032 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-YESTERDAY-TEX     07-08 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-YESTERDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME REPEATS ITSELF IN `YESTERDAY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot to be said for being first, especially when it
comes to movies forming their own coincidental subgenres. ``The
Matrix'' looks like the best of this year's virtual-reality movies
because it initiated a wave of similarly themed films. Likewise,
last year's ``Sliding Doors'' may have been the best in the latest
series of films about romantic fate, simply because it started that
series.
</P>
<P>
   One of those films was called ``Deja Vu,'' and that's exactly
the feeling you're likely to get from ``Twice Upon a Yesterday,''
at least if you've seen any of the other films in this minigenre.
In ``Twice,'' a boozing slacker actor named Victor (Douglas
Henshall) gets a second chance after screwing up with his
girlfriend. This happens not because of the generosity of her
heart, but because he meets a couple of quixotic characters who
allow him to turn back time and _ well, if he had to do it all over
again, he'd do it differently, right? Isn't that always the way?
</P>
<P>
   It must be the way with a certain brand of filmmaker, the kind
who's so interested in playing with time that you begin to think
that he or she has been spending too many hours in editing rooms
rearranging reality. Maria Ripoll, the Spanish director who made
``Yesterday'' with a mostly British cast, at least has some
interesting visual ideas to go along with all the existential
questing. If you're the most incurable of romantics, it might be
worth seeking out. But even then, you might think that a more
accurate title would be ``Been There, Done That.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Twice Upon a Yesterday''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Maria Ripoll
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Douglas Henshall, Penelope Cruz
</P>
<P>
   Length: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ language and sexual content
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
