<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALCIUM-HNS &LR;      07-08 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALCIUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO GET MORE CALCIUM IN YOUR DIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's been all over the news recently: Americans
aren't getting enough calcium. As a result, the body leaches the
mineral from your bones, weakening them and leaving them brittle, a
condition called osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of calcium also may contribute to high blood pressure and
increasing calcium may cut the risk of colon cancer and the
symptoms of premenstrual syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   But increasing calcium intake may be difficult and confusing.
Here's help:
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much calcium do I need?
</P>
<P>
   A. That depends. The National Institutes of Health recommends
the following amounts per day: 800 to 1,200 milligrams for children
ages 1 to 10; 1,200-1,500 milligrams for people 11-24 years old and
pregnant and nursing women; 1,000 milligrams for premenopausal
women, postmenopausal women using estrogen and men ages 25-65;
1,500 milligrams for postmenopausal women not using estrogen and
all people older than 65.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What foods are the best sources of calcium?
</P>
<P>
   A. With 300 milligrams of calcium in an 8-ounce glass, milk
contains a lot of calcium. Tofu set with calcium, yogurt, canned
ricotta cheese, navy beans, turnips, broccoli and calcium-fortified
foods such as orange juice, bread and cereal are also good sources.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Wait a minute. I'd have to drink three and a third glasses of
milk to get the calcium I need. That adds 495 calories and 27 grams
of fat every day if I drink whole milk. What do I do if I'm trying
to lose weight?
</P>
<P>
   A. Skim milk contains as much calcium as whole milk without the
fat and calories. Three and a third glasses of skim milk a day
would give you the calcium and only 284 calories and 1.32 grams of
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm lactose intolerant and don't drink milk at all. How can I
get enough calcium?
</P>
<P>
   A. Lactose-free products such as Lactaid usually contain as much
calcium as milk. In addition, there are calcium-fortified
lactose-free products that contain even more calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I eat a vegan diet (no meat or dairy products) for
humanitarian reasons. Can I get enough calcium without compromising
my ethics?
</P>
<P>
   A. Sure. Milk-like products made from soy are frequently
calcium-fortified too. Or, drink calcium-fortified orange juice and
eat food high in calcium such as navy beans, broccoli and collards.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does calcium-fortified orange juice taste different from
regular orange juice?
</P>
<P>
   A. In an informal but blind tasting, five out of 10 tasters
couldn't tell a difference between Minute Maid Premium Original Low
Pulp orange juice and Minute Maid Original Low Pulp Orange Juice
With Calcium. Another four tasters said the difference was
insignificant. The only person who detected a change in flavor
happened to be hanging around when the juices were being poured and
new of the difference in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The National Institutes of Health recommends calcium intake
in milligrams but nutrition labels list calcium amounts in
percentages. How do I calculate how much calcium I've consumed?
</P>
<P>
   A. Add up the percent of daily value of calcium in each food
you've eaten. When you've reached 100 percent, you've gotten enough
calcium for the day, if you need 1,000 milligrams.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm confused. You say I need 1,000-1,500 milligrams of
calcium a day and my husband needs 1,000. According to the
nutrition label on the carton of yogurt I bought, it contains 30
percent of the daily value of calcium. Who's daily value are they
referring to, his or mine?
</P>
<P>
   A. Generally, his. The percentage of daily value of calcium
indicated on the label is based on the amount of a nutrient
required for most adults (1,000 milligrams). If you have higher
calcium needs, you'll have to eat more of a food to get the same
percentage of your daily value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
