<SLUG> BC-TREK-RENNY-HARLIN-DIRECTS-DEEP-BLUE-SEA-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING WITH THE SHARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of actor Thomas
Jane confronting an immense shark in a scene from ``Deep Blue
Sea.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Think ``Jaws,'' only more of them. And bigger. With more teeth.
Lots more teeth.
 &HT;    Think genetically manipulated sharks, with new brainpower, new
cunning, new imagination ... and the same old appetite.
 &HT;    No wonder they're calling it ``Jurassic Shark.''
 &HT;    Actually, the studio's name for director Renny Harlin's new
sci-fi thriller is ``Deep Blue Sea.'' Opening July 30, it's about a
group of scientists who, seeking a cure for Alzheimer's disease,
genetically enhance a laboratory group of sharks _ and,
predictably, learn not long thereafter that it's not such a good
idea to mess with Mother Nature.
 &HT;    ``Technically, I guess you'd have to call the movie sci-fi,''
Harlin says over a drink at the swank Mercer Kitchen in Manhattan.
``It's not sci-fi in the sense that `Star Wars' and `Star Trek' are
sci-fi. They're set in space, in a different time, on other worlds,
and they have aliens. `Deep Blue Sea' is set here and now, with
real people.
 &HT;    ``It could almost happen,'' the director adds. ``We're
practically there, with all the gene therapy and cloning that's
going on now. The film is more science fact than sci-fi, more like
`Jurassic Park' in that sense.''
 &HT;    Unlike Steven Spielberg's crew on that 1993 classic, though,
Harlin and company didn't rely on computer-generated critters. They
filmed real sharks and created a variety of mechanical sharks for
closeups and sequences in which the sharks interact with cast
members. Only a few shots added CG sharks to the mix.
 &HT;    ``If the sharks are not convincing, the movie is not
convincing,'' Harlin says. ``I would not have done the movie if we
couldn't see that our sharks would work. They're ferocious
creatures, very realistic.
 &HT;    ``On more than one occasion they scared the s--t out of the
actors,'' he adds. ``That only made the performances more real.''
 &HT;    Delivering those performances are Saffron Burrows, Thomas Jane,
L.L. Cool J, Deborah Kara Unger, Stellan Skaarsgard and Michael
Rapaport as the crew aboard the floating science facility, and
Samuel L. Jackson as the businessman funding their project.
 &HT;    Jackson is the film's biggest name, but he's still a notch down
from the true A-list of stars _ which, Harlin says, is no accident.
 &HT;    ``The movie needed to come in at a price,'' he says, ``and I
wanted the money on the screen.
 &HT;    ``Also, if you have too many names in a movie like this, you get
into issues of who dies and when,'' he adds. ``Certain stars won't
do a movie if they die. Other stars will only die if they go out
heroically in the last scene.
 &HT;    ``I needed actors who could be part of an ensemble,'' the
director concludes. ``I wanted the audience to care about everybody
and believe in these people, even if you don't always like them or
what they do. Too big a presence in this movie would have rocked
the boat.''
 &HT;    The early buzz on ``Deep Blue Sea'' is encouraging, tagging it
as a solid sci-fi/actioner with a good shot at swallowing up a
chunk of the summer box-office take.
 &HT;    If so, it couldn't come at a better time for the Finnish-born
director. It's been a long time since the late 1980s and early
1990s, when ``A Nightmare on Elm Street IV,'' ``Cliffhanger'' and
``Die Hard 2'' marked him as an action-adventure master. After his
past two films, the disastrous pirate epic ``Cutthroat Island'' and
the under-performing thriller ``The Long Kiss Goodnight'' _ both
starring his then-wife, Geena Davis _ Harlin could use a hit.
 &HT;    ```Cutthroat Island' got out of hand,'' Harlin admits. ``We had
actor problems, boat problems and weather problems, and as soon as
the problems started, we were called a `problem' film.
 &HT;    ``Then, after we finally got it finished, nobody put any money
into promoting the film,'' he says. ``We never had a chance. It's
not a horrible film, and I'm not embarrassed by it.
 &HT;    ```Long Kiss' was a different story. It was not a big hit, but
it had a very good opening weekend and it's well-regarded in the
industry,'' he says. ``People who saw the film liked it, and it did
very well on video.''
 &HT;    Still, Harlin acknowledges that he has a lot riding on ``Deep
Blue Sea.''
 &HT;    ``If it's not successful, the studios may think twice about
using me again ... until I make something else that's successful,''
he says.
 &HT;    ``I've actually already won part of the battle,'' he adds.
``After `Die Hard 2' and `Cliffhanger,' I didn't think I could do
anything wrong. What happened with `Cutthroat Island' and `Long
Kiss Goodnight' made me less arrogant.
 &HT;    ``Also, `Deep Blue Sea' came in on time and on budget, and I
needed to show that I could do that. I think the film came out
well, and now hopefully the reviews and the box office will back
that up.'' 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Deep Blue Sea,'' consult the
film's official Website at www.deepbluesea.net. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
