<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-AID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF AGENCIES SEE KOSOVO AID CAUSING SHORTFALL ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Angola's civil war has displaced 1.6 million
people, who face widescale starvation. The United Nations says it
has only one or two weeks' worth of food in the besieged central
highlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Eritrea-Ethiopia border war, the bloodiest armed conflict in
the world, has just expanded into war-wracked Somalia, where
another 1 million people are at risk of famine due to drought.
</P>
<P>
   For a hungry 1 million people in the shattered central Asian
nation of Tajikistan, money has dried up. The United Nations has
asked for $28 million to feed them, but so far has received less
than $1 million, or 4 percent of what it needs.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the humanitarian disaster in Kosovo stands to make
things worse.
</P>
<P>
   With the disaster in the Yugoslav province acting like a magnet
for relief agencies, UN and American officials fear that many
desperately needy places around the world soon will face deadly
shortfalls of food, water and aid.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of major calamities, from Hurricane Mitch in
Central America to the Colombian earthquake and now Kosovo, relief
agencies say it has become increasingly difficult to find money for
even the largest emergencies. Hundreds of millions of dollars may
be going to the Balkans now, for instance, but the UN has raised
just 35 percent of its goal this year for the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest concern is that nations will shift money away
from Africa and Asia and into Kosovo, and that private charities
will fold other operations to focus there.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agency officials say it is too early to prove
statistically that Kosovo will siphon funds from other locales, but
small indicators are starting to point in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   A US Senate bill would cut tens of millions of dollars in
Africa-related programs, including $50 million for the Peace Corps,
from the Clinton administration's fiscal 2000 budget request. At
the same time, the bill would add $142 million for reconstruction
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Denmark has reduced its non-Kosovo foreign assistance
by 26 percent because of the Kosovo crisis. And a Los Angeles-based
charity, International Medical Corps, recently announced it will
suspend its nine-year Angola program due to lack of funding.
</P>
<P>
   As the charity hunts for $1.5 million to pay for the Angola
program, it has raised $5 million in recent months to help those in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggle with funding for Africa,'' said Nancy Aossey,
president of International Medical Corps, which has programs in
five other African countries. ``A lot of it is donor fatigue. Some
areas have had a civil war that has been going for 20 years. And a
lot of it is anytime there is a huge crisis of this magnitude, it
becomes The Story, at the expense of other stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, UN Under-Secretary-General Sergio Vieria de Mello
told the Security Council that of the 23 million people in need
throughout the world, only 3 million live in the former Yugoslavia
and its neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   De Mello outlined a tour of the neediest spots on Earth,
spotlighting UN shortfalls everywhere. In Sudan, where 2.3 million
people rely on food aid to survive, the World Food Program has a
shortfall of 40,000 tons, leading to expected shortages later this
summer. Donor assistance to Burundi has been at about 5 percent,
delaying health, education and water purification programs.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from his Angola coordinator, DeMello said, ``sound like
a SOS to the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in an telephone interview late Wednesday from Angola,
Francesco Strippoli, the UN coordinator, thanked donors for past
assistance but also made an urgent appeal:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to compare misery. I think the Kosovar people are
suffering, they need assistance. Unfortunately, we have these other
tragedies unfolding around the world, and what I can say about
Angola is that we are asking for life-saving support.''
</P>
<P>
   He described how the war in Angola forced people to flee rural
areas for cities, how cities are being bombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have one Sarajevo. We have many Sarajevos,''
Strippoli said.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Chipman, a top official at the UN Office for the
Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs based in Geneva, said the
message to donor countries has been not to forget ``Angola and
Afghanistan and other crises around the world. We're saying, `Hold
everything, folks. Yes, Kosovo is important, but don't let other
emergencies suffer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the UN itself is giving mixed messages about the importance
of Kosovo versus the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   A UN official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said
funds for Kosovo are now racing through various UN agencies,
``compared to when we get funds for Angola, Sierra Leone, Somalia,
Sudan, when everyone has to cross-check things and it takes
forever.'' The UN also is putting many of its top relief workers in
Kosovo, including de Mello himself, now the temporary overall UN
humanitarian coordinator there.
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, the UN has given priority to Kosovo. Fully
one-half of the UN's $2.2 billion worldwide appeal this year is
designated for the former Yugoslavia and its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   And of that $1.1 billion, UN agencies have requested $740
million _ one-third of its annual appeal _ for the nearly 2 million
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. They represent just 8 percent of the
people around the world designated as needy.
</P>
<P>
   What is behind the outpouring for the Kosovars?
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials say more money is necessary for the Kosovo
humanitarian disaster than comparable African crises because of
different needs and expecations, pointing out that items such as
satellite phones have been necessary for the ethnic Albanians to
locate relatives. And they say NATO's political decision to go to
war against Serbian troops, and the media's intense spotlight on
the Connecticut-sized province, started a stampede toward Kosovo
that relief agencies naturally followed.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the entire Kosovo effort, from the perspective of
military, political and humanitarian involvement, has the issue of
race at its root. A death in Kosovo, many point out, draws more
attention than a death in, say, Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Salih Booker, director of Africa Studies at the Council on
Foreign Relations in Washington, noted that the January massacre of
about 45 ethnic Albanians in the town of Racak led to a UN Security
Council meeting. At the same time, rebels invaded Freetown, the
capital of Sierra Leone, and killed 3,000 to 4,000 people. That
drew no calls for Security Council action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imagery of human crises seen in Africa is viewed as
normal, while the same images coming out of Europe are not normal
and not acceptable,'' Booker said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brian Atwood, the departing administrator for the Agency for
International Development, said policymakers need to rethink how
they respond to different crises around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has something to do with the politics of international
affairs,'' he said last week. ``It is seemingly too easy to ignore
the problems of Africa because there is an expectation that Africa
will be associated with problems. There is a higher acceptance of a
level of violence in Africa than there is elsewhere. This world is
too small to allow that to happen to one region.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
