<SLUG> BC-TOMATO-SANDWICH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN COMES IN SLICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heaven on Earth is a tomato sandwich. As long as the tomatoes
are locally grown, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I got a little trip to the Promised Land the other day when I
bought several home-grown tomatoes and have since devoured them
sliced thinly and placed with mayonnaise, salt and pepper between
two slices of plain white bread. This is one case where commercial,
presliced bread is a better ingredient than those crusty gourmet
loaves. There's something exquisite about the contrast of the soft,
bland bread and the acidic tanginess of a fully ripe tomato.
</P>
<P>
   The key to fully appreciating a tomato sandwich, though, is to
eat it as soon as it's assembled. I remember my mother trying to
pack tomato sandwiches in my lunch box and arriving at the
cafeteria table with a bunch of plastic wrap full of soggy pink
bread and tomato seeds. Yuck.
</P>
<P>
   I still have tomato sandwiches for lunch, but instead of putting
them together at home and expecting them to stay fresh, I simply
make the sandwich without the tomato. Then, I take a tomato to the
office, slice it and place it between two pieces of bread slathered
with real mayonnaise (not low-fat, not salad dressing) and
sprinkled with generous amounts of salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise on your palate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-08 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q AND A: PLAY DATES, WEANING, SEXUAL MISBEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time, this column answers selected readers'
questions. Please send yours to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe,
Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; fax 617-929-2813 or email
meltz(at)globe.com. We regret that we cannot answer all questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was raised in Asia. Children there usually just play with
neighboring kids and relatives' kids . . . (and) almost never go to
other people's houses alone to play with kids from school. Now I am
a mother of two boys, 6 and 4. They get invitations for play dates
all the time. I am very happy they are making friends in school,
but I am very reluctant to send them to other people's houses. I
don't really know the other parents and they only invite the kids,
so I feel awkward to tag along. I worry about child abuse,
firearms, swimming pools, etc. . . . If I don't allow my children
to go, I am concerned that will affect their social life. I also
invite other kids and their parents to our house. What advice do
you have, and at what age is it appropriate for kids to have play
dates without their parents around?
</P>
<P>
   A. As you wisely recognize, this is more than a matter of what's
developmentally appropriate. But let's take that first:
</P>
<P>
   The typical child will let you know when he's ready to go
without you, either by telling you point-blank _ ``I'm not a baby
anymore, Mom. I don't need you to come'' _ or by his behavior,
perhaps showing that he doesn't need you by ignoring you at the
friend's or by being angry or testy with you before or after the
visit. (That's because he can't identify and/or verbalize his wish
for independence.)
</P>
<P>
   There is no magic age when this will happen, says Eleanora
Villegas-Reimers, an associate professor of early childhood
education at Wheelock College. For some children, it can be as
young as 3, for others not until 5 or 6, and the independent
behavior may be rife with inconsistencies. For instance, he may
feel competent and grown-up enough to go alone one day but not the
next; he may feel comfortable without you in one playmate's home
but not in another's. These are typically normal blips.
</P>
<P>
   Your comfort level may be more complicated, says
Villegas-Reimers, who specializes in multicultural education and
moral development. On the one hand, she says, there are cultural
values that are intrinsic to your identity that you shouldn't feel
you have to give up. At the same time, it's important to
distinguish between fears that are valid and fears that develop
from what you see on the TV news.
</P>
<P>
   When you don't know the family issuing the invitation, she urges
you to continue to invite yourself along (``My son would love to
come, and I would too, if that's OK; we can get to know each other
and I can help out with the kids'') or to invite them to your
house. Most importantly, she says, ``Don't be shy about sharing the
cultural differences that make you anxious. You don't have to hide
your concerns or be embarrassed by them. Most people will be
pleased to learn about your culture and to share information and
offer support.'' If they aren't, follow your instinct: Perhaps
these are not homes where you are comfortable having your child
play.
</P>
<P>
   If your son wants to go alone and you don't know the family,
tell him, ``In our family, we like it best if a parent goes with
you the first time. It's more friendly that way, and we get to know
the other parents.''
</P>
<P>
   The more open you are with the other parents, the more you'll
get to know them, and the more information you have, the better
able you'll be to decide if you have a valid reason for not wanting
to leave your child there. By the way, finding out if you have
shared values is what gives any parent a critical comfort level.
It's something all of us should do more of, even when we share a
cultural background and especially as our children get older.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read your article on weaning from breast-feeding (April 22)
with great interest. My 13-month-old daughter is currently
``weaning herself.'' I wonder if you have encountered anything
about bottle feeding during your research. Is it difficult to wean
a child from the bottle (either formula or breast milk)? One of the
mothers at my daughter's day care wants the parents to have a
concerted effort to wean them off their bottles together.
</P>
<P>
   A. Whether it's difficult to wean from the bottle depends on how
emotionally attached a baby is to it, says Gale Pryor, co-author of
the classic ``Nursing Your Baby'' (third edition, Simon &AMP; Schuster)
and author of ``Nursing Mother, Working Mother: The Essential Guide
for Breastfeeding and Staying Close to Your Baby after You Return
to Work,'' (Harvard Common Press). It's more likely a baby is
attached to the bottle if:
</P>
<P>
   --He has only been bottle-fed and you have made it an intimate
and loving experience;
</P>
<P>
   --She uses the bottle as a source of comfort, for instance at
times of stress;
</P>
<P>
   --He takes the bottle into the crib as he falls asleep.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases, Pryor says, ``You need to wean as gently as you
would from the breast,'' preferably by reading your child's cues
that she's ready to move on. If a child depends on the bottle for
comfort, Pryor recommends substituting something else when the need
arises: a soft stuffed animal or a cuddly blanket. For some
children, sucking is what comforts them, and this can be a time
when they turn to their thumb if they haven't already.
</P>
<P>
   While bottle weaning can be emotionally difficult, there is at
least one way in which it tends to be easier than weaning from the
breast. ``Mom isn't going to have the same ambivalence,'' says
Pryor. ``This is not a two-way weaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of trying to wean some or all of the children in a
day-care class at the same time is not only unrealistic but also
not in each child's interest. ``Weaning is individualized, whether
it's from breast or bottle,'' says Pryor. ``It's not something you
can legislate. It's not a group effort.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I described the behavior of a friend of my son's to a
therapist friend (the 6-year-old was mooning his parents, my
husband, and myself over the loft balcony of their vacation condo
and not stopping when his somewhat embarrassed mother asked him to;
very violent behavior of this boy toward his pushy and teasing
older brother; plus other sexualized behavior that I've seen over
the past few years), I expected to be chastised for my prudishness.
Instead, my friend suggested that that kind of behavior can
sometimes indicate sibling sexual abuse. How could one recognize
such abuse? If one does suspect it, what does one do?
</P>
<P>
   A. Can you have an open conversation with one or both parents?
That's what ideally needs to happen, says Joan Tabachnick, director
of public education for Stop It Now!, a national, nonprofit, child
sexual abuse prevention program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many parents either get desensitized to a behavior and assume
it's age appropriate, a `boys-will-be-boys' kind of thing, or they
get so panicked by it, they are immobilized,'' she says. A trusted
friend who can bring it to their attention and give them a place
where they can take their questions can be the jump-start they
need.
</P>
<P>
   That a 6-year-old would moon adults does not on its own indicate
a sexual behavior problem; it's possible that the developmentally
normal fascination at this age with bathroom humor and behavior
could fuel it. But Tabachnick concurs that the combination of other
behaviors, as well as not responding to the mother's request to
stop, point in that direction. What probably needs to occur, she
says, is for an adult, preferably a parent, to have a quiet
conversation with the child, asking him a range of questions from,
``I'm wondering why you did that?'' to, ``Has anyone ever done
something like that to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Stop It Now! has a free phone line where counselors answer
questions and offer help (888-773-8368) as well as a Web site,
www.stopitnow.com. You may hear more about this organization in the
near future: A newly inaugurated national public-service campaign
is aimed at getting adults to ask questions about children's
sexualized behavior. ``This reader is doing exactly what we're
encouraging adults to do more of,'' says Tabachnick. ``Not enough
people have the courage to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, this comment from a reader:
</P>
<P>
   Re. your column of May 20, ``Should boys have war toys?'' my
answer is a loud NO. Several years ago I was baby-sitting a
grandson, then about 8. He had his GI Joes out and wanted to play
war. I told him that first we should play ``Let's go camping,''
which my husband and I did for many years with our children, and
which he knew about. We used the Joe figures to put up a tent, go
fishing, and do other fun things at a campsite. We had a great
time, and the next day when he got out his GI Joes again, he said
to me, ``Let's play camping.'' I think this is a good illustration
of how an adult can influence a child and turn their thoughts
around from playing in a destructive way to an instructive one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
