<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCH UP WITH GREAT PERFORMANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
BY ROB LOWMAN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With ``Affliction'' and ``Hilary and Jackie''
coming out this week, and ``Life Is Beautiful'' coming out Tuesday
on video, it's a perfect time for those who didn't see these
smaller films to catch up on some terrific Academy Award-nominated
acting. (Did you ever notice that it's the smaller films that
garner most of the acting nominations?)
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hilary and Jackie,'' nominees Emily Watson and Rachael
Griffiths shine as renowned cellist Jacqueline Du Pre and her
sister. Like 1996's ``Shine,'' this true story revolves around the
cutthroat and high-pressure world of classical music and family
relationships. And like ``Shine,'' there were those who were
unhappy with the way the story was brought to the screen. As the
high-strung virtuoso, Watson brings believability to Jackie's
volatile mood swings as she faces the rigors of concert life and
pitfalls of being married to a famed concert pianist, while
Griffiths, in a less splashy role _ she's an accomplished flutist
who opts for quieter life and a loving marriage _ shows an
emotional strength in Hilary. Even when this highly stylized film
is less than successful, Watson and Griffiths' performances keep
you watching. &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   While it may be unfair to say that Roberto Benigni, the star,
director and co-writer (with Vincenzo Cerami) of ``Life Is
Beautiful'' didn't deserve the best-actor Oscar, it seems a shame
that Nick Nolte didn't win it for ``Affliction.'' (We'll leave
``Life Is Beautiful'' for another time.) It would seem that the
59-year-old actor was made for the role of Wade Whitehouse, a
small-town cop and a big-time burnout whose wife has left him. A
1991 New York magazine article called Nolte the ``dysfunctional
version of the Hollywood leading man. Nolte is himself a recovering
alcoholic and former drug abuser who has been through divorce three
times and a palimony suit once, and the misery shows in his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in an action-comedy such as ``48 HRS.,'' it was Nolte's
loser-outsider that gave the film some heft. In the 1991 Barbra
Streisand-directed film ``Prince of Tides,'' the only other film
role for which he received an Oscar nomination, Nolte gave an
outstanding and believable performance as a man who kept a lifetime
of torment locked up inside of him. From comic characters (``Down
and Out in Beverly Hills'') to a racist cop (``Q&AMP;A'') to a
sympathetic father struggling to find a cure for his young son's
disease (``Lorenzo's Oil''), Nolte has consistently given
outstanding and credible performances.
</P>
<P>
   While Nolte didn't win an Oscar, veteran actor James Coburn, who
plays Wade's sadistic father, did pick up the best-supporting-actor
statuette in the Paul Schrader film. There is something
synchronistic about the pairing of Nolte and Schrader _ call it
their dark, downbeat sides. It would be nice if Hollywood and the
academy would recognize Nolte _ one of their own _ at least before
he's Coburn's age of 70.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Schrader appears to be another American artist
who is too often overlooked when it comes to handing out Oscars. In
fact, he's never even been nominated. As a screenwriter, he is
best-known for his work with Martin Scorsese _ ``Taxi Driver,''
``Raging Bull,'' ``The Last Temptation of Christ.'' But you'll see
the same intensity in the scripts he's done for his own films _
``Blue Collar,'' ``American Gigolo,'' ``Light Sleeper'' and
``Touch.'' The onetime film critic, however, has turned out a
striking body of work that is always provocative while remaining
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader has, for the most part, recently worked outside the
Hollywood system in order to adhere to his own vision without
studio interference, and by doing so has elicited numerous
wonderfully nuanced performances. As harrowing as it is to watch
sometimes _ especially when Nolte and Coburn go toe-to-toe _
``Affliction,'' adapted from the Russell Banks novel, shows off
Schrader's strength: a willingness to get to the grittiness of a
subject. American cinema could use more of that.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that Schrader's script for the Steven
Spielberg film ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' was rejected.
But that was 1977. I wonder what the post-``Saving Private Ryan''
Spielberg would think of it now.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
