<HEADER>
A3059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-NEWCOMBE-BO     07-08 1527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-NEWCOMBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMBE, ROCHE TRUE TEAM PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   White City Stadium had a capacity of 10,000, but that wouldn't
do for this epic. Not even close. So 16,000 seats were added just
for the occasion, this showdown for the 1954 Davis Cup between
Australia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed all of Sydney _ no, all of New South Wales _ was
there. At least that was the impression of 10-year-old John
Newcombe, who came across town with his father, a local dentist.
And it was perhaps even more special for 9-year-old Tony Roche, who
traveled the 220 miles from Tarcutta, a hamlet of 300 halfway
between the big cities of Sydney and Melbourne, with his dad, a
country butcher, for the big event.
</P>
<P>
   They were tennis nuts, young Newcombe and Roche, and as they sat
in separate sections of this makeshift arena swollen with humanity
_ the largest crowd ever to watch an official tennis match _ they
were inspired by the efforts of the great Lew Hoad and Ken
Rosewall, gallant losers to American aces Tony Trabert and Vic
Seixas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do that someday,'' thought Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to do that someday,'' thought Roche.
</P>
<P>
   Now they've gone past someday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Telepathy? Coincidence? Call it whatever. John Newcombe and Tony
Roche have formed perhaps the most enduring alliance in tennis
history _ vise-tight even by the standards of the Australians, who
long have been renowned for their bonhomie.
</P>
<P>
   It's an inevitable byproduct of place, of growing up in and then
venturing forth from an isolated island nation-continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you leave Australia,'' says Newcombe, now 55, ``you don't
leave for two weeks. You leave for a long time. You become
dependent on your mates. You develop a close bond. Mateship is very
important to the Australian way of life. If someone doesn't look
after his mates, the other guys ostracize him.''
</P>
<P>
   No chance of Newcombe or Roche being drummed out of the club.
Their 35-year doubles partnership _ which continues in Grand Slam
senior events today _ produced 11 major championships and a
relationship of such fiber that their families still vacation
together.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, they fulfilled their Davis Cup dreams. With a
vengeance. Playing both singles and doubles, they helped the
vaunted Australian dynasty of a generation ago capture five
championships _ four in a row from 1964-67 and again in 1973, five
years after tennis entered the open era and the first year contract
professionals were allowed to compete for the Cup. In other words,
five straight, for all intents and purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't stop there. When the Australians visit Longwood
for a quarterfinal Davis Cup match against the United States July
16-18, Newcombe and Roche will be running the show. Together.
Continuing a precedent they established six years ago when, as
usual, they refused to separate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late 1993, Neale Fraser stepped down as the Australian Davis
Cup captain. The sport's governing body, Tennis Australia, was
unaccustomed to the hiring process, since its Davis Cup team had
been run by only two captains in the previous 50 years _ the
legendary Harry Hopman and then Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Applications were solicited. Newcombe and Roche both submitted
resumes. As a unit.
</P>
<P>
   Under their arrangement, Newcombe would be the captain. Roche
would be the coach. One problem. Tennis Australia had never had a
Davis Cup coach. Tennis Australia didn't want a Davis Cup coach.
Tennis Australia wanted the status quo _ a Davis Cup captain.
Period.
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe and Roche both were offered the job, though Newcombe
swears he can't remember who was approached first. Didn't matter.
Each told Tennis Australia he wouldn't work without the other.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis Australia now has a Davis Cup coach.
</P>
<P>
   That's Roche, a full-time employee of the organization who
travels 22 weeks a year and is responsible for the tennis tutelage.
The captain is Newcombe, who is more or less the front man,
handling the administrative details, the public and media
functions, and the actual matches in addition to assisting Roche
with the on-court work.
</P>
<P>
   It's a part-time position _ Newcombe hasn't the time to devote
exclusively to the Cup squad, given his other enterprises: a tennis
resort he owns in San Antonio, a marketing company he owns in
Australia, overseeing his personal investment portfolio, and
serving as an Australian television commentator for such events as
Wimbledon and the US and French Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the job requires two people now,'' he says. ``Tony's
total concentration is to give 100 percent to the boys and what
they need on the court. But there's 101 other things to do off the
court, and I take care of those. Plus, I'll ask Tony, `What do you
want me to do with this guy?' or `What does that guy need?' He'll
tell me what needs to be worked on, and I'll help there.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, this brain trust hasn't had the success of its
predecessors _ perhaps because Newcombe has no player in his ranks
the caliber of the young John Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His parents played tennis socially. John took it to another
level. ``I was good at all hand-eye coordination sports,'' he
recalls. ``Cricket. Rugby. Tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially tennis. From the age of 10, he was Australia's
top-ranked junior. He won convincingly at every age level. Until he
got to the 18-and-under clay final.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I played Rochey,'' he says. ``Our match was before
the national final. It took us three hours. Rochey beat me, 6-4,
14-16, 6-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's when it occurred to Newcombe that if he couldn't
beat Roche, he should join him. Actually, the choice was eventually
made for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1964 on a trip overseas, my partner, Ken Fletcher, got a
chance to play with Emmo (Roy Emerson),'' recalls Newcombe. ``The
selectors decided Tony and I should play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that, Newcombe experienced far more success in
singles than Roche _ or any other Australian of the
post-Emerson/Rod Laver era. Playing in the period that bridged the
sham of so-called amateur tennis, with its clandestine payments,
and the inclusion of legitimate professionals in Grand Slam events,
Newcombe won seven major singles titles: three Wimbledons, two US,
and two Australians. He and Roche numbered five Wimbledons among
their doubles trophies, and Newcombe earned six other Grand Slam
doubles titles with other partners; his total of 17 Grand Slam
doubles crowns remains a record.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he earned universal admiration as a man without
pretense or guile, and now he tries to impart that approach to the
players under his stewardship. At Longwood, that means Patrick
Rafter and 17-year-old rookie Lleyton Hewitt, the replacement for
injured Mark Philippoussis, in singles, and the veteran doubles duo
of Mark Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge, the Roche-Newcombe of this
era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony and I are very strong on team spirit,'' says Newcombe.
``We really believe in working together as a unit.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy was put to the ultimate test after the Davis Cup
debacle of 1995, when Australia lost to Hungary and was relegated
out of the World Group, meaning it could not compete for the Cup
the following year. ``It was a national disaster,'' says Newcombe.
And the team was under siege. Newcombe and Roche used the
opportunity to reinforce a sense of solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said to the guys, `The true mark of a champion is when you
get knocked down, can you stand up taller than before?' '' he
recalls. ``We said it was up to us to prove to people that we were
champions and we'd be at their side every step of the way. I think
that was a turning point for Australian tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in an individual context. Newcombe said the Aussies felt
a sense of achievement if one of their number gained a major
quarterfinal during the dark days. Since then, Rafter has won the
last two US Opens, was a Wimbledon semifinalist this year, and
Philippoussis reached the US final last year and had eventual
champion Pete Sampras on the ropes in the Wimbledon quarters this
month before a knee injury knocked him out of the tournament and
the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger scope, there is still a lack of fulfillment by the
Aussies. Their best Cup finish under Newcombe and Roche was the
1997 semifinals, where they were eliminated by the US. And Newcombe
believes that the loss of Philippoussis tips the balance slightly
toward the Americans at Longwood. ``Before, I'd call it 50-50,'' he
says. ``Now it's more like 55-45.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Australians fail again, Newcombe won't go into
hiding. He never has. ``The flak comes with the territory,'' he
says. ``I've never minded it. The funny thing is, if people know
it's going to get to you, they give you more. If they know it
doesn't, they leave you alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he doesn't envision being on the firing line much longer,
Cup or no Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll finish up at the end of 2000,'' says Newcombe.
``That's what Tony wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And they've always been on the same wavelength.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
