<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUBURBAN-COWBOY-HNS &LR;      07-08 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBURBAN-COWBOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE EMUS AND CATTLE ROAM, A SUBURBAN COWBOY GOES TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGSBURY, Texas _ On a recent afternoon, Bubba Jahns wandered
pastures and rural roads around here for hours, looking for a
cantankerous, retired rodeo bull that was wreaking havoc by
knocking down fences and chasing property owners.
</P>
<P>
   Jahns, driving a pickup truck and armed with a tranquilizer dart
gun, never spotted his quarry.
</P>
<P>
   It was an off day for Guadalupe County's ``contract cowboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jahns, 39, uses his truck, his horse, six dogs, plenty of rope
and the occasional tranquilizer dart in his part-time job.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban cowboy is responsible for rounding up livestock
that gets loose in this county east of San Antonio where
subdivisions and ranches exist side by side, though not always
harmoniously.
</P>
<P>
   When livestock _ be they goats, emus or bulls _ get out of their
pastures and become a traffic hazard, the county calls on Jahns to
take care of the problem. The problem can be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Guadalupe County Sheriff's Deputy Anthony
Slaughter was seriously injured when he hit a horse while driving
his patrol car. Slaughter is not expected back at work for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   Jahns earns a fee only when he catches a stray, and often the
hours are tough. And on days like Thursday, when his target gives
him the slip, Jahns does not even get paid for the mileage he
drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really need it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get plenty of business rounding up cattle for other people.
A lot of times the county calls at two in the morning and I don't
really want to go. Half the time the animal gets back into the
pasture and I can't even find it. So I get out of bed at two in the
morning, saddle my horse, drive 30 miles or so, spend an hour
looking for the darn animal, and I get nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some weeks the county never calls and other times the calls
stack up. But the average is three or four times a week, and Jahns
always loads up his horse and goes to work.
</P>
<P>
   His least favorite calls involve lassoing loose emus,
flightless, ostrich-like birds from Australia that were a huge fad
in Texas ranching during the 1980s. Then the bottom fall out of the
emu market and it became easier for owners to turn them loose
rather than feed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not really worth anything,'' Jahns said. ``What I
generally do is get them along a fence and just drive alongside
them in my truck and put a rope on them right out the window of my
pickup truck. When you get a rope on them, they really try to kick
it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Roping emus, after all, is not real cowboy work.
</P>
<P>
   When he does find a bull, the regular routine is to shoot it
with a tranquilizer, wait for it to go down, then rope it, and get
it moving into a waiting trailer with a cattle prod.
</P>
<P>
   His boss at his real job at the Seguin Cattle Co., Benno
Luensmann, doesn't seem to mind that Jahns regularly disappears for
a couple of hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good cowboy,'' Luensmann said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Jahns' six dogs that impress his boss the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll back up the trailer along a fence and those dogs will go
get the cow and put it right in the trailer. That's unbelievable,
but it works. It takes a special dog to do that. Not every dog can
be trained to do it. He trains them from the time they're pups,''
Luensmann said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
