<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-RYDER-STEWART-BOS     07-08 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-STEWART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART CHECKS OUT THE COUNTRY CLUB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ No knickers, no cap, but no mistaking the
persona, either. It was Payne Stewart playing a practice round at
The Country Club Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh off his second US Open triumph and ready to head on a golf
vacation in Ireland to prepare for next week's British Open,
Stewart squeezed a little bit of homework into his schedule. He was
answering captain Ben Crenshaw's challenge to his Ryder Cup
players: Play the golf course, study its subtleties, be prepared.
</P>
<P>
   It was a trip Stewart was anxious to make and it was in the
works even before he secured a spot on the team with his US Open
triumph at Pinehurst No. 2 June 20. Stewart has never tried to hide
his passion for the Ryder Cup, an event he played in four times _
1987, '89, '91, and '93. But he failed to make the team in 1995 and
1997 and since those years resulted in US losses, Stewart is
anxious to reverse the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special event,'' said Stewart. ``I can't feel for
anybody else. I can't get their emotions the way mine are. So
hopefully they'll see my emotions and something may rub off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Country Club, which will host the international golf
spectacle Sept. 24-26, is a course cut in the ``classical'' mold, a
type today's players play infrequently. That makes it imperative,
Crenshaw has said repeatedly, that players familiarize themselves
with the layout.
</P>
<P>
   If Stewart is any indication, there is much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one of those players who can remember every shot of
every round for years, not like a Lanny Wadkins,'' said Stewart
after his round. ``I played here in the 1988 US Open, but haven't
seen it since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I played well that year (he shot 73-73-70-67_283 and
was tied for 10th), but I didn't remember many of the holes.''
</P>
<P>
   As he toured The Country Club, Stewart took notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see what Ben was thinking about with the width of
the fairways. And they are ample. They are much wider than I
remember them being in 1988.''
</P>
<P>
   The rough will also be down from what he remembers. Those are
the good parts, said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side? ``I don't remember these greens being as small as
they are. These greens are small. I thought the greens at Hilton
Head were small, but these greens are tiny.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this aspect of The Country Club that is mentioned most
often when observers discuss the course's character. While it will
not play long, at least not for the world's finest players, hitting
those small targets will offer the most demanding challenge. And
when you miss the greens at TCC, you often are left with awkward
chips from funky lies in rough.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart discovered this in his round Wednesday, which was casual
(he was dressed in shorts and a white Ryder Cup baseball cap),
though quite solid. ``He kept hitting it in the fairway and on the
greens,'' said Toni Facella, an assistant golf professional at The
Country Club. It was her job to video the round for club archives,
but ``he didn't give me much to film because he played so well. No
bunker shots, no trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The only greens he missed (the par-4 eight and 15th) resulted in
his two bogeys. He offset that with birdies at the par-5 14th
(driver, 4-wood, two putts) and par-3 16th in an even-par round of
71.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great day today. We had fun,'' said Stewart, who
played with his longtime coach, Chuck Cook.
</P>
<P>
   And the fun, he said, will continue overseas. He flew out of
Boston Wednesday night and will be in Ireland through Sunday. There
are four days of golf planned with some pretty fair players _ Tiger
Woods, David Duval, Mark O'Meara, and Stuart Appleby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always enjoying over there the week before the British
Open,'' said Stewart. ``You get yourself on the right time zone and
get accustomed to the wind that you have to play in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a friend who hosts us and the Irish people are so
great to us. It's a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
