<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-08 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTY PLAYING INSPIRED GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of miles away, back at his home in Ireland, the phone
kept ringing and ringing. Congratulations were in order, though the
hero wasn't even in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred-thirty-two calls,'' said Christy O'Connor Jr., who
prompted the outpouring of support by winning last weekend's Senior
PGA Tour event in Columbia, Md. ``Can you believe it?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes. A figure 10 times that would be believable, too.
We are, after all, talking about one of the truly splendid
gentlemen in the world of golf, a man whose great character and
unending charm and dignity have been put to the ultimate test the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Darren, the youngest of his beloved children, was killed in a
car accident last August. That he was one of Ireland's most
promising golfers and represented another generation of this
celebrated golfing family was just a footnote to this tragic
reality: Darren O'Connor was a mere 17 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means so much to me and my family,'' O'Connor told the
crowd after his victory at Hobbit's Glen Golf Club. ``I won today
for my son. He was with me today.''
</P>
<P>
   They were going to be together last fall, before fate cruely
interferred. The man affectionately known as Junior (he is named
after his legendary uncle, Christy O'Connor Sr.) was going to turn
50 on Aug. 19 and head to the United States to pursue the Senior
PGA Tour. Darren was going to go with him and look at colleges in
hopes of gaining a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The accident changed that plan and it was six months before
O'Connor got back to golf, accepting an invitation to the PGA
Seniors' Championship in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. He wrestled with
his emotions as he sandwiched a pair of 76s around a 71 and 73 to
finish in a tie for 50th. O'Connor was disappointed in the way he
played, but his many friends and admirers were just thrilled that
he played at all.
</P>
<P>
   Brian O'Keefe is one of those friends.
</P>
<P>
   Business had taken him to Ireland many times over the past 10
years or so and one great bonus was the friendship developed with
O'Connor. No surprise then that when the PGA Seniors' Championship
got under way, O'Keefe and his wife walked all 72 holes with their
friend.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, either, that the O'Keefes had a small party at
their summer home on the Cape to watch Sunday's final round on
ESPN. It was not broadcast back to Ireland, so the phone calls went
back-and-forth with updates. ``I'll probably have a $400 bill,''
said O'Keefe, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's victory was lost in the glare of a most impressive
weekend for professional golf. There was Tiger Woods and his
magical game, flop shots and all, at the Western Open; a six-way
playoff in the LPGA Tour stop in Ohio; and a 19-year-old Spaniard,
Sergio Garcia, charging from behind with a charismatic and youthful
game that won the Irish Open.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful stories, all of them, but none more so than O'Connor's
triumph in a furnace that passed as a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It nearly killed me,'' said O'Connor of the intense heat at
Hobbit's Glen. He comes from the land of ``soft rain'' where
golfers routinely look at pins that are nearly bent in half thanks
to wind, which probably isn't even considered wind until it reaches
gale proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Was he used to such heat? ``No. God no. It was something like
112 degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a few days after the victory and O'Connor was laughing,
which is such a nice thing to hear. Another heat wave beckons, this
time in Des Moines, where the US Senior Open begins Thursday (July
8) but O'Connor has confronted far more difficult tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The three-shot lead he took into the final round at Hobbit's
Glen meant it was his event to lose. No problem with that. The best
player this year, Bruce Fleisher, was supplying even more heat. No
problem with that, either.
</P>
<P>
   But how was O'Connor to hold up when (not if) images of Darren
popped into his head?
</P>
<P>
   The answer was: Just fine. On the strength of a 65-66-67
performance, the popular Irishman had earned not only a $195,000
prize, but a one-year exemption on the Senior Tour. ``It was so
tough,'' said O'Connor. ``But it was so fantastic. It was like a
miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   When he went to Chicago Sunday night to meet his wife, Ann,
O'Connor thought he'd be the one telling her the good news. ``But
she already knew. She had called our daughter (Ann) back home. The
poor girl was back there answering all those phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann and Christy continued on to Des Moines for the Senior Open.
No surprise to his many friends, but he said ``I'd like to be out
celebrating.'' This is a man, after all, who enjoys a good
``sing-song'' and whose singing voice and ability to play the
spoons are legendary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said O'Connor, a party would be nice, but Ann would have
none of it. She reminded him that there is another golf tournament
to be played. ``I don't know how I can win two in a row, but we'll
try our best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After that, said O'Connor, ``I'm going home to get my thoughts
together and re-schedule my whole year.'' The Maryland victory will
then be celebrated in the company of his wife, daughter, son Nigel,
and many, many friends.
</P>
<P>
   Darren will be there, too. As he always will be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIDEBAR &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His victory last week at the State Farm Senior Classic assures
what was already a pretty sure thing: Christy O'Connor Jr. will be
in the field at the BankBoston Senior Classic (Aug. 20-22).
</P>
<P>
   Tracy West, tournament director, confirmed that O'Connor would
be playing at Nashawtuc CC in Concord. West is in Des Moines for
this week's US Senior Open, a trip that also yielded a commitment
from Lee Trevino. He is the latest to say yes to a tournament that
is quickly establishing itself as a strong one.
</P>
<P>
   The Senior Tour's leading money winner, Bruce Fleisher, will be
in Concord, as will two-time defending champion Hale Irwin, and
Dana Quigley of Rhode Island. Dave Stockton, Chi Chi Rodriguez, Bob
Charles, and Isao Aoki are also committed.
</P>
<P>
   All those names in addition to arguably the biggest attractions
_ Arnold Palmer and Gary Player.
</P>
<P>
   For O'Connor, the trip to Boston will feel like a homecoming as
he visits the city often and has lots of friends here. Many of his
visits to Boston involve corporate outings that raise money for
charity back in his native Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, is a rookie to the Senior tours, having turned 50 last
August. A longtime favorite in Europe, he is well remembered as the
author of a dramatic 2-iron into the 18th hole at The Belfry that
stunned Fred Couples and helped Europe to a dramatic Ryder Cup
victory.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor has been playing in Senior events in the US on
sponsors' exemptions, though his victory earns him a one-year
exemption. Still, his goal is to finish Top 31 on the money list
(he's currently 22d). He will return to Europe for the British
Seniors Open and Wentworth Senior Masters, then come back to the US
in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
