<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENICE-GONDOLAS-BOS &LR;      07-08 1532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENICE-GONDOLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONDOLIERS UNDULATE, AGITATE AS CITY EYES CALMER MOTOR CRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNE WEIL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE _ Paolo Dalla Pieta hopped across a row of slender,
bobbing black boats. His was the fifth from the dock. He stripped
off its tarp and dipped the long, single oar in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Then he stepped to the stern, planted his feet firmly, and _
churning with both hands _ glided away from the land.
</P>
<P>
   Dalla Pieta, 35, is a born gondolier. His family has been
guiding this swan of a vessel and its predecessors for four
centuries. It is in his blood.
</P>
<P>
   So naturally he gets his blood up over a problem that has dogged
the gondoliers of Venice for more than 30 years: motorboats, and
the damage they leave in their wake.
</P>
<P>
   More than air or water pollution, or even the occasional
high-speed crash, the main complaint about powerboats in Venice is
``il moto ondoso,'' or wave motion. It is blamed for eroding the
city's foundations, eating away at 14th-century palaces, and
wrecking the powerless craft that are this city's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Venice agreed to buy a new wake-flattening hull
design for its fleet of water buses, which may promise smoother
waters if it catches on. But for the 405 gondoliers, powerboats
from private launches to the public transit vessels produce daily
aggravation: A run-in with a quay chips the paint; tourists get
nervous and stay away; muscles are sprained while fighting to keep
a sliver of a boat upright.
</P>
<P>
   In one such struggle two years ago, Dalla Pieta suffered a
hernia and could not work for a month.
</P>
<P>
   The waves are especially tough on the gondolas themselves. ``If
they topple over,'' said gondola-maker Roberto Tramontin, ``they
can lose parts that are hard to replace. And when a boat smashes
into something hard, it takes 40 to 50 days to put everything
right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually a gondola will last up to 25 years,'' he added, ``but
with the punishment they take in the waters of Venice today, they
have a life span of maybe 10 to 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalla Pieta's father, Fausto, was head of a gondoliers'
cooperative when he called the watery problem to city authorities'
attention in an April 1970 letter.
</P>
<P>
   It read, in part: ``Our beautiful gondolas . . . find themselves
ever more frequently tossed about by the incessant increase in wave
motion, provoked by motorized means in ever greater numbers and
driven without conscience, without scruples, by people who could
not possibly love their city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city wrote back,'' Paulo said with a grin over a
cappuccino. ``Their response was, `Wait until after the next
elections _ then we will talk.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the elections passed, and nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did anything happen eight years later, when the gondoliers
demonstrated by hauling their boats out of the lagoon and onto St.
Mark's Square.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Paolo Dalla Pieta has joined numerous other
protests, such as the gondola blockade on the Grand Canal in August
1995. It slowed traffic on the city's main thoroughfare for about a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, gondoliers put up a 120-foot-long, floating
fence across a choppy stretch of water in an attempt to create a
breakwater. The illegal contraption worked, but the mayor had it
removed. He said that the city council would propose a similar
barrier, but months later, the agency responsible for safety in
Venice's lagoon rejected the idea because it would have meant
relocating a water-bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political will is not there to solve this problem,'' Paolo
Dalla Pieta sighed. ``It has never been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the turbulence has increased. The busy seaport has
become the city's main industry, surpassing tourism. The number of
powerboats plying the waters for public transit, to deliver goods,
and for personal use has grown dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   About 5,500 Venetians own registered motorboats. And a fleet of
150 water buses is the main public transit for Venice's 264,000
residents and 17 million annual tourists. Several-hundred more
powered vessels serve as ambulances, police vehicles, and garbage
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Venetian problem is that we have all the means of
transport of any city,'' said Deputy Mayor Michele Vianello. ``But
the impact of the transport on the city and its environment is more
dramatic because of the water. The more boats there are, the more
the water will be tossed, and the more damage will be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Vianello ticked off a list of proposals to calm the waves that
had been rejected due to cost or for other reasons. He also listed
some of the 21 local, regional, and national agencies that have a
say _ and a veto _ on any issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been our experience through the years that once in a
while someone proposes to us the `solution,' '' he added. ``Then
`the solution,' shall we say, encounters reality.''
</P>
<P>
   One program, though, seems to be going full steam ahead:
replacing part of the municipal fleet with ``wave-eating'' boats. A
prototype, a sort of catamaran, has been tested. By January, local
boat yards may be making them by the dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Seen from the front, the special hull looks like two parallel
tunnels. These tunnels reduce the water resistance, creating a
smaller wave off the bow.
</P>
<P>
   The tunnels also lessen turbulence under the boat, further
diminishing drag. Propellers are mounted in the middle, rather than
on the stern. The resulting wake is smaller and less churned-up
than that of conventional craft.
</P>
<P>
   A shipping magnate and former US deputy secretary of state,
Charles W. Robinson, who owns a home in Venice, designed the hull
and called it ``Mangia Onda'' _ wave eater in English, except that
someone had copyrighted that name before Robinson got his idea.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Santa Fe, N.M., Robinson said he
paid the development costs for the craft himself. On July 2, he
signed a $700,000 contract with the Venetian transit system giving
it the right to use his hull design. Officials plan to use it first
for a new fleet of boats that will carry 150 passengers each.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who divides his time between Santa Fe and Venice,
knows there is still a sales job to be done. Gondoliers, water-taxi
operators, and boat builders are all skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is sensitive to Venetian sensibilities, but has ``not
been handicapped by experience or by tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Alessandro Cassone, in charge of project development at the
Venice Transport Authority, is enthusiastic. ``Chuck Robinson is a
real inhabitant of Venice,'' he said. ``He has a home here in
Venice. And Venice is not only for Venetian and Italian persons.
Venice is the patrimony of all the world, and Mr. Robinson has the
right solution.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giorgio Piva, president of Venice's largest cooperative of
powered water taxis, is not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Mangia Onda' is not right for this city,'' he said from
the pilot's seat of a lacquered craft with a high-powered engine at
the back. ``We in Venice have been building boats for hundreds of
years. We know how to construct boats. We do not need new ones from
the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Piva similarly dismissed other plans to reduce wave motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always waves,'' he said. ``Bad weather also brings
waves. Why try to stop them?''
</P>
<P>
   As she watched a baby-blue patrol boat trail a water taxi like a
shark, Gabriella Cigogne, 62, whose family has lived near the
Renaissance-era Rialto Bridge since the early 1800s, expressed
little faith in the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are doing their best, poor things,'' she shrugged. ``We
should not expect too much of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venice was born for traveling by gondola. Sadly, the modern
era is taking that away from us. The wave motion is a dolorous note
for our city.''
</P>
<P>
   If the gondolas are to fall victim to powerboat wakes, despite
such innovations as the Mangia Onda, it won't be because no one
tried to save them.
</P>
<P>
   A city agency, the Institute for the Conservation of the Gondola
and the Tutelage of the Gondolier, mediates between gondoliers and
the authorities, intervenes in disputes over right of way, and
promotes the gondola as a symbol of Venice.
</P>
<P>
   But its president, Franco Vianello Moro, said gondoliers are
engaged in a ``quixotic battle,'' and noted that many of them own
powerboats themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And their motivation for preserving the classic vessels in this
tourist mecca, he said, has more to do with ``an occasion for good
earnings than an occasion for taking part in the city's culture and
tradition. Still, some of them have a passion for it because, in
their personal culture, they have the history of the gondola.''
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Dalla Pieta is clearly one of those. But lately, he said,
even the call of the blood has not been enough to rouse his
colleagues to anger over Venice's troubled waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become tired,'' he sighed, gazing across a row of
gently rocking black boats with bows tethered to the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier this year, a few of the gondoliers asked me to
organize a protest. I told them there was no point. They will not
stick together in a fight. And out of one hundred rabbits, you
cannot make a horse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
