<HEADER>
A3087 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-TROOPS-BOS &LR;      07-08 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAITI STILL IN CHAOS, 5 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ When bandits attacked his wife outside a
beauty salon and made off with the family's Nissan, Richard
Widmaier did what any citizen might be expected to do: He called
the police.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, Widmaier spotted the car and summoned
authorities again. Instead of returning the stolen property, police
demanded he show papers proving he was the car's owner. It was only
after pleading with the precinct chief that Widmaier, the owner of
one of the country's largest radio networks, had the keys thrown at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got played around,'' Widmaier recalled. ``But I refused to
give in.''
</P>
<P>
   Widmaier's experience with crime in Haiti is mild compared to
other recent episodes.
</P>
<P>
   In January, President Rene Preval's sister was shot at after he
dissolved the parliament. Last month, 11 people were gunned
execution-style by police during a raid in a slum. Three weeks ago,
a US military vehicle was pelted by rocks when it stalled on a
Port-au-Prince street.
</P>
<P>
   The growing sense of unease and insecurity that now shrouds this
small Caribbean nation is once again feeding doubts about Haiti's
ability to build a stable democracy after decades of authoritarian
rule.
</P>
<P>
   And as the United States and its allies begin a new peacekeeping
chapter in Kosovo, many of those who have lived through the
5-year-old, US-led efforts in Haiti say that little, if anything,
has improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Americans first came, they were applauded and cheered
here, just like in Kosovo,'' Prime Minister Jacques-Edouard Alexis
said in an interview. ``But they have to be careful to deliver what
they promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the 20,000 troops that landed on Haiti's shores in
September 1994 quickly reinstated the country's democratically
elected president, Jean-Bertrand Aristide, and disbanded the ruling
military group that ousted him three years earlier, that ``was only
part of the problem,'' Alexis added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were entire questions of economic and social development
that have never been properly taken into account by these
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the US troops withdrew from Haiti three years ago,
handing over peacekeeping and rebuilding work to a smaller United
Nations force. But the country's path to prosperity seems as broken
and treacherous as the pothole-scarred streets that snake their way
around the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The government here has been without a budget for two years
because of ongoing disputes between the parliament and the Preval
administration. Hundreds of millions of dollars in international
aid has not been delivered because stubborn political factions will
not stop squabbling. And the country still does not have a
functioning parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politicians don't see themselves as serving the general
population and they don't believe in sharing power,'' said one
European diplomat. ``After a while the people will begin to wonder
what the whole point of this thing called democracy is.''
</P>
<P>
   That frustration is already beginning to show. Street protests,
some of them involving rock-throwing demonstrators, have grown both
in size and frequency over the past three months, against the
government's gridlock and the worsening economic plight.
</P>
<P>
   Several international observers and Preval government officials
privately accuse Aristide loyalists of fomenting the street
disruptions to set the stage for the former president's messianic
return to office in the next elections. Already, scores of walls
throughout the capital have Aristide's nickname _ ``Titid 2001'' _
scribbled on them.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide did not respond to requests for interviews. But Yvon
Neptune, a spokesman and top-ranking official of the Family Lavalas
political coalition headed by Aristide denied involvement in the
uprisings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have already stated that they are waiting for''
Aristide ``to return,'' Neptune said during an interview at the
offices of Aristide's Foundation for Democracy. ``We have no need
to invent some scenario for his return to office.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the disappointed voices of those discouraged by Haiti's
current plight echo throughout this mountainous nation of 8 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, tourists came to Haiti and they bought many
things,'' said Felder Revolis, 46, who once sold hand-woven baskets
but now practices a more practical but less lucrative trade
peddling mangoes from a wooden stand in downtown Port-au-Prince.
``I'm not wishing for the old days of dictators, but there is so
much chaos today.''
</P>
<P>
   To help end the political paralysis, Alexis pledged that new
parliamentary elections will be held in November and December. ``We
all agree that the way to get things back on track is to have
elections,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without political stability, Haiti, already the poorest country
in the hemisphere with an annual per capita income of $250, risks
tumbling deeper into poverty, economists say.
</P>
<P>
   To help keep some basic services running, the government has
increased taxes, mostly on manufacturing businesses, where there
has been slight growth. The country also relies heavily on
approximately $800 million residents receive every year in
remittances from Haitian immigrants who live abroad, mostly in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another more troubling source of wealth into the country has
come from the growing drug trade, officials said. Located on the
western end of the island of Hispaniola due north from Colombia,
Haiti's sparsely populated southern coast has become a popular
drop-off point for South American cartels.
</P>
<P>
   US and Haitian authorities now say that as much as 20 percent of
the cocaine destined for the United States passes through Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fractiousness of the political atmosphere has helped
create a climate where poor people are willing to take big risks,''
said one high-ranking US official in Haiti who requested anonymity.
``And drugs has become one of the biggest attractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite unemployment levels that exceed 60 percent and an even
higher illiteracy rate, there are signs everywhere of new,
unexplained wealth.
</P>
<P>
   On the northern edge of Port-au-Prince, clusters of bright pink
and yellow Miami-style homes have sprouted. Shiny sport utility
vehicles, many of them bearing the names of car dealers in Florida,
zip along the capital's narrow, hilly streets alongside local
vehicles that sputter and belch black clouds of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The growing drug trade has also stretched the resources and
ethics of Haiti's young national police force.
</P>
<P>
   The force was formed in 1995 after the country's military was
disbanded and trained by a multinational UN group. Many of the
6,000 officers have found themselves either the victims of Haiti's
growing crime wave or accused of adding to it. Over the last three
years, 56 officers have been jailed for drug corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an inexperienced police force and we're desperately
short of resources, so sometimes an agent will seize other
opportunities,'' said Pierre Denize, Haiti's National Police chief.
``This is a country where political gridlock was usually ended by
the military or public force. This time it will have to be solved
by the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as the insecurity grows, many of the international
groups whose presence here over the past five years has provided at
least a symbolic sense of safety for many Haitians are preparing to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Both the UN Observer's office and the police-training group are
scheduled to close their operations at the end of November. The
commander of the US military's Southern Command, General Charles E.
Wilhelm, told Congress in February that he would like to pull out
the remaining 500 troops, who mostly provide medical and
humanitarian assistance, out of concern for their safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more intolerance and more threats,'' said Colin
Granderson, chief of the UN Civilian Mission in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't say that any one group has been targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to compare the task ahead for international workers
in Kosovo with the lessons learned in Haiti, Granderson said, ``The
transition to democracy is a long, slow and often painful process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to build institutions, it can't happen
overnight. It requires a long-term commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
