   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Leskovac) _ Voices of discontent: Leskovac, a
hotbed of anti-Milosevic sentiment, sent 25,000 reservists to
Kosovo. They're back now, furious with the way the government has
treated them (little pay) and their families (little food). By
Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RALLIES (Prokuplje) _ Anti- and pro-Milosevic rallies are
scheduled for tonight in this Serbian city. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ The vice chairman of the Joint
Chiefs gives a report on the Kosovo bombing campaign. By Steven Lee
Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ A news analysis: The Congo
and Sierra Leone peace plans raise questions along with hopes. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-BARAK (Jerusalem) _ While he pursues lofty goals of
peace, Edhud Barak, the new prime minister, is still weighed down
by political maneuvering. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-TRUCKERS (Buenos Aires) _ Truckers end their strike
after Congress delays the disputed tax. The end comes after
President Menem declares strike illegal and authorizes military to
deliver food. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-KOREA (Tokyo) _ Two members of the Japanese parliament
charged Thursday that key elements of North Korea's missile program
come from Japan, and they called for tighter export restrictions.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ACCESS (Washington) _ The Commerce Department releases
an extensive study on access to the Internet, looking at the gaps
in access to technology and information. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-MONEY (Washington) _ It's not just George Bush, but
everybody who is raising a ton of campaign money. There's more of
it around than anyone can remember. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton winds up his
poverty tour with a visit to a youth training academy in Los
Angeles. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DRUDGE-ABC (Undated) _ ABC Radio, over objections from the ABC
News president, has hired Matt Drudge, operator of the Internet's
Drudge Report. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   AIRBUS-OUTLOOK (Toulouse, France) _ Airbus Industrie has never
been busier. It now has models that compete with Boeing in every
category except the giant 747 and has recently snagged some
previously all-Boeing customers, such as British Airways. But
Airbus's three-year-old effort to transform itself from a
four-nation consortium into a conventional corporation has stalled,
sowing doubts that it will ever happen. Airbus executives and
industry analysts see the move as a crucial step if Airbus is going
to continue to compete effectively with Boeing, which is struggling
to emerge from an embarrassing production foul-up two years ago. By
Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
