<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-VALUES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE US, IMMIGRANTS SEE A TEST OF VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Like millions before her, Wenjie Qin came to America
to taste the fruits of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Chinese immigrant and her husband, Henry, have
built a new life in Brighton. They live in a modest two-bedroom
condominium _ a palace by the standards of their hometown in Anhui
province. Doctorate in education in hand, she revels in her
independence, a feeling she never knew in China, where prudence
dictated self-censorship and conformity.
</P>
<P>
   Qin cherishes this freedom. It's why she and her family watch US
history videos on Independence Day and why in early July they
always take a bus trip to explore the country _ this year
Tennessee. It's why a small US flag sits on a pedestal beside the
TV. ``That,'' says Qin who came to America shortly after the 1989
Tiananmen crackdown, ``is why we stay here: the freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Qin watches her 11-year-old sons, Yelun and Yening,
head off to school in their Lee jeans and Nikes (they will only
wear Nikes), she worries they are taking the freedom of America in
directions that she never wanted or anticipated. They have embraced
a different America, that of Burger King, Star Wars, and Michael
Jordan. They pump their fists in the air at the very mention of his
name.
</P>
<P>
   The story of two generations of immigrant families is a
bittersweet tale of changing values and expectations. It is also
the story of the United States and what it means to be an American
living on the edge of the millennium. And it is an old story.
</P>
<P>
   It was John Adams, America's second president, who wrote in 1780
that he studied war and politics so that his sons could study
mathematics and philosophy, so their children might study
``painting, poetry, music . . . tapestry and porcelain.''
</P>
<P>
   The new immigrants, like the waves of Irish, Italians, and Balts
who preceded them, have fled famine, war, tyranny or economic
hardship to sell their labor on the open market. For many of the
families, the new life has been characterized by toil.
</P>
<P>
   In her native land, Honduras, Leslie Garo was a teacher; her
husband was an accountant for a luxury resort. In the United
States, they've worked as personal care assistants, emptying
bedpans and bathing the sick, so their three children might one day
go to college. A colleague from her old school wrote her in Boston
and asked how someone with her education could be cleaning
Americans' behinds. The remark still stings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a struggle,'' said Garo, whose job now is providing
AIDS education for a community service agency. ``We're young _ not
even halfway down our road _ but we're already tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The new immigrants love America's freedom, but their patriotism
for their homelands remains. Victims of the Argentine junta's
atrocities in the 1970s can still be moved to tears by talk of the
country's claim to the Falklands. You can talk to Chinese
immigrants who will be sharply critical of their government's human
rights record, but who still insist that China must never part with
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   And many still pine for their native lands. Garo, who says she
will return to Honduras the very day her youngest child enters
college, dreams of the cocoanut and mango trees in her yard.
</P>
<P>
   Abebe Woldu, an Eritrean who owns Asmara Restaurant in
Cambridge, goes home once a year and says he looks forward to the
day when he can retire to Eritrea. ``If you don't have money, you
are nothing'' in the United States, Woldu said. ``Over there, if
you are my friend, I'm your friend forever. If you are rich and
become poor, I will support you until you die.''
</P>
<P>
   The children of immigrants have complicated senses of their
identities. Marina Belozerskaya of Cambridge is deeply grateful to
her mother and father for leaving the Soviet Union. When
Belozerskaya was 13, they left because of anti-Semitism. At the
same time, after nearly two decades in this country, Belozerskaya
still doesn't feel like an American.
</P>
<P>
   When she travels in Europe she tells people she is a Russian.
``I feel that my home is where I am and what I create around myself
rather than a particular country,'' said Belozerskaya, a Bunting
Fellow at Harvard University. ``I have a sense of being a turtle
with a home on my back.''
</P>
<P>
   However, her younger sister Eugenia, 17, was born in the United
States, and, to her parents' utter bewilderment, has developed
American sensibilities. Her parents, who converse in Russian
(except when they lecture Eugenia) are enthusiastic readers and
wish she would spend more time reading the Russian classics. But to
Eugenia, freedom means watching ``Dawson's Creek.'' It means
shopping trips to the Gap, ``chilling'' with friends and body
piercing _ ears, nose and tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I was put in the wrong family,'' Eugenia says. ``I
belong in an American family, but I am stuck in a Russian family.
Though I do love them to death.''
</P>
<P>
   At Wenjie Qin's house on a recent weekday evening, the air was
redolent with the smell of frying bok choy and duck. Qin's husband,
Henry, served while Qin sat at the table. The two boys, Qin noted
proudly, helped with the cooking and the laundry. In the old days,
back in China, Henry never would have done the dishes. But in
America, where he is a BMW salesman, she has persuaded him to pull
his weight around the house. ``I became stronger in this country,''
she said. ``Women have more power here.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she noted with dismay that her children were
also staging a quiet revolution for more freedom and rights. ``They
want to be equal,'' she said. She sighed. ``They are very
Americanized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
