<SLUG> BC-HAITI-HELP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOME QUARTERS, US MILITARY ROLE IS APPRECIATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ In the heart of one of the poorest slums
in the poorest country in the Western hemisphere, the people gather
at dawn on the days they know the US troops are coming to run their
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the medical personnel arrive, usually by 1 p.m.,
hundreds of residents of the Cite Soleil neighborhood and other
areas of Port-au-Prince have come with ailments that run from
tuberculosis to a gangrene-infected leg that requires immediate
amputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely a challenge, because this is a country that
clearly needs a lot of help,'' said Captain Adam Robinson, who last
month was overseeing an army group of doctors, nurses and
assistants based in Jacksonville, Fla. ``But the Haitians accept
us. Sometimes when we arrive, there are 1,000 people waiting for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Three times a week, the remaining US troops here run this clinic
in the dusty courtyard of a school run by the Brothers of Charity
in this slum of cramped, tin-roofed shacks where mountains of trash
sit next to streams that run with sewage and seawater.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner of the clinic, there is a primary care cluster to
diagnose patients. In another, there is a minor surgery section.
And a third corner holds the dental area.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic is part of the overall humanitarian assistance
program run by the US military, but now seems to be in jeopardy.
Once a 20,000-member strong force that in 1994 ran the military
junta out and reinstated Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the democratically
elected president, the US presence now numbers about 500 soldiers
who provide mostly medical assistance and build schools and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago during testimony before a congressional
subcommittee, General Charles E. Wilhelm, the commander of US
forces in Latin America and the Caribbean, recommended that the
United States end its five-year military presence in Haiti, arguing
that the remaining troops in Haiti are in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the House of Representatives voted to stop funding
the $22 million-a-year operation in December. But some
representatives say in a country that needs still needs so much
help, pulling out the troops would be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last signal that we should be sending to a country
that is trying so hard to develop its own democracy,'' said
Representative William Delahunt, of Quincy, who visited Haiti last
month with two Florida congressmen. They are asking the House to
rethink their vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``During such a tenuous time, there ought to be more of an
international presence in Haiti, not less, because more instability
could result in more refugees in boats for the US,'' he added in a
phone interview from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian officials insist that no international workers have been
targeted by Haiti's growing wave of violence, which has come amid
continued bickering between the country's political parties and a
worsening economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, a US military vehicle was pelted with rocks
by residents after it stalled on a street near the makeshift base
it operates in an waterfront industrial park. No serious injuries
were reported, but soldiers now are required to wear flak jackets
and carry weapons whenever they leave the compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a wakeup call for us that not everybody here
considers us friends,'' said Colonel Walton Walker, the commander
in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   But those at the clinic said its loss would only make a bad
situation worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at us, our own government doesn't take care of us like
these soldiers do,'' said Jacque Maraud, 42, whose wife, two sons
and three daughters have all been treated at one time or another at
the clinic. ``Unfortunately, we cannot pay. All we can do is say,
`Thank you very much.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
