<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIZZLY-ARMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GRIZZLY OBSESSION SUITS HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH BAY, Ontario _ Lost cause just isn't a concept to give
pause to Troy Hurtubise. The 34-year-old former scrap metal dealer
is a natural-born dreamer of big dreams.
</P>
<P>
   He quit school to become a modern-day mountain man. And in the
mountains, he found his fate when a grizzly bear charged. Or ambled
over. Versions vary.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, since then, Hurtubise has chased a vision of the day
when bear researchers, as he considers himself, can clump through
the grizzly-haunted wilds of the West in perfect safety, protected
from fang and claw _ indeed, protected from anything short of
nuclear blast _ in his soon-to-be-patented Ursus Mark VII
anti-grizzly bear suit.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the Genesis model, or ``G-Man,'' as he calls it.
The one with thermal night vision, a bite-meter on the arm to
measure the power of the grizzly's chomp and even a black box to
record the researcher's final shrieked ``field notes'' in the
unhappy event of a systems failure during an attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to get down with grizzlies, you've got to have
gear you can count on,'' says Hurtubise, a buckskin-clad inventor
of the old school _ the school whose motto might be ``perseverance,
improvisation, duct tape.'' He used nearly 7,000 feet of the stuff
on the last prototype suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you want to cover every possibility, even the possibilities
you don't want to think about,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For 13 years now, Hurtubise has endured ridicule, rejection,
financial ruin and domestic disharmony as the result of his
obsessive quest to build the world's first effective anti-grizzly
armor.
</P>
<P>
   He's also routinely risked his life testing the suit, although
very little of the risk has come from actual bears. But more on
that later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective of the suit is to achieve the protective
capability to conduct close-quarter research on the world's most
dangerous land mammal,'' he says. ``But the G-Man also has
applicability for bomb disposal, firefighting, UN peacekeeping,
police work and professional sports.''
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Hurtubise has been mocked by Harvard, scorned
by serious investors, and _ perhaps the unkindest cut _ made the
subject of a National Film Board of Canada documentary movie
portraying him as a Quixotic nutcase.
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, he's also become a sort of northlands folk
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something very Canadian about Troy and his suit, this
attempt to keep savage nature at bay,'' said Peter Lynch, director
of the quirky 1996 film, ``Project Grizzly,'' which Hollywood's
Quentin Tarantino hailed as one of the finest documentaries ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtubise himself has mixed feelings about the flick, which has
gained something of a cult following, especially in Europe and
Japan. On the plus side, it brought attention to his life's work.
On the negative side, it strongly suggested that his life's work is
lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science-wise, the film is garbage,'' he said. ``I mean you
come away thinking, `Here's this crazy guy, and he's kind of
pathetic.' But what gets left out is the science of what I'm trying
to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there have been six more or less functional prototypes
of the bear suit, and Hurtubise is now working on the most advanced
design, the Ursus Mark VII Genesis, or G-Man.
</P>
<P>
   The particulars of the latest model are shrouded in secrecy
since he can't afford the costs of patenting a design that's ``10
years ahead of its time,'' he says. Having gone through more than
$100,000 of his own money _ not to mention watching his scrap metal
yard go bust while his wife, Lori, very nearly took that last walk
out the door with their 7-year-old son, Brett _ Hurtubise is
desperate for financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has good saleability, but I'm going to need $1.2
million to get it off the ground,'' he says, stressing: ``Make sure
you say $1.2 million Canadian,'' or just a bit more than $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to an article in New Scientist, a British publication,
the contrivance is made mostly of Boralyn E5 _ a lightweight metal
composite produced by California's Alyn Corp. _ with a
``honeycomb'' shock-absorbing system packed between the
endoskeleton and exoskeleton. Hardly any duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suit makes Robocop look like the Tin Man in `The Wizard
of Oz,' '' Hurtubise says. ``With the G-Man, you can tap dance in a
minefield. You can take a dynamite blast. You can take AK-47 rounds
all day. You can walk through 4,000-degree Fahrenheit heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking one tough suit.''
</P>
<P>
   The G-Man's predecessor, the Mark VI, came to a sad end, seized
by creditors _ although they were forgiving enough to let Hurtubise
borrow it for a trip last fall to Harvard, where he accepted an
``Ig-Nobel'' award in the field of safety engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The annual awards are tongue-in-cheek Nobel opposites, bestowed
for ``research that cannot or should not be replicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtubise stole the show, happy to endure an evening of jibes,
jabs and guffaws from university slickers for the chance to stand
behind an honest-to-God Harvard lectern and speak passionately _ if
somewhat unintelligibly, given his strong up-north-Canada accent _
about the Genesis suit and its endless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Possibilities such as live volcano exploration. Or riot control.
</P>
<P>
   Even cynical souls were charmed by his earnestness.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, an anti-grizzly suit may not be what the world is waiting
for, but there really is something wonderful about Troy and his
work,'' said Marc Abrahams, editor of Annals of Improbable
Research, the Cambridge-based journal that chooses the Ig-Nobel
winners. ``He's a classic inventor, just like Edison and a lot of
others who've been labeled crackpots.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurtubise said: ``Sure, the award was a set-up: Let's all hoot
at the bear suit guy. But, face it, for a researcher from North
Bay, Ontario, getting invited to Harvard for any damn reason is a
real breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps especially so for a 9th grade dropout who seemed
destined for a drifter's aimless life until one hot day in August
1984.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtubise, age 19, was panning for gold on Humidity Creek,
British Columbia. Then, pounding down through a mountain meadow,
came an enormous speciman of Ursus arctos horribilis, the
``horrible bear,'' or grizzly.
</P>
<P>
   The bear knocked Hurtubise to the ground with a snout-shove to
the chest. Then padded off.
</P>
<P>
   It was vaguely anti-climactic. Not getting torn apart or
gobbled. But a great fascination was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me a sense of mission. I wanted to study these
awe-inspiring animals at close quarters,'' says Hurtubise.
``Trouble is, I realized right away, if you hang out too close to
grizzlies, you can get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   He went back to class, got that high school diploma. He
completed courses in ``forest recreation technology'' at Ontario's
Sir Sanford Fleming College.
</P>
<P>
   And he started working on the Ursus Mark I, the first of the
bear suits.
</P>
<P>
   Field tests conducted by Hurtubise swiftly became legend.
</P>
<P>
   To test the awful forces of a bear mauling, for example, he'd
enlist a few local biker types, stoke their empirical instincts
with beer, provide blunt instruments _ planks, baseball bats, axe
handles _ clamber inside the anti-bear armor as their boisterous
spirits rose. Then he would give his colleagues in science the
thumbs up. Or chainmail mitts up. And let them rip.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe tests couldn't be as carefully calibrated as in one of
those fancypants labs run by grant-happy geniuses at NASA or MIT or
wherever.
</P>
<P>
   But Troy and his ``Project Grizzly'' team of brothers, uncles,
pals and assorted hangers-on got the job done, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   And give the guy credit, he never used stand-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, in the pursuit of lighter, more rugged and more
flexible anti-bear suits, Hurtubise has been head-whacked by logs
swung from ropes, withstood pointblank blasts from a 12-gauge
shotgun, fallen intentionally off the 150-foot Niagra Escarpment
and hacked with chainsaws.
</P>
<P>
   Also: bounced off the mattress-wrapped bumper of a pickup truck
traveling at 25 miles per hour. Also: run over by the same pickup
18 times.
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasizes that the armored suit is just a means to an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I want to be studying bears at close quarters, I
want to work among bears the way Jacques Cousteau worked among
creatures of the deep,'' he says, naming one of his great heros.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtubise's particular obsession is to film a live grizzly bear
birth, no easy undertaking given that bear moms are proverbially
defensive of their cubs, and would presumablytake unkindly to
strangers crawling into the den in the last moments of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   On the commercial front, he's had tentative expressions of
interest in the suit from fire departments in the United States,
Germany and Japan. Then there was that lady who called from the UN.
But she never called back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Troy Hurtubise has heard the laughter, and it stings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen years is a long time to carry a dream. I've been
discouraged at times,'' he acknowledges with a sigh. ``You'd like
your work to be taken seriously, you'd like to win respect as a
scientist or at least a technologist _ not some crazy person who
wants to wrestle bears.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a long pause. Another sigh. But when he speaks again,
his voice has regained its bravado.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm on to something grand here, something that goes way
beyond grizzlies,'' he says. ``Maybe they'll remember my name 100
years from now, maybe not. All I know is I'm never giving up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
