<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD POLISH GAVE PANELING AN ODOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wood paneling has a peculiar odor after I applied some
Olde English polish. I tried straight vinegar and the odor got
worse. I washed with detergent but it didn't help much. How can I
reduce that odor?
</P>
<P>
   A. J., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Use lots and lots of ventilation; get the air really moving
through the room. Try paint thinner to remove that polish, which I
feel strongly should not be used on paneling. And that applies to
all polishes. Several applications of paint thinner, with vigorous
rubbing may be necessary. If that doesn't work, make a strong
solution of baking soda and water, and wash the paneling with that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a lot of double-hung wooden windows that I would like
to keep. Where can I find someone who will repair and reglaze them?
Would I have to take the windows to the repairer, or would he fix
them while they are on the house?
</P>
<P>
   HAIG AVEDISIAN, Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the Yellow Pages under ``Windows _ Repairing.'' Whether
he does the work in situ (at the house) or wants them in his
workshop is up to him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My Victorian house needs paint. I was looking at a Dutch (not
Dutch Boy) paint called Schroeder. It is an alkyd (oil) paint that
costs $130 a gallon and is warranted for 20 and 30 years. The
manufacturer says it is self-priming and breathable. Is it worth
that much?
</P>
<P>
   J.C., Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If it does what it promises, it is worth $130 a gallon, and
therefore worth buying. But those promises (20 and 30 years?) sound
too good to be true. Most paints fail because of moisture behind
the clapboards or shingles. You could try the paint in one area, or
even on one wall. If it passes muster for five years or more, then
you can be safe in doing the rest of the house. If your problem is
moisture, this paint might work because of its claim to be
breathable (allowing water vapor to pass through it). But the
handyman has heard too many horror stories of failing paint because
of moisture to make him a believer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My new deck is made of pressure-treated lumber. The people at
Hingham Lumber told me not to use solid acrylic on the floorboards.
The people at Home Depot suggested Behr vinyl-acrylic solid stain
for the floor, adding that it will last 10 years. Who am I to
believe, and what should I use?
</P>
<P>
   LAURIE DIODATI, Hull, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Who to believe is a good question that the handyman is
reluctant to answer. So let's evade the question and suggest this:
Never use a solid stain or paint on a deck floor; anything that
forms a film can peel, sooner or later; if it does not form a film,
it is too tender for foot traffic. Something that is claimed to
last 10 years on an outdoor deck floor is too good to be true. If
you want a color on the floor, use a semitransparent house stain.
Colors are limited with semitransparent stain, but the good thing
about it is that it has a 95 percent chance of not peeling, only
one coat is needed, and it should last three to five years. As it
begins to wear or fade, apply another single coat. In fact, I think
such a semitransparent stain is good for the entire deck: railings,
framework, and all.
</P>
<P>
   While semitransparent house stains are not exactly designed for
deck floorboards, they do perform well on them. A semitransparent
deck stain will also work, but the main characteristic of any such
stain _ house or deck _ is that it is semitransparent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a ladybug house at the Mill Stores. How can I use
it?
</P>
<P>
   MAUREEN O'CONNELL, Kingston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It seems to me that the store could tell you, or there should
be instructions as to where to put it and how. At any rate, you can
hang it almost anywhere in the yard, but generally close to shrubs
and bushes. Hang it above head height and see what happens. If you
get no tenants, you must have done something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My four-family was rehabbed in 1983. The new kitchen cabinets
have round hinges that are set into the back of the door and into
the jamb, but there is nothing showing on the outside. I need some
more of those hinges as replacements. Where can I find them?
</P>
<P>
   KEN LaBRICQUE, Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those hinges sound like Blum hinges, the European invention
that is completely invisible from the outside and allows many ways
to mount a door. Try the Woodworker's Catalog, which carries two
pages of Blums and a page of other concealed hinges; telephone
800-279-4441.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
