<HEADLINE>
PACKING UP THE HISTORY THAT MOVES US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've been moving. At one point last week, as the Worst Movers
in the World (name supplied on request) threw yet another gross or
so of boxes into their trucks, I actually found myself envying
people who lose all their belongings in a natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   I wished for a small, selective tornado that would rip through
the neighborhood, sparing everybody and everything except all our
carefully packed stuff, so I would never have to see it or think
about it ever again. Where did all this rubbish come from? These
books? These dishes? And how many changes of underwear does one
woman really need?
</P>
<P>
   I asked myself similar questions last year, when we moved my
mother into an apartment, after some drunken fool drove his
Cadillac through her living room. My mother was shocked, but
unhurt. The worst was over, or so I thought. Then we started
cleaning out her house.
</P>
<P>
   There was her Army nurse's uniform from WWII, her tax returns
dating back to 1953, a trove of painting supplies from her
watercolor period, her college biology textbooks, three bureau
drawers of tissue-wrapped underthings that appeared to date back to
the early 1950s. My mother grew up during the Depression; she has
the pack rat instinct so common in her generation. That's her
excuse for hoarding unnecessary stuff. What's mine?
</P>
<P>
   A week before we moved, my husband and I took my mother on a
trip to Nova Scotia, where she was born, a place she last saw 77
years ago, when she was 7. It was a wonderful trip. I've seldom
seen my mother so happy. She was a little dismayed, though, to find
a highway running through the family farm. There were no buildings
to remind her of her childhood; the fields were overgrown with
trees. But the stream that powered her grandfather's grist mill is
still there, running down from a spring on Skye Mountain, the water
so clear and fresh that local people stop to fill bottles to take
home.
</P>
<P>
   We asked the postmistress in the nearby town, Whycocomagh, where
we could find the old cemetery. She didn't know, but she called the
former postmistress who, the incumbent said, knew everybody and
everything. And so she did.
</P>
<P>
   Was my mother a Campbell from the west or the east side of Skye
Mountain? the former postmistress asked. She directed us to the
cemetery, on a dirt road, about a quarter of a mile up the
mountain. We found the family plot in a little grove of linden
trees. My mother moved slowly from stone to stone, her face alight.
There they were. Her grandparents, Donald and Maggie Belle. Aunt
Margaret and Aunt Minnie and Uncle George and all the others.
</P>
<P>
   The people who settled that part of Cape Breton were highland
Scots, some immigrants by choice, many driven off by English
landlords. I looked around at the gravestones, at all those
Campbells and MacDonalds and MacKenzies and Stewarts and Fergusons
and MacKinnons and wondered what everyone must wonder about all our
immigrant forebears: How did they do it? Where did they get the
strength? It's humbling to think how tough they were, how far they
came, how relatively little they possessed.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about them Tuesday, as I sifted through the
post-moving day mess, trying to decide what to keep and what to
toss. I wondered how many changes of underwear my
great-great-grandmother carried with her to Canada. I thought about
how many I'd carried from Cambridge to Arlington. I remembered the
expression on my mother's face as she studied her grandparents'
gravestone and reminded myself that the most valuable things can't
be packed up in boxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
