<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-08 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR MOM AT THE MALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All my life I've had a shopping compulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not quite correct. It's been more of a browsing
compulsion, an ongoing desire to examine the merchandise in any
store I pass. Sometimes I make expensive purchases. Mostly, I come
home with little things, like candles or underwear. I'm not judging
whether this is good or bad. What has been disturbing about it is
the feeling that it's not entirely within my conscious control.
</P>
<P>
   I understand why I do this. My mother rarely gave compliments,
and although I knew she was proud of my swimming medals and pleased
with my good grades, I had proof of my success in those areas
already. As an adolescent, what I wanted to hear, because it was
what I doubted, was whether I was pretty enough to be loved, and
the only time my mother ever praised how I looked was when we went
shopping together.
</P>
<P>
   My mother, you have to understand, weighed 180 pounds. As a
teenager, my measurements were 36-26-36, just right according to
1950 standards. It can't have been easy for my mother to watch me
twirling in the triple mirrors of the department store, but she'd
say things like, ``I can't believe your waist is that tiny,'' or
``Linda, you look like a dream in that dress.''
</P>
<P>
   I soaked up every word.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the family was in agreement that my cousin Margie
was the pretty one while I had to settle for being the smart one,
but here was my mother, delighted by how I looked. ``That's
stunning on you,'' she'd say, and my heart would rise up with hope
that Prince Charming himself would be bowled over when I walked
into the room.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, whenever I felt depressed, at loose ends,
unappreciated, bored or restless, I felt an intense pressure to
escape those feelings by going shopping. As I went through racks
and tried on outfits, I had the sense that my mother was somehow
present, murmuring, ``lovely color on you,'' or ``so flattering,''
or ``you look lovely.'' When I left the store, with or without
packages in hand, all the magic vanished and I'd be standing alone
in a parking lot, right back where I'd started. I knew that was how
the process always ended and yet, although over the years the
pressure to shop has waxed and waned, it still has power over me.
</P>
<P>
   I was speaking to a friend, an English professor in Illinois,
the other day, and he began reminiscing about spending his
childhood summers in a cottage on a little lake near DeKalb.
Fishing with his dad, Bill experienced a deep companionship with
his father, a closeness that was otherwise missing in their
relationship. Bill inherited the cottage when his folks died, and
he confessed that for years, he used to go fishing, mostly as a way
of re-creating an experience that brought feelings of inner
tranquillity back into his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while,'' Bill said, ``I realized I liked casting, but
not catching fish, so I began to go out in the boat and simply sit
there, casting without using a hook. I was still in the boat. Then
it occurred to me that I could just as easily re-create the feeling
of fishing by casting from my deck. From there it was a very small
step to engaging in what I call Zen fishing. I wait for a lovely
warm afternoon. I sit on my deck. And then I go through the motions
in my head. It has exactly the same effect.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bill, Zen fishing is a spiritual practice. He believes that
what is transpiring is a connection that transcends the limitations
of time and place, one that, he says, ``enables me to feel the flow
of love and energy through the universe.'' Later, I thought about
whether Bill's feeling of oneness with nature when he was with his
dad bore any resemblance to my shopping trips with my mom. As I
remembered our times together in all those dressing rooms, I
started to cry.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't about dresses or flattery, even then. My mother was
often distracted and inattentive; I felt as if for once I had my
mother's full attention. Despite her own issues about her body, she
gave herself over to loving me. For some reason, in this one
setting she was able to appreciate and affirm the insecure girl
standing before her. I see now that the intensity of that
experience came from the fact that it was one of the few times we
actually felt the loving energy of the universe flowing between us.
</P>
<P>
   I think I may be able to forgo walking into stores and go
straight to Zen shopping as a spiritual practice. I think Bill's
right. My mom will be waiting for me anywhere I look for her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
