<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIGHT WAY TO PROTECT THE FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF JACOBY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It will take 67 votes in the Senate to send the proposed
flag-protection amendment on to the states for ratification. That
is two more votes than the amendment is believed to have, and so
for the fourth time since 1989, the amendment will fail.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment's supporters want to undo the Supreme Court's
rulings in its 1989 and 1990 flag-burning cases. They are right to
reject the court's holding that torching the star-spangled banner
is protected by the First Amendment, but wrong to think that their
only option is to change the Constitution. The Supreme Court, its
own propaganda notwithstanding, is not the final authority on what
the Constitution means. And when the justices err, it does not
require a constitutional amendment to correct their mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed amendment reads, in its entirety: ``The Congress
shall have power to prohibit the physical desecration of the flag
of the United States.'' But nothing in the Constitution withholds
that power from the Congress. Certainly, the First Amendment _ as
it has traditionally been understood by most Americans and most of
the states _ does not.
</P>
<P>
   After all, flag-burning was illegal in 48 states and the
District of Columbia when the Supreme Court reached its
idiosyncratic 5-4 decision in 1989. No sooner was the ruling in
Texas v. Johnson handed down than Congress passed, and George Bush
signed, the Flag Protection Act of 1989. When that statute was
struck down in the 1990 case, US v. Eichmann, 49 states passed
resolutions calling for the decision to be undone. That adds up to
a lot of officials _ legislators, governors, members of Congress,
the president _ who believe the malicious burning of an American
flag should be a crime. And each of those officials, like justices
of the Supreme Court, took an oath to uphold the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the policy of the government upon vital questions affecting
the whole people,'' Abraham Lincoln declared at his first
inaugural, ``is to be irrevocably fixed by decisions of the Supreme
Court the instant they are made . . . the people will have ceased
to be their own rulers, having . . . resigned their government into
the hands of that eminent tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Supreme Court does not have the last word on what
is and isn't constitutional. The people do. If they feel strongly
enough that the justices have gotten something wrong, they can
correct the error.
</P>
<P>
   It would be best, of course, if the Supreme Court corrected its
own error. Congress and the states can pass new flag-protection
statutes and allow them to be challenged. Four of the justices who
decided the Johnson and Eichmann cases _ William Brennan, Thurgood
Marshall, Harry Blackmun, and Byron White _ are no longer on the
bench. A majority of the current court might well reverse the
1989-90 holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans have other options. They can pressure Congress
into stripping the Supreme Court of the authority to hear
flag-desecration cases. (Article III of the Constitution empowers
Congress to carve out ``exceptions'' to the high court's appellate
jurisdiction.) They can demand that presidential candidates declare
themselves on the issue. White House hopefuls are routinely asked
whether they would have an abortion ``litmus test'' for Supreme
Court nominations. Why not ask about a flag-burning test _ and
refuse to support candidates who refuse to apply one?
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment's guarantee of free speech does not
encompass the public incineration of flags. It isn't only
mossbacked strict constructionists who think so.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years before Texas v. Johnson, another flag-burning case
reached the Supreme Court. The defendant, a black man named Street,
burned an American flag in Brooklyn on June 6, 1966. That was the
day James Meredith, the civil rights leader, was shot by a sniper
in Mississippi; Street heard of the shooting on the radio, and
boiled over with outrage. From a drawer in his apartment he took
his own flag and burned it at the corner of St. James Place and
Lafayette Avenue. ``We don't need no damn flag,'' he said. ``If
they let that happen to Meredith, we don't need an American flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Street was convicted under a New York law that made it a crime
to ``cast contempt'' on the flag. When the case reached the Supreme
Court, a bare majority found a way to avoid ruling on the
constitutionality of New York's statute. Four justices dissented,
among them some of the most liberal interpreters of the First
Amendment in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' Chief Justice Earl Warren wrote, ``that the state
and the federal government do have the power to protect the flag
from acts of desecration and disgrace.'' Hugo Black, the great
First Amendment absolutist, was even more adamant: ``It passes my
belief that anything in the federal Constitution bars a state from
making the deliberate burning of the American flag an offense.''
Byron White and Abe Fortas expressed similar views. ``Protest,''
Fortas said, ``does not excuse lawlessness.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people can differ on the wisdom of flag-burning laws.
I would rather rely on stigma and social condemnation to protect
the national symbol than on prison terms. But it is not irrational
for the states, or for Congress, to decide otherwise. What is
irrational is the notion that because Americans are free, they may
not guard their foremost symbol of freedom from mockery. That isn't
what the Constitution says. If a Supreme Court justice says
otherwise, it is the justice, not the Bill of Rights, that must be
amended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jeff Jacoby is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
