<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS09-C     07-08 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVALS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern festivals
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  McConnells, S.C. _ The Revolutionary War battle of Huck's
Defeat will be re-created Saturday and Sunday on its original site
219 years after the fact at Historic Brattonsville. Both days
include 1770s cooking, medicine, musketry, camp life and a hands-on
children's area. Historical dramatist Howard Burnham as Lord
Cornwallis will deliver a description of the British experience in
the back country. Vendors representing historical trades will sell
gifts. 803-329-2121.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Myrtle Beach, S.C. _ Art in the Park Saturday and Sunday
features arts and crafts including woodworking, sculpture and
glassblowing. 843-249-4937.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cordele, Ga. _ The 50th annual Watermelon Days Festival
continues through Saturday. The event includes entertainment,
watermelon-spitting contests and food. 912-273-1668.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ The Thomasville Cultural Center presents
its 10th annual Summer Showcase, a juried show featuring 67 works
by artists living within a 275-mile radius of Thomasville. Also,
works by Dick Inman, whose oil paintings depict people and animals
from faraway places. Through July 25. 912-226-0588 or www.tccarts
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Berea, Ky. _ The 18th annual Berea Craft Festival Friday
through Sunday at Indian Fort Theater features 120 crafters from 20
states, daily crafts demonstrations, regional foods and strolling
musicians and dancers on the festival grounds. 1-800-598-5263.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Des Allemands, La. _ Louisiana Catfish Festival Saturday and
Sunday includes a catfish eating contest, catfish cooking contest
and live entertainment. 504-758-7542.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boone, N.C. _ The Appalachian Summer Festival, through July,
includes nearly 30 music, dance and theater performances at
Appalachian State University. An outdoor concert with fireworks
July 17 will feature Mary Chapin Carpenter. Tickets: 1-800-841-2787
or online at appsummer.appstate.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Grandfather Mountain, N.C. _ The Highland Games Thursday
through Sunday celebrate Scottish traditions at this annual event
in MacRae Meadows. 828-733-2013.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Craft Fair of the Southern Highlands is
July 15-18 at the Asheville Civic Center. The fair showcases works
by the 700-member Southern Highland Craft Guild and presents
demonstrations in various media as well as live mountain music and
storytelling. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville _ The Southern Highland Craft Guild presents
``Buck-Os and Lady Misses,'' a dramatic musical presentation of
stories about life in the Blue Ridge Mountains by North Carolina
poet laureate Fred Chappell, at the Folk Art Center Friday-Sunday
and July 16-18. 7:30 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays; 3:30 p.m. Sundays.
$10; under 10 free. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Philadephia, Miss. _ The 50th annual Choctaw Indian Fair, July
14-17 on the Choctaw Pearl River Reservation, includes cultural
foods, dancing, arts and crafts and stickball games. 601-650-1537.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Key West, Fla. _ Hemingway Days Festival July 16-25, honoring
the American author, includes a lookalike contest, writers workshop
and conference and fishing clinics. 305-294-2918 or
www.hemingwaydays.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Beaufort, S.C. _ The Beaufort County Water Festival July 16-25
includes a sailing regatta, river rally, children's day and an
air/sea rescue demonstration. 843-524-0600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young Harris _ The 11th season of the state's official
historical drama, ``The Reach of Song,'' continues through Aug. 22
and features local musicians and cast members in a celebration of
the Appalachian spirit and a tribute to mountain poet Byron Herbert
Reece. 1-800-262-7664.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Highlands, N.C. _ The Highlands Playhouse presents the farce
``Cash on Delivery'' today through July 18, the musical ``Crazy for
You'' July 21-Aug. 8 and the comedy ``Take This Man'' Aug. 11-22.
828-526-2695.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmond _ The Virginia Museum of Fine Arts presents the
exhibition ``The Splendors of Egypt,'' a panoramic view of one of
the world's oldest and most sophisticated civilizations, with more
than 200 masterpieces, some at least 5,000 years old. Through Nov.
28. 804-367-0878 or www.vmfa.state.va.us.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
