<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GETAWAY09-COX     07-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta actors have found a summer home in `Hills'
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cherokee, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, a small troupe of Atlanta actors pack up and
travel unto these hills to flex their dramatic chops in _ talk
about an apt title _ ``Unto These Hills.'' The venerable outdoor
drama, in its 50th year of retelling the story of the Cherokee
Indians, has become sort of a theater camp in the country for these
refugees from Atlanta's progressive stage scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the Cherokee Mafia,'' jokes Rita Dolphin, a
Marietta (Ga.) actress who plays sympathetic white settler Anne
Worcester in the physically demanding saga that compresses three
centuries into a three-hour event. Dolphin, 23, was last in the
children's production ``Let's Talk About AIDS'' at the Alliance
Theatre this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta posse also includes Decatur's Frank Roberts as
Cherokee Removal enforcer Major Davis and Bill Murphey of East
Atlanta as Cherokee folk hero Tsali. Roberts was in a recent,
critically acclaimed adaptation of Dostoyevsky's ``The Devils'' at
Actor's Express; Murphey won raves for his hilarious portrayal of
Sir Andrew Aguecheek in Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' at Seven
Stages earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Artistic director Peter Hardy is another Georgia boy _ he's the
dramaturge (artistic adviser) for Marietta's Theatre in the Square
and the director of the Essential Theatre company, which recently
produced three plays at PushPush Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   The tight-knit group keeps adding members _ when a part comes
open, the Atlantans will tell friends back home to come up and
audition. Not that parts come open often. ``Most of the actors
playing principal characters have been here at least 10 years,''
says Murphey, who boasts a 15-year run in the drama, the last six
as Tsali.
</P>
<P>
   The play's story line, by Kermit Hunter, has changed little
since 1949, although a few scenes, such as a pivotal wedding, have
been made more authentic. Gun-popping battles and elaborate dance
numbers still drive home the sobering message: that the Cherokees
were robbed of the land they so loved.
</P>
<P>
   For the actors, the show can be grueling. Along with the fancy
footwork and faux armed skirmishes, it requires much forceful
enunciation _ the better to be heard over a symphony of outdoor
night noises.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Fowler of Mableton, who plays a villainous deputy, says the
main difference between doing ``Unto These Hills'' and other plays
is that ``you have to do this one 63 times.'' (The drama runs from
early June through late August every year.) Others complain about
the strenuousness of dancing on the sand stage, swallowing a bug
midbellow and even spying a snake or two backstage. So what keeps
the Atlantans coming back, taking their place in the 175-member
cast, 50 of whom are Native American?
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is very close to me,'' says Roberts, who first
witnessed the drama the year it opened, when he was 6 years old.
``I still remember being so excited by the battles.'' Roberts vows
he'll stay in the show ``as long as I possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphey likes the stable paycheck. ``If you're an actor and you
have a chance to get good, steady work, you take it.'' But the
thirtysomething thespian also relishes the cameraderie among his
fellow Atlantans and the other cast members. After many
performances, actors gather in the canteen of their homey dormitory
area behind the amphitheater for a potluck supper. Every Saturday
night, they put on plays for each other _ Murphey recently directed
a production of Martin McDonagh's ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane.''
</P>
<P>
   And after 15 years, Murphey admits he's emotionally invested in
the play, too. ``Before I played Tsali, I was in another role, and
one night I did this gesture with my hand which has since become
part of the character's blocking. You really get the chance to put
your own stamp on the production.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Unto These Hills.'' 8:45 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays through July
24; 8:30 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays July 26-Aug. 21. Reserved seats
$14; general admission tickets $11 adults, $5 children 6-12. Call
828-497-2111 to reserve tickets; visit www.dnet.net
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)cheratt for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
