A3120 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BABIES11-COX     07-08 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BABIES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loaded like a pack mule with the essentials of survival, we
venture forth into the wide world
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wait at the ticket counter at the Raleigh-Durham Airport was
long enough to hear repeated warnings from the ticket agent that
all passengers were limited to two checked bags. Finally, it was my
turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have two bags,'' the agent chirped, more statement than
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I have ... all this,'' I said wearily.
</P>
<P>
   At my feet lay the flotsam and jetsam from a family beach
vacation: a trunk-size duffel bag, suitcase, set of golf clubs,
portable crib, mesh baby gate, box full of hand-me-down clothes and
plastic seat that clamps to a table in lieu of a high chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you're traveling with an infant,'' she replied, limits
suddenly vaporized. She swiftly tagged the huge pile of belongings
and lugged them to the conveyor belt. It was the sort of
benevolence you imagine from a cop who's about to ticket an
illegally parked car then discovers the driver is handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, my 18-month-old daughter played in the metal contraption
that shows the size limits for carry-on luggage. Hmm. I couldn't
help but notice she'd fit quite easily under a seat or in an
overhead compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with a little kid can make you imagine scenarios that
keep DFACS busy. Calling it an adventure is like describing a
marathon as a long race. You can imagine the challenge, but you'll
never truly know how exhausting it can be until you've done it
yourself. After the memory of all the hassles subsides, a certain
elation sets in from enduring it all.
</P>
<P>
   Johanna has flown 19 times now, and I look at loading up all her
necessities like the provisioning of a small militia. Keeping this
29-pound dervish entertained for any amount of time in close
quarters brings to mind the phrase ``by any means necessary.''
Survival sometimes depends on the kindness of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   As we boarded the Boeing 757, I made my way down the narrow
aisle, trying not to bash anyone with my Santa Claus-size diaper
bag. Joey was dressed in a 1960s-looking sundress with huge
flowers. Other parents may save a child's best outfits for church
or the portrait studio, but I always try to maximize cuteness on
the days we fly, to build goodwill with other passengers. The
strategy seemed to be working. Lots of people smiled at her,
including one of the men sitting next to us. I apologized to the
surly-looking one on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it's a short flight,'' I said weakly. He didn't
respond.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to empathize with the members of the traveling
majority, the ones without kids, who travel leisurely and
unencumbered. The line demarcating the two is as absolute as the
Atlanta Perimeter _ either you're in or you're out. You're either
stuck with an overloaded stroller as you wait for an elevator or
striding confidently down the concourse unfettered by no more than
a single, sleek rolling suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago and child-free, my husband and I were rooted on
the other side. We spent five months seeing the world, proud of our
shoestring budget and that all we needed fit in our backpacks. When
foreigners asked us if we were parents, we replied, ``No, maybe one
day,'' with all the insouciance of Phileas Fogg.
</P>
<P>
   Now that that day has come, so has all the baggage, both literal
and otherwise. We get to the airport early; we can't exactly
picture ourselves bolting to the gate. We don't cram a lot of
sightseeing into our trips; we prefer modest outings. We spent
hundreds of dollars extra on a trans-Atlantic flight that would
coincide with Joey's bedtime, and it was worth it when she slept
almost the whole way.
</P>
<P>
   We are no longer among those fliers paging through the latest
best seller; we read material from the seat pocket in front of us.
The cartoonlike safety instructions provided a few minutes'
diversion on the flight from Raleigh, until Joey started popping
out the Airfone and jamming it back in. Countless times. With
squeals of pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   That might have bothered the passenger in front, but thank God
she was busy with her own squirming toddler. We were supposed to
sit beside them, but the flight attendant switched us because there
weren't enough oxygen masks in that row. I fantasized that if those
suddenly descended, I'd forgo the safety warning and put one on my
kid first _ just to silence her.
</P>
<P>
   We sang. We read. We snacked. NBA seasons have gone by faster
than these 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At least she didn't have a meltdown this time. On our last trip
together, from Texas, she woke up with a look of agitated betrayal
as if to say, ``WHY ARE WE STILL ON THIS PLANE?'' and proceeded to
wail inconsolably for the longest 20 minutes of my life. I had to
stand up to rock her, alerting everyone to the source of all the
ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   As I'm writing this, I'm wondering why we don't just stay home.
And a vision flashes in my mind of my parents packing up my two
brothers and me for cross-country trips each summer. My husband's
family of six went on long excursions, too. Of course we don't
remember where we went as toddlers, but as we grew up, we learned
to look forward to new discoveries, and return with renewed
appreciation for home. We learned to see ourselves as part of a
much larger world that wasn't just on paper or TV, and that's what
I hope traveling will eventually impart to Joey.
</P>
<P>
   One day, we would love to take her around the world with us, to
see what we have seen and to explore new places together. But one
thing's for certain: She'll have to pack her own stuff and carry
it.
</P>
<P>
   We've done enough of that already.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
