<HEADER>
A3121 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING09-COX     07-08 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SHOPPING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Come on in _ the waterfront's fine
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEAUFORT, S.C. _ Beautiful Beaufort by the sea, 26 miles from
Yemassee.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, kids have chanted this rhyme that aptly describes
South Carolina's second oldest town, on the Beaufort River. More
than 300 visitors a day flock to shop, eat and tour its stately
pre-Revolutionary War and antebellum homes and enjoy the
picturesque waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 437 historic houses in Beaufort (pronounced
BEW-fert) boast charming gardens and stand along narrow streets
shaded by dreamy-looking, moss-covered live oaks. One of the most
photographed homes is James Fripp's 1856 Tidalholm, a two-story
white mansion seen in the films ``The Big Chill'' and ``The Great
Santini.'' Like other visitors, Hollywood honchos love Beaufort and
have made 13 movies here.
</P>
<P>
   This picturesque Lowcountry town is nestled between Savannah,
about 55 miles to the south, and Charleston, about 75 miles to the
north. Established by charter in 1711, Beaufort's history actually
goes back much further.Spanish explorers visited in 1514, and
French Huguenots attempted a settlement at nearby Parris Island in
1562. The Spanish reappeared from 1564 to 1587. Others, including
the English and Scots, battled over the coastal plain while
Yemassee and Tuscarora Indians fought to protect their claims.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged is Beaufort, today home to 10,000 year-round
residents and more than 60 shops and art galleries. They offer
tourists everything from a special-edition Madame Alexander doll
($199) to a utilitarian lobster cracker ($4.98) to a one-of-a-kind
Taylor Nicole Turner sculpture of a Gullah woman ($1,000).
</P>
<P>
   For the past two decades, downtown Beaufort has been a vibrant
shopping destination. Duncan Nelson, manager of the visitors center
at the Chamber of Commerce, attributes this to the opening of the
Henry C. Chambers Waterfront Park in '79. ``Before the park, the
area was a landfill,'' she said. ``After the park opening,
restaurants moved in and built patios that overlooked the water.
People with creative minds and merchandise came to town and soon
shops and galleries followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Bayden, who's lived in Beaufort 10 years, gives the town
high marks for a ``really quality shopping area.'' Said Bayden, ``I
like the fact there are several independent booksellers as well as
good art galleries and gift shops such as Rossignol's for wedding
gifts and Boombears for toys, which I think rivals the toy store
FAO Schwarz.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are a local or a visitor, you can do most of your
shopping on foot, after parking your car in a city lot (two hours'
free parking) or anchoring your boat in the marina. Bay Street is
the heart of the shopping area, where Lipsitz's department store
has outfitted its customers from head to toe for more than 97
years.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Joe Lipsitz, who was born 79 years ago on the store's
second floor, says more and more tourists have discovered his
hometown. ``We have the same things to offer as a Savannah or
Charleston but on a smaller scale,'' said the unofficial historian
of Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife, Lucille, and I used to know everybody who walked down
the street. But not anymore. We see visitors from Germany and
France as well as all over the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Lana Hefner, who co-owns Bay St. Gallery, is a transplanted
Atlanta artist who fell in love with Beaufort. ``The natural beauty
of the area brought me here,'' she said. ``I wanted to be on the
coast yet not too far from Atlanta.'' Her gallery features the
world-famous sweet grass baskets _ so called because of the
pleasant fragrance of the grass _ woven by descendents of slaves
from West Africa. Twice a month, Hefner spends the day going up and
down the Carolina coast locating the best baskets for her
customers. They start at $75 for a small-handled basket and top out
at $400 for a large one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming a lost art,'' she said. ``Sweet grass is getting
scarce because of extensive coastal development, and many of the
basket makers are elderly women. But shoppers love the baskets.
They want to take this area home with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to spend a fortune for a South Carolina
souvenir. Stones &AMP; Bones is a neat Bay Street gift shop selling
shark teeth found in the Lowcountry starting at $1.50 as well as
cedar boxes ($20-$50) and all types of jewelry ranging from $2 to
$200. And the Beaufort Butterfly Co. offers, you guessed it, all
types of butterfly-trimmed gifts, including rock paperweights
($15), canvas totes ($18) and kids' T-shirts ($14). On a recent
Friday, 8-year-old Patti Alexander of Dayton, Ohio, was snapping up
``fluttering'' butterfly hair clips ($3 each), which she pronounced
``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're in need of a bit of heavenly support, stop by the shop
in the 1790 John Mark Verdier museum house on Bay Street and buy a
``coastal angel.'' This $5 trinket, which makes a good tree
ornament or knickknack, is fashioned from one part shell, one part
moss and wood, and two parts cotton _ the perfect reminder of your
shopping foray to beautiful Beaufort.
</P>
<P>
   If You Go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From Atlanta, take I-75 south to Macon, then
I-16 east to 1-95 north. Take Exit 8 (U.S. 278) in South Carolina
and pick up S.C. 170 northeast to U.S. 21; continue east and turn
right on Charles, West, Scott or Carteret street into the historic
district. It's about a 5 1/2-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most stores and galleries are open 10 a.m.-6 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays, with flexible Sunday hours. It's best to call
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Free two-hour parking in lot on Bay Street, near
Waterfront Park. On-street parking on Bay Street and side streets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Shops are accessible to the handicapped.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Henry C. Chambers Waterfront Park on Bay Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Greater Beaufort Chamber of Commerce:
1-800-638-3525. Or visit Beaufort's Web site at www.beaufort.com.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  11th Street Dockside Restaurant. Overlooking the shrimp boat
docks of Battery Creek, this Port Royal restaurant serves fresh
seafood (shrimp or flounder, $12.95), steaks (ribeye, $14.95) and
Lowcountry favorites including she crab soup ($4.50 a bowl), hush
puppies with honey butter ($2.95) and Battery Creek crab cakes
($14.95). 4:30-10 p.m. daily. 11th Street West, Port Royal.
843-524-7433.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plums: Between shopping stops, duck into this local favorite.
The lineup includes gourmet soups and sandwiches, also all types of
salads ($3.25-$6.55). Save room for homemade ice cream ($1.89 a
scoop). Lunch: 11 a.m.-5 p.m. daily; dinner: 5-10 p.m. daily. 904
1/2 Bay St. 843-525-1946.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Bank Waterfront Grill &AMP; Bar: Housed in the renovated 1916
Beaufort Bank, this casual restaurant has a clever menu and good
food. Servers are known as tellers and the Beginning Balance
(appetizers) includes nachos, fried mozzarella cheese sticks and
oyster shooters ($4.95-$8.95). Drinks are known as Liquid Assets.
And the Ending Balance? Dessert, of course. Most lunch entrees
around $7. Sit inside or out on the terrace. 11 a.m.-10 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays. 926 Bay St. 843-522-8831.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best Western Sea Island Inn: This pleasant, two-story brick
inn, with 43 rooms, faces the water. Amenities include bicycles,
swimming pool and complimentary continental breakfast. Because this
inn is right on Bay Street, you can easily walk to shops and
restaurants. $89-$119. 1015 Bay St. 843-522-2090.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other options: Beaufort's historic district is filled with
lovely bed-and-breakfast inns. For a romantic stay, choose the 1820
Rhett House Inn, with afternoon tea and complimentary dessert trays
at night. 1009 Craven St. 843-524-9030. Or try the Old Point Inn, a
Victorian B&AMP;B with four rooms. Amenities include a full breakfast,
library, gardens and wraparound verandas. $65-$110. 212 New St.
843-524-3177. Note: Most rooms in these lodgings are smoke-free.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   The 44th annual Beaufort County Water Festival is July 16-25 at
Waterfront Park. Entertainment includes concerts in the park, a
Lowcountry supper, water skiing, talent and air shows, boat races
and parades. Many events, including the craft market, are free.
Tickets for concerts and dinners are about $10. 1-800-638-3525.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
