<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SOUTHEAST11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southeast is a mecca for family tourism
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These Southeast destinations took top honors in FamilyFun
magazine's 1999 Family-Friendly Travel Awards. The summaries,
included in the June/July issue:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gatlinburg/Pigeon Forge, Tenn.: This neon-lit tourist town is
for families who want to blend Nashville-style ``glamour'' with
their Smoky Mountain getaway. 1-800-251-9100.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. Space &AMP; Rocket Center, Huntsville, Ala.: Space lovers
flock here for the sheer volume of gadgetry, including ride-on
simulators, a Space Lab model and rockets galore. 256-837-3400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Audubon Zoo, New Orleans: At this 58-acre zoo in the Big Easy,
a renovated bayou exhibit mixes creatures and culture.
504-861-2537.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Destin, Fla.: Crowning a peninsula on Florida's Emerald Coast,
this low-key historic fishing town seems made for vacationing
families. 850-837-6241.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SeaWorld Orlando: Zany animal shows, aquarium displays, a
shark exhibit and a kids waterpark are all part of SeaWorld's
watery appeal. 1-800-423-8368.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Walt Disney World, Orlando: Far more than an amusement park,
Disney World remains a must-visit destination for our readers.
407-934-7639.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kennedy Space Center, Cape Canaveral, Fla.: Time your visit to
witness a fiery shuttle blastoff at NASA's Launch Complex 39.
407-867-7110.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla.: America's oldest city is replete with
history, funky museums, Ponce de Leon's ``Fountain of Youth'' and
white sand beaches. 1-800-653-2489.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jamestown Settlement, Jamestown, Va.: Settlers landed here in
1607; now a re-created village and harbor take visitors to those
first Colonial days in the New World. 757-229-1607.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monticello, Charlottesville, Va.: An innovator, statesman and
architect, Thomas Jefferson poured his genius into this fetching
Virginia mansion. 804-984-9800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mount Vernon, Va.: Kids can see where George Washington lived,
farmed and snoozed on his Potomac River plantation. 703-780-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Washington: With dozens of museums and monuments free to
tourists, our nation's capital is the vacation deal of any
millennium. 202-789-7000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The National Air and Space Museum, Washington: Moon rocks,
Martian gardens and the evolution of human flight are highlights at
this gigantic, free museum. 202-357-2700.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The White House, Washington: If you're fascinated by the lives
(and decorating tastes) of present and past presidents, it's worth
queuing for a White House tour. 202-456-7041.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
