<HEADLINE>
`TROPHY' TREES: MADE-IN-THE-SHADE GRANDEUR FOR YUPPIE YARDS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance and Lifestyle Editors)   (RESENDING from July 1 for those needing)  
  
 (This 500-word ``separate buy'' story is from the June issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial, ``a'' domestic/general and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By E. BINGO WYER  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year before completing their home in Ross, Calif., Mary and
Bill Poland began scouting for a Valley oak, a picture-perfect
wide-branched tree that would exactly match the one depicted by
their architect in his sketch of their new home.
</P>
<P>
   After searching up and down the state, Mary eventually found one
_ a 30-foot, 50-year-old beauty for $12,500 _ at a nearby nursery.
</P>
<P>
   She reserved it, waited for her house to be finished, and then
had it brought over by truck and planted by her driveway, where it
offers shade for her house and takes the newness off her property.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can tell when the home was built. It has an old-world
look,'' Mary says.
</P>
<P>
   Trophy trees: The trend was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   As people look to recreate the grand houses of the past (the
Polands' is 8,000 square feet, in the French Mediterranean style),
they want the trees around them to be just as lofty.
</P>
<P>
   Says Barry W. Starke, president of the American Society of
Landscape Architects, ``Older trees, the really large ones, used to
be bought by older folks, who didn't have the time to watch a tree
come into its glory. But now it seems the younger people with money
don't want to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, trophy trees are American classics such as
maples, oaks, and beeches; most are found on farms and older
estates about to be subdivided or in large nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   A lush, ample copper beech, valued for its leaf color and
beautiful bark, can cost $25,000. A 60-year-old disectum Japanese
maple _ typically slow growing and prized for its delicate, lacy
leaves _ can command over $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tom Verderosa, a landscaper in East Hampton, Long
Island, trees and shrubs go through fashions, much like houses.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent hemlocks were popular a few years ago in the Long
Island/Connecticut region; now he says, the demand is for topiaries
at least 60 years old and big hydrangeas, preferably 50-plus (their
prices range from $20,000 to $30,000).
</P>
<P>
   Dallas landscape architect Caye Cook says that live oaks, cedar
elms, magnolias, and American sweet-gum trees are now status
symbols par excellence in residential neighborhoods and commercial
parks in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Many new homeowners are surprised by the lead time trophy trees
require.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the tree's extensive root system must be pruned in
stages, a process that can last roughly a year and a half or the
time it can take for the architect to secure the proper permits
from highway authorities; sometimes traffic lights have to come
down.
</P>
<P>
   And the home's value? Says Jo Bishop, a Kentucky-based realtor
who specializes in affluent communities, ``Trophy trees can easily
add 20 percent to a home's value, especially on smaller
properties.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: E. Bingo Wyer reported on trophy homes in the May
1997 WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this interesting 500-word ``WORTH'' magazine
article, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
