<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-McCAIN-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      07-08 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN FOCUSES ON CHANGING THE POLITICS OF MONEY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Looking for traction in his uphill campaign
for the presidency, Arizona Sen. John McCain is tying his chances
for the Republican nomination to his crusade for an overhaul of the
nation's campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is betting that voters, fed up with the money politics of
Washington, will be attracted to a candidate who promises changes.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why this fall he plans to try to force a
discussion on the Senate floor of legislation that would ban
so-called soft money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he admits he doesn't have the 60 votes he needs to
break a Republican filibuster of his bill, he is hoping to reignite
debate on campaign finance as the 2000 presidential race heats up.
And if it becomes a top national issue, that it will in turn boost
his own chances in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   With the possible exception of Republican hopeful Steve Forbes
and his flat tax, no candidate in the presidential hunt is as
closely identified with one issue as McCain. He raises the way
campaigns are funded in every speech. He says his name has become
so closely connected to that of the co-sponsor of his bill, Sen.
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., that his colleague sometimes gets letters
addressed to ``Mr. McCain Feingold.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``soft money'' the McCain-Feingold bill attacks is
designated for party-building purposes and is separate from
donations to a specific candidate, although soft money often is
used to tout issues advocated be a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill would outlaw soft money donations to
the Republican and Democratic parties from companies, unions or
special interest groups. And it would impose restrictions on
organizations that mount independent ad campaigns within two months
of an election. It also would require new disclosure requirements
on campaign donors.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans typically have the edge over Democrats in such
donations, McCain has said his own campaign has followed the intent
of the bill in raising money.
</P>
<P>
   McCain delivered a campaign speech Wednesday at the Hoover
Institution, the conservative think tank at Stanford University,
with a simple message: Until there is a change in campaign finance
laws, there will be no tax reform, no education reform, no tort
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't reform anything until we first reform the way we
finance our political campaigns,'' he told an audience of 100 at a
lunch to benefit the Hoover Institution. ``As long as special
interests dominate campaigns, they will dominate legislation as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, McCain singled out major contributors to both
Democratic and Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He attacked teachers unions for opposing teacher competency
standards and school vouchers. He targeted Archer Daniels Midland
Co., the agribusiness giant, for giving huge sums to both parties
to help secure a multibillion dollar ethanol tax subsidy. He
criticized trial lawyers for nearly derailing the recent Senate
bill to limit liability for companies if computer problems develop
related to the Year 2000 glitch.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the former Navy pilot who was a war prisoner in Vietnam
for 5 1/2 years, attacked Pentagon suppliers for lobbying for more
money for sometimes outdated or unnecessary military equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reform is not possible when defense contractors and their
patrons in Congress use their influence to protect sales rather
than promote national security,'' said McCain, 62. ``Our nation can
do better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain's rhetoric on campaign finance also serves a political
purpose. By railing against fat-cat interest groups and
money-obsessed politicians in Washington, he can appear to voters
as an outsider, a candidate for change, even though he served two
terms in the House and has been elected to the Senate three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is the reform candidate in this race,'' insists
Dan Schnur, his California political adviser. ``He's talking about
pork-barrel spending. He's running against the Republican
establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, the campaign finance issue will be what Schnur calls
a ``campaign within a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain is taking a risk by putting such a strong emphasis on
campaign finance, one analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Wolfinger, a political science professor at the University
of California at Berkeley, said many voters might agree with
McCain's call to ban soft money. Yet at a time when voters are
generally content with a booming economy, they may not be
sufficiently angry at Washington to join McCain's crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the country were in a different mood _ for example, back in
1976, when one thing that helped Jimmy Carter get elected was that
he didn't know anything about Washington _ I think there would be
more punch to this issue,'' Wolfinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfinger said McCain's stance on campaign finance reform has
gained him support among Democrats and independents, who applaud
him for bucking GOP leaders who have resisted changes in the way
soft money is handled. But he said the Arizona senator has yet to
prove that he has strong enough support in his own party to win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``To succeed in the contest for the nomination, you either have
to have a constituency or you have to have money,'' he said. ``It's
not clear that McCain will have a constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, it's not clear if he'll have the money, either.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush took in more than $36 million in less
than four months. McCain was second on the money list among
Republicans, but a very distant second, with just over $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he expects to raise about $15 million for the race,
not including the $6 million he expects to add in federal matching
funds. It will be enough, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it's over March 7, when California and 15 other
states vote, so you don't have to have a whole lot of money for the
long haul,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
