<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STIRRING DESCRIPTION OF AN AMERICAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a copy of a creed that begins ``I do not choose to be
a common man.'' What information is available on this?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.S., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: That creed was written by Dean Alfange, a founder of the
Liberal Party of New York, and first published in This Week
magazine in December 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The text: ``I do not choose to be a common man. It is my right
to be uncommon _ if I can. I seek opportunity _ not security. I do
not wish to be a kept citizen, humbled and dulled by having the
state look after me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take the calculated risk; to dream and to build, to
fail and to succeed. I refuse to barter incentive for a dole. I
prefer the challenges of life to the guaranteed existence; the
thrill of fulfillment to the stale calm of utopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not trade freedom for beneficence or my dignity for a
handout. I will never cower before any master nor bend to any
threat. It is my heritage to stand erect, proud and unafraid; to
think and act for myself, enjoy the benefit of my creations, and to
face the world boldly and say, this I have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is what it means to be an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the very early '70s there was a song by a group named Rose
Colored Glass that I used to play on a local restaurant's jukebox
every day at lunch. For the life of me, I can't remember the name
of the song. What's the title?
</P>
<P>
   _ R., Wilkes-Barre, Penn.
</P>
<P>
   A: Rose Colored Glass had two Top 100 singles on the Bang
Records label in 1971: ``Can't Find the Time'' and ``You're Good
for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Find the Time,'' which reached No. 54, had ``Mystic
Touch'' on the flip side. ``If It's Alright With You'' hit No. 95
and was accompanied by ``You're Good for Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Record Finders, a dealer in out-of-print LPs and other music,
has both singles in stock. For ordering information, call (804)
264-0300 or write to Box 1047, Glen Allen, VA 23060.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't Find the Time,'' which sometimes is called ``I Can't
Find the Time to Tell You,'' is also on the 1996 CD collection
``Dick Bartley Presents Collector's Essentials Vol. 2: The '70s.''
That CD is available from the online retailer CDNow at
www.cdnow.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Bob Ross of ``The Joy of Painting'' deceased?
</P>
<P>
   _ U.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ross, who painted ``happy little trees'' on his PBS
art-instruction show for 12 years, died of lymphoma in 1995 at age
52.
</P>
<P>
   He became interested in painting while in the Air Force,
inspired by a 1963 assignment to Alaska. After retiring from the
service in 1981, Ross taught art and was offered a program by a PBS
station after officials there saw a tape of his class. He lived in
Florida and filmed his show at a Muncie, Ind., station.
</P>
<P>
   The Bob Ross Co. continues to offer art instruction, supplies
and other products. To request a catalog, call (800) 262-7677 or
visit the Web site www.bobross.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
