<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE09-COX     07-08 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspiring masters of zinnias plant seeds of hope for next year
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Failure has company. So it is with my inability to
grow zinnias from seed. Since detailing my zinnia misery in a June
17 column, I've heard from a number of gardeners in similar
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Dean Carpenter of Duluth (Ga.), for example, writes in an
e-mail that he identifies with unfulfilled ``expectations of great
things from seeds.'' For him, ``Herb seeds seem to be the most
difficult.'' On the up side, he's growing great buckwheat from
seed.
</P>
<P>
   And in her e-mail, Sandy Springs gardener Madonna Powers says,
``I can relate to your frustrations,'' noting that, ``Zinnias seem
to you what lavender is to me. I have tried and tried to grow every
variety of lavender from seed, to no avail.'' She finds some solace
in marigolds from seed and in seed-grown morning glories, which
``have helped ease my sense of seed-starting failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, there were notes of triumph _ gardeners letting me know
they had succeeded in producing hearty zinnias in colorful
profusion. Among those who invited me to visit and marvel and,
maybe, learn, was the Rev. Ron Crispens of Cumming, who with his
wife, Helene, lives on a verdant 50 acres, some of which also is
home to their three grown children and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Ron has gardened and farmed that spot for 19 years, growing just
about any food you'd want or need, growing flowers, too, including
radiant marigolds and sunflowers. But the zinnias are the thing.
He's proud for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Several large patches, blooming mostly orangy-red, light up
spaces around the house. No straggly stems here. No skanky leaves.
These plants are rock solid from head to root, standing some 3 feet
tall.
</P>
<P>
   After a walkabout, we retired to the screened porch, a space
that catches the breeze in the same way as those roomy verandas on
Charleston homes by the bay. Sipping Coke, we talked zinnias.
</P>
<P>
   When we got around to how he grows them, Ron couldn't resist a
good-natured dig at the zinnia-challenged: ``Unlike some people,''
he said, giving me a hard look, ``I find them easy to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy for him to say.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his method does sound easy _ and straightforward. His
foundation is rich earth, compost-filled beds. ``I save all my
leaves,'' he says, adding to them vegetable scraps and composted
pine straw, whose consistency is much like peat.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as spring planting time nears, Ron starts his zinnia
crop indoors, sowing last year's seeds in little pots. When they're
big enough (3 or 4 inches tall), and that rich outdoor soil is warm
enough (at least 50 degrees at night), in go the baby zinnias. With
that rich soil and some hot weather, the plants shoot up like
rockets. And bloom the same way.
</P>
<P>
   What a payoff those blooms are. (Several zinnia growers say that
while the plant is an annual, it readily reseeds for them.) Always
a popular flower in old-style gardens, zinnia, with its big
pinwheel flowers, enjoys ever wider popularity among gardeners and
commercial growers alike. Not surprising, as its range of colors,
including red, orange, yellow, purple, pink, add a bright rainbow
quality to the garden, attracting butterflies by the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Helene points out, as a cut flower, zinnia works: ``At
least a week they last.''
</P>
<P>
   She is quick to acknowledge that she leaves the gardening to
Ron. ``I love picking flowers, but I don't grow them,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I don't grow them from seed, but not because I haven't
tried. When I try again, I'll use some of Ron's seeds _ seeds
gathered from this year's crop.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, however, I had to have zinnias for this year. So,
spying a roadside flower and vegetable stand in Hiawassee during a
Sunday drive, I wheeled in (no vehicle I ever drive can pass plants
for sale) and sure enough, I was in luck. Now, I've got zinnias.
Not many, but enough to satisfy my need for having this old-timey
plant as a reminder of the lovely country gardens I've known and
lived with.
</P>
<P>
   About a foot tall, the half-dozen zinnias are in full flower _
yellow, red, white, pink. Nearby, those seedlings I planted this
spring remain stuck at 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all right; I've been to the zinnia patch, met the
Zinnia Man. Come next year, inspired, I'll seed again.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
