<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL CARS? SOME PEOPLE REALLY GET INTO THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take my word. These cars are small.
</P>
<P>
   How small?
</P>
<P>
   So small that if you drive one, you dance on the razor edge of
political correctness: Fume at that looming Bulbous Bug, the new
Volkwagen Beetle, as you hope it doesn't crush you. Rage at that
gas-guzzling, view-blocking Volvo station wagon whose imperious
owner doesn't care that she could be driving something smaller,
safer (for you), and more fuel efficient.
</P>
<P>
   So small that if you lined up a brood of these tiny autos behind
a Volkswagen bus, called it installment art and placed it, say, in
the heart of green space in downtown Boston, you could name your
work ``Make Way for Ducklings _ with Motors.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the mini- and microcars whose genesis was the need for
cheap transportation (not to mention jobs in idled aircraft
factories) in Europe in the years after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   How small? Microcar engines have three or fewer cylinders and a
displacement of 510 ccs; minis are four cylinders, or less than
1,000 ccs, or less than 13 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   The first prototypes were produced in the late 1940s and early
'50s and, with Germany at the forefront, most were built in Europe.
Messerschmitt, the aircraft manufacturer, took the lead when Fritz
Fend, a German designer, showed his tiny vehicle, which he had
designed as a car for those disabled in the war, to Willy
Messerschmitt, whose factory, under post-war agreement, was not
allowed to produce aircraft. By 1953, little Messerschmitt autos
were rolling off the lines. They look like small planes with their
wings clipped. The cockpit canopy is derived from the fighter plane
and the steering yoke is right out of the aircraft. A single
passenger sits behind the driver, just like pilot and copilot.
</P>
<P>
   It fit the bill for those looking for cheap-to-buy, cheap-to-run
autos. At $520 new, that was about $1 per pound. But Messerschmitt
was not alone in cranking out cars that cost between around $200 to
$1,100, were cheap to register, were taxed low, and got 60-100
miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with what Charles Gould, a Newton, Mass. collector,
calls ``a clean sheet of paper,'' Heinkle, Vespa (under aircraft
manufacturer Piaggio), and BMW, among others, produced the little
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Many were exported to the United States, but in 1950s America,
gas was cheap and the people were in love with big chrome, big
steel, and speed. Sixty-miles-per-hour was screaming fast for many
of these microcars _ and that often required a good tailwind. So
they never caught on here in any serious way and by the time the
Austin Mini and Mini Cooper were introduced in the early 1960s _
small cars that were real cars _ the microcar craze was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese manufacturers produced some in the late 1960s and into
the '70s, and even today in California an electric mini called the
Sparrow (looking remarkably like a Messerschmitt) is in the works.
But for all intents and purposes, the micro- and minicar realm is
now dominated by collectors who scour garages and fields and
cellars and barns for the few tens of thousands that may still
exist.
</P>
<P>
   Gould says they are found in two distinct conditions: rotting
where they were tossed away, or in near perfect condition where,
because they were so small, people were able to carry them indoors
to store away from the ravages of time. Remember: These cars were
so cheap, they were almost disposable. Gould found one of his
Messerschmitts hanging on a wall in a barn. Today, they can be had
as cheaply as $1,000 or less, or up to $20,000 for the rarest
models. The latter would include such prizes as the 4-wheel
Messerschmitt Tiger; a Goggomobile Transporter Van, and Honda S600
and S800 Roadsters from early '60s, with 4-cylinder, 4-carb, DOHC,
600 cc engine that redlined at 9500 RPMs.
</P>
<P>
   The Messerschmitt KR 200, with its 191 cc, two-stroke, aircooled
engine, had an integrated four-speed gear box and no reverse. But
the car can be run in reverse by turning off the engine and
restarting it to run backwards _ thus, four speeds in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The Goggomobile, built in Dingofing, Germany, features an
elaborate electric preshift so it runs through the gears much like
an old, far more expensive Cord.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW Isetta is perhaps the most easily recognized example of
these cars for those outside the craze _ familiar because its front
opens, much like a refrigerator door, to allow access. An
articulated steering linkage with two universal joints lets the
steering wheel and column move up and out of the way when the door
is opened.
</P>
<P>
   Besides many of the standards, there are some rarities: the
Velorex, a Czech auto made as a crude tubular frame covered with
fabric that has at its heart a Jawa motorcycle; a 1958 Brutsch
Mopetta, the smallest car ever manufactured and resembling a
motorcycle sidecar. It is steered by motorcycle handlebars and is
one of three still known to exist from the original 11
manufactured; and the George Jetson-mobile, a 1964 Peel Trident,
fiberglass with a clear bubble dome, built on the Isle of Man and
sold as ``cheaper than walking'' at about $200 new.
</P>
<P>
   Also there is the BMW Isetta 300, 600 and 700s, and cars from
Messerschmitt, Kleinschnittger, Goggomobile, Zundapp, Vespa,
Heinkle, Fiat, Crosley, King Midget, Fuji, Daihatsu, Honda and
Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
