<SLUG> BC-COURT-INTERPRETERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT INTERPRETERS TO GET PAY RAISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hoping to slow the loss of translators in
California courts, a state panel has announced it is increasing the
daily pay for certified interpreters from the $200 most were being
paid a day to $243.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is necessary because the state's pool of certified
interpreters has fallen 39 percent in the last four years _ from a
total of 1,675 in 1995 to 1,026 this year, the state Judicial
Council said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely essential ... that we have competent
interpretation services available,'' said William C. Vickrey,
administrative director of the courts for the Judicial Council.
``It's an issue of access and fairness to the citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 languages are spoken in California, and more than
100 on any given day are interpreted in the courts, Vickrey said.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the high proportion of Cantonese speakers,
particularly in San Francisco, there are only 22 certified
Cantonese interpreters in the state, according to the Judicial
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The Judicial Council is the policy-making body for the state
courts and is in charge of setting pay rates for interpreters in
the criminal courts.
</P>
<P>
   With California's non-English-speaking population growing, the
courts are in dire need of more qualified people to translate court
proceedings for defendants, interpret non-English-speaking
witnesses' testimony for juries, and make sure that lawyers
themselves know what their clients are saying, interpreters and
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not do my job without the services of very qualified,
competent, professional interpreters,'' said Cheryl H. Wallace, a
private criminal defense attorney in San Francisco. ``The system
couldn't function without them, particularly in San Francisco,
where we have so many people of different backgrounds and different
languages.''
</P>
<P>
   The interpreters are independent contractors and not court
staff. Interpreters in the criminal courts earn far less than those
working in the private sector, where they are paid as much as $100
per hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1438EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3201 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-BUMPING-HNS &LR;      07-08 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-BUMPING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AIR PASSENGERS GETTING LEFT BEHIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Overbooked planes and crowded skies mean more
and more passengers are getting left on the ground, involuntarily
bumped from their flights.
</P>
<P>
   During the first quarter of 1999, the number of ticketed
passengers who were denied a flight because of overbooking rose 55
percent compared to the same period last year, according to the
Department of Transportation. The government figures also showed a
general increase in consumer complaints about air travel.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers are bumped when an airline oversells seats to
compensate for no-shows. An average of 10 to 15 percent of ticket
holders never show up at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   More than 17,000 passengers were involuntarily bumped during the
first three months of the year, the government said. Another
282,500 volunteered to take later flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines want to ensure there are no empty seats and the
only way to guarantee that is to overbook the flights. The result
is a lot more people are getting bumped,'' said Brad Hudson, owner
of the Travel Zone agency in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Air Lines had the worst record with 8,144 of its 24.4
million passengers being denied flights because of overbooking,
nearly as many as the nine other major carriers combined.
</P>
<P>
   Based strictly on the number of passengers bumped, United
Airlines came in second with 2,142 of its 18.3 million passengers
involuntarily left at the gates. Southwest Airlines fared only a
little better with 1,938 of its 14.6 million customers being told
they had to wait for another flight.
</P>
<P>
   As required by federal law, airlines have guidelines for
bumping. First, the airlines offer incentives to tempt ticketed
passengers to give up their seats. If that doesn't work, they start
bumping either on a first-come, first-served basis or in a pecking
order with first-class passengers least likely to lose their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overbooking, it's great that it gives the profits to the
airlines but it's hell on the business traveler,'' said Udaya
Kotamarti, a marketing representative for a Washington, D.C.,
telecommunications company who was traveling from San Francisco to
Seattle on United Shuttle Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   His colleague, Amir Dehdashty, had a ticket on an overbooked
United Airlines flight from Washington to San Francisco Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dehdashty said he volunteered to give up his seat for a $300
voucher. But just before the plane took off, United rescinded the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get on the plane and it's all booked up _ someone has taken
my seat and I ended up in the middle seat,'' said Dehdashty, adding
that he had trouble finding room for his carry-on.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta representative acknowledged Wednesday that the airline
had problems correctly forecasting its passenger loads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fully intend to significantly reduce involuntary (bumpings)
to an acceptable level. That is a corporate goal,'' said Delta
spokesman John Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
