A3258 &Cx1f; tad-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-BOX-$ADV11-COX     07-08 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BOX-$ADV11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIMELINE: EUROPE'S HEALTH 'SCARE' CRISIS
 &HT;    With COX-COKE-EUROPE-$ADV11.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., July 11 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGIUM COKE CRISIS: This time the chicken came first
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mid-January _ Farmer in West Flanders region of Belgium
notices that some chicken eggs aren't hatching and chicks are
deformed. Tests show very high presence of cancer-causing dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 21 _ The Belgian agriculture minister is alerted to the
dioxin problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 27 _ The Belgian health minister is informed of the
dioxin problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 27 _ The Belgian agriculture minister informs the public
of dioxin problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 28 _ In the midst of the dioxin food scandal, Luc Van den
Bossche, the deputy prime minister, is named health minister as
well minister for social services and minister for environment. On
the same day, the first recall of chickens and eggs from the
marketplace is ordered.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 31 _ The prime minister is given his first official report
on the dioxin findings.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 8 _ Thirty-nine adolescent students in Bornem, Belgium,
complain of headaches, vomiting and nausea after drinking bottled
Coca-Cola at school. Fifteen are admitted to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 9 _ A Coca-Cola executive in Belgium sends a fax to the
school in Bornem acknowledging that Coke products may have
something to do with the illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 10 _ Eight children are hospitalized in Brugge after
drinking Coke and Fanta soft drinks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 11 _ Coca-Cola officials are summoned to the Health
Ministry for a meeting. Thirteen children are hospitalized in
Harelbeke, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 12-14 _ Belgium establishes a call center for health
complaints about Coca-Cola products that receives 200 calls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 13 _ The government of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene,
in power for seven years, is defeated in national elections.
Dehaene offers to resign a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 14 _ Thirty adolescent students are taken to a hospital
in Ghent after drinking canned Cokes from a machine at a school in
nearby Lochristi. The Belgian government orders all Coca-Cola
products off store shelves and stops production at bottling plants
at Antwerp and Ghent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 15 _ Eight children are reported sick in Kortrijk,
Belgium. Luxembourg bans Coca-Cola products. France closes a
bottling plant in Dunkirk. The Netherlands bans Coca-Cola products
shipped through Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 16 _ Germany bans Coca-Cola produced at the Dunkirk
plant. Coca-Cola issues its first apology to European consumers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 18 _ M. Douglas Ivester, the chairman of Coca-Cola,
arrives in Belgium to personally oversee management of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 22 _ Coca-Cola apologizes to Belgian consumers in
full-page newspaper ads. Ivester meets personally with Dehaene.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 23 _ Van den Bossche reluctantly lifts Belgium's ban
after Coca-Cola agrees to new precautions at bottling plants. The
cause of the illnesses remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 25 _ Other countries lift restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 3 _ Prestigious British medical journal Lancet carries
letter from doctor representing a Belgian government committee
arguing that the symptoms were caused by Mass Sociogenic Illness
related in part to the dioxin crisis. Government testing of Coke
products continues.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
