<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3260 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOOSE-COLLISION-TEX     07-08 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOOSE-COLLISION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF MOOSE AND MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM LEFERINK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After spending parts of three days in Glacier National Park and
seeing only three deer and a couple of chipmunks, the first thing
to cross my mind was, ``Wow, a moose.''
</P>
<P>
   Next I exclaimed, ``Oh, my gosh.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Brenda, my wife, engrossed in yet another novel in the
front passenger seat of the minivan, looked up and said, ``You're
going to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, right there at mile 57.6 of U.S. 2, approximately
20 miles southeast of Libby, Mont., on the second leg of our family
trip in June, it happened: We smashed into the right front shoulder
of a moose. I later learned the moose was ``just a baby,'' though
its head easily towered above the top of the van.
</P>
<P>
   In the rearview mirror, I watched the animal stagger into a
thicket on the side of the highway, while I maneuvered the minivan
to the side of the road just beyond a guardrail.
</P>
<P>
   Our sons, Derek, 11, and Connor, 4, were certainly distracted
from the tape they had been watching, but fortunately, none of us
was injured. I cringed, however, about the damage to the minivan.
Having spent six years living in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan
when I was a teen-ager, I have seen what a deer can do to a
vehicle, much less a moose.
</P>
<P>
   Getting out, I noticed that the left side mirror was dangling
from its support. The driver's door would open only about halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Later, an insurance adjuster would estimate the damage to the
left front fender, driver's door and the left sliding passenger
door at $2,000. The van was still running, however, and a highway
patrol officer who wrote up the accident report said, ``That's the
least amount of damage I've ever seen from a moose.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said there had been eight or nine such accidents in the
area this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Although all of this was comforting, I found myself worrying
about the condition of the moose. We were out of cell phone range
and did not know what to do after we hit it. Of course, the boys
were more than eager to go see the moose.
</P>
<P>
   A few drivers stopped or slowed down to ask about what had
happened, and finally a state highway department truck pulled up. I
walked with the driver to the spot where I saw the moose enter the
thicket. Seeing us approach, the moose tried to get up and get
away, but collapsed. I'll never forget that moose looking me square
in the eye and letting out just an awful moan. I know he's going to
haunt me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have long,'' the highway worker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do have to put him down?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   The highway worker's partner had radioed the Fish &AMP; Wildlife
Department, the state police and a couple of his fellow highway
workers, telling them to bring a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after, a second set of highway workers showed up, but
without a weapon. It was decided that the first worker would hit
the animal over the head with a metal pipe, confident one blow
would kill it.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't watch.
</P>
<P>
   One blow did it.
</P>
<P>
   They pulled the moose to the side of the road just as the Fish
and Wildlife official pulled up.
</P>
<P>
   I had retreated to the van and told the boys I would take them
for a quick glimpse of the moose, so they could see how big it was.
As we approached, the wildlife official had just begun gutting the
animal, not a sight I particularly cared for the boys to see. So I
held them back about 10 yards while one of the highway workers
lifted the moose's head, easily two feet long from snout to the
back.
</P>
<P>
   About that time the state trooper pulled up and asked if we were
OK. One of the pleasant memories of this adventure was the concern
that everyone had for my family's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   As the trooper finished taking notes, the Fish and Wildlife
official pulled away with the moose in the back of his pickup. The
highway workers told me the moose would be taken to the local food
bank.
</P>
<P>
   The highway workers pulled away. The trooper got into his car,
looked out the window and said, ``Be careful, now.''
</P>
<P>
   How prophetic. We drove off and not five miles down the road,
two deer darted across the highway about 20 yards in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you're probably thinking that as a journalist, I must have
documented our experience with a photo or two. Unfortunately, in
all the excitement after hitting the moose, I forgot to pull out
the camera to chronicle what will be remembered as one of the most
memorable moments of this or any of our family vacations.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
