<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3271 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-08 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY: ISLAND OF CHARM IN A SEA OF MUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Major-league baseball can't get to Fenway Park
fast enough. The All-Star Game is close and the event will look
spectacular in Boston, at the sport's most charming venue.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball needs a dose of Fenway, a reprieve from the decidedly
less charming events of recent weeks. The sport should still be
wallowing in the good will created by Misters Sosa and McGwire last
season, but most of it has already been spent.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, the owners have cost overruns. They're out of charm,
and out of money for their new park, the cacophonously named Safeco
Field. After draining $340 million from the public till, the
Mariners want at least another $100 million. They're not asking
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask your kids what they'll think when we (can't) afford
Griffey or Rodriguez,'' one team executive said to a member of the
board that oversaw construction of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When this statement was reported, Ken Griffey Jr. reacted by
saying that he didn't want to be used as a pawn. Who can blame him?
He and Alex Rodriguez both have contracts that expire after next
season. They are worthy of monstrous deals, and Mariners management
is trying to pretend that their contract expectations are the only
reason that the team has to beg for public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the greedy players. That's the easy way to go. But
in Seattle, it might not work. Management botched its dealings with
Randy Johnson last year, creating a malcontented superstar who had
to be traded at a bargain price. The team already used Griffey as
extortionist bait once, to get the original ballpark funding after
the 1995 playoff run. But some franchises have no shame.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Mariners should have drafted pitcher Ben Christensen
out of Wichita State. He, too, has no shame. He was chosen by the
Cubs in the first round, about a month after he threw at a college
opponent's head. Just baseball, right, part of the game? But
Christensen wasn't a modern-day Bob Gibson or Don Drysdale,
claiming every scrap of the plate. When Christensen threw his
beanball, the other player, Evansville's Anthony Molina, was in the
on-deck circle, 30 feet away from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Molina's vision was damaged. He was scheduled for laser surgery.
He has no idea whether he can play baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen faces a lawsuit for his actions, but the Cubs have
already tacitly condoned his behavior by taking him with the 26th
pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, a lot of fans in Chicago have made it clear
that they disapprove of the decision. Christensen appeared at a
news conference two weeks ago to explain himself. All he could say
was that it was an accident, even though he had already said that
his college coaches trained him to go head-hunting in exactly that
manner.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have pleaded for the fans and the media to give
Christensen a second chance. But, as a first-round draft choice, he
seems to have lost not a single perk. Maybe he was drafted lower
than he might have been before the beaning, but the first round
looks like an unmitigated reward. If Darryl Strawberry could spend
time rehabbing his image in the Northern League, why couldn't
Christensen? And for all of Strawberry's misdeeds, he never
committed a grotesque act of violence on the field.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, even Juan Gonzalez's prima donna snit seems mild.
Peeved that he finished fifth in the All-Star voting among American
League outfielders, Gonzalez said he didn't want to be a reserve.
So Joe Torre, the AL manager, obliged by not picking him.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has been criticized for letting the fans down, which is
only partly true. After all, if the fans really wanted him to be an
All-Star, they would have voted him into the top three. Instead,
the folks in Cleveland went berserk at the ballot box and placed
all three of their starters ahead of Gonzalez, a two-time MVP who
is having another spectacular season.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez protested too much. He could have bailed out
discreetly, saying simply that he wanted to rest his body, a
reasonable view. Or he could have just gone to Fenway, just to
enjoy a national spectacle in the world's greatest ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once everyone is in Boston for the game, the old
yard's short comings will be placed prominently on display _ the
cramped aisles, the narrow seats, limited bathrooms, the woeful
dearth of luxury boxes. The Red Sox want a new park, a near-replica
of the beloved and cursed Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, they'll be telling their fans: ``If we'd had proper
luxury boxes in here 80 years ago, we might not have traded that
kid named Ruth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
