<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3283 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-COPLAND11-COX     07-08 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-COPLAND11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Copland bio long on facts, short on editing
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not quite a decade after Aaron Copland's death comes a
definitive biography of America's most important composer. Howard
Pollack, a musicologist at the University of Houston, sets the
standard for years to come with ``Aaron Copland: The Life and Work
of an Uncommon Man.'' But as decent and thorough as it is, no one
but a dedicated musical scholar would want to wade through almost
700 pages _ 556 of which are text, and rather routine text at that.
</P>
<P>
   Copland was born in 1900, the son of Russian Jewish immigrants
(original name: Kaplan) who accepted his musical ambitions
politely; his was not the struggle of a passionate artist with a
stern and materialistic father. But there was an artistic gene
somewhere in the family pool: Copland's cousin was Harold Clurman,
the brilliant director who founded the Group Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Once past a rather routine apprenticeship, which included three
years of study with Nadia Boulanger in Paris, Copland became one of
the few American composers to make a living from composition. He
wasn't a university teacher like Walter Piston or a
composer-performer like Philip Glass (though in later years he
became a proficient conductor) but cobbled together a living from
commissions, book reviews and essays, lectures, books based on the
lectures, teaching the occasional course or tutoring the occasional
younger composer, and various odd projects such as State Department
tours to promote American music.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his life was singularly without drama. A discreet
homosexual, Copland carried on his affairs quietly and ended them
without rancor. His sole controversial gesture seems to have been
taking a leftist political stance in the '30s. The House
Un-American Activities Committee took him to task for it during the
paranoid '50s, but Copland emerged from the inquisition with his
musical reputation intact and without betraying his friends or his
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The biography recognizes that the events of his life are
secondary to the music he produced. It was Copland who placed
American music on the map with works including ``Appalachian
Spring,'' ``Rodeo,'' ``El Salon Mexico'' and Symphony No. 3, which
incorporates the ``Fanfare for the Common Man'' (hence the book's
title).
</P>
<P>
   Pollack sensibly weaves together a thematic and a chronological
approach. Using the biographical facts as a spine, he'll insert a
chapter on, for instance, ``Copland and His Peers,'' a
well-supported discussion of Copland's lifelong championship of
musical colleagues through avenues such as the League of Composers,
essays and concert reviews in Music &AMP; Letters magazine, the
Copland-Sessions concerts and the Berkshire Music Center in
Massachusetts, to which he brought composers from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack also explores such influences as jazz, Jewish religious
and secular music, Latin American music, and 12-tone and other
20th-century musical movements on the composer's work. (Copland was
a barely observant Jew, but the klezmer colorations of many pieces,
and even a shofar call or two, assert that the Old Country left its
mark.) Some of these observations are readily accessible to any
reader, some only to a music professional, but all would be helped
by a listening guide for each topic.
</P>
<P>
   Musical discussion is always intelligent but often on far too
technical a plane for the general reader. And these chapters cry
out for musical examples. This is inexcusable for a quality
publication. At one time, musical excerpts were expensive to
engrave, but now that music notation programs are available on
computer, there's no excuse for the publisher of a major musical
biography to cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   The book has many pleasures, among them the threads that weave
so many great artists into the fabric of Copland's life. The
composers range from Leonard Bernstein and Marc Blitzstein to
Israel Citkowitz, Harold Shapero, Bernard Herrmann (who composed
serious music in addition to the scores to Alfred Hitchcock's
films) and Ingolf Dahl, among others. Most are not household names,
but they wrote a lot of useful work, and it's interesting to see
how they peopled the American musical landscape from 1930 to about
1965.
</P>
<P>
   If only Pollack were a livelier writer! He manages to make even
Copland's sex life dull. The biography may be intended primarily
for scholars, but with a little effort and a better editor it could
be enjoyed by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGRAPHY
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Copland: The Life and Work of an Uncommon Man.
</P>
<P>
   By Howard Pollack. Henry Holt. $37.50. 690 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A thorough biography that needs to get a life.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green is classical music and dance critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
