<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE11-COX     07-08 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The presidency and `Shadow' of Watergate
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 11.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Shadow: Five Presidents and the Legacy of Watergate. By Bob
Woodward. Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, in an interview on CBS with Dan Rather, the only
president in this century to be impeached by the House of
Representatives confessed his human fallibility and said he did not
regard impeachment ``as some great badge of shame.'' The U.S.
Senate had acquitted President Clinton of the House's charges, and
now, in speaking with Rather, he seemed relieved he could put
behind him the events that had come at last to a political
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, as Bob Woodward argues in the epilogue of his new
book, Clinton's words were directed more to the future than to past
or present. The disgraced president, Woodward writes, ``had set out
to drive his impeachment from the first paragraph of his obituary.
Somehow he would remove the shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Shadow,'' Woodward sets out to exhume long-dead
presidential scandals and perform a final autopsy on one that many
are eager to bury, others to keep on life support. The common
thread in all _ from Gerald Ford to Bill Clinton, with Jimmy
Carter, Ronald Reagan and George Bush in between _ is denial
accompanied by coverup, and Woodward, for one, is astonished that
American presidents do not learn from the mistakes of their
predecessors:
</P>
<P>
   ``After Watergate, I never expected another impeachment
investigation of a president in my lifetime, let alone an actual
impeachment and a Senate trial. (Richard) Nixon's successors, I
thought, would recognize the price of scandal and learn the two
fundamental lessons of Watergate. First, if there is questionable
activity, release the facts, whatever they are, as early and
completely as possible. Second, do not allow outside inquiries,
whether conducted by prosecutors, congressmen or reporters, to
harden into a permanent state of suspicion and warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporting based on anonymous sources
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of all these post-mortems is the interview, whose
subject is usually anonymous. In a perceptive New Yorker article,
Nicholas Lemann, who acknowledges professional debts, writes that
Woodward's reporting technique depends on scenes presented
firsthand. ``In an omniscient voice,'' Lemann writes, ``he offers
an account of the meeting at which the deal went down as if he had
been there, though he hadn't.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but the problem in a book like ``Shadow'' is that
the degree of scandal and impropriety varies widely from president
to president. The reticence of one is not the dishonesty of
another. Ford, Woodward believes, did the right thing in granting
Nixon a pardon, but then cast himself in doubt by refusing to
disclose details of an agreement with his predecessor. Reagan lied
about Iran-Contra _ Deep Throat here is clearly former Secretary of
State George Shultz _ and then, in depositions given to independent
prosecutor Lawrence Walsh, sank into a haze of not remembering.
Woodward asks Walsh how Iran-Contra will affect Reagan's name in
history. ``I think it'll be remembered as a nonsordid disregard of
constitutional restraints,'' Walsh tells him. ``I think the
President was wrong, he was defiant, he was deliberate, but he
wasn't dirty.'' Indeed, Walsh _ by Woodward's account _ has a
grudging respect for Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Carter's moral high ground
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's predecessor, Carter, had become president by claiming a
moral high ground lost during Watergate. But he, too, found the
footing slippery once in office. When Bert Lance, his budget
director, was accused of corruption, Carter told reporters, ``My
faith in the character and competence of Bert Lance has been
reconfirmed.'' Soon after, Carter was asking for Lance's
resignation. A claim to a higher morality, Carter acknowledged,
``helped me get elected, but it also came back to haunt me later
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter was not a president for whom Woodward has great
admiration. He may not have engaged in sex with White House interns
or conspired to violate the Constitution, but he ``regularly broke
his most basic promise when he campaigned for the presidency. He
did not always tell the truth.'' Neither did Bush, who knew more
about Iran-Contra than he admitted (``I wasn't really in the
loop'') but was never in danger of impeachment. Like the three who
preceded him, Bush wanted the truth to serve him rather than the
other way around.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Bill Clinton, ``the most self-defeating'' of
modern presidents. When an aide asked that he level with him so he
could best present his case, Clinton said, ``I get the sense you
don't believe me.'' To which the aide replied: ``Mr. President, my
job is to run the pump and the motors, not to fix the hole in the
bottom of the boat.'' It's of only incidental interest that the
aide happened to be Dick Morris, whose own raft would soon sink
when allegations of time with a prostitute were made public.
</P>
<P>
   From all of this, Woodward draws no overarching conclusions
about the presidency, only the familiar one that the office is a
smaller one than Lincoln and Roosevelt occupied. Perhaps the men
are smaller as well. But after Vietnam and Watergate, the
presidency ``has been limited and diminished. Its inner workings
and the behavior of the presidents are fully exposed.'' They've
been exposed despite the efforts of one president after another to
conceal them. They leave office, but the shadow remains.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE09-COX     07-08 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-DIVIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MISSING FATHERS A KEY FACTOR IN 'DIGITAL DIVIDE,' STUDY SHOWS
 &HT;    With DIGITAL-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To a surprising degree, daddies are the drivers
getting children onto the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   While race and income play an enormous role in determining
whether a child has access to the Internet, having a father in the
home appears to be a key factor in computer literacy, according to
a study released Thursday by the U.S. Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   The department's ``Falling Through the Net'' survey shows huge
numbers of Americans are buying or seeking out computers to use the
Internet for sending messages via e-mail, searching for job
information, learning new skills and more.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Internet's popularity is growing in every corner
of the country, access remains very uneven. Money, education and
location are major factors in determining who uses the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the study found that a family living in an urban
area with annual income exceeding $75,000 a year is 20 times more
likely to have Internet access than a rural, low-income family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, education and income are only part of the picture. The
government study found that among families earning $15,000 to
$35,000, more than 32 percent of whites owned computers, but only
19 percent of blacks did. ``Even when holding income constant,
there is still a yawning divide among different races and
origins,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at the statistics suggests that even more than
race, family structure determines whether children get access to
the Internet, either through a computer at home or through one at a
library, school or community center.
</P>
<P>
   A white child growing up in a home with two parents is nearly
twice as likely to have access to the Internet as a white child in
a single-parent household, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   The gap was even greater for African-American children. A child
in a black family is almost four times as likely to have Internet
access as a child in a single-parent black household.
</P>
<P>
   Among single-parent households, those headed by fathers used
computers far more than those headed by women. For example, the
government found that in urban households headed by a man with
children, 21.5 percent used the Internet. But among female-headed
urban households, only 15 percent used the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Other key findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ The families most likely to own a computer are of Asian ethnic
origin, with 55 percent having one in the home. About 47 percent of
whites own computers, but only 23.2 percent of blacks do. About
25.5 percent of Hispanic families own computers.
</P>
<P>
   _ A white child in a low-income two-parent family is three times
more likely to have Internet access as a child in a comparable
black family, and four times more likely than a Hispanic child.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regardless of income, people living in rural areas are lagging
in Internet access. At the lowest income levels, those living in
urban areas are more than twice as likely to have Internet access,
compared with those earning similar amounts in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the third in a series by the government since 1995,
did not suggest specific policies to boost Internet use except to
recommend more online access at community centers, such as schools,
libraries and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference held to release the study,
representatives of Ameritech Corp. and the National Urban League
also announced they will spend $350,000 to build five new Internet
community centers in Aurora, Ill., Cleveland, Detroit, Indianapolis
and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 3Com Corp. said it plans to offer $1 million in
donated equipment and training to 10 cities to help teach students
to be computer network engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
