<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-SERGEANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO AIR FORCE INSTRUCTORS CHARGED WITH SEXUAL MISCONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Two Air Force sergeants face a hearing next month
on charges they had sex with several female students at a Brooks
Air Force Base training center.
</P>
<P>
   Master Sgt. Mark E. Gibson and Tech. Sgt. Apolinar Paul Bernal
have been accused of having ``unprofessional relationships'' with
seven women, all of them recent basic training graduates from
Lackland Air Force Base, Maj. Erin Campbell, a spokeswoman at
Brooks, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bernal, a Gulf War veteran with 17 years in the Air Force, also
reportedly gave advance copies of tests to two women with whom he
is accused of having sex, Campbell said, citing legal documents.
</P>
<P>
   Both sergeants are charged with multiple violations of the
Uniform Code of Military Justice and last year were removed from
their jobs as instructors at the U.S. Air Force School of Aerospace
Medicine at Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has been closed and no other allegations have
been made against instructors at the school, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force is dedicated to providing a safe, professional
environment for its members,'' said Brig. Gen. John Jernigan,
commander of the 311th Human Systems Wing that oversees the school.
``These instructors allegedly used their authority over newly
enlisted trainees to entice them into unprofessional conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, a 15-year veteran, is accused of having sexual
relationships with two women and making sexual overtures to a third
from Oct. 1, 1996, through March 1998. He faces a maximum of 21
years in a military prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Bernal is accused of having sexual relations with two women,
groping a third, and attempting to develop an unprofessional
relationship with a fourth student from January 1997 to May 21,
1998. He could get up to 17 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Both face an Article 32 hearing, similar to a grand jury
investigation, in early August. The Air Force then will determine
if there is enough evidence to proceed with a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said some of the women were students of the
instructors, but did not know how many. She said the trainees are
considered victims and will not be prosecuted for anything they may
have done, including possible cheating on exams.
</P>
<P>
   The women have since left the School of Aerospace Medicine for
other assignments in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said she did not know how the case first came to the
attention of commanders at Brooks. However, Campbell said the Air
Force's Office of Special Investigation began a probe in late May
1998. Bernal was relieved of instruction duties the next month,
while Gibson was relieved in mid-July 1998, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
