<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: VIEWING PIECES OF PALESTINE; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viewing Pieces Of Palestine
</P>
<P>
   Playing himself in his film ``Chronicle of a Disappearance,''
Elia Suleiman is called onto a stage in Jerusalem to explain his
less than obvious methods of moviemaking to an audience of ordinary
citizens, among whom, it is supposed, he will be shooting parts of
``Chronicle of a Disappearance.'' But as he adjusts the microphone
to speak, audio interference develops. A technician darts out to
correct the problem and withdraws. Again Suleiman begins to speak,
but again there is interference. Again the technician scrambles.
After several repetitions of this, the audience begins to lose
interest, reading, making cell phone calls and finally leaving.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what Suleiman was going to say about his movie,
which got good reviews when it was released in 1997 and was issued
last week on videocassette by Fox Lorber. ``Theme and story are
never exactly centered,'' he said the other day from Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In and out of art houses in a flash, films like this usually
present a fuller view of themselves on video. On a structural
level, ``Chronicle of a Disappearance'' is a series of vignettes,
some of them recurring. Whether acting as a suspected political
operative who draws a SWAT team to his apartment or listening to
stories of old Istanbul from Palestinian writer Paha Mohamed Ali,
Suleiman is seen throughout. But, he explained, the film is not
about him. ``It's an invitation to participate through my camera,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Nazareth in 1960, he returns to his homeland after long
periods in Europe and New York. What he finds doesn't make much
sense to him personally or politically. ``I can't tell you what is
going on,'' he said. ``I can only tell you what I see.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first part of the film, set in Nazareth, a woman sits in
her sister's house and cattily rips her family apart in the
nastiest of terms. At a store by the road different pairs of men
stop their car and get out to fight each other, only to be
separated by the shopkeepers and sent on their way again.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Holyland gift shop, full of religious bric-a-brac,
two men endlessly sit and smoke as a rack of postcards turns
squeakily in the breeze. A gangster has his underlings check his
car for a bomb. On the radio, a report from Bosnia says the land is
being partitioned as all sides wear down.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, a Palestinian woman trying to rent an apartment on
the telephone is rebuffed but is complimented on how well she
disguises her accent. Later she reappears as the head of a
surveillance team that does nothing but rush around on her orders,
accomplishing nothing and finally withdrawing. Jerusalem ``is
nothing special,'' she concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, these pieces suggest a question: What does any
of it matter? ``The hopelessness of the politicians and racist and
tribal notions,'' Suleiman said. As for expressing that in his
film, he added: ``Image comes first. After that I try to understand
what I saw. When it comes together, a certain attitude becomes
apparent.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   `A Civil Action'
</P>
<P>
   A self-serving Boston lawyer, Jan Schlichtmann (John Travolta)
at first doesn't see much promise in the case of a group of
citizens whose children have been poisoned by a river. Then he
spies some sudsy water and traces it to a tannery with links to
deep-pocketed corporations. For Schlichtmann that might have
spelled a big pay day in a movie with the standard conspiracy and
environmental ramifications. Instead, Steven Zaillian's film avoids
anything that obvious in, Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``a finely nuanced tale of right, wrong and the gray area in
between.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $107.37. 113 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: July 13.
</P>
<P>
   `Blast From the Past'
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, at the start of the Cuban missile, crisis Calvin Webber
(Christopher Walken) hustles his pregnant wife, Helen (Sissy
Spacek), into his elaborately equipped fall-out shelter. For the
next 35 years they and their son, Adam (Brendan Fraser), labor
under the impression that the superpowers have traded big ones and
they will have to remain entombed until the radioactivity subsides.
By the late '90s Helen has imbibed all the cooking sherry and Adam
would appreciate getting out of Calvin's pastel '50s underworld and
finding a woman. That he does in the person of a tough babe named
Eve (Alicia Silverstone), but ``it's mostly the fallout shelter
notion that makes for the laughs'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. New Line. $104.17. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: July 13.
</P>
<P>
   `Little Voice'
</P>
<P>
   Here is the unlikely story of Jane Horrocks, who gets her own
movie to showcase her astounding talent for mimicking great voices
from Judy Garland's to Marilyn Monroe's. In the film, Little Voice
(Ms. Horrocks) has a blowsy mother (Brenda Blethyn) with a low-life
talent agent for a boyfriend (Michael Caine), altogether the
perfect pair to exploit her vocal gifts to the fullest. They and
Little Voice's soulmate (Ewan McGregor) give a conventional twist
to ``the enchanting notion that beneath the mousiest exterior may
lurk a spectacular diva festival'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Miramax. $104.16. 99 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `She's All That'
</P>
<P>
   In another high school adventure, a standoffish intellectual
type named Laney (Rachael Leigh Cook) is pursued by Zack (Freddie
Prinze Jr.), the star of the senior class. So why would that
happen? Zack, it seems, has been dumped by the school bombshell
(Jodi Lyn O'Keefe) and to retain his image makes a wager that he
can turn the geekiest girl in school into the prom queen. Behind
the plain looks and snappish disposition, of course, Laney is quite
a zinger in a comedy with ``enough glimmerings of originality and
wit to make you wish it were much bolder and funnier than it turns
out to be'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $107.37. 91 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   `WACO: THE RULES OF ENGAGEMENT': William Gazecki's grim
documentary methodically assails the United States government for
its siege of the Branch Davidian sect's compound in Waco, Texas,
and the assault, on April 19, 1993, that left four federal agents
and 76 sect members dead. Maintaining the detached, scholarly tone
of a courtroom inquiry, the film takes the position that the sect
acted in self-defense. Heat-sensitive infrared photography appears
to catch the government firing at the compound from tanks. ``How
persuasive is the evidence?'' Stephen Holden asked in his review in
The New York Times. ``It depends on how much you trust
technological expertise.'' 1997. New Yorker. $29.95. 135 minutes.
No rating.
</P>
<P>
   `DASH AND LILLY': A bad script undermines two strong
performances by Sam Shepard and the fiercely energetic Judy Davis
as Dashiell Hammett and Lillian Hellman, turning their messy,
decades-long affair into something trite primarily, Caryn James
wrote in The Times, so ``the characters can float through pretty
period settings of the '30s, airily dropping names.'' 1999. A&AMP;E.
$19.95. 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF ICHABOD AND MR. TOAD': In a 50-year-old
animated pairing, Washington Irving's ``Legend of Sleepy Hollow,''
sung and narrated by Bing Crosby, and Kenneth Grahame's ``Wind in
the Willows,'' narrated by Basil Rathbone, are presented on the
same videocassette. Toad sells out to weasels, leading to a
conclusion that ``should even get laughs from cynics and realists
well into the age of reason,'' A.H. Weiler wrote in The Times.
1949. $22.99. 68 minutes. G. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
