<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARLINGTON-FILM-REVIEW     07-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARLINGTON-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ARLINGTON ROAD': THINK AGAIN BEFORE BORROWING A CUP OF SUGAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suspect Thy Neighbor was the commandment behind some of the
best, most delectably unnerving films of the 1970s. And with its
strong echoes of paranoid classics like ``The Parallax View'' and
``Rosemary's Baby,'' the crackerjack thriller ``Arlington Road''
keeps that alarmist spirit alive.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into fears much more contemporary than those stirred up
by old staples like witchcraft and assassination plots, the film
dares to suggest that the convivial people in khakis at the
suburban back-yard barbecue could be a lot like Rosemary's
neighbors. Only worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road,'' a major boon for anyone realizing that
there's life beyond the lead-footed summer blockbuster, stars Jeff
Bridges as Michael Faraday, a recently widowed history professor
whose specialty is domestic terrorism. This tight, ingenious second
feature directed by Mark Pellington (``Going All the Way'') and
written by first-time screenwriter Ehren Kruger begins with a
near-hallucinatory encounter, the kind that shows why not all '70s
nostalgia need be of the shagadelic variety.
</P>
<P>
   Driving home along an antiseptic suburban street, Faraday
happens upon a wounded boy. After racing to the hospital, he finds
out that the boy is his immediate neighbor on Arlington Road, a
name that deliberately resonates with thoughts of patriotism and a
national cemetery. The boy's wholesome-looking parents, Oliver and
Cheryl Lang, are effusively grateful, explaining that ``a failed
rocketry experiment'' injured their son.
</P>
<P>
   The release of ``Arlington Road'' was tactfully postponed after
the Columbine High School shootings, since this is a film in which
schoolboys play with explosives casually, and their parents do it
for real.
</P>
<P>
   The Langs, played to smiling, sinister perfection by Tim Robbins
and Joan Cusack, begin treating Faraday like a newfound best
friend. And even in a movie whose characters make a back-patting
show of bonhomie and address one another as ``neighbor,'' their
blandishments seem excessive. But Faraday seems weary and lonely,
even though he lives with a former student (played by Hope Davis,
in a film with an especially high-caliber cast). So he lets himself
grow close to the over-eager Langs.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ``Arlington Road'' starts innocently enough. But it has
delved into a terrorist network as malevolent as anything in
``American History X'' by the time it's over. Methodically building
its tension, the film watches Faraday grow suspicious about
Robbins' diabolically pleasant Lang and start wondering who Lang is
and where he came from.
</P>
<P>
   It also ponders the scheme that destroyed a government office
building like the one in Oklahoma City and considers how convenient
it is to have a disgruntled Timothy McVeigh-like individual to
blame for such an elaborate crime. In his classroom, Faraday
eloquently doubts whether knowing the names of terrorists who
supposedly acted alone should make Americans sleep any more easily.
</P>
<P>
   The film, well paced and cleverly constructed as it builds to
one last killer twist, becomes a battle of nerves between Faraday
and Lang. It also becomes a splendid showcase for two exceptionally
commanding actors as their characters square off.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from slouching hilariously through ``The Big Lebowski,''
Bridges begins by playing Faraday as a disheartened, grieving man,
then lets him spring back to life on a whiff of galvanizing
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins plays Lang with such expert duplicity and such a wary,
glittering gaze that the character is capable of keeping endless
tricks up his figurative sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Planted loyally by his side, Ms. Cusack's squeaky-clean Cheryl
makes the blood run even colder.
</P>
<P>
   While this film's conception of a terrorist threat is apparent
early on, its strength lies in a string of ingenious little
surprises, and in an overall deviousness that doesn't show until
the story is over, unless you happen to have ``The Parallax View''
clearly in mind. If the coincidences within ``Arlington Road'' are
sometimes a shade too convenient, the material is so vividly
fleshed out that that's hard to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Alert to real underground terrorist activities like those it
depicts, ``Arlington Road'' turns a sharp eye on the disparity
between carefully colorless surfaces and murderous secrets. When it
contrasts a fiery argument between Lang and Faraday with the flat,
impersonal backdrop of a plain wooden fence and the roof next door,
it starkly illustrates the jarring dissonance that can keep an
audience on edge, or a nation stunned by seemingly inexplicable
acts of vengeful fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road'' makes imaginative use of its unremarkable
settings, thanks to behind-the-scenes personnel not usually
associated with straight-arrow Americana. The score by Angelo
Badalamenti is suitably spooky; the taut editing is by Conrad Buff,
who edited the best of James Cameron's films and whose work won an
Oscar for ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bukowski's cinematography is crisp yet eerie, and Therese
DePrez, whose production-design credits include ``I Shot Andy
Warhol'' and ``Living in Oblivion,'' knows how to invest bland
settings with quiet malaise. Ms. DePrez is also the production
designer for ``Summer of Sam,'' another film worth leaving the
megahits to see.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ARLINGTON ROAD'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Mark Pellington; written by Ehren Kruger; director
of photography, Bobby Bukowski; edited by Conrad Buff; music by
Angelo Badalamenti, with additional music by TomandAndy; production
designer, Therese DePrez; produced by Peter Samuelson, Tom Gorai
and Marc Samuelson; released by Screen Gems.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 117 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: ``Arlington Road'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and
scattered, mostly implicit violence.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Jeff Bridges (Michael Faraday), Tim Robbins (Oliver Lang),
Joan Cusack (Cheryl Lang), Hope Davis (Brooke Wolfe), Robert
Gossett (FBI Agent Whit Carver), Mason Gamble (Brady Lang), Spencer
Treat Clark (Grant Faraday) and Stanley Anderson (Dr. Archer
Scobee).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
