outside under the canopy on one rainy day, and Hutto's voice is
raspy, sore from several days of negotiating for the release of an
American worker _ ``a big guy from Alabama.''
 &HT;    It seems he took his boat up a canal near the oil station in
Kula to check on a well when half a dozen young men jumped him. The
worker spent nine days in the mangrove swamp with his captors
pointing guns at his head. After a $25,000 ransom is paid, the
Alabama man is released.
 &HT;    ``I don't know how we'll operate,'' Okoaye says, worried that
such incidents will rise under the new civilian government. ``I
don't know, because security is going to be a big problem.'' Hutto
rubs his forefinger and thumb together.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes it doesn't go far enough, money alone,'' Okoaye
says.
 &HT;    ``Yeah, spend more money?''
 &HT;    ``Spend more money.''
 &HT;    ``Keep them quiet? Make them happy?''
 &HT;    ``Yup.''
 &HT;     (Norimitsu Onishi is the West Africa bureau chief of The New
York Times.) 
