<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESTRUCTION-THEATER-R     07-08 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESTRUCTION-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DAYS BEFORE: DEATH, DESTRUCTION AND DETROIT III': LABYRINTH OF
DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At his best, Robert Wilson can reduce you to the
state of a spaced-out, slack-jawed teen-ager, the sort who attends
midnight shows of Disney's ``Fantasia'' with an attitude of
religious awe. ``Oh, wow,'' you think, as Wilson summons yet
another phantasmal image that seems to have stepped right out of
your own subconscious. ``How incredibly cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you might attempt to formulate that reaction in loftier
terms, something more coherent and intellectual. But description,
for the most part, doesn't really become Wilson's work, and rigid
analysis even less.
</P>
<P>
   Try, for example, defining one of the more spectacular tableaux
in ``The Days Before: Death, Destruction and Detroit III,'' the new
Wilson extravaganza that runs at the New York State Theater through
Sunday as part of Lincoln Center Festival '99, and you may start to
feel embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this floating, long-bodied blue angel with a deer's
head,'' you say, ``and it has a sash that turns out to be a scroll,
which keeps unwinding into the hands of this rooster. Now the way I
see it, the angel represents the limitations of religious
knowledge, because . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``Oh, wow'' is probably as appropriate a response as
you could come up with, a tribute to a director who creates a
language of the stage that is as elusive as it is distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson addicts, a small but very chic cadre of esthetes, who are
in search of a new fix of this sense-scrambling imagery won't go
home feeling starved from his latest production, which is only the
second to have its world premiere in New York in the last two
decades. But they're also unlikely to feel entirely satisfied with
the alternately ravishing and tedious ``Days Before,'' which Wilson
has fashioned as a culture-blending meditation on visions of the
apocalypse throughout history.
</P>
<P>
   The intermissionless show, which lasts an hour and 45 minutes,
only occasionally achieves the hypnotic, dreamlike flow that was so
beguilingly realized in Wilson's masterpiece, ``Einstein on the
Beach,'' the 1976 opera he created with composer Philip Glass.
There's a jagged, disjunctive feeling to ``The Days Before'' that
causes you to step back and assess coolly. Wilson's intuitive work,
which he insists is not intellectual, suffers from this kind of
scrutiny; what you want it to do is sweep you away.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem here is in Wilson's use of a spoken text,
largely taken from ``The Island of the Day Before,'' Umberto Eco's
1995 novel about a 17th-century shipwreck survivor, and read aloud
by no less a personage than Fiona Shaw, the great Irish actress who
so memorably brought T.S. Eliot's ``Wasteland'' to theatrical life
several seasons ago. (Ms. Shaw is intermittently assisted by an
eclectic trio of actors who suggest the basis for a high-culture
``Hollywood Squares'': Isabella Rossellini, Tony Randall and Jeremy
Geidt.)
</P>
<P>
   Eco's novel is thick with labyrinthine reflections on time and
creation, eternity and decay, the subjectivity of human perception
and the ways we try to mark and measure an eternally mutable world.
Since these are all implicit themes of Wilson's work, the choice of
``Island'' would seem perfectly appropriate. But while the book may
be driven by metaphor and semiotic gamesmanship, it also has a
linear logic and explanatory clearness that are the opposite of
Wilson's usual style, which refuses to explain anything.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is of course aware of this contrast and is making
deliberate use of it. ``His text, his ideas are very dense, like a
rock,'' Wilson said of Eco in a recent interview. ``I put some
space around them. And the text weighs down my ideas, keeps them
from flying up.''
</P>
<P>
   But that anchor is too heavy by half. Ms. Shaw is a commanding
reader, and her resonant voice is heavily amplified here. And since
what she, and her fellow narrators, are saying seems to bear some
thematic relation to the airier images onstage, you take Eco's
words more literally than you should, as though they provided an
annotative key to Wilson's mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   This tends to flatten things, to shrink Wilson's radiant,
shifting tableaux to the status of visual aids in a lecture. If
you're not careful, you wind up giving more attention to what is
said than to what you see, which is self-defeating in Wilson's
world. After all, this director has always insisted that, in his
own words, ``the `visual book' doesn't have to be subservient to
what you hear.'' Yet in ``The Days Before,'' it often is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This is especially unfortunate, since much of Wilson's staging
is so ineffably eloquent on its own terms. Working with an ensemble
of more than 20 performers, and carefully mixing ritualized,
Kabuki-style motion (the choreography is by Suzushi Hanayagi) with
projected film and gorgeous, astral lighting (overseen by
Christopher Kondek and A.J. Weissbard, respectively), he creates a
gallery of melting pictures drawn by the grammar of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these sequences are unqualified stunners, both
exquisite and deeply disturbing. In one, the assassination of the
Romanovs is enacted in grimly serene pantomime while photographs of
faces of the real royal family are projected onto transparent
scrims that undulate plaintively in midair.
</P>
<P>
   In another, a child, with what looks like a porcelain Bhudda's
head, peers through an immense white telescope at a tiny meteor
suspended from a pole. Behind her, on those ever-present,
ever-shifting rectangular scrims, is a black-and-white film showing
a landscape as seen from a moving train. Behind that, a light show
conjures a comet streaking through a multicolored sky. These images
coalesce into a magic visual poem of cosmic physics and our limited
perception of the forces that govern the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also makes as keen a use of basic human physiognomy as
any director working now. He can induce appreciative gasps simply
by having a literal giant of a man fully extend his arms. A
gnarled, bearded, gnomelike man, so frail-looking you expect him to
break, suddenly erupts into transporting laughter. And you are
always aware of the contrasts in the sizes and shapes of the people
onstage, who suggest a multiplicity of forms of being and, by
extension, seeing.
</P>
<P>
   The music, by Ryuichi Sakamoto, is correspondingly eclectic,
segueing between sappy New Age chords to ominous percussive thunder
to 1970s-style synthesizer disco vamps, which offer some witty and
welcome relief from the governing solemnity. So does the unexpected
deconstruction of Barry Manilow's hit song ``Mandy'' by autistic
poet Christopher Knowles. Tibetan singer Dadon Dawadolma introduces
the evening with a luminous chant that seems to keep expanding in
your ears.
</P>
<P>
   And in the evening's most haunting convergence of sound and
image, Semiha Berksoy, a 90-year-old Turkish opera singer, is
pushed across the stage on a red divan, looking like a Baroque-age
Norma Desmond, while she raspingly warbles along with Isolde's
``Liebestod.'' ``Sic transit gloria mundi,'' the vignette seems to
say. But it also speaks touchingly of the tenacity of the artistic
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the scenes in ``Days Before,'' especially those
featuring headless torsos and seemingly empty suits of clothes that
come to life, bring to mind the paintings of Magritte, de Chirico
and Dali. Others, which prominently display chairs and lighting
fixtures of Wilson's design, suggest a furniture showroom in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The effect can be studiedly, glacially glamorous, as though
Wilson were auditioning to be the new editor of Harper's Bazaar.
And it's easy to see why the director, whose work is more
celebrated in Europe than in the United States, has always
attracted the rich and fashionable as fans and patrons.
</P>
<P>
   This quality of chic has traditionally been a part of Wilson's
cachet, but often the mise-en-scene is so enthralling that you
don't stop to isolate its individual elements. With ``Days
Before,'' you find yourself growing impatient with such familiar
Wilsonian touches as stately slow-motion choreography and silent
screams.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine who saw the production with me, a Wilson
admirer and an abstract painter with a high tolerance for the
obscure, said she sometimes felt as though she were back in high
school math class, waiting for the bell to ring. She's right; it's
hard to avoid feeling that way. But she was also right when she
said that this restlessness was a price worth paying for the
evening's most resplendent effects.
</P>
<P>
   When everything meshes in a Wilson vignette, there is a
transcendent sense of both the baffling chaos of existence and the
innate beauty of the forms we instinctively impose upon it. ``The
Days Before'' may be about the apocalypse, but it is also oddly
comforting. Would that the world could end as Wilson envisions it,
not with a bang but with a celestial shimmer.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DAYS BEFORE: Death, Destruction and Detroit III'
</P>
<P>
   Conceived, designed and directed by Robert Wilson; music by
Ryuichi Sakamoto; text from ``The Island of the Day Before'' by
Umberto Eco and ``Tone Poems'' by Christopher Knowles; choreography
by Suzushi Hanayagi; costumes and makeup by Jacques Reynaud;
lighting by A.J. Weissbard; sets and images by Peter Bottazzi;
sound by Peter Cerone; video by Christopher Kondek; props by Hans
Thiemann. Presented by Lincoln Center Festival '99, Nigel Redden,
director. At the New York State Theater, Lincoln Center, Manhattan.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Fiona Shaw, Jeremy Geidt, Tony Randall, Isabella
Rossellini, Semiha Berksoy, Dadon Dawadolma, Arthur Beatty, Elettra
Bottazzi, Francis Bouc, Fritzi Haberlandt, Meg Harper, Makram
Hamdan, Marianna Kavallieratos, Christopher Knowles, Restu
Kusumaningrum, Keith McDermott, Brian Nishii, Fernando Nogueira,
Maria Pessino, Arco Renz, Elisabetta Rosso, Ines Somellera, Carlos
Soto and Tassy Thompson.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
