<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV WEEKEND: CHRIS ROCK FAMILY VALUES ON HBO; HOLLYWOOD FAMILY
SITCOM ON WB 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes follow Chris Rock item; air time given
is Eastern)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Rock is making Littleton jokes. What's wrong with ``these
white kids shooting up schools?'' he asks, two and a half months
after the massacre in Colorado that left 14 students and a teacher
dead. And why, he wonders, are people looking for social ills that
caused it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to crazy?'' says Rock. ``You can't be crazy
no more?'' Pretty soon, he predicts, ``you're going to have little
white kids saying, `I want to go to a black school _ where it's
safe.'''
</P>
<P>
   Great comedy is about going where no one else dares to tread and
making it work. Chris Rock's third HBO stand-up special, ``Chris
Rock: Bigger and Blacker'' (Saturday at 11:15 p.m.), is great
comedy. Rock hits the stage running, and his structure is flawless;
just as the laughter is dying down after a successful punch line,
he throws in a post-punch that refers back to some earlier riff
(Robitussin and ``La Vida Loca'' are used prominently in this way)
and keeps it going.
</P>
<P>
   Rock may use a lot of four-letter words, but his humor has a
real family-values morality at its core. He's in serious favor of
the old-fashioned two-parent family, for instance, because children
who grow up without fathers are headed for trouble, he says. ``If
the kid calls his grandmama Mommy and his mama Pam, he going to
jail,'' says Rock. So his family needn't bother with saving up
college funds, because ``that money's going to Johnnie Cochran.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Rock even has something new to say about the Monica
Lewinsky scandal. It all comes down to a man lying about sex so his
wife wouldn't find out, he explains. ``Do you need a Supreme Court
for that one? Is that illegal? You could have took that one to the
People's Court!'' And what, Rock asks, was wrong with the
president's asking a friend to help Ms. Lewinsky get a job? ``After
what she did for him, the  &UR; least &LR;  he could do is give her a
recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock is not happy with the tax system, particularly Social
Security. ``You don't get the money till you're 65; meanwhile, the
average black man dies at 54,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't live that long,'' he adds a little later.
``Hypertension, high blood pressure, NYPD _ something'll get you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock also complains about the state of medical research, makes
suggestions for better marriages, clears up the question of black
anti-Semitism (``We don't hate Jews. We hate all white people.'')
and makes a case against any form of racism or intolerance
(``Whoever you hate will end up in your family'').
</P>
<P>
   His comments on gun control are a little worrisome to the white
liberal mind-set (but his bullet-control idea sounds workable) and
no good feminist can sit back and let a stand-up comic lay the
blame for Monicagate at Hillary Rodham Clinton's bedroom door, but
having a couple of offenses in an hour of dead-on comic
observations isn't half-bad.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CHRIS ROCK: Bigger and Blacker'
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office, Saturday at 11:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Chris Rock; Rock, Michael Rotenberg and Sandy
Chanley, executive producers; Keith Truesdell, director; Tom Bull,
producer; Monteria Ivey, announcer.  &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   `Movie Stars'
</P>
<P>
   Sunday and Monday, 9 p.m., WB
</P>
<P>
   How can you not like a series in which a child runs away from
home by hijacking Mom's limo and checking into Chateau Marmont?
Unfortunately, you can, if the rest of the situations are trite and
have no connection with the concept.
</P>
<P>
   In WB's new series about the home life of Hollywood royalty,
Harry Hamlin is appealing as Reese Hardin, action film star, and
Jennifer Grant (daughter of Cary and of Dyan Cannon) is likable as
his wife, Jacey Wyatt, an equally big star. They live in Malibu
with their adorable children, Apache and Moonglow. A wacky brother
and a levelheaded mother pop in and out. Lori, Reese's 16-year-old
daughter from a previous marriage, has just arrived to live with
them, and Marnette Patterson has apparently been instructed to play
her as Christina Applegate's trampy character in ``Married . . .
With Children.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking in at a world like this could be fun _ Dad has dinner at
Morton's, next weekend's children's birthday party is at Mel
Gibson's house, and Robin Williams is driving the car pool _ but
name dropping alone isn't comedy. The first two episodes have a few
funny, promising lines, but overall the plots and the
characterization fall flat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
