<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     07-08 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: PROPS TAKE OFF IN INTERNET SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Movie memorabilia often takes on a life of its own.
Fans of old films will pay huge sums for items like the ruby
slippers Judy Garland wore as Dorothy in ``The Wizard of Oz'' or
wait in long lines to view gowns worn in classic movies or even the
cars that stars once drove.
</P>
<P>
   But New Line Cinema has discovered, to its surprise and delight,
that in today's speeded-up world, moviegoers no longer wait a
generation to covet props from films. They want them now and are
willing to pay big bucks to get them.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, New Line announced that it was opening a Web site
(auction.newline.com), in conjunction with America Online, through
which it would auction props from some of its more successful
movies, from the current rage, ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me,'' starring Mike Myers, to ``Boogie Nights'' and ``Dumb and
Dumber.'' The venture was regarded as much as anything as just
another form of promotion, to generate awareness of the company and
its films.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just hoped it would create a little excitement,'' said Jim
Rosenthal, the company's executive vice president for business
development.
</P>
<P>
   But the response has taken the company by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea where it would go when we started this,''
Rosenthal said. ``But after the first day the response was such I
said, `We have to put more stuff out there.' I have staff going
through the warehouse now.''
</P>
<P>
   The red, white and blue Corvette (a 1965 model) driven by
Felicity Shagwell in the latest ``Austin Powers'' film was bid up
to $106,999. The silver outfit worn in the movie by Mini Me has
been bid up to $3,600. Up next is his baby baby grand piano. Here's
one for real film buffs: the glass beaker, shaped like a teapot,
that held a stool sample has been bid to more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we're responding to consumer demand,'' Rosenthal
said. ``The truth is I had no idea how much this stuff was worth.''
</P>
<P>
   The major Hollywood studios all have warehouses jammed with
props, costumes and sets from their movies. Most of these items
gather dust, get reused and maybe, just maybe, find a buyer down
the road. What is striking about New Line's unexpected success
selling some of its recent props is that the most popular items
come from slightly daffy comedies that appealed largely to a
younger and very loyal audience.
</P>
<P>
   The company will be selling some fuzzy boots worn by Jim Carrey
in ``Dumb and Dumber,'' the roller skates worn by a main character
in ``Boogie Nights,'' as well as one of the western outfits worn by
another character, Buck. A dress worn by Alicia Silverstone in
``Blast From the Past'' is due up soon, as well as the television
repair kit used by Don Knott's character in ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   There will also be items used in ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Blade,''
``Rush Hour'' and ``Spawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think movies have become such a part of popular culture
that people crave these things,'' Rosenthal said. ``The Internet
has changed all the rules and brought so many people to the
auctions.''
</P>
<P>
   mafia.com? Yup
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bonanno has led what he describes as a generally good life,
notwithstanding the 11 years he spent behind bars for conspiracy,
wire fraud and things like that. His father is the famous mob boss,
Joseph Bonanno, and he has acknowledged that he, too, became a
``made'' member of the Sicilian Mafia before moving on to other
pursuits, which have ranged from writing the book ``Bound by
Honor'' to movies.
</P>
<P>
   He has produced the forthcoming Showtime film ``Bonanno: A
Godfather's Story,'' largely about his father. But, hey, it's the
'90s, and so in addition to the confessional film, Bonanno is
developing a Web site that he said would be called mafia.com. It is
to be devoted to describing the mob as he would like it to be seen,
honor bound and businesslike.
</P>
<P>
   The Showtime film is a two-part mini-series that will run
starting July 25. It stars Martin Landau, Edward James Olmos and
Patti LuPone, among others, and was directed by Michel Poulette.
</P>
<P>
   Bonanno, 66, perhaps the only movie producer to have declared
himself a mafioso to produce a movie, says this is a tale of
self-justification; his mob, he says, is the good mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to set aside the misconceptions,'' Bonanno said.
``People just don't understand the life style. The statement I want
to make is there's another side to the story. Movies like `Casino'
or `Goodfellas,' using a baseball bat or making an appointment to
kill somebody, it's not a true picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Sure, there were acts of violence. But for every
one, there were 10,000 peaceful accommodations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonanno said the old Mafia essentially collapsed in the early
1960s. It is that old Mafia that he defends as trustworthy, at
least to its friends. Today, he added, the mob hews to none of the
old principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not defending the life style of what is known as the Mafia
today,'' he said. ``I am defending a tradition of what is right and
what is wrong. I am defending, pardon the expression, family
values. But what happened to the rest of the country happened to
us, too.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his movie, the government spins out of control, too. For
instance, he claims that John F. Kennedy was elected president with
the Mafia's explicit help, and he adds that he believes Kennedy was
murdered by a mobster, not by Lee Harvey Oswald.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Showtime film is completed, Bonanno said, he
expects to focus on producing other kinds of movies. He said he was
considering a romantic comedy and, his dream, a western. The
transition to this new world of filmmaking, he added, has been
easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life I've been in the people business,'' Bonanno said.
``This is no different.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Fogies
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has embraced youth culture in recent years with a zest
rarely seen before. Movies are increasingly aimed at young
audiences (read: audiences that see movies over and over, helping
the box office) and they are often made by young filmmakers with
sensibilities somewhere between MTV and ``Natural Born Killers.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a generation of people in their 20s has been brought up
making movies that essentially take little seriously, are often
intensely violent or take remorseless violence as a fundamental
element of movies, embrace scatological humor and love the dark
thrills of life on the lam.
</P>
<P>
   Marni Banack, a 26-year-old Canadian, says she is not a fan of
that school. She has directed a small film, produced by J.B. Sugar,
that is noteworthy, if for nothing else, as an old-fashioned bit of
storytelling with an O. Henry twist. In other words, it is about
plot and character. And this year it won a student Academy Award in
the narrative category.
</P>
<P>
   The film, ``John,'' which is 21 minutes long, is quiet and
understated, focusing on an evening in the life of John, a
soft-spoken gentleman who works as a bathroom attendant at an
Italian restaurant. The camera almost never leaves the men's room.
Not only is there no violence; there's no sex either.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences offers, in
addition to its grand Oscars, awards to aspiring student filmmakers
every year. Ms. Banack took the gold medal with Sugar several weeks
ago for their drama.
</P>
<P>
   In the past the award has been won by John Lasseter, Robert
Zemeckis and Spike Lee. Ms. Banack and Sugar recently graduated
from the American Film Institute's master's program and have wasted
no time throwing themselves into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar, with his own production company and a cellular phone,
said he already had two feature film projects in the works. Ms.
Banack was reached in Vancouver, where she has just completed
directing an episode in the Disney Channel drama ``So Weird,'' a
fairly traditional television suspense story except that much of it
involves the Internet. Sugar's father, Larry, is the show's
executive producer, which Ms. Banack admitted helped her land the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Banack said she saw almost every movie made these days and
was a fan of many styles, but she said she was tired of gratuitous
violence and dark moodiness as a replacement for character
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence, guns, drugs, blood, all of those things are typical
of student productions,'' Ms. Banack said. ``My interest absolutely
doesn't lie in those kind of action stories. Those things can just
be gimmicks.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``When people hear you're a young filmmaker, they
immediately think, like, edgy. I don't think I'm edgy right now. I
think I'm an old soul a little bit. But I think people like to see
stories well told, you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
