<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Cooperstown, N.Y.) _ First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton signals an independent course in her fledgling bid for the
U.S. Senate. She downplays her husband's proposed patients' bill of
rights legislation, calls for a more aggressive effort than his
plan to drive down drug costs and voices a strong commitment to
Jerusalem as the capital of Israel. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Seattle) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush campaigns in
Washington state, urging the protection of salmon, but not at the
expense of dams. The Republican presidential candidate also plans
to tour a computer center. By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-GOP (Washington) _ Some 500 college Republicans begin
their national convention here with all GOP presidential candidates
except George W. Bush on hand to court their votes and youthful
campaign energy. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Los Angeles) _ President Clinton visits Anaheim
and the community of Watts to make the case for private companies
to help disadvantaged young people gain the skills they need for
high-tech jobs in the new millennium. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE (Houston) _ NASA sets a launch date for the Chandra
X-ray observatory, which will be carried aboard the space shuttle.
The flight features the first command by a woman, veteran astronaut
Eileen Collins, and will likely lift off July 19. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Phoeniz, Ariz.) _ Scott Elarton will make his second
start of the season for the Houston Astros as the team wraps up a
three-game road series against Arizona. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS'-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Senate takes up legislation
that would enlarge the rights of patients in dealing with their
managed health care programs. A key issue is the patient's recourse
when treatment has been denied. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-LABOR (Washington) _ An issue that could become part of
the presidential debate is coming up in the Senate this week. Texas
Republican Phil Gramm, reacting to fears in the high-tech industry
that it is running out of qualified workers, plans to introduce a
bill to expand the number of skilled foreign workers allowed to get
jobs in this country. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   The MEANS-COLUMN will resume Monday, July 12.
</P>
