<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-08 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: JOLLY POTS IN HOT COLORS ARE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the return of hippie chic, will Bizarre wares be next?
</P>
<P>
   Next Friday, Phillips auction house in London will conduct its
first sale devoted to the works of Clarice Cliff, the innovative
British potter (1899-1972) who invented Bizarre wares.
</P>
<P>
   Mick Jagger helped put Cliff back on the radar screen two
decades ago when he bought a gaily colored ``Age of Jazz''
centerpiece she designed. Young people started paying attention to
her exuberant, oddly shaped pots painted in brilliant red, orange,
turquoise and pink designs. Many were geometric, others flowery or
scenic.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, such collectors as Anna Wintour and the Missonis
started scooping up hand-painted biscuit barrels, chargers and
teapots with the uninhibited designs. Demand soared, then slowed
until the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cliff's works are back in the public eye, probably because
it looks so wild and modern you half expect to see one in ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' And for the uninitiated, there
are suddenly several new opportunities to see the designer's work.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Web site (www.claricecliff.co.uk.); an international
Clarice Cliff Collectors Club and a new book, ``Clarice Cliff: The
Art of Bizarre, a Definitive Centenary Celebration'' (Trafalgar
Square Publishing) by Leonard Griffin, the president of the club.
</P>
<P>
   The Susan P. Meisel gallery has 35 works on view through July 23
at 135 Prince Street in Soho. This summer the Wedgwood Museum has
an exhibition of 600 works by Cliff in Stoke-on-Trent,
Staffordshire; the show runs through Sept. 5. Christie's in South
Kensington has already held two Cliff sales this year. The last
one, on May 5, was 82 percent sold and made $593,224. A Bizarre
centerpiece, a pair of dancing figures from Cliff's ``Age of Jazz''
series, sold for $18,080.
</P>
<P>
   The recent sale was so successful that Christie's is having
another one on Nov. 10 in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such a broad base of Clarice Cliff collectors _ they
are spread across the U.K., the U.S., Australia and South America _
that it makes for a solid, safe market,'' said Michael Jeffery, the
specialist at Christie's. ``It doesn't fluctuate much. It just gets
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   What's all the fuss about?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fashion,'' said David Hare of Gardiner Houlgate, an
auction house in Bath, England, that will conduct an auction of
Cliff wares on Tuesday. ``Pieces from the early jazzy period are
very popular now.'' The auction house's Web site is
www.thesaurus.co.uk/gardiner-houlgate/aucdates.htm.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the current interest may simply be in Cliff herself.
``It's a story of how a poor paintress rose up to run a company,''
Jeffery said.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff was born into a large working-class family in
Stoke-on-Trent, a part of England known as the Potteries. According
to ``Clarice Cliff: The Bizarre Affair'' by Leonard Griffin and
Louis and Susan Meisel (Abrams, 1988), she showed an independent
streak at an early age. She began making clay pots on her own
initiative at age 10, when she visited an aunt at a factory nearby.
She left school at age 13 and became an apprentice at an
earthenware manufacturing firm where she learned how to paint
freehand on pots. She studied painting at night.
</P>
<P>
   In 1916 she applied for a job in the decorating department of a
large factory, A.J. Wilkinson. She got the job, and one of the
directors, who later became her husband, recognized her native
talent and encouraged her.
</P>
<P>
   Highly motivated, she spent her lunch breaks walking around the
factory and learning about the kilns and glazing techniques. By
1920 she was assigned to a separate studio to help the company's
two top male designers.
</P>
<P>
   By 1924 she was allowed to produce some of her own designs and
sign them ``Clarice C'' alongside the Wilkinson mark.
</P>
<P>
   She volunteered to paint the thousands of pieces of undecorated
wares in outdated shapes that the Wilkinson company inherited when
it acquired the Newport Pottery. They were in storage, and she
thought she could make them salable. The salesmen were doubtful,
but the pieces sold well. They were revolutionary in color and
design.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later she was producing her own brash designs in
brilliant ``hot'' colors. She had a group of apprentices whom she
taught to paint with unorthodox, rough brush strokes. She called
the line Bizarre and started to give public demonstrations in
London department stores. The work caught on.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was producing at a time in England when nothing as bright,
personal and vivid was available,'' Jeffery said.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff added flowers to her repertory. She borrowed children's
stick-figure drawings for children's china. She did bucolic outdoor
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   As sales increased, she applied the Bizarre patterns to vases,
teapots, candlesticks and bowls. Because they were all
hand-painted, the wares had a hand-made look.
</P>
<P>
   She studied articles in the French magazines on Desny, the Paris
design firm. She created her own Deco shapes, from conical sugar
sifters to angular, Cubistic vases.
</P>
<P>
   The wares were stamped ``Bizarre by Clarice Cliff.'' Many were
best sellers during the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new shapes and bold colors captured the public's attention
when they first came out,'' said Johanna Freidwall, Phillips'
pottery specialist in London. ``They were unlike anything that
people had seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Now art director of the factory, Cliff seemed to have caught the
mood of the late Jazz Age; her customers included celebrities from
the stage, screen and radio.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff worked as manager and artist until the outbreak of World
War II, trying to maintain the momentum of her earlier success. But
she found it increasingly difficult. ``She was jolly but
impractical,'' said Muir Hewett, owner of Art Deco Originals in
Halifax, England. ``After the war, the work fell off. I think she
lost interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff died in 1972 after years of failing health, oblivious to
the budding new interest in her work.
</P>
<P>
   Today, people collect Cliff wares by date, style, shape or
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly by pattern or shape,'' Jeffery said. ``The English
prefer smaller items like the conical sugar sifters, so they can
display a lot of them together, to show the different patterns.
Americans tend to like the larger pots, and they sell for a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   One note of caution: Wedgwood has done authorized reproductions,
which are clearly marked, but other companies have made copies. Be
on the alert if a Clarice Cliff piece is too cheap _ a good piece
may cost $500. There is even a Web site to help with
that:www.claricecliff.com/fakes/.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
