<HEADER>
A3356 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     07-08 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT MOVIE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies playing this weekend. (Star) denotes a
highlyu recommended film. Ratings and running times are in
parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AFTER LIFE,'' starring Arata, Taketoshi Naito and Erika
Oda. Directed by Hirokazu Kore-eda (not rated, 118 minutes). Much
of this transcendentally compassionate, gently humorous Japanese
film is set in a drab office building where courteous caseworkers
welcome the week's new clients. The place turns out not to be a
social service agency but a metaphysical way station where the
newcomers are people of all ages and types who have just died and
have three days to select one memory to take with them into
eternity. Before they depart, those memories will be filmed. As
they tell their stories and make their choices, the movie becomes a
profound meditation on life's meaning and value and the
relationship of movies, memories and dreams (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME,'' starring Mike Myers,
Heather Graham and Elizabeth Hurley. Directed by Jay Roach (PG-13,
95 minutes). There may come a time when even Austin Powers tires of
the words ``Oh, behave!'' but it isn't here yet. Although the
sequel with the fab title is several love beads short of its
predecessor and more than a few scenes play like outtakes, this is
still a crafty, intermittently hilarious comedy. Myers' neo-Sellers
multiple-personality act is fine even when the material is less so,
and this sequel makes the most of Dr. Evil, his most inspired
creation. A scatological Scotsman, the film's walking id and
bathroom joke, is more of an acquired taste. Costumes and pop
references are still a hoot, as is the adorably benighted Austin.
Ms. Graham makes terrific eye candy but doesn't share Ms. Hurley's
quick-witted air of being in on the joke (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``BIG DADDY,'' starring Adam Sandler, Cole and Dylan Sprouse,
Joey Lauren Adams, Jon Stewart and Leslie Mann. Directed by Dennis
Dugan (PG-13, 95 minutes). It's awfully early in the career of Adam
Sandler to find him sharing the screen with a scene-stealing
6-year-old (actually the Sprouse twins). Besides, the cute kid in
Sandler's movies is usually the star himself. But he's in a
position to do whatever he likes, even if it's a flimsy sentimental
comedy with more product plugs and fewer laughs than might have
been hoped for. Having greatly expanded his following with the
romantic comedy and '80s kitsch of ``The Wedding Singer,'' not to
mention the inspired rustic lunacy of ``The Waterboy,'' he falls
back on much less inventive material this time. And the barrage of
brand-name junk food is enough to make skin break out in the
audience (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER,'' starring John Travolta, Madeleine
Stowe, James Cromwell, Timothy Hutton and James Woods. Directed by
Simon West (R, 118 minutes). Murder on a military base was once
enough of a pretext for a detective thriller, but nowadays it takes
more. The prevailing sleaze quotient calls for kinks, and this
galling adaptation of a Nelson DeMille best seller is happy to
oblige. So the title character, a pretty young officer whom the
film thinks has no place in the military, is the victim of a lurid
crime. Travolta and Ms. Stowe affably investigate whodunit, though
the unraveling of the crime is laughably arbitrary. The real point
of their ponderous investigation is that the victim asked for what
she got (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``AN IDEAL HUSBAND,'' starring Cate Blanchett, Minnie Driver,
Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore and Jeremy Northam. Written and
directed by Oliver Parker (PG-13, 97 minutes). The best thing about
Parker's likable but diluted screen adaptation of Oscar Wilde's
1895 comedy of politics and Victorian morality is Everett's
portrayal of Wilde's elegantly epigrammatic alter ego Lord Arthur
Goring. In underplaying this seemingly incorrigible (but actually
wise, witty and caring) rake, Everett makes him all the more
charming. Northam and Ms. Blanchett are well cast as a politician
and his priggish wife, but Ms. Moore and Ms. Driver miss hitting
the right notes in a screenplay that streamlines Wilde into a
quasi-contemporary style, keeping some but not all of the
playwright's scintillating bons mots. The settings are so lavish
they're almost edible (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``LIMBO,'' starring Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio and David
Strathairn. Written, directed and edited by John Sayles (R, 126
minutes). Part survivalist drama, part satirical portrait of
contemporary Alaska, Sayles' powerful new film is almost as vast as
the great outdoors it contemplates. Ms. Mastrantonio, as a
well-traveled folk-rock singer working Alaskan lounges, and
Strathairn, as the brooding local fisherman with whom she becomes
involved, make one of the most compelling adult couples to be seen
in an American film in quite some time. When they find themselves
castaways along with her teen-age daughter on a remote Alaskan
island, the movie becomes both a suspense thriller and a sorrowful
meditation on survivalism, civilization and the ties that bind.
Though marred by an abrupt ending and glaring literary devices,
``Limbo'' is eminently worthwhile (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LOVERS ON THE BRIDGE,'' starring Juliette Binoche and
Denis Lavant. Directed by Leos Carax (not rated, 125 minutes). A
1992 one-of-a-kind cult film, famed for an amazing set that
recreates Paris' Pont Neuf and part of the Seine, and for the
stubborn determination of its director to see his film through. A
beautiful half-blind artist (played enchantingly by a scrappy young
Ms. Binoche) and an indigent alcoholic fire-eater are the title
characters, and that alone is enough to make this romance an
acquired taste. But there's no denying the visual loveliness of its
most rapturous moments or the power of its daring (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``NOTTING HILL,'' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant.
Directed by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic
notion here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts
might be out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to
bring her together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome echoes
of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright, winsome
romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters themselves,
inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's burdens of being
world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``THE RED VIOLIN,'' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal. As it makes its way from Vienna to England to China, the
instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly photographed
historical tableaux. If the movie's narrative energy is undermined
by a plodding screenplay and wooden acting, the music, composed by
John Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and the London
Philharmonia Orchestra, is sublime (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SOUTH PARK: BIGGER, LONGER AND UNCUT,'' with the voices
of Trey Parker, Matt Stone and Mary Kay Bergman. Directed by Parker
(R, 88 minutes). The movie spinoff from the outrageous Comedy
Central cartoon series following the adventures of some
potty-mouthed third-grade boys in the Colorado town of South Park
is extremely funny and jubilantly obscene, with several sewers'
worth of bathroom humor. It is also a smart, pointed satire that
demolishes the hypocrisy of a conservative culture that allows
almost unlimited violence and gore in movies and on television but
goes ballistic at the prospect of children being exposed to dirty
language and sexual explicitness. When a group of tykes sneak into
a Canadian movie filled with obscenities and come home spewing
smut, their parents raise such a ruckus that the United States
declares war on Canada. Armageddon looms when the Devil, who has
been having a troubled affair with the recently deceased Saddam
Hussein, decides to put in an appearance. Contributing to the
madness are 15 clever songs spoofing everything from Rodgers and
Hammerstein to ``Les Miserables'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``SUMMER OF SAM,'' starring John Leguizamo, Adrien Brody
and Mira Sorvino. Directed by Spike Lee (R, 145 minutes). This raw,
enthralling evocation of a Bronx neighborhood gone mad in 1977
plunges its audience headlong into a pre-AIDS libidinous frenzy. It
also summons an atmosphere of macho posturing and mounting
prejudice reminiscent of ``Do the Right Thing'' a decade ago,
though the locals this time are white Italian-Americans. The
killing spree of David Berkowitz is used as a catalyst, joining
disco, punk, drugs, a heat wave and the Yankees to summon the
crazed spirit of that time. The characters are thin, but a fine
cast brings them to life. Leguizamo (in high ``Saturday Night
Fever'' style) and Brody (with hair in spikes) are outstanding as
the film's two most visible signs of the times (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,'' starring
Liam Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd.
Directed by George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of hype and
breathless expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy
surprise: it's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the
series and offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating
illusions that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding
raptors of ``Jurassic Park.'' While the human stars here are indeed
reduced to playing action figures, they are upstaged by amazing
backdrops and hordes of crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis
Carroll in Lucas is given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise
was funnier and scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't
capable of this (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``TARZAN,'' with the voices of Tony Goldwyn, Minnie
Driver and Nigel Hawthorne. Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris Buck
(G, 88 minutes). No need to wonder how this animated Tarzan movie
could improve on the 47 others that preceded it. Disney animation
turns the hero into a supple, long-haired hunk, lets the apes talk
to him and whooshes through lush jungle settings with exultant
agility. This ``Tarzan'' is sprightly and likable in ways that are
hard to resist, with lively vocal performances, excitingly kinetic
animation and Phil Collins singing tunefully in the background.
Parents will stay awake, and children will be charmed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``WILD WILD WEST,'' starring Will Smith, Kevin Kline and Salma
Hayek. Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld (PG, 107 minutes). Another big,
lavish movie with no there there. This post-Civil War James Bondish
contraption-happy sci-fi film is hard to categorize, a quality not
to be confused with originality. Directed by Sonnenfeld without the
deadpan-alien sensibility that worked for ``Men in Black,'' this
stylistic grab bag is similarly kinky but a lot more chaotic,
however heroically Smith, as a newly hunky and debonair action
hero, tries to save the day. Good-looking but dopey, with an
emphasis on toylike but vaguely ghoulish special effects. A movie
with that much potential kiddie appeal didn't have to start in a
bordello, either (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE WINSLOW BOY,'' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca
Pidgeon and Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G,
110 minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's
trial that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down
to its essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation. Played
with unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous cast, it
works as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the family
of a cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the
consequences of that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography
is beautifully lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch
acting style sets the film's tone and gives her suffragist
character a sharp edge (Maslin).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
