<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-BLACKS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR WANTS TO INTEREST MINORITIES IN RACING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 THE LEDGER, LAKELAND, FLA.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In part because of its origins in the deep South and in part
because it is still often stereotyped as a sport of good ol' boys,
stock car racing has had little appeal to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, with NASCAR spread across the country and beginning
to infiltrate more urban areas, stock car racing attracts little
interest in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say it hasn't made inroads.
</P>
<P>
   Brian France, NASCAR's senior vice president and part of the
France family that rules the sport, attended a recent conference
sponsored by Rev. Jesse Jackson's Rainbow Coalition in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went just to let them know we're interested in promoting
diversity,'' France said. ``We'd like to see more minorities
involved with racing.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference came at about the same time former Olympic star
Jackie Joyner-Kersee, her husband Bob Kersee and Kurt Roehrig, who
presently has a team in NASCAR's truck series, announced they were
getting together with the object of forming a Winston Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   At the present time, there are no black sponsors, car owners,
drivers or crew chiefs in stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   The only black team that has achieved any success in the sport
was a family operation headed by Wendell Scott, who drove regularly
from 1961 through 1971. In 1964, Scott won what was then the
equivalent of a Winston Cup race in Jacksonville, Fla., and for
four straight seasons, 1966-69, he finished in the top 10 in points
with his best a fifth in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   But as NASCAR moved away from the small, independent operations
into today's technical, high-priced teams, there has been no
minority participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know when we'll see a black driver in the Daytona 500,
but we need to find ways to make it easier for minorities to get
into the sport,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, France said, NASCAR will form a diversity council to
assist minorities in getting resumes to the right people, and will
also try to interest minority firms, such as BET, a black
television network, in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a marketing standpoint, you always want your audience to
be getting younger and bigger,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we plan to do is institute an intern program for
minorities in NASCAR with all our offices involved,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   It will be more difficult from a competitive standpoint. Before
any blacks are competing in the Daytona 500, they will have to get
into short-track racing and work their way up.
</P>
<P>
   For that to succeed, NASCAR needs to interest minority youth in
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about just throwing money at it; a lot of guys have
done that and never gone fast,'' France said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a program in Philadelphia where they have an
inner-city racing league with go-carts to attract kids,'' he said.
``We would have an interest in seeing more of that.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1634EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3359 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-MCREYNOLDS-NYT     07-08 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-MCREYNOLDS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME RUNNING OUT ON MCREYNOLDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 THE LEDGER, LAKELAND, FLA.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds has a decision to make, only it isn't really
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds, the crew chief for Mike Skinner, has been trying to
start his own team for two years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he failed to find a sponsor and he is rapidly reaching
the point of no return for 1999 as well.
</P>
<P>
   At last weekend's Daytona's Pepsi 400, McReynolds said that if
he didn't have a sponsor in place by the end of this week, he would
not go forward with his plans.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, McReynolds set June 15 as a drop dead date for
starting his team. Then he extended the deadline to July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even my wife, who has not been vocal about anything we've
done, she told me I couldn't move the deadline any more,''
McReynolds said. ``She said it wasn't fair, and she was right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the racing side, I've got to have an answer real quick,''
McReynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   He needs an answer, he said, because he owes answers to Skinner
and car owner Richard Childress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what I'll do if it doesn't work out,'' McReynolds
said. ``It's something Richard Childress and I will have to sit
down and talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds, one of the most successful and respected crew
chiefs, left a long association with Robert Yates to become Dale
Earnhardt's crew chief in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he prepared the car in which Earnhardt won his first
Daytona 500. After that Childress, who owns the cars driven by
Earnhardt and Skinner, decided the team would have better chemistry
if McReynolds took over Skinner's car. So after 13 races in 1998,
McReynolds became Skinner's crew chief, a position he still holds.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds' goal, though, has been to be a car owner, and he has
been pursuing that with his partner, businessman John Dangler. If
they can find a sponsor, Dangler will oversee the operation while
McReynolds concentrates on the car as crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   If McReynolds sticks to his latest deadline, though, it appears
likely that he will be unable to form his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Established operations are now getting ready for the 2000
Daytona 500. If McReynolds, who will be starting from scratch,
doesn't get going soon, he won't be able to get competitive cars
built in time.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds said he had been talking with two potential sponsors.
One was believed to be BellSouth, which sponsors the car driven by
Joe Nemechek, and the other was Tide, which recently ended a
nine-year association with Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth apparently backed off because it did not want to be
involved with sponsoring two cars, and the buyout price to
terminate its contract with Felix Sabates, who owns Nemechek's car,
was too high.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, Tide switched to Cal Wells, who owns a CART
team (open wheel racing) and is moving into Winston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's over with. That's done,'' McReynolds said. ``We've got
one more company we're working close with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meetings have gone well, but it isn't done yet, and I've
learned not to judge it until they either say yes or no,''
McReynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds would not identify the company he is still
negotiating with, other than to say it is presently in Winston Cup
as an associate car sponsor. It is believed McReynolds is talking
with Burger King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
