<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW-AR     07-08 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PEONY PAVILION': A DREAM BECKONS FUTURE TO PAST AND WEST TO EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The peony is a hardy flower. Its theatrical
counterpart has survived 400 years in China and now a trip across
the Pacific. It has been thwarted by bureaucrats at home, shortened
and modernized abroad. Now, as ``The Peony Pavilion,'' it faces
another test: maximization. Placed at the center of Lincoln Center
Festival '99, Tang Xianzu's wandering epic of love, death and the
supernatural is testing the endurance of both its players and its
audience: 6 episodes, 20 hours, the cycle to be repeated three
times this month.
</P>
<P>
   The production, originally by the Shanghai Kunju Opera, was to
have been in New York precisely a year ago, but Chinese officials
in a late-hour fit of moralizing (though other reasons may have
been in play) found this ``Peony Pavilion'' unfit for export. The
director, Chen Shi-Zeng, was encouraged to try again. Sets,
costumes and props already belonged to Lincoln Center and its
co-producer in France, Festival Paris d'Automne. The leading lady,
Qian Yi, and a key musician, Zhou Ming, made their way to the
United States. New singers and instrumentalists for this populous
and complicated event were recruited both in and out of China, and
all parties decided to try again. The restart began on Wednesday
with ``Episode I: The Interrupted Dream'' at the La Guardia Concert
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, a great adventure is at hand;
interpreting a Ming Dynasty entertainment intended for the affluent
16th-century Chinese home for the delectation of a Manhattan
audience strains simile and metaphor to their limits. We are given
translations in the form of surtitles and plenty to read about
history and style. But we _ even the Westerner who speaks Chinese _
are necessarily at a distance.
</P>
<P>
   Literary Chinese speaks in layer upon layer of allusion,
references learned as much by osmosis as by study. Think of sports:
the European will understand the rules of baseball and the American
those of soccer. Less easy to come by is the culture and history
that suffuse these rules. Yet if we approach ``The Peony Pavilion''
with humility and are ready to take much on faith, we shall be
happy. Some of its pleasures are unambiguous: the stunningly
beautiful costumes, the dancelike gesture of the players, the
extraordinary sense of decorum. The swooping vowels and slushy
consonants of Chinese speech are a music in themselves, and the
music itself _ simple pentatonic language accompanied in equally
simple unison _ is delivered in the thin, sharp whining tones of a
very different style of singing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Chinese dress, decor, music and poetry, this
production is as much a Western invention as a re-creation of old
China. The tools of the early-music movement and the principles of
authenticity are brought to bear, even though the Chinese
themselves have little idea of what those first performances were
like. There is no history of ``The Peony Pavilion'' having been
done complete.
</P>
<P>
   Completeness is an idea more indigenous to European and American
musicology and current notions of textual integrity. Performing
tradition in China has come down orally over the centuries, and we
all know how stories change with new tellings.
</P>
<P>
   The music, we know, was adapted from existing compositions. The
story is unclouded: a beautiful girl who pines away for lack of
love, a student's posthumous love for her, and finally a happy
ending rising up from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   We are also aware of the great impact of ``The Peony Pavilion''
on those who read and saw it later. The emotional traumas and
occasional suicides surrounding this work are similar to the
emotional stir that swept Europe in the wake of Goethe's ``Sorrows
of Young Werther,'' a faraway literary sensation 200 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Huang Hai Wei's set is luxurious and literal, wrapping itself
around the proscenium end of this small ampitheaterlike space. The
pavilion roof is at the center, the 10 musicians in a box at stage
left, and a working pond is to the front, stocked with ducks,
goldfish and waterlilies and hung on its edges with bird cages
(also operative). Dressing areas to the rear are left exposed, and
occasionally at stage right players sit for makeup and costume
adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to represent, if only obliquely, the freewheeling
atmosphere of a Chinese opera theater. Audience members on
Wednesday were encouraged to emulate their Chinese counterparts by
coming and going freely during this uninterrupted three-hour-plus
evening. Some did, gingerly; most didn't, sitting sedately with
their hands folded. Hardly authentic behavior given the ruckus of
the real thing: no milling, sunflower-seed spitting and private
conversation. If a Chinese theatergoer laughs or cries, it is not
necessarily about anything happening onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The fascinating byproduct of this venture is the eery no man's
land it occupies between East and West, a territory shared by both
performers and audience. We are intrigued, to give one example, by
the stagecraft, but from a distance. As an engine of emotion, it
does not stir us from the gut.
</P>
<P>
   All theater everywhere is artificial by nature. It is the degree
of abstraction that is so different here: beards that are
splendidly fake, men playing women, or the young playing the old.
The grace and composure, the emotional reticence, of the body that
greet passionate situations and the ritual and highly virtuosic use
of eye movement as an acting device are worlds away from
Stanislavsky or the Actors Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Western ideas of humor and drama creep into this production.
Maybe the discreet slapstick between the Tutor (Shan Jing) and
Spring Fragrance (Jia Yong Hong) is one of the touches that set off
those grumpy Shanghai bureaucrats. If there is a bridge between two
worlds here, it is Qian Yi as the heroine, Du Liniang. She is a
graceful charmer, and if there is one sequence in the final scene
that easily passes over the gulf between cultures, it comes in the
dream sequence with her lover, Liu Mengmei (Wen Yu Hang). The body
is discreet, but the eyes speak ambiguously of both innocence and
knowingness. It is a directly touching moment.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Peony Pavilion'' is a rare opportunity and something of
an endurance test. It worked hard to get to New York, and its loyal
followers will work equally hard through its six episodes. Even
piecemeal, it should be sampled.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about history or authenticity. History, in the eyes
of some, is what we know at this moment, the past being an
illusion. ``The Peony Pavilion'' is both ancient and modern, but
maybe it is simply right now.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PEONY PAVILION'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in six episodes by Tan Xianzu, music notation by Ye Tang;
director, Chen Shi-Zheng; music director, Zhou Ming; Pingtan
adaptation, Rao Yichen; set designer, Huang Hai Wei; costume
designer, Cheng Shu Yi; lighting designer, Yi Li Ming. At La
Guardia Concert Hall, Amsterdam Avenue at 65th Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Quin Yi (Du Limang), Wen Yu Hang (Liu Mengmei), Wen Fu Lin
(Du Bao, Ghost), Lin Sen (Sister Stone, Janitor, Soldier), Shan
Jing (Tutor, Flower Spirit), Song Yang (Madam Du, Elder, Taoist
Nun, Prostitute), Yu Qing Wang (Judge of Hell, Dame Li, Tartar
King), Jia Yong Hong (Spring Fragrance, Prostitute, Elder) and Liu
Ming (Commissioner Miao, Camel Guo).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
