<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENGHIS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GENGHIS BLUES': CAPTURING LISTENERS IN GENGHIS KHAN COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Paul Pena, a blind San Francisco-based blues
musician of Cape Verdean descent, was listening to his shortwave
radio when he was riveted by some eerie vocal sounds on a program
broadcast from Radio Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   What captured his ear turned out to be ``throat singing,'' a
technique by which the human voice produces multiple sounds,
typically a low-pitched warbling drone (much like the sound of the
didjeridoo, an Australian aboriginal trumpet made out of hollowed
wood) accompanied by higher whistling overtones.
</P>
<P>
   The style is one of several art forms developed in Tuva, a
Central Asian republic of nearly 400,000 people, about the size of
North Dakota, on a plateau wedged between northwestern Mongolia and
southern Siberia. It is the home of descendants of Genghis Khan.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 10 years, Pena worked to develop similar vocal
sounds, which he incorporated into his blues music. And in 1993,
when he learned that a group of Tuvan throat singers were touring
the United States for the first time, he attended their concert in
San Francisco and afterward introduced himself to the musicians and
sang some of their traditional songs to them. The rich gravelly
style he had developed prompted the Tuvans to nickname Pena
``Earthquake,'' and they invited him to travel to their country to
participate in its triennial throat singing contest in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Roko Belic's good-hearted, wonderfully revealing film ``Genghis
Blues'' is the record of that arduous but triumphant journey, which
Pena made with a small film crew and some friends. At the contest,
Pena, accompanying himself on the guitar, so delighted the Tuvan
audience with his performance in what is called the kargyraa style
of throat singing that he was chosen the audience's favorite. It's
easy to see why. The music Pena made was very different from the
hovering, ethereal chantlike sound of traditional Tuvan throat
singing. Muscular, earthy and aggressive, it melds American blues
music and Asian chant into a rugged Asian-American fusion.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Genghis Blues'' shows, the journey from San Francisco to
Central Asia was fraught with difficulties. Pena, who is clinically
depressed as well as blind, periodically found himself disoriented,
and the trip almost had to be cut short when his antidepressant
medication ran out. One member of the group also had a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The climate in Tuva ranges from extreme heat to cold, and life
there is rustic, with an economy still largely based on nomadic
animal herding. The film shows a sheep slaughtering ceremony, and
the serving of delicacies like the fat from a lamb's rump and a
vodka distilled from milk. But the Tuvans, most of whom practice a
mixture of Tibetan Buddhism and animist shamanism, radiate a
beatific joy. Pena's host and guide around the country was its
leading throat singer, Kongar-ol Ondar, who is said to be the
country's Elvis Presley, John F. Kennedy and Michael Jackson rolled
into one. He radiates a gracious, smiling exuberance that appears
completely unforced.
</P>
<P>
   Without being mushy about it, ``Genghis Blues'' reminds us that
music is a universal language that can go a long way toward
bridging cultural and linguistic gaps. It also reminds us that in
some ways modern telecommunications and transportation have turned
the world into a global village, enabling musical roots 10,000
miles apart to intertwine.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GENGHIS BLUES'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Roko Belic; in English and
Tuvan, with English subtitles; director of photography, Roko and
Adrian Belic; produced by Roko and Adrian Belic; released by Roxie
Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 88 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Paul Pena and Kongar-ol Ondar.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
