r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-ROOTS-TEX     07-08 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-ROOTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AN ITALIAN VILLAGE, A SEARCH FOR ANCESTORS DIGS UP MORE THAN
HERITAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The photo of the bright-eyed schoolgirl was a little crinkled
and brown, not much bigger than my thumbnail. She didn't look like
anyone I knew.
</P>
<P>
   But three little words squeezed onto the back offered promise of
an impossible coincidence, a pot of genealogical gold at the end of
a long and uncertain journey to the remote Italian town where my
great-grandparents were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questa e Lisa,'' it read in neatly written script. ``This is
Lisa.''
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather's sister is named Lisa. She was born 90 years ago
in Boston to Modestino and Clorinda Vozzella, who came to America
at the turn of the century from the southern Italian town of
Montemiletto. Lisa has never been to Montemiletto or, indeed, to
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here was a clerk in Montemiletto's town hall, a stranger
who'd helped me look up family birth and marriage records, telling
me we were related and offering what she said was a photograph of
my great-aunt.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't know for sure whether the picture really was of my
relative until much later that day. But the possibility alone was
enough to convince me that trekking to this tiny town was the best
travel idea I'd ever had.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't look that way from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Montemiletto is so small that even the Italian Tourist Bureau
couldn't find it on a map. My husband, Jeff, and I set out from
Rome knowing only that it was near the town of Avellino and that we
had a reservation at Montemiletto's one and only hotel. The closest
the train could take us was Salerno, about 30 miles south of
Naples.
</P>
<P>
   The view from the Salerno station was postwar bleak: a
collection of worn, charmless apartment buildings. The guy at the
train information booth had never heard of Montemiletto. We boarded
a bus and wondered what we were getting ourselves into.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty, industrial scenes we passed were hardly reassuring,
but the view turned increasingly rural as the bus began to climb
2,000 feet to our destination.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival, we were delighted to find ourselves in a medieval
mountain town, complete with castle, quaint crumbling houses and
5,000 residents unaccustomed to foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of our $35-a-night pensione, Francesca and Luigi,
greeted us with excitement. We were their only guests.
</P>
<P>
   It was quiet that evening as we walked the cobblestone streets,
ignoring a light rain and the fatigue from our five-hour journey.
The few people out appeared to stare. We dined at the only
restaurant we saw, enjoying a local version of fusilli, loose coils
nearly as long as our forks, baked in a clay bowl with tomato sauce
and mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   We awoke the next morning to find the sleepy central square
transformed into a bustling marketplace. Vendors hawked fruit and
vegetables, meats and cheese, shoes and housewares _ even live
ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone we met, starting with the guy who sold us pistachios,
heard the spiel that my husband, who speaks Italian, had helped me
memorize: ``Mia bisnonna e mio bisnonno sono da Montemiletto'' (My
great-grandparents are from Montemiletto). I couldn't manage past
tense, even with Jeff's help, so I'd tack on ``cento anni fa'' (100
years ago). It got the message across.
</P>
<P>
   They would ask the name, and I'd say Vozzella and Nuzzolo, my
great-grandmother's maiden name. Nuzzolo they knew. Vozzella drew a
blank.
</P>
<P>
   We spent hours admiring piles of fennel and vats of green
olives, scanning the crowd for folks who resembled my relatives. We
didn't see any striking look-alikes, but we did see plenty of
generous schnozes and petite frames that would blend in at any
Vozzella family gathering.
</P>
<P>
   We finally tore ourselves away to head for the town hall, in a
former Dominican monastery on the main square. Two clerks, a man
and a woman, offered to help us look through the old record books.
The woman, Bruna Brogna, seized on Clorinda's maiden name. Her
husband had Nuzzolos in his family. She phoned him, quickly hung up
and announced that we were related.
</P>
<P>
   That lightning strike was followed by hours of fruitless
searching through yellowed volumes. Finally, the other clerk
discovered the problem. We'd been looking for Clorinda Nuzzolo. She
was, in fact, Angelamaria Anastasia Clorinda Nuzzolo, born
September 1871 to a shoemaker and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   We never turned up a record of Modestino's birth, but we found
one of his marriage to Clorinda on March 5, 1899. Both were 27
years old. He was a blacksmith, as was his father.
</P>
<P>
   Our digging done, the clerks told us to come back in a few hours
and they'd have the records photocopied for us. Bruna offered
something even more precious when we returned: the tiny picture of
Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   The photo had been passed down through her husband's family with
other old pictures. Bruna thought the girl was Clorinda's daughter.
That would mean my grandfather's sister, my great-aunt Bette, who
went by Lisa until her Boston schoolteachers told her that was her
``Italian name.'' Her real name, they told her, was Elizabeth,
which she later shortened to Bette.
</P>
<P>
   The coincidence was almost too great to believe. But there was
no time to absorb the news, to study the likeness of the schoolgirl
in sausage curls for any resemblance to my elderly aunt. The clerks
hustled us off to meet the mayor, who presented us with a ceramic
plaque bearing the town seal.
</P>
<P>
   Bruna invited us to meet her husband and children that evening.
At her home, built in the 1500s and topped by a red tile roof, she
served a dinner of pizza, asparagus frittata, homemade sopressata
salami and ``vino artigianale'' _ delicious, locally produced wine
that came in bottles without labels.
</P>
<P>
   The warm family reception made for a beautiful evening. Bruna's
husband, Paolo de Angelis, topped it off by laying to rest any
doubt that the Lisa in the photo was, indeed, my great-aunt, Bette
White.
</P>
<P>
   He said the girl in the picture used to write to her cousin,
Arcangela Nuzzolo. They kept up their correspondence into
adulthood. Paolo, Arcangela's nephew, had seen a letter from Lisa
about 15 years ago, when the unmarried Arcangela lived with his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Arcangela was dead now and Paolo didn't have the letter. He
couldn't remember the town or state where it had originated. But
one detail stuck in his mind a decade and a half later: Lisa's
married name wasn't Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bianca? Bianca?'' Jeff asked, translating the name in his
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Paolo picked up a pen and wrote it down: ``White.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Italy, I'd asked my Aunt Bette about anyone
she used to write in Montemiletto. Too many years had passed. My
aunt had just lost her husband, and her health was failing; she was
in no shape to recall names or dig up an address for me.
</P>
<P>
   But she was sharp enough to recognize herself in the photo once
we returned home, full of stories of a wonderful place her parents
called home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me,'' she marveled. ``That's my picture.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
