<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3368 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     07-08 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING HOT GROUPS TO GET MOST OUT OF UNTRADITIONAL WORKERS IS KEY TO
SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Small is getting really, really big.
</P>
<P>
   Small means fast, flexible, innovative, creative. It can move
with the customer's wants and the market's desires, ahead of the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   But what do you do if you're big? How does a giant corporation,
or even a business with a couple of hundred employees, move with
the speed of lightning and the creativity of DaVinci?
</P>
<P>
   The answer may be identifying and nurturing what may already be
there: untraditional types who usually don't ``fit'' in the
corporate structure. Once scorned by management as ne'er-do-wells,
these people often have what it takes to compete in a fast-paced
business environment.
</P>
<P>
   One author described such people as ``intrapreneurs,'' but they
can't move mountains alone. They need a group _ a hot group.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas on finding and nurturing such groups is behind ``Hot
Groups: Seeding Them, Feeding Them, and Using Them to Ignite Your
Organization'' (Oxford University Press, 299 pages, $25). Jean
Lipman-Blumen and Harold J. Leavitt are the authors, and management
guru Tom Peters did the foreword.
</P>
<P>
   Peters once again shows his amazing sense of clarity in a muddy
business world when he discusses the value Wall Street places on
personnel-driven companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a traditional industrial company _ circa 1975 _ the ratio
of stock market value (in dollars) to hard assets might run about
one-to-one,'' Peters writes. ``Near the end of 1998, the equivalent
ratio at Microsoft was 212-to-one. Yikes!''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft might be an extreme example, but it's not unique.
America Online has a stock market value about 1 1/2 times greater
than that of General Motors, Peters writes.
</P>
<P>
   He adds that this book is unique in business literature, and
that the authors are dead-on in discussing this business
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot Groups are passionate, task-obsessed,'' Peters writes.
``They are the meat and the potatoes of what an organization needs
in order to fling itself productively at this shifting, wild,
woolly economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipman-Blumen and Leavitt present a thorough and detailed
discussion of hot groups, a new term but not a new concept. The
authors suggest that hot groups have been around as long as
humanity, citing such examples as the Impressionists who reinvented
art in Paris during the 19th century, the Bauhaus group in Germany
that changed architecture and the physicists who demonstrated the
possibility of nuclear fission.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' group at Microsoft is the natural example of how hot
groups work in the business world, the authors contend. As Gates is
quoted about his early days, before Microsoft:
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even obey a 24-hour clock. We'd come in and program
for a couple days straight ... when it was time to eat, we'd get in
our cars and kind of race over to the restaurant and sit and talk
about what we were doing. Sometimes I'd get (so) excited about
things, I'd forget to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipman-Blumen and Leavitt show us that hot groups live
``volatile, temporary, impassioned'' lives and struggle in big
organizations. Hot groups tend to work alone and create enemies,
and are often viewed as expensive or idiotic. At the same time,
parent organizations tend to overcontrol hot groups, making them
fill out forms, dress within the company code and keep regular
working hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, the synergies that can follow from such a Mutt and Jeff
marriage are so enormous, so awesome, that they easily eclipse the
difficulties,'' the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   To manage hot groups, Lipman-Blumen and Leavitt suggest finding
a project or subject that is specific and has ``soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, find qualified people who are excited by the
idea,'' they write. ``Give them lots of room, provide the best
markers of progress you can find, protect them, help them up when
they are down, and get the rest of the organization to appreciate
them. Then, give them the space they need to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The authors have a timely premise and identify a group that may
be down the hall just waiting for a chance to light a fire under
your organization.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing With Your Values: Making Money and Making a
Difference''
</P>
<P>
   By Hall Brill, Jack Brill and Cliff Feigenbaum
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg Press, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   Several books have been written in this vein, but none is as
thorough. This effort is also more up to date and includes the
latest mutual funds, stocks and other investments that are
``green,'' or socially screened, in ways that reflect an individual
shareholder's values. Hal and Jack Brill are financial consultants
who have specialized in values-based investing for more than 10
years. Cliff Feigenbaum is editor of ``GreenMoney Journal,'' a
quarterly newsletter and Web site that provides information on
socially responsible investing.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustaining the Family Business: An Insider's Guide to Managing
Across Generations''
</P>
<P>
   By Marshall B. Paisner
</P>
<P>
   Perseus Books, $26
</P>
<P>
   Of the nation's 15 million businesses, a whopping 90 percent are
considered family-owned. But only one-third of those businesses
survive to the second generation and only 10 percent to the third.
Marshall Paisner, who has run a major carwash chain for 30 years,
relates his experience and those of others in family-owned
businesses. Managing family conflict, naming the next chief
executive and developing tax and estate strategies are among his
topics.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legal Edge for Homeowners, Buyers and Renters''
</P>
<P>
   By Michel James Bryant
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Books, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate Ralph Nader heartily endorses this book as
readable and informative. It's written by an attorney who also
stars in the syndicated TV news show ``The Legal Edge,'' now
running in more than 50 markets nationwide. The book is in
question-and-answer format, with typical questions involving
homeowners and renters.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
