<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-HNS     07-08 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER WATERS DOWN DOMESTIC PARTNERS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Delivering a blow to liberals in the state
Legislature, Gov. Gray Davis urged a lawmaker to water down a major
piece of domestic partnership legislation and limit health care
benefits to state workers in same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor, who promised during his campaign to
sign a new domestic partnership law, doesn't want to require health
maintenance organizations to provide the benefit plans to private
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the state should serve as a moral exemplar,'' Davis
said Wednesday. ``We should do what we think is right, not mandate
the private sector to follow our lead. There are obviously
exceptions to every rule, but that's the line I draw.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' decision was a blow to liberal Democrats in the
Legislature who expected more support after 16 years of Republican
governors. Former Gov. Pete Wilson vetoed every domestic
partnership bill that reached his desk.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the governor, Assemblywoman Carole Migden,
D-San Francisco, gutted her domestic partnership bill Wednesday and
replaced it with a measure allowing state agencies to provide the
benefits to workers. There are about 250,000 state workers in
California.
</P>
<P>
   With limited debate Wednesday, the measure passed the Senate
Judiciary Committee. Davis said he would sign the measure as now
written, but Migden has to get the support of the full Senate and
the Assembly again before it reaches the governor's desk. The
deadline is early September.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change in Migden's bill wipes out a requirement for
health maintenance organizations and other health plans to offer
domestic partnership benefits to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Many major health plans, such as Kaiser Permanente, already
offer domestic partnership benefits, and many large companies, such
as Nike, Eastman Kodak, Disney and Chevron, provide those benefits
to their employees.
</P>
<P>
   About 570 companies, 141 colleges and universities, and 87 local
governments offer domestic partnership benefits to employees,
according to the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   But Migden's bill had been designed to help smaller companies
looking to provide domestic partnership benefits. Many of those
companies can't buy the benefits for their employees because they
aren't big enough to pressure HMOs into complying or giving them
good rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pieces that will come out of this bill are very
good steps, but they are not comprehensive,'' said Rebecca Isaacs,
political director for the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
``More and more places are offering domestic partnership benefits,
and it would be good to have the HMOs on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs objected to another change requested by Davis. The bill
now defines domestic partnerships as between same-sex couples. The
original bill would have included heterosexual umarried partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have been better to have it broader, so you
don't get into the situation of having other groups feeling
dscriminated against,'' Isaacs said.
</P>
<P>
   Migden said she wanted more from the bill, but succumbed to the
governor's wishes in order to get something passed this year.
Earlier in the year, Migden had announced Davis was ready to sign
the tougher version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But ``at that point we had not discussed details of the
measure,'' Migden said. ``And while engaging in those discussion,
we were informed that this is the version he feels he can
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill now looks identical to a measure moving through
the Legislature to provide domestic partnerships to state
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The other bill was written by Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los
Angeles, who is facing a tough election battle next year in a
heavily gay state Senate district.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' announcement that he would sign Migden's bill means
Migden would get the glory for passing a domestic partnership bill.
Knox said he would continue with his measure, but was clearly livid
Migden took his bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a longstanding tradition in the Legislature that
legislators respect each other's authorship of measures,'' Knox
said. ``Without some restraint in this area, what's to stop
outright piracy of each other's bill on a daily basis? If someone
asked me to steal another Assembly member's bill, I'd tell them
no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
