<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3392 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALS-3-AZR &LR;      07-08 3020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALS-3-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FOR BETTER OR FOR WORSE, IN SICKNESS AND IN HEALTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (ADV: WITH ALS-1 AND ALS-2)  
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ The husband of Rorie Susan Buchanan wrote the
following recollection of his
 wife's and family's ordeal over her losing battle with Lou Gehrig's
disease. 
  
 By MICHAEL G. BUCHANAN  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Now, after all the people have left, all the thank-you
cards have been signed, all the friends have expressed their
sympathy, and the ashes are at home awaiting the journey to Hawaii,
I can sit down and tell our story. Maybe it will be of help to
someone.
</P>
<P>
   Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis: What a name for a diagnosis that
dooms the patient to death. No cure, no real government research
support, no FDA support of drugs that can ease the burden, no
insurance company understanding of the need for coverage, and no
real time frame other than an average life expectancy of three to
five years after diagnosis. Some patients have gone longer, but
most last less. If it's not diagnosed early _ and there are still a
lot of doctors who don't know what to look for _ it can be too late
by the time a diagnosis is made for anything to help.
</P>
<P>
   ALS gets the young, the old, man, woman, priest, secretary,
rich, poor, wife, husband, brother, sister. Less than 5 percent of
the cases are inherited. It affects walking, talking, eating,
breathing. Wheelchairs, canes, ramps, hospice, home health care,
beds, special diets, support groups, church, work, community. All
become a part of your day. &QL; 
OUR JOURNEY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Rorie and I were in San Francisco. I was on business, and, with a
long weekend, we decided to take some time for us. We had noticed
that she had started to slur her speech _ not always, just
occasionally. Someone had commented that after one glass of wine,
she was smashed. That's what led her to believe what the family had
been trying to tell her for months. Something was not right. She
also was having trouble with her right foot. Two episodes of
tripping and falling. (The foot doctor said all she needed was some
corrective surgery and all would be healed. What a dork!)
</P>
<P>
   A small thyroid problem was discovered, and she began medication
to treat it. That helped somewhat, but the slurring and foot drop
were not getting better. An MRI was next. What else could be
causing this? Brain tumor? Cancer? All of the really ugly (or so we
thought) diseases. But nothing showed up on the MRI. Now what? The
doctor suggested we consult a neurologist.
</P>
<P>
   We were scared _ not terrified, but anxious about what might be
causing this. Our attitude was that we'd just get another opinion
if we didn't like the first one. Besides, we had plans and dreams.
Rorie was going back to school to finish her degree; I was going to
work until she had a job, and then retire and become a flight
instructor. Great plans. ``Man plans and God laughs.'' &QL; 
QUESTIONS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Begin ital) When did you first notice the speech problem? When
did you first have problems with your foot? Have you noticed muscle
twitches? Let's do an exam, and then we can talk.
</P>
<P>
   I have noticed what we call fasciculation _ muscle tremors. I
would like to do one more test, an EMG, where we will be inserting
a needle into different parts of your muscles and measuring the
impulses or motor neuron signals to be absolutely sure of what I
think, but I am pretty sure of your diagnosis: ALS. Have you ever
heard of it?
</P>
<P>
   (End ital)
</P>
<P>
   Silent shock! ALS. We were very familiar with it. A friend had
died recently after battling ALS. Now we were devastated. Not MS,
not a tumor, not something ``simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis was confirmed by the EMG and a neurologist who
specializes in neuromuscular diseases. No mistake. We tell him
thank you. We have to come back in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ALS. We caught our breath. We cried. We hugged. We went home.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet in the house. Tears. Talking without really talking. Both
of us trying to work it out. OK, we can work with this. ALS, we can
do this. We're OK. No we're not.
</P>
<P>
   What to do. Whom to talk to. Let's get as much information as
possible before we have to go back to the doctor. Call the National
ALS Association. Don't tell the family until we're sure. Hold out
hope that maybe, just maybe, the tests will show something else. We
could live with MS.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks, the kids are asking, ``How's Mom? What did you
find out?'' Info has come from the various sources. It doesn't
really say anything other than we're in for the ride of our lives
and to send away for even more info.
</P>
<P>
   All the test results are back, and the diagnosis is confirmed
again. ALS. Maybe we should try the Ford Clinic. Cleveland? Mayo?
Houston?
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) But are you 100 percent certain?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. (end ital) &QL; 
THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One daughter away at school. Son here. Other daughter in Ann
Arbor with her newborn son _ our first grandchild. He's struggling
to make it after surgery to repair his heart. Another whole story.
</P>
<P>
   We have to tell them straight. Tell them all at the same time.
Varied reactions. All sad, but all hoping that there will be hope,
help, a new drug. Let's get busy gathering data. This is our new
project, educating us so we can help Rorie. Daughter leaves college
and moves home.
</P>
<P>
   Rorie's sisters are in the hunt, too. Everyone is trying to help
us find a miracle out there. New drugs reported in various rags and
relayed by friends and family, but none have been approved. You
have to get in the lottery for a chance to get them. The first few
times we're rejected but told our request will go into the next
pot. It's expensive.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) How long until we hit the insurance cap? (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Another project. Now we have to decipher insurance coverage and
definitions. The beginning of the hard questions. Who will take
over the information gathering? Who will put their life on hold?
Close friends _ actually family by default since ours live so far
away _ circle the wagons. Nancy, Rorie's best friend and surrogate
sister, says she'll be there no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ALS, family and friends. The first requires the other two.
Without them, nothing can get done. This is not a disease that can
be handled alone. You find out what a friend is. You find out just
how very much you can't do by yourself. &QL; 
THE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK. We need to plan. Go over wills and get a durable power of
attorney for health care. What's our financial position? Let's not
panic. We still have some time. Continue to work until it's too
hard to get into the job. Stick with the vacation plans. Let's talk
about remodeling the house. A bedroom and bath on the first floor.
Maybe another car that's easier to get in and out of.
</P>
<P>
   Initial panic, then a resigned atmosphere that we need to stop
worrying and live as much as possible. A few months pass.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) I'm not dying from ALS. I choose to live with it.
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   She's braver than I give her credit. There's no real
breakthrough in the medications. The FDA doesn't consider this a
serious enough affliction to warrant a lot of time. Congress
doesn't fund ALS research. The doctors and researchers who are
fighting for a cure are almost alone. New drugs, new hope but no
cure. (Later, there will be a bill before Congress funding ALS and
neuromuscular disease research and putting pressure on the FDA to
get off its butt and let ALS patients have Myotropin, a drug that
has proven to add a few months to their lives. Initially, the FDA
couldn't be bothered.)
</P>
<P>
   We went to Hawaii. A few years earlier than expected, but it was
now or never. Our community, our friends pooled their
frequent-flier miles and hotel coupons so we could go. It was a
second-honeymoon dream to get there someday.
</P>
<P>
   Rorie really can't enjoy the beach. She's not steady enough to
stand and let the waves roll over her feet and ankles. The sand is
too hard for her to walk on, so we sit and watch others enjoy it.
It's a little difficult getting into the pool, but this is where
she wants to be. The legs work underwater. We take a helicopter
tour and an airplane ride _ open cockpit. She's afraid of flying in
anything smaller than an airbus. She flew with me a few times in a
single-engine Cessna but never really liked it. Now she's giving me
an open-cockpit biplane ride and not a word of complaint.
</P>
<P>
   It's peaceful here. She's happy. Maybe we'll just stay until . .
.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) No, let's go home. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Hand in hand. Slow, deliberate. Dragging the foot.
</P>
<P>
   January: (begin ital) Let's go to the mountains. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Great time. Bought a cane. It helps with the walking. She loves
the mountains. Spent a lot of time in the Colorado Rockies when she
was younger. &QL; 
ANOTHER PLATEAU
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALS is a disease of plateaus. Always down, never up. The job has
to go. It's getting too hard to get into the car and drive. Almost
tripped in the lobby. The kids are worried. People who overhear her
talk wonder if she's had a stroke or if she's been drinking. The
kids press for medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Shouldn't we have it?
</P>
<P>
   No, not yet. Give her dignity a little while longer. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   We go to the support group in Ann Arbor. Hopefully, we can find
one closer, but our grandson is still in the intensive-care nursery
and it gives Rorie a chance to see him and to hold him. The support
group is depressing. One man without the use of his legs, though
perfectly able to talk and eat. Another with a respirator since he
caught pneumonia, but still very active. Some old, many young. And
still no hope.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Will I be like that?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Let's move. A house with everything on the same floor. Abandon
the big house. She loves to entertain, but it's not much fun
anymore. It's become too hard to do all the preparations and then
watch people look at you like you're disabled or shout as though
you were deaf. Without the muscle control of the diaphragm, she
can't generate enough air to speak above a whisper. Speech therapy
is next. Later, perhaps oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) No respirators. No heroic measures. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   A do-not-resuscitate order in the living will.
</P>
<P>
   Time again for her family reunion. This time, it's on board a
cruise ship out of Los Angeles. It's a long way away, it's
expensive, but we go. She wants to see the family. She spent a lot
of time with her cousins growing up. We'll take the wheelchair. It
gets us on early and in line first. Big family gathering and a good
way to get away from home and doctors. Cousins strain to understand
her when she talks. They sit with her, push her wheelchair in port.
Push her around the dance floor in the disco. They know they
probably won't see her again. Tears. Hugs. Tough goodbyes. We
decide to stay longer in California and visit the cabin at Lake
Arrowhead where we spent our first honeymoon. We take the kids.
Lots of good memories. Lots of sad ones now.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time she asks, (begin ital) Why did I have to get
this damn disease? (end ital)  &QL; 
HOSPICE
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The family is finally starting to realize the end is drawing close.
Time to take more time to smell the roses. The newest plateau is a
hard one: We need to start thinking about some help. Up in the
morning to help with the bath and dressing and toilet care. Home at
noon. Home early from work. She doesn't want strangers helping her
do such private things. Spend a lot of time doing maintenance
things late at night _ laundry, cleaning, paying bills.
</P>
<P>
   A new word enters the vocabulary: caregiver. A new job, only
more intense. Husband, lover, friend for almost 30 years. Now this.
For better or for worse. Strong statement. How many can live it?
</P>
<P>
   A decision has been made to ``talk'' about hospice. She's not
ready, but we need them. Angels enter the house: Hospice workers
give 110 percent and ask for nothing in return. $100 per day.
Limited days for now. More later.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company says it won't pay for hospice. OK, let's
drag them into the 20th century. We can put Rorie in the hospital
for $1,000 per day, or they can approve hospice. Another battle. An
OK, very grudgingly, with a $20,000 cap. (This becomes another
battle later when the cap is exceeded.)
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) So, who cares? Sign 'em up. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   There's a retirement fund that can pay if needed. After this,
who's going to work another 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   Hospice comes three days a week, a few hours a day. Rorie
finally gets used to the angel _ Mary _ who is going to be her
friend, nurse, bather, dresser, listener. Mary becomes part of our
family. The family grows ever larger with great friends who
volunteer time, meals, errands or to just hang around for company.
Our church family gets its marching orders from Nancy. Judy,
Rorie's other surrogate sister, starts a weekly lunch visit _ food,
dishes, talk, listen. Judy and Nancy are a lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   We decide to take a weekend away with Nancy and husband Steve.
Up north in wine country. We used to do this all the time, but now
it's more important. Good time, even with having to lug the
wheelchair up a steep staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas. Rorie's favorite season. She always goes overboard
decorating. The girls try to do it the way their mother would.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice is now fully involved, and Nancy, a home-health-care
nurse by trade, announces she's adding Mondays, her normal day off,
to fill the gaps in Rorie's care. Our oldest daughter, whose son is
still critically ill and requires in-home nursing care, takes
Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Our son moves to Florida to go back to school. His mother tells
him to go and get on with his life. Don't put it on hold because of
her. She will miss him, and it pains her to see him go. She worries
when he and his wife drive non-stop for two days each time they
come home to see for themselves how she is doing. &QL; 
ANOTHER PLATEAU
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: chair, bath aids, suction machine, hospital bed. Over
the next few months, it all ends up in the house. A motorized
recliner is needed for comfort and ease of moving her. Another
fight with the insurance company. The doctor has ordered it, but
the insurance company doesn't think it's needed. So what? Insurance
workers should be given a six-month case of a disease that they
have to live with to get a taste of how their industry treats
people.
</P>
<P>
   Rorie spends most of her day in her recliner. Her legs ache, and
she needs me to adjust her position several times each night. More
time in the chair and a start at considering the hospital bed. The
regular bed is getting too hard to work with. She's exhausted. We
all are.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) I don't want to give up sleeping beside you. It's
the last of so many things lost. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   The hospital bed stays in the garage for a while longer, and she
sleeps in the recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Eating is becoming a drawn-out affair. Even though swallowing is
becoming difficult, she eats what everyone else eats. No feeding
tube. Meals take on a new light. Eventually, it takes more than an
hour to feed her. Meals start early and end late. Thank God for the
people who drop a meal by. A lot of chicken. Sometimes something
special and different. Grateful for it all.
</P>
<P>
   We're all tired. Nerves are frayed. We're spending about 14
hours a day as caregivers. Demands are high. For better or for
worse, in sickness and in health. If this schedule continues, we'll
need to consider alternatives. Respite care, a nursing home. But
she wants to stay home. I want her to stay, but I can't give much
more.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) I'm tired. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the start of a hernia from lifting her in and out of bed,
in and out of her chair, in and out of the shower, the commode. I'm
not sleeping. Hospice is concerned. Her care is taking a lot out of
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance cap is met. Another fight for a (begin ital)
reasonable (end ital) amount of coverage. If we don't win this one,
I'll quit and take my retirement to pay for care. It's three weeks
before the company can make a decision. I hope none of them ever
need this kind of care, or do I? They need to live this to
understand. Cap is increased from $20,000 to $35,000. We're at
$28,000, and hospice is billing about $1,800 a month. Do the math.
Maybe a nursing home for a while, just to get a respite. Hospice
can get us in for about $125 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Another plateau: This time it's big.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) I want to see my mom. I want to see my son. I'm
tired of fighting, and I want to rest. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   More candid talks late at night about us, the last 30 years, the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Finally in the hospital bed. She knows, we all do.
</P>
<P>
   It's done. A few days of being there. A few days of not.
Sometimes she's awake, sometimes coherent. The drugs help. We have
to keep increasing the dosages to help with the breathing and the
peace of mind. It's not going to be pretty. The kids are all here.
Her mom is here. Say goodbye now. Don't wait.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Promise to take care of everyone. Promise. (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   30 years gone.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to go back to Hawaii, ashes spread with orchids on the
sea. &QL; 
IT'S OVER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, we did all this. Over three years. Some days went fast. Some
went very slow. It was physically very demanding the last few
months. Mentally, you think you are prepared, but you're not. I
can't believe how ingrained our routine had become. Days after the
funeral, my youngest daughter and I were both up in the middle of
the night ready to move her, stretch her legs, help her get
comfortable. But she wasn't there. The hospital bed, everything was
folded up and in the garage waiting to be taken away. Katie and I
stood there in the dim light of the hallway and realized there was
nothing for us to do. Rorie didn't need our help anymore.
</P>
<P>
   People say they don't know how we coped for so long. We're a
family, and we did exactly what was required to make Rorie
comfortable for as long as possible. Toward the end, we were tired,
sick and worn out beyond comprehension, but we did what we had to
and blocked out the outside world for a while.
</P>
<P>
   We did the best we could.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
