u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-COLLEGES09-COX     07-08 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-COLLEGES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOAN DEFAULTS THREATEN 14 COLLEGES' AID, REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Soaring default rates on student loans threaten the
existence of 14 historically black colleges and universities, a
government-sponsored corporation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Student Loan Marketing Association, known as Sallie Mae,
said the schools had default rates of 25 percent or more during the
last three fiscal years. Under a 1998 law, these schools could be
declared ineligible to provide need-based federal financial aid for
their students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these 14 institutions would close if they could not
participate in federal financial aid programs,'' warned the report.
</P>
<P>
   The schools must submit default management plans to the U.S.
Department of Education and have three years to improve their
default rates.
</P>
<P>
   While the overall default rate on student loans at all four-year
colleges and universities is about 6 percent, the problems of
student debt extend far beyond these 14 historically black
institutions, emphasized Albert L. Lord, Sallie Mae's vice chairman
and CEO. ``This issue is rather color-blind, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Department of Education lists 45 schools _ mostly
community colleges and for-profit trade schools _ that face
immediate expulsion from the federal aid programs because of their
high default rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Sallie Mae study focuses on why so many students at these
particular historically black colleges don't repay their loans and
recommends ways to reduce the default rate.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 14 endangered colleges, 13 are located in the South. All
largely educate students from families with low incomes. More than
half of their undergraduates came from families with annual incomes
of below $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the report found that poor students are the
least likely to repay their loans. It found that 53 percent of the
students who defaulted came from homes with annual incomes of
$10,000 or less, while another 22 percent had family incomes of
between $10,000 and $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that the troubled institutions lacked the
technology needed to track student data. Many lost track of
students who transferred to other colleges, for instance, and could
not inform them on ways to defer payment rather than to default.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 historically black colleges and universities involved in
the Sallie Mae report were Allen University in Columbia, S.C.;
Arkansas Baptist College in Little Rock, Ark.; Barber-Scotia
College in Concord, N.C.; Central State University in Wilberforce,
Ohio; Huston-Tillotson in Austin; Jarvis Christian College in
Hawkins, Texas; Lane College in Jackson, Tenn.; Mary Holmes College
in West Point, Miss.; Miles College in Birmingham, Ala.; Paul Quinn
College in Dallas; Southwestern Christian College in Terrell,
Texas; Texas College in Tyler; Texas Southern University in
Houston, and Wiley College in Marshall, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The report recommends that the schools develop a default
management team that includes the school's president and other
campus leaders. Because the defaults are related to retention rates
and other issues, the problems go beyond the financial aid office
and must be addressed by faculty and other administrators, said
Kenneth Redd, the Sallie Mae researcher who wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping students in school reduces the default rate, the report
indicates, so it advocates ``more mentoring, academic advising,
peer counseling and tutoring'' to prevent dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni even figure into the equation, said Redd. The schools
with default problems have meager endowments and, thus, less money
of their own to provide to needy students.
</P>
<P>
   The report also urges more counseling on debt management and
consumer finance for students.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
