<HEADER>
A3445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOUNTAIN-BALLET-REVIE     07-08 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNTAIN-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 `FOUNTAIN OF THE BAKCHISARAI': KIROV REVIVES A '30s CURIOUSITY  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The kind of weight and urgency that helped make ``The
Fountain of the Bakchisarai'' so thrillingly exotic on film in 1953
are no longer a part of dance.
</P>
<P>
   To see the work today _ as presented by the Kirov Ballet in a
staging by Sergei Radlov of the 1934 original by Rostislav Zakharov
_ is to see not less, perhaps, but something very different. If the
ballet were a tapestry, it would look more like the work of Matisse
than the rich hangings designed by Valentina Khodasevich for this
production, given the even musical flow of the dancing and the
somewhat abstracted acting.
</P>
<P>
   Altynai Asylmuratova came closest to a blend of the two
generations in a New York role debut as Zarema, the jilted, loving,
favorite wife of the Tatar leader Girei, on Wednesday night at the
Metropolitan Opera House. Ms. Asylmuratova's slender, arching body
radiated pathos. Her face was a mask of tragedy so believable _ and
so hauntingly like portraits of Anna Pavlova in the 1920s _ that
Ms. Asylmuratova's curtain-call smiles were startling.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Part was appropriately youthful as Maria, the Polish
princess with whom Girei falls in love. But her bouncy,
girl-next-door portrayal, well-danced as it was, gave no hint of
the sadness that was to come in her somewhat more believable third
act, when Maria, alone in a foreign country, is stabbed to death by
Zarema. Ilya Kuznetsov was elegant in his slower moments but rather
bland as Vatslav, Maria's fiance. Vasili Sherbakov was superb as
Girei's wild high-flying lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Ponomarev repeated his stirring performance as Girei,
his stretched arms, expansive chest and heel-bound strides
suggesting the wide wind-torn prairies of an alien land and culture
in an intriguingly modern-looking stylization. The lead cast was
completed by Elena Chmil, Alexandra Iosifidi and Petr Stasiunas.
Boris Gruzin conducted Boris Asafiev's shapeless score. (Bring back
Minkus, one balletomane muttered.)
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fountain of the Bakchisarai'' will be performed Saturday
afternoon at the Metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
