<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(jt) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Fran Drescher Tries New Cure
</P>
<P>
   Add the Nanny to the list of television types taking to the New
York stage.
</P>
<P>
   Details are still being worked out, but it looks likely that
come this fall, Fran Drescher will star in ``Sweet Deliverance,'' a
new comedy by Eric Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which is expected to begin rehearsals in November with
a Broadway opening scheduled for December, will have a staged
reading on Monday at an undisclosed, Off-Broadway theater.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drescher, best known as the sexily obstreperous caretaker in
the CBS comedy ``The Nanny,'' will play Cora, a hospital intern who
transforms herself into an ``amalgam of Dr. Kevorkian and Martha
Stewart,'' the show's producer, Alexander H. Cohen, said. As that
description implies, the show's subject matter includes euthanasia,
a topic that may not scream comedy but that Cohen believes will be
in safe hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Fran is the most gifted comedienne since Mary Tyler
Moore or Elaine May,'' said Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Rich, Ms. Drescher's manager, said the play would be the
actress' first professional stage appearance in New York. Ms. Rich
said Ms. Drescher appeared in ``The Rug Merchants of Chaos,'' a
play by Ronald Ribman, at the Pasadena Playhouse in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had six years of a series, and this is kind of an
interesting turn in the road,'' Ms. Rich said.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ms. Drescher's limited theatrical credits, one theater
professional said she may be a powerful draw at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fran Drescher is an extraordinarily potent attraction for
theater parties,'' said Ronald Lee, president of Group Sales Box
Office, a ticket sales service. ``She has legions of fans that
connect to her New York brand of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   No director has been signed to the project, but Cohen said he
has discussed the play with David Warren, who most recently
received good reviews for his direction of Richard Greenberg's
``Hurrah at Last,'' at the Gramercy Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Great Minds ...
</P>
<P>
   Let the parties begin.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmation came this week that both the Joseph Papp Public
Theater and the Manhattan Theater Club will produce versions of
``The Wild Party'' next spring, and that they may play
concurrently.
</P>
<P>
   The first contestant up will be at the theater club, where
previews will begin in late January for a February opening of the
composer Andrew Lippa's version of ``Wild Party,'' based on the
lengthy jazz-era poem by Joseph Moncure March. Gabriel Barre
directs; Mark Dendy will handle the choreography.
</P>
<P>
   The Public's version, also based on the March poem, was written
by George C. Wolfe and Michael John LaChuisa and will begin
rehearsals on Jan. 11, 2000. No opening date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The Public's production has been rumored to be headed for a
Broadway theater, a suggestion given extra credence this week when
talent agents received word that performers would be paid under a
Broadway contract with Actors Equity, rather than the lower Off
Broadway rates usually paid at the Public.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Fineman, a spokeswoman for the Public, said she could not
confirm a Broadway booking but said the show was part of the
Public's 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Change for Elaine May
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could fault the 1998-99 Broadway season for lacking
serious drama. But with the exception of a few dark cacklers like
``The Lonesome West,'' it was woefully short on laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine May hopes to change that. The veteran comedian and
screenwriter has a new play in the pipeline, and her producer is
looking to make it her first play on Broadway. The play, ``Taller
Than a Dwarf,'' concerns a man and woman in a faltering
relationship. Alan Arkin, who partnered with Ms. May on last year's
``Power Plays,'' will direct. Tony Walton will design the sets.
</P>
<P>
   The producer, Julian Schlossberg, said he was aiming for a
spring 2000 opening in a mid-size Broadway theater. ``Elaine has
appeared on Broadway but never written for it,'' Schlossberg said.
``It should be a gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Was That Celsius?
</P>
<P>
   If any more evidence were needed of her British roots, Ruthie
Henshall says she enjoyed this week's weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a novelty,'' Ms. Henshall said, of New York's recent
ovenlike climate. ``We don't get summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henshall knows a thing or two about heat. For the last
month, she has been raising the temperature of the musical
``Chicago,'' playing the sexy shooter Velma Kelly. The role, her
Broadway debut, is a new one for Ms. Henshall, even if the show
isn't; in 1997, she starred as Velma's foil, Roxie Hart, in the
London production of ``Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the switch? ``I'd had enough of Roxie,'' Ms. Henshall said,
``But to do Velma? It was just too tempting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Henshall, 30, said she has had remarkable luck since landing
her first acting job at 18 in a British touring company of ``A
Chorus Line.'' Since then, she's appeared frequently on the West
End, where she won an Olivier Award for ``She Loves Me,'' in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Her knack for good choices included passing on the ill-fated
spring revue, ``The Gershwins' Fascinating Rhythm,'' in favor of
another run in ``Chicago.'' Immediately after her run as Velma, Ms.
Henshall will join the cast of ``Putting It Together,'' a Stephen
Sondheim revue, set to open in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in trusting my instincts,'' she said, with a smile.
``And things keep materializing for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
