<HEADER>
A3478 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-EDGE09-COX     07-08 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-EDGE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coming of age on the `Edge'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's not much cutting-edge about ``Edge of Seventeen,''
another gay-teen saga of coming out/coming of age. Still, there's
much here to like _ from its refreshingly unforced tone to its
really appealing young lead, newcomer Chris Stafford, who,
depending on the angle, resembles either a young Jim Carrey or a
young Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   It's the summer of '84 in Sandusky, Ohio. Young Eric (Stafford),
a music-loving high school junior with Manhattan dreams, has taken
a summer job dishing up Tater Logs at the local theme-park
restaurant. His quasi-sorta girlfriend, Maggie (Tina Holmes), works
there, too. So does Rod (Andersen Gabrych), a bottle-blond Ohio
State student who, when asked if he has a girlfriend, says without
hesitation, ``Yeah. His name is Danny.'' By summer's end, Rod has
seduced Eric, who stops dressing like a Sandusky senior and starts
secretly frequenting the town's gay bar, the Fruit and Nut Club.
</P>
<P>
   What works best about ``Edge of Seventeen'' is the way Eric
slowly but surely edges into a new identity. Not just a new sense
of sexual orientation, but a new sense of himself as a whole.
Further, this isn't just another
insecure-but-likable-gay-falls-for-tantalizingly-insensitive-hunk
story. Rather, the film explores an impressive range of emotional
issues _ from Maggie's conflicted feelings as she realizes
something's not quite ``right'' about her relationship with Eric to
the reaction of Eric's mom (Stephanie McVay), who's spunky,
supportive, sympathetic and yet pure Sandusky when it comes to even
thinking that her son might be gay.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, a crowd favorite last year at the Los Angeles Gay and
Lesbian Film Festival, tends to run out of steam by the last 20
minutes. But it never runs out of ideas. Or intriguing emotional
situations. Plus, it has the courage to leave some things
unresolved. When Eric confesses to Angie (Lea DeLaria), the raucous
yet goodhearted lesbian who runs the Fruit and Nut Club, that he
thought things would be easier after he came out, their initial
reaction is laughter. It's followed by a knowing moment of awkward,
eyes-averted silence that tacitly acknowledges that in 1984 _ or
1999 _ being gay isn't always easy, no matter which side of the
closet you're on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edge of Seventeen''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chris Stafford. Directed by David Moreton. Not rated,
but there are sexual situations, strong language and adult themes.
1 hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An appealing take on a familiar theme.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
