<HEADER>
A3479 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FANATIC09-COX     07-08 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FANATIC09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Fanatic' addicted to cultural confusion
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hanif Kureishi, the sardonic Brit writer responsible for ``My
Beautiful Laundrette'' and ``Sammy and Rosie Get Laid'' in the
'80s, ends the '90s with another look at English culture clash.
He's gone from angry young man to miffed middle-ager, and the
transition isn't convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Son the Fanatic'' centers on Parvez (Om Puri), a Pakistani
immigrant who drives a taxi through the puddly streets of an
industrial British town. He hasn't struck it rich like old pal
Fizzy (Harish Patel), but he's a big booster of Western values.
He's thrilled when his teenage son, Farid (Akbar Kurtha), gets
engaged to the Anglo daughter of the local police chief. So when
Farid abruptly calls off the nuptials and starts selling off the
contents of his bedroom, Parvez assumes there's only one answer:
His son must be on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. He's addicted to something else _ religion, specifically,
Islam. When Farid coerces his dad into allowing a Muslim leader
into their home, Parvez finds himself crowded out. So he spends
more time with Bettina (Rachel Griffiths), a prostitute he
chauffeurs late into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter Kureishi fills the movie with stark conflicts _ the
women-excluding puritanism of Islam, contrasting with the
lecherous, boozy debauches of a visiting German businessman
(Stellan Skarsgard, representing the worst of Western excess). The
film heads toward a climactic street fight (similar to the one in
``Laundrette''), which pits the young Muslim radicals against the
local hookers, placing Parvez smack in the middle of a battle
between Farid and Bettina. The symmetry is all too convenient. More
damaging is the developing romance between Parvez and the
prostitute. It's tender, but scarcely plausible, and Griffiths is
stuck trying to make sense of hooker-with-a-heart-of-gold cliches,
British style.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Son
</P>
<P>
   the Fanatic''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Om Puri, Rachel Griffiths. Rated R for sexuality,
language and a scene of drug use. At the Tara. 1 hour, 32 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A culture-clash drama marred by heavy-handed
plotting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
