<HEADER>
A3483 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PIE09-COX     07-08 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PIE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Say bye-bye to dignity in sophomoric, sex-obsessed high school
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's no dignity at the movies these days.
</P>
<P>
   Not with what Mike Myers' big, ugly Scotsman leaves for Austin
Powers to drink. Not with what those poorly drawn 'toonsters sing
over and over in the big-screen ``South Park.'' And certainly not
with any of the high school juvenilities tossed about in ``American
Pie,'' the latest gargantuan gross-out movie made for an audience
that probably shouldn't see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' is about four high school seniors. Not girls.
Girls at that age are always smarter than boys. It's about dumb
guys, a quartet of virgins so desperate for sex they make a
dumb-guy pact to finally score big by prom night.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and there's a pie in the plot, too. An apple pie. Freshly
baked by a good-hearted mom and left on the kitchen counter for her
dumb, desperate-for-sex senior son, Jim (Jason Biggs).
</P>
<P>
   Many young adult and younger moviegoers out there already have
heard through the preview grapevine what happens to that pie. It
isn't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   But it is kind of grotesquely funny. Which is also an accurate
statement about several of the jokes in ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a raunchy, throwaway, pre-adult, R-rated sexcapade with
dirty dialogue and more than one risque encounter between Jim and a
foreign female student that's broadcast over the Internet. There's
also the grossest joke involving a beer you're ever likely to see
on film.
</P>
<P>
   Many early preview audiences _ and there have been many
pre-screenings to generate talk about the movie _ have laughed
themselves silly.
</P>
<P>
   But little in ``American Pie'' really deserves honest laughs.
The movie rarely comes close to matching the free-spirited hilarity
of the embarrassingly funny ``There's Something About Mary,''
``Pie's'' obvious inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary'' moved at a breakneck pace, and many of its grossest
moments were mere flashes onscreen. Audiences could think, ``No,
they're not going to show that, are they? They wouldn't dare.''
Then, voila. For an instant.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pie,'' directing brothers Chris and Paul Weitz have chosen
to linger over their stinkiest stuff. As we watch our four doofus
heroes march toward their expected moments of physical bliss, the
movie becomes not just a comedy with rank moments, but a fully
formed rank comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the four guys has a tale that, every now and then,
rises above it all. ``Pie's'' jock, Oz (Chris Klein, the brainless
jock of ``Election''), starts to fall for chorus member Heather
(Mena Suvari). He's joined the choir in a bid to meet girls, and
their flowering romance evokes some genuine charm.
</P>
<P>
   But charm isn't really what ``Pie'' is about. It's about losing
your virginity _ and any dignity you ever thought you had. That it
does very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Biggs, Alyson Hannigan and Chris Klein. Rated R
for strong sexuality, crude sexual dialogue, language and drinking
(all involving teens). At metro theaters. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Gross-out is in. This is one of the grossest.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
