<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ROAD09-COX     07-08 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ROAD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A taut trip on a chilling `Road'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The squeaky-clean suburbs of Washington darken into something
strange, almost hallucinatory, as a bloodied young boy stumbles
down a tidy street in the opening moments of ``Arlington Road.''
</P>
<P>
   In director Mark Pellington's paranoia thriller, the boy is
Brady (Mason Gamble), son of Oliver and Cheryl Lang (Tim Robbins
and Joan Cusack). They've just moved next door to Michael Faraday
(Jeff Bridges) and his son Grant (Spencer Treat Clark). These
newcomers seem like an impossibly wholesome bunch, almost a
throwback to the '50s ideal of lemonade stands and tag football in
the back yard. They're so perfect there's something off about them.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Michael starts to believe. A professor of
domestic terrorism, he's well-informed about our country's history
of bloody personal vendettas. In the classroom, he links Timothy
McVeigh and the Unabomber back to John Wilkes Booth, and even the
leaders of the Revolutionary War. He also has a personal interest
in the subject, since his wife, an FBI agent, died in a bloody
shootout with what appeared to be a survivalist group.
</P>
<P>
   So when Oliver vaguely describes his line of work as
``structural engineer,'' quickly hides the blueprints he's poring
over and turns out to have gone by another name in his youth,
Michael becomes convinced that the Langs are up to some deadly
secret business. His suspicions are amplified by parental jealousy.
While Grant remains aloof and distant toward his actual dad, he
finds in Oliver a safe father-figure he can talk to, someone
untainted by the shared tragedy of the death of Grant's mom.
</P>
<P>
   So is Michael onto something? Or is he having a meltdown,
letting his personal and professional lives intertwine? The movie
keeps us guessing, though it can't totally sustain its suspense. In
its second half, it becomes too moody and baroque for its own good,
relying on monster-movie shots of Robbins and Cusack to reflect
Bridges' anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Hope Davis as Michael's long-suffering girlfriend is largely
wasted in a one-note role. And Bridges has to sweat through one
freak-out scene too many. Pellington overuses the gimmick of
characters surprised by someone walking up unexpectedly behind
them, among other hokey screen cliches. Even so, Ehren Kruger's
script manages to stay a few steps ahead of us, luring us toward a
climax that's bound to be one of the most talked-about endings of
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The film's key strength is the savvy casting of baby-faced
Robbins and expert comedian Cusack. They're the sort of actors who
can switch from cozy to creepy in a heartbeat. Though it's marred
by patches of obviousness, ``Arlington Road'' arrives in theaters
with a sharp sense of timing. It's a variation of Alfred
Hitchcock's chilling 1943 film ``Shadow of a Doubt,'' hot-wired to
a national nervous system that's already jolted by heavily armed
teenage commandos and Midwestern spree shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arlington Road''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeff Bridges,Tim Robbins, Joan Cusack. Rated R for
violence and some language.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A smart, unsettling paranoia thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
