<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VANYA-THEATER-REVIEW-     07-08 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VANYA-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNCLE VANYA': CHEKHOV VIA DUBLIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The nighttime sky glows with summer lightning, and
the listless residents of the estate wilt in the suffocating heat.
Yet a discernible nip chills the air of the Gate Theater Dublin's
new production of ``Uncle Vanya.'' It is an emotional cold front
that lowers the temperature of Chekhov's stifling household and
leaves its members as distanced from one another as solitary
figures in a winter whiteout.
</P>
<P>
   This frosty ``Vanya,'' with a fresh translation by Ireland's
eminent playwright Brian Friel, is not destined to be a crowd
pleaser. The passions simmer so faintly, you can hardly tell when
its pilot light is on. Not even Vanya's violent stalking of
Serebryakov, the pompous professor who has ostensibly ruined
Vanya's life, has much urgency to it.
</P>
<P>
   The defining face in this portrait belongs neither to Niall
Buggy's disintegrating Vanya, nor to Donna Dent's valiant Sonya.
Susannah Harker's Yelena, the ice princess and object of Vanya's
and Astrov's affections, is the clarifying presence here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harker's performance is emblematic of the stinginess of the
Gate's production, which opened on Wednesday night as part of
Lincoln Center Festival '99. You can give yourself over to the
beauty onstage, but it doesn't offer much in return. With the
assistance of a chromatic text by Friel, whose work has often been
compared to Chekhov's, and an unobtrusively elegant set by David
Gaucher, the director, Ben Barnes, has the appropriate
accouterments. You wait in vain all evening, though, for him to do
something wonderful with them.
</P>
<P>
   At the right moments a delicate touch is the most consoling
gesture in the world. Too much delicacy onstage, and you want to
slap the hand away.
</P>
<P>
   Russian theater ensembles have an instinctively adverse reaction
to treatments of Chekhov's works as if they were made of porcelain;
these days companies like the Sovremennik and the Moscow Art
Theater employ a go-for-broke ethic with the words of their
greatest playwright, italicizing the characters' tragic romances
and existential crises. Barnes and his Anglo-Irish troupe take a
more measured approach, which has its satisfactions. The outlines
of suppressed aches _ Sonya's for Astrov; Vanya's for the life he
didn't live _ are finely etched.
</P>
<P>
   And the simple directness of Friel's translation often
invigorates the discourse. Yelena's retort to Vanya's profession of
love, usually rendered as something like, ``There's nothing I can
say to you,'' is translated here as, ``I feel nothing for you.''
The desolate effect on Vanya is abundantly clear and makes Vanya's
gun-toting pursuit of the focus of all his disappointments _
Yelena's husband, Serebryakov _ seem almost reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Buggy, who made a splash in New York a decade ago as the
childlike Casimir in Friel's ``Aristocrats'' for the Manhattan
Theater Club, is again the main attraction. His Vanya is a sad
little afterthought of a man who might be recruited to sing
``Cellophane'' in a Slavic road company of ``Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   In a houseful of unhappiness, of embittered, spineless or
self-deluded souls, Vanya is the most fragile, and Buggy's
breakdown in the third act of this four-act play provides it with
its most affecting moments. You can sense his Vanya cracking up by
degree, and then watch him crumble completely in his confrontation
with Serebryakov (T.P. McKenna) when he coldly announces his plan
to sell the failing estate out from under Vanya and his niece
Sonya.
</P>
<P>
   But Vanya is often the only truly passionate being on the stage
of the La Guardia Drama Theater, where the production runs through
next Sunday. ``Bored, bored, bored'' is the characters' mantra, and
all too frequently Barnes and his cast give in to a burdening sense
of ennui. The actors' pauses between lines, one presumes, are
intended to give depth to the household's searing silences.
Instead, they merely add to the theatrical airlessness and to the
feeling that the director approached this project with a little too
much reverence.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harker's Yelena, the petulant trophy wife who flirts
guiltlessly with Astrov even as she destroys the hopes of Vanya and
Sonya, is a case in point. Serene and shapely, she is all steely
hauteur. The performance is statuesque and virtually frozen. No
sparks are set off between Ms. Harker and John Kavanagh, whose
brilliant Joxer was a memorable part of the Gate's production of
``Juno and the Paycock'' that visited Broadway briefly during the
summer of 1988. But he is a bit remote as the dissipated heartthrob
Astrov, ``Dr. Vodka'' in Friel's terrific labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Most productions of ``Vanya'' present Sonya as plain, lovelorn
and devastatingly sad. Ms. Dent's performance is along those
classical lines; in one instance in which the silence works
beautifully, Barnes places Sonya in a doorway at the play's end as
the sound of hooves of the horses carrying her beloved Astrov fade
away.
</P>
<P>
   The other performances range from stodgy to serviceable,
although Eamon Morrissey exceeds expectations in the usually
peripheral role of Telegin, which Friel has built up considerably
for comic effect.
</P>
<P>
   What one pines for here, however, is a little more comedy. And
for that matter, a little more drama.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `UNCLE VANYA'
</P>
<P>
   An adaptation by Brian Friel of Anton Chekhov's play; directed
by Ben Barnes; sets by David Gaucher; costumes by Jacqueline
Kobler; lighting by Rupert Murray. The Gate Theater, Dublin,
presented by Lincoln Center Festival '99, Nigel Redden, director.
At the La Guardia Drama Theater, Amsterdam Avenue at 65th Street.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Daphne Carroll (Marina), John Kavanagh (Astrov), Niall
Buggy (Vanya), T.P. McKenna (Serebryakov), Eamon Morrissey
(Telegin), Donna Dent (Sonya), Susannah Harker (Yelena), Ann Rowan
(Maria) and Ciaran Reilly (Laborer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
