u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAVITY-FILM-REVIEW-N     07-08 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAVITY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEFYING GRAVITY': WINNING A POPULARITY CONTEST BUT LOSING HIS
SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timeliness is the principal virtue of ``Defying Gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after the brutal murder of a gay college
student touched the conscience of the nation, this modest,
well-meaning debut film pivots on a vicious assault on a homosexual
college student.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Defying Gravity,'' while illuminating the fraternity house
culture that is the breeding ground of this particular outburst of
hatred, is chiefly concerned with the angst of John Griffith
(Daniel Chilson), one of the fraternity brothers, and with
imparting lessons of self-understanding, decency and tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   For all its praiseworthy intentions, ``Defying Gravity,''
written and directed by John Keitel, plods along, never catching
dramatic fire, sometimes suffering from amateurish acting and often
relying on its intrusive and treacly music to impart mood and
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Griff, as he is known, has been having an affair with Pete
Bradley (Don Handfield), while still pretending to the fraternity,
to girls on campus, to his best friend, Todd Bentley (Niklaus
Lange), and even to himself that he is heterosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Pete, who used to live in the fraternity house, is angry with
Griff, because he is keeping their affair a secret, refuses to
spend the night and cannot be counted upon for dates and a
long-term future like that the loving Todd plans with his
girlfriend, Heather (Lesley Tesh).
</P>
<P>
   So Griff and Pete agree one night to meet to talk things out.
The meeting place is a gay coffee house, where Griff feels
uncomfortable. Pete and Griff leave and argue. Just after they
part, Pete is attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The assault forces Griff literally and figuratively to look at
himself in the mirror, to understand that there are others
struggling with the same problem, like Denetra Washington (Linna
Carter), a black classmate, and with Todd's help, to come to grips
with who he is and how he feels about Pete.
</P>
<P>
   Good intentions don't necessarily make good drama.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DEFYING GRAVITY'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by John Keitel; director of photography,
Thomas M. Harting; edited by Matthew Yagle; songs composed and
performed by Jon T. Howard and music composed and arranged by Tim
Westergren; production designer, Scott McPhail; produced by David
Clayton Miller and Jack Koll; released by Jour de Fete Films and
Boom Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 100 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Daniel Chilson (John Griffith), Niklaus Lange (Todd
Bentley), Don Handfield (Pete Bradley), Linna Carter (Denetra
Washington), Seabass Diamond (Matthew McDougal) and Lesley Tesh
(Heather).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
