</P>
<P>
   FILM-AMERICAN PIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The new comedy ``American Pie'' doesn't seem new. It
shrewdly rekindles the spirit of the 1982 raunch-comedy,
``Porky's,'' where every member of the cast was obsessed with sex.
But _ surprise _ ``Pie'' manages to be both smart and calculating.
In the end, the movie is about romance. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story
has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ROAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Road,'' directed by Mark Pellington, feels a little
like a pastiche: a little methodical Alan J. Pakula paranoia here,
a little manic Brian de Palma paranoia there, with the Hitchockian
undercurrent still in place, all wrapped up in Pellington's
music-video background. The surprising thing, given all these
ingredients, is how well ``Arlington Road'' manages to cohere. By
ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
