<SLUG> BC-FILM-ARLINGTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDING OF `ARLINGTON ROAD' ISN'T ENOUGH TO SAVE THE MOVIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This almost never happens. ``Arlington Road'' is a clumsy and
incompetent thriller for nine-tenths of its running time but has an
ending that is so clever and goes so wildly against expectations
that it almost exonerates the film.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, the operative word here is ``almost'' _ because, as
daring as it is, it's not enough to ultimately save this turkey of
a movie. But if you do happen to find yourself in this thing, and
you're thinking of leaving before it's over, think again.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about a George Washington University history
professor (Jeff Bridges) who teaches a class in political terrorism
and is having a hard time getting over the death of his wife _ an
FBI agent who was killed in a botched, Ruby Ridge-like operation.
</P>
<P>
   One day, he begins to suspect that something is not quite right
with his likable next-door neighbor (Tim Robbins), and it isn't too
long before he concludes that the guy is a big-time terrorist who
masterminded a massive, Oklahoma City-like bombing of a St. Louis
federal building.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if it seems overly coincidental to have Ruby Ridge,
Oklahoma City and an academic expert in terrorism in one premise,
be warned that this is only the beginning of a string of amazing
coincidences that motivates every scene in the film.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the script _ by first-timer Ehren Kruger _ also has a
definite lunatic edge to it. It's seriously out to convince us that
domestic terrorist acts like the Oklahoma City bombing are not the
work of small groups of disaffected weirdos, but an organized
conspiracy of ``millions.''
</P>
<P>
   And this paranoia is accentuated by director Mark Pellington
(``Going All the Way''), who has a way of painting his scenes with
the broadest imaginable strokes, and encourages all his actors to
overact _ especially Bridges, who runs around the movie like Jack
Nicholson in ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the only real saving grace of the movie is its end,
which nicely shakes us of our cinematically induced catatonia for a
few moments, and demonstrates what a pleasure it can be when a
formuliac Hollywood dares to break its formula.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington Road. Directed by Mark Pellington. Written by Ehren
Kruger. Cast: Jeff Bridges, Tim Robbins, Joan Cusack, Hope Davis,
Robert Gossett. Screen Gems/Columbia. 117 minutes. Rated R for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
