<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINNER-FILM-REVIEW-NY     07-08 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINNER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DINNER GAME': GUESS WHO'S COMING TO DINNER (TO BE THE
ENTREE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francis Veber's giddy, lightweight odd-couple comedies are
guilty pleasures. Enough French moviegoers know that to have made
``The Dinner Game'' the second-biggest hit in France last year,
after ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the beguiling silliness of his best French farces,
like ``Les Comperes'' before it became ``Father's Day,'' few have
traveled well. Bad things happen to Veber's fluffy conceits when
they cross the Atlantic, as evidenced by a sorry string of remakes
like ``Jungle 2 Jungle,'' ``Pure Luck'' and ``The Toy.'' ``La Cage
Aux Folles,'' which he wrote with Edouard Molinaro, is still the
best-known illustration of this filmmaker's light, remake-ready
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put a cat and a dog in the same bag and they end up
friends, I like that very much,'' Veber recently told The Los
Angeles Times. Now ``The Dinner Game'' finds him trying that tactic
yet again, this time with a wicked twist.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a smug, wealthy publisher named Pierre Brochant,
played by Thierry Lhermitte as the apotheosis of aging yuppiedom,
regularly joins a group of his friends in a contest to see who can
bring the biggest fool to dinner. ``The Dinner Game,'' Veber's
brightest comedy in a long while, plays off that nasty joke.
</P>
<P>
   Handsome, blue-eyed and imperious, Brochant doesn't even bother
to procure his own talent. But when he hears second-hand about an
unkempt clownish bore who makes architectural models out of
matchsticks and takes them very seriously indeed, he decides that
Francois Pignon (Jacques Villeret) must be the perfect date.
Feeling even more contemptuous after he meets this hopeless
bungler, Brochant would undoubtedly like to get the dinner over
with and lose Pignon. What Veber likes better (and the audience
will surely agree) is having the fun of watching Pignon wreck
Brochant's complacent life.
</P>
<P>
   With a setup like this, we know immediately where the film is
going. First of all, it's going to Hollywood (where Dreamworks will
remake it, Veber hopes, as a vehicle for Robin Williams). Second,
it's going to turn the tables on Brochant and show him what being
an idiot really means. It's a good thing that Veber's films are
less about speechifying in the final reel than about the very funny
and diabolical bumbling it takes to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dinner Game,'' which Veber wrote and directed, is one of
his better-constructed comedies of errors. It gets going as Pignon
arrives at Brochant's apartment on the appointed night, only to
find that the irritable publisher has injured his back and can't
attend the mean-spirited dinner party after all. (Good thing: it's
not an event through which many viewers would like to squirm.) This
would eradicate any relationship between the two men if Pignon were
willing to go away. But he's not. He stays around to do helpful
things, like mixing up Brochant's wife with his girlfriend and
referring to the latter as ``the nympho with the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a class by himself,'' Brochant and his friends agree,
once they begin marveling at Pignon's handiwork. It turns out that
no task is too simple for Pignon to bungle, no instructions too
straightforward for him to misconstrue. All the film needs is the
abrupt departure of Brochant's angry wife, and Pignon has more than
enough to work with, as he ``helps'' to track her down and find out
if she has a lover.
</P>
<P>
   The story reaches its peak as Pignon invites a hard-nosed tax
inspector to visit Brochant's apartment, which is filled with
undeclared artworks that have to be hidden in a hurry. Brochant is
even forced to poison a bottle of expensive wine with vinegar so
that the tax man will think him a man of modest tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dinner Game,'' which features a particularly wry
performance from Francis Huster as the suspicious inspector, is
staged modestly in high-sitcom style, with a spareness not liable
to be found in its Hollywood version; it began as a theatrical
comedy by Veber and still has the feel of a one-set play. It
depends on the actors instead of the scenery to set its tone.
</P>
<P>
   While L'Hermitte's hauteur makes him the perfect fall guy,
Villeret clowns blithely without sentimentalizing his character. He
won a Cesar as best actor for what will remain his role, regardless
of which American actor eventually plays it.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DINNER GAME'
</P>
<P>
   Written (in French, with English subtitles) and directed by
Francis Veber; director of photography, Luciano Tovoli; edited by
Georges Klotz; produced by Gaumont International/Alain Poire;
released by Lions Gate Films.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 82 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   RATING: This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Jacques Villeret (Francois Pignon), Thierry Lhermitte
(Pierre Brochant), Francis Huster (Just LeBlanc), Daniel Prevost
(Cheval), Alexandra Vandernoot (Christine), Catherine Frot
(Marlene), Edgar Givry (Cordier), Christian Pereira (Sorbier) and
Petronille Moss (Louisette Blond).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
