<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3497 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV15-     07-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV15-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR DIGNITY AT TABLE 4
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, July 15)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea that work is superior to welfare because it provides
self-esteem and dignity can be difficult to appreciate when your
boss discourages bathroom breaks. Or you're not allowed to talk to
your co-workers unless it's about refilling the ketchup bottles.
</P>
<P>
   This is some of what writer Barbara Ehrenreich learned when she
went undercover as an unskilled worker in Florida to get a
firsthand look at the world of the working poor, the only one open
to most former welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the writer and lecturer, whose books take a biting
and informed look at the status quo in America, passed herself off
as a divorced homemaker with brief experience as a housekeeper. She
ended up working two full-time waitress jobs, with time only for a
shower in between. She quit after a month when she still wasn't
making enough to keep her $500-a-month spot in a trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrenreich's story, ``Nickel and Dimed,'' published in Harper's
Magazine in January, introduced readers to some of the real people
who work at a Florida chain restaurant attached to an economy
motel.
</P>
<P>
   She's gratified, though a little surprised, that it got more
attention than any magazine piece she's ever written. ``It wasn't
intended to be an anthropological or sociological study,'' she
says. ``I just wanted to see if I could survive.''
</P>
<P>
   She also felt frustration because she doesn't think she broke
any big story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to say, `You already know this, people. You've seen
this arithmetic before.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The arithmetic is you take the cost of prevailing rents against
entry-level wages, or in her case $2.43 an hour plus tips, and
there's little left for gas, food, waitress uniforms, laundry and
for a welfare parent, child expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Her co-workers, many of whom worked two jobs, put as much as
they could into housing but had to live in shared rooms, with
relatives, the occasional motel room. One woman who lived in an old
truck was delighted when her boss let her park overnight in the
motel parking lot. Ehrenreich's comment: ``With benefits like that,
how could anyone think of leaving?''
</P>
<P>
   There was no time or money for extras and for those with two
jobs, little time for family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck,'' she says, ``by the distance from the mass
media and their lives. They didn't even talk about movies. There
also wasn't much talk of TV, because you have to have time to watch
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrenreich, who grew up in a blue-collar family and was married
to a union organizer, said the camaraderie of the workers, covering
for each other so one could run to the bathroom or grab a
cigarette, rang true to her experience. Their approach to the
meanest chore surprised her. ``I was astonished all the time by
their work ethic, almost enthusiasm.'' She described her co-workers
as ``far too smart and funny and caring for the work they do and
the wages they're paid.'' And she really wishes they'd form a
union.
</P>
<P>
   Their biggest complaint, she said, was management's basic
attitude that employees can't be trusted. ``We were always being
scolded.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming from her world, that was a shock. ``I'm a free-lance
writer. How privileged is that? No one tells me what to do.'' But
for the first time in her life since junior high she said she felt
that she wasn't trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shaken the first day when another employee warned me to
be careful of what I had in my purse because they (the managers)
would search it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could be fired for anything. There was no freedom of
speech. No freedom of assembly.'' One place had a rule against
gossip, which meant that you couldn't talk to another worker unless
it was about the job. Employees were not allowed to patronize the
adjacent bar and couldn't eat in their own restaurant after their
shift.
</P>
<P>
   The writer made a few conclusions from her experience _ one,
that low-wage work may not be a solution to poverty or even
homelessness _ and is now looking into lack of privacy issues on
the job, not only in entry-level work but the workplace in general.
</P>
<P>
   She believes there's a growing lack of civil rights in the
workplace. ``In some places it's becoming almost totalitarian.''
</P>
<P>
   How much one magazine story can make a difference is hard to
judge, but she can claim one small victory. One of the restaurant's
owners contacted her and said he was appalled by what she'd
reported, including the lack of soap and toilet paper in the
employees' bathroom. He promised to make those bathroom
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't say anything about raises.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
