u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-POLITICS09-C     07-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP UNVEILS ONLINE TV
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican National Committee on Thursday
launched what might be called GOP-TV, a Internet-based broadcast
outlet with a global reach that requires no federal license.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just video, it's history,'' RNC Chairman Jim
Nicholson gushed about the party's new video streaming technology.
``Not even the self-styled father of the Internet, Al Gore, had a
hand in this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' initial online offering was a caustic put-down
of the vice president, the leading candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Philadelphia at the RNC's annual summer meeting,
Nicholson said the video technology will let Republicans air news
conferences and special political events live over the Internet
during the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also envisioned, he said, is the ability to provide party
activists with ``two-way real-time feedback over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   This is but one tool, he said, in a budding ``e.GOP Project''
that he described as ``a comprehensive cutting-edge commitment by
the Republican Party to harness the Web's power for its
communications, organizing and fund raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson pledged that in the presidential campaign after this
one, Republicans will be raising at least 25 percent of the
small-donor contributions through e-mail solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2004 elections, he said, all 50 GOP state parties and
their affiliated groups will be wired for special intranet
programming. He also envisioned building a ``national community of
100,000 on-line activists.'' By that time, he said, the Republicans
will be able to append e-mail address to as many as 30 million
names in their database of 150 million registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's Democratic counterpart, Joe Andrew, wasn't much
impressed. A technology maven in his own right, Andrews said the
Democratic National Committee is developing a cutting-edge plan of
its own to leverage the Internet for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DNC technology plan ensures that in every state, in every
district, in every election, Democrats can run campaigns that are
both high-tech and high-touch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These campaigns, he added, ``will fuse the innovation of Silicon
Valley with the intimacy of Main Street'' and ``combine the sizzle
of Hollywood with the steak of the union hall.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Republican ``revolutionary video technology''
seemingly delivers, as advertised, TV-quality, full-motion,
full-screen video broadcasting with stereo sound on the Internet.
It can be seen via the committee's Web site (http://www.rnc.org.)
</P>
<P>
   But would-be viewers must first download a proprietary module
produced exclusively for the Republicans by Pixelon Corp. of San
Juan Capistrano, Calif. It required nearly 40 minutes Thursday
afternoon to download a ``buffer'' of an anti-Gore film on a
mid-speed Pentium machine running the Windows NT operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Once acquired, however, ``The World According to Gore'' ran
without a technical flaw. And it could be queued up repeatedly
without any further downloading delays.
</P>
<P>
   The film, among other purported Gore failings, portrays him as
an environmental extremist who would do away with gasoline-powered
cars and a two-faced hypocrite on tobacco issues. The movie also
highlights the close ties between Gore and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A version of the module for Apple Macintosh machines is
scheduled to be available by Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
