<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAME-PHOTOGRAPHY-EXHI     07-08 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAME-PHOTOGRAPHY-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACING FAME'S TRAJECTORY FROM QUEEN VICTORIA TO KATO KAELIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1954, Photoplay, the doyen of fan magazines _ it
had been around since 1911 publishing feel-good stories written by
publicity agents _ printed an article about the early love lives of
Jeff Chandler and Susan Hayward, who were childhood friends. The
article was flattering, but Chandler, the magazine said, thought it
invaded his privacy. So Photoplay polled its readers. The question
(accompanied by another full-page glossy of Chandler, beaming) was:
Is it proper to write about a star's private life?
</P>
<P>
   Quaint, no? We have traveled so far from that moment in the
evolution of fame that the poll seems to belong to another
civilization. By the mid-50s, with the rise of gossip sheets like
Confidential, the American public was already demanding a price for
fame. The line between public achievement and private pathology was
eroding.
</P>
<P>
   Now there isn't even the expectation of public achievement as a
requirement for fame, just the capacity to be humiliated publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fame After Photography,'' a breezily entertaining show
organized by Carole Kismaric and Marvin Heiferman at the Museum of
Modern Art through Oct. 5, includes that long-forgotten June 1954
issue of Photoplay along with hundreds of other pictures that
illustrate our passage from William Faulkner's notion of fame (``to
be, as a private individual, abolished and voided from history,
leaving it markless, no refuse save the printed books'') to the
society of O.J. Simpson, People magazine and ``The Jerry Springer
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical Modern exhibition this is not. Several galleries of
the museum are crammed with 19th-century daguerreotypes, cartes de
visite, publicity stills, newsreels, movie trailers, old tabloid
newspapers, modern supermarket glossies, Wheaties boxes and
excerpts from television programs and advertisements, including
Pepsi commercials, the Johnny Carson show and ``Life Styles of the
Rich and Famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Since this is the Modern, there is a small section devoted to
art about fame, which includes an early Cindy Sherman film still,
for example, but it's a footnote to the main event. The subject is
celebrity as a phenomenon redefined by photography, which is a
different and more alarming matter.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean that the show is alarming because we dislike and
disdain what's in it. I mean the reverse: it's irresistible. We
meet people like Peggy Hopkins Joyce, the Lady of the Orchids, as
she was called. In 1931, Vanity Fair, then the grandest of highbrow
celebrity magazines, published one of Edward Steichen's glamorous
portraits of her as a soft-focus siren gazing down her pointed
nose; the picture accompanied an article describing her as a
dabbler in film and a woman with many sables, former husbands and
dimples.
</P>
<P>
   We meet other equally ridiculous characters from the last
century and a half whose celebrity, fleeting and otherwise,
coincided with the rise of photography and the media that succeeded
it, namely film, television and the Internet. The exhibition's
argument, not original but cleverly presented, is that change in
pictorial technology since the middle of the 19th century has
altered the nature of fame.
</P>
<P>
   So the proliferation of hand-held cameras let photographers
catch people off guard and paved the way for paparazzi. Halftone
printing, by which daily tabloids could publish pictures alongside
text, increased the public's appetite for news-maker snapshots,
which created a need for fresh photographs and new faces each day _
which in turn fostered the publicity agent industry.
</P>
<P>
   When television brought celebrities into people's living rooms
in the '50s, it added the illusion of intimacy to the situation.
One of the television clips in the exhibition shows Jack Paar
chatting with Fidel Castro, the two of them sitting side by side
talking about their children as if at a cocktail party. It's an
example, par excellence, of television's transformation of a
historically significant figure, a famous person in the old sense
of fame, into a modern celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   After all, to be famous, that is, to be a celebrity,
increasingly meant to pretend that you were like everyone else, a
fiction that gradually caused the entire population of the country
to believe it could (should) be famous. Programs like Paar's and
``Person to Person'' hastened what we could call the banalization
of fame, its normalization. This has culminated in the use of the
Internet, on which any narcissist can transmit his or her image
around the globe and, with luck, become famous just for doing so.
It used to be that a minimum requirement for fame was another
person interested enough in you to print your picture or point a
camera in your direction. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, who is Jeff Chandler anyway? Raise your hand if
you've ever seen him in ``The Jayhawkers'' or ``Return to Peyton
Place.'' Once famous as a romantic lead, he has gone the way of the
Hula-Hoop. My point isn't simply that fame is ephemeral but that it
once was a matter of posterity, something that counted above all
after you were dead. Today celebrities just hope to sustain their
fame through the week by providing the public with a constant flow
of novel revelations; otherwise they drop off the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as their now gets summed up, we move immediately on to
another person,'' Andy Warhol said, ``and another now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   This is the crucial matter: fame stripped of its everlasting
value, its promise of a life after death, at least for one's
reputation, has lost its spiritual underpinning. Historically
speaking, it used to be a spiritual matter, and it retains certain
aspects of its spiritual character while no longer necessarily
attaching itself to the ultimate spiritual goal, eternal existence.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the vocabulary of fame still borrows from religion:
charisma, idol. We still collect and revere pictures of the famous
as if they were icons, whether they're baseball cards or rock star
posters. And what is an endorsement, in the end, but the
sanctioning of something by the sanctified, the famous person's
lending his or her aura to a product? One of the memorable sights
in the show is an old magazine advertisement in which Eleanor
Roosevelt endorses a mattress (in another Steichen photograph). If
the underlying issue were not aura, what difference would it make
that a basketball player staked his reputation on the quality of a
hamburger or that a First Lady liked a particular bed? Why should
their word on these things have any special value to us?
</P>
<P>
   Then there is St. Augustine's paradox, which confronts every
famous person today. Augustine said that to be purged of the sin of
pride, a person must also purge the pride that comes from being
humble, ``the desire,'' as Leo Braudy once put it in ``The Frenzy
of Renown: Fame and Its History,'' ``that an audience witness (and
applaud) your contempt for fame.'' The trick, of course, is to deny
the appeal of fame while seeking it out: the politician who claims
to want to spend more time with his family, the actor who complains
about the loss of privacy and seeks to lead the quiet life. Or the
spectacle of Joan Crawford in an apron pretending to slice a
turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Fame in the ephemeral sense of celebrity certainly existed in
the past. But the point of the exhibition is that photography
brought with it a whole new range of social effects. Before
photography, most people obviously didn't even know what their
public figures looked like. The mid-19th-century craze for cartes
de visite, which at the time were postcard-size photographs of the
famous, reflected the enormous desire to put faces to names. So did
the proliferation of illustrated magazines. From the end of the
last century, we find a magazine called Success, which posed Edison
in his workshop, as if casually reading; success was being
signified not only by a man's accomplishments but also by the mere
reproduction of his face on the magazine's cover, a process that
rapidly became self-generating.
</P>
<P>
   Famous people had to adapt to the new medium. The standard
example is Lincoln, the homely hayseed, who with a little
retouching became a handsome statesman through Mathew Brady's lens.
But soon everyone, not just public figures, learned how to pose.
Then came moving pictures. It's sweet to look at some of the early
newsreels, in which no one seems quite sure how to act in front of
a movie camera, the paradox being that everyone looks unnatural
when in truth they are really too much themselves. They haven't yet
assimilated the theatrics of appearing natural on film.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't really need this exhibition to tell us that fame
eventually came to attach itself to those who learned the tricks of
the camera best, people whose celebrity derived from the fact that
they looked good in photographs and on film, but we see many lively
examples of it here. Billy Wilder's great remark about Marilyn
Monroe was, ``The first day a photographer took a picture of her,
she was a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   As Monroe demonstrated, image, having become a source of fame in
itself, also became a marketable commodity.
</P>
<P>
   True, to a degree this had been the case from the beginning of
photography; a century ago, P.T. Barnum sold pictures of his
performers and paid them royalties. But today we think we know who
Cindy Crawford and Kate Moss are just because we've seen their
photographs. They're famous for being photographed. No wonder
people now expect that getting their pictures in the paper or their
faces on television means they're automatically famous.
</P>
<P>
   The show's unspoken question is whether something that has
become so commonplace is still meaningful, beyond its value as a
commodity. Fame analysis is a growth industry: countless magazines
and television programs have arisen during the last decade to
dissect the sources of fame, the ways in which fame is produced and
spun. The hosts of these programs, who are sometimes more famous
than their subjects just for being on television, talk about the
barometer of fame as if it were the blue chip index, which in a
sense it has become.
</P>
<P>
   We must return in the end to the issue of spiritual value
because you might say that without it, fame has been reduced to a
plunging stock. The exhibition charts a trajectory from the world
of Queen Victoria to that of Kato Kaelin. Now that everyone is
famous for 15 minutes, is anyone really famous any longer?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
