<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIM DUNCAN: FRONT AND CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.C.)  (mk) 
 By DICK SCANLON   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ No one seems less impressed with Tim Duncan than
Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' young star had his own way of celebrating an NBA
championship while San Antonio partied and the rest of the world
marveled at his ability and consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sleeping since it happened,'' Duncan said after
joining the USA Basketball men's senior national team for a week of
practice Tuesday. ``I had a week off before I came here, so I've
been kind of resting. I haven't done anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yah, I've been on a high pretty much the whole week.''
</P>
<P>
   That last part comes off as something Duncan feels he is
supposed to say. In two professional seasons, he has done about all
a basketball player can do. You would expect him to act and sound
ecstatic, but he doesn't. Maybe he can't. Duncan is a 7-footer who
goes through life without expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in my house, in my bed, haven't seen much of
anybody,'' he said. ``Just trying to keep to myself for a little
while, trying to mellow down.''
</P>
<P>
   If he mellows down much more, he may play next season asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Tim,'' laughs Orlando Magic forward Matt Harpring, an
old friend of Duncan. ``He just won a championship, but we talk
together and he's like: `Who cares?' That's just the way he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have an ego. He's just an average guy who goes with
the flow. If he didn't play basketball he'd be just like everyone
else. He doesn't even dress like an NBA player. I mean, you would
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   But we do know. At age 23, Duncan is at the peak of the
basketball world. He was first-team all-NBA in both of his seasons,
first-team all-defense this season. He was MVP of the Spurs'
five-game NBA finals victory over the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is the answer to two standard argument-starters: ``With
which player would you most like to start a franchise?'' and
``Which player would give you the best chance of winning a
championship next season?''
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA of 1999, there is no argument: Duncan and Duncan. He
was the NBA's sixth-leading scorer (21.7), fifth-leading rebounder
(11.4) and seventh-leading shot blocker (2.52) even though he
didn't play center. Playing alongside David Robinson, Duncan is
technically a power forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never considered myself a center,'' he said. ``It's a
title that's been given to me, but I like playing where I play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? I don't know. I just don't like the name `center,' I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond what Duncan has accomplished as a player, what NBA people
most appreciate is the way he does it. Without expression. Without
dunkin' his way onto ESPN SportsCenter. Without flashy jewelry or
trashy talk.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan grew up in the Virgin Islands and didn't take up
basketball seriously until he was in the ninth grade. He didn't
think about playing in the NBA until well into his college career
at Wake Forest, where he earned a degree in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went four years to college. Most kids who are drafted early
haven't done that,'' said USA senior national team coach Larry
Brown. ``And don't forget, Tim went to a team that has won 50 games
every year David Robinson has been healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But also, Tim Duncan is unique. I don't know how many guys
come into our league with that type of ability and personality.
He's unbelievable. He has no ego. He just wants to enjoy playing,
enjoy the people he's around and do the best he can, and that's
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had some breaks. Coming to San Antonio and playing with
Robinson was a big one. And this season everything fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great. It's been a dream come true,'' he said
without expression, an ice pack taped to his left knee and a cell
phone in his right hand. ``It's been a short season, but a lot
happened. There were a couple of times in there where we really
turned things around, like the time we came back on Houston from
being down 18. But so far I haven't really had a chance to sit down
and enjoy what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpring is trying to help him do that. He has known Duncan
since Duncan showed him around Wake Forest on his recruiting visit
five years ago. Harpring has been showing Duncan around Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the same Tim,'' Harpring shrugged. ``He's into videogames
and he collects knives. And he loves to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if he wanted to go golfing this week and he said:
`No, I don't golf.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But he might, just to go out and have some fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
