<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEVER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ITALIAN FEVER:' APPREHENSION AND MISAPPREHENSION IN ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly as long as lines of tourists at the art shrines of
Florence and Rome is the procession of fictional Britons and
Americans queuing up to tangle with Italy and the Italians. Henry
James, E.M. Forster, Barry Unsworth and Penelope Fitzgerald are
just a few of the writers who have dispatched their protagonists to
get their hearts, brains and cultural assumptions upended.
</P>
<P>
   This season's upending, if not on the level of those just
mentioned, is wittily administered in ``Italian Fever'' by the
American novelist Valerie Martin. Administered, that is, like a
stiffish but ultimately improving summer-school course. The
student-victim is a young New York woman of lively brain, sluggish
self-esteem, an impressive capacity for seeing things crooked, and
enough pluck and appetite eventually to see them straight.
</P>
<P>
   D. van Kamp (invariably referred to as D.V.), a trashy
best-selling expatriate writer, has been found dead near his home
in Tuscany. His agent sends Lucy Stark, D.V.'s long-suffering
freelance editor, to tidy up his affairs and arrange a funeral.
Cool, practical and relied upon to possess a level head, Lucy
proceeds to lose hers.
</P>
<P>
   The overwrought, half-finished manuscript left by D.V. has
something to do with it. So does the dazzle of Italy's light,
beauty and sensual appeal. So do the layered difficulties the
country presents to foreigners who go beyond tourist routines and
try to accomplish practical matters. So do the oddities and
inscrutable intentions of the Cini family, D.V.'s aristocratic
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, Lucy's feverish, occasionally hallucinatory
few weeks center on her wild fling with Massimo, a charming (of
course) and married (also of course) Italian. Wild on her part,
that is (again of course), and on his, a matter mainly of deftly
managed pleasure (still of course).
</P>
<P>
   Those four ``of courses'' are what you might call the warp of
Ms. Martin's novel. She has written an entertainment, one that
follows a well-worn path of New World vs. Old: the romance between
the naif and the sophisticate, the comedy of cultural
misapprehension, the contrast between the European as historical
iceberg (seven-eighths of him the underwater past) and the American
as skating rink (all surface ice, and just frozen yesterday).
</P>
<P>
   Threaded through this warp, though, is a weft of pure comedy,
ironic perception and a glitter of phrase. In the throes of his
masterfully arousing love-making, for example, Massimo reminds Lucy
``of a man who has purchased an expensive and complicated new
automobile; he wanted to maintain it perfectly in order to run it
hard and fast.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a surface suspense in ``Italian Journey.'' It has to do
with the paranoid rantings in D.V.'s posthumous manuscript, a
hysteria that communicates itself to Lucy in her first few days
alone in D.V.'s house. Aggravated by a nightlong agony of
indigestion (garishly evoked) after a rich meal, it leads her to
encounter the writer's ghost and experience a brief breakdown.
These semi-Gothic passages _ ghost or hallucination reappear quite
unnecessarily at the end _ do not accomplish much.
</P>
<P>
   The real suspense is that of character. It is not that Massimo _
and his counterpart, the apparently effete and arrogant Antonio
Cini, scion of the aristocratic family next door _ actually move or
change or reveal themselves in any significant way. It is that
Lucy's misapprehensions, painfully righted only to give way to new
ones, beautifully provide a sense of change and revelation.
Sometimes you see things through a glass darkly that you could
never see face to face.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy's first glimpse of Massimo is at the Rome airport, where he
meets her on behalf of D.V.'s Italian publisher. Big, elegant as a
peacock who has been up all night grooming, he stands at the
barrier holding the tiniest of signs (part of the anti-package
prejudice of the traditional Italian male) and not looking at the
arriving passengers. Instead he is examining a possible spot on his
impeccable suit.
</P>
<P>
   Driving her to the village where D.V. lived and is to be buried,
and helping her make the complicated burial arrangements, he is
inexplicably, to her, cold and helpful by turns. It is only after
her collapse that he becomes attentive, then tender, then
passionate. The passion continues through her stay in the village,
and then through a few days in Rome, where she begins to perceive
the balancing of time and attention he manages among her, his
business affairs and his evenings at home.
</P>
<P>
   As Massimo's mystery fades _ though Ms. Martin's portrayal,
within the conventions of such a character, is delightful to the
end and finally a touch unexpected _ the character of Antonio Cini
begins to blossom. Just how would be unfair to say, since to the
extent that ``Fever'' is a mystery, it is one of persons, not plot.
But the last scenes between Antonio and Lucy are astonishing. They
bring her chain of mistakes and illusions to an ingenious close.
They make this entertainment something more; it is all surfaces,
true, but they are onion surfaces, and their successive peeling
constitutes a heart.
</P>
<P>
   At times Lucy seems an unsatisfactory character. She is all
apprehension and misapprehension: the personage as seeing or
unseeing eye; the one to whom things happen and who, after they
happen, good or bad, declares ``Oh'' or ``Ouch'' respectively. She
seems, in other words, to be an instrument through which we are
able to measure and test the author's Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Although thin, or at least not fully fleshed out, she is
interesting in a different way. It is her mind that counts. Even
wrong, it is a graceful and discriminating mind. When at the end
she reaches an understanding of what has been happening, the
experience is intellectual as well as emotional.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, when not caught up in her own swirl, she reflects
upon what she sees; there is a provocative passage, for example,
where she contemplates Bernini's sculpture of Apollo and Daphne and
compares, startlingly, this artist's ruthlessness toward his
subject with what she has undergone with Massimo.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment apart, Ms. Martin has written a novel of ideas. If
Lucy comes out OK _ improved, even _ it is her brain that has
achieved it. That and a wonderful appetite. There are a half-dozen
excellent meals in ``Fever'' and, indigestion aside, she does
justice to them all. The flesh made spirit.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ITALIAN FEVER'
</P>
<P>
   By Valerie Martin
</P>
<P>
   259 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
