<SLUG> BC-TV-MOVIESTARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOVIE STARS' SNEAKS ONTO THE WB SUMMER SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a list of the celebrities mentioned, but not seen, in the
first two episodes of ``Movie Stars'': Robin Williams, Tina Turner,
Jack Nicholson, Michael Douglas, Jennifer Lopez, Drew Barrymore,
Joe Pesci, Mel Gibson, Dweezil Zappa, Roseanne, Harvey Keitel,
Michael Eisner and Jeffrey Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Take a breath. There's more.
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart, Christina Ricci, Marilyn Manson, Arnold
Schwarzenegger, Adam Sandler, Sylvester Stallone, John Travolta,
Patrick Swayze, Robert Downey Jr., Courtney Love, Barbara Walters,
Sean Penn, Minnie Driver and Matt Damon.
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking I ran all those names because I have nothing
nice to say about ``Movie Stars,'' you'd be correctamundo. Despite
The WB's assurance that ``Movie Stars'' might be back as a
midseason replacement next winter, this is one of those series that
networks like to burn off in the summertime when few people are
watching.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest clue is that only eight episodes were made. The next
biggest clue is that one episode will air on Sunday and another on
Monday, so in four weeks the entire ``Movie Stars'' oeuvre will be
out there for historians to ponder. After that, it'll be ``Movie
Stars'' reruns until it's time for the new fall shows.
</P>
<P>
   The premise of ``Movie Stars'' is that movie stars have a home
life. It just happens to be in Malibu and includes more
name-dropping than an Oscars telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hamlin and Jennifer Grant play husband-and-wife celebs.
Their success makes a nice home for three kids named Apache,
Moonglow and Lori (his daughter from a previous marriage), plus her
wisecracking mother and his freeloading brother. The real-life
brothers of Travolta, Stallone and Swayze also appear regularly to
pick up a paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   The hilarity that ensues is reminiscent of a bad comedy from the
'70s, which means that sometimes the acting is funnier than the
lines. As the Bruce Willis type, Hamlin is amusing, but for all the
wrong reasons. He's supposed to be a charming, flesh-and-blood guy
playing a one-note actor, but there's no difference between the
character, Reese Hardin, and the character he plays in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Grant, the daughter of Carey Grant ant DyanCannon, is a
little more accessible as Jacey Wyatt, a star more devoted to her
craft than is Reese. But, as a parody of Hollywood, ``Movie Stars''
never gets under the skin. Like so much of Tinseltown, it's pretty
to look at, but ultimately artificial and superficial.
</P>
<P>
   Movie Stars. Half-hour comedy series about the home life of two
film stars. Starring Harry Hamlin, Jennifer Grant, Marnette
Patterson, Mark Benninghofen, Anne Haney, Zack Hopkins and Rachel
David. Premieres Sunday on The WB. Parental guideline rating:
TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
