<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      07-08 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: HOW MUCH FOR THE DEGAS?; THE ART OF HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Since it is considered taboo to ask the price of a work
of art hanging on the walls of a museum, it was daring for Sarah
Hyde, a curator at the Courtauld Institute of Art's gallery in
London, to organize an entire exhibition based on the value of art
in its permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curators think prices are something we should stay away from,
that once a work of art is in a museum it's protected from the art
market,'' Ms. Hyde said. ``But that's wrong. A lot of work art
historians do has an effect on the art market. Just because
something isn't for sale doesn't mean it isn't important.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``The Value of Art,'' which runs through Aug. 30,
consists of 15 pairs of unlabeled works from the Courtauld's
collection. Ms. Hyde said she purposely included a wide range of
objects, everything from Impressionist and Old Master paintings to
drawings, prints, silver and porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   Each pair of works is accompanied by a simple question: Which is
more valuable?
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent wall texts explain what the work is, including its
provenance and the range of factors that went into determining the
values.
</P>
<P>
   Considerations like condition, an artist's reputation,
workmanship and medium are carefully explained. Next to each pair
of works is a sliding panel that reveals the estimated auction
values of the works, as determined by experts at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Why should two silver George II coffeepots, both made in 1732
and both engraved with coats of arms, be worth different amounts?
One has an estimate of $8,000 to $9,600, while the other would be
expected to fetch $12,800 to $16,000. On the lower-priced coffeepot
the engraving is so worn that the surface is nearly smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been cleaned too much over the centuries,'' Ms. Hyde
said. ``The more valuable one is in far better condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do two images of the same woman, both by Matisse, made two
years apart, have drastically different values?
</P>
<P>
   One is a lithograph from 1925 that is said to be worth $32,000
to $40,000, while a 1923 signed drawing carries an estimate of
$144,000 to $192,000.
</P>
<P>
   The lithograph is an edition of 50, while the drawing is unique,
Ms. Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   That pricing art is often a more complex process than it seems
is underscored by two works in the show by Degas, for whom a record
price was set when a pastel and gouache work was auctioned last
week at Sotheby's. (That work, ``Dancer in Repose,'' went for $27.9
million.) In the exhibition is an oil painting, ``Two Dancers
Onstage'' (1877), which Sotheby's estimated could bring $32 million
to $48 million. Next to it is a pastel, ``After the Bath, Woman
Drying Herself'' (1889), which the auction house believes would
fetch only $3,200 to $4,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``The painting is highly finished, was signed by the artist and
sold by him within months of its completion, whereas the pastel was
not sold by Degas, is not signed and therefore might be
unfinished,'' Ms. Hyde said. ``Drawings also are often regarded as
preparations for finished works and are generally worth less than
oil paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sotheby's estimate for ``After the Bath'' is drastically
lower than the $8 million to $11.2 million estimate it had given
``Dancer in Repose'' before it brought $27.9 million here last
week. This raises the question of how accurate auction house
estimates are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't actually talked to Sotheby's about the price,'' Ms.
Hyde said. ``It was an astounding amount for a work on paper, and I
wonder if it would cause them to revise their estimates for these
Degases.''
</P>
<P>
   But Melanie Clore, deputy chairwoman of Sotheby's in Europe and
head of its Impressionist and modern art department, said the
auction house would not revise its estimates. The estimates put on
the two Degas works in the exhibition, she said, are in line with
the prices achieved last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancer in Repose,'' although done in pastel and gouache, is in
many respects closer to the Courtauld's ``Two Dancers Onstage,''
which Sotheby's estimated at $32 million to $48 million, Ms. Clore
said. ``Even though one is an oil painting and the other a pastel
and gouache, `Dancer in Repose' is unlike most of the artist's
pastels in that it is very painterly,'' she explained. ``It's an
exceptional work, which is one of the reasons it made such an
extraordinary price.''
</P>
<P>
   The Art of History
</P>
<P>
   Although the Tate Gallery of Modern Art doesn't open until the
spring of 2000, its curators are already staging events to get the
local neighborhood of Bankside involved with the new institution.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to showing films by artists on the facade of the
renovated power station, which is across the Thames from St. Paul's
Cathedral, they have invited the American artist Mark Dion to lead
an archaeological dig of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Dion, whose work often includes discovered treasures shown as
life-size curiosity cabinets, has put together a team of 10 local
volunteers to search in the Thames at Millbank, the site of the
original Tate Gallery, and the Thames at Bankside, to see what they
can discover.
</P>
<P>
   Each site has a rich history. Millbank was home to an
18th-century prison; as early as the 16th century, Bankside housed
theaters, brothels and bear- and bull-baiting pits.
</P>
<P>
   The public is allowed to watch the digs, and the finds will be
examined and classified by the artist in tents on the lawn of the
Tate Gallery at Millbank from July 19 to Aug. 13.
</P>
<P>
   They will be exhibited inside the museum from Oct. 26 through
Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Test digs have already unearthed an 18th-century thimble,
early-19th-century clay pots and a medieval shoe,'' said Frances
Morris, a curator at the Tate Gallery of Modern Art. ``This is the
first collaboration we have had between the two museums. Until the
Tate Gallery of Modern Art is finished, we are a museum without
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
