<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3536 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SCURRY-HNS &LR;      07-08 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SCURRY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GOALIE STAYS COOL IN THE HOT SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One of the first things that strikes you about
Briana Scurry is her patience.
</P>
<P>
   Following her dominating performance in the United States' 2-0
win over Brazil in the Women's World Cup semifinal at Stanford
Stadium last Sunday, Scurry stood in the still-hot sun outside the
locker room and answered questions for the best part of an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As the session went on and on, the questions took on a numbing
familiarity, but she never lost her smile _ or her cool.
</P>
<P>
   That cool has been evident throughout the World Cup, along with
Scurry's skill, which, until the last few weeks, has never been
fully recognized.
</P>
<P>
   When she joined the team out of college in 1994, U.S. coach Tony
DiCicco predicted she would emerge as the best female goalkeeper in
the world. And, a few days ago, DiCicco said he thinks she has now
reached that point.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence in this World Cup of such sterling keepers
as China's Gao Hong _ whom the U.S. team will face in the Cup final
Saturday at the Rose Bowl _ Sweden's Ulrika Karlsson and Norway's
Bente Nordby, it would be tough to argue with DiCicco.
</P>
<P>
   In five matches, Scurry has given up just two goals (not
counting Brandi Chastain's own goal against Germany). And when it
mattered most, in the semifinal against a previously high-scoring
Brazilian team, she was impenetrable, making six saves, at least
half of them spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   That performance brought to mind what Scurry said before she
stepped into the U.S. net for the first time five years ago: ``It
has always been a dream of mine to be the best at something. And
this opportunity to play with the best team in the world ... you
bet I'm going to grab it with both hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, however, the 27-year-old Scurry has been more
symbol than star.
</P>
<P>
   She is the only black player to start for the U.S. team (and one
of only two on the squad along with backup goalkeeper Saskia
Webber).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fact,'' Scurry said. ``I'm the one you see, and it is a
responsibility. I'm not so naive to think it isn't. I realize
people look at me and the question is going to come up, but it's
something I embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of African-Americans playing soccer, so it's
something I take seriously. I would love to see a lot more
African-Americans get into the sport, and I hope when they see me
playing, they'll say, `You know, I should try soccer. She's
playing.'''
</P>
<P>
   She might not be playing, however, if her family had not moved
from inner-city Minneapolis to the almost-all-white suburb of
nearby Anoka when she was 5, and Scurry gave up her first athletic
love _ football _ for soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we moved was my parents wanted me to get a better
education,'' she said. ``In actuality, I don't think I would have
had nearly the opportunities to play multiple sports (basketball,
softball, track and soccer) in high school if we hadn't moved. It
opened up more opportunities, and it molded me.''
</P>
<P>
   After being named National Goalkeeper of the Year for 1993, she
joined the national team and, going into the World Cup, she had set
a U.S. record with 49 career shutouts and an 0.56 goals-against
average in 90 international appearances.
</P>
<P>
   She was always relaxed and focused, but at 5-feet-8-inches and
135 pounds, she was also a bit light, at the beginning, for the
big-time grind.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were pushing me around,'' she said. ``So I hit the
weight room and gained 15 pounds going into the 1996 Olympics. It
helped immensely.''
</P>
<P>
   You might say so. In five Olympic matches, she gave up only five
goals as the U.S. won a gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   And she's continued to improve.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said, ``She is incredibly important to us. The two
things I look for in a goalkeeper most of all _ and I think Bri is
strong in both of these _ are athleticism, because it's the hardest
thing to teach, and mental skills. There's times we play that I
think things are getting pretty hectic back there, and everyone's
on the verge of panic except for Bri. She seems to get calmer.''
</P>
<P>
   So it appears established, then, that Scurry is unflappable,
regardless of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   There was that time after the '96 Olympics, though.
</P>
<P>
   In a candid moment during an early-morning magazine interview,
Scurry promised that if the United States won a gold medal, she
would run through the streets of Athens, Ga., naked.
</P>
<P>
   That celebration, not recorded for posterity, hasn't come back
to haunt her.
</P>
<P>
   But she said, ``I have no predictions for this World Cup. I just
want to win _ and keep my clothes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
