<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      07-08 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Very humid air streamed northward into the deserts of southern
California and Arizona from the warm Gulf of California. Meanwhile,
18,000 feet above the ground, steering winds slacked to speeds as
slow as 5 mph. As a result, thunderstorms that erupted moved
slowly, setting the stage for protracted heavy rain and flash
flooding. Friday, the same pattern will persist, with slow-moving
thunderstorms dousing the deserts. Storms will move westward into
the mountains of southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tropical moisture invading the Southwest will surge
into parts of Colorado, northwest Texas, Oklahoma and Missouri
ahead of a cool front pushing slowly south over the Plains. As a
result, clusters of heavy showers and thunderstorms, some capable
of producing more than 2 inches of rain will develop. Severe
weather is also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy rain,
damaging winds and large hail, will erupt ahead of the northern
flank of the cool front across the Ohio Valley and into the Great
Lakes region. Storms may consolidate into a line and forge across
the Northeast on Saturday evening into the night. Early in the day,
a cluster of showers and storms will sweep across New York into New
England as a warm front, marking the leading edge of returning
humid air, presses north across the region.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated heavy thunderstorms will flare in Florida in concert
with sea-breeze fronts moving inland, while another cluster of
storms fires in the central Gulf Coast states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Balancing Act
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms lashed the Virgin Islands on Thursday as a
disturbance moved westward across the Atlantic. While weather
systems outside the tropics generally travel from west to east, the
steering winds for tropical systems blow from east to west.
Hypothetically, if winds blew from the west everywhere on Earth,
they would, by producing an increased eastward drag on the Earth's
surface, cause the Earth's rate of rotation to increase. In
reality, winds from the east over the tropics balance the drag of
winds from the west over higher latitudes, keeping the Earth's
rotation constant. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3547 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HUNLEY09-COX     07-08 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HUNLEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strong crew powers Confederate `Hunley'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hunley was a Confederate submarine named for its inventor,
Capt. Horace Hunley. Capt. Hunley died while testing an earlier
version of his submersible, which sank to the bottom of Charleston
Bay and stayed there, along with its crew.
</P>
<P>
   In his honor, the Confederates named the infernal weapon after
him and sent out another batch of men in it, men who knew full well
what had happened to the inventor.
</P>
<P>
   All of this hangs over the new movie ``The Hunley'' like
inevitable doom, like the Spanish moss that festoons the trees of
Charleston, S.C., where our story is set.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1864, and the South is in trouble all over, and nowhere
more than in Charleston, where a blockade of Union ships off the
coast fires shells into downtown at will. The only way to sink any
of the ships is for the Hunley to sneak out and attach a land mine
to it; torpedoes that can be fired won't be invented till much
later.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering for this ill-fated job is Lt. Dixon, who appears
not to have a first name, but has sweaty charisma to spare as
played by Armand Assante. He also has a quite believable Southern
accent, although he's so
</P>
<P>
   prone to mumbling you may ratchet up the volume to catch his
swallowed dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's more than willing, Dixon is also under pressure
from Gen. Beauregard (a rheumy-eyed Donald Sutherland) to end the
shelling. Neither man thinks there's a chance the South can
actually win, and there's no talk about the honor of the South;
they're in it to the bitter end because they're soldiers, and
that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon's crew of six volunteers, with no shortage of macho
sweatiness among themselves, not only have to set out on a mission
of likely death, but have to work like dogs to get there. The
Hunley is so primitive it's hand-powered, and the crew's main job
is to sit in a cramped metal hold and turn a huge crank to get the
vessel moving. When they're not cranking and diving under the
water, they're drinking, fighting and bonding on shore. As is
usually the case with these movies, the claustrophobic underwater
sequences are far more dramatic than the sometimes cliched shore
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Although it flounders a bit at times, by the time the Hunley
makes its fateful run, this TNT movie has full steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hunley''
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on TNT
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
