<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 9. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BLACKOUT-POWER (New York) _ The blackout that stilled upper
Manhattan for nearly a day was a sort of distress call, a warning
that the electric power system in New York City and Long Island _
and, to a lesser degree, in other parts of the country _ is bumping
up against its physical limits, experts in the field cautioned. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BLACKOUT-RESEARCH (New York) _ Columbia University medical
researchers said Thursday that the power failure that darkened
northern Manhattan may have destroyed or set back by months
millions of dollars worth of experiments into illnesses ranging
from Alzheimer's disease to cancer to AIDS. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-WORKERS-ALCOHOL (Wellington, South Africa) _ The
tradition of keeping workers drunk with free alcohol _ a way of
keeping them working for next to nothing _ continues on many farms.
But even where the system is ending heavy drinking goes on and new
hardships emerge. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POVERTY (Anaheim, Calif.) _ With Magic Johnson at his
side, President Clinton wrapped up his four-day tour of poverty in
America with a whirlwind visit to a job-training program at a high
school in the heart of the Watts section of Los Angeles, then
challenged corporate executives to provide more support for
preparing disadvantaged students for jobs in the booming
information economy. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LUNG-SCANS (Undated) _ Death rates from lung cancer could be
greatly reduced if smokers and former smokers were given regular CT
scans of their lungs, doctors are reporting Thursday. The scans are
far more sensitive than conventional chest X-rays, and can detect
tumors when they are still small enough to be cured. By Denise
Grady.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-FIRING-RANGE (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ For two months
now, about three dozen people have occupied the eastern tip of this
small island off the coast of Puerto Rico in an act of deliberate
defiance. They have set up tents, built a chapel and walked among
the craters, target boards and unexploded bombs of a live fire
range, vowing not to leave until the United States Navy stops
military practice here. Story will describe how the navy has used
this island for target practice since 1941, but a series of
accidents has caused an uproar in Puerto Rico, uniting political
parties and environmental and religious groups. A civilian security
guard was killed and four others injured in April when a Navy plane
dropped a bomb a mile and a half off the intended target. Puerto
Rico demanding an end to the exercises. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Leskovac, Yugoslavia) _ Voices of discontent:
Leskovac, a hotbed of anti-Milosevic sentiment, sent 25,000
reservists to Kosovo. They're back now, furious with the way the
government has treated them (little pay) and their families (little
food). By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-PANEL (Undated) _ Major Jewish organizations are
attacking the appointment of a prominent Southern California
Muslim, Salam Al Marayati, executive director of the Muslim Public
Affairs Council in Los Angeles, to a national counterterrorism
commission. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ If the warring sides in
the Congo's 11-month-old war sign a cease-fire that won preliminary
approval on Wednesday, it will be the first time that they try to
bring closure to the single event that has destabilized all of
Central Africa in the last half decade: the genocide in Rwanda. A
news analysis by Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ACCESS (Washington) _ The Commerce Department releases
an extensive study on access to the Internet, looking at the gaps
in access to technology and information. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW (New York) _ Bernard Holland reviews ``The
Peony Pavilion,'' Tang Xianzu's 20-hour wandering epic of love,
death and the supernatural written during the Ming Dynasty. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
