<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-BEETLE-BOOKS-ART     07-08 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-BEETLE-BOOKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HUMBLE BUG, AND HOW IT GREW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `s' news category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summer reading season coincides with the summer driving
season. Here, just in time for perusal at poolside or in a
beach-bound traffic jam, is a look at some new books with
automotive themes:
</P>
<P>
   BEETLE BOOKS: When Adolf Hitler was imprisoned in 1923, he spent
his time writing ``Mein Kampf'' and reading a biography of Henry
Ford, which helped to inspire the future dictator's vision of a
``people's car.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, with the Fuehrer dead and Germany occupied
by the Allies, the British were in charge of a zone that included
Wolfsburg, home of the fledgling Volkswagen factory and the
manifestation of Hitler's automotive dreams. In 1947, VW produced
only 8,978 cars (which had been designed by the legendary Ferdinand
Porsche, who went on to build some of the world's best-known sports
cars). The next year, the British offered to turn the plant over to
Henry Ford, but he rejected it. His advisers had told him it was
``not worth a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitler's brainchild, of course, became the best-selling car
ever, with more than 20 million sold worldwide; it broke the 15
million record of Ford's Model T in 1972. Called the Type 1 in
Germany, the VW was dubbed the Beetle or the Bug in America.
</P>
<P>
   Such historical tidbits are the best parts of ``Beetlemania,''
by Kate McLeod (Smithmark, $12.98), and ``The Volkswagen Bug
Book,'' by Dan Ouelette (Angel City Press, $30), two coffee-table
books full of pictures of the car that became an icon.
</P>
<P>
   The books cover much of the same territory, although ``The
Volkswagen Bug Book'' is more text-heavy and comprehensive. The
pictures, especially those in Ouelette's book, illustrate the
dichotomy of the Volkswagen image. Colorful, warm and fuzzy photos
of Bugs in America, some with exotic paint and others with happy
dogs hanging out open windows, are presented along with stark,
grainy, black-and-white images of the car in the Third Reich. ``The
Volkswagen Bug Book'' almost naturally falls open to a shot of a
smiling Hitler, a swastika on his sleeve, inspecting an early
model.
</P>
<P>
   There are some interesting minor differences between the two
books. Ms. McLeod writes that the British offered to sell the VW
plant to Henry Ford; Ouelette says that they wanted to give it to
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Both books trace the Volkswagen Beetle from its Nazi-era roots
to its demise in the United States in the late '70s, when it
succumbed because of a tired design, aggressive Japanese
competition and ever-tighter safety and pollution rules. The
original, essentially unchanged since the 1940s, continues to be
produced in Mexico, still with its rear-mounted, air-cooled engine.
</P>
<P>
   The books also cover the ``rebirth'' last year of the
not-quite-dead car as the New Beetle, which shares little with its
predecessor except the general shape that makes it instantly
recognizable. The New Beetle is an all-new model that uses the VW
Golf's front-mounted engine and platform. It has received good
reviews and high scores in safety tests and has sold briskly, while
also unleashing waves of nostalgia for the old Bug.
</P>
<P>
   The authors write that one of the secrets of the original's
success was the company's willingness to abandon conventional
wisdom. Instead of changing models every year, Heinz Nordoff, who
was put in charge of VW following Henry Ford's rejection, kept
refining the same car, making it better and better, while other
carmakers were obsessed with bringing out ever-more-flashy new
models every year.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom was also rejected by VW's U.S. advertising
agency, the old Doyle Dane Bernback. Ads were simple and clever;
they poked fun at the car's unusual looks and urged potential
buyers to ``think small.'' In 1953, 2,173 Beetles were sold in
America; by 1968, that number rose to an all-time high of 569,292.
</P>
<P>
   For the New Beetle, Arnold Communications of Boston is also
producing advertisements that make you smile. ``If you sold your
soul in the '80s,'' one says, ``here's your chance to buy it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected result of the Beetle phenomenon is that a car
intended for the average person ended up crossing all class lines.
The same is true for Beetle redux; the new car has been snapped up
by celebrities, commoners and college students.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the original Beetle really did float. Events staged by
the Waterbugs of America Racing Association required participants
to drive their cars into the water and negotiate a course of about
a mile. There were even unsuccessful attempts to cross the English
Channel in floating VWs.
</P>
<P>
   One more tidbit: Ms. McLeod reports that 103 college students
set an unofficial record by packing into a Beetle and driving it 15
feet. She does not report the exact date of this feat or the car's
condition afterward.
</P>
<P>
   If your interest in the Beetle is more practical than
historical, you might prefer the 18th edition and 30th anniversary
issue of ``How to Keep Your Volkswagen Alive,'' by John Muir (John
Muir Publications, $25). This folksy guide to keeping older models
running became a hippie handbook that has sold more than 2.3
million copies since it was first published in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The book, whose subtitle is ``A Manual of Step by Step
Procedures for the Compleat Idiot,'' is not just a detailed how-to
book on fixing a car. It is a chronicle of one man's love affair
with VWs _ it could have been called ``Zen and the Art of
Volkswagen Maintenance.'' Muir writes about how one must do
mechanical work on a VW with love or the result will be failure. He
even suggests talking to the cars. A drawing of the VW ``control
system'' is a diagram of the human brain.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be misled. This is an extremely practical book that
really will help you keep an old Beetle or Microbus on the road.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other noteworthy, recently published books on
automotive matters:
</P>
<P>
   BUYING USED: A new guide to buying a used car, ``Lemon-Aid Used
Cars 1999,'' by Phil Edmonston (Stoddart Publishing, $17.95), is
one of the most valuable of its kind because it includes
information on secret warranties and confidential service bulletins
that most owners aren't aware of and most automakers want to keep
that way.
</P>
<P>
   These often result from lawsuits or government intervention that
may not be widely publicized. For instance, few Honda owners are
likely to be aware that under a settlement with the Environmental
Protection Agency, the company extended its emissions warranty to
14 years or 150,000 miles for 1995-97 Civics and 1996-97 Accords,
Preludes and Odysseys. This means that if you own one of these
vehicles, you are entitled to a full engine check and
emission-related repairs at 50,000 to 75,000 miles, and free
tune-ups at 75,000 and 150,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemon-Aid'' also has information on prices and defects for two
decades of used cars, and advice on getting your money back if you
buy a lemon. The book's layout and organization are daunting, but
the information is worth the trouble it takes to find it.
</P>
<P>
   BUYING NEW: Once again, the ``Dummies'' series increases your
smarts with ``Buying a Car for Dummies'' by Deanna Sclar (IDG
Books, $16.99), one of the best all-round guides available to
buying or leasing a car. Little icons on almost every page serve as
flags for helpful tips, warnings or things to remember; for
example, there is specific advice on how to get a better deal by
using an auto broker or a buying service.
</P>
<P>
   BERLITZ FOR BREAKDOWNS: ``Car Smarts,'' by Mary Jackson (John
Muir Publications, $17.95) is a lighthearted, easy to understand
guide for dealing with mechanics and speaking their language. It
could be very useful, especially for those mystified by a car's
innards. The drawings and diagrams are clear; technical terms are
nicely explained, and the writing is free of jargon.
</P>
<P>
   TAURUS WATCH: Mary Walton had unrestricted access to Ford
executives, designers and engineers as they set out to redesign the
popular Taurus. In her very readable book, ``Car: A Drama of the
American Workplace'' (W.W. Norton, paperback version, $17), she
tells you more than you may want to know about the 1996 model. But
her account is particularly interesting now that the market has
passed judgment on that car _ not entirely favorably _ and Ford is
bringing out a 2000 Taurus that eliminates or tones down a number
of the distinctive features of the 1996-99 models. Despite the
minutiae, a reader will come away with an appreciation of the
complexities of building a car.
</P>
</TEXT>
