<HEADER>
A3556 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRIDE-ESKRIDGE-BOS &LR;      07-08 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRIDE-ESKRIDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIDE RITE CHIEF RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After barely seven months on the job, Stride Rite Corp.'s
chairman and chief executive, James A. Eskridge, abruptly resigned
Thursday following an apparent clash over strategy with the
Lexington-based footwear company's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Myles J. Slosberg, the 62-year-old grandson of the man who in
1919 founded the company that would later be known for Keds, has
been appointed as interim chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Slosberg said he would lead a search team that will seek a
permanent successor to Eskridge, a former executive at Mattel Inc.
and General Mills Inc. who moved from California to assume the top
job at Stride Rite late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely a shock,'' said Steven A. Richter, an analyst
for Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull, who added of Eskridge's departure,
``Clearly, there was some disagreement over the direction of the
company. Clearly, there was a clash.''
</P>
<P>
   Stride Rite shares fell on the news despite the company's strong
performance in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Stride Rite shares fell 1 7/8 to
close at 8 11/16 on trading that was more than 10 times heavier
than the three-month daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge is well regarded on Wall Street, and so was his plan to
aggressively pursue acquisitions for Stride Rite, said Midwest
Research analyst Jeff Stinson.
</P>
<P>
   To assist Slosberg, Stride Rite promoted Diane M. Sullivan to
president and chief operating officer and also brought back Joanna
M. Jacobson to serve as vice chairman. Two weeks ago, Stride Rite
announced Jacobson was leaving as president of its Keds division to
spend more time with her family.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who had been president of another Stride Rite
division, might be ``a very logical successor'' to Eskridge ``down
the road,'' analyst Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   But Slosberg declined to comment on the timetable of his search
and its likely list of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got her hands full right now,'' he said of Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to pin down the precise nature of the rift between
Eskridge and the Stride Rite board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to the company, and they would not delineate any
further about the parting of the ways,'' said Steven Marotta, an
analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Eskridge said, ``While I disagree with the board
about the direction of change in the company, as a shareholder, I
wish Stride Rite only the best in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Slosberg of Eskridge, ``There really wasn't a good fit
between him and our vision of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been a hostage to fashion cycles. When its
brands are in vogue, the company thrives. When canvas shoes fell
out of favor earlier in the decade, Keds slumped and so did Stride
Rite.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Stride Rite hired Robert Siegel from the Docker's
division of Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. to help engineer a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to be less dependent on Keds, the company entered
licensing agreements to make various shoe lines under the Tommy
Hilfiger and the Nine West brand names.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999's second quarter that ended May 28, sales were up 16
percent to $166.3 million. If a one-time gain from the second
quarter of 1998 was excluded, net income rose 37 percent to $9.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, sales of Keds were up 9 percent. Sales for
Sperry Top-Sider, another Stride Rite brand, were up 13 percent,
and sales for the Tommy Hilfiger lines ``more than doubled,'' said
Stride Rite, which reported 1998 sales of $539.4 million. Last
year, Siegel retired, and Eskridge was tapped to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Slosberg, a long-time company director who held many key jobs at
Stride Rite before leaving to pursue a legal career, noted that the
groundwork for Stride Rite's comeback strategy was laid before
Eskridge joined the company. With the long lead times needed to
plan shoe lines, Eskridge's presence was not a factor in Stride
Rite's second-quarter results, Slosberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should not be concerned that Stride Rite's performance
was his performance,'' Slosberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst don't foresee a slowdown in that performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnaround continues,'' Richter said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Stride Rite's strong portfolio of brands, its solid
balance sheet, and its team of seasoned executives, Marotta said,
``This is a strong company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
