<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT &LR;      07-08 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAIL SALES ROLL ALONG WITH THE ROCKING ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keeping time with the nation's rocking economy, retailers posted
another month of robust sales gains in June.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in stores opened at least a year, a key industry
measurement, rose 6.5 percent last month, according to the Goldman
Sachs retail composite index. Since January, the index has risen at
the torrid pace of on average 6.47 a month. ``This is the strongest
year since we started keeping track of the data'' in 1988, said
Margaret Mager, retail analyst at Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With both unemployment and inflation low, Americans were eager
to open their pocketbooks and spend. ``Certainly one of the key
drivers of this is that consumer confidence is at the highest we
have seen in 30 years,'' said Angie Selden, a partner in Arthur
Andersen's global retail practice.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong economy was not the only reason for the strong
performance. Many retailers have been improving their merchandise,
especially in clothing and housewares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a great fashion cycle,'' said Maura Hunter Byrne, an
analyst at Solomon Smith Barney. She credited retailers with
creating excitement by changing lengths and styling in common
apparel items, noting this year's must-have summer items like
three-quarter length sleeved T-shirts and mid-calf length capri
pants.
</P>
<P>
   The strong sales numbers are expected to translate into good
earnings. Jeff Feiner, managing director at Lehman Brothers, said,
``Because this was not a month with a lot of markdowns, profits
were strong.'' He increased his earnings estimates for seven large
retailers including Costco Companies Inc., Federated Department
Stores and Tiffany and Co.
</P>
<P>
   As customers rushed to suit up for the hot weather in clingy
tanks and sportswear with surfer motifs, they particularly shopped
at specialty apparel stores. Limited Inc., which includes Lane
Bryant, Express and Victoria's Secret, had a gain of 11 percent at
stores opened for a year as all its divisions showed strong
increases. Ann Taylor sustained its comeback with a 7.7 percent
rise. Eddie Bauer had an increase of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Discount stores similarly benefited from an unusually steamy
June, as consumers purchased air-conditioners and patio furniture.
Wal-Mart Stores, the world's largest merchant, had an increase of
6.5 percent over June of last year. Kmart Corp. rebounded from last
month's anemic sales gain to post a strong increase of 9.2 percent.
Shopko Stores Inc. and Ames Department Stores Inc., a regional
discount chain, each reported increases just north of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even the department stores, which have trailed the performance
of the discounters in recent years, had a fine showing. Dayton
Hudson was up 6.9 percent, Kohl's rose 15 percent, and May
Department Stores and Federated Department Stores each had a
whopping 8.4 percent rise. ``In every merchandise category in every
part country there have been strengths that exceeded the plan,''
said Carol Sanger, spokeswoman for Federated, sounding pleasantly
surprised herself.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mostly glowing numbers, a few merchants stood out
for their poor performance. Sales at the long-struggling J.C.
Penney Co. fell 2.3 percent from last June. In a press release, the
retailer, based in Plano, Tex., blamed ``softer than expected
Father's Day sales and the elimination of a major sales event.''
Penney's, the nation's fifth-largest department store chain, has
been battling disappointing sales results for two years now.
</P>
<P>
   Gap Inc. reported a powerful 13 percent sales gain, with the
growth coming entirely from its two hot divisions. Gap's tony
Banana Republic division had a sales increase of 17 to 19 percent
over June of last year, and Old Navy, showing no sign that its
slightly gimmicky concept was wearing thin with consumers, posted
growth of nearly 37 percent over May of last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gap stores, which generate a little less than half of
the chain's $9 billion in revenues, had flat sales for the second
consecutive month, as did Gap Kids. Warren Hashagen, the company's
chief financial officer, said Gap Kids was ``working its way
through some fashion missteps.'' He added that both chains had
revamped fashion items for the fall and ``are positioned well for
the back-to-school season.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts cut Gap slack anyway since the flat numbers came
on top of a stellar performance last year for the casual apparel
giant. Last Spring, Gap introduced an ad campaign showing
attractive models boogieing in its khakis, and sales shot up in the
double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also remain optimistic that retailers were in a strong
position for the rest of the year, including the all-important
back-to-school and holiday seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the strong numbers, retailers are watching inventories
tightly,'' Feiner said. ``They are not over-ordering for
Christmas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
