A3566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-GOP-HNS &LR;      07-08 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE REPUBLICANS LOOK AT THE CANDIDATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the pantheon of American presidential politics,
college students rank far below high-tech and Hollywood moguls as
sources of campaign cash. But they offer candidates other things:
their votes and their zeal.
</P>
<P>
   So with a modicum of self-importance 500 members of the College
Republican National Committee arrived here Thursday for a two-day
meeting, ready to be wooed by the GOP's crowded presidential field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ones who stand on the corner in the rain in Iowa, or
in the snow in New Hampshire,'' said Joe Singara, the group's
second vice-chairman from Burlington, Vt. ``Maybe we don't have the
checkbooks, but if you don't have college students stuffing
envelopes or going door-to-door, you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, publishing magnate Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes,
told them that ``America today is truly at a crossroads'' before
launching into his standard campaign speech advocating lower taxes,
school vouchers and Social Security individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate, Alan Keyes, a radio talk-show host and a
former assistant secretary of state in the Reagan administration,
was also scheduled to speak Thursday. On tap Friday are former
American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, Rep. John Kasich,
R-Ohio, conservative activist Gary Bauer, and Sen. Bob Smith,
R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Among those absent from the speakers' roster are conservative
commentator Pat Buchanan, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and _ most
conspicuously _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP frontrunner.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Brohimer, chairman of the college Republicans, shrugged off
Bush's absence. ``He's got a tough road out there,'' Brohimer said.
But he added that he is sure Bush and the others understand the
importance of young voters, particularly young GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the future of this country. and candidates understand
the importance of youth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 students attending this year's meeting number 200 more
than those who attended the 107-year-old group's last session in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday the young Republicans will announce results of a straw
poll showing which presidential candidate they favor.
</P>
<P>
   David Castleman, a Dartmouth College student, said he supports
Bush. ``He's willing to focus not just on the stereotypical
cigar-chomping Republicans,'' Castleman said. ``I think he's a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Gladden of Indiana University said he likes McCain. ``I
think he's a little more of a maverick on issues like tobacco and
campaign finance,'' he said. ``He doesn't always do the expedient
thing, and he's a war hero who's given a lot to his country.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Saeger, a student at Valparaiso University in Indiana,
said she favors Dole. ``She's a great role model,'' Saeger said.
``She'd be a great leader.''
</P>
<P>
   The students' meeting is being held at the old Watergate Hotel,
now called Swissotel Washington-the Watergate. It was the scene of
the famous 1972 burglary that set in motion events that brought
down a Republican president, Richard Nixon, in 1974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
