<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-FISHING-ART-NYT     07-08 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-FISHING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN JOURNAL: OLD MEN AND THE SEAS THEY FISHED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: China, Peru, Chile)  (ART ADV: A photo and map are being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSHIMA, Japan _ It is just past dawn as Yasushi Yamashita guides
his white fishing boat through the waves, finds his buoy and then
grunts as he hauls his nets to the surface in hopes of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Yamashita's rugged face radiates pleasure as he finds the
surprise _ a rich harvest of hundreds of squirming fish about 18
inches long _ and begins throwing the fish into the hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good haul, wasn't it?'' he said, exultantly. ``This
is as good as it would have been a decade ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Then his face dropped a bit, and he added, ``Of course, back
then the price was twice what it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yamashita, a stocky 50-year-old fisherman as weather-beaten as
the little island of Oshima where he lives in the Goto chain of
southern Japan, is a fading breed.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is still by far the world's leading consumer of fish, and
for decades if not centuries it was also the top fishing nation.
But in 1989 its fish catch was surpassed by China, and since then
by Peru and Chile as well.
</P>
<P>
   So while Japan is one of the few places in the world where it is
possible to have a rapturous conversation about the taste of
pufferfish, or fugu, this is no longer a nation with many
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Most Japanese sushi today comes from foreign nets, and Japan's
catch has dropped in half since 1985, with the number of fishermen
dropping almost as rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is likely to quicken, for nearly half of Japan's
290,000 remaining fishermen are in their 60s or 70s. Many families
have been in the business for countless generations, but now for
the first time there is no one to take over the boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little sad that fishing will end in my generation,''
Yamashita said as he piloted his boat back to the dock at Oshima.
``But I think my eldest son will have a better life if he gets out
of fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is not the only country facing problems with its fishing
fleet. The United States and other fishery nations have also faced
difficulties, partly because of overfishing, and after quadrupling
between 1950 and 1988, the world's ocean fisheries production has
leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen in Japan face special challenges because they were
used to exceptionally high prices, but fish imports have increased
nearly 10-fold since 1970 and have brought Japanese prices down to
international levels. Moreover, Japan's distribution system is so
unwieldy and expensive that it costs more to transport fish to the
markets in Tokyo from here in southern Japan than from China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see what's ahead for fishing, and as a parent I've no
regret that my sons aren't doing this,'' said Takemitsu Takashima,
a leather-skinned 58-year-old man who has been a fisherman since he
was 16. ``The catch is so small that it's just as well that it ends
with my generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Takashima was drinking beer over dinner _ rather too much beer,
it seemed _ with another old fishing buddy, Yoshinobu Yamashita,
70. The more the alcohol flowed, the more enthusiastically they
reminisced about the old days of fishing in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began as a fisherman, we didn't have motorboats,''
Yamashita recalled. ``We just rowed our boats out onto the ocean
and then used a sail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be dangerous,'' he added. ``So many of my classmates
died fishing out there in the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   These fishing villages along Japan's endless coast are full of
the lore of ancient glory and catastrophe. People here in Oshima
still talk about the nearby island that in one day lost all of its
men, when a storm capsized their boats as they were fishing
together.
</P>
<P>
   Whaling in Japan has mostly ended, but the old-timers still talk
about how the villagers would surround a whale and harpoon it and
feed the island for a year _ or, even more thrilling, would first
capture it in a net before killing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people now can't imagine what it was like,'' Yamashita
said, reaching again for his glass. ``Even for me, it feels as if
it was a different world.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 205,000 Japanese households _ one-half of 1 percent of the
total _ are now engaged in fishing, and even they get most of their
income from other sources. Some run sports fishing charter boats or
even operate sightseeing boats for whale-watchers from the cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just fewer and fewer fish out there,'' said Tanisaku
Makiyama, a 44-year-old fisherman. ``Many of the young fishermen
are still single, unable to find a wife, because their incomes are
so low.''
</P>
<P>
   Makiyama looked out at the ocean and sighed. ``I think the
fishing era is over for Japan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The one part of the fishing industry that is doing reasonably
well is fish-farming, of everything from shrimp to yellowtail,
although even there the competition is tough.
</P>
<P>
   Japan also has the remnant of a deep-sea fishing fleet, but its
deep-sea catch is just one-quarter of what it was in 1970. Even on
Japanese deep-sea boats, the crews these days are often
non-Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I went fishing as far as Alaska and
Indonesia, and we did pretty well for ourselves,'' said Iwao
Yamashita, a 51-year-old fisherman. (Oshima is thick with
Yamashitas, all members of an extended clan.) ``But then the
captains realized that they could save money by hiring
Indonesians.''
</P>
<P>
   His son, Daiki, a 14-year-old junior high school student, was
nibbling on squid sashimi and listening to his father. So what does
he plan to do in life? ``I don't know what I want to be,'' he
answered. ``But I don't want to be a fisherman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
