<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-08 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY DIFFERS FROM WHITE HOUSE ON ISSUE OF JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``a'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton signaled
an independent course in her bid for the U.S. Senate Thursday,
going beyond White House policy on Israel and vowing more ambitious
steps to fix the nation's ailing health care system.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton met with health care specialists here and, later,
with senior citizens in Utica, N.Y., on the second day of her
on-the-ground exploration of a campaign to succeed retiring Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In a high profile break with her husband's policies, the first
lady deviated from administration pronouncements and said she
considers Jerusalem ``the eternal and indivisible capital of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials, who have resisted congressional
pressure to move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, have
never publicly adopted Israel's contention that Jerusalem is the
``eternal and indivisible'' capital of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   The president contends that the status of Jerusalem should be
decided in negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians that
also would settle disputes over borders, refugees and Jewish
settlements on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign released her July 2 letter to Mandell L.
Ganchrow, head of the Orthodox Union that represents about 750
orthodox Jewish synagogues across the United States. In the letter,
she vowed to ``be an active, committed advocate for a strong and
secure Israel able to live in peace with its neighbors, with the
United States Embassy located in its capital, Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Creation of a Palestinian homeland _ endorsed by Mrs. Clinton
last year _ remains an ``issue that should be decided as part of
the final status negotiations by the parties,'' said Howard
Wolfson, Clinton's campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of 1.6 million _ 9.1 percent of the state's
total _ Jews are a key ingredient to political victory in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton played to her expertise on health care policies by
meeting with New Yorkers invited to Bassett Healthcare, a regional
network of physicians, clinics and a 180-bed hospital that serves
an eight-county rural area.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may recall that I've had some thoughts about health care
and health care reform in the past,'' Mrs. Clinton wryly told an
audience of more than 50 health care specialists. She added: ``But
I now come from the school of smaller steps,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady led the Clinton administration's development of a
comprehensive blueprint to overhaul the nation's public and private
health care system in 1993. But her plan was so controversial that
neither the House or Senate _ then controlled by Democrats _
brought it up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The setback contributed to the GOP takeover of Congress in 1994
for the first time in 40 years _ creating a politically divided
government that has stymied many other administration initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to John Clow, a university professor, describe
his battle with insurance companies to cover eight years of cancer
treatments for his late wife, Clinton said that greater government
action is needed to free patients and doctors from having to fight
for insurance reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton criticized legislation sought by the White House to
strengthen the hand of patients and physicians in their dealings
with health maintenance organizations and private insurance firms.
The proposal is ``a diversion,'' Clinton said, because it will
leave ``more people arguing over what should be done for patients''
rather than freeing physicians to care for patients.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate vote on the measure is scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said she favored the measure because ``there is no
alternative,'' but added: ``It is not the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called for more aggressive efforts to drive down
the market price of drugs. The issue is greater than the remedies
offered by a White House proposal to provide first-ever, voluntary
prescription drug coverage to the nation's 40 million Medicare
beneficiaries, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturers must be required to publicly disclose the
actual costs of research and development for new drugs rather than
being allowed to pass on the costs without scrutiny, she declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really find out how much a drug actually costs to
develop _ you have to take the word of the drug manufacturers,''
she said, adding: ``It is something that we're going to have
address.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's positions on health care drew mixed reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Struck, president of Bassett Healthcare, said health
care specialists welcome Mrs. Clinton's commitment to debating
changes in the health care system, even if they don't agree with
the specifics of her proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any resentment anywhere about her
willingness to focus attention on health care,'' Struck said. ``But
the direction that she takes is not always one that everyone agrees
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Sellers, assistant director for medicine and
pediatrics at the complex, said he was leery of Clinton's heavy
emphasis on health care reform rather than concrete steps to
revitalize the economy of upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conceded that if upstate New York were viewed as a
separate state, it would rank 49th in job creation and economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in upstate New York is very concerned about
the upstate economy and would really like to hear from all the
Senate candidates what they could do to help the economy,'' Sellers
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
