<SLUG> BC-TRADER-SHUTDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS CITE VIOLATIONS AT DAY TRADER, SEEK SHUTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts regulators moved to shut down the Boston
office of Houston-based Landmark Securities Corp. Thursday, saying
the firm engaged in some of the most ``egregious'' practices yet
found in the state's campaign against day-trading companies.
</P>
<P>
   In an administrative complaint, the Massachusetts Securities
Division alleged ``numerous violations'' of state securities laws,
including a falsified customer account form, forged customers
signatures and improper loans to Landmark customers that carried
``usurious rates of interest.'' Landmark denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen some of these things before, but it's not been as
brazen as it has been in this case,'' said Secretary of State
William F. Galvin, whose office has taken action against six
day-trading firms in the state since last fall. ``What we're
alleging here is very troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Day trading, which gets its name from the practice of holding
stocks for less than a day, has become big business across the
country. Firms like Landmark have sprung up to cater to a growing
number of amateur investors who trade huge blocks of stock in
transactions that often last only seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated traders work in boutiques like Landmark eight hours a
day, five days a week, often performing hundreds of trades a day in
pursuit of profits on miniscule movements in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators, particularly in Massachusetts, have taken a dim
view of the practice, saying it's little better than gambling.
Spurred in part by alarms sounded by Massachusetts regulators, the
federal Securities and Exchange Commission, the National
Association of Securities Dealers and key members of Congress have
warned that day-trading is extremely risky.
</P>
<P>
   Many inexperienced traders hoping to tap a vein of stock-market
riches have instead found themselves buried in debt after months of
nonstop trading. Meanwhile, day-trading firms collect large
commissions on stock transactions whether traders make money or
lose it, regulators say. According to estimates by a consortium of
state agencies, just two in 10 professional day traders make money,
and only a small number of those make large returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a practice that is not for most people, and for all
those reasons we have to make sure the laws are strictly adhered
to,'' Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's complaint, the securities division said Landmark's
Boston office manager, Scott Kurland, approved accounts for
customers who didn't have enough experience or money to be day
trading. In one case, Kurland approved a day-trading account for a
customer with an anual income of just $15,000 and no investing
experience, the complaint alleges.
</P>
<P>
   On a new account form, Kurland misrepresented the customer's
income and net worth ``to create the false impression that day
trading might be suitable'' for the customer, the complaint
alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Through Kurland, the complaint states, Landmark ``routinely
promoted and arranged loans between customers'' so that customers
who ran out of money could continue trading, ``thus generating more
commissions.'' the complaint alleges.
</P>
<P>
   To move money from one customer's account to another, Kurland
forged customers' signatures on transfer authorization forms, used
forms that had been forged by others and used photocopied
signatures he kept on file, according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also states that Kurland participated in an
improper lending scheme in which a Landmark subsidiary borrowed
money from one customer then lent it out to other customers. A
portion of any profits made by the borrowers went to Kurland and
other owners of the Landmark subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Kurland, 24, didn't return phone calls Thursday. But his
attorney, Michael Unger of the Boston firm Rubin and Rudman, said
Landmark's office manager is a victim of overzealous regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another case being pursued by the securities division,
which has decided it is going to go after day-trading firms,''
Unger said. ``My client has a blemish-free record. He's never had
any problems. He's never had a single complaint from a customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts led the nation with the first regulatory action
against a day trading firm last October, shutting down Block
Trading in Boston. The securities division alleged that just one of
a total 68 day traders at Block Trading made money. Block has
denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Kurland worked for Block Trading at the time regulators closed
it, securities division officials said. He was questioned but not
cited with any wrongdoing in that case.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the securities division has taken action against
local offices of five other national firms _ Bright Trading Inc.
for failing to register with the state, All-Tech Investment Group
for abuses ranging from deceptive marketing to forging customers'
signatures, On-Line Investment Services for deceptive marketing and
churning accounts, and TCI Corp. for making ``outrageous'' claims
of guaranteed income.
</P>
</TEXT>
