u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-750&AMP;ADD-     07-08 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER AT GOVERNMENT GROWS AMONG YUGOSLAV ARMY RESERVISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also KOSOVO-RALLIES) 
(mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LESKOVAC, Yugoslavia _ Beneath a sign for the Swing Jeans Shop,
a dozen or so Serb policemen in powder blue uniforms stood around
Thursday night, glaring at locals who dared to gather here for the
fourth night running to demand the resignation of President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   All around the police in the town square, there were hundreds of
Yugoslav army reservists, some in soiled camouflage uniforms and
many drinking beer.
</P>
<P>
   They were home from the lost war in Kosovo, unpaid, jobless and
angry enough about it all to tangle this week with Milosevic's men,
who call all the shots in Leskovac, a city in a part of Serbia
known as the ``Red South.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, about 20,000 people, most of them reservists and
their families, filled this square and astonished much of
Yugoslavia by staging the largest demonstration since the end of
the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, about 2,000 of them rushed the police station and
vandalized the house of a local boss from Milosevic's governing
Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a drunken military policeman shot a cafe owner in
the town square. And on Thursday night a thousand or so people,
many of them reservists, milled around, shooting dirty looks at
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear has disappeared,'' said Vlada Djordjevic, 31, an
infantry conscript who served for 65 days in Kosovo, while
listening every night with his friends from Leskovac to American,
British and German short-wave radio broadcasts about the war. ``We
were in the field and we could see that Serb radio was telling us
lies about the war. We believed BBC. And now we are not afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be a growing popular movement to force the
Yugoslav leader from power, the wild card may well prove to be the
Yugoslav army and its reservists. In previous bouts of
demonstrations against Milosevic, the army has either come out in
favor of Milosevic or sat on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But the sudden anti-government activism of reservists in this
most unlikely of cities suggests that the army could prove to be a
muscular ally, if the fractious opposition movement can figure out
how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   The reservists' anger is not confined to this city. Demanding
unpaid wages from the Kosovo war, they have sporadically tied up
roads and blocked bridges across much of central and southern
Serbia in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The principal object of the reservists' frustration here in
Leskovac is Zivojin Stefanovic, the local chairman of the Socialist
Party who runs this down-at-the-heels textile town of 170,000.
Stefanovic declined Thursday to return repeated phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   It was his house that reservists smashed up on Tuesday night,
and it was his resignation that remains a non-negotiable demand of
their demonstrations, which are scheduled to go on until he quits
or is fired.
</P>
<P>
   The reservists are also demanding the release from jail of Ivan
Novkovic, a TV Leskovac technician turned local hero. Stunning
local TV viewers, he sneaked his own videotape on the air last
week. It called for the people of Leskovac to gather in the square
on Monday and demand the ouster of Stefanovic. After a huge crowd
did exactly that, throwing in the demand that Milosevic resign, the
TV technician was arrested and sentenced to 30 days in jail.
</P>
<P>
   What infuriated reservists about the local party boss was his
mobilizing zeal for the war in Kosovo. Apparently trying to curry
favor in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, Stefanovic organized the
call-up of about 40,000 local men, according to opposition party
leaders and human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter joke here is that as a result of Stefanovic's
mobilizing passion, there were just two combatants in the Kosovo
war: NATO versus Leskovac.
</P>
<P>
   When reservists came home from the 11-week conflict in early
June, they learned that the government had not provided their
families with food and household supplies, as the army had
promised.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have they been paid the $50 a month they were promised when
they went off to war. So far they have received about a third of
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not the kind of guy who makes trouble, but we need those
wages for electricity bills, for school books for our kids, for
firewood,'' said Bratislav Stamenkovic, 37, a reservist who laid
mines along the Kosovo-Macedonian border during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The reservists said they had also learned that there were going
to be no jobs for veterans and that the local economy was in even
deeper trouble than before they went off to Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The one thing that they have not been told by local officials is
how many soldiers from Leskovac were killed in the war. The local
Serbian Orthodox Church has an unofficial list of 70 names.
Reservists say they will demonstrate on the streets of this town
until they get an official number from the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``In ten years, all we have is war,'' said Pasan Cosic, 55, who
was slightly drunk and very bitter in the town square Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has started and lost wars in the former Yugoslav
republics of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia, as well as in the Serb
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Cosic said he had been conscripted by the Milosevic government
to fight in Croatia, where he lost a son and was wounded in the
knee. Equipped with a plastic knee, he said he was later
conscripted to fight in Bosnia and then in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have war, and I am getting poorer,'' repeated Cosic, a
taxi driver who spoke to the crowd Thursday night from an open
microphone that was made available to anybody who had a complaint
against the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have bread, cigarettes, sugar or cooking oil,'' he
said. ``I am asking Milosevic, `How long can you keep this up?'''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the reservists who gathered here Thursday night said
they were well aware of the atrocities and theft committed by some
Serb fighters in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   They said they personally had not committed crimes against
civilians, a claim that, in general, has been supported by Kosovo
Albanians, who in hundreds of interviews have said that nearly all
the killings of civilians were committed by Serb paramilitary
forces and not by regular army troops.
</P>
<P>
   But the reservists said that everywhere in Kosovo they were
surrounded by Serb men in uniform carrying stolen televisions,
satellite dishes and other electronic equipment. The scene was so
familiar that it generated one of the best jokes of the war, said
Djordjevic, the reservist who spent much of his war listening to
the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Rambo volunteers to fight for the Serbs,'' Djordjevic said.
``In a few days Rambo is back in the states and drunk. Asked why he
quit the war, Rambo answered, `I couldn't carry a gun and a
television set at the same time.'''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing very funny, though, about the Kosovo war,
Djordjevic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, what I care about is finding out who died from
Leskovac,'' he said. ``I don't give a damn about Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
