<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEACEKEEPERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS SAY THEY'RE THE VICTIMS NOW, AS NATO STANDS BY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO POLJE, Yugoslavia _ Almost four months after NATO's bombs
began falling, the tables have turned in Kosovo _ and now it is
Serbs who complain they are being ``ethnically cleansed'' right
under the eyes of international protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs, once the privileged class in Kosovo, are fleeing in fear
_ and, in many cases, being forcibly expelled through threats,
intimidation or arson of their homes _ a tragic mirror image of the
campaign that Serbs mounted against ethnic Albanians over the past
months.
</P>
<P>
   A Serb monitoring organization reports that it receives daily
complaints of Serbs being killed, or their houses being burned.
More commonly, Serbs are being harassed or threatened _ often with
violence _ to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Postwar Kosovo is not a hospitable place for the Obradovic
family and other ethnic Serbs, whose lives and futures were
suddenly upended when the war ended last month.
</P>
<P>
   They sit huddled in fear, afraid to speak their own language,
nervous about walking the streets. They fear for a cousin who
disappeared weeks ago; they think she was kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fear among us. KFOR (NATO's Kosovo Force
peacekeepers) is supposed to protect us, but they don't,'' said
Gavrilo Obradovic, who believes his cousin was abducted by the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Serbian people, it's dangerous to walk in the street,''
said Dragan Kristic of the Center for Peace and Tolerance, a
Serb-government funded organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is intimidation going on. There are many reports of
harassment, intimidation, looting, burning, abduction and
killings,'' agreed Ron Redmond, a spokesman for the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees, which has been coordinating relief
efforts on behalf of refugees from the Kosovo fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The armed international peacekeepers charged with maintaining
order here appear as helpless to protect the Serbs from such crimes
as unarmed international monitors were a year ago, when Albanians
were the victims.
</P>
<P>
   KFOR doesn't even keep close track of incidents reported to them
regarding attacks on Serbs _ even murders, said spokesman Lt.
Commander Louis Garneau.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't keep statistics on civilian deaths,'' Garneau said.
``We keep statistics on the ones we have shot,'' which amounts to
six fatalities and four injured people, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention means you have to protect every person here,'' said
Maj. Jan Joosten, another KFOR spokesman. ``That is an
impossibility here. It happens nowhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no one has more than sketchy statistics on attacks and
crimes against Serbs; peackeeping contingents do not typically
break down crimes along ethnic lines. But spokesmen said that since
Serb forces pulled out of Kosovo under the settlement that ended
the bombing, the incidents have been overwhelmingly against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb-run Center, Kristic said, receives, on average,
complaints of five kidnappings, 10-20 forced evictions, and scores
of reports of harassment daily. Reports of murders are less
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   International refugee agency officials say they are deeply
concerned about the voluntary and forced departure of Serbs, but
they can do little about it except urge Serbs to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed and, officials say, desperately underfunded for
coping with the burden of 650,000 Albanian refugees returning to
burned-out homes and barren fields, the UN refugee agency has not
focused on the Serb exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see one group of refugees coming back, and
another group of refugees leaving,'' said Sadako Ogata, who heads
the UN agency operation here.
</P>
<P>
   But according to government reports in Belgrade and local
evidence in Kosovo, that's exactly what is happening. Serbs say
more than 100,000 Serb civilians _ more than half the Kosovar Serb
population _ have left Kosovo, a count not disputed by UN refugee
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very concerned about people leaving. But in many
cases, we understand why they are leaving,'' Redmond said.
``Unfortunately, a lot of people are coming back bent on
vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   The international community has a political predicament as well.
The KLA and its sympathizers want an independent Kosovo, which the
West has repeatedly insisted it does not support. And the goal of
preserving the territorial integrity of Yugoslavia _ which includes
the Serbian province of Kosovo _ depends on having a multi-ethnic,
non-partitioned state.
</P>
<P>
   Without any ethnic Serbs, the ``multi-ethnic'' status of the
province would be a fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the West's pronouncements of concern do not persuade
two groups of people who just endured a brutal war against each
other that they should live together in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   In one apartment building in the provincial capital of Pristina,
a newly posted sign tells Serb families they must leave.
</P>
<P>
   In one day this week alone, 15 houses were set afire in Prizren,
four in Pristina and five in Stimlje, peacekeeping troops reported.
In the case of Prizren, ``it was a disappointing experience that
the population for the most part was unwilling to help KFOR in its
efforts to extinguish the fires,'' the peace-keepers said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot do anything'' about the burning houses, because ``by
the time we get there, it is too late,'' said Vincente Dalmau,
spokesman for the KFOR base at Pec.
</P>
<P>
   The environment for Serbs is particularly hostile in western
Kosovo, where the worst reported atrocities against ethnic
Albanians occurred. In Pec, the few Serbs left are heard speaking
Albanian in the streets. They are the brave ones; no Serb,
residents here say, is welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they try to come back, they will only find murder here,''
said Mantor Kasapolli, 23, an Albanian. ``There would be every day,
5-10 dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a problem for Serbs who come back,'' added
Jeton Bala, 22, in starkly similar terms. ``If they want to come
back, they know they are all dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood in Kosovo is virtually the same as it was a year ago,
except that the players have changed places. It is now young KLA
members who strut confidently along the streets, while Serbs stay
indoors, at home with their families.
</P>
<P>
   Cafes and restaurants once run and patronized by Serbs are now
populated with laughing, gleeful Albanians _ the Albanian flag is
displayed, letting all know that the establishment has been
commandeered by Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs _ who nine years ago benefitted when Albanians were fired
en masse from their jobs when President Slobodan Milosevic revoked
the largely autonomous status of the province _ worry that there
will be no work for them in an Albanian-dominated province.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian students are excited about going to public schools and
colleges, learning in their own language. Serbian students wonder
if there will be places for them in the post-war university, and
whether their former Serb professors will return to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers at the Serb Center for Peace and Tolerance work with
armed KFOR guards protecting them, gathering evidence of crimes
against their people and complaining that no one is listening _
just as Albanians did for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Even the everyday act of taking a cab is a loaded proposition
here: Serbs say they are afraid to get into an Albanian taxi.
</P>
<P>
   Health care is also political, as it was under Serb
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian doctors who were fired from their jobs in 1990 have
come back in triumph, and Serb doctors have elected not to return
to work, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't tell them to go. We told them to do the work they
were doing,'' but the Serbs left anyway, said Dr. Gazmend Kaqaniku,
an ethnic Albanian opthamologist. ``They didn't say why.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian doctors say they wish their Serb colleagues would
return, and add that they will treat any patient, regardless of
ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   The patients are less egalitarian: some of the war-wounded who
were treated _ mistreated, they say _ by Serb doctors during the
war are now being treated by fellow Albanians, a change they say is
dramatically better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serb doctors cut off my leg; they didn't even try to save
it,'' said Shajip Loshaj, 24, injured as he was fleeing Kosovo in
April. ``Then they beat me in my bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now? I feel like I'm in my own home,'' Loshaj said. ``We were
all waiting for this day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
