<HEADLINE>
DON'T GO TO PIECES OVER NEW TOY 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JEANNIE KEVER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) Back off, Jar Jar.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector Gadget is coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   Just not all at once.
</P>
<P>
   This year's version of the modern-day seasonal affliction _
summer blockbuster marketing mania _ started with Star Wars' ``The
Phantom Menace,'' but that was just the beginning. The latest
technofest begins next weekend under the Golden Arches.
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to visit early and often.
</P>
<P>
   Like eight times over the next month, collecting eight separate
pieces to assemble into one 15-inch Inspector Gadget.
</P>
<P>
   One toy, eight Happy Meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspector Gadget,'' in case you've been in a coma and missed
the ubiquitous movie trailers, is a special-effects blowout
starring Matthew Broderick as a bumbling security guard who, thanks
to robotics and the obligatory gorgeous scientist/love interest,
becomes a virtual crime-fighting machine, via various grafted-on
gizmos.
</P>
<P>
   Think Maxwell Smart on steroids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspector Gadget'' opens July 23. The McDonald's promotion
begins a week earlier and runs through Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the eight pieces functions separately: the siren hat,
which produces a mechanical siren noise when the propeller is
rotated; the lever-activated hand; the arm that squirts water; the
leg with an enclosed pair of pliers ...
</P>
<P>
   The Gadget Man is one handy dude.
</P>
<P>
   No batteries needed, but some assembly required.
</P>
<P>
   Two pieces will be available each week, according to Kevin
Bradbury, a McDonald's spokesman. You'll be able to request which
piece you want, one per Happy Meal, to ensure you get both pieces
available that week. (And yes, you can buy two Happy Meals and get
two different toy parts on one visit.)
</P>
<P>
   The following week, those pieces will be retired and two new
pieces will be available. Bradbury said he didn't know how many
toys were being produced for inclusion in the $1.99 Happy Meals,
but restaurants order enough for the markets, based on what they
believe they need.
</P>
<P>
   He's not predicting a run of Teeny Weeny Beanie Baby
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the multipiece marketing ploy isn't blackmail _
parents are free to buy their kids only part of Inspector Gadget.
</P>
<P>
   Just try explaining that one.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
