<HEADER>
A3601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICHELIN09-COX     07-08 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michelin may choose S. Carolina
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An offer of tax incentives and a spot in a new
industrial park may not be enough for a northeast Georgia community
to beat out South Carolina for a new $400-million Michelin tire
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson County in South Carolina appears to be ahead of
neighboring Stephens County in Georgia in the rivalry for the plant
and up to 350 jobs, according to a story in Thursday's Anderson
Independent-Mail.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper quoted unnamed sources as saying pivotal
advantages for Anderson County include additional tax incentives
recently approved by South Carolina legislators, as well as a
workforce that the company prefers. Michelin's North American
headquarters is in Greenville, S.C., and it has more than 9,000
workers and eight plants in that state. It has no manufacturing
operations in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Anderson County Council gave preliminary approval Tuesday to
issuing up to $400 million in industrial revenue bonds for a plant,
which county officials call ``Beta Company.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, company spokesman Jim Morton said that it is ``pure
speculation'' that the company will build a new plant or that it
has a site in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens County Development Authority executive director Lonnie
Edenfield Jr. said, ``It's our standard procedure not to comment on
an active working project.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens is mostly rural, sitting along Lake Hartwell and
Georgia's border with South Carolina just north of I-85. The county
has 28,000 residents and no zoning to regulate development.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials have pushed to recruit new employers: A year ago
the development authority bought 243 acres for a new industrial
park and took out options on land to increase it to more than 800
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, no new major employers have located in the county
in the past three years, according to Edenfield.
</P>
<P>
   Many rural Georgia communities have complained they are losing
too many jobs prospects to other Southeastern states. They point
out that Georgia tax incentives offered to employers are often far
less lucrative than those provided by nearby states such as Alabama
and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Department of Industry, Trade &AMP; Tourism proposed
beefing up the state's incentive package, but earlier this year
Gov. Roy Barnes put the effort on hold. He said he wanted a more
comprehensive review of the value and the costs of incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local officials say prospective employers are
slipping away. ``The playing field is not equal on the state
level,'' Edenfield said. ``Local communities are not able to make
up the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
