<HEADER>
A3602 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUS-OUTLOOK-ART-2T     07-08 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-OUTLOOK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS, NO. 2, STRUTS, BUT NOT ENOUGH TO REALLY ANNOY BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Spain, Wash.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOULOUSE, France _ In the giant hangers here where Airbus
Industrie's single-aisle jetliners are assembled, only a handful of
workers can be found, testing systems, attaching the landing gear
or drilling holes to fasten wings to the fuselages.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the busy _ and until recently, chaotic _ assembly
line in Renton, Wash., near Seattle, where Boeing Co., the world's
biggest commercial jet producer, makes its narrow-body jets, the
atmosphere is almost ghostlike. But don't be fooled.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus consortium, which is now Boeing's only competitor,
has never been busier since it was founded 30 years ago as a way to
revive the flagging European aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   The eerily quiet Airbus assembly line _ a reflection of
decentralized production and a surprisingly efficient operation _
is one of the many apparent contradictions about the consortium
that have altered expectations about its future prospects and
seriously vexed Boeing. Long derided in Seattle as a European jobs
program, Airbus now produces more revenue per employee than
Boeing's commercial airplane division. Supposedly burdened by an
unwieldy ownership structure that requires consensus between four
partners in four countries, Airbus has proved surprisingly nimble.
It boasts lower production costs than Boeing, though that is
difficult to determine because of the Airbus structure.
</P>
<P>
   These days the plucky irreverence of a perennial No. 2 has given
way to a subtle, but perceptible swagger. But for Airbus, as for
many an adolescent coming of age, the conceit is laced with
insecurity and fear.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which is emerging from an embarrassing production
foul-up two years ago that cost it billions of dollars, is
committed to lowering its costs so that it can recement its
domination of the global market. At Airbus, the goal is to hang on
to the 50 percent market share it recently achieved. But the
consortium's effort to transform itself into a conventional
corporation _ a move both Airbus executives and industry analysts
see as crucial for competing with Boeing over the long run _ has
stalled, sowing doubts that it will ever happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our competitor is not the Boeing of today,'' Noel Forgeard,
the Airbus chief executive, said. ``It is the Boeing that will be,
that is to say probably a more streamlined, rejuvenated Boeing.
That is what we have to prepare ourselves for.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Callan, an aerospace analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. in New
York, agreed. ``There is a window of opportunity that the Airbus
partners have to keep one step ahead of Boeing,'' he said. ``It
would not be good for Airbus' standing if they squandered this
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Airbus now has models that compete with Boeing in every category
except the giant 747 and has recently snagged such previously
all-Boeing customers as British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is owned by Aerospatiale Matra of France and
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG of Germany, which each hold 37.9
percent, British Aerospace PLC, which holds 20 percent, and
Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain, which holds the remaining
4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Each partner acts as a subcontractor, supplying different parts
of each airplane: the nose section and cockpit, the center
fuselage, the wings and so on. Whereas Boeing has historically
hired and fired tens of thousands of workers as the demand for its
airplanes rose and fell, European labor laws make it prohibitively
expensive to lay off so many workers. Consequently, the Airbus
partners have relegated more work to suppliers and largely
automated their own manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   The result, contrary to all expectations, is a much more modern
and efficient production system than Boeing's. Large sections of
Airbus airplanes are flown to Toulouse and Hamburg from factories
around Europe by a fleet of giant modified Airbus cargo jets called
Belugas. There, the largely complete components are ``snapped''
together by small crews.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Airbus executives learned of Boeing's plans
to cut its production costs by 25 percent in a bid to underprice
Airbus and gain market share. Word went out to the Airbus partners
that they would need to streamline. While Boeing ultimately failed
to carry out its plan _ in fact, its costs ballooned _ the Airbus
partners succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   British Aerospace, which makes all the Airbus wings, cut
employment more than 44 percent to 6,000 from about 11,000 between
1992 and 1996 but still managed to produce its wings 50 percent
faster at the end of that time than it had at the beginning.
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, or DASA, which makes fuselages, cut its
costs by about 40 percent in the last three years. The time between
when an airline ordered a single-aisle Airbus A320 and when it was
delivered has collapsed from 18 months four years ago to nine
months today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its recent difficulties, Boeing refuses to concede half
the market to Airbus. ``In the foreseeable future, we will still be
producing twice as many airplanes as Airbus,'' Seddik Belyamani,
Boeing's executive vice president in charge of sales and marketing,
said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Forgeard, who took the helm at Airbus last year,
insisted that he was only interested in a 50 percent share because
any more would ``trigger a desperate reaction from Boeing.'' Airbus
would like to maintain its steady march toward building 350
airplanes each year, about half the forecast demand. That way it
can control its costs and maintain a stable level of employment.
</P>
<P>
   The market share wars do not help either manufacturer, Forgeard
said. ``What we are interested in is building profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like the much-heralded global duopoly many aerospace
analysts became excited about when Boeing bought the McDonnell
Douglas Corp. in 1997. European and American regulators are
investigating Airbus and Boeing for recent rises in their catalog
prices. Forgeard dismissed the notion that there was any collusion
with Boeing and insisted that strong competition would continue
even when the two have roughly equal market share.
</P>
<P>
   But for Airbus to keep pace with Boeing, it must become a bona
fide corporation with a single management in charge of expenses,
finance and customer support, analysts and Airbus executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Under its current structure, the four partners are responsible
for the cost and financing of their various operations. Airbus,
with a staff of just 3,000, is responsible only for design, sales
and marketing and flight testing. It does not even know how much
its airplanes cost to produce because the partners do not reveal
their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard believes that putting all of Airbus under one roof
would bring huge advantages. Pooling the $10 billion worth of raw
materials now purchased annually by the partners would slash costs,
they say. In addition, a corporate Airbus would be able to use its
own assets to help finance sales of its jets instead of having to
rely on the assets of its partners. A single company would be able
to streamline decision-making in key areas like customer support.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But getting the four partners to consider giving up prize
operations has not been easy. In December, talks between the four
partners collapsed when they could not agree on how to value the
assets each contributes to Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Massey, the Airbus financial controller, said that it might
have been easier to transform the consortium five years ago, when
it was smaller. But now, with $15 billion in annual revenue, the
stakes have become too high. ``Ask someone to make a 1 percent
concession to the others and it is $150 million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the negotiations has been a larger consolidation of
the European aerospace industry that has also involved all the
Airbus partners.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, British Aerospace was in talks to merge with
DASA when it angered the Germans by deciding to buy Britain's
GEC-Marconi instead. Then, last month, DASA announced that it was
merging with Construcciones Aeronautics, or CASA, reducing the four
Airbus partners to three. Also last month, shares of Aerospatiale
Matra, which was formed by the combination of the state-owned
Aerospatiale and Matra Hautes Technologies, another French company,
were floated on the Paris stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Callan of Merrill Lynch said he could no longer be sure that
Airbus would ever unify under a single corporate umbrella. He said
some bilateral agreements, perhaps merging the three remaining
partners into two, might occur instead.
</P>
<P>
   But Forgeard said he was encouraged by the recent deals, which
merged each of the two state-owned Airbus partners _ Aerospatiale
and CASA _ with more market-oriented companies. Aerospatiale, in
particular, has been the partner most resistant to the idea of a
single corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the dawn of a complete transformation of the
corporate culture of Aerospatiale,'' he said. ``That is reason to
be much more optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard should know. Before joining Airbus, he spent 12 years
as an executive at the Lagardere Group, which owned Matra Hautes
Technologies, and is now, after the French government, Aerospatiale
Matra's second-largest shareholder. A graduate of the elite Ecole
Polytechnique, Forgeard, 54, has swung between government service
and private business over the course of his career. He is part of a
new wave of French executives who are committed to increasing
shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   One of Forgeard's toughest decisions will be whether to commit
Airbus to spend more than $10 billion to develop a new
550-passenger super jumbo jet called the A3XX. Boeing has concluded
that demand for such a jet is too limited to justify the investment
but Airbus is continuing its development work and hopes to decide
next year whether to begin building the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said he would not proceed with the A3XX unless he was
persuaded that the project will deliver a 20 percent return on
capital. Nevertheless, he sees the plane as critical to future
competition with Boeing because a quarter of the dollars spent on
new airplanes over the next 20 years will be for jets the size of
the 747 or larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must take a proactive position,'' he said. ``I cannot let
Boeing say there is no demand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
