<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRAH-MAGAZINE-NYT &LR;      07-08 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRAH-MAGAZINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST TO PRODUCE OPRAH, THE MAGAZINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Oprah Winfrey frequently graces the covers of women's
magazines, but now she is getting in on the editorial side of the
publishing business.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winfrey has teamed up with Hearst Magazines to publish a new
magazine that will seek to capitalize on her enormous popularity
with women. The magazine, which has not been named yet, will hit
newsstands next spring with 850,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion victims, be warned, though. Ms. Winfrey will not be
pontificating on the pros and cons of leopard-print pants and
frosted eye shadow. The magazine, which will have four to six
issues in the first year and then come out monthly, will cover
issues related to spirituality, community, family, relationships
and work, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine will also provide an additional outlet for Ms.
Winfrey's popular ``Oprah's Book Club,'' in which she chooses books
on her television show and encourages viewers to read along. The
magazine may include reviews and excerpts of the book and will
provide some format for readers to interact with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This magazine provides a different way for people to be
informed and inspired,'' Ms. Winfrey said. That is not to say it
will be entirely void of buzz about fashion trends and ``in'' hair
styles.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, ``this new magazine will reflect her
business and personal life principles and will be another media
outlet for the 33 million women viewers who watch her each week,''
said Cathleen P. Black, president of Hearst Magazines, which
publishes Good Housekeeping, Cosmopolitan, Harper's Bazaar and 13
other magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winfrey is essentially licensing her name to Hearst, which
will oversee editorial, publishing and distribution of the
magazine. Terms, which do not preclude her from appearing on the
covers of competing magazines, were not disclosed. Ms, Winfrey will
not be listed on the masthead and will likely only write one
article in each issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, ``she is going to have a lot of input about content,
images, visuals and layout,'' said Ellen Levine, the editor in
chief of Good Housekeeping, who has been working closely with Ms.
Winfrey and Ms. Black on the magazine's concept and design.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking the same sort of lift Ms. Winfrey's seal of approval
provides to book publishing, the magazine title ``will involve
Oprah's name one way or another,'' Ms. Black said, and she will
appear on the first cover. But will women toss out Good
Housekeeping in favor of the new Oprah-inspired magazine?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a direct overlap,'' said Alan Jurmain,
executive vice president and media director at Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS
advertising agency, noting that the publication will appeal to
marketers who already advertise on the talk show. ``I think Oprah's
personality is fairly distinct from the standard Hearst magazine
profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is counting on the magazine having wide appeal. But,
``obviously they want to try to attract the better-educated
contingent of the television program, those who follow the Oprah
way of living,'' Jurmain said. ``She's doing a reverse Martha
Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Winfrey's new venture, however, does not mean that the queen
of daytime chat has grown bored with her show, according to her
company, Harpo Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   Though there has been much speculation about when she will end
the long-running show, ``Oprah is fully committed to `The Oprah
Winfrey Show' through the year 2002,'' a Harpo spokeswoman said.
``At this time, we are not making any announcements regarding
Oprah's continuing beyond the year 2002.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
