<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON GENDER ISSUES, CHANGE HASN'T COME EASILY FOR TEXAS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lisa Sheppard wanted nothing more than to become
the first female Texas Ranger seven years ago but got tagged an
independent-thinking ``woman's libber'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   For so long, the legendary Texas lawmen had been the bastion of
tall, Anglo males who wore Stetsons, rode horses and wielded guns,
big men upholding law and order on the wild frontier. Today there
are women in the ranks, but only two out of 107 Rangers _ Christine
Nix of Waco and Marrie Garcia of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an open 1990s organization,'' contends Texas Department
of Public Safety spokesman Mike Cox. ``It doesn't make any
difference if an applicant for a job is male or female as long as
they're qualified. We're delighted to have female troopers and
female officers and female Rangers ... and I'm in sure in the
future we'll have even more.''
</P>
<P>
   As a federal appeals court decision handed down Tuesday makes
clear, however, such changes in thinking have not come easily.
</P>
<P>
   Although the appeals court favored a former Texas Ranger chief
accused of derailing the &UR;  &LR; highly qualified Sheppard, the DPS still
faces a related sex discrimination and sexual harassment lawsuit
that could be heard this summer by U.S. District Judge David
Hittner in Houston, lawyers on both sides said this week. In it
Sheppard alleges sex discrimination, while another woman who
briefly was a Texas Ranger claims that she was sexually harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard first abandoned her dream to join the elite force in
1992 when individual Rangers advised the DPS trooper that ``it was
not yet time for a woman to join the Rangers,'' according to a
summary of the case by the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the state's Public Safety Commission, which oversees
the DPS, decided the following year that the time for women had
come, it generated ``no small amount of controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard tried again in 1993 to no avail, even though she had
scored among the highest on a written exam of all the applicants.
Upon learning the selection process was rigged, she filed suit
against Maurice Cook, the former captain of the Rangers. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Sheppard said two Ranger officers on the selection committee
said that Cook told them to adjust their scores so that two other
women _ Garcia and Cheryl Steadman _ could be chosen instead.
</P>
<P>
   Cook wanted to reject Sheppard because she was ``too independent
and ... opinionated,'' according to the appeals court. Sheppard
claimed his actions were in retaliation for her political beliefs
and that they violated her right of free speech. She said he wanted
to blackball her because she was a ``woman's libber.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that it was a ``close'' call of judgment, the court
dismissed that suit Tuesday. Because Sheppard ``concedes that she
never verbally expressed'' any feminist beliefs to Cook, wrote
Circuit Judge Carl E. Stewart, the Rangers captain couldn't have
violated her free speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the court had harsh words for Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is overwhelming that Cook acted unreasonably in
deliberately rigging the selection process,'' the court said.
``Cook even willingly admits that he made the offensive statements
at issue. Although we readily note our disdain for Cook's improper
actions, we nevertheless conclude that Sheppard presented
inadequate proof for her claim that she engaged in speech or other
activities entitled to protection under the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what effect, if any, the appellate court's opinion might
have on the upcoming discrimination and harassment suit against DPS
and the Rangers remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an appellate panel just reading papers sees it that
clearly, a jury will obviously see the overwhelming evidence of him
rigging the process because we're going to have live witnesses,''
said Beatrice Mladenka-Fowler, an attorney for Sheppard and
Steadman.
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard was first discouraged, then bypassed and finally hired
as a Ranger in 1994. She turned down the once-coveted assignment,
her lawyer said, believing she would be shunted into
secretarial-style administrative work rather than active field
investigations. Steadman, on the other hand, joined the Rangers but
didn't last long after complaining of unfair treatment and sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was given menial chores to do. She was not allowed to go
out and do Texas Rangers stuff, like investigations,'' said
Mladenka-Fowler, noting the harassment claim was based on an
overnight meeting at which the men told off-color jokes designed to
make Steadman uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I filed the lawsuit in 1995. It was probably a year before
that when I tried to work it out within the department,'' Steadman
said. ``Really I've been waiting since '94 for some end to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Steadman, &UR;  &LR; who works in the vehicle theft division of DPS in
Houston, declined to comment further. Sheppard, &UR;  &LR; a state trooper in
the Corpus Christi area who has since been promoted, was
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   While sex discrimination complaints from the past await a final
resolution, DPS spokesmen insist Texas' two female Rangers today
are in the field investigating high-profile cases, such as a
controversial charter school in Waco and a string of Texas murders
along a railway line. Neither of the female Rangers returned phone
calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department's policy is not to discuss litigation,'' Cox
said. ``We think it's always the highest ground for matters pending
in court to be discussed in the judicial process and not in the
news media.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
