<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: DUBLIN PLEA TO IRA
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bertie Ahern of Ireland urged the IRA to make a
``clear, unambiguous statement'' that it intends to disarm under
the terms of the Northern Ireland peace accord. This, he said,
could ease the entry of members of the IRA's political wing, Sinn
Fein, into a new Protestant-Catholic cabinet by next Thursday's
deadline for establishment of the new body. The IRA, which has
observed a cease-fire for two years, has repeatedly said it has no
plans to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET'S COST TO TAXPAYERS
</P>
<P>
   The Law Lords, England's highest court, ruled that Gen. Augusto
Pinochet would have to pay little of the costs stemming from the
legal actions since his arrest in London last October on a Spanish
request to extradite him to Madrid to face charges of crimes
against humanity. The seven-judge panel did not speak of money
amounts, but its breakdown of the 83-year-old former Chilean
dictator's responsibility for legal fees meant that most of the
estimated $10 million the case has cost so far would be borne by
British taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: PREMIER'S AIDE TO TESTIFY IN CORSICA
</P>
<P>
   Clotilde Valter, an aide to Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, will
testify in Corsica on Friday about whether authorities on the
island ordered the police to set fire to an illegally built
beachfront restaurant last April. After the police were caught,
authorities in Paris blamed the chief government administrative
official in Corsica, Bernard Bonnet. Recently released from jail,
he denied ordering the firebombing and said he kept Valter fully
informed of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: NEW DATE ON HOLOCAUST REPORT
</P>
<P>
   A twice-delayed report on Switzerland's treatment of Jewish
refugees fleeing the Holocaust is to be made public in November, an
independent historical commission announced. The report has been
more than two years in the making. Switzerland did accept a number
of Jews who fled Germany, but has been accused of sending thousands
more back over the border.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ALGERIA: TIES WITH FRANCE ON MEND
</P>
<P>
   The president of Algeria, a former French colony that has viewed
Paris warily ever since winning a bloody war of independence in
1962, told Europe 1 radio that he would be glad to welcome the
president of France ``any time.'' President Abdelaziz Bouteflika,
who has begun releasing 2,300 Islamic militants jailed in a civil
war that he said had killed 100,000 people since 1992, urged
President Jacques Chirac to come to Algeria to cement a ``special
relationship.'' Chirac said last weekend that he hoped he could go
``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: REBELS STRIKE NEAR BOGOTA
</P>
<P>
   After gaining a two-week postponement of peace talks with the
government, the country's largest left-wing guerrilla group, the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, began a series of attacks
on villages near Bogota, the capital. A spokesman for the military
acknowledged ``heavy losses on both sides'' and said the rebels'
objective is ``to carry out attacks in the capital.''
</P>
<P>
   PERU: EX-PRESIDENT STYMIED
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stop an exiled former president, Alan Garcia,
from campaigning for Congress next year, legislators passed a law
prohibiting Peruvians accused of corruption from running for
office. Garcia, who faces charges that he took more than $1 million
in bribes while president in the 1980s, has been planning a run for
Congress from his apartment in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TRADING POLITICAL CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   The two politicians leading in the race for the governing
party's presidential nomination are accusing each other of using
public funds for their campaigns. Francisco Labastida said Roberto
Madrazo spent Tabasco state funds to pay for a television campaign
promoting his own image before quitting as governor. Madrazo
accused Labastida of turning tours to distribute anti-crime grants
into a campaign of self-promotion before resigning as interior
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: AN ADDRESS ON KASHMIR
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has yet to explain publicly his
plans for getting Muslim militant fighters to withdraw from Indian
Kashmir, though he is expected broadcast an address to the nation
Friday or Saturday. His minister of information, Mushahid Hussain,
said in an interview that the ``freedom fighters'' cannot be
expected to withdraw until India agrees to a cease-fire.
``Otherwise,'' he said, ``they'd just be sitting ducks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
