<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYE-DISCOVERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTEIN MAY HOLD KEY TO EYE DISEASES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Md., Pa.)  (jw) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers working on control of the body's blood supply have
found a protein that regulates the blood vessels in the eye. The
discovery may help explain the longstanding puzzle of how the
transparent parts of the eye are usually kept free of blood
vessels.
</P>
<P>
   It could also prove helpful in treating eye diseases like
age-related macular degeneration and diabetic retinopathy, in which
unwanted blood vessels invade the eye.
</P>
<P>
   The protein is an angiogenesis inhibitor, a substance that
inhibits blood vessel growth. Angiogenesis inhibitors are promising
candidates for attacking tumors by cutting off their blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the new angiogenesis inhibitor was discovered by Dr.
Noel Bouck of the Northwestern University Medical School in
Chicago, Dr. David Dawson of the University of California at Los
Angeles and other colleagues. They are reporting their finding in
Friday's issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
   The protein, which is made by the retinal pigment epithelium
cells that line the back of the eye, had already been discovered in
another role by Dr. S. Patricia Beccera of the National Eye
Institute. Dr. Beccera named it pigment epithelium-derived factor
or PEDF.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bouck and her colleagues found the protein in a culture of
retinal tumor cells. She was pursuing a theory that the agent known
to suppress tumor growth in these cells might also control an
angiogenesis inhibitor protein. The theory turned out to be wrong,
but she found an angiogenesis inhibitor protein anyway. Further
tests showed it was identical to Dr. Beccera's protein.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bouck said that blood supply in the eye seems to be
controlled by the prevailing balance between a pair of substances,
PEDF, which inhibits new blood vessel growth and a factor called
VEGF (pronounced veg-eff) which is known to stimulate vessel
growth.
</P>
<P>
   When oxygen is low, as is the case in certain eye diseases, the
pigment epithelial cells produce less PEDF, allowing blood vessels
to invade and more oxygen to come in. When oxygen is sufficient,
the cells step up production of PEDF, which suffuses the eye and
banishes blood vessels, Dr. Bouck said.
</P>
<P>
   Invasion of the eye by new blood vessels is a critical cause of
vision loss in many kinds of blindness, particularly two of the
most common, diabetic retinopathy and age-related macular
degeneration. Understanding how the healthy eye excludes blood
vessels should in principle help researchers devise treatments for
conditions in which the normal system breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Campochiaro, professor of ophthalmology and
neuroscience at the Johns Hopkins School of Medicine, described Dr.
Bouck's finding as ``fascinating'' and said her data suggested that
PEDF was part of the eye's natural mechanism for regulating blood
vessel growth. Although angiogenesis inhibitors known from other
tissues of the body have been found in the eye, they do not seem to
play an important role, he said.
</P>
<P>
   PEDF may have a role in treating eye disease, Campochiaro said,
but maybe not until researchers find a way to insert the gene for
the protein into retinal cells, because proteins are hard to
deliver in pill form.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Berger of the Scheie Eye Institute at the University
of Philadelphia said that the discovery of PEDF had increased
understanding of blood vessel regulation in the eye but that there
was ``a long way to go'' before it might play a role in any
clinical trial.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
