<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-COMFORT09-COX     07-08 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-COMFORT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Major appliances plug into 30% of electric bill
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A couple weeks ago we talked about the efficient
use of air conditioners, fans and shade trees to keep your home
comfortably cool at reasonable cost this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Today we'll go over a few other tips associated with summer
comfort and energy efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Appliances
</P>
<P>
   Air conditioning isn't the only thing driving up electrical
bills at this time of the year. For example, children and adults
are outdoors more, prompting more wardrobe changes over the course
of a day, so you may find yourself washing more clothes in summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Information Administration of the U.S. Department of
Energy says major appliances consume 30 percent of the total
electricity in the average home, compared with 26 percent for
heating and cooling. Another 10 percent goes toward heating water.
</P>
<P>
   Making a few minor changes in your household habits, along with
a little preventive maintenance, will reduce energy consumption and
save money, says Dixie Trout, a spokeswoman for Amana Home
Appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Start by increasing the use of an appliance now found in 90
percent of American households _ the microwave oven. Using a
conventional electric oven to bake a potato uses about 18 times as
much power as cooking the same potato in a microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Open the refrigerator door as infrequently as possible, and
don't hold it open for long periods.
</P>
<P>
   Allow leftovers to cool slightly before storing them in the
refrigerator. Plan meals ahead so you'll have time to move foods
from the freezer to the refrigerator for defrosting. It takes
longer, but the defrosting foods help keep the refrigerator
compartment cool.
</P>
<P>
   When storing food in the refrigerator, place it in an airtight
container so the refrigerator doesn't have to work as hard to
control humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Vacuum the coils of your refrigerator about once a quarter, more
often if dust accumulates there quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Don't overload your washing machine, and remember to adjust the
water level to suit the size of the load you are washing. Use
cold-water wash and rinse cycles when you can.
</P>
<P>
   Take advantage of the sun and breeze by drying clothes on a line
outdoors. If you use a clothes dryer, remove clothes promptly, and
don't overload the dryer.
</P>
<P>
   Clean the lint trap before each new dryer load. Check the vent
hose regularly to be sure it isn't clogged. Set the temperature
according to the fabrics you are drying; the dryer doesn't always
have to be set on the highest temperature.
</P>
<P>
   You might use less hot water and less energy if you wash large
loads of dishes in your dishwasher instead of constantly filling
and draining the sink to wash a few dishes at a time by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the drying cycle on the dishwasher. Instead, open the door
of the dishwasher after the wash and rinse cycles so the dishes can
air-dry.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling humidity
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you heard the phrase ``It's not the heat;
it's the humidity''?
</P>
<P>
   Humidity is a measure of the amount of moisture suspended in the
air. When the humidity is high, our natural personal cooling system
_ sweating _ becomes less efficient.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cooling the air, air conditioners reduce
humidity, and that helps us feel more comfortable. But even without
air conditioning, reducing humidity makes your house more pleasant
in summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to have a bathroom exhaust fan and to run it for
a while after every shower. The same goes for your range hood _ run
it when cooking to take excess steam out of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, it's a good idea to use tight-fitting lids when
cooking. Not only do the lids reduce the steam produced, but they
also speed cooking time and reduce the energy used in cooking.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a dehumidifier, remember that it needs regular
attention. When it's been running a while, it collects water and
must be emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Check your foundation and attic vents. They should be set to
allow air circulation above and below your living areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some houses are drier than others, and some people actually have
to run humidifiers during summer months to add moisture to the air.
</P>
<P>
   If you're using a humidifier, follow the manufacturer's
instructions on inspecting and replacing the media pad. You'll
probably need to do at least one replacement over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: Make sure your appliances and household controls
are all set in summer mode.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a furnace-mounted humidifier, it should be turned
off unless you have one of those unusually dry houses that needs
year-round moisturizing.
</P>
<P>
   Check your programmable thermostat. Is it set for the patterns
your family is following now? In general, the system should turn
itself on in the morning before the family wakes up, so the house
is cool for morning activities, and shut itself off to conserve
energy while the family sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   If no one is home during the day, the system should shut off
when the family leaves and turn back on before people come home
from work or other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Some clothes-dryer vents have switches that allow you to set
them to retain some of the warm, moist air indoors during the
winter. Make sure the switch is set to direct all the exhaust
outside during summer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
