<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-PIE09-COX     07-08 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PIE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My, my, this 'American Pie' is lewd, but filled with laughs
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Fans of gross-out comedies and simulated
sex with baked goods will be the prime audience for ``American
Pie,'' the latest movie to nudge the bounds of movie humor for a
mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   There is lots of oral sex, masturbation, loss of virginity,
nudity and diarrhea humor, not to mention the brief full frontal
contact with an apple pie that, reportedly, had to be edited to
avoid an NC-17 rating. Despite all of that, ``American Pie'' turns
out to have a gooey center, with gentle instructive messages about
the difference between love and sex, the importance of respect for
women and how initiation into the world of sex really is a
regrettable loss of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, don't be surprised if all moviegoers will be talking
about is the ``hair gel'' in the beer cup, the Internet voyeurism
and that darned pie.
</P>
<P>
   Move over Farrelly brothers, there's a new sibling team in town.
It's director Paul Weitz and producer Chris Weitz, whose
screenwriting credits on ``Antz'' and ``Madeline'' hardly prepare
us for the crude comedy of ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Humor is a highly subjective matter, but this is a considerably
wittier movie than the wildly popular ``There's Something About
Mary,'' which it so clearly tries to emulate (without that
picture's mean-spiritedness). Say what you will about the Weitzes,
at least they don't abuse any dogs in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Pie'' opens with high school senior Jim (forlorn,
frustrated Jason Biggs) squinting at a scrambled porno channel, and
planning a little solo sex. If this goes beyond your taste level _
and it might _ you'll never make it through this movie. When Jim is
interrupted by his flustered parents, his well-meaning father (a
bumbling, very amusing Eugene Levy) begins a running gag's worth of
intrusions into Jim's sexual attempts, eventually catching him
having carnal knowledge of the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Jim is one of four guys who form a pact to do whatever it takes
to lose their virginity before graduation. There's Oz (``Election''
's Chris Klein) who tries to fake sensitivity pursuing a girl in
the jazz choir, Kevin (Thomas Ian Nicholas of ``Rookie of the
Year'') who is stopped by his inability to say he loves his
longtime girlfriend and egghead Finch (Eddie Kaye Thomas of the
little-seen ``Illtown''), who is smart enough to pay for gossip
about his physical endowments to improve his chances for a prom
date.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a ``Porky's'' or almost every other teen sex comedy, the
girls of ``American Pie'' also have raging libidos, but they want
it done right. When Jim is observed on the Internet clumsily trying
to seduce a foreign exchange student, groups of girls enjoy
laughing at him as much as the boys do.
</P>
<P>
   Director Weitz may or may not have ambitions beyond gross-out
comedy, but his ability to sustain the humor in his debut feature
already puts him above many young filmmakers. He also has a nice
touch with actors, drawing solid performances from an ensemble of
relative newcomers. Worth noting among the female cast are Natasha
Lyonne (``Slums of Beverly Hills'') as a senior who manages to stay
above the sexual fray, Mena Suvari as the wary choir quarry and
Alyson Hannigan (Willow on TV's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'') as a
geeky refugee from band camp who defies her prom date's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe gross-out comedies are just a fad that will soon fade, but
``American Pie'' is not the movie that will stop, or even slow, the
phenomenon. Teens everywhere will want to see it, putting further
strain on theaters to try to police the R-rating admission policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMERICAN PIE''
</P>
<P>
   3 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Language, nudity, sexual situations, pastry abuse
</P>
<P>
   Running time: One hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Another gross-out comedy, but a funny one, about
high schoolers trying to lose their virginity, from a new talented
filmmaking brother team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
