<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ROAD09-COX     07-08 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ROAD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Arlington Road' twists delightfully _ until cliches ruin the
rideBy Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ One day, some clever entrepreneur will
create a film festival that shows only the first half of movies,
turning off the projector before the stories get out of hand, the
cliches pile up and the action sequences grow outlandish. Then, and
only then, can we enjoy suspense pictures like ``Arlington Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Director Mark Pellington (``Going All the Way'') and
screenwriter Ehren Kruger seem to be onto something with their
methodically constructed, gripping tale of paranoia in the Northern
Virginia suburbs. But they squander what they've built when the
hazy cloud of doubts gives way to the usual car chases and fights.
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary history Professor Michael Faraday (Jeff Bridges)
lectures on domestic terrorism and plies conspiracy theories at
George Washington University by day. At night, his suspicious
nature begins spilling over into his peaceful residential
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   What about that new Norman Rockwell-esque couple across the
street, cardiganed Oliver Lang and his sweet, soccer mom wife
Cheryl (the astutely cast Tim Robbins and Joan Cusack), who lie
about their history, receive suspicious mail and are so guarded
about some blueprints? Could they be planning to blow up a
government office building?
</P>
<P>
   In a consciously slow, but effectively tense first hour, widower
Faraday is seen as a caring, protective dad to his 10-year-old son
Grant, telegraphing that the kid will soon be in serious jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The death of his FBI agent wife in a Ruby Ridgelike shootout
sets up Faraday's bitterness at the government, making him unstable
enough to have those around him question his suspicions. Is he
coming unhinged? So far, all Faraday suspects is circumstantial and
the movie's tone is deliciously noncommittal and creepy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if director Pellington flipped a switch, ``Arlington
Road'' shifts into overdrive and subtlety gets traded in for
heavy-handed pyrotechnics. Michael's previously dubious girlfriend
(Hope Davis) stumbles onto a few clues and turns into a regular
Nancy Drew. With only-in-the-movies timing, as soon as she utters
what she knows or whenever Michael stares at his evidence, up pop
Oliver or Cheryl.
</P>
<P>
   Michael starts canceling classes to play sleuth, shuttling
across country to quiz tenuous witnesses, before chasing a van-full
of explosives through downtown Washington with all the skill of a
demolition derby driver. And in a particularly excessive scene, he
crashes a party Oliver is throwing for his right-wing wacko
brigade, garishly photographed as if they were a coven of witches
and warlocks.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Pellington is right and today's mass audience has no
interest in a merely eerie thriller of ideas, preferring action
bombast. Give me Alan Pakula's ``The Parallax View'' (1974), a very
similar movie, but one which has the courage of its own
intelligence. When ``Arlington Road'' forgets the head and goes for
the gut, it loses its edge and settles for being aggravatingly
ordinary. But, ah, that first hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``ARLINGTON ROAD''
</P>
<P>
   2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Rated R: Violence, language
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 55 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Intriguing tale of urban paranoia which gets
squandered in its second half as it turns obvious and ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
