u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHARMACY-BENEFITS-NYT     07-08 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHARMACY-BENEFITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PLOY, REPUBLICANS SET DEBATE ON DEMOCRATIC PATIENTS' BILL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., S.D., Okla.)   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an odd bit of political jujitsu, Senate
Republican leaders said Thursday that they would use a Democratic
bill as the main vehicle for four days of debate next week on the
rights of patients buffeted by turmoil in the health care industry.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was introduced in January by the Senate Democratic
leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts, whose proposals are normally anathema to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the assistant Republican
leader, announced Thursday that Republicans would call up the
Daschle-Kennedy bill as the first order of business when the
four-day debate begins on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal will be ``the underlying bill for the
purpose of next week's health care debate,'' Nickles said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans apparently hope that this tactic will enable them to
spend hours attacking the Democratic bill, rather than defending
their own bill.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, before the debate ends on Thursday, Republicans
said, they intend to replace the Democratic bill with the
Republican version.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the ploy does not indicate that Republicans like the
Democratic bill. Rather, it may suggest the lengths to which
Republicans will go to avoid being on what they fear is the
``wrong'' side of a popular consumer protection issue that
Democrats will exploit in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Ranit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Daschle, said, ``The
Republicans don't really want to have an honest debate on the
patients' bill of rights.'' She said the Democrats would still try
to arrange for votes on amendments that would highlight the
differences between the two parties on specific issues.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Manley, a spokesman for Kennedy, said, ``The Republican
leadership is desperate to prevent members from taking tough votes
on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The two bills have the same title, the Patients' Bill of Rights
Act, and appear to have similar objectives, establishing minimum
federal standards for health maintenance organizations and health
insurance companies. But the bills differ in many important
respects, and some Republicans say they worry that their votes
against Democratic proposals could be misconstrued by their
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill appears, for example, to provide more
protections for more people, and would make it easier for patients
to sue if they were injured as a result of a health plan's
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the Democratic bill would ultimately increase
the number of uninsured because it would increase the costs of
health insurance by imposing dozens of new federal mandates and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Nickles asserted that the Democratic bill ``sharply increases
costs, puts lawyers and bureaucrats in the treatment room and
forces millions more Americans out of their health care coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The starting point for the debate is significant, Nickles said.
``But it's where we end up that really counts,'' he added. ``At the
end of next week, the Senate will have passed a bill that protects
patients and doctors, enhances health care quality and dramatically
increases access to health care coverage for uninsured Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say their bill is more explicit in guaranteeing
patients access to emergency care, medical specialists,
prescription drugs and clinical trials testing experimental
treatments. Democrats also contend that their bill is better for
patients because it gives doctors, rather than health plans, the
authority to decide what services are ``medically necessary'' and
gives patients a greater opportunity to appeal decisions denying
care.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association urged patients to join doctors
in lobbying Congress for strong patient protections. Dr. Nancy W.
Dickey, former president of the association, said doctors should
have the ``final say about what is medically necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
