<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, July 9. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALS-1 (Phoenix) - The hard part about having a fatal disease in
1999 is that the promises of miracle cures, genetic antidotes and
biococktails twinkle all around like lights of distant rescue ships
_ too far off to be of assistance. ``It's very maddening,'' said
Kevin Spicer, afflicted with Lou Gehrig's disease, or ALS. Though
the disease has no cure, many of its victims do not sit and wait.
</P>
<P>
   They explore, looking for something that works, something that
will extend their time and give them a fighting chance. With PHOTO
and sidebars ALS-1 and ALS-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By MAUREEN WEST. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALS-2 (Phoenix) - Wendy L. Marshall's sister, Rorie Susan Buchanan,
died in the middle of the afternoon on Oct. 14, 1997, of
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) _ also known as Lou Gehrig's
disease. After all she'd been through, she just wanted to die
peacefully, life leaving her gracefully like a dancer gliding
across a ballroom floor. That image gave her comfort. She loved to
dance. With PHOTOS. By WENDY L. MARSHALL. Story moved in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALS-3 (Undated) - Now, after all the people have left, all the
thank-you cards have been signed, all the friends have expressed
their sympathy, and the ashes are at home awaiting the journey to
Hawaii, I can sit down and tell our story. Maybe it will be of help
to someone.
</P>
<P>
   Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis: What a name for a diagnosis that
dooms the tient to death. No cure, no real government research
support, no FDA support of drugs that can ease the burden, no
insurance company understanding of the need for coverage, and no
real time frame other than an average life expectancy of three to
five years after diagnosis. By MICHAEL G. MARSHALL. Special for the
Arizona Republic. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
