<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN CENTRAL AFRICA, A CEASE-FIRE AMID WIDESPREAD
DISTRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ If the opponents in Congo's 11-month war
sign their planned cease-fire agreement, they will be trying to
bring closure to the single event that has destabilized all of
Central Africa: the genocide in Rwanda. It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire plan _ which the heads of six governments and two
rebel movements agreed to Wednesday and which they could sign this
weekend _ calls for the disarmament of the Hutu militia that is
responsible for much of the 1994 genocide that killed a
half-million of Rwanda's Tutsi minority.
</P>
<P>
   Disarming this militia is the most difficult task outlined in
the cease-fire plan. And its failure would make lasting peace
impossible, officials involved in the negotiations concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Rwanda is concerned, the most interesting aspect of
the agreement is that the countries involved have committed to
disarm and fight the ... genocidal forces, and that was our
objective,'' Rwanda President Pasteur Bizimungu said Thursday at a
news conference in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that all countries involved have pledged to neutralize
them, then we have no other reason to fight,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The militia and other rebel movements have been hiding in Congo
and using the country as a launching pad to attack governments in
neighboring countries. The militia is believed to consist of the
most hard-core opponents of Rwanda's Tutsi government, which has
otherwise repatriated and reintegrated many Hutu soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   It was partly to deal with the militia that the Tutsi-led
government of Rwanda and its close ally, Uganda, plucked Laurent
Kabila out of obscurity and helped him two years ago to topple
Mobutu Sese Seko, under whose dictatorship the Congo, then called
Zaire, had become a huge shell of a nation in the heart of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But after a while Rwanda and Uganda began to believe that Kabila
was unwilling to settle their security concerns, and they backed
another rebellion, this time against him.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more complicated, Kabila and his allies
eventually drew the battle-hardened militia known as the
Interahamwe to their side to fight the Rwanda-backed rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were recruited by Kabila to fight, to recover their
strength and to launch another campaign against Rwanda,'' said a
diplomat involved in the negotiations, held in Zambia's capital,
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having lost the support of Kabila, the militia either has
to disarm or defend itself. But disarming may not be attractive to
the militia, because many of its members may be ineligible for
amnesty, leaving them little choice but to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they have nothing to lose,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the cease-fire plan, a joint military commission made up
of the warring parties will begin disarming and putting into effect
other aspects of the agreement, until a peacekeeping force takes
over, either from the Organization of African Unity or the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, while the plan will grant a widespread amnesty, it
excludes those suspected of genocide, a category under which many
Interahamwe will presumably fall.
</P>
<P>
   How to disarm the Interahamwe, whose numbers are estimated to be
from 15,000 to as many as 50,000, is yet to be worked out. And the
process will take place in a country where troops from five
governments are still present, along with fighters from two main
rebel movements and countless smaller factions.
</P>
<P>
   They are full of mistrust. For instance, the secretary general
of one of the main rebel groups, Olivier Kamitatu of the Movement
for the Liberation of the Congo, said in an interview from Lusaka,
``We couldn't put this in the cease-fire agreement, but we have
said that we will consider any attack against us by the Interahamwe
after the cease-fire takes effect to be an attack by Kabila.'' His
group controls much of northern Congo. At the moment, Uganda and
Rwanda are backing the rebel movements, but Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia are supporting Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, all foreign forces will have 180
days to leave Congo.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also sets out an ambitious timetable for the government
and various military and political parties inside the Congo to work
toward a national reconciliation. Within 45 days of the signing of
the cease-fire, the Kabila government, the two rebel movements and
the various political opposition parties are to find a location and
a facilitator for a national debate on the future of the Congo.
Then the debate, consisting perhaps of government officials and
rebels meeting for talks, must be held within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila had softened his position on a national debate in recent
months; still, agreeing to it marked a sharp departure from his
original position. When he came to power two years ago, Kabila, a
rebel who had lived in the bush for decades and had few political
skills, shunned the parties that formed Mobutu's political
opposition and lost many opportunities to build a political base.
</P>
<P>
   For many months after the war started last August, Kabila
rejected any negotiations or meetings with the rebel groups,
arguing that they were puppets of Rwanda and Uganda. In recent
months, though, the war and the deteriorating economy caused
Kabila's popularity to plummet in the capital and pushed him to
open the door toward the internal opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire plan also includes a provision stating that all
ethnic groups enjoy equal status in the Congo, an item clearly
intended to protect Congo's Tutsi minority.
</P>
<P>
   Tutsi, who have been in the Congo for generations, have long
been the targets of other eastern Congolese groups that contested
their right to own land or become citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these Tutsi took part in the rebellion that overthrew
Mobutu, and belong to the current revolt against Kabila. When
rebels forces almost seized Kinshasa last August, the Kabila
government relied heavily on propaganda against the Tutsi to rally
the population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
