<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3637 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAR-FLIGHT-SPI &LR;      07-08 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAR-FLIGHT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE EMBARKS ON EMERGENCY AID FLIGHT TO SOUTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCHORD AFB, Wash. _ A hand-picked crew of 22 aviators and
support personnel scrambled on an emergency flight to the South
Pole Thursday to air-drop medical supplies to a civilian scientist
who has been diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10 a.m. takeoff, the McChord-based C-141 mission,
commanded by Col. John Pray, rendezvoused with an Air Force KC-10
aerial tanker enroute to Hickam Air Force Base in Hawaii before
making the second leg of the flight to Christchurch, New Zealand,
said Col. Ray Johns, commander of the 62nd Airlift Wing. The
one-way trek from McChord to the South Pole is 9,200 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things with which we're most proud is the
flexibility we have to respond to a national need,'' said Johns,
who commands a fleet of 41 C-141B Starlifter aircraft and about
5,000 military and civilian personnel at the Pierce County air
base.
</P>
<P>
   Barring weather delays, the air-drop mission will take place
Sunday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis began three weeks ago when the scientist, a
47-year-old woman, was diagnosed by a physician at the
Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station as having a cancerous lump on one
breast. After a review of her condition by the local physician and
medical experts consulted by the National Science Foundation, the
decision was made to request Air Mobility Command help in
delivering the necessary supplies by parachute air-drop, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies include additional medical diagnostic material, medical
supplies and additional communications gear.
</P>
<P>
   Science foundation officials declined the release the name of
the scientist, citing her right to privacy. Requests to interview
officials at the polar station by telephone or e-mail were declined
because the station has limited communications links to the outside
world, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Johns said the mission team began preparations for the operation
immediately after the science foundation request came to McChord
last Friday, including a practice cargo air-drop flight and a
rehearsal mission in a C-141B flight simulator in which the pilot
used night-vision goggles to improve his ability to locate the drop
zone.
</P>
<P>
   All 15 aircrewmen on the flight have experience in Antarctic
missions, Johns said. McChord in recent years has drawn the bulk of
the Antarctic supply missions but none had been scheduled this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is for the C-141B to fly from Christchurch, New
Zealand, nonstop to the polar station escorted by the KC-10 tanker.
Once overhead, cargo loadmasters in the C-141B will open the two
paratrooper doors at the rear of the aircraft and push out six
cargo bundles that will float to the ground on parachutes. Each
bundle will have about 600 pounds of material, Johns said. The
flight will require several in-flight refuelings from the KC-10
tanker plane.
</P>
<P>
   Time and accuracy over the drop zone will be critical, the wing
commander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to get to those supplies within five minutes (of
hitting the ground) or they will be damaged and no longer useful,''
Johns said. Liquid medical supplies in particular will freeze
despite thick insulation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are 41 civilian personnel at the polar station, which is
cut off from the outside world between February and October each
year because of the severe weather conditions, particularly
temperatures that average 80 degrees below zero and which can be as
low as 150 degrees below zero at the aircraft flight altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Only during the warmest four months of the Antarctic summer,
from November until late February, smaller aircraft such as C-130s
using skis mounted on their landing gear can fly the 800-mile trip
from the main U.S. base at McMurdo Sound and safely land on an ice
airstrip at the pole, Johns said.
</P>
<P>
   A science foundation spokeswoman, Mary Hanson agreed there was
no alternative but to ask the Air Force for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never landed an aiplane there in the winter,'' Hanson
said. ``It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Mahar, safety and health officer for the science
foundation's Office of Polar Programs, said the organization will
reimburse the Air Force for the cost of the medical supply mission,
which other officials said would run in the hundreds of thousands
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the present time we're not concerned about the costs,''
Mahar said yesterday. ``We're concerned about the health and
welfare of the individual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
