<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HN     07-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
There has been no urge to pick up the phone to make even the
slightest suggestion. And with the exception of a cameo appearance,
the locks to the Astrodome doors haven't needed to be changed to
keep him out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball has taken a back seat for Larry Dierker in the last
four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the busiest parts of the season, there have been
no long road trips for the Astros' third-year manager. He hasn't
thought about strategy _ hitter-pitcher matchups or who is going to
bat cleanup _ and game involvement has been reduced to watching on
television and reading the morning newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't rested during a summer all my life,'' Dierker said
Thursday afternoon. ``I might as well take advantage of it and look
at the positive side.''
</P>
<P>
   When something has been done for more than three decades, the
routine is hard to break. But Dierker, 52, had no choice after he
collapsed in the dugout during the Astros' June 13 game with the
San Diego Padres after being stricken by a grand mal seizure.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he underwent brain surgery to remove a
life-threatening mass of malformed blood vessels. Eight days later,
he amazingly checked out of the hospital and headed home for rest
and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been counting down the days until his return, but he
quickly points out his scheduled date to rejoin the Astros is July
15 _ one month and two days after he was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   If possible, normalcy has returned to Dierker's life. His
physical condition isn't what it once was, the result of a
doctor-advised limited workout schedule. He isn't allowed to drive.
A scar across the top of his head is an all-too-vivid reminder of
the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some things, however, haven't changed. He still has an appetite,
and there have been times he has managed to sneak out for a round
of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``My appetite is the same; I just can't work out hard,'' said
Dierker, who has been spending his time devouring ice cream.
``Maybe I shouldn't be eating as much.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returns to his post, Dierker will find the National
League Central race much closer than it was when he left. He'll
also find wounded players returning and three new All-Stars on his
pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros held a four-game division lead at the time Dierker
was forced to take a leave of absence. Entering Thursday night's
game, the Astros were 10-13 under interim manager Matt Galante.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy to watch. I stay in touch, but I'm not
trying to be that involved. I've been trying to stay away,''
Dierker said. ``I'm not trying to be that involved _ why not hit
this guy fifth or pitch this guy in the seventh? They're doing
their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   While the results might not be what is expected from the
two-time defending NL Central champions, Dierker believes the
Astros haven't come close to reaching their peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I picked a good time to be out,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   A roster once injury-filled is beginning to show signs of
health, with reliever Doug Henry due back next week and third
baseman Ken Caminiti likely to return before the end of the month.
The Astros also could get a big lift with the expected return of
left fielder Moises Alou in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in a good position in regard to the standings
and injuries,'' Dierker said. ``I still think we are going to win
our division. I think we can only get better in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he is especially proud of the Astros' four All-Star
selections _ first baseman Jeff Bagwell and pitchers Jose Lima,
Mike Hampton and Billy Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, a two-time All-Star in his playing days, said he can
appreciate the difficulty in getting three members of one staff
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough to do. Probably with the number of teams there
are, you would get one per team at the most. We got three pitchers.
That's pretty good,'' he said. ``I am disappointed (second baseman
Craig) Biggio didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week at this time, Dierker will be back in the dugout, back
wearing the uniform that has hung in his honor since he left. And
before the Astros even play a game in the second half, they can
chalk up one of their biggest wins of the season with his return.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he knows he can't stay home forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my wife (Judy) is getting tired of having me around
the house,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
