<P>
   &UR; UNION _  &LR; Union Bank of California, the largest
Japanese-controlled bank in the U.S., is about to go through a
wrenching, American-style reorganization that is expected to cost
more than 1,000 jobs, or about one position in seven. The
initiative, dubbed Mission Excel, is in the final planning stages
and will go to top executives and the bank's board for approval
later this month. The bank expects to announce details to employees
and the public in August, and then put the program into effect over
the next 21 months. BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORKWAYS _  &LR; Workplace column. BY ILANA DEBARE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROCHE _  &LR; Roche Holding AG, Europe's fourth-biggest drugmaker,
said it plans to sell about 17 percent of Genentech Inc., a U.S.
biotechnology company, to the public at between $85 and $95 a
share. Using that range, the sale of about 22 million shares should
raise between $1.87 billion and $2.09 billion for the Swiss
drugmaker. BY TOM ABATE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAFEWAY _  &LR; Safeway Inc. reported net income of $236.4 million
($0.46 per share) for the second quarter ended June 19, 1999,
compared to $193.2 million ($0.38 per share) for the second quarter
of 1998, an increase of 22%. Second quarter sales increased 13.5%
to $6.3 billion in 1999 from $5.6 billion in 1998, primarily
because of the Dominick's acquisition. BY CAROL EMERT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHILDREN'S _  &LR; The latest magical adventures of Harry Potter _ a
young boy destined to be the wizard of all wizards _ is a
best-seller before it even hits the bookstores in London, eagerly
awaited by hordes of young readers and adults alike. Not everyone
is cheering, though: American readers can buy the third book online
from British bookstores, much to the dismay of American book
publishers. BY DAVID LAZARUS
</P>
