<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-ATLANTARECORDS09-     07-08 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTARECORDS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olympic records dispute in hands of Fulton judge
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The battle over public access to Olympic records went
before a Fulton County judge Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing a full day of arguments, Superior Court Judge
Bensonetta Tipton Lane said she hopes to decide soon whether the
state's Open Records Act applies to the Georgia Amateur Athletics
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation _ formed by Billy Payne in 1987 to bid for the
1996 Centennial Olympic Games _ sued The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution last month to have the bid records declared
private and immune from the state's records law. The newspaper and
Attorney General Thurbert Baker then filed a countersuit to open
the foundation's records. The newspaper's attorney, Peter Canfield,
said the Open Records Act applies because the foundation prepared
the bids for and lobbied on behalf of the city and state, which
were awarded the Games. Atlanta and Fulton County gave $250,000
each during the bid.
</P>
<P>
   The same group of people then staged the Games as the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games, he said. The foundation now has
ACOG's files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically every single person's life in Atlanta was
affected'' by the Olympics, said Deputy Attorney General Dennis R.
Dunn. ``This was an overwhelmingly public event.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne last week pledged to make public all the records except
the contents of eight boxes that he says include personal letters
and memos. Payne said, though, that a congressional committee could
have ``unfettered access'' to them.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Bankoff, the foundation's attorney, said the Open Records
Act does not apply to the foundation because it was never
officially delegated any governmental responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The case is ``about the future of public-private
collaborations'' like the one that brought the Games to Atlanta,
Bankoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Payne and former Mayor Andrew Young testified that Payne brought
the idea of pursuing the Games to Young, who wanted to be
supportive but without opening the city to any financial liability.
</P>
<P>
   Young said he does not know what is in the boxes. But some
donors wanted to maintain their privacy, he said, as did people who
provided information about members of the International Olympic
Committee who would vote to choose a host city.
</P>
<P>
   If Lane decides the foundation's records are public, it can
still seek to keep the eight boxes private by claiming one of the
Open Records Act's exemptions. Canfield said Lane then would need
to come up with a process for deciding whether the exemptions
apply.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
