<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NDC-MEDSCAPE09-COX     07-08 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NDC-MEDSCAPE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National Data invests in Web
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ National Data Corp. said Thursday it will invest $20
million in hopes of making Medscape.com the leading health care
site on the Internet, a hotly contested title of late.
</P>
<P>
   National Data's investment will give the Atlanta-based
information and networking company about a 5 percent stake in
Medscape.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, CBS said it bought a 35 percent
stake in Medscape in return for $150 million of advertising and
on-air promotions that will be carried by CBS properties, including
radio, television, the Internet and billboards. A revamped Web
site, CBS.medscape.com, is expected to be ready by late summer.
</P>
<P>
   In May, New York-based Medscape filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission for an initial public offering of its stock
under the symbol MSCP.
</P>
<P>
   The Medscape deal gives National Data access to Medscape's
registered users as well as the Medscape.com Web site, said Bob
Yellowlees, National Data chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of May, about 1.1 million people had registered at
Medscape.com. Of those, more than 200,000 were physicians, 550,000
worked in other health care professions and 380,000 were registered
as consumers.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of Medscape's registered users visit the site
regularly, said Paul Sheils, Medscape president and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   National Data has about $450 million in revenue from its health
care information technology. That division's products include the
electronic processing of drug prescriptions, including verifying a
patient's eligibility, determining how much will be reimbursed,
making sure the drug does not conflict with other drugs and sending
the claim to the insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as WebMD, are hoping to make the Internet
the place where such health-care-related transactions are
processed. WebMD, based in Atlanta at Perimeter Center, has had a
high profile lately, signing deals with CNN and Microsoft. WebMD
also filed for a initial public offering, then withdrew the
request. It merged with Healtheon in May and has agreed to acquire
Atlanta-based Medcast.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in April 1996, Medscape was the grandfather of online
health care content sites geared to physicians but is making a move
toward the consumer market, said Stephen D. Savas, an analyst with
Goldman Sachs. The CBS deal with help Medscape become more of a
household name, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as Claims.net, IDX, AccentHealth and
Atlanta-based Third Millennium, are competing to be the site to
handle doctors' ``back office'' business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   But Yellowlees said processing insurance claims is more complex
than just moving a transaction over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians need to be able to make sure patients are eligible
for insurance coverage and that the form in which the claims are
transmitted is legible to the insurance company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply dumping information on a payer's doorstep does not get
you paid,'' Yellowlees said. ``We are already doing a lot of this;
the Web presence just gives customers another way to access it. We
are doing more than anyone in more segments of health care and more
from an Internet point of view than anyone in that space.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
