<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez reports improvement
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More good news for the Braves from Javy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   He caught for the first time in batting practice on Thursday
afternoon, catching Tom Glavine for 15 minutes in the Braves
bullpen, and said afterward the knee responded well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised,'' Lopez said. ``I thought I'd feel some kind of
pain when I squat down, block pitches, go side-to-side, but I
don't. With this brace, I'm able to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said he thinks he cleared the last hurdle to being able to
say with confidence he'll be ready to return after the All-Star
break when the Braves play the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is it,'' Lopez said. ``I don't think I have to do
anything else to be ready for a game. ... Now I just need a couple
days to see how it wakes up (reacts).''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez plans to continue catching in the bullpen each day as he
tries to get used to wearing the bulky brace on his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might be a little up,'' Lopez said of his position behind
home plate. ``The target is going to be a little high. I don't know
how difficult it will be to block pitches because I'm high already.
I probably won't be as quick as I was.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves, who need his bat back in the lineup, can live
with that.
</P>
<P>
   Jones on a roll at the plate
</P>
<P>
   This late offensive surge heading into the All-Star break is
making Chipper Jones' first-half come together nicely. This after
going through a June in which he hit only one homer and struggled
from the left side of the plate. But after Monday's game he hit the
.300 mark for the first time since April 23 and was hitting .304 to
go along with 19 home runs and 52 RBI entering Thursday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   That includes a seven-game hitting streak in which he hit
10-for-21 (.476). He'd had five home runs in six games after going
21 games without one.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be lost in those numbers is his walk total. In 31 at-bats
in those seven games, Jones drew 10 walks to bring his team-leading
total to 61. That may be the most important number of all because
instead of that weak groundout on the infield, Jones has been
standing at first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the difference,'' Jones said. ``Early in the
season I was swinging at bad pitches, getting myself out. I'm being
patient and when they're coming over the plate, I'm not missing
them. It's easier said than done. There are pitches on the corner
of the plate you think you can hit, even six inches outside you
think you can send to left. It's a matter of being able to
recognize the pitches you can do something with as opposed to the
pitches you can't. I'm dictating the at-bats, not letting the
pitcher do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty locked in,'' hitting coach Don Baylor said. ``If
you're looking for a third baseman to go to the All-Star Game (as a
replacement), I know where you can find one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
