<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-THE-JOB-GENDER-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO THE CLUB, FINALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., Fla., Va.)   (For release Sun., July 11)  
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time, as the saying went, it was a man's world. But
times and customs change. The transition has not always been
without conflicts, perils and abrasions, but the mail shows that
the change has clearly been for the better.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president for human resources of a major corporation,
Ronald J. Rakowski of Bethel, Conn., was responsible for insuring
that the company complied with employment laws and that the staff
understood its commitment to equal employment opportunity and
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't always easy,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the time a division sales vice president burst into his
office to demand help in replacing a vital sales executive who had
just quit. ``And Ron, please don't send me any `girls,''' the
executive added. ``I know you think I'm a Neanderthal when it comes
to human resources, but humor me on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Rakowski reminded him of the law and, still steaming, turned the
recruiting assignment over to one of his best human-resources
representatives, who, in keeping with company practice, narrowed
the search to the five best candidates and compiled a report on
each. ``As luck would have it, the rep reported our best candidate
was Christina,'' Rakowski said.
</P>
<P>
   But he knew that if the executive was forced to hire Christina,
he would doubtlessly make her life miserable.
</P>
<P>
   Just before setting up a dinner with the executive to review the
candidates, Rakowski got an idea. He told his aide to change
Christina's name to Christopher in the paperwork and, contrary to
the company's normal practice of introducing the report on the best
candidate last, to move ``Chris'' into the first spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``After coffee and desert, the V.P. leaned back and told me that
we'd made a big mistake,'' Rakowski said. ``He thought `Chris' was
by far the best candidate and was anxious to interview `him.' Then
I told the V.P. what I had done. After a few `expletives deleted,'
he shook his head, chuckled and admitted that he had been had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve months later, `Chris' won the division's Salesman of
the Year Award.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales &UR; man &LR; ? ``Oh, well,'' Rakowski writes. ``Some things you
change and some things you can't.''
</P>
<P>
   As vice president for training and development of a large
financial services corporation, Lynn Brailsford of Teaneck, N.J.,
traveled internationally three or four times a year. But she
observed that her male counterparts would get better treatment,
more perks and larger rooms at hotels. Typically, they received
newly refurbished suites while she got closet-sized quarters.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to act. Her first thought was to have her assistant
book all her flights and rooms for ``Mr.'' But that was likely to
succeed only until she made an appearance. So her aide began to
tell airlines and hotels unequivocally that Ms. Brailsford was a
very important female executive. ``Suddenly there was eye contact
upon check-in,'' she writes. ``My hotel rooms were nicer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final satisfaction came while traveling to London with my
boss. We checked in together, and I alone was handed an envelope
with gold embossed lettering. The envelope, addressed to the `Lady
Executive,' contained a description of all the perks and services
available to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to be outperked, my boss leaned over and asked, `Hey, what
did you get?' I replied, `Oh, nothing more than a list of the perks
you get automatically. The difference is, I had to ask for it!''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, just hired as executive producer in the news
department of a television station in Orlando, Fla., Bette
BonFleur, now of Charlottesville, Va., was passing the news
director's office when she heard him telling a colleague in another
city about his new hire: ``I just hired an executive producer,'' he
said. ``And it's a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. BonFleur waited until he was off the phone, then walked in
and told him he sounded as if he were talking about a newborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got the point, and I'm happy to say he has gone on to be
one of the best supporters of women in the workplace,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it be because he and his wife actually did have a baby
girl a short time after?
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, I know it was because he was exposed to strong,
outspoken women and was man enough to recognize it and grow with
the times. He and I have laughed about the scene a hundred times
over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
