<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thumbs up to Ricky Rudd
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thumbs up to Ricky Rudd, who started on the outside of
the front row in last week's Pepsi 400 at Daytona International
Speedway. Rudd's qualifying effort came only one day after Procter
&AMP; Gamble announced that it wouldn't renew its sponsorship with
Rudd's No. 10 Ford. Rudd, one of the few single-car owners left in
the Winston Cup circuit, handling the embarassing situation with
class and dignity, said he hated to see his nine-year relationship
with Tide come to an end. Rudd then went out and proved with his
qualifying run that Procter &AMP; Gamble might be making a mistake.
Rudd finished a season-best 13th in the race.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Cal Wells, the California-based CART owner who plans to make
a move into NASCAR next season. Wells, who owns Precision
Preparation Inc., doesn't have a driver or crew chief yet, but he
already has managed to swipe two of NASCAR's biggest sponsors. And
he lured them away from two of NASCAR's old-timers. In May,
McDonald's said it will sponsor Wells' Busch Grand National team
next year. In 2001, McDonald's is expected to end its longtime
relationship with Bill Elliott and move its Golden Arches to Wells'
Winston Cup car. Last week, Procter &AMP; Gamble said it is negotiating
with Wells to sponsor a Winston Cup team next season. What will
Wells do next? Kick Richard Petty in the stomach?
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S HOT?
</P>
<P>
   M&AMP;M's debuted its new crispy candies paint scheme in last week's
Pepsi 400, and, surprisingly, driver Ernie Irvan didn't crunch his
No. 36 Pontiac. Irvan has taken his share of criticism this year,
but he actually made up some ground in the last month. Since a
35th-place outing at Dover on June 6 dropped him to 31st in points,
Irvan has had three top-10 finishes in the last four races. He
finished ninth at Daytona, after starting 32nd. Irvan was seventh
at Michigan on June 13, then finished eighth at Pocono and 30th at
Sears Point. He has climbed nine spots to No. 22 in points during
that streak, trailing 15th-place Ken Schrader by only 250.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S NOT?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe professional wrestler Bill Goldberg should stay away from
other sporting events. Two years ago, he gave the University of
Georgia football team a pep talk in Jacksonville, and the Dogs got
waxed by archrival Florida. Last weekend, Goldberg's face was on
the hood of Jerry Nadeau's No. 9 Ford, and Nadeau finished 37th.
There's probably not a Goldberg hex or anything, though. Nadeau was
slumping long before his paint scheme included Goldberg's bald
head. Nadeau hasn't finished higher than 20th in his last eight
starts, and his average finish in the last five was 30th. In the
last four events, he's fallen from 27th to 32nd in points.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   2: The number of Winston Cup points championships won by drivers
of Ford race cars in the modern era (1972-present). They were
Elliott in 1988 and the late Alan Kulwicki in 1992. Jarrett has
positioned himself to become the third with a 177-point lead at the
midway point in the season. ``I think it's surprising,'' Jarrett
said. ``It's surprising that it hasn't happened more with all of
the good Ford teams we've had over the years. Hopefully, that's
something that's gonna change this year.''
</P>
<P>
   TONY THE TIGER
</P>
<P>
   A big reason for Pontiac's resurgence this season is rookie Tony
Stewart. After 17 races, Stewart has four top-five and nine top-10
finishes, ranks sixth in the point standings and has no DNFs. At
the same point in his rookie season in 1993, Jeff Gordon had five
top-five and eight top-10 finishes, as well as five DNFs. Gordon
didn't win in his first Winston Cup season, and neither has
Stewart. ``I don't know _ if it happens it happens, and if it
doesn't it doesn't,'' Stewart said. ``I've got my own goals I set
each week, and that's what I'm focusing on. I hear the same things
you're probably hearing, too, but who knows what is going to
happen? If I knew what the future was, I'd probably be doing
something other than driving race cars, because I'd be making a lot
of money if I could predict what was in my future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
