<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin undergoes surgery
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup driver Mark Martin, who underwent surgery Wednesday
to repair a broken tibia plateau in his left knee, isn't expected
to miss any time behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, third in points and 234 behind leader Dale Jarrett, was
hurt in an accident during practice at Daytona International
Speedway on July 2. The fracture was identified during an MRI exam
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Chuck Kollmer performed arthroscopic surgery in New Smyrna
Beach, Fla., inserting a screw to hold the tibia in place. Martin,
40, will continue to wear a leg brace, which will allow him to
drive in Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300at New Hampshire International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Kollmer assured me that I will be able to drive this
weekend,'' Martin said. ``I'll go back to see him Monday after the
race to evaluate how long I should wear the brace. Once I get this
taken care of I should be much better since my wrist and ribs are
already feeling better.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, perhaps NASCAR's most well-conditioned driver, wore a
hard cast on his left wrist in last week's Pepsi 400. He completed
all 160 laps, despite telling his crew early in the race that they
were ``dealing with a one-armed driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch Grand National driver Matt Kenseth, who is expected to
drive a Cup car owned by Martin next year, will be standing by if
Martin needs to come out of his No. 6 Ford on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling a fast one
</P>
<P>
   Scott Eggleston, crew chief for Sterling Marlin's No. 40 Chevy,
was not surprised by the $50,000 fine levied by NASCAR for rules
violations found before last week's race. Eggleston also was placed
on probation until Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   In pre-race inspection on Saturday, NASCAR officials found an
illegal insert in the intake manifold on Marlin's engine. The
inserts are not allowed on Winston Cup cars at Daytona and
Talladega, where NASCAR requires restrictor plates to slow speeds
on the superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   Eggleston removed the insert before the Pepsi 400, so Marlin's
12th-place finish stands. The explanation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you try to get some things by,'' Marlin said.
``Everybody tries it. You're going to try something. . . . We'll
just have to take our lumps and go on. They've got `em before, and
they'll catch `em later on. ``You just try to get a little
advantage. Sometimes you get by, and sometimes you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH
</P>
<P>
   Krogh remains critical after crash
</P>
<P>
   Busch Grand National driver Jeff Krogh of Kamiah, Idaho, remains
in critical but stable condition at Froedtert Memorial Lutheran
Hospital in Milwaukee after suffering injuries in a wreck during
the final practice before last week's DieHard 250 at the Milwaukee
Mile.
</P>
<P>
   Krogh remains unconscious, but doctors reported no visible signs
of trauma or fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Krogh, 27, crashed his No. 56 Chevy in turn 1 of the one-mile
fairgrounds oval midway through Saturday's practice. It was his
second accident of the day, after he also crashed on the second lap
of his qualifying attempt. Krogh, 33rd in driver points, made the
field using a car owner's provisional. Krogh's parents, Molly and
Bob, and his brother Mark, 24, a third-year Busch driver, were at
the track in West Allis, Wis. His wife, Karla, was flown to
Wisconsin from North Carolina after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   AllCar set to return
</P>
<P>
   AllCar Motorsports, which fields the No. 22 Chevy on the Busch
circuit, remains on target to return at Michigan Speedway in
August.
</P>
<P>
   AllCar, which has former driver Bobby Allison as a consultant,
will test at Michigan the first week of August with at least two,
and perhaps, three cars, owner Dave Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grissom, the Winston Cup driver who has been assisting the
team the past two months, will drive during the team's test.
</P>
<P>
   ``This break is something we needed to get everything in
order,'' Carroll said. ``It has given us a chance to catch our
breaths and to get our cars and our shop the way it needs to be. We
gaveourselves a pretty tough timetable at the beginning, forming
the team in December and then racing in February. This break is
helping us overcome that and get everything right.''Alabama
short-track specialist Jimmy Kitchens opened the season as AllCar's
driver, but he was replaced after only six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
