<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SADLER09-COX     07-08 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SADLER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sadler's up and running
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ NASCAR driver Elliott Sadler hasn't shown much
consistency in his first season on the Winston Cup circuit, but the
rookie has shown vast improvement in one important area _ avoiding
wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, 24, of Emporia, Va., didn't finish his first two races
in the No. 21 Ford of Wood Brothers Racing. In the season-opening
Daytona 500 on Feb. 14, Sadler completed only 132 of 200 laps
before wrecking and finishing 40th. The following week at
Rockingham, N.C., he ran only 361 of 393 laps and finished 38th.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking those two cars back to Virginia in pieces, however,
Sadler has managed to be running at the end of the 15 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty hard,'' Sadler said. ``These veterans are
pretty good. Every race track we go to, you've got to go loaded for
bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler had two full seasons on the Busch Grand National circuit
before jumping to Winston Cup this year. Last season, he finished
eighth in points, with two victories and 10 top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tony Stewart, who had nine fewer Busch starts last
year because of his Indy Racing League commitments, was 22nd in
points and didn't win a race.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, Stewart is the biggest surprise in Winston
Cup, with four top-fives and nine top-10s at the midway point of
the season. Sadler is 31st in points and has only one top-10 in 17
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably had the better end of the deal, in all honesty,
compared to the other rookies this season,'' Stewart said. ``I've
stepped into an established team that finished in the top 10 in
points the last two years. I have a teammate (Bobby Labonte) to
reflect off of, and (rookies Buckshot Jones and Sadler) don't have
a teammate to go to during practice and say, `My car feels like
this or that. Does your car do the same thing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler stepped into a struggling team _ the famed Wood Brothers
of Stuart, Va., who have won 96 races since 1960, but none in the
past six seasons. Morgan Sheppard was the last driver to win in a
car owned by the Wood Brothers, in Atlanta in March 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Wood Brothers, who parted ways with driver Michael Waltrip
last year after three seasons, haven't won in their last 200
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've thrown a lot of new things at the Wood Brothers this
year, with a new crew chief coming in, a new driver and a new
engineer,'' Sadler said. ``We had to go through those learning
stages at the beginning of the year, but we feel like were getting
things settled down now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's most consistent run this season has come during the
last month. In the last three races, he hasn't finished lower than
22nd. Since a 29th-place finish in the DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway on April 25, he climbed from 38th to 31st in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team has really come around,'' he said. ``We got ourselves
in a lot of trouble at the beginning of the year, getting in wrecks
and getting in situations we didn't need to be in. The last six
races, we've accumulated a total of points that would be 20th over
that stretch, so we feel like we're making improvements and going
in the right direction. We're learning each and every week, and I'm
feeling more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler faces a tough four-race stretch, beginning with Sunday's
Jiffy Lube 300. In the next four events, he'll have to race at New
Hampshire, Indianapolis and Watkins Glen, N.Y., tracks he hasn't
driven this season. The other stop is Pocono Raceway in Long Pond,
Pa., where he needed a provisional to make the field for the Pocono
500 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the tracks we've been to are tracks I've never seen
before, and we've struggled a little bit,'' Sadler said. ``But we
knew we were going to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 11 of the last 13 races this year, however, Sadler will
return to tracks for a second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe then, we'll race a little harder and go a little more in
the right direction and maybe be a little more aggressive on our
setups on the car,'' he said. ``Then I think you're gonna start
seeing us better each and every week. These guys are the best of
the best, but we feel like we're gonna have something for 'em
before this season is over with.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
