<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERROR-PANEL-ART-NYT &LR;      07-08 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-PANEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOICE OF MUSLIM FOR TERRORISM PANEL IN JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (Eds: More to be filed by 9 p.m. ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., expects to withdraw
his appointment Friday of a prominent American Muslim leader to a
congressional counter-terrorism commission after sharp criticism
from Jewish organizations, a spokesman for Gephardt said late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Salam Al-Marayati to the National Commission
on Terrorism in June had been denounced by some Jewish
organizations that accused him of condoning terrorism against
Israel. But other political and religious leaders, many of them
Jewish, who have worked with Al-Marayati had begun speaking out in
his defense, praising him as a responsible moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's spokeswoman, Susan Harvey, said Al-Marayati was told
late Thursday that the nomination was in jeopardy because the
process of gaining a security clearance would take longer than the
six-month life of the counter-terrorism commission itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not withdrawing,'' Al-Marayati said Thursday. ``I think
that if there is a political will, there is a way to expedite these
security clearances and get down to the business of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Marayati, who is 38, says he has lived in the United States
since his family fled political persecution in Iraq when he was 4
years old. As executive director of the Muslim Public Affairs
Council in Los Angeles, Al-Marayati has visited the White House
several times for Muslim holidays and twice to witness the signing
of Middle East peace agreements. He was nominated by Mayor Richard
Riordan of Los Angeles to serve on that city's Human Relations
Commission, which he has done for more than a year. And his wife,
Dr. Laila Al-Marayati, was appointed by the White House to the U.S.
Commission on International Religious Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Marayati's appointment to the National Commission on
Terrorism had been cheered by Muslim-American groups and leaders,
who have long sought a voice in American public policy. These
groups had previously expressed concerns that aggressive new
anti-terrorism efforts could unfairly target Muslim- and
Arab-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The nine other members of the commission, which is charged with
reviewing policies on the prevention and punishment of acts of
terrorism against the United States, include Paul Bremer, former
ambassador for counter-terrorism; R. James Woolsey, former director
of the CIA, and Gen. Wayne Downing, commander in chief for special
operations and director of the Khobar Towers terrorist attack
review.
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt's choice of Al-Marayati immediately came under
attack by groups like the Conference of Presidents of Major
American Jewish Organizations, which represents 55 member groups,
the Anti-Defamation League and the American Jewish Congress.
</P>
<P>
   They point to excerpts of statements made by Al-Marayati, his
organization, his magazine or his co-workers that are critical of
Israel and appear to blame the Israeli government for provoking
Palestinian anger and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Among the quotations cited by the Jewish groups was this from a
March 1997 press release from the Muslim Public Affairs Council:
``Because the Palestinian people have no avenues to redress their
grievances, some of them have been pushed beyond the margins of
society and have adopted violent reactions to express their despair
and suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   And this from an editorial in the magazine The Minaret, where
Al-Marayati serves on the editorial board: ``The supporters of
Israel have created a quiet reign of terror in the U.S. People
cannot speak loudly against the apartheid policies of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In letters to Gephardt, the Jewish groups accused Al-Marayati of
failing to denounce Hamas and Hezbollah, of criticizing the recent
American bombing raids on Sudan and Afghanistan, of supporting
Saddam Hussein and of failing to support the peace agreements with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is somebody who has been associated with and who has
directly and indirectly defended organizations like Hamas and
Hezbollah,'' said Malcolm Hoenlein, executive director of the
Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations.
``To be frank, this is somebody people do not trust. And in his
presence it will cause people to be hesitant about what they will
say and to be free with information that will be essential to the
committee's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton Klein, national president of the Zionist Organization of
America, said: ``Salam Al-Marayati has justified Arab terrorism
against Israel. He's justified future terrorism against America.
He's compared America's behavior to Saddam Hussein's behavior. He's
compared Islamic terrorists to the American soldiers of the
American revolution.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
