<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON WILL SHUFFLE UNTIL DODGERS IMPROVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Dodgers manager Davey Johnson isn't used to losing, and
when his teams don't win, he refuses to remain idle and hope for
better fortune. His idea is to initiate improvement, which is what
he has been doing.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White was given Thursday off against the Rockies to give
sparkplug Trenidad Hubbard another start. Raul Mondesi and Eric
Karros also rested for a day during the four-game series with the
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The trend will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a painful time for all of us,'' Johnson said. ``I'm
not going to sit around. My motto is, `If you're going to get beat,
get beat making a change.' I'll go with the obvious, the regulars,
whatever. But if I keep getting hammered, I'm going to make a
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi is never happy when he's healthy and his name isn't in
the lineup. He arrived for Wednesday's game to find out he was
sitting. His body language told what he thought of it.
</P>
<P>
   Karros, throughout his career, has never liked sitting out a
game. But the Dodgers' futile offense has kept Johnson awake at
nights and flipping through lineup combinations through his days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to get beat, I'll get beat with a different look,
with younger players,'' Johnson said. ``I'll look for something
that might work next year, next week. I'll dream up options. Wait
until you see my lineup tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wasn't talking about younger players in the
system but rather the Dodgers' bench players. He said he'll
probably start the lefty-hitting Craig Counsell tonight against
Seattle to keep the mix going.
</P>
<P>
   __ Liking the altitude: Karros' second-inning homer was his 14th
career homer at Coors Field, the most by any opposing player. The
Cubs' Sammy Sosa is second with 13. Karros added a ninth-inning
solo shot, his second two-homer game this season. It's the 12th
time he's done it in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great place to hit,'' Karros said. ``Not just for
home runs but to hit because the outfield is so big. The key here
is not to strike out. If you don't do that, you're going to be in
business.''
</P>
<P>
   In 26 games at Coors Field, Karros is hitting .360 with 36 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   __ Brown returns home early: Kevin Brown threw his off-day
bullpen pitches early Thursday and then returned to Los Angeles to
tend to a personal matters for a day. He will be in uniform tonight
and is scheduled to pitch Saturday against the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: The Rockies are interested in
free-agent first baseman Juan Carlos Diaz, one of the two Cuban
defectors (the other is Josue Perez) declared free agents by the
commissioner's office after complaining the Dodgers illegally
signed them. Both were playing in the Dodgers' minor-league system
but have been inactive for nearly two weeks. Neither player has
signed with another team. . . . Johnson said right-hander Antonio
Osuna (elbow) will make three or four more rehab appearances for
Single-A San Bernardino before being activated after the All-Star
break. . . . Colorado's Larry Walker's solo homer in the first was
the 250th of his career. . . . The first inning, which had a
combined seven runs, seven hits and three walks, took 41 minutes.
When the Dodgers batted around in the inning, it was the first time
they accomplished it since June 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
