<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI CHIEF BEGINS QUEST AS SQUABBLES RISE AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As Ehud Barak, Israel's new prime minister, prepared
Thursday to fly off to Egypt on the first leg of an ambitious
mission to make regional peace, he was facing down a Welcome Wagon
of political squabbles on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a trip Friday to see President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt, Barak confronted opposition to his first domestic political
initiative, grumbling within his own party and a splintering of the
Russian immigrant party, which slightly altered the carefully
equilibrated dynamic of his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   For a volatile democracy like Israel's, such troubles are
nothing extraordinary, but they nonetheless served as a quick
reminder to Barak that political static is the background noise of
many grand projects. His first domestic political initiative, a
bill to expand the number of ministers in his cabinet, is
confronting a raft of opposition, and not only from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the expected criticism from the conservative
Likud Party, Barak's proposal has been condemned by three key
figures in his One Israel/Labor Party: his new justice minister,
Yossi Beilin; former Prime Minister Shimon Peres, and the new
speaker of the House, Avraham Burg. Newspaper editorials have
railed against it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said that he needs 24 ministers in his cabinet, and
not the 18 allowed by the basic laws of Israel, because of the
demands for representation from his unusually broad coalition of
seven parties. The coalition represents almost two-thirds of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the expansion see the additional ministries as
an expensive bloating of the government in order to mete out favors
to Barak's new coalition partners. And some _ like Beilin, who said
he would vote against the bill in the cabinet to make his point _
oppose amending the basic laws that represent the building blocks
for an Israeli Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Burg, who in a minor party revolt won the role of speaker over
the hand-picked candidate of Barak, said he would not make it easy
for the legislation to pass quickly through the parliament. It is a
sign of the adversarial role that Burg is likely to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not let anyone carry out hasty legislation, certainly
not in matters pertaining to the basic laws,'' he said. ``This is
the holy of holies in legislation. If they want to change a basic
law, it must be done with reverence, slowly, one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Barak, Haim Ramon, a special minister in the prime
minister's office, said that the government faced a difficult
choice between ``undermining a basic law and forming a government
equipped to deal with the hard tasks ahead of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The law is expected to pass, with smirks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As that debate raged, a power struggle within the principal
Russian immigrants' party has renewed the coalition's closed debate
about who should get what.
</P>
<P>
   Yisrael Baaliya, the party led by Natan Sharansky, lost two of
its six members on Tuesday. The two, Roman Bronfman and Alexander
Tzinker, quit to form their own tiny faction, citing ideological
differences over ``state and religion'' with Sharansky, who is more
right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman, who said he represented secular Russians, has called
the Russian leader a ``megalomaniac.'' Sharansky accused Bronfman
of ``treason'' and of stealing votes. The split has dealt Sharansky
a serious blow.
</P>
<P>
   It also introduced some disarray into the carefully negotiated
coalition, since Yisrael Baaliya became a very small party
overnight, but still holds considerable power. In addition to the
Interior Ministry, which Sharansky will run, the party was set to
control the Immigration Ministry, with Yuli Edelstein at the helm.
And Edelstein was expected to join the expanded cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party that lost the Interior Ministry,
immediately began to complain. One Israel officials said that the
deal to give Edelstein a ministry would likely be broken so as not
to lead to an unraveling of the whole coalition package, which,
negotiated over seven weeks, was calibrated on the basis of the
number of party seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Barak faced down some continuing discontent within his
party about the cabinet appointments he made. Many said they
believed his choices for key ministries were uninspired, and that
the cabinet did not represent the change he promised during his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On the larger level, Barak got off to such a quick start on the
peace effort that many Israelis felt excited, as if they were on
the brink of seeing a breakthrough after years of stagnation. But
it quickly seemed clear that the body politic would make sure that
nothing happened without a keen battle of wits, egos and ideologies
as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
