<HEADLINE>
GIFFORD TO GAIN KINGLY BUNDLE AFTER MERGER WITH FLEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He is the heir apparent, yet he will be compensated as
if he already sits on the throne.
</P>
<P>
   Charles K. Gifford, head of BankBoston Corp., has wrangled a
rich compensation package out of his future employer, Fleet
Financial Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, which includes lucrative stock options, a hefty
salary, and a ``golden parachute'' if Gifford is fired, reflects
the rich bounty that bank executives now reap when they sell their
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the package, detailed in a Fleet document filed Thursday
with securities regulators, may also reflect uncertainty over
Gifford's future at the combined Fleet-BankBoston, which could one
day become a takeover target for other banks seeking to expand into
New England.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford's new employment contract spans what banking lawyers and
compensation specialists said was a relatively short three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer the contract, the more protection the executive
has'' at the new company, said a banking lawyer who asked not to be
named. Still, the lawyer said the contract's generous terms were a
sign that Gifford's future at the new bank was secure.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston agreed in March to be acquired by its former rival
Fleet, in a $16 billion deal that will form New England's largest
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford is the number two at the new company, temporarily known
as Fleet Boston Corp., until Murray, 59, retires as chief executive
at the end of 2001. Then Gifford takes the top job. He assumes the
additional title of chairman a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Under his contract, Gifford will earn a salary equal to that of
Fleet's chief executive, Terrence Murray. Last year, Murray earned
a base salary of $992,000 and a $3.4 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford will also get 300,000 shares of restricted stock when
the Fleet-BankBoston merger closes later this year. At Fleet's
closing price Thursday of around $44, the shares would be worth
$13.2 million. Gifford plans to donate 75,000 of those shares,
worth about $3.3 million, to charity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gifford has the right to buy 900,000 stock options
over two years. According to a rule of thumb that says one option
is worth approximately one-third of a share, that lot would be
worth around $13.1 million today.
</P>
<P>
   The shares and options are tied to the new company's future
performance, and Gifford won't be able to exercise them all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Upon retirement, 56-year-old Gifford, who has been at BankBoston
for 32 years, will get $1.25 million a year for life. His wife
would get 75 percent of that sum after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they're paying him as if he were the CEO,'' said
Alan M. Johnson, managing director of Johnson Associates, a New
York-based executive compensation consulting firm. ``It's an
expensive deal for the shareholders, but it reflects his prominent
position in the new company.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford has also negotiated a lucrative package worth up to $15
million if he is forced out of the new bank. Fleet will amend its
charter to require a 75 percent majority vote by the new company's
22-member board to remove Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks also shelled out hefty sums to the New York
investment banks that put together their deal.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's advisers, Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, will each get $20 million. Fleet's advisers, Donaldson,
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and Goldman Sachs, will each get $15 million. The
fees are comparable to payments made in other major bank mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of BankBoston's 23,000 employees are also reaping a
miniwindfall from the merger, since a lucrative employee stock
option plan is now coming due.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston have the right to cancel their deal if it
is not completed by March 14, 2000. Both banks expect regulatory
approval for their merger later this year, with a deal formally
sealed in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   New England's two largest banks have also reserved the right to
renegotiate their deal should shareholders not approve it at
company meetings on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is swapping 1.1844 Fleet shares for each BankBoston share.
Fleet's offer valued BankBoston at around $53 per share when the
deal was announced _ a 13 percent premium to BankBoston's price of
nearly $47. Since then, BankBoston shares have risen about 11
percent, and now trade at just over $50.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's proxy confirmed that the new company expects to
eliminate 5,000 positions, or more than 8 percent of its combined
work force. It also reiterated that the combined bank expects
after-tax cost savings of $360 million a year, with 60 percent
achieved in 2000 and 100 percent in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
