<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLITON-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES INVESTMENT TO HELP YOUTH LEARN ECONOMIC SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ President Clinton Thursday wrapped up a
cross-country tour of economically distressed areas by calling for
greater investment in disadvantaged youths, saying it was in the
best interest of ``people who live in the ritziest suburb in
America'' for them to have the skills to function in the new
economy.
</P>
<P>
   After a four-day trip that took him from the Appalachia hollows
to the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation to the Mississippi Delta, the
president visited Watts and South Central Los Angeles. Both are
inner-city neighborhoods of high unemployment where riots have
broken out in the past 30 years and where complaints of economic
isolation have long resonated.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by former basketball star Magic Johnson at Southwest
College in South Central, Clinton said expanding opportunities for
disadvantaged youth was not only integral to the economic
development of poor communities but also a benefit to wealthier
areas because it would help keep the economy going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest way to keep it going is to go to places where
there aren't enough jobs and there aren't enough consumers and
create more of both...That's all growth completely without
inflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we hire a young person off the street in Watts and
give him or her a better future, we are helping people who live in
the ritziest suburb in America to continue to enjoy a rising stock
market,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the college to about 175 business and union leaders,
and five students clad in black t-shirts that read ``Yo,'' Clinton
added, ``Those of you who follow the business news know that every
time the Federal Reserve meets there's all this tense speculation,
will they raise interest rates or not? Well, what does that mean to
these young people here with their Yo shirts on?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said 60 percent of the young people who live in
distressed areas of the United States are neither in jobs nor in
school. And, according to figures provided by the White House, more
than 10 million youths age 16 to 24 are out of school and have only
a high school diploma or less; four million have less than a high
school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a former Los Angeles Lakers player who has revitalized
South Central Los Angeles and other inner cities with multiplex
movie theaters, said young people want the dignity that holding a
job can bring. ``They are hungry to work, they just want to do it
in their own communities sometimes.'' he said,``That's what I am
trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In his trip to Watts, Clinton toured a transportation technology
program at Locke High School, where he watched students using
computers to demonstrate, for example, the affects of aerodynamics
on the performance of a car. More than 90 percent of the students
who complete the program go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   He later traveled to nearby Anaheim for a speech to the National
Academy Foundation, a nonprofit group that provides education and
training for youths to prepare them for careers in finance, travel
and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   To coincide with that appearance, the White House announced a
program to be started by Lucent Technologies and other companies to
prepare public school students for careers in information
technology fields and address the nation's shortage of technology
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Academy of Information Technlogy, the $8 million
program comes on the heels of a recent report by the Commerce
Department's Office of Technology Policy, which projects that from
1996 to 2006, the United States will require more than 1.3 million
new highly skilled information technology workers ranging from
computer scientists and engineers to systems analysts and
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing speech of his anti-poverty tour, Clinton
reflected back on some of the people he met, and said that he would
send to Congress next week his proposed ``new markets''
legislation. The plan uses tax credits and other incentives to
encourage $15 billion in new investments in economically depressed
rural and urban areas over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he plans to take another poverty tour next
fall that will start in Newark, N.J., to challenge the owners of
professional sports teams and professional athletes to invest in
their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I want to say to you is this: This tour, this
last four days that we have all spent together, has been a
significant step toward opening America's new markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it can't be the end of the journey. It has to be, instead,
the opening salvo of a battle to build a real economy in every
community in this country. The real measure of our success is not
whether CEOs join the president on a trip like this which moved the
nation, but whether the same CEOs and others will return to those
markets and move the lives of the people there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
