<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BLACKOUT-POWER-800     07-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKOUT-POWER-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK, POWER SYSTEMS REACHING THEIR LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Md., Mass., Maine, Va., Ore., Calif., Fla.)  (jw) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The blackout that stilled upper Manhattan for
nearly a day was a sort of distress call, a warning that as the
demand for electricity sets new records, the power system in the
New York metropolitan area is surging perilously close to its
physical limits, experts in the field cautioned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Power demand is rising faster than the system's ability to
generate and deliver it, driven by a booming economy and the
proliferation of computers, fax machines, air conditioners and the
other amenities of an affluent, wired society. The more power is
pushed through the cables, the greater the likelihood that some of
those cables will fail, a lesson reinforced in dramatic fashion
Tuesday, when demand set records and power went out not just in
Washington Heights and parts of the Lower East Side and Long
Island, but in communities from Maryland to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater danger posed by the increasing use of
electricity is one that is not directly related to Tuesday's
blackout. The New York metropolitan area, more than any other part
of the country, runs the risk that in the near future it simply
will not be able to import, generate or deliver enough power to
keep up with demand.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Power Pool, a consortium of the state's utilities,
requires that each of its members be able to deliver at least 18
percent more power than customers are using at peak periods, and
pools around the country have similar standards. On Tuesday, for
the first time, Consolidated Edison, serving New York City and
Westchester County, fell to an 18 percent margin. The Long Island
Power Authority had just a 10 percent cushion, and Public Service
Electric &AMP; Gas in New Jersey came within 5 percent of its capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The capacity problem in New York City isn't critical today,
but it could be critical in a couple of years,'' said William
Balet, executive director of the New York Power Pool. ``And Long
Island is in worse shape than New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, utilities from Maine to Virginia cut the voltage
they supplied to customers by 5 percent because their three
regional power pools were approaching their capacity limits.
</P>
<P>
   Public Service shut off air conditioning to 145,000 homes whose
residents had signed up to sacrifice their cool air in case of an
emergency in return for lower rates. The Long Island authority
persuaded local governments to shut down for the day. In both
cases, officials said, those measures were all that prevented
rolling blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching the point where more generation is needed
in New York City to reliably supply demands in the future,'' said
Louis Rana, vice president of Con Edison for system and
transmission operations. Asked if the system had approached a
crisis on Tuesday, he said, ``I would say yes, we were close.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not unique to the Northeast, though it is more
pressing here than in most of the country. In 1996, with demand
straining the capacity to deliver electricity in the Northwest, the
failure of a couple of transmission lines in Oregon shut power to
parts of nine states. And last summer, utilities across the Midwest
lowered everyone's voltage, pleaded with customers to turn off
their appliances, and persuaded some industries to shut down,
because demand was pushing limits, threatening another vast
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   New York City and Long Island have an added problem: The ability
to deliver power from outside the region is severely constrained
simply because the lines to carry it are few. Transmission lines
from other places represent only about one-quarter of the region's
capacity to deliver electricity; the rest is generated locally.
That means that at times of peak demand, if a problem occurred with
the local power plants or the transmission system, the region would
not be able to rely on outside help to avoid blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   A few other population centers, like San Francisco, South
Florida and parts of New England, have similar limitations _ and
contributed to the failure that blacked out most of San Francisco
in December _ but none are as extreme as the New York metropolitan
area's.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison has one of the lowest rates of power failure in the
industry, and by far the lowest of any New York State utility. In
power failures that struck the region in 1996 and 1997 _ one caused
by a failed transmission line, the other by thunderstorms _ only
Con Edison's customers were unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   But as demand continues to rise, ``the risk of events like
Washington Heights, and of even bigger, systemwide failures, just
increases,'' said Ashok Gupta, an economist with the Natural
Resources Defense Council who specializes in energy issues.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kessel, chairman of the Long Island Power Authority,
urged immediate action. ``I think that this heat wave should sober
all of us up to recognize that we have a really big problem, and we
need to plan for the future right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Con Edison set a demand record of 10,700 megawatts in July
1991, it had a margin of more than 30 percent between that peak and
its overall capacity of 14,000 megawatts. That record stood for six
years, until an 11,013-megawatt day in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In planning for this summer, the utility anticipated peak demand
of 11,650 megawatts. Instead, it hit 11,850 on Tuesday, smashing
the old record by almost 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, in a system with a capacity of 5,100 megawatts,
the Power Authority delivered as much as 4,590 on Tuesday, 9
percent above the record set in July 1998. And Public Service in
New Jersey hit a peak demand of 9,794 megawatts on Tuesday, close
to its 10,272-megawatt capacity, and almost 3 percent higher than
the record set in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Energy experts say some combination is needed of four solutions:
construction of new power plants to keep up with demand that is
rising 2 to 3 percent a year nationally; construction of new
transmission lines to bring power into the metropolitan area; more
aggressive energy conservation programs; and the upgrading of the
local lines that deliver electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Power failures have long been a feature of heat waves _ in 1993,
a large segment of Brooklyn went dark, and in 1996 it happened in
Queens _ because the ``feeder cables'' that supply communities
become overheated as more energy is pushed through them and the
ground around them becomes hotter. In many cases, the cables were
installed a generation or two ago, for a less demanding market. It
was an overload and subsequent fire in feeder cables that forced
Con Edison to cut power to Washington Heights on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you have 10,000-, 11,000-megawatt days, the more
you're going to have problems like this,'' said Larry Shapiro, a
staff attorney for the New York Public Interest Research Group who
follows energy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison officials say that the company is installing new
cables with greater capacity and better insulation but that it will
take years to replace them all.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kelley, spokesman for Edison International, the parent
company of Southern California Edison, said, ``I think every major
utility in the country, including ours, is upgrading the
transmission and distribution infrastructure and investing a lot of
money to keep up with increasing demand.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a generation, companies are seeking to
build new power plants in New York, to take advantage of new
competition. New York, like several other states, is deregulating
the industry, abolishing the old utility monopolies and allowing
power suppliers to compete for customers. Among the proposals is
one for a plan on a barge moored off Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But completion of any of those plants is years away, and for
now, the projects are tied up in a squabble in Albany among state
lawmakers over how to draft a law on granting permits for new
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Rana, of Con Edison, said the utility was not considering
building new transmission lines to import power from outside the
region. New York, unlike many other cities, generates most of its
power in the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Long Island officials are looking into installing a major
transmission line across the bottom of Long Island Sound to bring
in power. Long Island is more isolated from the larger grid than
any other heavily populated part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can deliver 5,100 megawatts, but on a hot day, we can't get
5,100 megawatts to deliver,'' said Kessel, of the power authority.
``We normally buy some power from Con Ed, but on Tuesday, they
couldn't spare it. We nearly had a big, big problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
