</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODHAM CLINTON SAYS JERUSALEM SHOULD BE ISRAELI CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. - In a move that could boost her chances to be
elected Senator from New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton has told a
leading group of American Orthodox Jews that she favors making
Jerusalem ``the eternal and indivisible capital'' of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Her sentiment, which goes against official US policy, could do
much to reverse the negative attitude that many Jews have toward
the First Lady for a statement she made several years ago in
support of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's press spokesman, Howard Wolfson, who was
traveling with her on a campaign tour of upstate New York, waved
away the idea that she issued the statement about Jerusalem for
political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's her longstanding position,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that 50 percent of New York's Jews would vote for
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's likely Republican opponent,
if the election for Senate were held today _ with just 36 percent
supporting Mrs. Clinton. Giuliani has long held strong pro-Israel
views.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts think Mrs. Clinton, or any Democrat, must
attract a much larger share of support from Jews in order to win a
statewide election. Alfonse D'Amato, a former three-term Republican
Senator, won a number of squeakers by picking up 40 percent of the
Jewish vote. He lost last year, to Congressman Charles Schumer, in
part because he won only 20 percent of the Jewish vote.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton _ who expressed her view in a letter dated last
Friday to Mandell Ganchrow, president of the Union of Orthodox
Jewish Congregations of America, which represents 1,000 synagogues
nationwide _ did note a major caveat in her advocacy of moving the
capital to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' she wrote, ``the timing of such a move must be
sensitive to Israel's interest in achieving a secure peace with its
neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Authority, which also claims Jerusalem as its
spiritual capital, is opposed to the move.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's letter was first published in The Forward, a
Jewish newspaper. Ganchrow Thursday told the Associated Press,
which obtained a copy of the letter, that he would like to explore
the issue further with Clinton. ``I think it is important she
understands the significance of the issue'' and added that he would
like to meet with her ``to gauge her emotional attachment'' to the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made a similar promise about Jerusalem in his
1992 race for the White House, but never followed through after he
was elected. He has since adopted the State Department view that
the issue should be settled in negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman Thursday declined comment on Mrs.
Clinton's letter, other than to note that she was offering only her
personal views.
</P>
<P>
   An Arab-American leader, James Zogby of the Arab American
Institute, called it unhelpful pandering to New York's Jewish
community. ``It's wrong, it is unhelpful and frankly it is
meaningless, because this kind of pandering frequently is done,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those in the Jewish community pressuring politicians to take
such positions are damaging the search for peace and damaging
American interests and American leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Thursday _ on the second day of her ``listening
tour'' across upstate New York _ Mrs. Clinton seemed to draw mostly
on her ``policy-wonk'' talents, and, judging from the results, it
may be just the right move.
</P>
<P>
   She did her share of plunging into crowds of well-wishers,
shaking hands and holding babies, and had lunch in the town of
Clinton. (``I loved the idea of being in Clinton, N.Y.,'' she said
afterward, with a smile.)
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of the day was spent in what seemed more like
seminars than typical campaign whistle-stops. In the morning, she
talked _ and listened _ for 90 minutes with doctors and nurses at a
health-care center in Cooperstown. In the afternoon, she discussed
Social Security and family issues at a senior-citizens' center in
Utica.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of the campaign strategy _ at least this stage of
it _ seems to be to meet with specific groups and talk about their
specific issues, at great length, in awesome detail, with confident
authority, but also ask them for their ideas and views.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems to be that, if she does this in enough towns,
with enough groups, for enough time, the most powerful complaint
against her _ that she's a ``carpetbagger'' who has never lived or
worked in New York and, therefore, knows nothing about the state's
problems _ will be wiped away.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy may already be working. After her talk at the East
Side Senior Center in this medium-sized city, Ann Fusco, who
described herself as a registered Republican, said, ``Before, I was
sure I wouldn't vote for her. I thought what the heck's she doing
here? She's not even from New York. But now, I don't think it makes
a difference where she's from.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bassett Health Care in Cooperstown, a doctor, Andrew Rausch,
expressed the sort of doubts that her campaign is trying to
overcome. ``I don't know how much she knows about upstate New
York,'' he said, but then added, ``I don't know how much Rudy
Giuliani knows about upstate New York, either.''
</P>
<P>
   In another attempt to shake off the ``carpetbagger'' charge,
Mrs. Clinton told reporters, ``I am committed to serving a full
term in the Senate'' if she is elected in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This statement, made in reply to a question, was obviously meant
to rebut suspicions that she might use the Senate seat as a
stepping-stone to running for President in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Giuliani has explicitly declined to make any such pledge,
saying it would be dishonest to make such predictions about the
future. He similarly decline to pledge to serve out his full term
as mayor during his reelection campaign two years ago _ and,
indeed, if he wins the Senate race, he would have to step down from
that office a year before his term runs out.
</P>
<P>
   During her question-answer period with reporters, Mrs. Clinton
declined to take two questions about Giuliani, one dealing with
their differences, the other dealing with how well she thinks he
has done as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be plenty of times in the campaign to go into
that,'' she said, ``and I look forward to that opportunity when it
arises.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Mrs. Clinton nor Giuliani has officially entered the
race _ Mrs. Clinton calls her tour this week the first step of
``exploring'' whether she will be a candidate _ but polls show it
would be a very tight contest. Mrs. Clinton is way ahead in the
predominantly Democratic New York City. Giuliani is way ahead in
the more Republican suburbs and upstate regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
