<HEADLINE>
EXITING FOREIGN AID CHIEF WARNS OF AFFLUENT AMERICA IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From J. Brian Atwood's perspective, two numbers out
of Washington are combining to send a dangerous message to the
world: the Clinton administration forecast of a $1 trillion budget
surplus and Congress's refusal to pay back $1 billion in dues to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, the Wareham, Mass., native who leaves his job today
(July 9) as US foreign aid chief, said in an interview Thursday
that the world's disfranchised are increasingly looking at
ever-richer America as ``arrogant'' as it hoards its bounty.
</P>
<P>
   After overseeing an almost steady six-year decline of funding
for foreign assistance at the Agency for International Development,
Atwood, will head international development programs at Boston's
Citizens Energy Corp. beginning in August.
</P>
<P>
   But before he leaves Washington, Atwood, 56, has been using the
last days of his high government pulpit to speak with a degree of
candor almost never heard in official Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He has held little back. He called the government's foreign
affairs budget a ``joke,'' blaming Congress for whittling foreign
assistance in the AID budget from $7.5 billion in 1993 to $6.9
billion last year, and for cutting AID staff by a third.
</P>
<P>
   He has said no one is speaking out about one of the most
troubling global trends: The widening gap between rich and poor.
Further US aid cutbacks could doom America's push for emerging
democracies because fewer people are reaping democracy's fruits, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood took his job at Citizens Energy _ founded by former
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II _ after realizing his
nomination as US ambassador to Brazil would never come up for a
vote before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Senator Jesse
Helms, the North Carolina Republican who chairs the panel, and
Atwood had long feuded over the senator's plan to merge AID into
the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   In his spaceous office in the Ronald Reagan Building and with
pictures still on the walls Thursday, Atwood said he hoped his
words would inspire development professionals and perhaps a
presidential candidate or two to raise the issue of helping the
less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone leaves a job like this, they all of a sudden have
a platform. It is important to try to provoke people into thinking
about what is right and what is wrong. ... It just seems to me that
I have almost an obligation to speak out. There are probably no
other voices in this town that are going to speak out on behalf of
the poor around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   America, he said, ``needs to be shaken out of our lethargy'' and
begin helping the world's poorest. ``We'll be lost if we don't, and
the resentment toward the US will only grow.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged the United States to immediately pay back its UN debt
without conditions. The Senate has passed a bill that would earmark
$800 million for the United Nations as long as the international
body reduced the US contribution to 20 percent from 25 percent of
the UN's budget.
</P>
<P>
   With the expected $1 trillion in US surplus, Atwood recommended
putting $10 billion a year for five years toward development
projects in the neediest parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, a career diplomat long connected to the Democratic
Party, said he wasn't upset about leaving Washington this way. His
new job, he said, would keep him doing the work he enjoys most.
Later this month, Kennedy and Atwood plan to travel to Angola and
Nigeria to help steer corporations toward development projects.
</P>
<P>
   People want to portray him as angry, ``but I really don't feel
that way,'' Atwood explained. ``It was just fate. It wasn't meant
for me to go to Brazil at this time. I was prepared to go. I was
excited about going. But what I'm going to be doing in Boston is, I
think, going to be more important. ... If I went to Brazil, no one
would hear my voice on these issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
