A3686 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UV-RAYS-HNS &LR;      07-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UV-RAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERY MAY ENABLE SCIENTISTS TO PINPOINT THOSE AT RISK OF DEADLY
SKIN CANCERS &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By KEVIN MORAN
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Geneticists here have discovered an ancient
mechanism that protects life from the sun's harmful ultraviolet
rays, a find that could eventually make it possible to identify
people prone to deadly skin cancers.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery springs from results of a study published earlier
this year in which University of Texas Medical Branch scientists
identified a new enzyme that can replicate damaged DNA without
mutations that increase chances of developing skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in Friday's edition of the journal
Science, the UTMB researchers reveal how they deduced that humans
are protected from ultraviolet rays in the same way as yeast that
evolved 300 million years earlier than man.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, their deduction started with a look at an enzyme
found in brewer's yeast. Searching a genetic library, they were
able to confirm a hunch that a defective form of the enzyme in
humans could lead to skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists said they were able to use information on the
Internet to hasten their research.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier study had identified the new enzyme, known as a DNA
polymerase. Based on that identification, UTMB geneticists Robert
Johnson, Christine Kondratick, and Satya and Louise Prakash
predicted that humans with normal forms of a gene called hRAD30 are
protected from ultraviolet rays' harmful effects.
</P>
<P>
   In the February issue of Science, Johnson and the Prakashes had
reported that people who have a genetic disease known as xeroderma
pigmentosum have defective hRAD30 genes that make them extremely
vulnerable to skin cancer caused by sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, who are with UTMB's Sealy Center for Molecular
Science, believe that the normal hRAD30 and similar genes found in
organisms as diverse as plants and worms keep most healthy people,
plants and animals from being killed by ultraviolet rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was totally unexpected that there would be a protein
sitting in yeast as well as in humans whose job it is to faithfully
replicate DNA in an error-free manner,'' Satya Prakash said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's allowing life to adapt to ultraviolet rays,'' he said.
``So, when you have something so consistently present all over, it
means it's played a very important part in the evolution of life
and our adaptation to sunlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Prakash said he and his colleagues believe that the beneficial
DNA polymerase they discovered will turn out to be just the first
in a group of undiscovered DNA polymerases that will overcome
various kinds of DNA damage.
</P>
<P>
   Other polymerases likely will help overcome routine breaks in
DNA caused by toxic metabolic byproducts as well as exposure to
pollution and other environmental carcinogens, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prakash emphasized that the new DNA polymerase doesn't repair
damaged DNA but replicates it without mutations that cause cells to
develop cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's other machinery at work which repairs the damage,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of six previously identified DNA polymerases, five have no
positive effect on cells or DNA damaged by ultraviolet rays, the
scientists said. The sixth goes to work on sun-damaged DNA but
frequently causes mutations in replicated DNA that can cause cells
to develop cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The newly discovered DNA polymerase is able to bypass roadblocks
around DNA damaged by ultraviolet light without making potentially
fatal mistakes, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The UTMB researchers used a huge genetic library now available
in part on the Internet to pinpoint hRAD30 as the human counterpart
to the yeast gene that shares a code with the DNA polymerase they
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't had that database available, we still could have
accomplished this, but it would have taken several years to come up
with the same conclusion,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said scientists who reviewed the UTMB research before
publication consider the work significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know that there will be further studies in this area
which will hopefully develop either a potential cure or at least
early diagnosis of people who may be defective in this gene,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a professional standpoint, it's always nice to know that
you're helping humankind discover new and different ways of helping
people avoid damage from something we encounter every day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The UTMB team already has discovered eight hRAD30 defects that
could destroy the effectiveness of their newly discovered DNA
polymerase, Prakash said. Those defects could cause rapid genetic
mutations and lead to development of skin cancers in humans in
early age.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
