<HEADLINE>
ARCHER PUSHING EDUCATION TAX BREAKS &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By DAVID IVANOVICH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, will seek tax breaks for
families with school-age children as part of a 10-year, $864
billion tax-cutting package to be rolled out next week.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats on Capitol Hill intend to fight a provision they
consider an effort to provide school vouchers for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Archer, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee and the
primary tax writer in the House, said Thursday his tax bill would
allow private universities to offer prepaid tuition plans for
prospective students. Currently, only state-funded schools are
allowed to offer such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's proposal also would exempt the income earning in such
plans from taxes. Current law only defers the taxes until the money
is withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Using these pre-pay systems, families can begin to pay for
college long before their children are ready to enter a university.
By paying now families can lock in college costs at current rates
rather than wait for tuition prices to continue to escalate.
</P>
<P>
   Archer pointed to numbers from the National Commission on the
Cost of Higher Education, which calculated that the average annual
tuition for a four-year, public university rose from $642 in 1976
to $3,151 by 1996. For private colleges, the average annual tuition
soared from $2,881 in 1976 to $15,581 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some 700,000 families in Texas and 18 other states already have
begun paying for college under these pre-pay plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the federal government has a limited role in the
education of our school children, we should work within that role
to lighten the education tax bite whenever possible,'' Archer said
in a written statement. ``That means helping students and parents
save for college.''
</P>
<P>
   A far more controversial measure would allow families to set up
individual retirement accounts _ called education savings accounts
_ to help pay for elementary and high school expenses. The income
generated from these accounts would be tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Current law allows families to establish individual retirement
accounts to save for college but not for students in kindergarten
through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal also would raise the caps on these individual
retirement accounts, from $500 a year to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue the education savings accounts would help 14.3
million families pay for school, including an estimated 10.8
million whose children attend public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Ways and Means Committee, however, say the
education savings accounts are a way to force the federal
government to help fund private schools. And they argue the
benefits that would accrue to the children would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   To help school districts fund construction of new schools and
repair existing buildings, Archer's proposal also would give school
districts greater flexibility when using money raised with
tax-exempt bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, school systems must use those funds within two years.
Archer's proposal would increase that time to four years, giving
school districts greater opportunity to invest those dollars and
expand their building funds.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, say the proposal would provide only minimal
benefits to larger school districts.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
