<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thurssday, 07/08/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- CLINTON-POVERTY-B&AMP;W, 07-08 --
This week President Clinton returned to the tradition of Democrats
who held or sought the presidency by spending four days wending his
way through poverty-stricken corners of the nation. Invoking the
image of Robert F. Kennedy, shown during his famous tour of the
Mississippi Delta in 1967 with television cameras following him,
Clinton returned to the Delta on Tuesday. (George Tames/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- July 8, 1999 -- WEST-VETERANS, 07-08 --
Secretary of Veterans Affairs Togo D. West, Jr., in an undated
photo. West has told President Clinton that he plans to resign
before the end of the term but has set no date for his departure, a
White House official said on Thursday. (Department of Veterans
Affairs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- NY-SQUEEGEE-SHOOTING, 07-08
-- Officer Michael W. Meyer declares that ``justice was served'' as
he leaves the Bronx County Courthouse on Thursday after being
acquitted of assault charges for shooting a squeegee man. The
officer says that he had shot in self-defense. (George M.
Gutierrez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) LOS ANGELES -- July 8, 1999 -- TERROR-PANE, 07-08 --
Salam Al-Marayati, executive director of the Muslim Public Affairs
Council in Los Angeles on Thursday. House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt expects to withdraw his appointment on Friday of
Al-Marayati to a Congressional counter-terrorism commission. The
appointment to the National Commission on Terrorism in June had
been denounced by some Jewish organizations that accused
Al-Marayati of condoning terrorism against Israel. (Ted Soqui/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) HEALDSBURG, Calif. -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 11 -- CALIF-GALLO-PROFILE, 07-08 -- Seven years ago, when the
giant E.&AMP;J. Gallo Winery launched its first entries in the
superpremium-and-up wine category, Gina Gallo was just 25 and
preparing for a career in sales with the family business. Today she
is a winemaker at Gallo's money-no-object Sonoma operation, and
perhaps more importantly, the face of the new Gallo in a
multi-million dollar ad campaign aimed at taking the venerable
brand up market. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- JAPAN-FISHING, 07-08 --
Yasushi Yamashita, 50, still hauls his nets, but Japan's fishermen
are a dwindling breed in what was for decades the world's top
fishing nation. Japan is still by far the world's leading consumer
of fish. But in 1989 its fish catch was surpassed by China, and
since then by Peru and Chile as well. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) CLINTON, N.Y. -- July 8, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 07-08 --
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton greets supporters on Thursday.
Mrs. Clinton said Thursday that she would ask her husband to do
some campaigning for her if she moves forward with a New York
Senate race. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- NY-BLACKOUT-RESEARCH-2,
07-08 -- Drs. Indra Koracith, left, and Jens Husemann throw away
tissue samples and other materials on Thursday after they were
damaged when the refrigerator they are in stopped operating during
a power outtage. The damaged samples were being used by a team led
by Dr. Samuel Silverstein, chairman of physiology and cellular
biophysics at the hospital, which were part of a research project
investigating white blood-cell activity for use in understanding
inflammation in illnesses like rheumatoid arthritis. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- July 8, 1999 -- SUB-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS, 07-08 --
Charles Gould with some of his mini-cars, from left, a 1972 Velorex
350 from Czeckoslovakia, a 1964 Peel Trident from Great Britain,
and a 1955 Messerschmitt KR 200 from Germany. These are the mini-
and microcars whose genesis was the need for cheap transportation,
not to mention jobs in idled aircraft factories, in Europe in the
years after World War II. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- NY-BLACKOUT-RESEARCH, 07-08
-- Dr. Samuel Silverstein, center, hands a bucket of dry ice to
Arlene Albala as Yong Mei Lee reaches for more dry ice from a
freezer in Silverstein's laboratory at Columbia Presbyterian
Hospital on Thursday. Columbia University medical researchers said
Thursday that the power failure that darkened northern Manhattan
may have destroyed or set back by months millions of dollars worth
of experiments. Some of the cells in Dr. Silverstein's lab which
were damaged were from human umbilical cords, being used to
investigate white blood-cell activity for use in understanding
inflammation in illnesses like rheumatoid arthritis. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- July 8, 1999 -- GOTTI-SENTENCE,
07-08 -- John Gotti, Jr. arrives to Federal Court for his
sentencing on Thursday which was postponed until Sept. 3. Gotti
pleaded guilty in April to racketeering crimes including bribery,
extortion, gambling and fraud. He also pleaded guilty to tax and
loansharking charges that were looming in Brooklyn. On Thursday,
Gotti railed at reporters for using excerpts of conversations in
which his father mocked his intelligence. His lawyer assailed the
government for releasing the quotes.(Suzanne DeChillo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 11 --
ABOUT-CARS-XTERRA-2, 07-08 -- The roof on the Nissan Xterra rack
has a basket for wet gear, right; on the rear, a stamped-in
``backpack.'' The 2000 Xterra is unapologetically aimed at
20-somethings. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 11 --
ABOUT-CARS-XTERRA-1, 07-08 -- High, bulging and plainly assertive,
the Nissan Xterra sneers at today's soft, cushy SUVs. Its designers
actually chilled out at trailheads, surfer beaches and other haunts
of the young and restless to observe how vehicles were used. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 11 --
CAR-SMART-MERCEDES, 07-08 -- At $48,000 and up, the Mercedes-Benz
CLK Cabriolet isn't cheap, but it is practical for year-round use.
The company's goal is to stir the market for luxury coupes and
convertibles just as it recast the roadster segment with its SLK230
Kompressor. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PROKUPLJE, Yugoslavia -- July 8, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RALLIES,
07-08 -- Serb demonstrators demonstrating against the rule of
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, one wielding a stick,
approach pro-government supporters on Thursday. The government,
which had planned to couteract an opposition rally here on Thursday
with a demonstration of its own, canceled that plan, but scuffles
broke out anyway between Milosevic's enemies and supporters.(Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- NY-SUMMERS-ECON, 07-08 --
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, center, tours a construction
project in Upper Manhattan on Thursday. In one of his first acts as
Treasury secretary, Summers met with a number of the city's
financial leaders to urge them to do more to help small businesses
in poor New York neighborhoods. (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ST. HELENA, Calif. -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 11 -- CALIF-NAPA-WINE, 07-08 -- Field hands checking vines on
a terraced hillside near St. Helena at Stuart Smith's 30-acre
Madrone Vineyards and Winery in the Napa Valley. Shrewd marketing
and a robust economy have propelled premium Napa wines into a $100
million-a-year business whose carefully cultivated images of
prestige and romance help lift sales of wine produced throughout
the state. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NAPA VALLEY, Calif. -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 11 --WINE-PARTNERSHIPS, 07-08 -- Michael Mondavi does some
product testing at the Mondavi Winery in the Napa Valley of
California. By teaming up with partners who know the local soil,
climate and people, ``we are able to jump-start the process,'' he
says. ``We produce a better wine in less time and for a lower
initial investment,'' than Mondavi can on its own. (Anne Dowie/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- SUB-PEONY-OPERA-REVIEW,
07-08 -- Qian Yi, left, as Beautiful Du and Wen Yu Hang as Willow
Dream of Plum in a scene from Episode 1 of ``The Peony Pavilion,''
part of the Lincoln Center Festival. Placed at the center of
Lincoln Center Festival '99, Tang Xianzu's wandering epic of love,
death and the supernatural is testing the endurance of both its
players and its audience: six episodes, 20 hours, the cycle to be
repeated three times this month. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 11 --
THEATER-HOLOCAUST-2, 07-08 -- Theodore Bikel, center, with Jesse
Adam Eisenberg, in ``The Gathering,'' presented by the Jewish
Repertory Theater. Whether onstage or in films, the Holocaust
survivor is often reduced to a one-dimensional cliche, a cartoon of
a stock character that seems to dominate the perceptions of those
in the dramatic arts. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 11 --
THEATER-HOLOCAUST-1, 07-08 -- Dianne Wiest in Cynthia Ozick's
Holocaust play ``The Shawl.'' Apparently, filmmakers and
playwrights like their Holocaust survivors tortured, tyrannical and
delusional - often all at the same time. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- July 8, 1999 -- CARS-BEETLE-BOOKS, 07-08 --
Three books, new and re-released, pay tribute to the world's
favorite car, the Volkswagen Beetle. The books cover much of the
same territory, although ``The Volkswagen Bug Book'' is more
text-heavy and comprehensive. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 11 -- MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-2, 07-08 -- Britney Spears is not just
a superkid; she's obedient, too, singing the songs and hitting the
marks that are choreographed for her. This season belongs to the
kiddie-pop brigades. Applause is passe; the reaction most eagerly
sought by pop culture right now, from music to television to
movies, is a high-pitched squeal from a mob of young girls. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- July 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JULY 11 -- MUSIC-KIDDIE-POP-1, 07-08 -- Young fans at Zootopia '99,
a radio-station charity concert at the Continental Airlines Arena
in East Rutherford last month. They are the kiddie-pop brigades and
this season belongs to them. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 07-08 --
Ruthie Henshall, who joined the cast of ``Chicago'' as Velma last
month. The role, her Broadway debut, is a new one for Ms. Henshall,
even if the show isn't; in 1997, she starred as Velma's foil, Roxie
Hart, in the London production of ``Chicago.'' Why the switch?
``I'd had enough of Roxie,'' she says. ``But to do Velma? It was
just too tempting.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MODENA, Italy -- July 8, 1999 --
DESTRUCTION-THEATER-REVIEW, 07-08 -- A scene from ``The Days
Before: Death, Destruction and Detroit III,'' a new work by Robert
Wilson. There's a jagged, disjunctive feeling to ``The Days
Before'' that causes you to step back and assess coolly. Wilson's
intuitive work, which he insists is not intellectual, suffers from
this kind of scrutiny; what you want it to do is sweep you away.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 8, 1999 -- VANYA-THEATER-REVIEW, 07-08
-- Niall Buggy has the title role, and Donna Dent plays Sonya in
Brian Friel's adaptation of ``Uncle Vanya.'' This frosty ``Vanya,''
with a fresh translation by Ireland's eminent playwright Brian
Friel, is not destined to be a crowd pleaser. The passions simmer
so faintly, you can hardly can tell when its pilot light is on.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GREENVILLE, S.C. -- July 8, 1999 -- PLAYBOY-MODEL-NYTR,
07-08 -- Brooke Richards trys a firefighters hat and coat as Martin
Williams of the Wade Hampton Fire Department looks on. Richards, of
nearby Walhalla, is the cover model featured in the July issue of
Playboy magazine. (Tim Kimzey/Spartanburg S.C. Herald-Journal)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) GREENVILLE, S.C. -- July 8, 1999 -- PLAYBOY-MODEL-NYTR,
07-08 -- Brooke Richards trys a firefighters hat and coat as Martin
Williams of the Wade Hampton Fire Department looks on. Richards, of
nearby Walhalla, is the cover model featured in the July issue of
Playboy magazine. (Tim Kimzey/Spartanburg S.C. Herald-Journal)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HAMBURG, Germany (top) RENTON, Wash. -- July 8, 1999 --
AIRBUS-OUTLOOK, 07-08 -- Airbus Industrie's A319's and A321's
undergo final assembly at the Daimler-Benz Aerospace Airbus factory
in this 1998 photo. At bottom, 737-800's are assembled for Royal
Air Moroc in April of last year. Compared to Boeing's busy assembly
line, the atmosphere at the Airbus plant is almost ghost-like. The
eerie quiet however is a reflection of the consortium's
decentralized production and surprisingly efficient operation. The
contrast is just one of the many apparent contradictions about
Airbus that has altered expectations about its future prospects and
seriously vexed Boeing. (Airbus Industries/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEVADA CITY, Calif -- July 8, 1999 --
GOLD-COUNTRY-2-LADN, 07-08 -- Nevada City, perched on a wooded
hillside in the northern reaches of California's Gold Country, has
been faithfully restored. California's Gold Rush country, which
stretches out along the Sierra Nevada foothills east of Sacramento,
continues to hold appeal as a travel destination. It is an easily
romanticized era of the state's history, all the more so this
summer, during the 150th anniversary of the 49ers' frantic stampede
to the gold fields. (Eric Noland/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEAR SONORA, Calif -- July 8, 1999 --
GOLD-COUNTRY-1-LADN, 07-08 -- A young visitor to Columbia State
Historic Park checks for gold in a pan. The park features a
restored mining town with many working shops and these series of
wooden troughs, some of them ``salted'' with gold flakes so kids
can gently swish water and sand in a tin pan, in hopes that the
heavier gold will separate toward the edge, like shells on a beach.
(Eric Noland/Los Angeles Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON, Mass. -- July 8, 1999 -- IMMIGRANTS-VALUES-BOS,
07-08 -- Wenjie Qin helps her son Yening, 11, and Yelun,
background, pack for their trip to Tennessee. Like millions before
her, Qin came to America to taste the fruits of liberty. But when
Qin watches her sons head off to school in their Lee jeans and
Nikes, she worries they are taking the freedom of America in
directions that she never wanted or anticipated. The story of two
generations of immigrant families is a bittersweet tale of changing
values and expectations and is also the story of the United States
and what it means to be an American living on the edge of the
millennium. (Suzanne Kreiter/Boston Globe Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- July 8, 1999 -- BBO-ALLSTAR-IMPACT-BOS, 07-08
-- The Hynes Veterans Memorial Convention Center on Wednesday.
Major League Baseball's All-Star Game opens with the John Hancock
FanFest at the Hynes on Friday. Companies are striving to promote
the game and the events surrounding it, hoping to polish their
images by association. Tourism officials see a promotional bonanza
with an impact long after the last baseball fan leaves. And
observers say the huge event will help the Red Sox demonstrate why
they need a new stadium. (Frank/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
