<SLUG> BC-LIBERIA-FIRST-LADY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERIA'S FIRST LADY SEEKS AID FOR NATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Vials of saline, unopened rolls of gauze,
unused bed pads and an excess of sterile gloves and masks could
have all been tossed in the trash at the Vencor care facility in
nearby Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Amy Tinney, a respiratory therapist, gathered the
supplies and donated them to Liberia for use by doctors treating a
population debilitated after a bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian first lady Jewel Howard-Taylor encouraged individual
efforts such as Tinney's on Thursday during a breakfast at the Fort
Worth International Center. More than 100 people attended the
event, including several city and state elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to strengthen, renew and open up lines of
positive communication with our friends and our brothers and
sisters from around the world,'' said Howard-Taylor, who is on a
four-day visit to Fort Worth-Dallas. ``We're struggling to create
an enabling environment of positive, sustainable growth and
development in our nation, for all Liberians.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard-Taylor was invited to Fort Worth by Global 2000, a
year-old nonprofit organization created to help rebuild the West
African nation after the civil war ended in 1996. Liberian
President Charles Taylor began the war after he launched a coup in
1989 to overthrow former dictator Samuel Doe. About 200,000 people
died and half of the country's population of 2.6 million people
were left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Howard-Taylor urged her audience to help Liberia find long-term
solutions to its problems by investing in its natural resources,
providing supplies to schools and training students at Liberian
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although the war is over, Liberians are still suffering,
Howard-Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Liberian children, many of whom have gone a decade without
education, sell candy and popcorn on the street to earn income for
their families, hospitals operate without electricity, and some
schools have untreated water and old textbooks, Howard-Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The civil crisis produced a mass destruction of all of our
infrastructure _ social, economic and civil,'' she said. ``Our
government is struggling to rehabilitate.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
