<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-POLLUTION09-COX     07-08 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLLUTION09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin mayor urges state to enforce new fuel laws in 2000
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mayor Kirk Watson says he hopes the state will
put its new rules for cleaner gasoline into effect for Austin as
soon as May 2000, and not wait until 2004 as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The cleaner gasoline would mean cleaner air but also slightly
higher prices at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner we can do those things that make good sense, the
better off we're going to be from a health standpoint and from an
economic standpoint,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission last week
adopted new rules affecting a 95-county area that includes much of
the eastern half of the state.
</P>
<P>
   A key provision of the new rules _ to reduce sulfur levels in
gasoline by about half _ won't take effect until Jan. 1, 2004.
Reducing sulfur in gasoline enables a catalytic converter to remove
pollutants from engine exhaust more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of how much the new rules would add to the price of
gasoline range from two-tenths of a cent to 3 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The city councils of Austin and San Antonio, as well as the
Environmental Defense Fund, had urged the commission to require the
lower sulfur levels as soon as 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, increasing air pollution in the two cities has
threatened to tip them into noncompliance with federal clean air
rules, as has happened in Dallas and Houston. Cities in
noncompliance have to take steps to reduce pollution, such as
regularly checking their vehicles' pollution equipment and imposing
emission restrictions on plant expansions or new construction.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules allow individual cities and counties with at least
200,000 people to ask the commission to allow implementation sooner
than 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Watson said he hoped the commission would apply the new rule
sooner in Austin, as the city requested.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is still studying just what process it must
follow to approve the requests from Austin and San Antonio, said
Patrick Crimmins, a commission spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision in the new rules requires that gasoline sold
in the hottest months of the year, between May 1 and Oct. 1 of each
year starting next year, evaporate less easily.
</P>
<P>
   Koch Industries Inc., whose Corpus Christi refinery provides
more than 90 percent of the gasoline sold in the
Austin-metropolitan area, already complies with the new evaporation
standard, said Jay Rosser, a company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Koch has said, however, that the state should defer to the
federal Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is considering its own rules on reducing sulfur that,
if adopted, would override the new state rules.
</P>
<P>
   The new state rules on sulfur don't take effect until 2004 to
give refiners plenty of time to upgrade their refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's new rules take no position on the use of a
chemical additive, MBTE, or methyl-tertiary-butyl-ether, by
refiners to reduce engine ``knock,'' a problem that arises from the
process of removing sulfur as gasoline is refined from crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   MBTE _ used in about 15 percent of the gasoline sold in the
Austin area _ is highly soluble in water and is suspected of
causing cancer and other health-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   East Texas local governments, most of which are not facing the
same imminent air pollution problems as the state's larger cities,
had criticized the proposed gasoline rules, saying they could lead
to increased MBTE contamination of their water resources.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Environmental Defense Fund and the Sierra Club
applauded the new rules, but said the state needs to do more to
clean up its air.
</P>
<P>
   Mark MacLeod, a spokesman for the defense fund, said the state
should have ordered an even larger reduction in sulfur. And Neil
Carman, clean air director for the Lone Star chapter of the Sierra
Club, said MBTE should have been banned, but that ``Texas
refineries and chemical plants are the biggest producers of MBTE in
the nation, so they decided to dodge that bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
