r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GRIFFEY-LADN-(SLA     07-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GRIFFEY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S MOST EXCITING PLAYER VISITS L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There is no greater endorsement for interleague
play than Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a Yankees-Mets series, or Cubs-White Sox, or, for sure,
Dodgers-Angels. Not this year, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It's Ken Griffey Jr. or, simply, Junior _ as he's called by his
Seattle Mariners teammates _ who is arguably the best player in the
game but someone pretty well tucked away in the Great Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   His national exposure is largely restricted to a few at-bats
every year in the All-Star Game, maybe nightly highlight clips on
ESPN, or a flock of television commercials. He has been in two
division playoff series and one championship series but no World
Series so far.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he's well known in American League circles, where for
the fifth time he was the leading AL vote-getter for the All-Star
Game. The National League? That's Mark McGwire-Sammy Sosa country.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until the advent of interleague play, a novel tinkering
of the schedule that offers select matches between the two leagues
NL West vs. AL West, for example. That has allowed Griffey's
exposure to widen a little. And, clearly, he's the draw, not the
Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last year, when Seattle played an interleague
series against the expansion Diamondbacks in Arizona _ where the
Mariners hold spring training _ he was roundly booed when he came
to bat for the first time. When he walked, more boos, only this
time they were aimed at the Arizona pitcher, not Griffey. He was
wearing the other team's uniform, perhaps, but the fans didn't pay
to watch Griffey walk.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it'll be that way this weekend at Dodger Stadium, where
Griffey will perform for the first time in two years. Promos for
the series have a clear message: ``Come see Ken Griffey Jr. . . .
and the Seattle Mariners.''
</P>
<P>
   Advance sales for the three-game series which begins tonight at
7:10, the final series before the All-Star break, have picked up
noticeably, according to the Dodgers' ticket office. And that's
particularly interesting.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier interleague series at Dodger Stadium involving the
Texas Rangers, the first-place team in the AL West, an outfit with
such bona fide stars as two-time AL Most Valuable Player Juan
Gonzalez and All-Star catcher Ivan ``Pudge'' Rodriguez, drew fewer
than 30,000 fans the first two games. The third, on free-towel
night, lured more than 45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's an indictment of the Southern California sports
fan. Towels, not Pudge, bring 'em in. Or maybe they were merely
awaiting Junior's arrival. If so, it's no surprise to Lou Piniella,
the Seattle manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this,'' Piniella was saying the other evening at Edison
International Field, where the Mariners were playing the Angels,
``I certainly enjoy watching him play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an outstanding player, very graceful,'' Piniella went on.
``He's been in the (AL) more than 10 years now. He knows the
pitchers. He has great speed in his hands to make the plays. He
takes pride in it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how long he wants to stay and if he stays
healthy, he has the ability to challenge some really big records.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest, of course, would be Henry Aaron's career home run
record of 755, unattainable in the eyes of many. Yet Griffey passed
the halfway point on Monday night at Anaheim, when he hit the 378th
homer of his career.
</P>
<P>
   It's often said that if anyone could overtake Aaron, it would be
Griffey, who hit 56 homers each of his last two seasons, has
averaged better than 49 homers four of the past five years, has 28
this year and doesn't even turn 30 until November.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Griffey isn't one of those doing the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here a while. . . . I've been in the league 11
years,'' he said to a group of reporters in the visitors clubhouse
at Edison Field. ``If you look ahead too far, you can get into
trouble. This game is humbling enough. One day you're hitting .400,
got 60 home runs . . . the next you're hitting .167.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, besides, I'm a quiet guy. I kind of sneak in and out of
the clubhouse. I don't have a lot to say about myself. I don't
believe in putting myself above my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play, whether it's good or bad, is just one more
thing for the radio sports-talk shows to hash over. But this week,
it's definitely good for Ken Griffey Jr. It's three games in
Anaheim, then three this weekend at Dodger Stadium. An entire week
on the road without climbing aboard an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of flying for us,'' acknowledged Griffey, who
will be on another long, late-night flight after Sunday game, bound
for Boston and his 10th All-Star Game. ``Anywhere we go, it's a
long flight. We fly more than anybody else in major-league
baseball. We have the least rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, then, what Junior might be able to accomplish if he all
the shuteye he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if could compare Griffey with any of the other greats of
the game, Piniella smiled, shook his head and said, ``No. Junior
has his own unique style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
