<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMODITIES-MARKETPLA     07-08 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMODITIES-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LED BY OIL, KEY COMMODITY PRICES CLIMB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Australia, Germany, Canada)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prices of key commodities, whose decline helped
restrain inflation the last few years, are climbing again.
</P>
<P>
   Oil is leading the charge. Crude has been flirting with $20 a
barrel this week, and financial analysts expect it to pass that
benchmark easily. Some see $25 a barrel by the end of the year, a
further increase of 25 percent. The price has jumped 73 percent
from its low point of the year, $11.37, reached in February.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prices of some other important commodities for
industrial uses are staging small rallies. Copper has risen 15
percent this year while aluminum has gained 12.8 percent, nickel
44.1 percent and zinc 20.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the lows behind us in March,'' said Ted Arnold,
minerals strategist at Hamburg Metals Division of Prudential-Bache
Ltd. in London. This rebound has not spread to agricultural
commodities, however, which continue to slump.
</P>
<P>
   One factor in the industrial commodity rebound, analysts say, is
a revival in many of the world's economies from the global
financial crisis that began in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data for world economic growth suggest that rates are going to
be higher than thought just a few months ago,'' said Michael
Rothman, senior energy analyst at Merrill Lynch. ``In the first
year of a recovery there is always a rise in demand for copper and
other base metals.''
</P>
<P>
   But some other factors have also pushed up commodity prices and
will continue to put pressure on the market in the months ahead.
For example, the rally in copper in the last month has been abetted
by a series of announcements about production cutbacks. Asarco is
reducing its copper mine output by 7 percent. Phelps Dodge Corp. is
trimming production by 8 percent, while Broken Hill Proprietary of
Australia will shut all its mines in the United States and reduce
global production by 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some other influences will probably be temporary. Gasoline
prices jumped to a 19-month high on Wednesday after Sunoco said a
power failure had closed the Point Breeze unit, which normally
produces 130,000 barrels a day, at its Philadelphia refinery for a
week. Copper jumped 3 percent on Wednesday because of speculation
that Canadian workers would strike at Falconbridge's metallurgical
division in Ontario. When the strike was called Thursday, copper
slipped four tenths of a cent to 77.80 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   For oil, which closed at $19.71 a barrel for August delivery
Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the improved outlook
can be directly linked to the success of the OPEC countries in
maintaining production cutbacks. While the price of oil surged
after the countries reached an agreement in March to reduce
production, many analysts questioned whether the parties would
adhere to the terms.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman of Merrill Lynch said that oil analysts were expecting
70 percent compliance. But compliance was 93 percent in May, he
said. (Analysts use different measures, but their compliance
estimates were clustered around 90 percent.) The confirmation of
that unity was what was needed to get oil's second 1999 rally
going. The price had fallen as low as $16.34 a barrel June 1 after
peaking at $18.98 May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman predicts oil could end the year as high as $22 a barrel,
although he adds there could be a selloff between now and $22.
Frederick P. Leuffer, the senior energy analyst at Bear Stearns &AMP;
Co., is speaking of a ``shockingly high'' $25 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The compliance of OPEC members and the resulting decline in
inventories of both crude oil and refined petroleum products will
drive the price higher, he said. He estimates that if OPEC
production remains steady at May's 26 million barrels a day,
inventories at the end of this year will be lower than at the end
of 1996, when oil averaged $24.56 a barrel in the fourth quarter
and finished the year just below $26.
</P>
<P>
   American Petroleum Institute reported after the market closed
Wednesday that crude oil inventories dropped 1.92 million barrels
to 327.94 million barrels last week. Gasoline inventories dropped
4.4 million barrels to 216.38 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The oil outlook has changed so quickly that Leuffer still has an
official forecast of $19.50 a barrel in the second half of the
year. But, he said, ``I see a case developing for $25 oil or
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   This jump in oil and other industrial commodities is important
for investors, even though it is not expected to produce any big
jump in consumer prices or inflation over the longer term. Kathryn
Kobe, senior economist at Joel Popkin &AMP; Co. in Washington, said
that the jump in oil prices _ and the resulting surge in gasoline
prices _ has forced her to add about two tenths of one percentage
point to her forecasted gain in the consumer price index this year.
She now expects it to rise 2.4 percent from December to December,
compared with a 1.6 percent increase last year.
</P>
<P>
   That would put inflation back at its pace in 1997. So it is in
no sense an inflationary breakout.
</P>
<P>
   But an outsized jump in just one month could be enough to force
the Federal Reserve to raise its short-term interest rate target
another quarter of a percentage point. The quarter-point increase
that Fed policy makers announced at the end of June was prompted,
in part, by the seven-tenths of one percent surge in consumer
prices in April.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Shepherdson, the chief U.S. economist at High Frequency
Economics, estimates that an average oil price of $21 a barrel this
month would push up gasoline prices to $1.28 a gallon. That would
be enough to produce a five-tenths of one percentage point jump in
the CPI.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer price figure for July will be reported Aug. 17, a
week before the next meeting of Federal Reserve policy makers.
Lawrence Kudlow, chief economist at American Slandia Life Assurance
in Shelton, Conn., said a move of that magnitude would force the
Fed's hand. ``If the CPI jumps up again because of oil or because
of other commodity price increases, they will snug up again,'' he
predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
