<HEADER>
A3720 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2NDTAKE     07-08 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: own funeral.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coelho was brought in as campaign manager to fix the problem of
blurred lines of authority in a top-heavy operation. But it is
unclear how the Eskew hiring will streamline the organizational
chart unless Squier leaves, a step he said he had no intention of
taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my job is,'' Squier said. ``This is way too
important to throw away for some frivolous reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said that when Coelho came to him a month ago, ``I asked
him if he was aware of the tensions and history, and he said,
`Yeah, I'm willing to take that on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Though supremely gracious, serving chevre and an '82 Chateau
Montrose way too fine for a business lunch, along with frittata and
rice salad he had made himself, Squier moaned periodically
throughout the interview: ``Can't we go swimming instead? I despise
this!''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew, for his part, was unruffled. Over a drink _ Evian,
actually _ he said he regretted the bad feelings of his past with
Squier. ``Bob was my mentor and taught me a lot of what I know
about this business,'' he said, ``but I needed to establish myself
on my own. If I had it to do over, I'd leave differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his hiring, he said, neither he not Gore have rehashed old
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I decided to come on, he said, `Welcome aboard,' and
`Get to work,''' Eskew said.
</P>
<P>
   On their difference of opinion over his work for tobacco
companies, he said: ``I can't imagine we'd have much to say. I'm
here to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew met Gore when both worked on The Nashville Tennessean
newspaper in the 1970s, but they did not know each other well. They
had a lot in common, including Tennessee roots and Washington
childhoods. Eskew, whose father was an orthodontist, went to
Sidwell Friends, Phillips Exeter Academy and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Squier, who comes from Minnesota, was on his own from a young
age, losing his mother to breast cancer when he was 12 and his
father to cancer, too, on the day he graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost two parents who were heavy smokers to cancer. I found
my mother,'' he said, explaining why Eskew's work for tobacco
companies got under his skin.
</P>
<P>
   He was a TV producer brought into politics by President Johnson
_ two days before Johnson decided not to run for another term. But
he stayed on to work for Hubert Humphrey, and has worked for
Democrats ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Squier and Eskew, then 24, met while working on Elizabeth
Holtzman's 1980 senatorial campaign. Later, it was Eskew who
brought in Gore's business, and the three became personal friends.
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said he hopes the reunion of the three will work. ``I
don't recall the '96 Clinton campaign being particularly
harmonious, but they bucked up and did it, and that's what we're
going to do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
