<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN AUDIT PINPOINTS BANK CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Negligent government regulators allowed corrupt
practices to drive Mexico's banking system into insolvency, forcing
a financial rescue that has cost Mexican taxpayers $80 billion over
the past four years, say congressmen who have seen an auditor's
report to be released next week.
</P>
<P>
   Ending a six-month review of the government's handling of the
banking crisis requested by the Mexican Congress, the report
criticizes both shoddy oversight by government agencies assigned to
regulate the banking system before the disaster began in 1995 as
well as corruption and insider-dealing in the bailout that has
followed, the congressmen said.
</P>
<P>
   The audit by Michael W. Mackey, a Toronto auditor who
coordinated five Mexican accounting firms, looked into the
government's takeover of 13 collapsing banks and financial rescue
operations in a dozen others. The government intervened to avoid a
general financial meltdown as soaring interest rates bankrupted
thousands of businesses after the devaluation of the peso in
December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its apparently sweeping criticisms of President Ernesto
Zedillo's administration, the report has angered opposition leaders
because it will not include details about what they believe were
illegal donations by some banks to Zedillo's Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, during the 1994 election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Leftist and independent legislators are accusing the
pro-business National Action Party of cutting a deal with the
government to stifle further investigation, bringing the audit to a
quick conclusion to avoid prolonging the country's financial
turmoil. The government, citing secrecy provisions of the banking
laws, has refused to turn over documents from a bank that made
apparently illegal donations to Zedillo's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're covering this up,'' Pablo Gomez, the legislative
coordinator of the center-left Party of the Democratic Revolution,
or PRD, said of National Action's decision to cooperate with the
government in ending the audit. ``We're not going to become
accomplices to this and we urge National Action to avoid a cover-up
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fauzi Hamdan Amad, the National Action deputy who has overseen
Mackey's work and is one of several lawmakers who reviewed the
report this week, said further confrontation with the government
over the audits could slow down efforts to rescue the financial
system, harming the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's clear in the report is the highly relaxed, even
negligent performance by the government authorities,'' Hamdan said.
``They permitted a series of hot spots that were highly damaging
the system to emerge, without ordering corrective measures.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mackey report will criticize government authorities for
allowing Mexican banks to issue thousands of imprudent loans and
for disguising the banks' ailing financial health by doctoring the
books, Hamdan said in a radio interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Mexican banks that collapsed had extended large
loans to their own executives and stockholders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mackey's report also concludes that once the financial rescue
got under way in 1995, authorities were overly generous in
negotiating the purchase of bad-loan portfolios from some banks,
said Marcelo Ebrard, another congressman who read parts of the
auditor's report.
</P>
<P>
   Other banks that had been poorly managed should have been
allowed to go bankrupt rather than be rescued, the report
concludes, Ebrard said.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress, in which Zedillo's governing party has slightly
fewer than half the seats and opposition parties led by National
Action and the PRD have a thin majority, debated for much of last
year about how vigorously to pursue investigations of wrongdoing by
bankers and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In December, PRI and National Action lawmakers passed a law that
substituted a new banking rescue agency for the one that executed
the flawed bailout. The law also empowered Mackey to carry out his
audit.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mackey's jobs was to identify ``reportable operations,''
that is, bad-loan portfolios issued by banks in illegal or
particularly irresponsible ways that were subsequently purchased by
the government. Such questionable or corrupt rescue transactions
identified by Mackey are to be nullified, with bank shareholders
absorbing the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdan said Mackey had identified ``an important number'' of
reportable operations, but he declined to say how much they
totaled.
</P>
<P>
   Many Mexicans believed there would be no more bank bailouts
after the establishment of the new agency. But authorities have
identified two banks, Grupo Financiero Serfin and Bancrecer. that
will need to be rescued with huge new injections of cash. The
government announced Thursday its formal takeover of Serfin, at a
cost of $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2150EDT &QL; 
