<HEADER>
A3722 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDRENS-BOOK-SFCHRO     07-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDRENS-BOOK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AMAZON.COM CONJURES UP BATTLE OVER BRITISH BOOK  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Amazon.com was stirring things up again Thursday, but not by
discounting best-sellers or losing lots of money.
<P>
   This time, the leading online bookseller's British site was
offering American readers first crack at the latest installment in
the hugely popular Harry Potter series of children's books by
author J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   The series' British publisher, Bloomsbury Children's Books, has
sold U.S publication rights to New York's Scholastic Inc., which
suddenly found itself losing potential customers to its British
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, brick-and-mortar booksellers in America, which
had been looking ahead to another windfall in sales from the third
Harry Potter book, were crying foul that readers could get their
hands on the latest installment a full two months ahead of the U.S.
publication date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's illegal for Amazon to import it and resell it,'' said
Margaret Simpson, a children's book specialist at A Clean
Well-Lighted Place for Books in San Francisco. ``It wouldn't be
legal for someone to travel to Europe and then resell the book.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. edition of ``Harry Potter and the Prison of Azkaban''
isn't scheduled to appear until September 8. But it was flying off
the shelves Thursday in London, and quickly jumped to the top of
the sales chart at Amazon's British site.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's U.S. site is taking orders for the book, but it's not
yet selling it or advertising that it's available on its British
site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Net-smart shoppers quickly figured out that the latest
Harry Potter was up for grabs at www.amazon.co.uk, and jumped at
the chance to take advantage of this latest example of the global
economy in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is shadowy,'' said Bill Petrocelli, a lawyer and
co-owner of Book Passage in Corte Madera. ``These are not pirated
editions. These are legally published editions.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that if Amazon is making the British edition available
to American readers, his own shop will work to stock the book as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is having a serious effect on the whole
publication process, and this is just one aspect of it,''
Petrocelli said.
</P>
<P>
   For those late to the Harry Potter phenomenon, the books center
on the bespectacled young hero's magical exploits while studying at
Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   The first two books in the projected seven-book series occupy
the No. 3 and No. 6 spots on the New York Times Best-seller list,
and booksellers say it is extremely rare for a couple of kids'
books to be on the list simultaneously, especially two from the
same author.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of CHILDREN (99560 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  About 1.7 million Harry Potter books have been sold in the United
States, according to Scholastic Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For Amazon, bringing young Harry to his American fans in a
timely fashion is not a matter of turning a quick buck (or pound).
It is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an example of people getting the book they want when
they want it,'' said Bill Curry, a spokesman for the online
bookseller. ``The world is going to have to change to keep up with
the Internet. The Internet makes the notion of territorial rights
archaic.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason that Amazon has not broken any laws, he explained, is
because U.S. copyright statutes allow for citizens who travel
abroad to purchase and bring home a single copy of a
foreign-published book ``for personal use.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop at Heathrow and buy a book and bring it with you,
you've done nothing wrong,'' Curry said. ``When Amazon.co.uk ships
it you, we've done nothing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's British site notes that buyers with a U.S. address can
only order a single copy.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the cybershopper has not in fact set foot in
Britain, Curry pointed out that Amazon's British servers are on
British soil, so, in that sense, you have made your purchase
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of the series is so great that Scholastic has
been forced to advance its publication dates for each successive
book.
</P>
<P>
   A full year went by from the time the first Harry Potter book
debuted in London to when it arrived on this side of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   For the second book, Scholastic narrowed that gap to seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest book, the publisher cut the difference down to a
mere two months. But with Amazon U.K. already making copies
available in the United States, Scholastic will offer up the fourth
book at the same time it debuts in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arthur Levine, who edits the Harry Potter books for
Scholastic's Arthur A. Levine Books imprint, insists that American
readers benefit from displaying a measure of patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been translated for an American audience,'' he said.
``I worked with the author to make sure the American reader has the
same experience as the British reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, young Harry dons a ``jumper'' in the British edition,
while here in the New World he's content to toss on a sweater.
</P>
<P>
   In England, the first book in the series was titled ``Harry
Potter and the Philosopher's Stone,'' while American readers,
unaccustomed to philosophy in their children's books, were treated
to ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be an understatement to say that Mike Kelly's
12-year-old daughter, Alta, enjoys the Harry Potter children's
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``She devoured them,'' the Albany attorney said. ``She read the
last one in one night. It's a big deal among kids her age.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that his daughter is expecting the third Harry Potter
adventure in September, so he has no plans to point and click his
way to an advance peek at the text.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the kid next door shows up at summer camp with it, I'd
go online and get one,'' Kelly admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
