<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retired Gingrich may be busier than ever
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich's eclectic pursuits take him to some
interesting places, like a northern California resort that hosted
an Independence Day weekend clinic on weight and stress reduction.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no mere effort by the former speaker to slim down.
The time spent at the Claremont Resort and Spa was for scholarly
study.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, a senior fellow at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute in Washington, is researching the future of
health care in the information age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to learn a program is to participate in it
yourself,'' said Gingrich spokesman Mike Shields, rejecting the
idea that Gingrich attended the clinic for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   No longer constrained by the practical politics of running the
House of Representatives or the weight of being second in line to
the presidency after Al Gore, Gingrich is pursuing his interests
and getting paid at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's recent undertakings include signing on as a
consultant with Freddie Mac, the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
The 20-year veteran of Congress will provide general advice about
legislation, but he will not be a lobbyist, Freddie Mac spokeswoman
Sharon McHale said.
</P>
<P>
   As a nonlobbyist working on legislative matters, Gingrich does
not have to disclose what he is being paid or worry about running
afoul of House ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-speaker is expected to soon debut as a radio commentator.
Los Angeles-based Premiere Radio Networks, the same folks who bring
listeners Rush Limbaugh and Dr. Laura Schlessinger, hopes to
announce soon that Gingrich will do regular spots on topics of his
choosing, spokeswoman Jennifer Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   He has formed a consulting concern, the Gingrich Group, which
has entered into a ``strategic alliance'' with the accounting giant
PriceWaterhouse Coopers, said PriceWaterhouse spokesman Dave
Nestor. There are no financial ties, Nestor said.
</P>
<P>
   While still claiming Marietta as his home base, Gingrich also
has signed on as a senior fellow at Stanford University's Hoover
Institution, joined the board of the buyout firm Forstmann, Little
&AMP; Co. and traveled the country making speeches for reportedly up to
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The frenetic pace is vintage Gingrich, part of what alternately
attracted and frustrated his congressional colleagues. Now, though,
the time is all his.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got a person like Gingrich who's got the kind of
mind he has, for all its good and all its ill, anybody who thinks
they can use his eclectic mind for their benefit, it makes some
sense to latch onto it,'' said Rich Galen, a longtime Gingrich ally
who is executive director of GOPAC, Gingrich's onetime political
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The striking aspect of Gingrich's schedule is that he has
managed to stay somewhat in the public eye while resolutely
rebuffing all interview requests. Gingrich has not granted a formal
interview since leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where he wants to learn how to do new
things,'' Galen said. ``He told me shortly after the turn of the
year that he spent two days with the senior leadership of a major
corporation to learn how deal with global challenges. I asked him
if he got paid and he said, `No, I was learning how to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Learning about preventive health measures is what took Gingrich
to the Claremont, a landmark hotel in the hills above San Francisco
Bay, said David Wallace, spokesman for the American Enterprise
Institute. The program was run by Dr. Dean Ornish, who developed a
regimen of exercise, diet and stress reduction to ward off heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich brought his daughter, Kathy Lubbers, who suffers from
rheumatoid arthritis, to see whether she might benefit from
Ornish's program, Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   The poolside clinic included a meal of veggie burgers, tofu hot
dogs, fat-free coleslaw and soy-based ice cream, the San Francisco
Chronicle reported.
</P>
<P>
   Ornish has worked with President Clinton on his diet and
consulted with White House chefs. He directs the Preventive
Medicine Research Institute in Sausalito, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
