A3726 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRENCH-STYLE-SIDEBAR-     07-08 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-STYLE-SIDEBAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
HOW TO ACQUIRE THE LOOK &HT;    w/FRENCH STYLE MAINBAR &HT;    By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) While the subject of what French style is wanders all
over the map, the guidelines on how to acquire it are more
specific.
</P>
<P>
   First, study French. Not only the language but the style. June
Rives, owner of June Rives Public Relations in Houston, said she
learns a lot about French style from magazines such as the French
Marie Claire and Elle, ``but obviously, direct observation is
best.'' For example, last October when she was in Paris, every
woman was in black leather _ ``just like in L.A.'' Visit antiques
shops to learn about French styles, museums to see French art and
foreign movies to see the French lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Keep up on fashion. While the French are not label-conscious _
you won't see designer names on their clothing or a French woman in
Chanel's big double-C jewelry _ they are very aware of fashion. For
example, the French are currently gaga over American Michael Kors'
designs for the French line Celine, and the newest Paris Gap is
opening on the Champs lyses.
</P>
<P>
   Be daring. Most fashion finds at French flea markets tend to the
exotic _ beads, paisley shawls, embroidered jackets, blouses,
skirts and shawls. These are often great for party or evening wear.
Try an embroidered Indian jacket with a pair of good white or black
pants, adding a shawl, dangling earrings or cuff bracelets. Sheer,
beaded dresses from the 1920s are perfect evening attire worn over
matching slips. Watch out for vintage bags that tend to look dated.
</P>
<P>
   Age gracefully. One reason Parisian women appear to age well is
because, surrounded by designers, they stay current on fashion,
said Gayla Bentley, a fashion consultant who also leads shopping
and style tours to Paris. ``People of all economic levels have more
of an understanding and respect for designers than in America, even
if they can't afford those clothes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Walk more. Europeans walk a lot, so despite the rich sauces, the
olive oil and the wine, many don't find it hard to stay fit and
trim.
</P>
<P>
   Forget faux body parts. ``In the United States,'' said Bentley,
``women spend a lot of money having fake nails put on, but no one
does that in France. They spend money on skin care, not nails or
boobs. Everything is real. And at St. Tropez and the Riviera, women
of all ages are going topless and proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dress simply but chicly. French women almost never go over the
top, and while they buy less, they buy the best they can afford. If
they cannot afford the very best, they visit it often to
familiarize themselves with what makes it best. Then they buy the
best similar styles they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Eschew fashion fakes. Wearing the real thing is important to the
French. They will never carry a fake Louis Vuitton or a fake Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   Don't overdo. Especially accessories. One good piece of jewelry
or one Herms scarf with an Herms or Louis Vuitton bag does the
French trick.
</P>
<P>
   Make up naturally. Most French women are minimalists in their
makeup and, with well-cared-for skin, they can afford to be. You
will never see the typical French woman in extreme rouge or eye
makeup. Their hair is simple, in ponytails or chignons or cropped
short.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule skin care. French women take very good care of their
skin, said Laura Mercier, whose cosmetic line will be joined by a
new line of skin-care products in September. The French learn skin
care at a very early age and usually avoid tanning.
</P>
<P>
   Wear perfume. But wear it sparingly. A pleasing fragrance is
like a petit cadeau (a little gift) that one person offers another.
Most women enjoy catching a whiff of men's fragrances as much as
men enjoy women in perfume.
</P>
<P>
   Iron things. The French often iron their underwear, socks and
jeans. Why? Because clothes dryers are not as common in France as
in the States, so ironing softens fabrics. The coincidental removal
of wrinkles gives the French a more polished look.
</P>
<P>
   Don't overdecorate. Europeans in general avoid the decorated
look in homes, preferring an eclectic mix of antiques and
contemporary furnishings. The French would never have an entire
house of French provincial or Louis the anything.
</P>
<P>
   Do the unexpected. Paint your bathroom yellow, your claw-footed
tub aubergine, and hang family portraits on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Acquire heritage. If you did not inherit antique furnishings,
buy some. The French are famous for haunting flea markets,
especially the Marche aux Puces, where one can find everything from
tassels to tinsel. Even in a thoroughly modern loft, a single
antique chair or table can lend credence.
</P>
<P>
   Rethink country. With the American penchant for casualness,
country styles have lingered for decades now. For a more
sophisticated look, try country French. You know the look _ olive
jars, lots of natural woods, baskets, lace curtains, blue, white
and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Don't dust. Although Paris apartments owned by Americans are
immaculate, clean enough to eat off the floors, the French are not
allergic to a little dust. It gives a patina of age to newer
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Develop attitude. If, as Mercier said, French women are full of
complexes and insecurities, they cover it well. The secret is in
being the best you can be. Look your best and don't worry.
</P>
<P>
   Get a dog. And train it. Dogs are everywhere in France, almost
accessories, said Bentley, but they are well-behaved and treated
with respect.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
