<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-TRUCKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARGENTINE TRUCKERS END STRIKE AFTER GOVERNMENT RETREATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Tens of thousands of truck drivers
halted a three-day-old nationwide strike Thursday after the lower
house of Congress voted to postpone a new vehicle tax intended to
cover a $100-a-month raise for public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers and shopkeepers, who were beginning to suffer
shortages of milk and other perishable foods, were relieved by the
announcement that the strike was over, as were business leaders and
economists, who feared the strike could worsen an already deepening
recession.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's retreat under pressure by an interest group
underscored the weakness of President Carlos Saul Menem as his
second term winds down. It also raised questions about how the
government would pay for the $700 million raise for teachers when
its deficit is widening to levels that are alarming international
bankers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   The government's estimated fiscal deficit, currently projected
at $5.1 billion by year's end, has already been raised three times
this year and is approximately double the total originally agreed
to in negotiations with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by the Chamber of Deputies late Wednesday night gives
the vehicle owners until Nov. 15 to pay what amounts to a tax of 1
to 1.5 percent of the value of their vehicles. That effectively
puts off the confrontation between the truck owners and government
until two weeks after the coming presidential election, and
potentially will create a major headache for the next president,
who is to take office in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is we have stopped the loss of production
peacefully,'' Defense Minister Jorge Dominguez told reporters. He
emphasized that the vehicle tax had not been rolled back, but
simply delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to go along with the Chamber and approve
the tax suspension next week. Some members of the Alianza
opposition coalition charged that the congressional action
represented a dangerous surrender to a tax revolt by a special
interest group that was likely to produce more revolts, but the
opposition is divided on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Menem's aides used threatening language against the strikers all
week, and on Tuesday the Cabinet even discussed the possibility of
enacting a state of siege that would suspend constitutional
guarantees and give the military and police broad powers to arrest
striking truck drivers and seize their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Menem signed a decree calling the strike illegal, and warned
that he would send Congress legislation declaring a state of siege.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed state of siege was attacked by the Alianza
presidential candidate, Fernando de la Rua, the mayor of Buenos
Aires, and by officials in Menem's own Justicialist Party. Congress
would most likely have rejected any presidential call for emergency
powers.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials backed off their tough talk on Wednesday
afternoon after the Buenos Aires governor, Eduardo Duhalde, the
Justicialist presidential candidate, said publicly, ``There aren't
any difficulties serious enough to justify declaring a state of
siege.''
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde worked behind the scenes to cobble together a compromise
solution in the Chamber of Deputies that would satisfy the demands
of the truckers without rolling back the tax altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, a congressional committee voted to cut back
the tax by 70 percent for the drivers while allowing taxpayers who
have already paid the tax on their trucks, automobiles, boats and
planes to deduct the amount from their next income tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Duhalde maneuvered to shelve the bill in an act that showed
that the Buenos Aires governor had taken control of the governing
party's congressional delegation and effectively replaced Menem as
the party's leader.
</P>
<P>
   The two major trucking associations called the strike Monday in
protest against the vehicle tax, and threatened to block the
nation's highways indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The strike caused fuel shortages around the country, and
supermarkets reported they barely had enough supplies for the
coming three-day holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
