<SLUG> BC-SAFEWAY-STOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SAFEWAY STOCK DOWN DESPITE GOOD EARNINGS  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Safeway Inc. stock declined slightly Thursday on
weak sales news, despite earnings that beat estimates.
<P>
   The Pleasanton, Calif., company reported that comparable-store
sales, or sales at locations open at least a year, rose a mere 1.5
percent in the second quarter, which ended June 19. That compares
to a comparable-store increase of 4.1 percent for all of 1998
versus 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shares dropped about $2 over the course of the day but partly
recovered to close at $52.13, down 88 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Comparable-store sales growth ``was not expected to be under 2
percent,'' said Elaine Hahn, president of Hahn Capital Management
in San Francisco, a Safeway investor. ``The top line clearly came
in under analysts' and the company's expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   She blamed the shortfall in part on pricing pressure from
discounters like Wal-Mart. Safeway has also been forced to keep
prices of its private-label Safeway Select merchandise low because
of price cuts by manufacturers of branded merchandise like
breakfast cereal, Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Dominick's stores are also performing worse than expected,
Hahn added.
</P>
<P>
   Total Safeway sales grew 13 percent to $6.3 billion in the
quarter, a gain attributed almost entirely to the acquisition of
Dominick's of Chicago in November.
</P>
<P>
   Net income rose 22 percent to $236.4 million, or 46 cents per
share, compared to analysts' consensus estimate of 44 cents.
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, Safeway reported that gross margins rose to 29.9
percent of sales from 29.01 percent in the second quarter of 1998.
Safeway attributed the improvement to buying efficiency and an
increase in private-label goods as a percentage of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Operating and administrative expenses declined to 22.49 percent
of sales, the 25th consecutive quarter of improvement, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Richardson, an analyst with Pacific Crest Securities,
described Thursday's news as a temporary negative. ``Overall,
Safeway is an extremely strong company,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
