<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION-BANK-SFCHRON &LR;      07-08 1362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-BANK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UNION BANK PLANS AMERICAN-STYLE OVERHAUL, JOB CUTS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO -- Union Bank of California, the largest
Japanese-controlled bank in the United States, is about to go
through a wrenching, American-style reorganization that is expected
to cost more than 1,000 jobs.
<P>
   The initiative, dubbed Mission Excel, is in the final planning
stages and will go to top executives and the bank's board for
approval later this month. The bank expects to announce details to
employees and the public in August, and then put the program into
effect over a 21-month period.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of San Francisco's Union, the second-largest bank
headquartered on the West Coast after Wells Fargo, say the shakeup
will include a mix of cost-cutting and revenue-generating steps.
The aim, they say, is to bring the bank to the fighting trim of its
all-American rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Union spent about 61.5 cents on overhead for every
dollar of revenue brought in, compared to an average of about 59
cents per dollar for other large banks. Mission Excel's goal is to
cut expenses to 55 cents for every dollar of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the decade, as one American bank after another
launched a ``downsizing`` program, Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
Union's Japanese majority owner, vetoed harsh cost-cutting
medicine. The parent company feared harm would be done to employee
and customer morale.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan, the bank was struggling with bad loans amid the
country's financial &LR;   &LR; crisis, so it raised cash by selling part of
its stake to U.S. investors early this year. Those buyers, mainly
big institutions, insisted that the bank take dramatic action to
rein in costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we could commit to them that we would be as efficient
as our peer group, no one would take our stock,'' said Vice
Chairman Robert Walker, who is overseeing the project. That, he
said, gave the bank ``a rare opportunity to impose discipline on
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said the bank will shed up to 15 percent of its
roughly 9,800 full-time positions, mostly through attrition, not
layoffs. ``We expect actual pink slips to amount to less than 5
percent'' of total job cuts, said Vice Chairman Richard Hartnack,
the bank's consumer banking chief.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the job cuts will take place in Southern
California, where Union's workforce is concentrated, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Union vice chairman estimated the bank will cut $2 dollars
of expenses for every additional dollar of revenue raised. But he
said the bank hasn't set specific cost-cutting or revenue targets
for getting to its 55 percent expense-to-revenue goal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect approximately $90 million to $120 million in
annual cost savings, roughly 10 percent of total expenses.
``There's pain involved in the process,'' said Joseph Morford, an
analyst with First Security Van Kasper in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the 1990s, dozens of big American banks _ including
such institutions as old-money Chase Manhattan and nouveau riche
Fleet Financial in the Northeast _ launched ``re-engineering''
programs to juice up profits in the face of slow revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Pains and Gains
</P>
<P>
   Those programs had a mixed track record. Some banks that went
through the process thrived, such as Michigan's Comerica. Others,
such as Pennsylvania's CoreStates, slipped into a vicious circle of
falling morale and slowing business growth, and wound up being
sold.
</P>
<P>
   To skeptics, the re-engineering initiatives amounted to
slash-and-burn job cutbacks under a fancy name.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are processes that sap the strength of the
institution,'' said New York consultant Charles Wendel, a critic of
such programs.
</P>
<P>
   Banks going through reorganizations typically say they will
match job cuts with revenue gains, but the promises often prove
hollow, Wendel said. ``It's a lot easier to fire people than to
implement price increases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Union's initiative doesn't reflect weak performance. Last year,
the bank posted record profits of $466 million and a solid, if not
spectacular, return on equity of 16.39 percent, slightly better
than average.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy Workers
</P>
<P>
   People close to the bank say the shakeup is taking a toll on
employees, especially middle- and senior-level managers who've been
drafted to work on the program and whose jobs may be at risk. Some
staff members have taken to calling the program ``Mission Expel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's had a pretty tough impact on morale,'' said one former
Union manager. ``But the word inside the bank is that they have to
go through with it. They're too top heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Union was created in 1996 following the merger of Bank of Tokyo
and Mitsubishi Bank in Japan. The old Union Bank, which was Bank of
Tokyo's San Francisco subsidiary, then combined with Bank of
California, owned by Mitsubishi, to form Union Bank of California.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese-controlled banks in the United States, which include
Los Angeles's Sanwa Bank California and Tokai Bank of California,
generally avoided such traumatic shakeups. While they didn't offer
Japanese-style lifetime job promises to employees, they rarely
carried out the kinds of large-scale staff purges common among
their American peers.
</P>
<P>
   Union has long been the most Americanized Japanese-run bank
here. While Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi owns about 64 percent of the
bank's stock, profit-hungry U.S. investors hold most of the
remainder. Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi executives hold the chairman
and CEO slots, but American managers run Union's main corporate and
consumer banking units.
</P>
<P>
   Resisted Trims
</P>
<P>
   The bank's American executives, whose pay included options on
Union's stock, had long pressed to make Union leaner. But instead,
the bank became more bloated after it merged with Bank of
California, and the combined institution moved at a snail's pace to
shutter overlapping operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese didn't have the stomach to do big cost cuts,''
said a former Union manager.
</P>
<P>
   Union's sale of $750 million in stock in February was the thing
that finally prompted the bank to act. Potential investors told the
bank they would pass unless Union took dramatic steps to improve
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Union was ``viewed as a big, lumbering company and wasn't
getting any respect on Wall Street,'' said Sutro &AMP; Co. analyst
Campbell Chaney.
</P>
<P>
   To help plan Mission Excel, Union hired EHS Partners, a Los
Angeles consulting firm whose principals had engineered the
successful reorganization at Comerica.
</P>
<P>
   EHS suggested a radical procedure: Take about 40 of the bank's
most senior managers, move them to a huge, cubicle-filled room at
headquarters and put them to work full time on Mission Excel.
</P>
<P>
   The executives were told to comb every nook and cranny of the
bank's 61 business units and look for ways to cut costs or raise
revenue by 50 percent, a target intended to make them stretch to
come up with creative ideas. Rank-and-file employees were also
asked to suggest ways to save money or raise revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the thousands of ideas put on the table amounted to
small change, such as trimming the number of manuals the bank uses
from 29 to nine. But some of the proposals go deep.
</P>
<P>
   The bank may shutter as many as half of its 20 telephone
centers, Walker said. Six of those centers are in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   New Responsibilities
</P>
<P>
   And while the bank probably won't close more than a handful of
its more than 240 branches, job responsibilities inside those
offices will change, Hartnack said. The result would be about one
fewer full-time staff person per branch, not counting any staff
increases that might be needed to handle business growth.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bank will probably increase spending on
Internet-related activities and on overseas operations, Hartnack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Union has a reputation for providing high-quality service,
something that skeptics warn could be jeopardized by a shakeup. But
the bank insists it has no choice. ``The times no longer permit the
old way of doing business,'' said Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wendel doesn't buy that argument. ``This concept of
shrinking to greatness does not work,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
