<SLUG> BC-WEST-VETERANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED V.A. CHIEF IS SAID TO PLAN EARLY DEPARTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Togo West, the embattled secretary of veterans
affairs, has told President Clinton that he plans to resign before
the end of the term but has set no date for his departure, a White
House official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at the Veterans Affairs Department would say
little more than that West did not intend to leave in the near
future and would continue his work through the ``formulation of the
budget for the fiscal year 2001,'' a task that will presumably take
him well into next winter at the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. West has set no date to resign,'' said the spokeswoman,
Laurie Tranter. ``He has not submitted his resignation, and he has
not been asked to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Since February, West has been criticized by several veterans'
groups on the ground that he has failed to push for adequate budget
increases for his mammoth agency, especially for its health
programs. At a breakfast meeting Thursday with senior officials of
five leading veterans' organizations, the secretary said he agreed
that the department needed better financing, several participants
said. He also declared that despite reports that he would be
leaving, which were first published in The Los Angeles Times on
Wednesday, he had no intention of departing soon.
</P>
<P>
   The department's current budget is $38 billion. For the fiscal
year that begins Oct. 1, the Clinton administration is seeking
$42.5 billion, of which $17.3 billion would be earmarked for
veterans' health programs. Veterans' organizations want at least
$1.5 billion more for the health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, West sent a memorandum to the director of the White
House Office of Management and Budget in March, objecting to the
proposed budget for his department and asking for greater financing
to demonstrate the administration's commitment to veterans. But the
White House did not comply.
</P>
<P>
   West has also been criticized for extensive travels while in
office, and an investigation to determine whether all his trips
have been legitimate business is being conducted by the
department's inspector general. In April, Sen. Christopher Bond,
R-Mo., said there ``appears to be a pattern of inappropriate
practices at the highest level of the department.''
</P>
<P>
   West has denied any inappropriate spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
