<HEADLINE>
THE 3-POINTED STAR PROMISES THE MOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mercury is soaring and the power is out. It's time to hit
the streets, and it sure would feel great to go topless. In a
convertible, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The newest ragtop on the market _ indeed, the only all-new
convertible this summer _ is the Mercedes-Benz CLK320 Cabriolet,
which actually made its debut last fall in more temperate weather.
</P>
<P>
   The CLK line, which began in 1998 with a six-cylinder coupe that
fell between the compact C-Class and full-size E-Class, was yet
another effort to inject some pizazz into Mercedes' once-stodgy
product line. For '99, Mercedes added a V8 coupe and this
six-cylinder convertible. The company's goal is to stir the market
for luxury coupes and convertibles just as it recast the roadster
segment with its SLK230 Kompressor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLK's have sold briskly, with waiting lists in some regions;
buyers can expect to pay list price. And while the Cabriolet did
not excite me as the SLK did, it turned heads while providing an
elegant way to take in the sun and stars.
</P>
<P>
   Although the coupe and Cabriolet have an obvious resemblance,
Mercedes says both CLK's were designed from the start as distinct
models. They share few panels behind the windshield pillars.
</P>
<P>
   But both have sweeping, slice-through-the-wind lines and sleekly
elegant profiles. It is a look that got a lot of attention, and
particularly appealed to my 40-something women friends. Inside, the
Cabriolet has soft leather and touches of burl walnut. The car is
reasonably roomy and comfortable for four adults, and its front
seats move automatically when the seatback is folded, helping rear
passengers to get in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though four adults can go for a spin, they had better travel
light. Although the CLK looks rather large on the outside, it
provides minimal storage. Officially, Mercedes says the trunk
measures 9.5 cubic feet with the top up, and about two-thirds of
that with the top down. But the car barely accommodated the basics
for two people on a three-day trip in Georgia. With the top down to
soak in the Southern sun, we could fit only one suitcase in the
trunk; the other stood upright on the back seat. It's a good thing
we weren't carrying golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The three-layer insulated power top can be raised and lowered in
seconds; when down, it disappears under a sleek panel that the
company says was inspired by its race cars of the 1950's. With the
top up, the interior is coupe-quiet. Indeed, the well-made top,
along with a traction control and a winter-shift mode for the
automatic transmission, makes this a convertible that could easily
serve year-round duty in the North. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first Cabriolet I drove performed flawlessly. The power top
on the second car, however, occasionally froze in midair. I got it
down by nudging it or starting the process over. That was the only
quality problem I encountered.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the original coupe, the CLK Cabriolet has a 3.2-liter,
215-horsepower V6. The engine is not overpowered for this
relatively heavy, 3,669-pound car. Mercedes says it can run from a
stop to 60 miles an hour in 7.7 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The power is delivered smoothly and elegantly, in keeping with
the car's overall grace. The ride is comfortable, typical of a
Mercedes, and the handling is a bit ponderous; the Cabriolet looks
sleek, but it performs like a rather large, heavy automobile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cabriolet comes with most of the coupe's equipment,
including a dual-zone automatic climate control, odor-blocking air
filters, 10-way power seats with memory settings for three drivers,
security alarm, cruise control and integrated garage door opener.
The premium Bose audio system includes a weather band and a
cassette player; a CD changer is optional.
</P>
<P>
   The typical Mercedes safety features are here, including side
air bags and Baby-Smart, which deactivates the passenger bag if it
detects the installation of a child seat. In a rollover, a roll bar
deploys and head restraints extend in less than a second. A yaw
control, the Electronic Stability Program, is optional to help
prevent fishtailing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All this class isn't cheap. The CLK320 Cabriolet starts at
around $48,000, about $7,000 more than the coupe. But think of it
this way: Adjusted for inflation, this is one of the least
expensive four-passenger convertibles ever to wear a three-pointed
star.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
