<HEADLINE>
MINDING THE MEETINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., July 11) 
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently took over as head of a department in which a
weekly meeting is a longstanding tradition. All the employees
(about 20) discuss what they have been working on and offer
suggestions for future projects. The problem is that when we go
around the table, I'm met more often than not with blank stares and
monosyllabic responses. Typically, the same one or two people do
the majority of the talking. How can I make these meetings more
productive?
</P>
<P>
   A. Forget tradition. The first question you should ask is: Are
these meetings necessary?
</P>
<P>
   Far too often, people have a meeting because they've always had
a meeting, said Donald E. Wetmore, president of the Productivity
Institute, a consulting firm in Shelton, Conn. ``Nobody ever asks,
`What would happen if we didn't have a meeting?' or if we didn't
have it so often,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the habit can be substantial. Calculate the
collective hourly pay and benefits of the 20 people who attend the
meetings, Wetmore advised. Say it comes out to around $750. ``Now,
ask yourself: `What did we accomplish in our two-hour meeting that
justified spending $1,500 of corporate resources?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the meetings are worthwhile, find out whether
participation has always been so pathetic. If the meetings were
livelier before your arrival as department head, maybe the staff is
not yet comfortable with you. Silence, after all, can be a sign of
shyness, said Odette Pollar, president of Time Management Systems,
a training and consulting firm in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe your employees consider the weekly ritual a monumental
waste of time. ``How long does that take _ 20 people going around
the room?'' Ms. Pollar asked. ``People may be quiet just because
they want to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Start asking employees what's wrong. Do the meetings start too
early? Last too long? Is the format intimidating? Does anyone even
remember the purpose of these gatherings?
</P>
<P>
   If meetings start to seem unproductive, employees will respond
accordingly. ``Sixty-five percent of business people report that
they daydream during meetings,'' Wetmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Seek suggestions on ways, aside from a weekly meeting, to keep
the group apprised of what its members are doing, Ms. Pollar
advised. E-mail and voice mail are possibilities _ and the
information you receive could help you draw people into the
discussion when a meeting is eventually called.
</P>
<P>
   Don't make the mistake of asking for critiques of the meeting
during the meeting, Ms. Pollar said. ``If people are shy in a
group, they're not going to tell you why they're shy in front of
the group,'' she said. Give them the opportunity to respond by
memo, e-mail or one-on-one. And make it clear that you expect to
hear from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get to the bottom of the problem may seem an
unnecessary aggravation as you adjust to your new job. But now is
the time to strike _ before you, too, are sucked into the
mindless-meeting zone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
