<HEADLINE>
THREE HOUSTON MEDICAL INSTITUTIONS MAKE TOP 10 LIST &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By LISA DAVIS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three Houston medical institutions are in the top 10
of U.S. News &AMP; World Reports' annual ratings of speciality
hospitals across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The July 12 edition of the magazine ranks the University of
Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in second place in two categories
_ cancer and gynecology. The Texas Heart Institute at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital placed seventh in cardiology and The Institute
for Rehabilitation and Research ranked third in rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best statement one can get _ to be recognized by
one's peers,'' said Dr. John Mendelsohn, president of M.D.
Anderson. ``We're proud that we give the kind of care that would
merit these rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   M.D. Anderson ranked second to Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in New York for cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is to make what we've learned available to more
patients,'' Mendelsohn said. ``We have better ways to detect
cancers early and treat them ... but we need to make these
treatments available around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Texas Heart Institute has pioneered many
advancements in cardiology and heart surgeries, including the first
heart transplant and the first implantation of an artificial heart
in a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pleasure to be recognized so consistently as a top
cardiovascular facility,'' said Dr. Denton Cooley, founder,
president and surgeon-in-chief of the Texas Heart Institute. ``We
plan to prolong and expand the high-quality research and education
programs that enable us to further combat the devastating effects
of cardiovascular disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Rehabilitation and Research specializes in
medical care, education and research in the field of catastrophic
injury.
</P>
<P>
   TIRR Systems President E. Ashley Smith said placement on the
list ``is a tribute to the innovative, collaborative, world-class
care of our physicians, therapists, nurses, technicians,
researchers and all our support staff at TIRR.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the 10th year U.S. News has published its ``American's
Best Hospitals'' issue.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, it ranked 188 hospitals. To qualify, hospitals had to
be a member of the Council of Teaching Hospitals, affiliated with a
medical school or offer a minimum of nine out of 17 key medical
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. News, the purpose of the evaluation is to be a
resource for patients needing maximum care in the diagnosis,
treatment and management of a difficult medical problem. Emphasis
was placed on hospitals that provided cutting-edge diagnosis and
treatment, rather than broad-based community care.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
