<HEADER>
A3742 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-08 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAKING A COMPANY'S RULES UNDERSTOOD  &HT;     By ILANA DEBARE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: I run a business with a large number of Spanish-speaking
workers. We have just developed a comprehensive employee manual and
are wondering how to present it to workers with limited English. My
wife speaks Spanish and we plan to hold employee meetings from time
to time to go over the main points in Spanish and English. We are
also considering putting the table of contents into Spanish as well
as English. Is our handling of this adequate both to serve our
employees and to protect us legally? Are there better ways to
handle this?
<P>
   A: Hats off to you for taking the time to develop an employee
manual. And hats off a second time for thinking about how to make
the manual truly useful to your employees, rather than just a fat
pile of paper that sits unread on some bookshelf in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ho _ an attorney with the nonprofit Employment Law Center
who specializes in handling workplace disputes over language _
suggests that you translate the entire manual into Spanish, not
just the table of contents.
</P>
<P>
   That will make it easier for your Spanish-speaking workers to
check a particular rule or policy by themselves. It will also help
shield you from lawsuits claiming discrimination on the basis of
national origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way to avoid potential claims like, `You told
these rules to the English speakers, but you didn't tell us,' '' Ho
said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the written translation, be sure to go over your
policies verbally with your staff _ both Spanish speakers and
English speakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you translate a manual doesn't mean people will
be able to read it,'' cautioned Rick Gilbert, a human resources
consultant with the Employers Group in San Francisco. ``Adult
literacy is still a problem in many workplaces. If you have a team
of 10 people and three don't read real well, it's a good idea to
hold a meeting and really have a conversation about what the
policies mean.''
</P>
<P>
   More questions about multiple languages in the workplace? The
Employment Law Center provides free advice to workers about their
language rights on the job at (800) 864-1664. For employers,
organizations like the Employers Group or the California Chamber of
Commerce can provide advice on how to manage a multilingual
workforce.
</P>
<P>
   ACCIDENT BENEFITS
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was recently struck by a truck while riding my bicycle to
work and was taken to the nearby hospital's trauma center for
treatment. The doctors told me I will be unable to work for two to
four weeks. My employer instructed me to apply for short-term
disability benefits through the state Employment Disability
Department. My question is: Since I was injured en route to my job,
should I be receiving workers' compensation rather than short-term
disability benefits?
</P>
<P>
   A: It would be nice if you could get workers' compensation
rather than short-term disability insurance, since workers' comp
often provides a higher payment than California's short-term
disability (SDI) program.
</P>
<P>
   But workers' comp covers injuries sustained in the course of
work _ not in commuting to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The so-called going and coming rule says that the commute to
and from work is not covered by workers' comp,'' said Julius Young,
a workers' comp attorney with Boxer &AMP; Gerson in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few limited circumstances where a commuting injury
might be covered by workers' comp _ for instance, if you were
detouring off your normal route to pick up some supplies that your
boss had requested.
</P>
<P>
   But in your case, a straightforward bike ride to work, the
injuries probably would not be covered by workers' comp.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING COLLARS
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have worked as a lead custodian and a regular custodian for
a school district for 14 years. Soon I'll be leaving for full-time
white-collar employment with a local county. I've worked several
white-collar jobs part time over the last four years, plus I've
taken a small arsenal of computer classes to help with the upcoming
transition. What advice can you offer to help make this change as
smooth as possible?
</P>
<P>
   A: The transition may be less abrupt than you fear. These days,
many blue-collar jobs require the exact same skills as white-collar
work _ teamwork, communication and problem solving. And the fact
that you've been a ``lead custodian'' signals to me that you've
already got some experience in these areas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, here are a few tips to keep in mind with this change:
</P>
<P>
   -- Be a student of your new workplace. Figure out who are the
stars of the office; learn from their examples. Find yourself a
buddy _ someone successful who understands the organization and can
help answer your questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always someone who's an informal font of knowledge,
although it may not be part of their job description,'' said Abby
Snay, executive director of Jewish Vocational Services, a career
resource center in San Francisco. ``Find out who that is and pick
their brain.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Actively manage your workload. One change may be the amount
of paperwork heading your way _ countless e-mails, memos and
reports. Don't get bogged down in trying to give each piece of
paperwork equal treatment; figure out which ones are most important
and which ones must be handled quickly.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ditto for meetings and phone calls. You may find that
meetings are devouring huge amounts of your work time. Carve out
some uninterrupted time each day when you can focus on things like
writing or planning. Maybe that means coming in at 8 rather than 9
a.m.; or maybe it means closing the door and ignoring the phone for
an hour each afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, your new job may have fewer clear-cut tasks and more
open-ended assignments than before. Keep your eye on the big
picture of what your organization is trying to do, and what you
individually need to do to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be assertive in asking for guidance and clarification about
whether you're doing OK,'' Snay advised.
</P>
<P>
   Want a good book on how to be a top performer at work _ in
either a blue-collar or white-collar job? Check out ``How to Be a
Star at Work,'' by Carnegie Mellon business Professor Robert
Kelley, which just came out in a new paperback edition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
