<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Practice site draws thousands of fans
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ This sleepy bedroom community 35 miles east
of Los Angeles was invaded by more minivans and sport-utility
vehicles filled with kids and bearing soccer bumper stickers than
usual Thursday afternoon as more than 2,000 people crammed around
the edges of a tucked-away practice field at Pomona College for the
U.S. training session.
</P>
<P>
   The Claremont police department dispatched four officers on
motorcycles to keep the peace and clear the area for a closed
Chinese practice that followed, but they didn't have a great deal
of success. That's because they had their pictures taken with U.S.
players before going back on duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more people at practices now than at some of our
games in the early years,'' said midfielder Kristine Lilly, who has
been with the national team since 1987. ``It's great to see what's
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity list grows
</P>
<P>
   One of those watching practice was actor Karl Malden, a nearby
resident and another celebrity who's taken an interest in the U.S.
team. In addition to President Clinton, who accepted FIFA's
standing invitation to attend Saturday's final, actor Peter Berg of
``Chicago Hope,'' actress Elizabeth Shue, country singer k.d. lang
and twin teen TV stars Mary Kate and Ashley Olsen also will be on
hand. Representatives of actor Bob Hope also have inquired.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, crews from celebrity TV shows ``Entertainment
Tonight,'' ``Extra'' and ``Access Hollywood'' have taped segments
with American players.
</P>
<P>
   USSF pro exploration
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Soccer Federation said Thursday it was continuing
efforts to help develop a business plan for the implementation of a
women's professional league as early as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The USSF and the Discovery Channel have kicked in roughly
$100,000 each for the project. U.S. coach Tony DiCicco has said the
creation of a pro league is essential for the Americans to stay
among the world powers of women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the National Soccer Alliance, an independent
group, announced plans for a league and enlisted support from
several U.S. national team stars before the efforts were deep-sixed
by then-USSF president Alan Rothenberg, who said they would hurt
World Cup preparations.
</P>
<P>
   The current goal is for the USSF to develop a viable plan,
possibly by early next year, and facilitate discussions with
investors who would run the league.
</P>
<P>
   China has seven all-stars
</P>
<P>
   Seven members of the Chinese team and five from the U.S. team
grace the World Cup MasterCard all-star team, as chosen by FIFA's
women's technical committee.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Briana Scurry, defenders Brandi Chastain and Carla
Overbeck, midfielder Michelle Akers and forward Mia Hamm were among
the 16 players who made the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry's opposite in the net, China's Gao Hong, was the other
keeper, joining forwards Sun Wen and Jin Yan, midfielders Liu
Ailing and Zhao Lihong and defenders Wang Liping and Wen Lirong.
</P>
<P>
   The only players breaking the U.S.-China stranglehold were
German defender Doris Fitschen, Brazilian midfielder Sissi, German
midfielder Bettina Wiegmann and Norway forward Ann Kirstin Aarones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
