<HEADER>
A3744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USCOACH09-COX     07-08 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USCOACH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. coach soccer's modest motivator
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLAREMONT, Calif. _ Women's World Cup coach Tony DiCicco faced
the question without hesitating.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a great job, or what?
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by 20 attractive, articulate young women who also
happen to be world-class soccer players, DiCicco understood the
tone perfectly. In reply, he offered up his usual deadpan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a great job,'' DiCicco said. ``I have the privilege
of working with a talented, motivated group of young women who are
committed to winning the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco is all business on a team whose bubbly personalities and
tales of lovey-dovey camaraderie have been revealed in the news and
on countless television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   But with this circus swirling about him, DiCicco and his top
assistant, Lauren Gregg, have been self-effacing while staying in
the background, letting the players take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   While it may be true that fans don't buy tickets to watch
coaches, DiCicco, 50, has been every bit as amenable as his
players. The man who inherited the job from Anson Dorrance in late
1994 is as easy-going behind the scenes as he appears. To listen to
his players, he doesn't even yell at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who said that?'' DiCicco said earlier this week, a wide grin
protruding from beneath his thick black mustache. ``I don't yell at
them a lot because I'm too busy yelling at the referees. I'm a
passionate guy, but I have a pretty good idea of how to impact a
player's performance. It's not my style to get in their faces. I
have too much respect for them to belittle them that way.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, DiCicco takes his cues from Dorrance, the
successful women's coach at North Carolina whose presence is still
deeply felt on this team. Eight World Cup players are ex-Tar Heels
who soaked up Dorrance's belief that the best way to motivate
female athletes is to build them as a unit and appeal to their
emotional desire for togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that DiCicco doesn't raise the roof when he
has to. He issued what players described as a pretty good Knute
Rockne speech at halftime of the Germany match in the quarterfinals
with the U.S. down 2-1 and lacking its normal sharp edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He raised his voice then, he really did,'' said forward
Tiffeny Milbrett. ``But it wasn't negative at all. He wasn't
telling us what we were doing wrong, he was encouraging us to carry
out the dream we've had about winning this World Cup. It was to
motivate us.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco's words must have made a difference, because he made no
tactical changes.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans scored two goals, both off corner kicks, and hung
on for a 3-2 win despite a far-from-convincing performance.
</P>
<P>
   A former goalkeeper who has run soccer camps for youths in the
Northeast for more than two decades, DiCicco is the married father
of four sons who lives in the same Connecticut suburb where he grew
up. After Dorrance stepped aside, DiCicco didn't change much and it
may have had an affect as the U.S. fell in the semifinals in the
1995 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, it was hard for him to impose his own style,'' said
Gregg, who came on board in 1989. ``What he's brought is a real
tactical sophistication to this team. He has incredible attention
to detail.''
</P>
<P>
   But delicately balancing the personalities on the team is just
as critical a job for DiCicco. Earlier this year, he dropped rising
star Debbie Keller from the roster shortly after she filed a sexual
harassment lawsuit against Dorrance. The timing appeared to be all
wrong, but DiCicco insisted that Keller, who had 14 goals in 1998,
wasn't versatile enough to play more than one role, a must for his
key attacking players, including Mia Hamm and Kristine Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   Keller filed a retaliation suit against DiCicco and the U.S.
Soccer Federation but lost when the matter came to arbitration.
Even now, DiCicco feels stung by the accusation, but says he isn't
bitter about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most difficult thing I've ever had to deal with in
my coaching career,'' he said. ``I think we made the right choice,
but what coach wants to hear that he's being dishonest? Debbie's
still part of our player pool and I think she's going to have a
chance to play for the U.S. in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters was the fact that Lilly, who is dating
Keller's brother, believed Keller should have been named to the
squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affected all of us in different ways,'' Lilly said, clearly
uncomfortable talking about the subject. ``I think Tony handled it
very professionally.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the essence of how he looks at a job that rapidly has
been pushed out into the spotlight. With typical deference, he
thinks too much is being made of how he's managed to keep things on
a relatively even keel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about me, it's about the team,'' he said. ``If any
team deserves to win this championship, it's this one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
