<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS LULLED INTO LOSING TO EXPOS 4-3  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday kept resembling one of those perilous
afternoons for the Mets, the kind of lethargic game in which they
were in front of the Expos yet were not really in control. There
was a listless atmosphere and the Mets always seemed to be in
danger of being lulled to sleep and into feeling that they were
fine. But they were not.
</P>
<P>
   After the vaunted bullpen faltered and the Mets fizzled during
what could have been a dramatic ninth inning, the Expos sneaked out
of Shea Stadium with a 4-3 victory and a surprising split of the
four-game series. For the post-season conscious Mets, it was
bewildering to lose two straight to a weak team that had lost 15 of
its last 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees invading Flushing for three games starting
Friday night, the Mets prepared for the important visit from their
talented neighbors with a shabby precursor.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost because they could not protect a 3-1 bulge, they
could not manage much offense after left fielder Ryan McGuire's
unreliable glove helped them score two runs in the first, and they
did not overpower Montreal when they had chances. Instead, the Mets
remained vulnerable and it destroyed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so upset that we lost the game and that we lost two games
to these guys,'' Turk Wendell said. ``These are the games we got to
capitalize on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Wendell and Dennis Cook had allowed the tying and
go-ahead runs in the seventh and eighth, the Mets had life in the
ninth because Montreal's Ugueth Urbina struggled to throw strikes.
The closer walked pinch-hitter Rickey Henderson to begin the inning
and Manager Bobby Valentine eschewed the sacrifice bunt because he
figured the career stolen base leader could swipe his 1,320th.
Valentine's strategy failed as Chris Widger made a powerful throw
to the right side of the base, where Orlando Cabrera tagged
Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had two outs left, but they were deflated. ``I should
have bunted,'' Valentine said. ``Again, it's tough to predict a
perfect throw by the catcher.'' Indeed. Widger had thrown out only
11 of 69 runners and Henderson did not dispute a theory that Widger
would nab him in 1 out of 25 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when they get you, 1 out of 25 times when they make a
perfect throw,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Urbina also walked Luis Lopez, but Roger Cedeno swung at ball
four on a 3-1 pitch, then struck out, and Edgardo Alfonzo grounded
into a fielder's choice as the Mets stranded their eighth and final
runner. That forced the Mets to address two topics that they
despise: losing to the Expos and playing the hated Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, who smacked his 17th homer, said falling to the
Yankees can make a player feel ``like an outcast in the city'' and
like ``complete losers.'' Thursday, the Mets were losers. Masato
Yoshii had a 3-1 lead in the sixth when Vladimir Guerrero reached
out and belted a shoulder-high fastball over the right-field fence.
It was a stunning homer because the 0-2 pitch was so high and
Guerrero still crushed it for Montreal's first homer in 64 innings.
Even Yoshii called Guerrero's homer incredible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yoshii left with a 3-2 lead after six decent innings and
complained of a cramp in his right thigh from a knee brace that was
too tight. Wendell made his team and major league-best 45th
appearance and it is not one the quirky reliever will want to
remember. After jumping ahead of Cabrera by 1-2, Wendell threw
another slider and Cabrera turned it into a souvenir to even the
score, 3-3, in what amounted to an amazing explosion of power by
the homer-deprived Expos.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets' fifth botched save in 34 chances and Cabrera's
first hit in five at bats off Wendell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slider that didn't slide, it hung,'' Wendell said.
``That's why he is a big league hitter. He's supposed to hit that
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilton Guerrero, who is more of a big league hitter, doomed Cook
in the eighth when he smacked a fat fastball off the left
center-field warning track and hustled it into a triple.
Pinch-hitter Shane Andrews then followed with a flyball to medium
center field. Brian McRae retreated a few steps to corral it before
making a high throw that floated home too late and allowed the
Expos to go ahead, 4-3. That is when the Mets really knew it was a
perilous afternoon. ``We're humans,'' Cook said. ``We're going to
go through some bad stretches. We gave up some runs today. It's one
of those things. I'm not going to go home and slit my wrists.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura's left big toe is still bruised and swollen and
Manager Bobby Valentine said he was doubtful to play against the
Yankees. ``I'm not expecting him to,'' Valentine said. ``If he
does, it'll be a pleasant surprise.'' Ventura, who was not in
uniform for the game, hopes to play again before the All-Star Game
break. ``It feels better,'' Ventura said. ``It's just sore.'' . . .
Octavio Dotel was not scheduled to start until July 19 in
Baltimore, so the Mets optioned him to Class AAA Norfolk and
promoted infielder Mike Kinkade to allow the rookie to pitch in a
game and to increase their bench flexibility. Dotel will start for
Norfolk Monday. . . . Rickey Henderson did not start Thursday and
strolled into the clubhouse 65 minutes before the first pitch, but
Valentine said the 40-year old has permission to arrive late
anytime he wants. . . . Edgardo Alfonzo, meet Rodney Dangerfield.
The second baseman was listed as Alfonso on the batting practice
time sheet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
