<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     07-08 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK COMES OUT OF THE DARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For the first time in seven weeks, the Dodgers scored
in double digits. For the first time in six weeks, right-hander
Chan Ho Park won.
</P>
<P>
   Snapping a losing streak at three games with an 11-8 victory
against Colorado on Thursday afternoon brought a few smiles into
the Dodgers clubhouse but no crazy talk of how this sinking ship
was all of a sudden sailing majestically.
</P>
<P>
   No way, no how, not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, we don't need to worry about where we're
at,'' said Dodgers reliever Pedro Borbon, who retired both batters
he faced in the eighth. ``You go out, not worry about it and not
worry about where we'll be in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeff Shaw recorded a save, his 19th but his first since
June 26. Of course, it was the following day when the Dodgers began
this horrific stretch in which they've lost nine of 11.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros homered twice and Mark Grudzielanek had three hits
and drove in three with a first-inning double. The Dodgers tied a
season-high with five runs in the first inning and avoided getting
swept in a four-game series for the first time in six years. The
also finished their 16-game stretch against the NL West 4-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could give a rat's (butt); we're just trying to win games,''
Karros said. ``We're not sitting here saying, `Oh (no), we may get
swept.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When the halfway point arrived Tuesday, the Dodgers talked about
needing to win 50 games in the second half to possibly propel them
into playoff contention. They say it's possible, though it's
unprecedented since the club moved to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving from Brooklyn for the 1958 season, the Dodgers
haven't won 50 games in the second half of a season after finishing
the first half below .500.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Dodgers (36-47) finished the season's first half 35-46
_ their worst half in 20 years. From this point, they would have to
play .620 baseball just to get to 85 wins. The more realistic win
mark for the playoffs is 90, meaning the Dodgers would have to go
54-25 to get there.
</P>
<P>
   But the last time the Dodgers won 50 games in a half-season was
1985. They were 45-36 at the midway point and finished 95-67 and
won the NL West by 5{ games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little fire, a little battle (in us), but one game
isn't going to matter,'' Grudzielanek said. ``Five games wouldn't
matter, though it would be nice. We need to play for a few weeks, a
month, and look where we're at. We're struggling. We can't go out
and say we have to win 50 games. That's just the wrong way to think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There were good points for the Dodgers, and that begins with a
win, which began with the pounding of former Dodgers left-hander
Brian Bohanon (9-7).
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, who signed a three-year, $9 million contract during the
winter, lasted two-thirds of an inning, his shortest start in seven
years. He walked in a run, gave up Grudzielanek's three-run double
and then was pulled after Park singled in a run.
</P>
<P>
   It was the beginning of a long-overdue offensive onslaught.
Karros added a solo homer in the second. The Dodgers scored three
more in the fourth, marking the first time since May 22 they scored
10 runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Although Park (5-7) gave up three more homers (23 this season)
and allowed seven runs on 10 hits in five innings, he was applauded
afterward for surviving a typical Coors Field game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies kept cutting into the Dodgers' five-run lead until
it was 6-5 after three innings, but the Dodgers always remained in
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the Chan Ho I expect to see,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``When he had adversity, he beared down and mixed his
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who got relief help from Mike Maddux, Alan Mills, Borbon
and Shaw, won for the first time since May 26. Since then he's lost
four times and his ERA is 9.49.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good because I gave up seven runs,'' said Park,
whose ERA rose to 6.52. ``But finally I can sleep tonight because I
won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
