<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-MELTDOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIREARMS MELTED DOWN TO MAKE BUILDING MATERIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY KEVIN SMITH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO CUCAMONGA _ Weapons of destruction became fuel for
construction Thursday when more than 14,000 confiscated rifles,
shotguns and handguns were converted into steel reinforcement bars
for the building industry.
</P>
<P>
   During the sixth annual Project Isaiah Meltdown and Recycling
Program at Tamco Steel Inc., the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department destroyed seized weapons that have been used in
assaults, robberies and other crimes, including those in the Santa
Clarita and Antelope valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Department and 37 other agencies provided this
year's cache of nearly 18 tons of confiscated firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today our streets are safer,'' Assistant Sheriff Larry Waldie
told the small group that had gathered to watch the event. ``Every
one of these guns has a story.''
</P>
<P>
   One semiautomatic pistol was found under a blanket in a baby's
crib, Waldie said. Another replica of a 9 mm handgun was used by a
15-year-old carjacking suspect who pointed the gun at deputies
before surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   This year's project melted down 3,623 rifles and shotguns, and
10,412 handguns.
</P>
<P>
   After the news conference, the pile of weapons was scooped up by
two bulldozers and dumped into a 15-by-15 steel bucket. A huge
hook-and-cable system lifted the bucket and dumped the guns into a
fiery, 3,000-degree furnace.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the recycled metal from this year's meltdown will be
used for the Alameda Corridor project in downtown Los Angeles and
for the new Staples Center Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the material will be used by artist Lin Evola, who is
creating 13 ``Peace Angel'' sculptures that will be placed in sites
of conflict throughout the world. Her works are made from
decommissioned nuclear casings, and surrendered and confiscated
street weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard E. Robinson, Tamco's environmental and safety manager,
started the program six years ago as a symbolic gesture to victims
of firearms violence and their families. The project is named for
Isaiah 2:4, which says, ``They shall beat their swords into
plowshares and their spears into pruning hooks; one nation shall
not raise the sword against another, nor shall they train for war
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamco, the only steel recycling mill in California, has
processed more than 500,000 pounds of confiscated weapons since the
program began.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
