<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASD FINES PRUDENTIAL $20 MILLION FOR DECEPTION
</P>
<P>
   In yet another penalty for misleading customers over more than a
decade, Prudential Insurance was fined $20 million by the National
Association of Securities Dealers, the highest fine ever imposed by
the association. The insurer, which has already paid more than $70
million in fines to state insurance regulators for deceptive sales
practices, is in the midst of a reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   GE POSTS 15 PERCENT INCREASE IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, benefiting from its continued push into
high-margin service businesses as well as from improved efficiency,
reported that its second-quarter earnings rose 15 percent, slightly
beating analysts' expectations by a penny a share. But its stock
still foundered in a down market. After investors drove the stock
up $4 this week in anticipation of stellar numbers, shares of GE
fell 93.75 cents, to $117.
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS POST STRONG SALES GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Retailers reported robust sales gains in June. Sales in stores
open at least a year rose 6.5 percent, according to the Goldman
Sachs retail composite index.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer borrowing grew at the fastest pace in four months in
May, rising $12.1 billion, to $1.345 trillion, Federal Reserve
figures showed. Demand for autos set a record.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY TO COMBINE TV OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney became the first large Hollywood production studio
to fold its operations under the same umbrella as a television
network when it announced that it would consolidate its ABC and
Disney television entertainment divisions into one unit.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC Radio network has hired Matt Drudge, who composes an
Internet news-and-gossip column called The Drudge Report, to do a
syndicated radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ CLIMBS AS DOW RETREATS
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks swept the Nasdaq composite index to its fifth
record in six sessions as it rose 28.82 points, to 2,771.86. The
Dow Jones industrial average fell 60.47 points, to 11,126.89, while
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index dropped 1.44 points, to
1,394.42.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose as Freddie Mac and Ford Motor found buyers for
$9.8 billion of securities. The yield of the benchmark 30-year
Treasury bond fell to 5.99 percent from 6.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OPRAH WINFREY IN MAGAZINE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey has joined with Hearst Magazines to publish a new
magazine that will seek to capitalize on her popularity with women.
The magazine, which will hit newsstands next spring, will cover
issues related to spirituality, community, family, relationships
and work, among other topics. The magazine will also provide an
additional outlet for Ms. Winfrey's popular book club, in which she
chooses books on her TV show and encourages viewers to read along.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK OBSERVER MAY BE SOLD
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Black, the Canadian newspaper publisher whose company
publishes The Jerusalem Post, The Chicago Sun-Times, The Daily
Telegraph in London and other papers, has discussed buying The New
York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   A RACIAL DIVIDE IN CYBERSPACE
</P>
<P>
   While minority groups are increasingly gaining access to
computers and the Internet, the racial divide remains stark, with
blacks and Hispanics less than half as likely as whites to explore
the Internet from home, work or school.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-DISTANCE TURMOIL IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   After competition was allowed in several regions of Brazil last
weekend, the long-distance telephone network nearly collapsed in
confusion and technical problems.
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS' RIGHTS BILL TO BE DEBATED
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican leaders said that they would use a Democratic
bill as the focus for debate next week over how to protect the
rights of patients buffeted by turmoil in the health care industry.
Republicans are then expected to replace the Democratic bill with a
Republican version.
</P>
</TEXT>
