<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAUD-INDICT-NYT &LR;      07-08 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY BROKERAGE FIRM INDICTED IN HUGE FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Manhattan district attorney brought an indictment
Thursday against A.S. Goldmen &AMP; Co., a small New Jersey brokerage
firm, and 26 employees on charges that the firm had orchestrated a
securities fraud that had cost thousands of investors $100 million
in losses.
</P>
<P>
   Among those named in the 240-count indictment announced by the
district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, were Goldmen's president and
owner, Anthony Marchiano, 37, of Naples, Fla., and his twin
brother, Salvatore, of Freehold Township, N.J., Goldmen's head
trader.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's chief financial officer, Stuart Winkler, 46, of
Morganville, N.J., was also named. According to prosecutors,
Winkler, who worked as a field examiner at the National Association
of Securities Dealers in New York from 1979 through 1986, devised
the firm's fraudulent schemes.
</P>
<P>
   From August 1992 to October 1998, prosecutors contend, A.S.
Goldmen employees broke numerous securities laws. The schemes,
prosecutors said, included the manipulation of markets in certain
stocks to benefit Goldmen employees; the use of phony accounts to
trade in securities that the employees were prohibited from owning;
trading on nonpublic information; the making of unauthorized
trades; refusals to adhere to customers' sell orders, and the
falsifying of the firm's records. Morgenthau also said that Goldmen
employees lied to regulators and destroyed documents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the indictment, Morgenthau brought a civil action
seeking $100 million in repayment for what he called the criminal
proceeds of the corrupt activities.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Helen Freedman signed a temporary
restraining order on Thursday prohibiting the defendants from
disposing of any assets without court approval. The investigation
into the firm's activities is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   According to Morgenthau, Goldmen brokers focused on retirees as
investors, many of whom lost their entire savings with the firm.
One victim, he said, was a retired bus driver in upstate New York
who lost all his savings and had to return to work as a result of
the loss. Another Goldmen customer was a Maryland woman who lost
the $25,000 nest egg she planned to use to pay for her daughter's
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were real people who lost real money to a bunch of
crumbums,'' Morgenthau said. ``These guys were heartless.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for A.S. Goldmen, Marchiano and Winkler did not return
telephone calls seeking comment. The firm closed most of its
operations last year.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney's two-year investigation into A.S. Goldmen
began as a result of numerous complaints from the firm's customers.
With offices in New York, New Jersey, Los Angeles and Naples, Fla.,
it had 50,000 investor accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which received mail at its headquarters in Red Bank,
N.J., in care of Body by Boris, had been the subject of 11 actions
by state securities regulators since 1991 and had been involved in
numerous investor arbitrations.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that Goldmen had a creative but fraudulent way
of dealing with some complaints it received from investors. Winkler
and Marchiano were said to place warrants in companies Goldmen was
underwriting in the accounts of dissatisfied investors,
guaranteeing them profits. By controlling the repurchase and resale
of the securities, the firm could propel the warrants' prices
higher _ a manipulation, according to prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler, prosecutors said, used his knowledge of regulatory
practices and capabilities to divert regulators' attention from
Goldmen's misdeeds. After seven years as a NASD regulator, Winkler
became a vice president for compliance at two small New York
brokerage firms, Middlegate Securities Ltd. and Steinberg &AMP; Lyman.
He joined Goldmen in January 1989, six months after the firm was
incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   The charges in Thursday's indictment involve the marketing of
securities in Millenium Sports Management Inc., Stadium Capital
Inc., Independence Brewing Co., Imatec Ltd., Wanderlust Interactive
Inc., Winfield Capital Corp., Veritas Music Entertainment,
Nickelodeon Theater Co., Cinema Ride Inc. and Innovative Tech
Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the crimes, prosecutors said, rose from the use of
phony, or ``nominee,'' accounts set up by Goldmen employees for
their own benefit using the names of friends and family members
with different surnames. The indictment included charges against
seven individuals for such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   To evade rules prohibiting underwriters from trading in their
own initial public offerings, money provided by the Goldmen brokers
would be placed in these accounts and used to buy low-priced
warrants on stocks underwritten by the firm, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, warrants offered at 25 cents each would be bought
back by the firm at 75 cents even though the warrants were trading
publicly for twice that price. The profits would then be repaid to
the Goldmen employees by the account holders in cash to avoid
detection.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission also instituted
administrative proceedings against Goldmen Thursday as well as a
cease-and-desist action charging it and eight employees with
securities violations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Walker, director of enforcement at the SEC, said that
criminal actions like those brought by Morgenthau against
fraudulent brokerage firms like Duke &AMP; Co., A.R. Baron and A.S.
Goldmen were crucial in fighting securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deterrents achieved by criminal sanctions are extremely
important in this battle because many of the people involved are
undeterred by civil sanctions,'' Walker said. ``The A.S. Goldmen
case shows that `boiler rooms' are corrupt enterprises that defraud
investors and we'll chase 'em high and low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
