<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUDGE-ABC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC RADIO HIRES INTERNET'S DRUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ABC Radio network has hired Matt Drudge, who composes an
Internet news-and-gossip column called the Drudge Report, to do a
Sunday night radio talk show that will be syndicated across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, completed on Wednesday, has caused concern for the
president of ABC News, said two ABC News executives who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News and ABC Radio are separate entities within ABC Inc., a
unit of Walt Disney Co., and Drudge's two-hour radio show, which
has been on WABC in New York for about a year, will not be billed
as news.
</P>
<P>
   Still, David Westin, the president of ABC News, was so concerned
about Drudge's reputation as someone who reports rumors and
occasionally does not adequately check facts that he tried to
dissuade his radio colleagues from making the syndication deal, the
two ABC News executives said. Westin declined to comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that Westin was concerned that Drudge could
be associated in viewers' or listeners' minds with ABC News.
Westin's opposition was first reported Thursday in The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge, who also has a half-hour Saturday evening television
show on the Fox News Channel, said Thursday by telephone from his
home in Los Angeles: ``I'm not a journalist. I'm an Internet
reporter. Everything I've learned about journalism I learned from
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Drudge has been criticized for tarnishing the reputations of
journalists because he describes what he reports as news, yet
deflects criticism by saying he is not trained as a journalist and
has no editor to supervise his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's not a journalist but he plays one on the
Internet,'' said Deborah Potter, a former CBS News and CNN
correspondent who is now executive director of NewsLab, a nonprofit
organization in Washington that assists local television stations
in improving their news operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Potter maintained that opinionated talk-show hosts like Rush
Limbaugh are heard on radio stations, and listeners apparently do
not mistake him for a journalist. If that were the case with
Drudge, she said, there would be no cause for concern. ``But the
creeping, fuzzy line can confuse people,'' she added, because ``on
his Web site, he purports to break news and he passes himself off
as an ersatz journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   Drudge said he did, in fact, break news, and added, ``My
triumphs and successes have overshadowed my mistakes or growing
pains.''
</P>
<P>
   On his radio show, which in the latest ratings had the most
listeners in its 10 p.m.-to-midnight time slot, Drudge talks about
news stories ``from all over the world,'' he said, and takes
telephone calls from listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Sunday, his show will be heard on 15 to 20 more
stations, including ABC Radio affiliates in Washington, Chicago,
Los Angeles, San Francisco, Detroit and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge is the subject of a $30 million defamation lawsuit by
Sidney Blumenthal, a White House aide, because Drudge reported on
his Web site, then retracted, rumors that Blumenthal had abused his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Drudge also helped break the story of President Clinton's
involvement with Monica Lewinsky, by reporting on the Web site much
of Newsweek magazine's exclusive story on the subject before the
magazine had finished double-checking its report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3769 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-08 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINCAY REGAINS FORM IN RACE FOR RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Pete Rose batted .264 the season he broke Ty
Cobb's record for career hits.
</P>
<P>
   Laffit Pincay fans feared their hero would be in similar
decline, a graying athlete hanging on for personal glory as he
tried to become horse racing's Pete Rose by surpassing Bill
Shoemaker's record for career victories by a jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears we needn't have worried.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Pincay, 52, is riding better than he has in years,
steaming toward Shoemaker's record 8,833, now 70 wins away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that way, too,'' Pincay said in the Hollywood Park
jockeys' room Thursday between races. ``A lot of people tell me I
look better and I'm riding better, and it makes me feel good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I'm just hanging in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, jinxed by injuries and losing business,
Pincay thought out loud about moving to a softer circuit in
Northern California or Washington state. That might have cleared
his path to the record and tainted it at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay decided against the move because it would have meant
flying on Mondays and Tuesdays to be with his wife, Jeanine, and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided maybe I could do something different and improve
myself so I could ride better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A new diet has increased Pincay's energy and stamina, allowing
him to stay home and pick up his win rate all at once.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the miniature Mr. Panama physique said he has been
able to increase his daily calorie intake to 850 by eating more
fruit, cutting back from two or three glasses of wine a week to
one, and eliminating the nondairy creamer from his morning tea.
</P>
<P>
   He spares no detail to weigh out at 117 pounds on a body made
for 140.
</P>
<P>
   The results: 86 wins (15 percent) in 1999, on pace for his best
season since 1992; 30 wins so far at Hollywood Park, good for a
fourth-place tie in the standings; a gratifying victory June 25 in
the four-race National All-Star Jockey Challenge at Lone Star Park
near Dallas; and Hollywood Park stakes victories last weekend
aboard Virginie in the Beverly Hills Handicap and Salish Shaman in
the Harry Henson.
</P>
<P>
   The only bad news lately is Pincay's split with trainer Bill
Spawr _ the result, the rider says, of a misunderstanding between
agent Bob Meldahl and Spawr over a riding assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he stays healthy and keeps winning at this rate, the
question is whether Pincay will break the record late in the Nov.
10 to Dec. 20 Hollywood Park meet or the Dec. 26-on Santa Anita
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Hollywood Park jockey Alex Solis, a fellow Panamanian,
said he senses the record chase is ``adding to his motivation.''
But Pincay said he tries not to follow the countdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure,'' Pincay said. ``I have all the time I
need. The way I feel, I can ride another five years.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Voice change: Michael Wrona is on his way home to Brisbane,
Australia, to be with an ailing grandfather. Alan Buchdahl will
call the races for the last nine days of the Hollywood Park meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been like a father to me,'' Wrona, whose parents divorced
when he was young, said of Harry Deane, hospitalized since March.
``It's very important I'm back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrona, who replaced the outstanding Luke Kruytbosch, has been a
delight in his return to Hollywood _ observant, informed, creative
and, refreshingly, intent on pronouncing names correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Trevor Denman will return from his Minnesota
farm to call the Del Mar, Fairplex Park and Oak Tree meets.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: Pincay will ride Quake in Saturday's Bel Air
Handicap, the race that set up 1998 winner Free House for a victory
in the Pacific Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Without anything resembling Free House in the 1 1/16-mile Bel
Air this time, 4-year-old Quake could win his first stakes, easing
trainer Richard Mandella's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not real smart and that's the best thing I can say about
him,'' Mandella said of Quake. ``But the bottom line is, he can
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Quake, coming off a three-length win in an optional-claiming
sprint with Pincay, faces seven horses, including Barter Town
(Victor Espinoza) and Scooter Brown (Alex Solis), second and third
in the All-American Handicap at Golden Gate Fields.
</P>
<P>
   __ Series injury: Puerto Madero, last in the Hollywood Gold Cup,
his third disappointing performance since his Donn Handicap
victory, will miss most of the rest of the year with a left-front
ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella said a nuclear scan, more intensive than an X-ray,
showed ``some kind of stress'' in the sesamoid bone, which could
have developed into a fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 5-year-old Chile-bred is expected to race again,
this is another blow to the inaugural ``NTRA Champions on Fox''
series for older horses. Puerto Madero, Free House (injured) and
Silver Charm (retired), third through fifth in the points behind
Behrens and Real Quiet, will miss the series-ending Pacific Classic
at Del Mar on Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero's 20 points would have been worth $100,000 to
owners R.D. Hubbard and Dwight Sutherland if he'd won the Pacific
Classic, less if he'd finished second through fifth. Under the
series' contrived rules, missing the climactic race will render the
points worthless. &QL; 
A WEEK AT THE RACES &QL; 
__ Hollywood Park leaders: Jockeys (through Wednesday): Alex Solis,
48 wins; David Flores, 41; Garrett Gomez, 36; Laffit Pincay and
Emile Ramsammy, 30. Trainers: Ron McAnally, 23; Bob Baffert, Julio
Canani, David Hofmans and John Sadler, 13. &QL; 
__ Handicapper helper: The tight turns of most turf courses give an
edge to horses starting from inside-post positions. At Hollywood
Park it depends on the distance. At 1 mile and longer, post 1 has
produced a staggering 19 percent of the winners. But in the
5{-furlong sprints, post 1 has yielded only 1 winner in 31 tries. &QL; 
__ On the stakes schedule: At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $125,000
Bel Air Handicap, 3-year-olds and up, 1 1/16 miles; Sunday,
$125,000 Khaled, California-breds 3 and up, 1 1/16 miles on turf.
At Belmont Park: Saturday, $150,000 Bowling Green Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1] miles on turf; Sunday, $150,000 Dwyer,
3-year-olds, 1 1/16 miles. At Monmouth Park: Saturday, $150,000
Monmouth Oaks, 3-year-old fillies, 1 1/16 miles. &QL; 
__ Mileposts: Frank Stronach's Magna International, which owns
Santa Anita, announced an agreement to purchase Gulfstream Park
near Miami from a Japanese concern for a reported $95 million. The
deal is expected to close before Gulfstream hosts the Nov. 6
Breeders' Cup. Stronach will control the nation's two major winter
thoroughbred tracks and take on Churchill Downs in both Los Angeles
(where Churchill is taking over Hollywood Park) and Miami (where
Churchill runs Calder). . . . The Meadowlands harness announcer
will resign in September but receive a reported $250,000 from the
New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority in a lawsuit settlement.
John Bothe accused track management of trying to force him to
conduct televised handicapping seminars, which he said could plunge
him back into compulsive gambling. The suit inspired debate last
winter over the very existence of compulsive gambling, including
Andy Beyer's assertion that people who find ruin at the track are
simply ``bad bettors.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Behrens' Suburban Handicap victory at Belmont Park solidified
his ``NTRA Champions on Fox'' series lead and sent him past Victory
Gallop to No. 1 in the NTRA media poll. . . . Louisiana refused to
renew the license Billy Patin used to ride at Evangeline Downs
after Arkansas suspended him for five years for using a battery on
Valhol in the Arkansas Derby. Patin's lawyer said he intends to
appeal. Valhol won the Arkansas Derby but was disqualified. The
Dallas Keen-trained 3-year-old was ridden by Donnie Meche when he
scored his first official victory June 30 in an allowance race at
Lone Star Park in Texas. . . . Cat Thief joined General Challenge
and Desert Hero among probables for the July 18 Swaps Stakes. Cat
Thief trainer D. Wayne Lukas is tied with Gary Jones for most Swaps
victories with three. . . . San Fernando winner Dixie Dot Com
(broken cannon bone) aims for a mid-August return. ``Our long-range
dream _ with an emphasis on dream _ is the Breeders' Cup Classic,''
trainer Bill Morey said. . . . Emile Ramsammy (broken collarbone)
thinks he could ride before Hollywood Park closes July 19. . . .
Average win payoff at Hollywood last Friday night: $33. . . .
National leaders just past the year's midpoint: Shane Sellers
($7,850,421) and Edgar Prado (244 wins) among jockeys; Bob Baffert
($7,475,101) and Dale Baird (156 wins) among trainers; Charismatic
($2,007,404) among horses. . . . The 12-day Vallejo fair opens
Wednesday. . . . Del Mar, whose meet opens July 22, will take
simulcast bets on Saratoga and Monmouth (N.J.) Park _ and Ellis
Park in Kentucky on Monmouth's dark Mondays. . . . Fries with that
trifecta? Lone Star has become the second track _ after Keeneland _
to offer drive-up windows for early-bird betting. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
