<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGN-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-08 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: DELIVERING A MESSAGE BEFORE THE CONSUMER SEES IT
COMING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alexander Gelman came to New York from Moscow six
years ago with few contacts in advertising but an impressive
``book'' of design work from a big Russian publishing house where
he was creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Now at the age of 31, he is one of New York's hot young art
directors with a tiny but thriving company called Design Machine, &UR;  &LR; 
which has done advertising projects for such powerhouses as J.
Walter Thompson, Dell Computer, Absolut Vodka and MTV.
</P>
<P>
   His success reflects the growing importance of art design in
advertising and marketing. Many design firms _ from the small ones
like Design Machine to big firms like the Attik &UR;  &LR; and Duffy Design
and Interactive _ are finding their talents more in demand as
visuals become more important to communicating a message.
</P>
<P>
   Strong art and design is taking the front seat as companies try
to cut through that growing enemy of advertising: media clutter. A
properly designed visual can provide an instantaneous message and
feeling. And it can capture the attention of consumers quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1 is that the consumer is on to us,'' Bill Oberlander,
executive creative director of Kirshenbaum Bond &UR;  &LR; &AMP; Partners and
president of the Art Directors Club, said. ``They know advertising
100 miles off and when they see it coming they're programmed to
shoot it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art direction,'' he said, ``offers a faster, deeper and more
emotional connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Designers are taking a greater role in defining and executing a
brand's look and image, from the logo design to the package to the
advertising. At Kirshenbaum Bond, designers recently sat with the
advertising team at work on a product line for Target stores. Duffy
Design regularly goes into pitch meetings with its owner, Fallon
McElligott, to offer clients a totally integrated campaign from
typeface to finished advertising.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Duffy Design created the logo and the packaging
for Coca-Cola's Fruitopia, and worked with the advertising agency
on the advertising. Duffy and Fallon are currently working on an
integrated program of brand identity, packaging and advertising for
FAO Schwarz, the venerated toy store, and for Nordstrom department
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Design firms are now often brought in at the start of a project.
In the past they might be the last to get an assignment after all
the important brand decisions had been made, said Jim Moran, who
heads the New York office of the Attik.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just an afterthought anymore,'' Moran said. ``We
have much more say now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the way some of the design firms describe themselves has
changed. Years ago, Design Machine might have been called a design
firm or a graphic-arts house. Gelman says he explains to clients
that his firm is a ``multidisciplinary branding company.''
</P>
<P>
   In the business, it is known as convergence. Gelman is a design
specialist but his firm does everything from brand research to Web
site design to planning a client's party. The Attik now produces
television commercials, and 40 percent of Duffy Design's work now
involves interactive design on the Web. Duffy said interactive
design alone has opened up a whole new world of design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if you're on top of what's going on there is no
distinction between branding, advertising or product design,''
Gelman said. ``We're a business consultancy that helps solve
communications problems using design and art.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon McElligott has been using designers as part of a
whole-brand approach for years, said Alison Burns, president of
Fallon McElligott, New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Design is no more separate than account planning or media,''
Ms. Burns said. ``Using design to help solve the brand problem
seems to me a no-brainer _ it's where the whole thing starts.`
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, in a media-cluttered world, the look everyone
is after is to not look like advertising. The trend is toward
minimalism, with clean lines, not much copy, a strong visual
element and often a clever message. The look is designed to catch
the consumer off guard _ like one print ad that shows a photograph
of feet, with just the toes sunburned. The ad is for Wonderbra.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas _ sometimes you have to search and think about it
before you get it and there's often a sense of humor,'' said Myrna
Davis, executive director of the Art Directors Club in New York.
``It's not about the product anymore, it's really about things
around the product that engage you, almost like guerrilla marketing
_ the product is noticed after the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the focus on design, many small shops have popped up
around the city, and the bigger firms are growing. The Attik, which
was started in 1986 in an attic in England, now has five offices
and 130 people on staff. The Art Directors Club, a venerable old
boys club dating back to 1920, says its membership is expanding and
its events are often sold out. People lined up at the opening
exhibit of its Young Guns II show, a biennial exhibit of
outstanding work in visual media created by people 35 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Gelman _ who wears his head shaved and goes by the moniker of
just ``Gelman'' _ believes his firm is growing because advertisers
and agencies are looking to young, small firms for cutting-edge
ideas. While he has just five staff members, he said he literally
had dozens of designers in all media at his disposal to work on
projects.
</P>
<P>
   The designers are known as perma-lancers who work in advertising
the way actors work in Hollywood, jumping from one job to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Oberlander agreed, saying creative companies are willing to take
new ideas wherever they can find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big business knows that the old ideas aren't cutting it
anymore, and it needs young renegade minds to connect to
consumers,'' he said. ``I definitely think there's a trend to find
unconventional ways to reinvent brands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
