<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MALONE-DAUGHTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL MALONE'S DAUGHTER MAKES HER OWN FOOTSTEPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For a long time, Cheryl Ford refused to play
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   To her friends and grade-school coaches, Ford seemed a natural.
Not only was she always tall for her age, but she was the daughter
of NBA star Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to follow in his footsteps,'' Ford said of her
father.
</P>
<P>
   Years of pestering finally persuaded Ford to take up the game as
an eighth-grader in her hometown of Summerfield, La. Now, whether
she likes it or not, she is following in her father's footsteps.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 post player is a Nike High School All-American and
was a member of last year's U.S. Junior Olympic team. She is
playing for the second-seeded Monroe Magic _ wearing No. 32, like
her father _ in this week's Amateur Athletic Union 18-and-under
Girls Basketball National Championships in Arlington and Mansfield,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   She will begin her college career on scholarship at Louisiana
Tech _ her father's alma mater _ this fall and says her eventual
goals are the Olympics and the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess \Rbasketball\S grew on me,'' she said. ``It's a huge
part of my life now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford would rather play basketball than deal with the media
attention that has come with being a top player and daughter of an
NBA star. Malone fathered Ford and her twin brother, Daryl, during
a brief relationship with Bonita Ford when he was 18. He had been
estranged from his daughter until last year and has been in
Arlington and Mansfield this week to watch her play.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic won its quarterfinal game yesterday, defeating
Indiana's Finest, 81-71. Monroe plays the Georgia Magic in the
semifinals at 10:30 a.m. today at Mansfield High School's north
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was unavailable for comment yesterday, and the
18-year-old Ford said she gets tired of the question about her
famous father. She said she wears No. 32 because it was the number
her mother, Bonita Ford, wore as a high school player, and that she
chose to attend Tech for her own reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets on my nerves when people ask me if I'm his daughter
because you know they already know,'' Ford said. ``I've made my
decisions on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Malone said he made a decision to re-establish a
relationship with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised by my granddad and my mom,'' said Malone, who is
married and has three children with his wife, Kay. ``My father
committed suicide when I was 5. I was bitter for a long time. I
finally got over it about five years ago. But I learned something
from it: If you ever have the opportunity to make things right, do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to do something about that for the twins. I
told the twins, `What me and your mom did was a mistake, but you
guys are not a mistake. I want to be part of your life. I want to
be a dad and a friend, and I am not going to overwhelm you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ford gives the credit for her basketball skills to Monroe Magic
coach Linda Harper, former head women's coach at Northeast
Louisiana in Monroe. Harper has guided Ford since Ford took up the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw her, I noticed how well she could run up and
down the floor. And she had great hands,'' Harper said. ``She just
needed help in developing her shot and some post moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford has developed those moves, and this season has averaged 19
points, nine rebounds and three blocked shots per game for the
Magic. She has been hampered by a sore right shoulder, which she
injured at the beginning of the season. Ford said she is scheduled
to have surgery on the shoulder Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the team would rather have Ford injured than not at all.
The Magic finished second to Team Texas in last year's tournament
without Ford, who was in Russia with the U.S. junior team.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't mind telling another player when they need to step
up,'' Harper said. ``And when a game's on the line, she plays
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said Ford has the ability to be a top college player, and
said Ford better be ready to handle even more attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to start comparing her to her father, and
that will put a lot of pressure on her,'' she said. ``But we each
have a mold that's our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Ford eventually decided basketball was part of her mold.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
