<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON SPLITS WITH PRESIDENT OVER ISRAEL ISSUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON, N.Y. _ Taking a position that differs from her
husband's policy on a rancorous Middle East dispute, Hillary Rodham
Clinton says she considers Jerusalem the ``eternal and indivisible
capital of Israel'' and favors moving the U.S. Embassy there from
Tel Aviv as soon as possible, according to a letter released by her
aides Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's position on what is perhaps the most difficult
issue in the Middle East peace negotiations _ the permanent status
of the city that Israel calls its capital _ was disclosed in a
letter she wrote to a conservative Jewish organization last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported in this week's issue of The Forward, a weekly
newspaper that covers Jewish issues. It marked the second time in a
week that Mrs. Clinton, who traveled through central New York on
Thursday in preparation for a possible run for the U.S. Senate, has
taken a position at variance with her husband's on a subject that
has particular political resonance in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton wrote the letter in response to an inquiry from
Mandell Ganchrow, president of the Union of Orthodox Jewish
Congregations of America.
</P>
<P>
   Her statements of support for Jerusalem _ a standard position
for politicians in New York _ came five months after some Jews
criticized her for expressing support for the establishment of a
permanent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, she said, ``I personally consider Jerusalem the
eternal and indivisible capital of Israel, and I admire the
leadership shown by Senator Moynihan on this issue.'' Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, whose seat she would fill, is a leading advocate
of moving the American Embassy to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am chosen by New Yorkers to be their senator,'' she
wrote, ``or in whatever position I find myself in the years to
come, you can be sure that I will be an active, committed advocate
for a strong and secure Israel, able to live in peace with its
neighbors, with the United States Embassy located in its capital,
Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   In tone and in commitment, Mrs. Clinton's letter was unlike
anything President Clinton or his administration has said on the
subject since he took office in 1993. The language she used _
calling Jerusalem ``the eternal and indivisible capital of Israel''
_ is the very language Israel uses in discussing Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's official position is that the
future status of Jerusalem, claimed by both Israelis and Arabs,
will be determined in the final round of peace negotiations that
are now about to resume following the seating of Israel's new prime
minister, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position, the administration's position, on the issue of
Jerusalem has not changed,'' said James Foley, a State Department
spokesman, when asked in Washington about Mrs. Clinton's remarks.
``Israel and the Palestinians have agreed that Jerusalem would be
one of the issues covered in the permanent-status negotiations.
This issue needs to be dealt with by the parties themselves in the
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Mrs. Clinton's views conflicted with the
administration's policy, Foley said, ``The first lady was
expressing her personal views and it does not complicate in any way
our efforts to promote and accelerate the Middle East peace
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Mrs. Clinton's position, he said, ``We don't have an opinion
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was the latest evidence of the uncommonly difficult
political road that Mrs. Clinton will have to negotiate if she runs
for the Senate. It is already clear that she will confront
conflicts between her husband's policies and her own political
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, she joined New York officials in a meeting at
the White House to lobby against Medicare cuts that the president
had proposed.
</P>
<P>
   The letter about Jerusalem became public as Mrs. Clinton dived
into a second day of campaigning in central New York. Tracked by an
outsized entourage of reporters and drawing large and cheerful
crowds along the way, she worked her way across the Mohawk Valley,
turning her attention to the issues of health care, Social Security
and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   As promised, Mrs. Clinton spent a good deal of her day listening
rather than talking. She spent three hours at two forums, the first
devoted to a detailed discussion of health care, the second to
issues of concerns to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Mrs. Clinton began gingerly to hint at how she
might campaign against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York this
fall, by pledging to serve out her full six-year term if she is
elected. Giuliani has declined to make a similar pledge, in what
most Republicans take as an attempt by the mayor to leave open the
option of leaving the Senate to run for national office. There has
also been speculation that Mrs. Clinton might like to run for
president some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to serve out the entire term,'' Mrs. Clinton said
during a 27-minute interview with 10 reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Giuliani declined to comment on Mrs. Clinton's
pledge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
