<HEADLINE>
BUSH, RIVALS MAKE CAMPAIGN VISITS TO UNITY CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The smooth, front-running GOP presidential campaign of
George W. Bush ran into turbulence Thursday during the Texas
governor's first visit to Washington state, amidst allegations that
Bush gave the brushoff to a national convention of minority
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did just fine among the party faithful, picking up the
endorsement of Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., packing a Spokane,
Wash., breakfast with 700 Republicans and taking in between
$250,000 and $300,000 at a party hosted by cellular telephone
billionaire Craig McCaw.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wasn't the only presidential aspirant in town. GOP Sen.
John McCain and Democratic former Sen. Bill Bradley, spoke to UNITY
'99, a convention that has drawn 6,000 journalists to Seattle. Vice
President Al Gore will speak Friday on the topic of race,
technology and the future of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has reached out to the minority community, preceding his
fund-raising appearances around the country with photogenic stops
at Boys and Girls Clubs. He used such an appearance Thursday to
project Clinton-like skills in the use of symbols, photo backdrops
and one-on-one politicking.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's aides had repeatedly turned down requests that he
speak and answer questions at UNITY '99. After reading a critical
newspaper article en route to Seattle, however, he decided to make
a brief appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, son of former President George Bush, shook hands
in the exhibition hall at the Seattle Convention Center, but did
not make a speech. ``I thought I would go by and see some
friends,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later, more seriously, Bush added that the drop-in was
designed to show he would be ``an inclusive-type president.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the conference were critical, however, that Bush
did not make remarks and field questions on sensitive issues like
his competitors in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no opportunity to engage in dialogue,'' said
Catalina Camia, president of UNITY and national president of the
Asian American Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Baca, UNITY vice president and head of the National
Association of Hispanic Journalists, added: ``I would think the
governor would have embraced a situation like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been ideal if he would have followed up our
invitation and made the same kind of appearance that Bradley and
Gore have scheduled,'' Baca said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, the Republican senator from Arizona, begged off a
Cincinnati appearance and rearranged his schedule to fly here and
speak to the minority journalists.
</P>
<P>
   He appealed for campaign finance reform, arguing that the
present system allows ``the wealthiest Americans'' to purchase
access to power through big political contributions. McCain said
that he and a Democratic co-sponsor, Sen. Russ Feingold of
Wisconsin, will try to add the reform measure to other legislation
pending in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also took on a pair of issues used by some Republican
groups, initiatives making English a state's ``official'' language
and measures denying social benefits to illegal immigrants and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should have to abandon the language of their birth in
order to learn and use the language of their future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Using the careful phrases of his ``compassionate conservatism,''
Bush steered clear of such hot button issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly oppose quotas and preferences,'' he told a news
conference after his Boys and Girls Club appearance. Bush said he
favors ``affirmative access'' but did not elaborate on what that
means.
</P>
<P>
   At a late afternoon rally in Bellevue, Wash., Bush promised to
``rally the armies of compassion'' and to make the American dream
available to every child in the land. ``The next president of the
United States must close the gap of hope and that is what I intend
to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has lost no opportunity to decry President Clinton's moral
conduct. He rallied Republicans Thursday night with a promise to
``uphold the dignity'' of the office of president.
</P>
<P>
   But he also has picked up many of Clinton's devices and
mannerisms on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend a lot of time shaking hands and looking people in the
eye,'' said Bush, who has mastered the Clinton style of the drawn
out, meaningful handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stood in shirstleeves Thursday at the Boys and Girls Club,
surrounded by enthusiastic young people. Bush put his arm around
one young man. He was introduced, not by a politician, but by an
Eastlake High School senior, Paolo de Guzman, recently named 1999
Youth of the Year for Washington state by the Boys and Girls Clubs
of America.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bush was asked if he seeks the advice of his father as he
hits the presidential trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do ask him for advice,'' the governor replied. ``The first
thing I ask him for is love.''
</P>
<P>
   At only one point did Bush seem surprised. ``Did you think you
would go to university 10 years ago?'' he asked de Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' replied the self-assured young man, who will attend
Pepperdine University in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has evolved a series of well-modulated positions. He did
not talk about proposed gun safety measures. He did, however, tell
the young people: ``Somebody shows up with a gun, throw him out of
school. Send him to an alternative school.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush made it clear that he is a free trader, and opposes those
in the Republican Party who would try to use trade as a political
weapon against China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely!'' Bush replied when asked if, as president, he
would seek fast-track authority to negotiate new free trade
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush came out strongly in favor of China's bid to join the World
Trade Organization. He argued it would enhance U.S. access to
Chinese markets, and foster growth of ``an entrepreneurial class''
in China that will agitate for democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley made another of the low-key Seattle appearances that
have become a trademark of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He took a poke at Bush, telling a hall of about 550 journalists,
``I didn't change my schedule to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley focused his 45 minutes of remarks on race, health care
and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm president and you want to please the boss, then one of
the things you're going to have to do is show what you've done
toward'' promoting racial unity, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Seattle last year, the former New Jersey
senator celebrated local efforts to create a dialogue on race
through a series of small dinner parties. He added that the
dialogue created should continue across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that should be part of the air you breathe, not a
project but the way you live your life,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Kimberly A.C. Wilson contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
