<HEADLINE>
ON GORE CAMPAIGN, TWO ANTAGONISTS MUST NOW COOPERATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert clarifying material in 6th graf of 2nd take,
beginning: Eskew, for ...)  (mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bob Squier is more than just another consultant to
Al Gore. He has worked for Gore since the early '80s and is among
his half-dozen closest friends and advisers. Funny and smooth,
Squier relaxes the vice president, frequently travels with him and
is typically the last person he sees before a debate or an
important speech.
</P>
<P>
   So it looked like a sure sign of panic last week when the Gore
presidential campaign hired Carter Eskew, Squier's former business
partner and protege, to whom he has not spoken in the seven years
since their bitter and public breakup. Eskew has also had minimal
contact with the vice president in recent years, especially since
he began representing tobacco companies, which Gore crusades
against and blames for the lung cancer that killed his sister.
</P>
<P>
   With the American Lung Association calling for Eskew's firing
before he has even gone to work _ and Republicans openly drooling
over the whole soap opera _ the campaign insists that the move was
simply part of a long-term strategy of building the strongest
possible team, one that would put personal differences aside for
the greater good of moving Al Gore into the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   But separate interviews with Squier and Eskew cast serious doubt
on whether that will be possible. Over a lunch of nearly three
hours at his farm in Virginia, Squier did not even try to put a
happy face on recent events and had almost nothing good to say
about the man many people see as his replacement as the Gore
``message guru.'' (So far, most of the press Gore has received on
the stump could run under the headline ``Stiff Guy Still Stiff.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I had six calls from the campaign this morning about this
lunch, telling me what to say,'' Squier said by way of a greeting.
``I told them I'd say what I want and we'll explain it later.''
When asked how he and Eskew could work together, he sighed deeply
and said, ``I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Public feuding among top aides in a presidential campaign, while
never a good sign, is highly unusual at so early a moment. Though
Gore's nomination once looked inevitable, he has taken a couple of
early hits, one from President Clinton, who publicly urged the
candidate to loosen up. Just two months ago, amid concerns that his
campaign lacked direction, Gore enlisted Tony Coelho, the former
congressman from California, as a top strategist. Now Coelho's
efforts to correct the problems seem only to have compounded the
sense that the campaign is in disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore communications team is still not communicating: Gore
did not deliver the news to Squier himself, and almost a week later
has still not spoken to him about it. Eskew and Squier have not
spoken at all. (Why not? ``He called me, but I haven't called him
back,'' Squier said. ``Maybe if I didn't have to speak to The New
York Times. Not that I wouldn't rather talk to you. And you won't
take that as a compliment, I hope.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is asking for trouble bringing in two people who hate
each other,'' said Dick Morris, who has generally been a fan of
Gore and, as chief strategist to the 1996 Clinton campaign, brought
Squier in as an adviser. ``It's like asking the Albanians and the
Serbs to work together on your campaign. I have high regard for
Carter, but I didn't bring him in in '96 because I wasn't about to
start a civil war. He's making all the wrong moves at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Why had Squier and Eskew fallen out in the first place? ``I've
never said because it would be harmful to Gore if I did. It was
deeply unprofessional behavior'' on Eskew's part, he said. Later,
Squier called back to clarify that the dispute at the time Eskew
left their firm after the '92 election was over money and had
nothing to do with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   By Eskew's account, they split for no other reason than his
desire to strike out on his own. His own view of the squabble is
that Squier was deeply hurt by the abrupt way he left his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a kid then,'' he said of years with Squier that were
like being part of a ``surrogate family.'' He added, ``I don't need
a family now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even to those who believe the hiring was a smart one, reuniting
Gore and a strategist so brilliant that personal considerations
should be disregarded, the timing seemed reactive, coming the day
after the news that both of Gore's leading competitors, Democratic
former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley and George W. Bush, the
Republican governor of Texas, had raised surprising amounts of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Both Squier, 64, and Eskew, 44, have stellar track records as
consultants and ad makers. Mandy Grundwald, who briefly formed a
company with Eskew after the '92 election, described her former
partner as ``part of the new generation'' who had simply outgrown
his mentor. ``In '92 Bob traveled with Gore. Carter was the
creative genius,'' she said. ``I'm just surprised they were smart
enough to ask him'' to join the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Squier's many friends said the suggestion that he was past
his prime as a strategist was unfair. One of them added, ``This is
not a problem that can be solved with ads.''
</P>
<P>
   And Eskew's sudden return to Gore's inner circle made even some
allies question the vice president's personal loyalty, so
frequently cited as Gore defended the president throughout the
Lewinsky scandal. Squier defended the vice president, but said he
had gotten so many condolence calls it was ``a little like
attending your own funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Coelho was brought in as campaign manager to fix the problem of
blurred lines of authority in a top-heavy operation. But it is
unclear how the Eskew hiring will streamline the organizational
chart unless Squier leaves, a step he said he had no intention of
taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my job is,'' Squier said. ``This is way too
important to throw away for some frivolous reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said that when Coelho came to him a month ago, ``I asked
him if he was aware of the tensions and history, and he said,
`Yeah, I'm willing to take that on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Though supremely gracious, serving chevre and an '82 Chateau
Montrose way too fine for a business lunch, along with frittata and
rice salad he had made himself, Squier moaned periodically
throughout the interview: ``Can't we go swimming instead? I despise
this!''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew, for his part, was unruffled. But over a drink _ Evian,
actually _ he said he did have regrets, particularly at leaving the
firm without discussing his decision with Squier. Instead, he had
his secretary distribute notes at a meeting of partners. ``Bob was
my mentor and taught me a lot of what I know about this business,''
he said. ``But I needed to establish myself on my own. If I had it
to do over, I'd leave differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his hiring, he said, neither he nor Gore have rehashed old
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I decided to come on, he said, `Welcome aboard,' and
`Get to work,''' Eskew said.
</P>
<P>
   On their difference of opinion over his work for tobacco
companies, he said: ``I can't imagine we'd have much to say. I'm
here to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskew met Gore when both worked on The Nashville Tennessean
newspaper in the 1970s, but they did not know each other well. They
had a lot in common, including Tennessee roots and Washington
childhoods. Eskew, whose father was an orthodontist, went to
Sidwell Friends, Phillips Exeter Academy and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Squier, who comes from Minnesota, was on his own from a young
age, losing his mother to breast cancer when he was 12 and his
father to cancer, too, on the day he graduated from high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost two parents who were heavy smokers to cancer. I found
my mother,'' he said, explaining why Eskew's work for tobacco
companies got under his skin.
</P>
<P>
   He was a TV producer brought into politics by President Johnson
_ two days before Johnson decided not to run for another term. But
he stayed on to work for Hubert Humphrey, and has worked for
Democrats ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Squier and Eskew, then 24, met while working on Elizabeth
Holtzman's 1980 senatorial campaign. Later, it was Eskew who
brought in Gore's business, and the three became personal friends.
</P>
<P>
   Eskew said he hopes the reunion of the three will work. ``I
don't recall the '96 Clinton campaign being particularly
harmonious, but they bucked up and did it, and that's what we're
going to do,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
