<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ BLASTS A TIE-BREAKING HOME RUN IN YANKEES FINALE AT TIGER
STADIUM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Tiger Stadium, ancient and rundown by modern ball-park
standards, never appealed to the esthetic side of Tino Martinez.
But, he added with a smile before Thursday night's game, he always
liked hitting here.
</P>
<P>
   In the final game between the Yankees and Tigers in this old
ball park, Martinez smashed a tie-breaking home run in the top of
the ninth inning, atoning for an earlier mistake, and the Yankees
nipped the Tigers, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   This was the 943rd meeting of the Yankees' franchise and the
Tigers at this address, at the corner of Trumbull and Michigan
avenues, and their 821st at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tigers first played the New York Highlanders _ who
preceded the Yankees in that franchise _ on June 1, 1912, the
Highlanders' best offensive player was Hal Chase, and Jack Warhop
was the best pitcher. Thursday night, Orlando Hernandez pitched
eight innings, and it was Martinez who was responsible for blowing
a lead and then establishing another.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and a runner at second in the seventh inning,
Detroit's Luis Polonia hit a hard smash toward Martinez, who fell
to his left in an attempt to stop the ball. But the grounder got
through him, a double. Hernandez looked skyward in disgust and
Martinez grimaced as Frank Catalanotto ran home with the run that
tied the score, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Nitkowski, a left-handed reliever who has piqued the
Yankees' interest as trade bait, relieved the Detroit starter Jeff
Weaver for the ninth inning, to face Martinez. The Yankees' first
baseman foiled the Tigers' strategy by whacking his 14th home run,
into the stands in right-center field _ only the eighth hit
Nitkowski has allowed to a left-handed batter all year. Mariano
Rivera pitched the ninth inning for his 22d save.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won't miss Tiger Stadium, which opened in 1912 _
before that, the Tigers had played in Bennett Park at this site _
and their list of complaints is shared by players around the
American League. The dugouts are small and uncomfortable _ if you
are taller than 5-foot-10 and stand up, you're liable to wallop
your head against the ceiling _ and the clubhouses are veritable
closets, compared with the huge clubhouses of the newer ballparks.
The place is dingy, the paint is peeling.
</P>
<P>
   But Tiger Stadium is unique. The second deck in the right- field
stands juts out over the outfield, some 10 feet, turning catchable
fly balls into home runs. Center field is monstrous _ the wall is
440 feet from home plate _ while the alleys are short, 365 feet to
left-center field, 370 feet to right-center. The bullpens, located
in foul territory adjacent to the foul lines, include remarkably
small dugouts that house the relievers. The stands behind center
field are a solid blue, and this background is part of the reason
why hitters have always done well here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't miss it,'' said Scott Brosius, the Yankees' third
baseman, ``but I appreciate the park, the history of it, when you
think of all the Tigers that played here. You have your Ty Cobbs,
and Al Kaline, and even for someone younger like me, there was Kirk
Gibson and Sparky Anderson.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius has toured the various corners of the park, sat in the
second deck above right field. ``The ultimate case scenario,'' said
Brosius, ``would be to have the same field and change everything
around it.''
</P>
<P>
   The reliever Jason Grimsley is looking forward to the new ball
park. Sitting in the bullpens at Tiger Stadium, said Grimsley,
makes you ``feel like you're sitting in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're in a bunker,'' he said. ``You figure
mortars will be come at you any second.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who grew up in Kalamazoo, Mich., guessed he might have
seen a dozen games here as a fan, and he liked watching the
double-play combination of Alan Trammell and Lou Whitaker. But
there is no warm and fuzzy side to Tiger Stadium, as far as he's
concerned. ``I think the field is in terrible shape,'' Jeter said.
``The grass, the dirt. I think it's bad. I just think it's time for
a new one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers won that first game against the Highlanders 87 years
ago. Let the record show that the New York franchise won the last.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees begin their second series of the season with the
Mets Friday at Shea Stadium, and Yankee Manager Joe Torre &UR;  &LR; believes
there isn't nearly as much anticipation for this three-game set as
there was for the series in June. For example, Torre said he has
been asked almost no questions by reporters about this series _ and
he was asked about the June series in 10 days leading up to it.
``We'll find out if six is too much this weekend,'' said Torre, who
has made clear his distaste for the games against the Mets. But
Torre acknowledged the emphasis placed on the games within the
organization. ``It's something you can't help but pay attention
to,'' Torre said. ``Both owners want to win very badly because it's
New York.'' . . . Paul O'Neill &UR;  &LR; mentioned that he was not sure how
he'll spend his All-Star break. ``I don't know, we've got to get
through the World Series this weekend,'' O'Neill said drolly.
``It's a World Series in July.'' &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
