<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-HNS &LR;      07-08 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POVERTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FINDS THAT THE POOR WANT A HAND UP, NOT A HANDOUT &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By NANCY MATHIS
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton completed his tour Thursday of
the nation's impoverished regions, following a path carved 32 years
ago by Robert F. Kennedy but eschewing the big-government politics
that made the New York senator an icon to the downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   From the desperate hollows of Kentucky to the tough streets of
Watts, Clinton's trip demonstrated how completely the Democratic
Party has overhauled its views on a major domestic plank _ its
compact with the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The party's emphasis on government action has given way to
Clinton's embrace of Wall Street investments as the key to lifting
the poor from poverty. And even Jesse Jackson, the party's leading
liberal figure, speaks of a needed ``war for profits'' in the war
on poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place we went, nobody wanted charity; nobody wanted a
handout. What they wanted was a hand up. That's why this will work.
What people want is a good private sector job, the simple dignity
of a paycheck, the ability to house and educate their children and
provide health care for them,'' Clinton told educators in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, saying he wanted to show investors the enormous
opportunities, escorted corporate chiefs into the poorest sections
of Appalachia, the Mississippi Delta, East St. Louis, Ill., the
Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in South Dakota and a Hispanic
neighborhood in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   He closed the trip by emphasizing the need for corporate
training of youths in neighborhoods such as Watts and spoke to the
National Academy Foundation in Anaheim, which links education,
business and government leaders to help high school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This last four days we have all spent together has been a
significant step toward opening America's new markets. But it can't
be the end of the journey. It has to be, instead, the opening salvo
of a battle to build a real economy in every community in this
country,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real measure of success is not whether CEOs join the
president on a trip like this which moved the nation, but whether
the same CEOs and others will return to those markets and move the
lives of the people there.''
</P>
<P>
   At each stop, Clinton maintained that the thriving national
economy _ 19 million new jobs and a jobless rate under 5 percent _
provides a historic opportunity to expand the riches to the poorest
sections. Clinton said those areas will be the key to continue
economic expansion without inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also used the trip to promote his New Market Initiative,
which would offer a series of tax incentives to businesses that
relocate or expand in areas of poverty. He said he will send
legislation to Congress next week and challenged the Republican
leadership to ``set aside its partisan differences'' and put into
law more investments for struggling communities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, while not ignoring poverty, has not placed it high on
his agenda until recently, said Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, political
science professor at nearby Claremont College.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of it is the political environment has changed,
the electorate has changed, the Democratic Party has changed. We
are all moving toward the center,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ideology-driven Kennedy, whose 1967 poverty tour also took
him to Watts and many of the same regions visited by Clinton, could
``wax lyrical'' about the need for government action, she said. But
Clinton is in a far different position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sitting president who is facing a Republican
Congress, a centrist electorate and a need to build a legacy,''
Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman, said: ``If you go back
and look at the language he used in 1991 (when he announced for
president), you'll find it's the same. There were those in the
Democratic Party in 1991 who were slightly uncomfortable with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Democratic Party has moved much more into a
mainstream, moderate view. The president has been preaching from
this page for some time and I think there is many more converts
both within the Democratic Party and the corporate community, as
well as out in the country,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jackson, who accompanied Clinton at every stop, calls access to
capital the latest battle in the civil rights movement. Jackson
recently created the Wall Street Project to encourage Wall Street
investment firms to hire minorities.
</P>
<P>
   And, his Rainbow/PUSH operation has invested in 250 public
corporations and uses its shareholder status to encourage firms to
expand jobs to low-income areas and open retain stores in those
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson repeatedly used the down-home analogy of two winos, one
black and one white, sitting on a railroad track. One drunk says he
thinks he'll buy the track; the other wino responds that he doesn't
want to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the man who owns the railroad track is at the table,
dialogue is almost irrelevant,'' Jackson said. ``For two unemployed
blacks or whites or browns, what does it matter what they think
about anything if they can't make the train stop and can't buy the
track. President Clinton brings to this dialogue are those who own
the railroad, those who own the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged to do another tour in the fall, starting in
Newark, N.J., to highlight the partnership between the New Jersey
Nets and the New York Yankees to dedicate a percentage of the team
profits to investment in local ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make another round here to show people that
there are things that we can do together that are both morally
right and good business,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
