</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN FLIGHT SUBSIDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   With the launching of Hillary Rodham Clinton's undeclared Senate
campaign, taxpayers are no longer paying for her trips around New
York. Or so it is said. In fact, the cost of Mrs. Clinton's flights
on Air Force jets will be reimbursed only by the equivalent of
first-class air tickets for her and her campaign assistants. Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, meanwhile, has begun using private jets for his
campaign travel, and is also paying the owner the equivalent of
first-class fare. In effect, both campaigns are being subsidized _
by the taxpayers in Mrs. Clinton's case and by private jet owners
in Giuliani's. There ought to be a better way.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's travel arrangements are dictated by the same
rules that the Secret Service has long imposed on sitting
presidents and vice presidents running for election. The Secret
Service believes that security needs are best served if the
candidates fly on Air Force jets. Both the president and vice
president are deemed to need an entourage of aides because their
official duties do not go away when they are in campaign mode.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is not an elected official, and she has no
official duties. Even so, she may have little choice but to listen
to the Secret Service. If she cannot fly commercial, it also seems
unreasonable to ask her to pay the full cost of chartering a plane.
Nevertheless, it seems fair to ask her to pay for a larger share of
her travel expenses, and to avoid abusing the privilege of an Air
Force jet by not using it unnecessarily.
</P>
<P>
   By availing himself of private jets, Giuliani is merely
following a long-established practice for candidates running for
president, the House and Senate. In fact, many corporations are
said to keep jets on hand simply to ferry candidates for federal
office around for no more than the price of a first-class fare.
This form of subsidy has long been one of the worst loopholes for
corporate patronage in Washington. It clearly invites abuses.
Common Cause and other groups have tried to challenge the practice,
but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Although what they are doing is perfectly legal, Giuliani and
Mrs. Clinton ought to exercise restraint and common sense. Mrs.
Clinton should figure out a way to ease the burden on taxpayers,
and Giuliani and all other candidates for the Senate should
minimize private or corporate jet travel or forgo it altogether.
The loophole on corporate-subsidized jet travel ought to be
closed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
