</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A VICTORY FOR TOBACCO'S VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 9:
</P>
<P>
   A Florida jury's strong ruling against the tobacco industry in
the first class-action lawsuit to reach a verdict may prove a
watershed in the history of tobacco legislation. The cigarette
makers earlier settled with all the states for $246 billion for
Medicaid costs arising from smoking-related diseases. But those
settlements did not deal with the potential claims of millions of
individual smokers, which may be far more expensive to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The current case was brought by nine plaintiffs representing the
class of Florida residents injured by certain smoking-related
illnesses. The ruling delivered in the first phase of this case,
which has lasted nearly a year, concludes that cigarette
manufacturers marketed an unreasonably dangerous product and
conspired to conceal the dangers and addictiveness of smoking. The
jury also ruled that smoking can cause 20 different diseases,
ranging from lung cancer to heart disease _ facts that the industry
has persistently denied.
</P>
<P>
   The jury also ruled that compensatory and punitive damages could
be awarded. The next phase of the trial will determine the damages
owed the nine plaintiffs. The ruling means that other Floridians in
the class, which may total hundreds of thousands of people, could
potentially go to court to get compensation for their illnesses
without re-litigating questions about the defendants' conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is likely to appeal the decision and seek to
decertify the class. But even if it were to prevail on appeal in
this case, it is unlikely to reverse a growing public perception
that the tobacco makers should be held accountable for products
that contribute to more than 400,000 deaths a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
