<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUPER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE EXTENDS KC SCHOOL BOARD'S DEADLINE FOR HIRING
SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple on Thursday
extended the Kansas City school board's deadline for hiring a
superintendent from today until July 19.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials who attended a two-hour closed-door conference
with Whipple, who doesn't comment on ongoing cases, said he also
left them with the impression that the board shouldn't feel
pressured to quickly hire Benjamin Demps Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge was very clear that he's not forcing them to make a
decision they don't want to make,'' said Charles McClain, a member
of the court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee. ``Just
because Demps is the last one standing doesn't mean they have to
take him.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still uncertain what would happen if the board is unable to
reach agreement with Demps, a longtime state and federal
administrator who lives in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple scheduled a hearing for 10 a.m. July 19 to review the
board's progress and to consider the district's future leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to do what the court has asked us to do, which is
hire someone,'' said board vice president Patricia Kurtz. ``I'm not
going to predict what's going to happen in this. It has been fairly
unpredictable so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the hearing Thursday said Whipple also
emphasized that he is not eager to put the district into
receivership, which would give the court day-to-day control of
district operations.
</P>
<P>
   Some board members had said they felt pressured to quickly
select a superintendent or face a court takeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Whipple's) not in any way trying to get them to select a
candidate based on their fear of receivership,'' McClain said.
``He's very adamant he doesn't want receivership.''
</P>
<P>
   Demps was one of four finalists identified by a Desegregation
Monitoring Committee-dominated screening committee. He has told
district officials he remains interested in the superintendent's
job. Demps did not return repeated phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Three other finalists withdrew, although one -- retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Jay T. Edwards -- also said he still is interested.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's conference, Whipple made no mention of seeking
additional candidates. And McClain said the screening committee has
no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? Maybe somebody could drop out of the sky,'' McClain
said. ``I suppose if we found somebody before next week we thought
could walk on water we could nominate them.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain also discounted any speculation that former Mayor
Emanuel Cleaver might be tapped for the role. ``He's not in the
equation,'' McClain said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the plaintiff schoolchildren
in the district's desegregation lawsuit, applauded the extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the prudent thing to do is not to rush,'' Benson
said. ``We don't want the district to be forced to choose the last
man standing if he's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members are struggling to find someone to serve as a
full-time replacement for former Superintendent Henry Williams, who
resigned under pressure last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Board members initially offered a contract to Edwards, now
general administrator of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission.
Edwards traveled to Kansas City last week but returned to Oklahoma
the next day after he and board members said they could not reach a
contract agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coalition that initially voted for him was a loose one,''
McClain said of the initial 7-2 school board vote to offer the job
to Edwards. ``It was solid in terms of numbers, but not in terms of
commitment. I think they were ready for him to go back to Oklahoma
by afternoon. I don't think it was related to the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has since notified the district he would still consider
the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't close the door if he's interested,'' Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   The board next turned its attention to Pascal Forgione Jr., a
former U.S. commissioner for education statistics. Most board
members said they considered Forgione the most qualified candidate
and on Monday voted 5-1 to offer him a contract.
</P>
<P>
   But in a twist, Forgione withdrew his candidacy in the midst of
negotiations Tuesday, saying he felt slighted by what he termed the
district's ``lowball offer'' and negotiating tactics he termed
``used-car salesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   District officials have disputed Forgione's version of events
and contend he simply got cold feet. They also contend Forgione
withdrew before monetary offers were exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, board members as late as Wednesday were discussing
sending a delegation to Washington to convince Forgione to change
his mind. In the end, board members voted 5-3 with one abstention
to pursue Demps should Forgione reject the approach.
</P>
<P>
   But Forgione on Thursday faxed a statement to The Kansas City
Star and the school board's secretary saying he should no longer be
considered for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was going to be that much sensitivity it probably
wasn't going to be a good marriage anyway,'' McClain said. He also
defended the board's handling of the Forgione negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were miscues, they were honest ones,'' McClain said.
</P>
<P>
   Several board members on Thursday expressed relief about the
extension.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz said board members were worn out from long meetings and
late nights. She said she didn't expect the board to meet again on
the superintendent issue until next week, when the board might try
to schedule an interview with Demps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody wants a little break,'' Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, are discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a positive outcome,'' said board member Fifi
Wiedeman. ``We need to have a lot more discussion about what needs
to happen rather than just filling the spot and repeating what
we've done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The district will continue its background investigation of
Demps, who was a top administrator for many years with the Federal
Aviation Administration. From 1991 to 1994 he was director of the
Oklahoma Department of Human Services. He now runs an aviation
consulting business in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Lee Barnes Jr. on Thursday continued to promote
consideration of the fourth finalist, Grandview Superintendent John
Martin. Barnes said some board members never gave Martin a chance,
even though the selection committee had deemed all four finalists
qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has said he is no longer interested in the position. He
could not be reached Thursday to determine whether he would
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to get the person they wanted and no one else was
going to do,'' Barnes said. ``They never had their mind set on
anyone but Forgione. It's just not fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
