u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINORITY-JOURNALISTS-     07-08 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-JOURNALISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 GOP RIVALS SURPRISE JOURNALISTS' CONFERENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two Republican presidential candidates made
last-minute appearances Thursday at a convention of thousands of
Hispanic, African-American, Indian and Asian-American journalists
here, after reading a newspaper article highlighting their decision
to decline an invitation to speak and take questions at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who leads all candidates in
fund-raising, arrived at the Washington Trade and Convention Center
here Thursday morning, with 10 minutes notice to convention
organizers. Glad-handing startled journalists as he passed by the
booths of a large job fair for journalists, he breezed in and out
in less than 20 minutes, without participating in the organized
question-and-answer session two other presidential contenders had
agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   As the knot of reporters around him expanded and he was asked
about affirmative action, Bush responded, ``I'm against quotas and
I'm against special treatment and I'm for breaking down barriers as
we did in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   After a few other shouted questions and quick answers, he was
off to meet with a group from a local youth club.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John W. McCain of Arizona, who is also a candidate for the
Republican nomination, came with a few hours' more notice and a
little more time. He said he decided to come Thursday morning after
reading an article in The Los Angeles Times that noted the absence
of Republicans at a convention which Vice President Al Gore is to
address on Friday morning, and which Gore's Democratic presidential
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, addressed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's press spokesman, David Beckwith, said Bush also decided
to appear after reading the article. Asked why the candidate had
rejected invitations that had been proffered as early as May and as
recently as Tuesday, Beckwith said, ``We have literally 100 to 200
invitations a day,'' adding, ``He can't do it all.''
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session after his prepared remarks to
reporters at the second convention of the group called Unity:
Journalists of Color Inc., McCain said that he favored affirmative
action, but added, ``It's a phrase we have to define better.'' If,
he said, ``it means what it takes to get people on a level playing
field,'' he supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bradley, who had accepted Unity's invitation, told the
journalists that he would defend affirmative action programs, but
added, ``Race in America is a much broader issue than just
affirmative action. If we constrain it to just affirmative action,
we will miss the broader picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Unity, a coalition of the National Association of Black
Journalists, the National Association of Hispanic Journalists, the
Native American Journalists Association and the Asian-American
Journalists Association, assembled 5,000 journalists at this
convention. About 3,500 are members of the four associations.
</P>
<P>
   The drop-in visit by Bush provoked reactions from bemusement to
indignation among those at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was deliberate of him to catch us off-guard,
because he didn't want to be bombarded with questions,'' said
Cheryl Martin, an anchor for Black Entertainment Television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
