<DOCNO> NYT19990708.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3906 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHTS-EXPANSION-KAN &LR;      07-08 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTS-EXPANSION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESULTS OF STREETLIGHT PROJECT STARTING TO SHINE ON CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- After a shaky start and a few glitches, the
$110 million project to brighten Kansas City's streets at night is
starting to show some results.
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 new or improved streetlights gleam in the city.
Nearly 7,000 more are under construction. An additional 56,000 new
or improved lights are still to come.
</P>
<P>
   The project, approved by voters in November 1997, is intended to
make Kansas City one of the country's best-lit cities by the end of
2001. Proponents said the city's quality of life would go up and
crime would go down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's on time and on budget,'' said Kansas City
Councilman Ed Ford, chairman of the council oversight committee.
``As long as we get it done on time and on budget, I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ford, ``We're getting terrific feedback from the
neighborhoods where we've had the lights installed.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods with high levels of street crime were the first to
get new lights, said James M. Lee, manager of the streetlight
project.
</P>
<P>
   For Beulah Thomas, who has lived in the 3900 block of Indiana
Avenue for 37 years, the new lights have had the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the lights and the security it might help
provide,'' Thomas said. ``Before, we had maybe one or two lights
scattered here and there. The visibility is much better. You can
see onto front porches, see a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvin Brooks, City Council member and president of the Ad Hoc
Group Against Crime, said he hasn't seen statistical evidence of
reduced crime rates in those neighborhoods. But, he said,
perceptions have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said it makes them feel safer,'' Brooks said.
``And it has created a different environment for dope dealers, who
feel less comfortable under the lights. ... It is a deterrent.''
</P>
<P>
   It has made a difference in Blue Hills, said Linda Spence, who
represents that east Kansas City neighborhood on the Citizen
Streetlight Advisory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting rid of crime is a multifaceted thing, but increased
light makes it easier on the neighbors and easier on the police,''
Spence said.
</P>
<P>
   Spence's only concern is that she has seen some lights in the
area out for days before they are replaced, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The November 1997 bond issue called for buying, upgrading and
expanding the city's streetlight system. Kansas City Power &AMP; Light
Co. owned the bulk of the system, and Missouri Public Service Co.
owned some streetlights in the city's outlying areas. The city
leased the system from those companies.
</P>
<P>
   So the city bought KCP&AMP;L's system for $21.5 million, and has
been expanding it ever since. The city recently paid $1.7 million
for the Missouri Public Service portion of the system.
</P>
<P>
   The project got off to a slow start when negotiations with KCP&AMP;L
faltered.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford said that wouldn't change the promised completion
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told people we'd get this done in four years,'' Ford said.
``We just didn't say four years from what. It really took six
months to get off the ground'' after voters passed the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Adams, a former member of the Citizen Streetlight
Advisory Committee, was less optimistic about the delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the project and its importance to the
community and its cost demand more efficient planning and
execution,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams suggested the city audit KCP&AMP;L and its contractors to make
sure the city is getting its money's worth.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the city and the utility company are working well
together and are committed to finishing the project on time.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody realized how big the tree problem was,'' Lee said.
``The city was really behind on tree-trimming. Trees have a huge
impact on streetlights.''
</P>
<P>
   So 30 workers will trim about 60,000 trees as part of the
project. Some trees will be lost, but the Public Works Department
is trying to treat the trees gently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working with the foresters in the tree service to make
sure we don't butcher the trees,'' said Mike Schoeppner, the
project's construction engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Finding -- and keeping -- qualified workers also hindered the
project. The booming local economy kept many electricians tied up
on lucrative private-sector construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   And because of natural disasters, many of the electricians on
the streetlight project kept getting better offers.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma suffered devastating tornadoes earlier this year.
Mississippi was hit hard by a hurricane last fall. Electricians
could make double time or overtime on projects in those states, Lee
said. Many took the opportunity, temporarily leaving Kansas City
shorthanded both times.
</P>
<P>
   Ten teams totaling about 100 workers are now on the project, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents have complained about the project's
implementation. Guidelines say streetlight poles should be placed
150 feet apart. That doesn't account for driveways, front doors,
odd plot sizes and other vagaries of real life.
</P>
<P>
   Officials log about a dozen citizen calls daily. They have tried
to stick close to the guidelines while taking into account
residents' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bend it as far as we can bend it,'' Lee said. ``99.5
percent of the time, we can make some accommodation to a citizen's
request by tweaking the pole's placement.''
</P>
<P>
   One tweaking took place in front of Ken Patrick's house in the
4700 block of Mercier Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just arrived and dug a hole,'' Patrick said. ``You walk
out the front door and there's a big, red, nasty pole. I said,
`You're not putting a pole there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Workers moved the pole. Patrick is happier -- although he still
doesn't much like the pole. He's not convinced his neighborhood
needs more light. Patrick said he'd prefer a steel pole to the
``aesthetically hideous'' wood one.
</P>
<P>
   Even Thomas, who said she appreciated the safety the new lights
provided, doesn't care for the wooden poles in her neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not too sharp,'' Thomas said. ``Of course, the
neighborhood's not too sharp, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhoods with wood poles for existing lights get wood poles
for the new lights. Putting steel poles in all the neighborhoods
probably would have doubled the project's cost, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Saving money is one goal of the project. The city already is
doing that in a couple of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing all the existing lamps with more efficient ones should
save the city about $250,000 a year in operating costs, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the city paid KCP&AMP;L 8 cents per kilowatt hour when the
utility owned the system. Now, the city pays the utility 4.7 cents
per kilowatt hour. Missouri Public Service offered the city a rate
of 3.7 cents. The savings is going into bond payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
