<HEADLINE>
FAA PROBE SET FOR AVIATION FACILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a team of special Federal Aviation Administration
investigators prepare to do a major examination of B.F. Goodrich
Aerospace, the company says it has made significant improvements in
areas which should enable them to better follow government
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The Everett company, which says it is the nation's largest
independent maintenance facility for commercial aircraft, has long
been the target of increased FAA scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Post-Intelligencer reported that FAA inspectors
had recommended closing the sprawling facility because of a series
of violations of FAA regulations and ``dangerously incompetent
work'' on several jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   Another inspector told agency lawyers that BF Goodrich's
``violations raise significant concerns for safety and clearly
raise the potential of a catastrophic failure leading to a crash.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidents noted by the FAA included cases where planes were
released for service with missing bolts, leaking fuel tanks and
other incomplete or improper repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA found that the company used under-trained mechanics
doing flight-critical repairs, unqualified inspectors signing off
on work improperly done, incorrect parts and tools.
</P>
<P>
   But FAA managers said they would rather allow the plant to
remain open under increased surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Michel, the FAA's principal maintenance inspector for the
facility, ran a one-man show there until last summer, when four
other inspectors were added to his team. That's still far less than
the dozen he requested.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Seattle-based safety inspectors say they are
eager to have the six-person team of national FAA experts check out
the operation, which includes repairs, heavy maintenance,
modifications and inspections on jets owned by dozens of passenger
carriers such as United, Northwest, Continental and Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The special team is to start its work next week.
</P>
<P>
   BF Goodrich managers said in February that Michel and his
colleagues overstated the severity of the violations and that ``all
problems cited have been addressed and resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday the FAA said 13 violations or administrative
actions have been filed against the company so far this year.
Inspectors say several other cases are being examined.
</P>
<P>
   Some inspectors continue to express concern over safety
deficiencies at the plant and FAA lawyers have again been asked to
consider sanctions beyond the $1,100 maximum allowed per violation.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, officials at the Everett plant _ the largest of BF
Goodrich's 25 repair facilities worldwide _ insist the FAA has
given the plant a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA may not agree with that characterization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the FAA would use the term `clean bill of
health,''' said FAA spokeswoman Kirsti Dunn. ``Goodrich has
implemented a series of improvements, but the FAA would say it's a
little too soon to measure the effectiveness of those programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the Post-Intelligencer report in February, BF Goodrich
brought in a team of outside experts to examine operations at the
Everett plant. Six weeks ago, the leader of that team, William
White, former deputy director of the FAA's Flight Standards
Service, briefed the FAA on some of his findings.
</P>
<P>
   White noted only one area of major concern or deficiency, which
dealt with repair manuals, said BF Goodrich spokeswoman Sherry
Bergstrom. But two FAA safety specialists who attended that
briefing said White confirmed shortcomings identified by the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, BF Goodrich said it has instituted an ``action plan''
to improve the ``safety and quality'' of work at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The effort includes hiring two additional senior managers: A
training director and a director of regulatory compliance, quality
assurance and safety.
</P>
<P>
   The company also pledged to improve its inspection manuals,
Bergstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   And in what Bergstrom called an unrelated move, the company
Thursday announced the resignation of a top official at the Everett
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Avery, vice president of the Maintenance, Repair and
Overhaul Group in Everett, resigned effective Aug. 31 after 32
years with the company. In a letter released to the media, Avery
said the move was ``to make a major change in my work and personal
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
