<SLUG> BC-NY-NEWSPAPER-TALKS-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIN OWNER WEIGHS DEAL FOR A PAPER IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, N.Y., Israel, Ill., Britain, Conn., Ala.)   (jw) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canadian newspaper publisher Conrad Black _ whose company,
Hollinger International Inc., publishes The Jerusalem Post, The
Chicago Sun-Times, The Daily Telegraph in London and 61 of Canada's
105 daily newspapers _ has turned his eye to New York City, and is
examining the weekly newspaper The New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's editor, Peter Kaplan, said that Black and
Observer owner Arthur Carter had discussions about a deal recently,
but he would not predict the outcome. Senior staff members at The
Observer said Carter had told them that the talks were serious and
involved a sale or a partnership arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Healy, who is vice president for corporate development of
Hollinger International Inc. and handles investor relations in New
York for Black, said that the two owners had discussed the
possibility of some collaboration or a sale within the last six
months. But Healy said that no specific transaction was in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has told senior staff members at The Observer that if
Black were to become involved with the newspaper, it might alter
its publishing schedule from weekly to five days a week, making it
a new entry into the intensely competitive daily newspaper field in
New York City. Carter did not return several phone calls seeking
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Black has searched for a presence in New York City in the past.
In 1992, he tried to buy The New York Daily News, which was then
bankrupt. After six months of negotiations, he backed off because
he was unable to reach an agreement with the 12 unions represented
at the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In circulation, Hollinger International Inc., is the world's
third-largest newspaper and magazine publisher, behind Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp. and the Gannett Co. Hollinger owns about 200
newspapers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Broadwater, a managing director of Veronis, Suhler &AMP;
Associates Inc., the investment bank that handled The Daily News
negotiations, said, ``At one time, Hollinger had an interest in
acquiring a newspaper in New York, but it is not clear that any of
them are buyable right now. Maybe The New York Observer is
buyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Several business associates who know Carter well said they
believed he would rather enter a partnership agreement than sell.
That would make for an odd coupling, since The Observer, which
claims a circulation of 50,000, mostly in Manhattan, has a
generally liberal sensibility and Black's views are strongly
conservative. Carter, a former investment banker, started The
Observer in 1987. He owned The Nation, the liberal weekly magazine,
before selling it in 1995 and still owns The Litchfield County
Times, a weekly in Litchfield, Conn., and The East Hampton, a
weekly on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern, a friend of Carter's and chief executive of the
Hartz Group, which owns The Village Voice, said: ``If you tell me
he will sell out to Conrad Black, well, every man may have his
price. But I don't think Arthur will sell it completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Because The Observer is privately held, it does not reveal its
finances. But two years ago, Carter said in an interview that he
lost about $2 million a year on the paper. Carter's own worth has
been estimated at more than $100 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Establishing a foothold in the world of New York newspapers
appears to fall within Black's corporate strategy, which in recent
years has been to sell his small and medium-size American
newspapers and focus his capital on newspapers in urban areas
around the world. This year, Hollinger sold 45 American newspapers
with circulations below 100,000 in a deal for $475 million to
Community Newspaper Holdings Inc., based in Birmingham, Ala., in
order to focus on the company's larger, more visible newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what is going on here? The company has basically decided
that they have other uses for their capital _ a larger, more urban
focus,'' Broadwater said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this strategy, Black bought The Financial Post in
Toronto a year ago, and then folded it into a new national
newspaper he created, The National Post. The resulting daily
newspaper, introduced nationally in Canada in November, offers
business news and gossip in an easy-to-read format that some
readers compare to that of USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   But starting another daily newspaper in New York would require a
leap of faith and a vast investment. Such a venture would have to
overcome an array of obstacles, from finding access to printing
presses to dealing with distributors and unions.
</P>
<P>
   Black committed about $100 million to the start of The National
Post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
