<HEADER>
A3917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS09-     07-08 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood pitches like an All-Star in 5-2 win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A day after being chosen for his first All-Star game,
Kevin Millwood sought a little reinforcement for NL manager Bruce
Bochy and win No. 11 while he was at it.
</P>
<P>
   Why not throw in a complete game and a 5-2 win over the Marlins
to end this four-game series with the Braves holding a 3-1 edge?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come out here and blow up and have an awful
game,'' said Millwood, who won his fifth start in a row Thursday
night to move to 11-4 and drop his ERA to 3.20. ``I wanted to end
the first half on a positive note and go in on a roll. That's what
I did.''
</P>
<P>
   To do it, Millwood, who'd had four losses all year, had to get
past the Marlins' Brian Meadows, who'd had four losses in his
previous five starts. Meadows held his own against everybody but
Chipper Jones and Ryan Klesko, who each doubled, homered and drove
in two runs off him to give Millwood the offense he needed.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood allowed seven hits in the first five innings and none
in the last four. He finished with 10 strikeouts and only one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had complete command all night,'' Jones said. ``He had a
good curveball, stayed ahead of hitters. What can you say? He's
been our horse so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won't be joining Millwood in Boston but should have Bochy
scratching his head after the third baseman hit his sixth home run
in his last seven games and third in the last three games. This one
came on a Meadows change-up in the sixth inning, the last of a
series of change-ups. Jones had homered on fastballs from Alex
Fernandez and Ryan Dempster the previous two nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good thinking on his part,'' Jones said. ``But to throw
me that many? Eventually I'll get it in my thick head to sit on
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones doubled in Bret Boone in the first inning for his eighth
RBI in the last eight games and extended his hitting streak for
that stretch as well. He gave the Braves a 1-0 lead in the first
inning, a lead they wouldn't lose thanks to Millwood.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood gave up a pair of runs off the bat of Marlins No. 3
hitter Bruce Aven, the second of which cut the Braves' lead to 3-2
on a double in the fifth. Millwood gave up an infield hit to the
next batter and nothing else, retiring the last 13 batters of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, Kevin would tire a little bit in the middle of a
ballgame when it got hot,'' said Atlanta manager Bobby Cox, who had
no problem staying with Millwood despite 116 pitches after eight
innings. ``Not this year. It seems like he gets stronger all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves ended this three-week jaunt through the National
League East with 11 wins and 6 losses and moved to five games ahead
of the second-place Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-08-99 2343EDT &QL; 
