<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER BLASTS PROPOSED FEDERAL RULES ON CONTRACTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)   (jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even before the Clinton administration issued new rules that
would bar federal contracts to chronic corporate lawbreakers, the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce was attacking the rules, calling them an
arbitrary ``blacklist'' and a sop to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules, to be announced Friday, recommend that
federal procurement officers award no contracts to companies guilty
of repeated and substantial violations of laws on discrimination,
labor, tax, environmental or antitrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government should not enter into contracts with
contractors who do not comply with the law,'' said the new
regulations, which expand on existing rules saying the government
should award contracts only to responsible companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Chamber of Commerce officials suggested that the new rules
would be used mainly to help labor unions and would create havoc
and uncertainty for the thousands of companies vying for more than
$170 billion in federal contracts each year. The chamber had
closely monitored development of the rules.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, listed hundreds of federal
contractors that had been found guilty of violating labor law. The
report did not include the hundreds of companies guilty of
environmental, tax and other violations.
</P>
<P>
   Chamber officials predicted that the new rules would be used
principally to punish companies found to have violated labor laws,
like those prohibiting companies from firing workers in
unionization drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's blacklisting regulation is not only bad
public policy, it's probably illegal,'' said Thomas Donohue,
chamber's president. ``The U.S. Chamber of Commerce will do
whatever is necessary to block this politically motivated policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Vice President Al Gore announced at an AFL-CIO
meeting that the administration would issue tougher procurement
regulations, but the administration delayed issuing the new rules
when congressional Republicans threatened retaliation. At an
AFL-CIO meeting in February, labor leaders pressed Gore to move
forward with the promised rules.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the presidential campaign, Randel Johnson, chamber
vice president for labor policy, said, ``We think Vice President
Gore has promoted issuing these regulations as a payoff to the
unions.''
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials insisted they were issuing the new
rule for reasons of good government, not for political motives.
``This rule says if you expect to do business with the government
then you had better follow the law,'' said Linda Ricci, spokeswoman
for the White House Budget Office. ``There is no reason for the
American government to do business with companies that don't pay
their taxes, don't respect our environmental laws and don't follow
health and safety regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamber officials insisted that the rules were unclear,
asserting that companies did not know how many violations _ 2, 20
or 200 _ might bar them from government contracts. These officials
voiced fears that procurement officers might use the rules'
ambiguities to pick on companies that have antagonized labor.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO officials welcomed the new regulations, saying they were
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These strike us as good, sensible reforms that reinforce the
idea that taxpayer dollars shouldn't be subsidizing chronic
lawbreakers,'' said Lynn Rhinehart, the AFL-CIO's associate general
counsel. ``This is not blacklisting. This is about responsible
contracting.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules, which face a 120-day comment period, also state
that the federal government will no longer reimburse contractors
for the amounts they spend in fighting unionization drives. The
rules also say the government will not reimburse legal expenses in
cases in which a federal contractor is found to have violated a
law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For years, labor leaders have pointed to the unionization
struggle at Avondale Shipyard in Louisiana as evidence that tougher
rules for government contracts were needed. The shipyard, which
relies heavily on Navy contracts, had refused to recognize a union
even though the yard's 5,000 workers had narrowly voted to support
unionization six years ago. A federal administrative judge has
found the shipyard guilty of more than 70 labor law violations,
including firing 28 workers because they supported the union.
</P>
<P>
   But Avondale won a major victory on Wednesday when a federal
appeals court overturned the union's election victory, accepting
Avondale's arguments that the National Labor Relations Board did
not do enough to check the voters' identification to prevent
election fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
