<SLUG> BC-CERNER-EARNINGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CERNER SAYS SECOND QUARTER WON'T MEET EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Cerner Corp. said Thursday that it expected
a shortfall in second-quarter earnings and revenue because of the
year 2000 computer bug and federal health-care cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The North Kansas City, Mo.-based medical software company, which
in June proposed a $237 million expansion, said it expected to
report that it broke even or earned up to 2 cents a share -- before
an extraordinary item of $1.4 million related to the early payoff
of debt -- during the quarter that ended July 3.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' consensus estimates had pegged Cerner's second-quarter
earnings at 10 cents a share. Cerner shares closed Thursday at 18,
down 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We indicated early in the year that there would be
uncertainties inherent in 1999 created by the impact of Y2K and the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997,'' said Neal L. Patterson, Cerner's
chairman, president and chief executive officer. ``Both are
contributing to a deferral of purchasing decisions. We believe that
this higher level of uncertainty will continue through 1999 and
into the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerner said it expected to report second-quarter revenue in the
range of $81 million to $85 million. Bookings are expected to range
from $66 million to $70 million. Final results are expected to be
announced July 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are clearly disappointed with the results for the
quarter, we did see a halt to the sequential decline in base
business bookings we had experienced over the last three
quarters,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner's HNA Millennium software is designed to loop together
the information systems of hospitals, pharmacies, laboratories,
doctors' offices and other health-related entities, thereby cutting
paperwork and streamlining services.
</P>
<P>
   Daren Marhula, an analyst who follows Cerner for U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis, said he wasn't surprised by
Thursday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has been saying for some time that there's a
Y2K-related slowdown in the market, and most research analysts have
been coming to the same conclusion,'' Marhula said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Marhula said it was encouraging that Cerner
expected its second-quarter bookings to exceed those of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said in late May that some potential Cerner customers
had delayed purchases until they finished fixing Y2K problems. He
also said then that the federal Balanced Budget Act of 1997 had cut
$115 billion of payments that were aimed toward hospitals, doctors
and home health agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson said Thursday that Cerner had a ``broad client base
and industry-leading technology. We remain committed to our
strategy of delivering the only contemporary enterprise system
architecture to health care across all sites of care. We believe
that this strategy provides us with a superior competitive position
in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Cerner in April reported a first-quarter earnings decline of 25
percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Cerner's expansion of its campus would be built in five phases
over 15 years, from 2000 to 2015, and would have space for an
additional 3,600 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The company is asking for about $42.09 million in property tax
abatements under Missouri's Chapter 353 redevelopment law.
Officials with Cerner said it needed the tax breaks to compensate
for the added costs of building on the site's erosion-prone soil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
