u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-TOUR09-COX     07-08 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-TOUR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady 'polished' early in N.Y. tour
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ She runs late, she runs long, and if she
doesn't totally run away from personal questions, she seems
determined to dance around them.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody gets a listen on the issues. Nobody gets much in the
way of answers yet.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, as happened here Thursday, Hillary Rodham Clinton
even admits to having learned from a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may recall I had some thoughts about health care in the
past,'' Clinton told a packed room at Bassett Healthcare, peals of
laughter greeting her gently self-mocking reference to her
far-reaching reform efforts back in 1993. ``But I now come from the
school of smaller steps.''
</P>
<P>
   If it both does and doesn't sound like a typical political
campaign, make no mistake about it: It's Hillary Clinton's version
of one. And on the second day of her much-ballyhooed ``Listening
Tour'' across central New York State, something else became clear.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, it's sinking in.
</P>
<P>
   Said Joseph Sellers, a Bassett physician and avowed Republican
with a barely contained sigh, ``I was very much impressed with Mrs.
Clinton. She was polished.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, Sellers had snapped to attention parts of the
packed meeting room by rising in the audience and informing Clinton
that much of largely rural central New York's health care woes
could be traced to the region's poor economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   He even invoked President Clinton's memorable 1992 campaign
phrase, ``It's the economy, stupid,'' causing Mrs. Clinton to
exclaim, ``That's a very good point.'' That got much of the
seemingly snoozing press contingent suddenly vying for interviews
with Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Day Two of Clinton's four-day visit here contained none of the
drama or glamour of Wednesday's endorsement by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan among the hay bales and weathered buildings of his
900-acre farm.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton conducted two more ``listening sessions,'' each
marked by the would-be candidate's attempt to demonstrate her grasp
of issues affecting the health care community and the elderly, and
her almost endless willingness to let people talk to her.
</P>
<P>
   Both sessions started on what has been called ``Bill Clinton
time,'' getting under way nearly an hour late. And despite what
members of her exploratory committee staff suggested ahead of time,
neither ended after only an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, she almost appeared to be begging for more time with her
audience Thursday afternoon at Utica's East Side Senior Center,
telling a crowd that had just spent some 45 minutes bending her ear
about the need to protect Social Security, reduce crime and lower
prescription drug costs, ``I'd like to learn from you. What ELSE
can we do to better economic conditions here?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the senior center audience responded enthusiastically
when Clinton reminded them of ``my husband's'' announced intention
to direct budget surplus dollars to assuring the future solvency of
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Such unwavering loyalty was not totally in evidence earlier in
the day, however, when Clinton took pains to tell her Bassett
audience when she didn't think the president's health care policies
went far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something my husband and others in Washington, D.C., think we
need is to empower patients more through the Patient's Bill of
Rights,'' Clinton said. ``But even that is a diversion. I'm for it.
I hope it passes. But at the end of the day, we'll have more people
arguing over what should be done for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   More evidence emerged later Thursday that the all-but-announced
candidate is as willing to publicly separate herself from her
husband on certain issues as she is to invoke his successes in the
appropriate settings.
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign released a letter she wrote last week to Mandell
Ganchrow, president of the Union of Orthodox Jewish Congress of
America, stating that she viewed Jerusalem as ``the eternal and
indivisible capital of Israel'' and would advocate to move the U.S.
embassy there from Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to put her at odds with her husband, who
recently blocked the embassy shift and maintains that Israel and
the PLO should together determine Jerusalem's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's statement on Jerusalem may play well with the
large Jewish community in New York and could help reverse the
negative attitude many Jews have toward the first lady for a
statement she made several years ago in support of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   Now if only she could approach her husband's campaign mastery.
Asked Thursday about reports President Clinton had advised her on
communicating with voters, she seemed to confirm that. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I decide to run I will certainly do that, and I will
practice in front of my husband,'' she said in an interview session
with reporters from New York newspapers, a transcript of which was
made available. ``If he gives me a passing grade, then I will go
out and tell the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
